<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE RECEDING INFLUENCE OF EMPIRES 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, Dec. 22:
</P>
<P>
   For all the strife at the dawn of a new millennium, one enduring
source of conflict may be receding. At least for now, the earth's
empires have disappeared as anchors of international order. Some
fear that a suffocating American imperium now enforces its culture
and unforgiving economic rules. But in today's global environment,
the cost and complexity of one people trying to control the
sovereignty of broad stretches of the globe no longer seem worth
bearing. Today's challenge is to make the new system of established
states, new states, failed states, would-be states, regional
conflicts and tenuous alliances work better than the old.
</P>
<P>
   The 20th century has seen three waves of collapsing empires, as
the political scientist Michael Mandelbaum points out. First came
the great dynasties of the Hapsburgs, Hohenzollerns, Ottomans and
Romanovs _ destroying each other in the calamity of World War I,
followed by the demise of the British, French, Dutch and Japanese
empires at the end of World War II and the disintegration of the
Soviet empire a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   The current epoch began not only with the birth of the Christian
era, but also the legacy of Rome. As the historian William McNeill
notes in ``The Rise of the West,'' the moment of Jesus' life
coincided with a profound demographic change in human history, as
``the submerged peoples and rootless populations'' who had migrated
to the urban centers of the Roman Empire, as well as the Parthian,
Kushan and Han empires to the east, struggled for spiritual
guidance. The spread of Christianity, Buddhism and Hinduism among
these peoples helped answer their needs.
</P>
<P>
   For 2,000 years, Rome has given its identity to the West's
political establishments. In Europe, Charlemagne and many
subsequent rulers chose for their domain the legitimizing name of
Holy Roman Empire. The Roman republic served as a model for the
revolutionaries in France and North America, where a nation was
established in 1776, the year of the publication of Edward Gibbon's
``History of the Decline and Fall of the Roman Empire.'' Gibbon
observed that barbarism and religion had destroyed an empire that
at its height offered a realm in which ``the human race was most
happy and prosperous.''
</P>
<P>
   In the book ``Empires,'' the Princeton historian Michael Doyle
suggests that empires today are dying from the spread of
nationalism, liberal democracy, global capitalism and the ease with
which the peoples of the world can subvert their subjugators. No
one can know whether empires will rise again, in part because
smaller nations may find it useful to ally themselves with larger
ones. But for now, Doyle suggests, the cost of imperialism has
risen to an unacceptable level.
</P>
<P>
   Yet much of Asia, Africa and Latin America remain organized
along boundaries designed by their onetime imperial overlords.
Immense countries like Indonesia and India are residual imperial
states, China rules coercively over its varied and restless
peoples, and even the subgroups within Britain and France seem
increasingly eager to assert their identities. The beginning of the
next millennium offers the challenge of inventing a new order to
replace the artificial, often brutal stability imposed by old
imperial structures. Without a new respect for the rights of
minorities, the world's thousands of ethnic, linguistic and
religious subgroups will increasingly wonder whether their moment
to press for independence as a nation has arrived.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of this century, Woodrow Wilson proposed the
concept of self-determination as the new organizing principle of
the world after the end of the era of empires. But his secretary of
state, Robert Lansing, wondered from the start whether
self-determination would create more problems than it would solve.
``The phrase is simply loaded with dynamite,'' he wrote in his
diaries. ``It will raise hopes which can never be realized. It
will, I fear, cost thousands of lives.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the millennium, the world has a much better idea
of what it is leaving behind than of what lies ahead. Yet surely
the challenge of the future is to preserve Wilson's vision while
avoiding atomization of the world into ever tinier nations. If
there is a new world order, its stability will only come by a
revitalization of each nation's identity, with or without new
boundaries drawn on a map. A new philosophy of respect for the
world's variety needs to replace the imperial designs that lasted
for more than 2,000 years. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
