<HEADLINE>
INCENTIVES COULD RAISE SOME SCHOOL PRINCIPALS' PAY BY 70 PERCENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If New York City school principals approve the pay
package recently negotiated by their union, some stand to increase
their pay by 70 percent and could possibly earn more than $143,000
a year beginning in April.
</P>
<P>
   In general, the contract calls for across-the-board raises of 33
percent for principals who have been without a contract for four
years. But bonuses and incentives in the new contract could
substantially raise many principals' compensation well beyond 33
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The largest gains are likely to go to only a small contingent _
principals with the most years of service and those who are willing
to work in large or underperforming schools, or those leading such
schools who perform in the top ranks among principals across the
city. Principals working in underperforming schools would qualify
for extra pay of $10,000, and those ranking in the top 5 percent
among all city principals would earn an extra $15,000.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the longest-serving principals will be willing to move
into the most challenging positions is open to question, as is
whether principals at low-performing schools can quickly turn in
top-ranked performances.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new contract's terms, the highest paid principals, who
now earn $83,921, could earn more than $143,000, an increase of 70
percent, through the base pay raise and incentive bonuses. And
lower-paid principals, whose salaries start at $69,599, could see
their earnings rise sharply if they agree to move to a
lower-performing school and subsequently earn increases based on
performance evaluations.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a high-school principal who now earns the average
salary of $79,347 would earn $105,661 under the negotiated
contract's base salary increase. If that principal worked at an
underperforming school, earning a $10,000 bonus, and earned a
$15,000 bonus for placing in the top 5 percent of all principals on
the basis of performance evaluations, the compensation would rise
to $130,661 _ a total gain of 65 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
