<SLUG> BC-BBN-BELTRE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELTRE DENIED FREE AGENCY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Despite the Los Angeles Dodgers admitting to
falsifying Adrian Beltre's age and knowingly signing him at an
illegal age, baseball commissioner Bud Selig made an expected
announcement Tuesday, denying the Dodger third baseman's request to
be granted free agency.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers were fined $50,000, markedly less than the club
anticipated, and ordered to pay Beltre damages. But in announcing
his ruling, Selig said Beltre and/or his representatives likely
were aware at the time of the signing he was not of sufficient age.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is hardly settled, though. The players union is
gathering the final pieces of information and is expected to file a
grievance, possibly by the end of the week. The case will then be
brought in front of arbitrator Shyam Das, and the union is expected
to ask for the process to be expedited. Still, it's unlikely the
matter will be resolved before mid-January.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers must also close their Campo Las Palmas complex in
the Dominican Republic for one year and are forbidden from scouting
or signing any first-year player who resides in the Dominican
Republic for one year. The Dodgers are still allowed to field teams
in the Dominican Republic, but they can't play, train, or lodge at
the complex.
</P>
<P>
   If Das rules in favor of Beltre, the 20-year-old would become a
free agent. But the fines and sanctions levied against the Dodgers
would then become void, several sources said. But once the
grievance is filed those sanctions are tabled.
</P>
<P>
   Major League Baseball also suspended Ralph Avila and Pablo
Peguero, the scouts who allegedly orchestrated Beltre's signing,
for one year.
</P>
<P>
   Avila and Peguero were also implicated in the illegal scouting
and signing of a pair of Cuban defectors that were in the Dodgers
minor league system until this past summer. Baseball ruled Josue
Perez and Juan Carlos Diaz free agents and fined the Dodgers
$200,000. Diaz then received an $850,000 signing bonus with the
Philadelphia Philles.
</P>
<P>
   Avila is retired and no longer associated with the Dodgers.
Peguero runs Campo Las Palmas, but a Dodgers official said
Peguero's time with the club is ``extremely limited.'' Even if an
arbitrator overturns baseball's ruling, it doesn't affect the
suspensions of Peguero and Avila, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a serious violation of Major League Baseball's
rules,'' Selig said. ``There are those who would like to dismiss
this kind of behavior as `business as usual.' We will not allow
such an attitude to prevail in our game, and we will vigorously
enforce the rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although these violations occurred under prior ownership, the
club must accept responsibility for the consequences of the acts,
no matter when they were committed.''
</P>
<P>
   The six-week investigation was conducted by Sandy Alderson,
executive vice president of baseball operations for the office of
the commissioner. Alderson, however, wouldn't comment on the case.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers did not comment either, but the club issued a
statement from president and COO Bob Graziano.
</P>
<P>
   ``We submitted this matter to the commissioner, fully cooperated
in the investigation process and will abide by his findings and his
ruling,'' Graziano said. ``As we have said before, the Dodgers
respect and strongly endorse the rules and regulations of Major
League Baseball, and we fully intend to comply with those rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have and will continue to improve our structure and to
strengthen our policies so that similar issues will not arise in
the future. We remain committed to protecting and upholding the
integrity of the game and the honored tradition of the Los Angeles
Dodgers.''
</P>
<P>
   The investigation concluded Beltre was 15 when he signed a
contract in 1994. Beltre received a $23,000 bonus. The Dodgers were
ordered to pay Beltre the difference between that figure and the
bonus he would have received had he signed at age 16, plus
interest. It works out to $49,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first step in the process,'' said Scott Boras, who
represents Beltre. ``Now, we can move forward and get the issue in
front of an arbitrator.''
</P>
<P>
   Once in front of the arbitrator, baseball is expected to base
its case on Beltre, and/or his representatives, having knowledge he
was signed illegally and he hid the issue until it benefited him
financially to come forward.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball's report said ``documents demonstrate Beltre's
awareness of the Dodgers' falsification of his birth date long
before the case was brought to the commissioner.'' It also said
Beltre used the falsified birth date.
</P>
<P>
   Boras, on behalf of Beltre, is expected to argue that Beltre had
no knowledge of the rule preventing a player from signing before
the age of 16. Boras said Beltre didn't know about the rule until
the two had a conversation March 10. Baseball rules state a claim
must be made within one year of when the violation was discovered.
</P>
<P>
   Beltre is an integral part of the Dodgers, and is considered one
of the top prospects in baseball. In his first full season he hit
.275 with 15 homers, 67 RBI and 18 stolen bases. Beltre made
$220,000 last season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
