<HEADER>
A6055 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ELMO-PUPPETEER-ART-NY     12-22 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELMO-PUPPETEER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEHIND SQUEAKY ELMO, 6 FEET OF BARITONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By JACQUES STEINBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The squeaky falsetto across the table was intimately
familiar, at least to anyone who has been a child or parent in the
last 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elmo loves sushi,'' he said, referring to himself in the third
person, as he always does. ``Especially wasabi. That's why Elmo
doesn't have eyelids. Heh-heh-heh-heh-heh!''
</P>
<P>
   But if the voice _ think Carol Channing on helium _ sounded as
if it was burbling from ``Rock and Roll Elmo,'' one of this
season's must-have toys, the body was all wrong: instead of two
ping-pong-ball eyes set atop a hank of ragged red fur, the speaker
was 6 feet tall and 195 pounds. Above his lips was a thin mustache
that was more Billy Dee Williams than Big Bird, and he was wearing
a cream-wool turtleneck that screamed Barneys, not Barney.
</P>
<P>
   To his interviewer, whose 18-month-old daughter thinks ``Elmo's
Song'' is the national anthem, the voice that came out next was
jarring. It was a baritone, one that can dip as low as Barry
White's bass, but, he says, is most comfortable closer to Joe
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think I must be a little, chubby, bald-headed guy with
glasses,'' said Kevin Clash, 39, who gives Elmo _ the ``Sesame
Street'' character and the toys _ his speech and his spirit, as
well as the motion in his paws and jaw. ``The bottom line is, no
one knows what a puppeteer is to begin with. And they're certainly
not going to think `black' first. It's not the norm.''
</P>
<P>
   A mouthful of lobster tempura and a swirl of merlot later, he
added: ``This is a very strange occupation.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so strange, perhaps, when you consider that Clash had been
dreaming of living on Sesame Street since age 9. The third of four
children, he grew up in Baltimore, where his father worked at a
steel factory. His mother ran a day care center out of the family's
two-bedroom home.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever there was a snowstorm, his parents would burrow a cave
through the neighborhood, crowning it with flags bearing names like
Fort McSnow. ``The Clashes were very silly people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clash's earliest memories are of turning garbage into stage
sets. ``I'd take a box and coat hangers and dolls and attach them
together, so the dolls would go up and down,'' he said. If he
wasn't watching ``Sesame Street'' _ trying to build Muppets like
those who have called the show home since 1969 _ Clash was buying
``fur, felt, eyes and noses.''
</P>
<P>
   As an adolescent, he would lure audiences to his puppet shows
with free candy. Soon, he was performing at fairs on the Inner
Harbor where he was discovered, in the 10th grade, by a local
weatherman, Stu Kerr.
</P>
<P>
   Within weeks, he and Kerr had their own children's television
show, ``Caboose,'' in which Clash performed characters like Bartee,
who wore Clash's grandmother's wig, and two skunks who sang ``You
and Me Against the World.''
</P>
<P>
   It was inevitable that Captain Kangaroo would call.
</P>
<P>
   Kerr had served in the military with Bob Keeshan, who played the
captain, and at Kerr's prodding, Keeshan's producers traveled to
Baltimore to raid Clash's shelves of puppets. He had not yet
graduated from high school.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after he did, in 1979, he was working full time on
``Captain Kangaroo'' in New York. At the same time, he was also
penetrating the Muppets' inner circle, through a budding friendship
with Kermit Love, who, though no relation to The Frog, was an
associate of Jim Henson's.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, after ending his run at ``Captain Kangaroo'' and
another show, ``The Great Space Coaster,'' Clash moved to Sesame
Street, which, it turns out, is in the Astoria section of Queens.
Struggling to find a character, Clash was relegated to playing
``miscellaneous pigs and chickens.'' That changed in 1985, when
Brian Meehl, the Muppeteer who originated Elmo, left the show after
playing him only three or four times.
</P>
<P>
   Elmo, a hand puppet who was barely defined beyond being a
3-year-old, was reassigned to Richard Hunt. But Hunt hated the
character immediately _ Elmo wasn't edgy enough _ and, on one
memorable morning, brought him into the Muppeteers' lounge
``hanging by the rods,'' the chopsticklike bars that control his
paws.
</P>
<P>
   ``He handed him to me like a piece of trash and said `Here, come
up with a voice,''' Clash recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Though Clash says that Elmo's BB-gun giggle erupted immediately,
it took a visit to his mother's day-care center to locate Elmo's
soul. ``What I got from those kids,'' he says, ``is that innocence
and sweetness and positiveness.''
</P>
<P>
   Though celebrity parents like Jamie Lee Curtis soon requested
guest appearances with Elmo, helping make him an international
star, Rosie O'Donnell certified him as a marketing juggernaut.
After she held up a ``Tickle Me Elmo'' doll on her show in 1996,
hundreds of thousands were sold.
</P>
<P>
   Clash, who owns no rights to the character, says he has been
well-compensated. But he says the richest payoffs often come off
the set.
</P>
<P>
   As Elmo, he has whispered in the ears of dying children, left
answering machine messages for strangers celebrating wedding
anniversaries and made his 6-year-old daughter, Shannon, the envy
of her friends.
</P>
<P>
   But the request that hit him hardest arrived in a letter from a
young girl, whose sick mother had clutched ``Tickle Me Elmo''
during rounds of chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had asked to be buried with Elmo,'' Clash says, his eyes
wet. ``And he went with her.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
