<SLUG> BC-TV-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARTY TIME FOR THE MAORI  
 GORE-BRADLEY DEBATE DRAWS VIEWERS  
 NEW GAME SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Millennium mania _ or madness or mayhem, depending on events _
will be all over television the next two weeks, with the ultimate
confluence of coverage on New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   A brief sampling of what is available ranges from the Time
magazine ``Person of the Century'' special on CBS on Monday at 10
p.m. (the magazine has gone to enormous lengths to try to keep the
selection secret) to the top 99 videos of 1999 on MTV starting at 9
a.m. on Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   The main focus, however, will be on the events of the turn of
the century itself, which has been designated the turn of the
millennium even though nitpickers and math majors are holding out
for 2001 as the real millennial event.
</P>
<P>
   ABC has been widely promoting its commitment to covering all
sorts of worldwide events as the clock changes around the world
that day. But that network will hardly be alone. All three cable
news channels will be devoting the day to both global millennial
celebrations and whatever Y2K-related disasters may occur.
</P>
<P>
   The other broadcast networks will have news crews in place for
the same reason, though they will mainly devote their prime-time
hours to entertainment-oriented celebrations, like a special David
Letterman show and the ``America's Millennium'' concert on the lawn
of the Capitol in Washington on CBS (complete with Will Smith as
host and a preview of a short film by Steven Spielberg, ``The
Unfinished Journey'') and live performances from artists like the
Red Hot Chili Peppers on Fox.
</P>
<P>
   NBC will have its news anchors Tom Brokaw and Katie Couric in
Times Square from 9 p.m. to 3 a.m. covering both whatever news
occurs and introducing such entertainment events as concerts by
Sting and Gloria Estefan and a special 15-minute monologue by Jay
Leno.
</P>
<P>
   Among the broadcasters, however, only PBS is going quite as all
out as ABC. In fact, because PBS belongs to the same special
millennial consortium as ABC, some of the coverage will be
duplicated.
</P>
<P>
   The ``PBS Millennium 2000'' special (beginning at 4:45 a.m. on
Dec. 31) will be a live 25-hour extravaganza with Gwen Ifill as
host. Like many of the other outlets covering live events, PBS will
have international high points, including shots of Maori warriors
dancing at dawn on their island off New Zealand, and Nelson Mandela
as the host for freedom celebrations in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Special PBS touches will include an acrobatic ballet from
Sydney, Australia, a performance of the musical ``Fosse,'' and a
millennium song from the Gipsy Kings in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   At least one veteran network news producer has questioned
whether the millennial New Year is truly worth all the fuss.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly some elements seem a bit contrived. Many of those
celebrating would seem to have little reason to mark a year made
significant only by the Christian calendar.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the best example is the Maori tribesmen, who seem to
have gone to great lengths to seek out this once-in-a-millennium
photo opportunity. CNN's president, Rick Kaplan, said that the
Maori had petitioned officials at the Greenwich Institute in
England to move up their time zone by 15 minutes so they would
indeed be the very first civilization on the planet to mark the new
millennium. (They are receiving worldwide coverage for their
efforts.)
</P>
<P>
   ``They are the Dixville Notch of the millennium,'' Kaplan said,
referring to the small New Hampshire community that always gets its
presidential votes in first.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan argued that reaching the year 2000 was far too
significant a moment to go uncelebrated or unexamined. ``It is
really an extraordinary opportunity,'' he said. And CNN intends to
observe it not only with all-day coverage from around the globe on
Dec. 31, but also by an entire weekend of special programming
devoted to a look toward the future.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan said that CNN had contacted world experts on subjects
from genetics to computer science to the weather and found a
remarkable number of them not only available on that weekend but
also eager to discuss where the world is heading in their areas of
expertise.
</P>
<P>
   CNN will be offering everyone from Mikhail Gorbachev talking to
Shimon Peres about water use to Bill Gates talking to Larry King
about where technology is leading the world.
</P>
<P>
   Will there be interest? ``Not everybody will be watching bowl
games,'' Kaplan said.
</P>
<P>
   Debate Scores
</P>
<P>
   ``Meet the Press'' rode its newsmaking debate between Vice
President Al Gore and Bill Bradley to an enormous ratings edge over
the other Sunday- morning political discussion shows last week.
</P>
<P>
   The debate added about 700,000 more viewers than the show had
averaged in November. The initial national ratings for the
broadcast gave NBC's ``Meet the Press'' a 3.9 rating, over a 2.3
for ``Face the Nation'' on CBS, 2.2 for ``This Week'' on ABC and a
1.5 for ``News Sunday'' on Fox. (Each rating point represents just
over 1 million homes.)
</P>
<P>
   The results further underscored the decline of ABC's ``This
Week,'' which until two years ago had been the regular leader in
the Sunday competition. Not only was ``This Week'' beaten by ``Face
the Nation'' for the second time in recent weeks, it also saw its
move to the 9 a.m. hour in New York result in even worse ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday ABC finished fourth in New York, beaten by Fox's
show, which faces it head-to-head at 9 a.m. ``Meet the Press,''
which is broadcast at 10:30 in New York, won in that market by
about four full ratings points.
</P>
<P>
   More Games
</P>
<P>
   CBS announced this week that it was adding yet another game show
to the prime-time schedule starting on Jan. 8. The show, ``Winning
Lines,'' is another British import and another creation of Paul
Smith, the man behind `'Who Wants to Be a Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS is committed to producing six of the shows and will put it
into full production if it likes the early rating trend. Few shows
have had a quicker development cycle.
</P>
<P>
   CBS is reaching deep into its history for its host. Dick Clark,
who has been serving as a television host for more than a
generation, will again take up the role on the new CBS show. That
will make him a major player in the game show phenomenon. Clark is
a producer of the game ``Greed,'' for the Fox network.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
