<HEADER>
A6059 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-INNER-CITY-EDUC-2TAKE     12-22 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INNER-CITY-EDUC-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDUCATION CENTER THRIVES, AND PROFITS, IN A POOR LOCALE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.J., Md.)  (mk) 
 By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Amid the pulsing rhythms that envelop Fulton Street
in the Bedford-Stuyvesant section of Brooklyn on most afternoons _
street vendors hawking gloves and sweatshirts, music flowing from
the open doors of stores onto the sidewalks _ the sound of learning
can easily go unnoticed.
</P>
<P>
   But it is there, tucked away in a second-floor corner of an
aging shopping plaza, in the Score Educational Center. Inside,
children raise their hands excitedly to ask questions or to point
out their completion of a lesson in math, spelling or reading. They
listen attentively through headphones connected to computers. Once
in a while, a student shoots a ball at a basketball hoop as a
reward for scoring at least 90 percent on a lesson.
</P>
<P>
   The center's interior, crammed with computers, posters of
athletes and snapshots of children's smiling faces, is little
different from the hundred or so other after-school centers run by
Score, a division of Kaplan Educational Centers, or from the dozens
of similar for-profit tutoring centers run by competitors like
Sylvan and Huntington in strip malls in well-to-do suburbs across
the country.
</P>
<P>
   What is unusual is the fact that a Score center even exists in
Bedford-Stuyvesant. It is one of the city's poorest neighborhoods,
and although schoolchildren there lag far behind academically,
their parents are generally less able to afford tutoring than
parents elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   But Kaplan says the center is profitable because of a unique
arrangement: It is a joint venture with the nonprofit
Bedford-Stuyvesant Restoration Corp., the country's oldest
community development group, which paid for improvements to the
office space in Restoration Plaza on Fulton Street and receives
half of the center's profits. The two groups see the center as a
model for similar neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   At $80 per month, tuition is 25 percent less than what Score
charges at most of its centers around the country and about half
the rate charged at some of its centers in Manhattan. For that sum,
students get two hourlong sessions a week, during which they
complete an increasingly challenging set of study assignments in
basic academic subjects.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the lowered rates, Robert Waldron, chief executive of
Score, says he was far from certain how Bedford-Stuyvesant would
respond to the center. In an area of the city where the median
household income is $19,300 a year, the Score tuition accounts for
5 percent of the average family's monthly earnings.
</P>
<P>
   The weight of that expense is not lost on parents. ``People
sacrifice to bring their kids here,'' said Beverly Torbert, a
neighborhood resident whose four children have participated in the
Score program since it opened in Bedford-Stuyvesant in October
1998. ``But they are rushing to join. That means this is a
community that needs something like this.''
</P>
<P>
   On most afternoons and Saturdays, the center is overflowing.
``It's more successful than we imagined,'' Waldron said. ``We want
to build more like it. The fact that we've been able to earn a
profit on the center will allow us to spread the idea to other
communities.''
</P>
<P>
   The center has become profitable for Score _ nearly as
profitable as centers where the company charges higher tuition
rates, Waldron said _ because more than 450 students have signed
up, 50 percent more than at the average Score center. In fact,
Score has had to restrict membership, allowing new students to join
only when current students resign.
</P>
<P>
   That Score ended up in Bedford-Stuyvesant was a result of a
fortuitous meeting of the minds between the leaders of the
restoration corporation and Score. Roderick Mitchell, president of
Bedford-Stuyvesant development group, said the organization
recruited Score after a former board member talked about his
child's experience in a center near San Francisco, Score's home.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``We were concerned that all of the Score locations were in
well-to-do communities,'' Mitchell said. ``But we were able to
convey that poor people and middle-class black people have as much
of a vested interest as anyone in making sure their kids are
prepared academically.''
</P>
<P>
   They found a willing listener in Waldron. After graduating from
Northwestern University, Waldron went to work on Wall Street in
Morgan Stanley's public finance unit, where his clients included
the New York City Board of Education. At the same time, he
volunteered at Covenant House, the shelter for homeless teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   Waldron's essay in application to Harvard Business School
focused on his desire to create and run a for-profit education
company. After graduation, he went to work for Kaplan, which bought
Score and put him in charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking to take a portion of what we do and try to give
something back to a community that needed it,'' Waldron said. ``To
the credit of Restoration, they said we don't want you to come here
unless you do it as a for-profit entity. They needed a business
that would come into the community and stay here.''
</P>
<P>
   The success of the center has been infectious, he said, with
some local businesses, including Consolidated Edison and Allstate,
recently donating scholarships for 15 children.
</P>
<P>
   Score is far from the only company in the business of providing
after-school tutoring and learning programs. Huntington Learning
Center, based in Oradell, N.J., operates centers across the
country, including three in Manhattan, which offer instruction to
help students reach grade-level abilities in various subjects. In
Baltimore, the city pays for a program for children from low-income
families to work with Huntington tutors.
</P>
<P>
   Sylvan Learning Centers also operates after-school centers and
contracts with school districts to offer tutoring services in the
schools. One such program operates at Morris High School in the
Bronx. Those programs, which operate under Title I, the federal
program that provides education money for poor children, are also
offered free to students.
</P>
<P>
   While its competitors' programs are largely based on individual
tutoring services, Score depends on a self-paced computer
curriculum. Its centers are staffed by three full-time employees
plus additional assistants, usually college or high-school
students, who answer questions, check progress and distribute
rewards.
</P>
<P>
   For children in a poor neighborhood who are bombarded with
advertisements for dot-com this and that but who are unlikely to
have computers at home, the appeal of getting to work on new
computers at a center like Score cannot be underestimated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like how they teach you on a computer,'' said Bernard
Gifford, a fourth- grader at Public School 282 in Park Slope,
Brooklyn. Bernard, who visits the Score center with his brother,
Bradley, said the work had helped him improve his test grades.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to just fill in any answers on tests,'' Bernard said.
``Now I think about it more. And I used to not like reading, but
now I do like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Parents express much the same sentiment. Benjamin Simmons, a
Crown Heights resident, said his daughter, Dajanee Miskedini, a
fourth-grader at the Holy Rosary School in Bedford-Stuyvesant, was
struggling in math before she started visiting the Score center.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this first quarter, she did better in math than she's ever
done before,'' Simmons said. ``Partly, that's because she gets
motivated here. She loves to come here. Her homework is better, and
she's enthusiastic to go to school. It's been a blessing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
