<SLUG> BC-SRILANKA-ELECT-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIOLENCE RAGES ON AS SRI LANKA ELECTS A PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Subs 2nd graf to update with voting results thus far) 
(DW) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOMBO, Sri Lanka _ Buffeted by one of Asia's most persistent
and ingenious insurgencies, Sri Lankans voted in large numbers on
Tuesday in a presidential election whose candidates offered little
real hope of peace.
</P>
<P>
   With results from half the polling stations counted on
Wednesday, President Chandrika Kumaratunga led her main challenger,
Ranil Wickeramasinghe, by about 7 percent of the vote after a
campaign that was overwhelmed by a surge of violence.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of themselves, the guerrillas may have created a
sympathy vote for the president, who was wounded Saturday in a
suicide bombing that took at least 24 lives.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, a second explosion killed 12 people at an
opposition rally on the other side of town. A total of 187 people
were wounded. The guerrillas, who are members of the country's
Tamil ethnic minority, are fighting for an independent homeland.
</P>
<P>
   The attacks brought home to the capital a distant war in the
northern Jaffna Peninsula, where the insurgents, the Liberation
Tigers of Tamil Eelam, have been fighting for 16 years.
</P>
<P>
   Storming back onto the offensive after a pause of a year and a
half, the insurgents in the last seven weeks have retaken much of
the territory captured by the army in 1995 and 1996. Retrained and
resupplied, they have augmented their well-practiced guerrilla
tactics with devastating artillery barrages.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, 500 government troops have been killed as the
guerrillas try to cut off Elephant Pass, Jaffna's only link to the
rest of the island.
</P>
<P>
   The offensive pushed aside issues of economic hardship and
galvanized an election campaign that Mrs. Kumaratunga called in
October, one year before her term was up, in the full expectation
of an easy victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were plenty of issues to begin with, but the principal
issue now is on the battlefield,'' said Saravana Muttu, who heads
the Center for Policy Alternatives, an independent policy group.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts say the attempt on Mrs. Kumaratunga's life,
which sent shrapnel into her face and left her with a white patch
over her right eye, may have improved her chances in the close
presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was leading when the election started, but by the time the
bomb went off she was losing,'' said Kingsley da Silva, executive
director of the International Center for Ethnic Studies, a private
organization that seeks to find formulas for conflict resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Such suicide attacks are a vivid demonstration of the commitment
of the Tamil separatists, many of whom are young women and many of
whom carry cyanide tablets in case of capture.
</P>
<P>
   Similar campaign-rally attacks attributed to the Tamil
insurgents have killed other Sri Lankan politicians, as well as a
former Indian prime minister, Rajiv Gandhi, in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Either because she was recuperating or because she feared an
attack, Mrs. Kumaratunga did not travel to her polling place just
outside the capital Tuesday but had her ballot papers flown in by
helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the electoral process, and disdaining even to comment on
it directly, was a man who over the years has become a leading
figure in Sri Lankan affairs, the guerrilla leader Vellupillai
Prabhakaran, 45. He has a reputation as a man who ``thrives on
war,'' and he is said to inspire the movement's suicide bombers.
</P>
<P>
   With Prabhakaran apparently uninterested in compromise, neither
of the leading presidential candidates has offered a creative or
persuasive approach to resolving the long-running conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Since the war began in 1983, it has taken more than 60,000 lives
and displaced perhaps a million people in this nation of 18
million. Total defense spending has been estimated to consume as
much as one-fourth of the national budget. Tourism, foreign
investment and domestic industry have all suffered.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Kumaratunga came to office four years ago on a wave of
euphoria with a promise of peace. But her early overtures to the
rebels made little headway and were replaced by what some analysts
now say was an over-ambitious, over-extended military campaign that
was distorted and weakened by the government's political agendas.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the president's promises of peace, da Silva said, ``If
you look at the number of soldiers killed in the whole war, 4,000
were killed before 1995 and almost double that since then.''
</P>
<P>
   The president now proposes a constitutional amendment that would
offer greater freedoms to the Tamils in the northeast. But the
amendment is general in its terms and unlikely to offer concrete
solutions, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Her chief opponent, Wickeramasinghe, has taken a more
conciliatory line, offering a pause in the fighting and the
possibility of talks. But Prabhakaran has in the past rejected more
generous peace-making overtures, including those of Mrs.
Kumaratunga.
</P>
<P>
   The Tamils are in a minority of just 3.2 million, but they have
close links to a far larger Tamil population just a few miles
across the sea in southern India, where they benefit from sanctuary
and financial support.
</P>
<P>
   Their grievances run deep, with roots in the British colonial
administration that favored the Hindu Tamils as bureaucratic
administrators.
</P>
<P>
   With independence in 1948, the mostly Buddhist Sinhalese, who
make up 74 percent of the population, struck back, imposing
discriminatory laws, making Sinhalese the national language and
withdrawing the citizenship of hundreds of thousands of Tamils.
</P>
<P>
   It is a conflict as deep and intractable as that of Northern
Ireland, said da Silva, and one that requires the kind of
painstaking, drawn-out negotiations that produced a peace agreement
there.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, he said, no one seems ready to take a deep breath
and seek real compromise.
</P>
</TEXT>
