<HEADLINE>
CHILDRENS GIFTS STOLEN FROM HOMELESS SHELTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LISA VAN PROYEN 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; NORTH HOLLYWOOD _ Bah, humbug! Grinch burglars stole $1,000
worth of Christmas gifts from a North Hollywood homeless shelter
that were intended for needy children in the San Fernando Valley
area of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, police officers played Santa Claus by dropping off
125 toys donated by their fellow officers, businesses and resident
``When you're stealing from those in need, it's truly a crime of
great magnitude. That's the lowest, meanest, most insidious type of
crime you could commit,'' said Jeffrey Farber, assistant director
for the Los Angeles Family Housing shelters.
</P>
<P>
   Burglars broke into the Los Angeles Family Housing Corp.'s
shelter sometime between 6 p.m. Dec. 10 and 8 a.m. Dec. 13,
stealing approximately 60 unwrapped toys that had been collected
for a month for 4.
</P>
<P>
   And now, as Christmas Day approaches, some of the same North
Hollywood Division officers who are investigating the crime are now
collecting donated toys.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's horrible, especially this time of year with the children.
We wanted to do something to help,'' said LAPD Sgt. William Martin,
of the North Hollywood Division.
</P>
<P>
   Shelter officials also are scrambling to find businesses and
others to donate replacement toys particularly for the
newborn-to-4-year-old age category. The gifts that were stolen were
for this age group, Farber said.
</P>
<P>
   And the message to the burglars: ``Be a caring adult and give us
our things back so these kids can have them for Christmas. You can
do this anonymously,'' said Steve Spence, director of security for
the shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Rosemary Madrid, 36, lives at the shelter with nine children who
range in age from 11 months to 19 years old. Some of them would
have received the gifts that have now been stolen.
</P>
<P>
   ``For these kids here, this is what they're looking forward
to,'' the mother said.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, the shelter threw a Christmas party with
Santagreeting the children. It marked a milestone for one of
Madrid's sons, who previously did not believe in Santa.
</P>
<P>
   ``He ran to Santa and gave him a big hug and later told me,`
`Mom, there is a Santa!''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She also had a message for the thieves: ``Have a heart and
return those gifts, because it's not only the parents, but the kids
that they're hurting. For a lot of families, this is their first
Christmas in a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said there was no sign of forced entry into the
building where the gifts were kept.
</P>
<P>
   Shelter officials believe someone not employed by the shelter or
staying there entered through a door that was possibly left ajar
before grabbing the gifts, which included a 3-foot-tall stuffed dog
and giant red Mickey and Minnie Mouse dolls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe that it was one of our employees or clients
because they help us make up the Christmas baskets and they know
how important it is,'' Farber said. ``For a lot of people here,
their last Christmas was spent in a car or camped out on someone's
living room floor.''
</P>
<P>
   The shelter tries to provide a home-like atmosphere for the
clients, giving each child at least one toy, employees said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to give them all the wonderful spirit and
treasures of the holiday,'' said Ann Jacobus, executive director of
the shelters.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the toys would have been delivered to the infants living
at the shelter, which provides food, shelter and support services
to 68 homeless families, including about 160 children.
</P>
<P>
   Shelter officials said they are determined to match the gifts
that were stolen, no matter how hard they must work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll do it one way or another. I think there's a special
circle of hell reserved for people who steal toys from homeless
people at Christmastime,'' Jacobus said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
