<HEADLINE>
SONICS CAN'T KEEP PACE WITH HOT-SHOOTING INDIANA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ There are the old Indiana Pacers. Then there are
(BEGIN ITAL) these (END ITAL) Indiana Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the Sonics, the refined Pacers were waiting at
Conseco Fieldhouse Tuesday night. And because open jump shots came
their way like early Christmas presents, the Pacers gave the Sonics
an old-fashioned thrashing from the outside.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana's well-balanced marksmanship added up to a 113-103
victory that snapped the Sonics' three-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't a game the Sonics (18-8) took lightly, unlike their
hard-fought win on Monday against Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the Pacers (16-9) appeared decrepit in the teams' first
meeting on Nov. 28, when the Sonics won 102-91 at KeyArena.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics held Pacers guard Reggie Miller to one field goal and
six points in that game. Since then, the Pacers have found a rhythm
and Miller's located his shooting touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``That loss woke them up,'' Pacers coach Larry Bird said.
</P>
<P>
   It was Miller's groove from beyond the 3-point arc that blew
apart the Sonics Tuesday. Miller sank six of 10 bombs en route to a
game-high 31 points.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana connected on 12 of 24 3-pointers in the game. Every
perimeter player who checked in for the Pacers made at least one
long-range basket.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there were times when the Sonics never rotated to
open scorers, moved too slowly or simply watched the Pacers rain
jumpers over their reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our defense sucked,'' said Sonics point guard Gary Payton, who
did his best to keep the Sonics afloat with 28 points, 12 assists
and just one turnover.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't cover our assignments the way we practiced. You'd
think we could get it right. We've only been doing this since
October. It's just something where everybody brain-locked.''
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 55-46 at halftime, the Sonics' alertness plummeted in
the second half. They struggled to keep up with Miller, Jalen Rose
and Sam Perkins _ all of whom shot high percentages.
</P>
<P>
   Miller's back-to-back 3-pointers with 6:56 left in the third led
to the Sonics' biggest deficit, 71-52. While the Sonics' offensive
execution wasn't terrible, they did little to stop the Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics trailed 85-70 when Miller began the fourth by burying
another 3-pointer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to play better defense and we, as a team, need to
rebound better,'' Sonics center Horace Grant said. ``We knew they
would play better than they did against us in Seattle. ... They
came out and played like the Pacers who made it to the Eastern
Conference Finals a couple of years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics expected Miller to free himself for good looks at the
basket. But Perkins' 19 points, which included two of three
3-pointers in the fourth, were daggers off the Pacers' bench.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, the Pacers made five consecutive 3-pointers in the
fourth. Those bombs turned the Sonics away each time they got
within 10 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really a good team that beat us,'' Sonics coach Paul
Westphal said. ``You have to give them credit. The shots that they
took and hit were not shots we wanted them to take. We didn't let
them hit 50 percent from the 3-point line, they just hit 50 percent
from the 3-point line.''
</P>
<P>
   What further exasperated the situation was the Sonics' poor
interior defense.
</P>
<P>
   They were outscored, 50-36, in the paint. Indiana's Dale Davis
and Rik Smits dominated down low. Vin Baker finished with 24 points
for the Sonics, but he had just six rebounds. Baker grabbed only
two rebounds in the second half and had none in the decisive third
quarter. He also turned the ball over six times.
</P>
<P>
   Westphal was clearly looking for better play when he pulled
Baker in favor of Jelani McCoy with 8:52 left in the third. Baker
did not return until the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   McCoy quickly parlayed his aggressiveness into two baskets and
three rebounds in 11 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Baker contends he did not take the benching as a message from
Westphal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jelani got in there and did a good job,'' said Baker, whose
defense has been suspect lately. ``At that time, he thought going
to another player (was better) and it worked out for us. It's too
early to worry about whether messages are being sent.''
</P>
<P>
   How about a small memo?
</P>
<P>
   Since starting the season 11-3, the Sonics' record is 7-5 in the
past 12 games. And all five losses have been lopsided ones to title
contenders because of _ among other things _ their flaky defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't play defense enough,'' Payton said. ``Anybody can
play offense. But we've got to play defense to win games.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Ronald Tillery can be reached at 206-448-8012 or
</P>
<P>
   ronaldtillery &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
