<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIAZZA PITCHES BIG APPLE TO GRIFFEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITAL) This week, Mets' general manager Steve Phillips
laid down the law to Mets players who may be trying to coax Ken
Griffey Jr. into reconsidering his position on a trade to New York.
</P>
<P>
   Said Phillips: ``I've made it clear that if there are any people
reaching out, they have to be careful about the tampering rules.
It's better to be ultra-conservative. No Met player, from what I
understand, has had any conversation with him at all.'' (END ITAL
</P>
<P>
   Ring. Ring. Ring. Click. Hello, you have reached the voice
messaging service for Ken Griffey Jr. He's not available to take
your call. Please leave a message at the tone. Beeeeep.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Piazza: Yeah, Junior. It's me, Mike. We gotta hook up, man.
I meant what I said last week when the TV news team caught me at
that Christmas party, wearing that stupid Santa hat. Tough to see
my new bleach-blond 'do under that thing but whaddya gonna do,
right? Can't go on camera with hat head. Not in this town.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway. Listen, man. You want a reason to come to New York, I'll
give you one.
</P>
<P>
   It's called a RING, man. Your daddy's got three and you can get
one because we're going all the way next season, baby.
</P>
<P>
   I mean, screw Bernie Williams and Derek Jeter and George
Steinbrenner. If I see Big George crying on his turtleneck during
one more World Series ceremony, I'm taking my best bat on the
uptown D train to go after him and Jim Gray.
</P>
<P>
   But like I was saying, Junior. I'll send a private jet to come
get you down there in Orlando. And don't worry about the pilot.
He's a close, personal friend of my uncle Tommy. He worked for
Valu-Jet only a short time. Otherwise, he checks out great. Call
me.
</P>
<P>
   John Franco: Ah gee, Mike! Don't bring up the private jet thing,
will ya? Gimme da phone. Let me say sumthin' to him.
</P>
<P>
   Yo, Kenny, man. This is Johnny Franco. I can understand you're
down on my hometown and you want to be close to your family and all
that, but listen. In Brooklyn, we know all about family.
</P>
<P>
   Fact of the matter is, Kenny, Billy Martin's dead. No one's
going to chase Trey out of the locker room at Shea. And when you're
winning, which we will be, all of New York is like one big, happy
family _ except for maybe Hillary and Rudy, but who gives a rat's
tail about those two Yankee-fan-wannabes, right?
</P>
<P>
   Besides, you move to New York, you can run for U.S. Senate. I'll
vote for you, man. Griffey in 2000. Just call us.
</P>
<P>
   Robin Ventura: He's not going to call.
</P>
<P>
   Newly signed free agent Todd Zeile, who actually wanted to live
in New York: He'll call. He's still buddies with Rickey Henderson.
Remember how Junior wanted the Mariners to sign Rickey last year?
Tell him Rickey wants to talk to him.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza: Let's drop it, fellas, huh?
</P>
<P>
   Ring. Ring. Ring.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza: Hello?
</P>
<P>
   Griffey: So how come the Mets didn't want me two months ago but
they wanted A-Rod and now that Olerud's left-handed bat in the
three hole's gone, the Mets suddenly want me?
</P>
<P>
   Piazza: Ken? That you, man?
</P>
<P>
   Griffey: I'm waiting.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza: Yeah, well, you know how crazy this business is.
Remember what happened to me in L.A.?
</P>
<P>
   Griffey: Still waiting.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza: Listen, Ken. Don't take this stuff personally. It's all
a game. You state your position. They wheel and deal and try and
freak you out. You sweat and dig your heels in. They do what they
gotta do.
</P>
<P>
   It's ugly. It's baseball. Let's play two.
</P>
<P>
   I mean, look at me.
</P>
<P>
   By the time I was traded to New York, I didn't know the Statue
of Liberty from the La Brea Tar Pits. I went from the Dodgers to
the Marlins to the Mets and I still wasn't sure where I wanted to
end up.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey: Well, that's not me. I'm going back to Seattle. Nuts to
Pat Gillick. Nuts to Chuck Armstrong. Nuts to Howard Lincoln. I'll
do what I want, when I want. I'm a 10-and-5-guy. They're just a
5-and-10-cent operation.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza: Now, Junior. Why you wanna go back? What's the point?
The M's aren't going to win the Series. Not with the Braves and us
and the Yankees all juiced for another run. Why not come here for a
year, find out for yourself how great this is, then ...
</P>
<P>
   Griffey: Got some unfinished business. Got to find out exactly
who in the Mariner organization called me ``a spoiled brat.'' I got
some ideas, but I'm going to have some fun nailing the sucker.
That'll keep me going.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza: Isn't there anything I can do to make you change your
mind?
</P>
<P>
   Griffey: Not unless you're talking about Cincinnati. I gotta go
now. We're on the 14th hole. Tiger and Mark O'Meara are getting
antsy. I'm making them drive with a pitching wedge while I get the
Big Bertha. My turn to hit.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza: OK. See ya.
</P>
<P>
   Click.
</P>
<P>
   Franco: What he say?
</P>
<P>
   Piazza: I have no idea.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura: He's not coming, is he?
</P>
<P>
   Piazza, scratching his head: No. And thank goodness.
</P>
<P>
