<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-TCU-EMICHIGAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TCU SHOOTS 70 FREE THROWS IN DOUBLE OT WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Launching his postgame address after a
battle with Eastern Michigan that defied several points of logic,
TCU coach Billy Tubbs was, as usual, succinct.
</P>
<P>
   ``Game ran a little long,'' he deadpanned. ``Kinda like one of
those \Rfootball\S games where you throw a lot of incomplete
passes.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the Frogs (7-4) displayed amazing marksmanship in one
crucial area _ making 56 of 70 free-throw attempts _ both figures
representing school records _ that carried them to a 107-101 double
overtime victory against the Eagles (5-3).
</P>
<P>
   TCU played the game without guard Ryan Carroll, who sat on the
bench, but has a mild case of pneumonia and could miss several
games. The Eagles finished it without five players _ including four
starters _ who fouled out.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is unbelievable,'' said EMU coach Milton Barnes, who
watched his team incur a 45-point deficit at the line, making 11 of
18. ``You're talking about 70 free throws to 18. It really does a
crime to the game, because I think both teams played hard. I've
never seen a game like this _ never heard of one.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, I'm proud of my team, and I want to thank Billy for
having us down here.''
</P>
<P>
   Tubbs, whose team leads the WAC in free-throw percentage, said
he felt the game actually ran true to form.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shoot free throws pretty well,'' he said. ``And we shot
about as well from the floor (.348 percent) as everyone else does.
They're a tough, physical team, and people have trouble shooting
against them. It's hard to shoot with 210 pounds draped over you.''
</P>
<P>
   During regulation, the Eagles outshot TCU from the field and
held a wide rebounding edge, although both figures diminished in
the late stages. For the game, Eastern Michigan outrebounded TCU,
53-49, had 21 assists to just 12 for the Frogs and had 19 more
field goals, but still lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we started fouling out,'' Barnes said, ``we got
smaller.''
</P>
<P>
   Although TCU had five players in double figures _ including
Marquise Gainous, Estell Laster and Larry Allaway with 20 each _
the Eagles led through most of the second half and seemed to have
survived a comeback by the Frogs when Craig Erquhart tied Gainous
up on the baseline with 15 seconds left in an 85-83 game.
</P>
<P>
   But Thomas McTyer stole EMU's inbounds pass and flipped it to
Allaway, who was fouled by Alvin Howard with 12.5 second left.
Allaway _ playing despite a stomach virus _ hit both shots to send
it into overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``How big was that?'' Tubbs said. ``Big big.''
</P>
<P>
   By this time, EMU's Calvin Warner (21 points, 10 rebounds) had
fouled out, but the Eagles tied the game early in the second
overtime at 92 on C.J. Grantham's two free throws with six seconds
left.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Eagles had finally run out of gas. TCU jumped
quickly to a four-point lead in the second overtime and doggedly
held on. With the score 103-101 with 30 seconds remaining, Laster
and Myron Anthony dropped in the last four free throws, and it was
finally over.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
