r s BC-FBN-HILL-COLUMN-TEX     12-22 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HILL-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE TROUBLES, GAILEY'S JOB IS SAFE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When asked recently how he copes with bad calls from the
officials _ and the Dallas Cowboys have seen more than their share
this season _ coach Chan Gailey said ``you hope you stay employed
long enough for it to even out.''
</P>
<P>
   This goes under the heading of ... since you brought it up.
</P>
<P>
   And, well, Gailey did bring it up _ his job security, that is.
</P>
<P>
   While Gailey hasn't been given a playoffs-or-else ultimatum _
the Cowboys (7-7) would qualify for the postseason by winning their
final two games Friday against the New Orleans Saints (2-12) and
Jan. 2 against the New York Giants (7-7) _ rumors have been
circulating that owner Jerry Jones is growing increasingly
dissatisfied with his team's dismal performances overall, and
offensively in particular.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Jones denied any truth to talk that Gailey's job as
head coach or offensive coordinator is on the line, and furthermore
said he regrets that the issue has even come up because Gailey
``doesn't deserve it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones did acknowledge extreme frustration with the Cowboys'
season but maintained he's not about to act punitively against his
coach.
</P>
<P>
   Jones remains supportive, despite a season that has somewhat
contradicted everything the second-year coach was supposedly hired
for _ offensive imagination and discipline.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys have demonstrated neither on a consistent basis in
1999. The offense has been predictable and unimaginative at times.
The on-field discipline is seemingly worse now than in the Barry
Switzer days, when you consider the Cowboys' league-leading penalty
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, however, said he has no plans to alter ``his'' decision
for Gailey to continue as his own offensive coordinator and play
caller. In fact, he said, it's encouraging to know that his head
coach is spending his time where the Cowboys were having their most
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Jones' continued support is based on a variety of reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, this season is far from over. The Cowboys could sweep
their final two games, make the playoffs and make a glorious run to
the Super Bowl. Though that seems unlikely, considering the Cowboys
play this season, Jones remains hopeful and refuses to think
otherwise until he has reason not to.
</P>
<P>
   And is it possible that he could rethink his position on Gailey
if the Cowboys don't make the playoffs?
</P>
<P>
   Because Jones hates losing, anything is possible.
</P>
<P>
   However, according to one Cowboys official, who certainly has
Jones' ear, the Cowboys litany of injuries in 1999 clouds the
situation. He said the injuries make it difficult for Jones to
judge Gailey. Thirteen players are on the injured reserve list,
topped b the loss of two of their top three receivers in Michael
Irvin and James McKnight.
</P>
<P>
   If you think the Cowboys' offense would be better with Irvin and
McKnight, then how can Gailey be at fault for circumstances out of
his control?
</P>
<P>
   Opposing this contention, however, are some cold realities.
</P>
<P>
   The NFC is bad and the NFC East is horrendous. Even without
Irvin, the Cowboys should be the class of the division and contend
for the Super Bowl in the wide-open, parity-filled NFC.
</P>
<P>
   It's mindboggling to most people, most notably Jones, that the
Cowboys offense, which still has running back Emmitt Smith,
quarterback Troy Aikman, receiver Raghib Ismail and one of the
league's top offensive lines, is this bad. Either Jones is wrong
that a healthy Aikman is the key to being a Super Bowl contender _
that is why he locked him to up 2007 for $85 million _ or the
offensive philosophy is wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Secondly, and potentially most damning for Gailey, is that his
offensive philosophy is not endorsed by the team's biggest stars.
Let's rephrase that, neither Irvin, Smith nor ... Aikman like the
Cowboys' offense. Irvin and Smith's disagreements with Gailey's
grand plan have already been on record.
</P>
<P>
   And while Aikman has been professional about not dissing
Gailey's offense in public, his body language and his generally
deliberate answers when talking about the offense seem to tell a
different story. And, according to a few Cowboys players, Aikman
isn't shy about voicing his displeasure behind closed doors.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, however, dismisses the bad feelings his stars have about
the offense as part of the baggage of change. He said all three
were highly successful in the Cowboys previous offense and
therefore are critical when things don't go well in a new system.
He said they will believe in this offense when they start having
more success in it.
</P>
<P>
   The question, however, is whether their lack of faith now is
part of the reason why they are not successful now. History has
shown _ 1997's 6-10 campaign _ that when Aikman and company don't
believe in something or somebody (Barry Switzer) they don't play
well.
</P>
<P>
   They certainly haven't played well in 1999. If the Cowboys don't
get on a miraculous run in the last two games, how is 1999 any
different than 1997?
</P>
<P>
   For the team or Gailey. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-22-99 0137EST &QL; 
