<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 01:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6075 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-SMITH-TEX     12-22 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-SMITH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BREAKS GOING COWBOYS' WAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The good news never stops coming for the Dallas
Cowboys this week.
</P>
<P>
   On a day in which they learned that the New Orleans Saints will
start 24-year-old rookie quarterback Jake ``The Cajun Snake''
Delhomme, who has never thrown an NFL pass, most of the players
found out Tuesday that they still have control over whether they
make the NFL playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The news from the league office that if the Cowboys win their
remaining two games, they're in, was met with a measure of reserve
by Emmitt Smith on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've controlled our own destiny all along anyway, from start
to finish,'' Smith said with a shrug. ``(This time) we've got to
take care of business.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking care of business for the 7-7 Cowboys means winning their
remaining games, against the 2-12 New Orleans Saints on Friday at
the Superdome and the New York Giants, currently 7-7, at Texas
Stadium on Jan. 2.
</P>
<P>
   But for the third week in a row, they will be facing an
inexperienced quarterback who didn't begin the season as his team's
starter: Philadelphia rookie Donovan McNabb, the Jets' Ray Lucas
and now Delhomme.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys, hovering at .500 for the fourth time this season,
are 1-1 so far in those matchups.
</P>
<P>
   Delhomme grew up in Lafayette, La., attended Southwestern
Louisiana, played two springs in NFL Europe and thinks that
spoiling Christmas (and probably the season) for the Cowboys with a
Saints victory on Friday would be great fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing spoiler,'' Delhomme said, ``that's really all we have
left for the rest of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys still have a shot at the NFC East title (depending
on what Washington does in its remaining two games against San
Francisco and Miami) but, more into the spirit of the holiday
season, the Cowboys received a gift in the form of some favorable
tiebreakers, which allow that if they win their remaining two
games, they are assured at least of one of the three NFC wild-card
bids.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we got last week was a gift, too,'' Cowboys offensive
tackle Erik Williams said with a touch of sarcasm. ``Everybody in
our division (Redskins, Giants and Cardinals) lost, and all we had
to do was go out (against the Jets) and win ....''
</P>
<P>
   When that didn't happen, the Cowboys did the next best thing.
They sat around and waited one day for the NFL's tiebreaker system
to give them control of their own destiny again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Surprised? Maybe,'' said Smith. ``But I'm not caught up in
what can happen. I'm more concerned about (improving) because we've
got some work to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys with work to do? Let us count the warts.
</P>
<P>
   Pass offense: The Cowboys rank a season-low 25th among the NFL's
31 teams.
</P>
<P>
   Touchdown passes: Only nine NFL teams have thrown for fewer
touchdowns than the Cowboys (16), and this after Troy Aikman opened
the season with a career-best five TD passes at Washington on Sept.
12.
</P>
<P>
   Total offense: The Cowboys rank 18th in the league. They've been
as low as 20th.
</P>
<P>
   Penalties: The Cowboys lead the league in both penalties (118)
and penalty yards (1,054), a dubious distinction that they've held
for most of the season. The NFL average per team is 93.8 flags for
780.9 yards.
</P>
<P>
   But it has been the ill-timed manner of these penalties,
nullifying long gains and even taking points off the board this
season, that has been more hard-felt than the total number of
flags.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had just too many penalties coming at critical times,''
said coach Chan Gailey.
</P>
<P>
   Smith is more troubled with getting the offense to work more
consistently. For example, he is concerned about what the Cowboys
have been able to do _ or not do _ on third-and-one all season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've got deeper issues than penalties,'' Smith said.
``We have yet to convert on third-and-short. That's been an issue.
That's been a problem. Then you add that on top of the penalties
... and you have what we are right now, 7-7.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion,'' Smith said, ``we haven't shown that we're a
good enough team to overcome those mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Can the Cowboys turn it around against the Saints and Giants?
</P>
<P>
   That would require the Cowboys to win back-to-back games for the
first time since they opened the season 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically against the Saints, it would mean winning on the
road for the first time since opening the season with an overtime
victory at Washington. Since that game, the Cowboys are 0-6 away
from Texas Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Also specifically against the Saints, it would mean beating a
non-divisional opponent on the road for the first time since the
1997 season opener at Pittsburgh. And it would mean paying back a
Saints team that beat the Cowboys, 22-3, just over 12 months ago in
a game in which Smith rushed 15 times for 6 yards.
</P>
<P>
   That's a lot of baggage to haul to New Orleans and back.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is no time to panic,'' Smith said. ``It's just a matter
now of going out there and doing it. That's something we haven't
done as a team, or enough on a consistent basis. How do we do that?
Where do we start? I don't have the answers to that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys, 4-7 since Oct. 10, are ready to get into the
playoffs any way possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heck, Buffalo went to the (1992) playoffs as a wild-card and
reached the Super Bowl,'' said Smith. ``The (1980) Oakland Raiders
did the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again, there is plenty of reason for hope with the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason we have hope,'' Smith said, ``is because it's not
over.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
