<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 01:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6097 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-MATCHUP-T     12-22 0503
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-MATCHUP-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOWN-TRODDEN SAINTS COULD MAKE ROUGH ROAD FOR COWBOYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ How do you spell relief?
</P>
<P>
   S-A-I-N-T-S.
</P>
<P>
   At least the Dallas Cowboys hope so. Dallas needs to win its
final two games _ at New Orleans and at home against the New York
Giants _ to be assured of a playoff berth. What better place to
begin a winning streak than in the Superdome against the miserable
Saints, losers of 11 of their past 12, on Christmas Eve?
</P>
<P>
   Well, the Cowboys aren't exactly looking past the Saints. Talk
in the locker room has focused solely on themselves and the serious
nature of this game. The Cowboys haven't won on the road since the
season opener, and fresh on everyone's mind is last December's
embarrassment in the Big Easy.
</P>
<P>
   Saints 22, Cowboys 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to take care of what we've got to do,'' said Emmitt
Smith, who was held to 6 yards on 15 carries as the Cowboys managed
8 yards of rushing in last season's meeting. ``Last year is a bad
memory. The only way to correct that is to play better.''
</P>
<P>
   The Saints muzzled the Cowboys with an onslaught of run-blitz
packages that Dallas never picked up from start to finish. Led by
defensive tackle La'Roi Glover, one of the few bright spots for the
Saints this season, New Orleans will again play to stop the run and
force the uncertain Cowboys' passing game to make something happen.
</P>
<P>
   Saints coach Mike Ditka has had nothing go right since he traded
the team's entire 1999 draft for the rights to Ricky Williams,
whose season has been riddled with injuries. Ditka said his defense
provides little confidence in holding the Cowboys down again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chances of us having a defensive game like last season are
slim and none,'' Ditka said. ``Not that we won't try. But, the
offense has to do their job, and the defense has to do their job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it would be good to stop the running game, but I don't
see that happening.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Saints' defense, which ranks 21st in the NFL, does not
inspire confidence, there's no describing their 20th-ranked
offense. Ditka said Tuesday that Williams will play, but he'll line
up behind fourth-string quarterback Jake Delhomme, a second-year
player out of Southwestern Louisiana (now Louisiana-Lafayette), and
a born Saints fan, in his first NFL game.
</P>
<P>
   This game likely will come down, again, to the Cowboys' offense.
Smith has run tough all season, so Troy Aikman and his young corps
of receivers will be responsible for taking the load off Smith.
That will be especially true when the Saints stack the line of
scrimmage and practically dare the Cowboys to beat them through the
air.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year they caught us off-balance,'' Cowboys right tackle
Erik Williams said. ``They had success doing that, so why not do it
again?''
</P>
<P>
   Said Smith: ``We still have to play our best. If we don't, we'll
be right back here singing the same old song in the same old nasty
tune.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-22-99 0150EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
