<HEADLINE>
COURT DATE NEARING FOR MAVERICKS ROOKIE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The lawyer for Dallas Mavericks rookie Leon Smith
expects to have the 6-foot-10 forward in a Chicago courtroom
Thursday morning at 9 to face three misdemeanor charges.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Berkson said Smith will leave the Dallas psychiatric
treatment center where he has been staying and fly to Chicago to
face charges of aggravated assault, violation of an order of
protection, and criminal damage to property. Those crimes are
misdemeanors punishable by fines and up to a year in jail.
</P>
<P>
   The aggravated assault charge stems from a Dec. 1 incident when
Smith approached his ex-girlfriend, Cappie Pondexter, at Chicago's
Marshall High School and allegedly threatened her with a gun. Smith
turned himself into Chicago police the next night after he
discovered there was a warrant issued for his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   He was released on bail on Dec. 3 and was arrested again after
the automobile of Vanessa Pondexter was rammed and the windows
smashed. Vanessa Pondexter is the mother of Cappie Pondexter. In
that case, Smith was charged with violating an order of protection
to stay away from Cappie Pondexter and of damage to property.
</P>
<P>
   Berkson said unless something unusual happens, he doesn't expect
Smith to be in court for more than 20 minutes. He also said the
psychiatric treatment Smith is receiving has been helpful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leon is doing better,'' Berkson said. ``He's progressing, he's
getting treatment. That's a good sign, and it's a very encouraging
sign.''
</P>
<P>
   Berkson refused to admonish the Mavericks for their alleged
shabby treatment of Smith, which included keeping him away from the
team's veteran players who possibly could have assisted him in his
transition from Chicago's Martin Luther King High School to the
NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they were sensitive to his needs in the
beginning,'' Berkson said. ``I think they probably should have
understood Leon a little more than they did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand that there's certain expectations when they draft
people. It's probably just the wrong team that he got picked by.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Smith walked out of a players' assistance aftercare
treatment facility in Atlanta in November _ combined with his two
arrests _ the Mavericks suspended him indefinitely without pay on
Dec. 6. Thus, those bimonthly $37,500 paychecks Smith was receiving
have been terminated until further notice.
</P>
<P>
   Berkson said he's sure Smith is in a financial bind, especially
since he has no source of income because of the suspension.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing Leon has going for him is he has insurance, and
he's being covered,'' Berkson said. ``The National Basketball
Players Association certainly isn't going to abandon him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The direct needs that he has now, as far as his
hospitalization, that's covered. (But his rent payment) is another
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   After Smith's court appearance, Berkson hopes to have Smith out
of Chicago and back in the psychiatric treatment facility as
quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Smith was raised in five different Chicago group rooms and was a
ward of the state of Illinois from age 4 through 18. He was
abandoned by his parents at age 5, and has said he has a difficult
time trusting people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know a lot of people are pulling for Leon,'' Berkson said.
``I told him, `There are millions of people who would like to be in
your position.
</P>
<P>
   `` `So, no matter how bad you think your position is, there's an
awful lot of people that would change places with you.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
