<HEADER>
A6103 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-BLAZERS-ROCKETS-H     12-22 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLAZERS-ROCKETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Public enemy No. 1 was running through his usual menu of assists,
rebounds and steals. With Rockets fans pouring derision like beer
at a frat party, Scottie Pippen had helped send the Trail Blazers
to a fast start and seemed to relish the boos that provided the
soundtrack for his every move.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Suddenly, he shot as if he were still wearing Rockets stripes.
He was Bobby Knight on a hunting vacation. He missed six straight,
including his first four in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets were poised to take a stunning and emotional win.
</P>
<P>
   But with the game on the line, the guy with six NBA championship
rings pulled up to nail a pair of jumpers, the second a crushing
trey. And the young Rockets, who had swept past the Trail Blazers
all night, were blinded again by the scoreboard's glowing ``4'' as
Portland coolly pulled away for an 89-79 win Tuesday night before
16,285 in Compaq Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's that Four Tops song?'' Rudy Tomjanovich lamented of the
latest fourth-quarter fold. ``It's The Same Old Song.''
</P>
<P>
   But the next line might have been just as telling because it
spoke of `` since you've been gone.''
</P>
<P>
   In his return, Pippen could not dominate any more than he could
in his abbreviated Rockets run. But unlike the crucial moments of
his failed season in Houston, with the Rockets within two with 4:55
left, he made consecutive shots.
</P>
<P>
   They were his first field goals since the first quarter, but
they staked the Trail Blazers to all the scoring they would need.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scottie is not a stand-still shooter,'' Rockets forward Matt
Bullard said. ``He hit both on pull-ups.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really close. We play well for 3{ quarters. But the way
the NBA game is, at the end of the game, you have to have a go-to
thing. We're still trying to figure out what our go-to thing is. In
the process, we're making bad mistakes that lose us the games. It's
not one person. It's the whole team.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Francis disagreed. He said it was not the whole team.
Francis blamed himself.
</P>
<P>
   But Francis was hardly reckless. He had two fourth-quarter
turnovers. He had the ball once as the shot clock expired.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last 8{ minutes of the game, the Rockets made just
one field goal, a Francis breakaway layup. Cuttino Mobley had
nailed a trey with 8:48 left to pull the Rockets within 76-74.
Francis' layup brought them back to within two with 4:55 left.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you need to get a shot, when you're down five points with
four minutes left, we make turnovers, offensive fouls, things that
winning teams don't do,'' Bullard said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets had committed six turnovers in the first six minutes
of the fourth quarter. Then after Francis' basket, the Rockets
missed their last six shots, scoring only on two Bullard free
throws with 3:24 left.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Thomas, who played the entire fourth quarter in place of
starter Carlos Rogers, missed a 3-pointer. Francis missed a pair of
jumpers and a trey.
</P>
<P>
   Mobley had burned Pippen throughout the night, scoring 20 points
off the bench. But the Blazers shifted Stacey Augmon to defend
Mobley.
</P>
<P>
   Augmon had been cut by the Rockets after coming over in the
Pippen trade, but he held Mobley scoreless in the last eight
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mobley was putting on a performance tonight,'' Blazers coach
Mike Dunleavy said. ``He was making plays and shots that you don't
see every night. I thought ultimately Stacey did a pretty good job
on him.''
</P>
<P>
   For most of the fourth quarter, Mobley hardly could get a shot.
In the last two minutes, Mobley drove to the rim but couldn't get a
roll. He missed a 3 from the corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had wide-open shots and didn't knock them down,''
Tomjanovich said. ``They came down and made two wide-open shots,
and the dam broke.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes our emotions distract us and cause us to have costly
turnovers. It's hard for the young guys to make the big play at
clutch time. We can't get distracted at the end of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth quarter, the Rockets made just three of 10 shots,
taking away their chances at an upset with eight turnovers in the
period. Their 11 fourth-quarter points were their fewest of a
season overloaded with late collapses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely turned the ball over at the end of the game,
especially me,'' Francis said. ``We've got to hit shots. A lot of
us missed a lot of shots. If we hit one or two of those shots, we
would have won the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``They played aggressive. We took good shots. Coach commended us
on taking open shots. The fourth quarter is definitely clutch time.
We have to learn to step up and hit those big jump shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you would have told me Scottie Pippen was going to come
down and hit back-to-back shots in transition, I would never have
believed that.''
</P>
<P>
   And Francis wasn't even around last season. Those who filled the
arena to send Pippen a message left hoarse and stunned, frustrated
by Pippen again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew the fans were going to get on me, but I tried to stay
focused on what our team needed to do,'' Pippen said. ``They were
taunting me. I really didn't say anything to the fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans made it fun for me. I like playing in an atmosphere
like this. It was like playing in the Finals.''
</P>
<P>
   It was as close as the Rockets have come lately. But in that
respect, at least Pippen did deliver on the promise to bring them
there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
