<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-FLAMES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS MOVE UP IN STANDINGS WITH TIE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALGARY, Alberta _ A lot was riding on Tuesday night's game for
the Dallas Stars.
</P>
<P>
   With St. Louis easily handling Phoenix, the Stars had a chance
to jump into a tie with the Coyotes for first place in the Pacific
Division. All they had to do was beat Calgary.
</P>
<P>
   Easier said than done.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars instead had to settle for a 0-0 tie as the two goalies
combined to make 63 saves. The tie gave the Stars one of the two
points they desired and jumped them into a second-place tie in the
division.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only positive is we jumped over a couple of teams
tonight,'' Stars forward Mike Keane said. ``And, hey, a tie is
better than a loss.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars were able to get that much out of the game because of
goalie Ed Belfour. He finished with 31 saves, including five in
overtime. They weren't able to get anything more because of Flames
goalie Fred Brathwaite. He finished with 32 saves, including three
in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought both goalies had full control of the game,'' Stars
coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``I think it's a good tie.''
</P>
<P>
   Overtime, just like the game, turned into an exchange of quality
chances, but the goalies weren't going to let anything by them.
Stars winger Brett Hull finished with a game-high eight shots. The
Stars' first line with Hull, Mike Modano and Kirk Muller had 17.
</P>
<P>
   They just couldn't score.
</P>
<P>
   ``You rely on Brett Hull to get the goal, and he doesn't get
it,'' Hull said. ``I think that's what is frustrating to me right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Flames had 11 shots in the first period, including a number
of near misses where if Belfour hadn't done the amazing or slid
into spots he really had no business of getting to Calgary would've
left the first period with a two- or three-goal lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``He, like all season, was our best player,'' Stars center Guy
Carbonneau said.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour wasn't supposed to start. Hitchcock had decided to go
with backup Manny Fernandez. But when a knee bruise sidelined him,
it was back to Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour looked sharp despite playing in his third game in five
nights. He had to be.
</P>
<P>
   He made his third consecutive start and he stayed pretty busy in
the first period.
</P>
<P>
   But the Stars returned the favor in the second period,
outshooting the Flames 13-5. Hull had five shots. Brathwaite
followed Belfour's lead, though, stopping a number of good Stars
chances. Their best ones came on a 5-on-3 early in the period, but
the power play was stalled when referees whistled defenseman Darryl
Sydor for interference.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars received another power-play chance at 13:58 of the
third period. But while generating a lot of good shots, the best a
whistler by Hull, they failed to score.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars came into Calgary riding an 8-2-1 streak in their past
11 games. The Flames were riding a streak of their own, undefeated
in their past five games at the Canadian Airlines Saddledome.
</P>
<P>
   And while the Stars didn't win, they didn't lose.
</P>
<P>
   The tie enabled them to leapfrog Los Angeles and Anaheim in the
standings.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad considering the Stars began the day in last place in the
Pacific Division and were playing without two of their best players
for a second consecutive game.
</P>
<P>
   ``A tie is always better than a loss, especially with all the
stuff we've had happen,'' Carbonneau said. ``We lost our captain
and were playing without (Joe Nieuwendyk), and we still managed to
make a move in the standings.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
