<HEADER>
A6107 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     12-22 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DaleRobertson
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
THE problem was, Scottie Pippen came ``home'' wearing the wrong
uniform. Had the Rockets sent him someplace bad, like back to
Chicago, there might have been more satisfaction to be gleaned from
jeering him every time he touched the ball.
</P>
<P>
   However, since everybody suspected from the outset Pippen's new
team, Portland, was going to prevail, the catcalls rang hollow.
Pippen, taciturn except for an occasional smug smile, ignored the
dogged harassment, played with his usual lack of overt passion or
emotion and, as fate would have it, scored the fatal five points
that squelched the Rockets' final rally. Hence, the big creep
laughed last.
</P>
<P>
   Trail Blazers 89, Rockets 79. The beat _ and beatings _ go on.
``The same old song,'' Rudy Tomjanovich called Tuesday night's
predictable, repetitive lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the Rockets did Pip the Drip a huge favor to ship him
out of town. At least the players they obtained for him _ Carlos
Rogers and Kelvin Cato _ who participated in the game outscored him
18-13 and outrebounded him 15-8. Small consolation, but consolation
nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot of fun,'' Scottie said of the predictable barrage
of taunts and barbs and smattering of audible obscenities, plus the
obligatory ``vacuum cleaner'' chant. ``The fans made it fun for me.
As a player, that's something you look forward to. You want to rise
to the occasion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't like you,'' one guy shouted at Pippen during a
timeout with a little more than three minutes left, prompting a
smirk from Scottie, who again is pulling down almost $15 million
for being exactly the same kind of role player he had been for the
Bulls and was last season for the Rockets. Except in Portland,
which is wallowing in talent, he can afford to be a pure-platinum
cog, a luxury sprocket, in the machine. Although the Blazers have
hardly been sizzling of late, don't be too surprised if Pippen, the
fink, doesn't cop a seventh championship ring come June.
</P>
<P>
   He is a perfect fit there, since Mike Dunleavy hardly needs,
wants or expects him to be The Man. His merely being a man, a tall
order sometimes for Scottie, will suffice.
</P>
<P>
   His line for the evening _ 13 points, eight rebounds and,
according to the stat sheet, eight assists _ should have looked all
too familiar to the Rockets and their tortured customers. It was a
typical Pippen performance, and plenty good enough for him to
contribute sufficiently to a winning cause in Portland.
</P>
<P>
   He is being paid like a super-duper star, yet he remains a
complementary player, if not in the case of his ex-teammate and
ex-friend, the fallen Charles Barkley, a complimentary one.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may not be the greatest go-to guy in the world,'' the
diplomatic Dunleavy says. ``If I'm going to start a team and pick
one player, there are a lot of others I'd pick. But he has the
ability to make all your guys go-to guys. He makes everybody
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Hmmm.
</P>
<P>
   Until Pippen sank back-to-back jumpers, the latter one a
3-pointer, with just inside of five minutes to go, he was 3-for-10
and hadn't made a field goal since the first quarter, when he went
3-for-4. But the Rockets had opted not to go straight at him with
Cuttino Mobley at the outset, keeping Matt Bullard in the starting
lineup instead, and Scottie's tank was full when money time began.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen's first bucket answered a Kenny Thomas miss that would
have tied the score at 79, and the second erased his oh-fer on the
night from beyond the arc.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even rub it in their (the fans') faces, did I?'' he
said of his bang-bang kill shots. ``I just kept playing like I had
all night. It's about us winning, not about the fans. We came here
to win, and we did.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets, whose points-to-turnovers ratio in the fourth
quarter was a dreadful 11-8, were done. Their finishing skills, as
they lurch into the painful process called rebuilding, are
nonexistent. They don't even suspect how to win when the tension
takes hold, which is why they stand (so to speak) 8-18, a ``pace''
that will leave them 25-57 and safely buried in the lottery mix
when April 19 mercifully rolls around.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great experience for these (young) guys,'' Rudy T said,
spinning for all he was worth. ``There's got to be some pain for
there to be a gain. It's not just in weightlifting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're losing our focus. We're making some bad decisions. But
we're doing some great things, too, to get in a position to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Or not to, as is most often the case.
</P>
<P>
   And were Pippen still a Rocket, the Rockets would still be going
nowhere fast. It is better for all parties that he was just passing
through, a good idea that begat insufficient results. Just the
same, might I take this opportunity to add one final booooo!!! on
behalf of the entire city of Houston?
</P>
<P>
   There. Everybody feel better?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
