e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (ATTN. EDITORS: FOR THOSE DESIRING A SHORTER VERSION, THIS ARTICLE
OFFERS TWO EDITOR-FRIENDLY OPTIONAL TRIMS, TOTALING 625 _ AT 575
(475 WORDS) AND 1,075 (150 WORDS). TOTAL OF UNCUT VERSION IS
1,350.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Defeated armies, like the Russians who limped out of Chechnya in
1996, eventually work out where they went wrong and _ as the
unfortunate Chechens are now discovering _ try to do better next
time.
</P>
<P>
