<SLUG> BC-GLOBAL-MARKETS-MILLENNIUM-RESEND-WORTH-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FUNNY THING HAPPENED ON THE WAY TO THE MILLENNIUM: PROSPERITY  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN. Business Editors: Looking ahead to 2000...)   (RESENDING from Dec. 1 for those needing Millennium copy!)  
  
 (This 650-word ``separate-buy'' financial story is from the
December issue of ``WORTH'' magazine. To publish this article, it
must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been filed into the ``f'' financial
news, ``i'' international news and ``a'' domestic/general news
files.)  
  
 By TODD G. BUCHHOLZ  
 c.1999 Worth Magazine  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A funny thing happened on the way to the millennium: prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   The world's economies grew stronger, not weaker. After a
disastrous 1998, when Asia imploded and Russian assets evaporated,
most pros bet that 1999 would be another year of global gloom.
Prominent brokerage houses forecast a recession in the U.S. _
wrongly.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest risk to the world economy today is not recession but
excessive growth, which spurs central bankers to apply higher
interest rates as a brake. At the end of October, the U.S.
Department of Commerce reported that gross domestic product grew
4.8 percent in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Take that, prophets of doom!
</P>
<P>
   Around the world, prospects may not be as uniformly sunny, but
there's plenty of good news. Japan, for example, is finally getting
off its knees. Last winter, the Nikkei still looked sick at 14,000
or so (about a third its 1989 peak), and the GDP was actually
shrinking.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Nikkei has gained 36 percent through October (in
U.S.-dollar terms). The government has cut income taxes, and
Japanese CEOs have started trimming fat payrolls.
</P>
<P>
   In October, Nissan and Mitsubishi announced major restructuring
deals in order to attract foreign investors and achieve
profitability.
</P>
<P>
   As Japan grinds forward, it will pull its neighbors along with
it. South Korea, Indonesia, and Malaysia have already bounced back.
</P>
<P>
   The benchmark stock indexes of South Korea and Indonesia have
jumped, respectively, about 48 percent and 45 percent through
October. Even Malaysia, which panicked and placed capital controls
on foreign investors, has enjoyed a 28 percent gain.
</P>
<P>
   The 1997-98 crisis created a lot of wreckage, but it also forced
banks to allocate credit more efficiently, rather than on the
nepotistic basis of who owes a favor to the prime minister's
brother-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   When Asia collapsed in 1997-98, global commodity prices
collapsed, too. The stock prices for such leading Canadian
companies as Inco, the world's largest nickel producer, fell down
the mine shaft.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the Commodities Research Bureau commodity price index
plunged almost 20 percent. But in the past six months, stronger
Asian economies _ which buy raw materials from countries like
Canada _ have lit a fire under commodities and under Canadian
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Europe has not done so well. Because the new euro began the year
with a belly flop that wiped out 12 percent of its value, most U.S.
investors have not made money on euroland stocks.
</P>
<P>
   This will change if the new European Central Bank, which to date
looks more like a rabble than a coherent group of decision makers,
achieves some credibility in its second year.
</P>
<P>
   Even though economies are recovering there and GDP is likely to
grow faster than 2 percent in 2000, big question marks hang over
the continent.
</P>
<P>
   Latin America is not yet a clear winner, either. In June, I
warned that the Mexican market had jumped too high too quickly and
was due for a big pullback. In May it was up 65 percent for the
year, while at the end of October it was up only about 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Latin America is plagued by Y2K fears, as well as political
tremors. Mexico will hold a presidential election in 2000, and
though it should be peaceful, investors remember the disaster of
1994, which began with a candidate's assassination and ended with
the peso's devaluation.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the markets should be more boring in 2000 than they
were from 1997 through 1999. That's not a bad way to start a new
century.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, such boredom will be challenged by the blaring
trumpets of the U.S. presidential election. But as long as Federal
Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan stays in good health,
investors will likely shrug off the noise. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (To publish this 650-word ``WORTH'' magazine article, it must
