<SLUG> BC-LIVERMORE-RICHARDSON-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENERGY CHIEF HINTS DISCIPLINARY ACTION POSSIBLE AT LIVERMORE LAB
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By BERNADETTE TANSEY 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ Even as he sought to boost morale at Lawrence
Livermore National Laboratory, Secretary of Energy Bill Richardson
said Tuesday some managers of a superlaser project face possible
disciplinary action for concealing delays and cost overruns from
him.
<P>
   Richardson assured employees at the lab that he would fight to
preserve funding for its troubled $1.2 billion National Ignition
Facility, but warned that problems have imperiled the project's
survival.
</P>
<P>
   The energy secretary swept through the San Francisco Bay Area
Tuesday trying to reassure scientists at Department of
Energy-funded defense laboratories where morale has sunk during a
year marked by spying allegations, research snags and charges of
racial discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   In a two-state tour that began at Los Alamos National Laboratory
on Monday, Richardson faced a difficult balancing act _ restoring
the Energy Department's credibility in the wake of reports that
nuclear secrets had fallen into the hands of Chinese espionage
agents, while healing rifts created by a subsequent security
crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson said he fully supported the indictment of Wen Ho Lee,
a Los Alamos computer scientist charged with mishandling classified
information.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree with the charges. They are serious,'' Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
   But the secretary also met with Bay Area Asian American groups
concerned that lab experts of Asian descent had been unfairly
singled out for scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``Asian Americans should not be racially profiled,'' Richardson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lee filed a lawsuit this week claiming federal agencies zeroed
in on him as a suspect in the Chinese spying investigation because
of his ethnicity. Lee has not been accused of sharing secrets with
another country.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson called the lawsuit ``unfounded and without merit.''
</P>
<P>
   Addressing the concerns of Livermore workers with top-secret
security clearance who now face polygraph examinations, Richardson
said the lie-detector tests will include no ``lifestyle-related''
questions and will be administered to political appointees as well
as rank-and-file scientists.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Pollaine, a physicist who designs targets for experiments
at the ignition facility, said he was relieved to learn that the
Energy Department plans to order polygraphs only for those in
intelligence, counterintelligence or those with special access to
information that would be militarily useful.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't include the run-of-the-mill nuclear designers,''
Pollaine said.
</P>
<P>
   Saying security weaknesses at the Energy Department's nuclear
weapons labs have been cured, Richardson pledged to keep the
security clampdown from creating a stranglehold over scientific
communication.
</P>
<P>
   ``This turbulent year is over,'' he said. ``We are going to
restore the balance of science and security in favor of science.''
</P>
<P>
   But in an interview with The Chronicle, Richardson acknowledged
that his promises to lab workers hinge on his ability to persuade
Congress to advance needed funding and back off on some security
mandates.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with orders from Congress that the Energy Department
interpreted as requiring polygraphs for some 13,000 workers,
Richardson scaled back the program to cover only 800 scientists
with access to nuclear secrets. But he said the Clinton
administration must seek ``cleanup legislation'' next year to
reduce the number of polygraph tests.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson said he will also seek legislation lifting limits on
the access of foreign nationals to scientific information generated
by Energy Department projects in energy research and other advanced
technical fields.
</P>
<P>
   Congress may also balk at continuing to fund Livermore's
ignition facility, where belated revelations about cost overruns of
as much as $350 million embarrassed Richardson in September.
</P>
<P>
   Calling the botched communications ``a comedy of errors,''
Richardson said disciplinary action is being considered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody has to be held accountable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Livermore lab director Bruce Tarter is among those who
reportedly knew the project was headed for trouble as far back as
June, when Richardson was assured the ignition facility was on
budget and on time.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Tarter's role, Richardson said, ``I have felt that
director Tarter has always been straight with me. He's a good
manager.''
</P>
</TEXT>
