<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NOTE: Tom Teepen's column that normally moves on Thursday is
moving a day early this week to accomodate early holiday deadlines.
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Urban sprawl can be stopped without calling out the
lifestyle police
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I mention this with some trepidation, because even to suggest we
might give a thought to the downside of urban sprawl is to be
accused of trying to call out the lifestyle police to round up
suburbanites, confiscate their cars and make them live in cities
and ride buses.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact remains that, as the U.S. Agriculture Department
recently reported, development is taking up farmland, forests and
other open space in this decade at twice the rate of the 1980s. In
the '80s, we bulldozed open land at the rate of 1.4 million acres
annually. Between 1992 and '97, some 16 million acres went to
development, a rate of 3.2 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Texas was the big loser, with 1.2 million acres gone. Some
others: Georgia lost 1 million acres, North Carolina 781,000,
Florida nearly a million, Ohio more than a half-million.
</P>
<P>
   The consequences are as you'd suppose: more cars, longer
commutes, worsened air pollution, lost family time and lost
community, frustration. And public massive resources channeled to
new roads and infrastructure, typically to the neglect of the old.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even the tentative concern over such matters that has
emerged in political discussions has excited a reaction charging
that car-hating, suburbia-bashing, anti-capitalist loonies are on
the march. It appears that an endless suburbia, spreading to every
horizon, is somehow God-given.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, of course, sprawl is the outcome -- in its current
excesses, the unintended outcome -- of quite deliberate public
policies.
</P>
<P>
   Federal FHA and veterans' loan programs subsidized suburban
development. Far more transportation money goes to new, often
speculative freeways than to public transit or the maintenance and
upgrading of existing roads. Zoning policies bar mixed-use
development and enforce low density housing. Public infrastructure
development subsidizes suburban builders, while environmental rules
makes it costly to reclaim used urban sites.
</P>
<P>
   And more: The home-mortgage tax deduction favors typical
suburban incomes and provides an incentive for bigger lots. Private
mortgage lending policies favor new suburban homes over city homes
-- and now often over older suburban homes, too.
</P>
<P>
   But mention that perhaps we ought to think about policies that
could slow sprawl and you'll be charged with trying to control
people's lives through social engineering. Well, we
social-engineered ourselves into this mess. Why it is ideologically
inadmissible to think about ways to get ourselves out of it?
</P>
<P>
   No special virtue resides in either city or suburban styles.
They needn't be at the expense of each other. Instead, a closer
coherence of development would support both. It is not an affront
to free-market values or personal choice to imagine development
that preserves countryside, requires fewer and shorter auto trips
and actually increases living options.
</P>
<P>
   Not even many suburbanites these days, steaming in their own
gridlock, would buy into their defenders' cry that the answer to
sprawl is more sprawl.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
