<HEADLINE>
AIG SAID READY TO ACQUIRE TROUBLED TRUST INSURANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A giant New York &UR;  &LR; insurance company whose operations
span the globe is interested in acquiring financially troubled
Trust Insurance Co. of Taunton, Mass., a source familiar with the
negotiations said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The source said American International Group, one of the world's
largest and most profitable insurers, is preparing to make a major
investment in Trust, presumably to take control of the company.
</P>
<P>
   The size of the investment is not clear yet, the source said,
although it would be well in excess of the $20 million proposed by
an earlier suitor, Worcester, Mass. auto dealer David ``Duddie''
Massad.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Trust nor AIG would comment Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Massachusetts Division of Insurance, whose
approval would be needed for any takeover, said the paperwork
required to complete such a transaction had not been filed.
</P>
<P>
   The source said AIG executives and state officials have
conferred, but the state agency's spokesman said he was not aware
of any meetings.
</P>
<P>
   If a deal is near, it would not only shore up a financially
ailing Bay State insurance company but presumably breathe new life
into the market for home and auto insurance in Massachusetts. Most
major national auto insurers have shunned the state since the late
1980s because of its restrictive regulatory policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``AIG entering the marketplace would be a very big event in the
Massachusetts insurance world,'' said Stephen D'Amato, a consumer
advocate on insurance matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Among insurers, AIG is a highly respected and even feared
competitor. It has a reputation for being an aggressive company
that will do what it takes to be a major force in a market. And
with local insurers cutting back on their safe-driver discounts,
AIG would be well positioned to gain market share by offering
larger discounts to drivers.''
</P>
<P>
   AIG has about 48,000 employees and a market value of $163
billion. In 1998, its most recently completed fiscal year, it
reported net income of $3.76 billion on revenue of $33.2 billion.
It sells all types of insurance, but the bulk of its income tends
to come from overseas insurance operations.
</P>
<P>
   While rumors of AIG's interest in Trust have circulated in
insurance circles for weeks, officials at Massachusetts companies
said they were puzzled why such a giant would be interested in such
a gnat.
</P>
<P>
   The source said Tuesday that AIG wants to grow its domestic auto
and homeowners insurance business and is interested in acquiring
Trust because of its network of insurance agents, which would let
AIG avoid starting from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would have a new 800-pound gorilla in town with this,''
the source said.
</P>
<P>
   Trust has been having trouble keeping its head above water
lately. The company was started in 1989 after founder Craig Bradley
left Commerce Insurance in Webster, Mass., after a dispute with
officials there. Bradley built Trust into one of the top 10
insurers in the state, but profits vanished last year.
</P>
<P>
   In May Trust said it lost $21 million in 1998; a couple of
months later, it increased that figure to $26 million. The loss was
enough to wipe out half of the company's reserves. Trust blamed
computer glitches and problems with its reinsurers.
</P>
<P>
   In October the company negotiated the terms of a $20 million
investment by Massad, only to see that deal fall apart in early
November.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors that Trust was about to fail were so strong at the time
that state Insurance Commissioner Linda Ruthardt took the unusual
step on Nov. 11 of stating that her agency ``has not concluded that
Trust is unable to meet its obligations in the normal course of
business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-22-99 1024EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991222.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 10:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6282 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-ITALY-MILLENNIUM-1223     12-22 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ITALY-MILLENNIUM-1223-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AFTER A FACELIFT, ROME PREPARES FOR CRUSH OF NEW MILLENNIUM
VISITORS
 &HT;    670 and add
 &HT;    DUPLICATION ALERT: Moving in (i) international and (l) lifestyle
categories
 &HT;    By ADAM FREEMAN 
 &HT;    c.1999 Special to Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Everyone knows that all roads lead to Rome.
</P>
<P>
   True or not, the accuracy of this proverb will be tested in this
historic capital over the next year.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 30 million Roman Catholic pilgrims are expected to
descend upon the Eternal City, arriving from all corners of the
globe to celebrate what is expected to be the Church's most
spectacular grand jubilee, its 26th. As a result, many expect that
the patience of Rome's four million inhabitants and the very fabric
of this ancient and delicate city will be tested _ if they haven't
been already.
</P>
<P>
   For more than five years, Italy and the Vatican have been
actively planning for the year-long event, which will kick off on
Christmas Eve and conclude Jan. 6, 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that it ushers in the new millennium, which coincides
with the 2000th anniversary of the birth of Jesus Christ, makes it
that much more enticing for the world's Roman Catholic's to heed
Pope John Paul II's call to bear witness in Rome and attend his
papal plenary indulgences.
</P>
<P>
   The first jubilee was called by Pope Boniface VIII in 1300 to
bring hope back to Rome after waves of plague devastated the city's
population and spirit. The event was attended by the poet Dante,
who wrote about it in his Divine Comedy.
</P>
<P>
   After suffering countless sieges and sacks by bands arriving
from all over Europe, Rome has seen its fair share of face-lifts.
This time, armed with rosaries, cash and credit cards, the expected
hordes will be far more benevolent.
</P>
<P>
   After the required stop in Rome, many are expected to spread out
through Italy to visit such noted relics as the Shroud of Turin.
The pilgrims should be welcomed with open arms _ or at the worst an
over-priced ice cream by Holy Year opportunists. Welcome or not,
visitors are expected to pump billions of dollars into Italy's
economy over the year.
</P>
<P>
   To prepare itself for the anticipated crush, Rome and much of
Italy has been making itself over. The facade of St. Peter's
Basilica, for example, has been scrubbed to a squeaky white at a
cost of $5.4 million. Elsewhere, the Basilica of St. Francis of
Assisi, which suffered severe earthquake damage two years ago, has
recently been re-opened after the 40,000 man-hours it took to
repair the exquisite 13th-century frescos attributed to Ciambue and
Giotto.
</P>
<P>
   Not all the public works have brought such pleasing results,
however.
</P>
<P>
   Every day, hundreds of thousands of commuters find themselves
entangled in bottleneck traffic, their cars and scooters collecting
dust from the myriad construction projects, most of which are far
behind schedule. During rush hour, honking is the only sound
capable of drowning out the sonorous knells from the bells in the
city's countless churches.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic has been continuously re-routed to accommodate the road
upgrading and repairs, which consume a major portion of the $950
million being spent nationwide on more than 700 improvement
projects.
</P>
<P>
   Construction plans require that new barricades be erected on an
almost daily basis. Drivers must constantly re-learn the daily
commute. For modern-day Romans, dead-ending into new construction
sites has been as routine as their morning pastry and cafe latte.
</P>
<P>
   A government-commissioned survey earlier this year stated that
7-out-of-10 public works projects may not be completed by the Dec.
31 deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Still, through all this chaos, many Romans see a light at the
end of the tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is worth it,'' said Emiliano Leonetti, who sells newspapers
and videos from a kiosk surrounded by barricades in the usually
picturesque Campo dei Fiori, a square in the historical city
center. ``We, like everyone else here have lost money, a lot of
business. Maybe 50 percent, but the work had to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Voicing what may be the Roman mantra of the day, he adds, ``It's
just too bad they decided to do it all at once.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By far the most contentious issue to surface this summer was
when workers building a ramp to a vast underground parking lot
happened upon the frescoed walls of an ancient Roman villa. The
Italian Ministry of Culture immediately halted the work until it
could be determined whether the first century villa is worth
saving.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the underground Vatican parking lot, when completed,
will be large enough to accommodate 115 tour buses and 800 cars.
</P>
<P>
   Rome Mayor Francesco Rutelli, a former leader of the Green
Party, infuriated many of his allies when he said that the ruins
constitute ``less than what is found in the average Roman's
basement.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding insult to injury, a police investigation turned up fresco
and statue fragments at a city dump, further incensing
conservationists, citizens groups and archeologists.
</P>
<P>
   Rutelli, having been accused of compromising history for a
parking lot, attempted to silence critics by saying that in Rome,
``relics are found everywhere you dig.''
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't alone. Despite the vocal protests _ including those of
Culture Minister Giovanna Melandri _ Italian Premier Massimo
D'Alema's Cabinet voted earlier this month for the ramp's
construction to be completed.
</P>
<P>
   With numerous artistic events planned for Jubilee 2000, secular
and religious visitors or residents should have little trouble
finding enjoyment in the Eternal City. New museums have been
opened, for instance, while the collections of others have been
expanded.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the frenetic activity and anticipation for the
historic millennium here, not everyone is caught up in all the hype
surrounding the year 2000 celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Daniela Benincampi's family has run a tobacco and souvenir shop
in scenic Piazza Navona since 1956. Asked what impact she expects
the Jubilee will have on Rome and her business, she shrugs her
shoulders, sticks out her chin and answers: ``Nothing, absolutely
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-22-99 1026EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
