<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 10:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6298 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-MILLENNIUM-REALITY-CH     12-22 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-REALITY-CHECK-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTENTION EDITORS: THIS PIECE MAY BE PUBLISHED ONLY BY SUBSCRIBERS
TO ``NEXT,'' A NEW COLUMN ON TRENDS FOR THE UNDER-30 CROWD, WRITTEN
BY JANE RINZLER BUCKINGHAM, PRESIDENT OF YOUTH INTELLIGENCE. FOR
INFORMATION ON BECOMING A CHARTER CLIENT _ OR TO SEE MORE SAMPLES _
CALL YOUR NEW YORK TIMES SYNDICATE SALES REPRESENTATIVE AT (888)
269-8796. EDITORS WHO SIGN UP BEFORE THE END OF THE YEAR WILL GET A
COPY OF YI'S RESPECTED ``CASSANDRA REPORT,'' WHICH FOCUSES ON
WHAT'S HOT AND WHAT'S NOT WITH GENERATIONS X AND WHY?  
 (FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE) 
 MILLENNIUM REALITY CHECK
</HEADLINE>
  By JANE RINZLER BUCKINGHAM  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The new year _ the new millennium _ is finally upon us. So what?
</P>
<P>
   Do you really expect to wake up Jan. 1 and find that you are
suddenly living a real-life episode of ``The Jetsons'' or ``Star
Trek'' ? It's doubtful.
</P>
<P>
   With so much fear of Y2K and so much angst about where to spend
Millennium Eve, many people have overlooked the fact that the Big
2000 could well be a big bust.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the real outlook for the next year, maybe even the next
century, has little to do with futuristic fantasies. If you truly
want to prepare yourself for the future, forget about robotic pets
and teleportation. Here are some of the biggest trends I see coming
_ and some of the things you'll definitely want to have for the new
millennium:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TIME AS STATUS SYMBOL &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For years we've been promised a futuristic world in which
tedious tasks would be taken care of effortlessly, enabling us to
spend our time on more enjoyable activities. While the future may
not have lived up to its promise, we are holding on to this idea.
</P>
<P>
   In our overscheduled, overstressed, on-demand world, time will
become the new status symbol. We will crave more free time and more
control over our time. Pleasurable, time-consuming activities _
such as playing golf, cooking extensive meals, even knitting _ are
quickly becoming the new symbols of success.
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM MUST-HAVE: The SAM (Secret Agent Man) watch will be a
hot way to keep track of time. This hip-looking black timepiece
from Spoon (Seiko) can store up to 100 memos and features three
alarms that can flash written reminders. Cost: about $215.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HIGH TOUCH &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it's great to be able to buy groceries over the Net at 2
a.m., and it's nice to know you can be faxed at altitudes of 35,000
feet. But along with all the benefits of technology is coming a
need for more human interaction and for products and services that
offer the personal touch, or what I like to call ``high touch.''
</P>
<P>
   Surveys done by my market-research company, Youth Intelligence,
show young people reacting against the impersonal feel of computers
and the fact that they can be reached at any moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're supposed to be more connected than ever,'' one
16-year-old from Los Angeles said, ``yet I feel like we're living
in our own worlds and missing each other.''
</P>
<P>
   As we seek personal connections and communication, E-mail usage
may actually decrease.
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM MUST-HAVE: Personalized stationery will be prized.
We'll send handwritten notes or letters when the thought ``really
counts'' and computer-generated text won't cut it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOME SWEET HOME &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After the wild partying of the millennium, we'll be ready to
take a break. For many, the world is getting scarier and more
fragmented. Young people say they are worried about where the next
random act of violence might take place.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, we'll be staying in and entertaining more _ and
turning our homes into private mini-vacation spots. This isn't just
``cocooning.'' In the next decade, home will become as interesting
a destination as the local megaplex!
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM MUST-HAVE: TiVo is a ``personal TV service'' that
offers more control over what you watch and when you watch it. It
can be programmed to record up to 30 hours worth of shows _ and
edit out the commercials. The service also enables you to activate
``slow motion'' and ``instant replay'' during live broadcasts or
receive suggestions about shows you might like, based on your
preferences.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CUSTOMIZATION &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many people today feel that the world is becoming one big
minimall. Everyone looks the same, acts the d has the same
values. To avoid this feeling of homogenization, we'll be looking
for products that make us feel special and individualistic. One
good example: Levi's ``Custom-Fit'' jeans are created for the buyer
only after his or her body has been electronically scanned and
measured.
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM MUST-HAVE: Name-plate necklaces. We'll want anything
that feels personalized _ especially things that have our names
emblazoned on them.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EXOTIC DRINKS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You may want to ring in the new year with something new in your
glass. By Dec. 31, we'll probably have had our fill of 20th-century
bubbly _ and may have suffered through one too many hangovers to
even consider ordering Champagne.
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM MUST HAVE: Mojitos and Caiparinhias are drinks
popular in South America, one of the trendiest vacation spots. Made
with lime, cachaca and sugar, they're less serious than martinis,
less expensive than Champagne. They embody the exotic spirit that
will be pervasive at the beginning of the millennium.
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; BOX: BE ON THE LOOKOUT FOR ... &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MOTOROLA TALKABOUTS (walkie-talkies with a 2-mile range)
</P>
<P>
   GO-PEDS (motorized skateboards with handlebars)
</P>
<P>
   ALEX AND ANI JEWELRY (glamorous yet inexpensive baubles)
</P>
<P>
   Jane Rinzler Buckingham is the president of Youth Intelligence,
a market-research firm specializing in the 7- to 35-year-old
market. Her company publishes the Cassandra Report, a comprehensive
survey focused on identifying emerging trends among Generations X
and Why?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-22-99 1046EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991222.0064 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 10:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6302 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-MILLENNIUM-REALITY-CH     12-22 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-REALITY-CHECK-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
