<P>
   Surveys done by my market-research company, Youth Intelligence,
show young people reacting against the impersonal feel of computers
and the fact that they can be reached at any moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're supposed to be more connected than ever,'' one
16-year-old from Los Angeles said, ``yet I feel like we're living
in our own worlds and missing each other.''
</P>
<P>
   As we seek personal connections and communication, E-mail usage
may actually decrease.
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM MUST-HAVE: Personalized stationery will be prized.
We'll send handwritten notes or letters when the thought ``really
counts'' and computer-generated text won't cut it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOME SWEET HOME &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After the wild partying of the millennium, we'll be ready to
take a break. For many, the world is getting scarier and more
fragmented. Young people say they are worried about where the next
random act of violence might take place.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, we'll be staying in and entertaining more _ and
turning our homes into private mini-vacation spots. This isn't just
``cocooning.'' In the next decade, home will become as interesting
a destination as the local megaplex!
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM MUST-HAVE: TiVo is a ``personal TV service'' that
offers more control over what you watch and when you watch it. It
can be programmed to record up to 30 hours worth of shows _ and
edit out the commercials. The service also enables you to activate
``slow motion'' and ``instant replay'' during live broadcasts or
receive suggestions about shows you might like, based on your
preferences.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CUSTOMIZATION &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many people today feel that the world is becoming one big
minimall. Everyone looks the same, acts the same and has the same
values. To avoid this feeling of homogenization, we'll be looking
for products that make us feel special and individualistic. One
good example: Levi's ``Custom-Fit'' jeans are created for the buyer
only after his or her body has been electronically scanned and
measured.
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM MUST-HAVE: Name-plate necklaces. We'll want anything
that feels personalized _ especially things that have our names
emblazoned on them.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EXOTIC DRINKS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You may want to ring in the new year with something new in your
glass. By Dec. 31, we'll probably have had our fill of 20th-century
bubbly _ and may have suffered through one too many hangovers to
even consider ordering Champagne.
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM MUST HAVE: Mojitos and Caiparinhias are drinks
popular in South America, one of the trendiest vacation spots. Made
with lime, cachaca and sugar, they're less serious than martinis,
less expensive than Champagne. They embody the exotic spirit that
will be pervasive at the beginning of the millennium.
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; BOX: BE ON THE LOOKOUT FOR ... &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MOTOROLA TALKABOUTS (walkie-talkies with a 2-mile range)
</P>
<P>
   GO-PEDS (motorized skateboards with handlebars)
</P>
<P>
   ALEX AND ANI JEWELRY (glamorous yet inexpensive baubles)
</P>
<P>
   Jane Rinzler Buckingham is the president of Youth Intelligence,
a market-research firm specializing in the 7- to 35-year-old
market. Her company publishes the Cassandra Report, a comprehensive
survey focused on identifying emerging trends among Generations X
and Why?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
