NYT-12-22-99 1048EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991222.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 10:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6312 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-LIFEINAMERICA1223-COX     12-22 1369
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIFE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 IN AMERICA 1223-COX &HT;    LIFE IN AMERICA: Utah town ripe with distinctive flavor
 &HT;    (Eds: This is another story in a series of reports on life in
small-town America _ the values, the stories and the characters _
at the end of the millennium. Photos and a sig/locator map are
available.)
 &HT;    By Rachel Sauer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREEN RIVER, Utah _ December is not the time to talk about
melons.
</P>
<P>
   Talking about melons now is just depressing because the anemic
softballs available in most grocery stores today, imported from
someplace nobody ever heard of like California, aren't Green River
melons, and that's a shame.
</P>
<P>
   No, the time to talk about melons is summer, when the fields
around Green River, Utah, are carpeted by curly, verdant vines
tangling and twisting around their treasure: honeydew and
cantaloupe and watermelon ripening in the high desert sun and
gloating with the promise of sweetness.
</P>
<P>
   Green River's got great melons. People who live here are proud
of the melons, which give the small town of 900 people something to
be known for other than being close to Moab and conveniently
situated on Interstate 70. Through more boom-and-bust cycles than
residents care to remember and current debates about county
boundaries and water and sewer lines, Green River has been the town
that grows those melons.
</P>
<P>
   And Tim Vetere is one of the guys who grows those melons. His
father began growing them in 1958, the year he was born, so his
whole life he's known about crimson sweets and crenshaws, casabas,
honeydew and cantaloupe.
</P>
<P>
   He thinks about melons year-round, planning how to plant the 60
acres on which he and his family grow melons. Even in winter, when
they're taking care of their 150 mother cows and the 250 cows they
winter for other people, he plans for the coming crop.
</P>
<P>
   The Veteres start about 90 percent of their melons in a
hothouse, transferring them to fields in April when the plants have
three leaves, then hot cap them to protect against possible freeze.
They fertilize and flood irrigate once a week, patrol the mounds of
melons for weeds and pests and watch the fruit grow. They usually
begin harvesting at the end of July, when they see signs of
ripeness: cantaloupes and honeydew cracked around the stem,
watermelon of a certain color, other subtle signs dependent on the
melon, the ground, the weather and many other factors.
</P>
<P>
   There is some debate about what makes Green River so ideal for
growing melons, ``but I think it's the way they're raised and
picked,'' Vetere said. ``They're all so fresh. And then the
temperature here's good with the warm nights. That's what makes
them really grow good: It needs to stay 65, 70 at night to make
them grow even.''
</P>
<P>
   During harvest the Veteres pick tons of melons each day, seven
days a week, and sell them to the Macy's grocery store chain and at
their stand by Westman's truck stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do good business there,'' Tim said. ``We've got people that
come through Green River and that's their whole reason to come this
way, to buy the melons.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite customers who drive hundreds of miles for the melons,
Green River melon growers are facing a market in which the price of
everything _ from fuel to farm equipment _ but melons is going up.
Vetere said he's getting a little bit less for the melons than he
was in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to compete with California, New Mexico, Arizona, all
those markets and it's pretty tough,'' he said. ``So you can see
why the price you sell for has stayed the same or gone down and
everything else has gone up.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a cycle Green River is familiar with. The town has boomed
and busted so much it has stretch marks. The town started in the
late 1870s as a settlement on the overland mail route between
Salina, Utah, and Ouray, Colo., according to Edward A. Geary,
author of ``A History of Emery County.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Denver &AMP; Rio Grande Western Railway was completed in
1883, Green River became a shipping point for livestock and mining
equipment, and the influx of railroad workers, cowboys, sheep
herders and prospectors from the Bookcliffs and San Rafael Desert
elevated the town's population to 375. However, when the railroad
moved its divisional operations to Helper, Utah, in the early
1890s, the town's population dropped by half.
</P>
<P>
   The town boomed again in 1901 when oil was discovered nearby,
but when no commercial producers moved in, the town busted again.
In 1906, land developer E.T. Merritt promoted Green River as a
fruit growing area, and dozens of farmers planted several hundred
acres of peach trees along both sides of the Green River. However,
the trees died before producing fruit. More consistent have been
the melons, which J.H. ``Melon'' Brown began growing in Green River
as early as 1900.
</P>
<P>
   The 1950s southern Utah uranium boom echoed positively in Green
River, but the town busted with the rest of the area when uranium
markets slumped.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest boom came with the 1964 establishment of the Utah
Launch Complex of the White Sands Missile Base north of town, which
brought Green River's population to nearly 2,000 before the complex
closed in the mid-1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that it took a lot of the town, a lot of people moved
out, and Green River just hasn't recovered yet,'' said Brian
Meadows, Green River treasurer.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, Green River's main industry is tourism, ``and I think
the whole strength of Green River is we're out here as an oasis,''
said Allene Spadafora, coordinator for the Green River Travel
Council.
</P>
<P>
   Green River is right in the middle of a whole lot of nothing _
107 miles to Salina, 90 miles to Grand Junction in the middle of
miles of brown, scrub brush desert ringed by the Bookcliffs and
Manti La Sal mountains _ so tired travelers get off I-70 and stop
at one of Green River's stores or stay in one of its dozen hotels.
</P>
<P>
   Spadafora said the travel council is hoping to promote the town
as more than a stop-over, but several town concerns have hindered
growth and development. The town council recently lifted a
moratorium on commercial building enacted because of worries about
the impact of development on the sewer plant and water lines.
Meadows said that during an informal voter poll at the last
election, people were in favor of supporting a new water and sewer
system.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest problem I guess we have is all the piping that
goes and feeds the water plant, it's all underneath cement, 30 feet
underground,'' Meadows said. ``That's hard to get to.''
</P>
<P>
   Another problem has arisen from Green River being a split city,
straddling Grand and Emery counties. Meadows said the city would
like to pull away from Grand County and be entirely in Emery
County, but Grand County has balked because Green River also is an
important starting point for river rafting trips and brings in
tourist dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big motels in Green River are all in the Grand County
side, but we get all our utility from Emery County,'' Spadafora
said. ``The sheriff's department and medical center and schools,
our help comes from Emery County.''
</P>
<P>
   That friction has prevented progress, Spadafora said.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever happens, Meadows said, there always will be a core
of Green River residents who stay through booms and busts, county
disputes and water line problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``People like the small-town atmosphere,'' he said. ``I think
that's probably the reason most people live here.''
</P>
<P>
   Green River residents cheer on the sports teams from Green
River's grade 7-12 school and support the elementary school, show
up for the Fourth of July parade and go all-out for the annual
Melon Days, held the third weekend in September. There's a square
dance festival, kids' games, a huge softball tournament, a talent
show, a parade and, most important, those melons.
</P>
<P>
   Green River grows great melons.
</P>
<P>
   PHOTO CAPTION
</P>
<P>
   Greg and Tim Vetere sell melons during the summer and fall from
their stand by Westman's truck stop in Green River, Utah. The
Vetere family has grown melons since 1958 and plants 60 acres of
melons each year.
</P>
<P>
   Photo by CHRISTOPHER TOMILSON / Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
