<DOCNO> NYT19991222.0068 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 10:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6314 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-SHAKEN23-TAKE1-COX     12-22 2007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAKEN23-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    (EDS: This is Take 1 of 4 takes.)
 &HT;    By Christie Evans
 &HT;    and Bruce Bennett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Five years ago, a father sat down to feed his
infant twin girls _ and something went terribly wrong. Now he's in
prison, his mother is raising his babies, and the twins no longer
match. One is healthy and smart.
</P>
<P>
   The other is broken. Michele Poole wants you to know why you
should never, ever shake a baby.
</P>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ It's dark.
</P>
<P>
   Only six people in the room.
</P>
<P>
   The table linens are red. Her suit is blue.
</P>
<P>
   Everything else is just. . . so . . . dark. The faces gathered
around the small tables are lined and worried, like the charcoal
portraits hanging in corners of museums.
</P>
<P>
   She lays her props out on a table. A doll. A plastic container.
An egg.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents Without Partners.'' She begins by repeating the
group's name. Maybe you're overwhelmed, she says. Maybe you're
stressed out. Maybe you know someone who is, and around the room,
grim faces nod.
</P>
<P>
   She hits the button on her tape recorder. A baby cries. Then
wails.
</P>
<P>
   She picks up the doll. This is how it begins, she says. Stop
crying, please. Please, stop crying. And then _ she shakes the
doll. The head jerks back and forth _ snap, snap, snap. The shaking
lasts just seconds, but just seconds, she says, is all it takes.
</P>
<P>
   Next, she holds up the plastic container. It is round, like a
head, and clear, like Tupperware. Inside: the egg. The brain.
</P>
<P>
   She shakes the container, hard.
</P>
<P>
   The egg shatters.
</P>
<P>
   This is what happens to the brain, she says. It slams against
the skull, bruises, tears, bleeds, swells, grapefruit against a
wall.
</P>
<P>
   Before anybody can say anything at all _ not that they would
know what to say, to that _ she disappears to the next room, comes
back in with one last prop. It is Gabbi.
</P>
<P>
   She looks so soft and sweet in her purple dress, like one of
those expensive American Girl dolls with the lush, dark curls and
smooth, white-china skin. ``Here you go, Gabbi,'' Michele says, and
she lifts the little girl up and lays her gently on her stomach on
a purple flowered pad on the small round table with the red cloth.
</P>
<P>
   The table is just big enough to hold her, and with an uumph,
Gabbi lifts her head and tries through her thick glasses to look
around, although she's almost blind.
</P>
<P>
   Michele strokes her curls.
</P>
<P>
   This is what you get, she says, when you shake a baby. Gabbi
can't walk, can't talk, can't sit, can't chew. Gabbi's stuck in
time, a baby forever.
</P>
<P>
   It is past dinnertime, so Michele pours Gabbi's formula into the
big syringe and lets it slip down the plastic tubing to the little
button-hole doctors made in her stomach. This is how Gabbi eats,
she says.
</P>
<P>
   It's dark.
</P>
<P>
   More people have come.
</P>
<P>
   A few are crying.
</P>
<P>
   On the table is a photograph of a little girl with fly-away hair
in a pink and white dress with flowers. Who is she? people have
been wondering.
</P>
<P>
   Gabbi's twin, Michele says. She is everything Gabbi would have
been.
</P>
<P>
   It is quiet as the single moms and dads and grandmas and
grandpas try to take this in.
</P>
<P>
   A woman raises her hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``About Gabbi,'' she ventures. ``Is this the most she will ever
_''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do?''
</P>
<P>
   The woman nods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Could be,'' Michele says. ``But maybe there's more.''
</P>
<P>
   Another hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does she know you?''
</P>
<P>
   Michele thinks so.
</P>
<P>
   ``By my voice.''
</P>
<P>
   One more hand, and in the dark the face behind it is angry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did somebody go to prison for this?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' Michele says.
</P>
<P>
   Silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, as far as Little Michele knows, when Gabbi was a
little baby, she hurt her head, and that's why Gabbi is Gabbi.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think she really understands the concept of being a
twin. She knows Gabbi's her sister, but she thinks of her as a
baby. She always asks, `When's Gabbi going to grow up so we can
play?'
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what really got to me when this thing first happened?
The doctors told me Gabbi would be a vegetable. That's precisely
the word they used. Vegetable. And I remember thinking, what kind
of word is that? My kid is not a vegetable! She's Gabbi! She's
Little Michele's twin! She's a person, not some carrot or turnip or
whatever. I mean, c'mon. Ridiculous. But that's what they said, and
then they told me anything she learned to do _ any little thing at
all _ would be a miracle.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think Gabbi has certain capabilities. I like to think we
get little miracles every day. You have to be an optimist, or
you're sunk.''
</P>
<P>
   Michele Poole, the twins' grandmother _ and, by adoption, their
mother _ is navigating her clunky van through suburbia while
keeping one eye out for a Dunkin' Donuts and the other in trview to check on the girls. It's another no-earring day, which
means when she weighed the benefit of looking nice against the few
minutes she would lose looking for and inserting a pair of
earrings, looking nice lost out. That's OK. In her world,
practicality counts. She keeps her dark hair unmercifully short
because short is easy, and if the wheelchair lift breaks, she gets
out a book and fixes it herself rather than wait on the mechanic.
</P>
<P>
   This morning, it was chaos as usual, with Little Michele
practicing her numbers and letters in the pink bedroom at the top
of the stairs _ her Shirley Temple hair flying and red nail polish
glittering as she demonstrated a few karate chops for the tutor _
and Gabbi gazing dreamily at the ceiling and listening to ``Feelin'
Groovy'' in her crib at the bottom of the stairs while Michele
changed her diaper. Then Michele jogged back up to see if Little
Michele wanted pigtails or ponytails, and then she loaded everybody
into the van, and they were off.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what makes it so hard?'' she says, turning into the
shopping center where Little Michele will have her piano lesson.
``You want to do so much for this kid, yet there is only so much
you can do. I can make some adjustments, tinker here and there. But
unless some brilliant scientist comes up with a brain replacement _
well, I do believe in miracles, but I could take Gabbi to Lourdes
and hold her little feet in the pond, and Gabbi would still be . .
. Gabbi.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes in the rearview she sees the twins sleeping, the
differences between them sweetly diminished, and she lets herself
fantasize for a moment that they are just the same, two little
girls, both happy, both healthy. But that's just fantasy. It has
been nearly five years since _ what? The calamity? The crime? The
truth is, Gabbi lost her chance the day her daddy picked her up and
shook her.
</P>
<P>
   It is startling sometimes how much people don't know. Michele
does not need surveys or studies to tell her this _ although there
are plenty of both. No, she learned about the deep pool of public
ignorance in her many informal walking tours.
</P>
<P>
   She might be in a bakery, ordering a strawberry doughnut for
Little Michele, or at the doctor's office, getting Gabbi's checkup,
when some curious observer will stop to comment on Little Michele's
sea-green eyes and Gabbi's snow-white skin. Then, almost always,
they ask The Question.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's wrong with her?''
</P>
<P>
   It's OK that they ask _ people are curious. There are many ways
to answer, depending on Michele's emotional reserves and the
questioner's level of interest. The short answer is always the
same: Gabbi's a shaken baby. Usually, this provokes blank stares. A
what? So Michele tries again. Gabbi has Shaken Baby Syndrome. That
is, when she was very small, an infant, not yet 3 months, somebody
shook her; the shaking probably only lasted seconds, but seconds
are long enough, and now Gabbi can't walk, can't talk, can't eat .
. . can't, can't, can't.
</P>
<P>
   Oh my gosh, people say. I had no idea.
</P>
<P>
   Well, neither did she.
</P>
<P>
   Before all this happened, she could not have guessed that her
only child, George _ the boy with dimples and an attitude _ would
meet a young girl named Monica and that before they could marry she
would be pregnant, and that after they married they would have not
just one child but twins. She could not know that the new parents
would be so overwhelmed that one day when Monica went to work and
George stayed home with the babies, something would go so wrong.
And she never would have fathomed that the dark-haired twin, the
gutsy little crier, would wind up in the pediatric intensive care
unit at Good Sam, so critically injured a priest was summoned for a
hurried baptism in case she did not last the night.
</P>
<P>
   And what a night. The detectives asking questions. The in-laws
arguing. The social workers giving everybody the up and down. The
tight knot of specialists hovering over Gabbi, unconscious and
gasping for air, her tiny, bandaged body lost in a thicket of wires
and tubes. Her head was swollen and her brain was hemorrhaging,
and, well, ``the poor little thing just looked like death,'' as
Michele's neighbor later put it, ``so lost up there in her high
hospital bed.''
</P>
<P>
   But the poor little thing was a fighter. Doctors operated to
relieve the pressure on her brain and hooked her to a ventilator so
she could breathe, and then Gabriela Sabrina Poole hung on _ and
hung on. In the meantime, Little Michele went home with Michele and
her husband Rodney, because in all the confusion, police were
certain of just one thing: In the window of time in question, the
elder Pooles had not been around the babies, and so they could not
have done the shaking.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, there would be a court case and a plea deal, and
then George Poole, the babies' father, would go to prison for 4 1/2
years. And he and Monica, the babies' mother, would agree _ in her
case reluctantly _ to give up the twins for adoption to Michele and
Rod. And in this way, one American family would be shattered and
another would begin.
</P>
<P>
   At Thanksgiving that first year, when the Poole family went
around the table naming what they had to be thankful for, Michele
thought of Gabbi lying in her high hospital bed, and she could not
say anything at all.
</P>
<P>
   So, no.
</P>
<P>
   People have no idea.
</P>
<P>
   And neither did she. ``You know what I'd like to see?'' Michele
says one morning at a Dunkin' Donuts, where she has stopped for
coffee after a business meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to see a unified national effort to get the word out
that you should never, ever, under any circumstances _ even if
you're exhausted, even if you're angry, even if you're stressed out
_ shake a baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why can't it be like seat belts?
</P>
<P>
   ``Or bike helmets?
</P>
<P>
   ``Or, hey! You know what's ridiculous? In the hospital, they
tell you all about breast-feeding, but they don't say a thing about
not shaking the baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm telling you, a few public service announcements aren't
going to do it. This thing has got to be hammered into people.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what we need? Something like Mothers Against Drunk
Driving. Everytime somebody dies, they're out there, calling the
press, getting the word out. Why can't it be the same way with
shaking a baby?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well? Why can't it!''
</P>
<P>
   Her hand is pale, and in it her coffee quivers in its plastic
cup. This is Michele Poole's second life. Her first was the kind
most people lead _ the usual ups and downs and setbacks and
victories. In this life, she is more single-minded and determined,
both blessed and cursed with a mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have just got to know about this,'' she says. ``I mean,
how can something so important not be common knowledge?''
</P>
<P>
   When she looks up, she sees that everybody in the little shop _
including a tall guy in a suit standing over her table _ is
listening.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorry,'' the tall guy says. ``But I just want you to know _
God! I agree with you!''
</P>
<P>
   Christie Evans and Bruce Bennett write for the Palm Beach Post,
West Palm Beach, Fla. E-mail addresses:
</P>
<P>
   christieevans(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   brucebennett(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   MORE _ SHAKEN-TAKE2-COX.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
