<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 10:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6315 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-SHAKEN23-TAKE2-COX     12-22 2666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAKEN23-TAKE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    (EDS: This is Take 2 of 4 takes.)
 &HT;    By Christie Evans
 &HT;    and Bruce Bennett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Five years ago, a father sat down to feed his
infant twin girls _ and something went terribly wrong. Now he's in
prison, his mother is raising his babies, and the twins no longer
match. One is healthy and smart.
</P>
<P>
   The other is broken. Michele Poole wants you to know why you
should never, ever shake a baby.
</P>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ There were warning signs. But she missed
them.
</P>
<P>
   Michele is thinking about this on a brilliant Tuesday afternoon
in April, in the windowless hall at Miami Children's Hospital. To
cheer things up, the nurses wear bright smocks and smiles. Gabbi,
with her limited vision, catches a splash of color now and then,
but no one knows if she can make out the outline of a smile.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Michele brought Gabbi here to see if her ketogenic
diet needed adjusting. The formula, high-fat and low-carb, has
helped immensely with Gabbi's seizures; when she has one, her whole
body tenses, then quivers, and her arms wing out like a bird's, and
for one awful moment she is on a cross, martyred. She used to take
barbiturates to control the seizures, and those made her sleepy.
But now with the diet, she's off the drugs and more alert.
</P>
<P>
   Today, doctors want to do an MRI scan of Gabbi's brain.
</P>
<P>
   A picture of Gabbi's brain is a sad thing to behold. When
doctors put it up on the light screen, it is easy for a laperson
to see that her brain has not only failed to grow since the injury,
it has atrophied and shrunk. The edges recede too far from the
skull's lining, and in the middle, where brain tissue should be,
the too-large ventricles are filled with nothing but cerebrospinal
fluid.
</P>
<P>
   Even Little Michele has a fundamental understanding of the
problem. One rainy day while looking through family vacation
pictures _ Gabbi in the glittery spray at Niagara Falls, Little
Michele at Pocahontas Village in Jamestown _ she came across a
stray photo of Gabbi on a stretcher with electrodes pasted to her
head. ``Here they are checking Gabbi's brains,'' she said, as if
continuing a travelogue. `` 'Cause, um, they don't work so well.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Gabriela Poole?''
</P>
<P>
   The nurse is ready.
</P>
<P>
   Gabbi needs a sedative so she will lie perfectly still for the
MRI. When the nurse pinches and sticks, because she can't find a
receptive vein, Gabbi cries, a high, sweet-sad sound, like the
hinges on a door that doesn't get opened enough. Michele strokes
her hair and cries, too; she hates it when Gabbi, who has to endure
so much already, gets the needle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gabbi's a shaken baby,'' Michele tells the nurse, who is
taking history. ``She's had chicken pox. Measles. Ketogenic diet.
Cortically blind. Stiff. Poor mobility. No allergies. Let's see.
What else? She's Twin B.''
</P>
<P>
   The nurse looks up, startled.
</P>
<P>
   ``What about Twin A?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Twin A is fine. She's in school today.''
</P>
<P>
   The nurse thinks about this for a moment, tries to process the
image of Little Michele at The Little Place, practicing her letters
and numbers, while her sister is here, getting a scan that will
show the big, empty places in her brain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see far too many of these cases,'' she finally says. She
does not know how many. But she remembers each one, because each
one seems so infuriatingly unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   In the MRI room, the attendant slides Gabbi into the big white
cylinder, and Michele slides into a folding chair, and then because
this is a hospital, and hospitals trigger memories, she thinks
about the biggest regret she has in life.
</P>
<P>
   The cylinder rattles and hums.
</P>
<P>
   The attendant hands her ear plugs.
</P>
<P>
   She puts them in, pulls them out, in, out, in, out.
</P>
<P>
   No good.
</P>
<P>
   They won't block out what she already knows.
</P>
<P>
   It was October 1994 _ a month before the shaking.
</P>
<P>
   George and Monica were living with Rodney and Michele, and one
day after Michele came home from work and from picking George up at
school, she noticed black-and-blue marks on Gabbi's tiny body. She
called her neighbor, Arlene Snyder, who later wrote a letter to the
court, describing the injuries: Gabbi's left ear was ``completely
black and blue, her face bruised in a line from her left ear to the
lower portion of her nose, bruises on her right cheek, her arm and
her leg.''
</P>
<P>
   Just who was responsible never became clear. George had not been
around the babies on the day in question, and Monica insisted she
had not handled the baby roughly. George thought perhaps Gabbi
might have slipped and bumped her head when he was playing with her
the day before, and yet no bruising had been apparent that night or
the next morning. Michele and Rodney talked in circles about
calling the police, but in the end Michele resisted. She thought
she could counsel the young parents on how to handle a baby.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was this:
</P>
<P>
   What if police suspected Michele? Or Rodney? What if they went
to jail? Who would take care of the babies then?
</P>
<P>
   ``So I didn't call.''
</P>
<P>
   The MRI is still humming when she finishes the story. Gabbi's
little feet peek out from the cylinder, the only physical reminder
she is in the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course I was so, so wrong,'' Michele says. ``Today I would
tell anybody: If you see a bruise on a baby, call the cops. Don't
worry about going to jail. Don't try to protect yourself. Don't try
to protect anybody except the baby.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mom!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, Michele?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Three things I don't know how to do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What, Pumpkin?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how to swim. I don't know how to read. And I
don't know how to play the piano.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But you're learning! You're learning all those things!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I'm learning. Plus, I don't know how to cook.''
</P>
<P>
   It is quiet for a moment.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle seat of the van, Little Michele leans over and
takes her sister's hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're learning how to swim, Gabbi,'' she says. ``You're a
very good swimmer. Don't you just love it, Gabbi?''
</P>
<P>
   In her wheelchair, Gabbi nods emphatically, dark curls bobbing,
but it is only because she is asleep, and the van just passed over
a bump.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes when people ask her what her life is like, Michele
tells them about Thursdays. Thursdays are crazy.
</P>
<P>
   You know, you get to be 49, a mother, a grandmother, a
businesswoman, you escape one bad marriage, settle in comfortably,
gratefully, to a second. You do all this, and somehow you don't
expect, at this fine stage of life, to be mixing formula on a
Thursday morning and racing out the door with two little halves of
a twin set _ one in diapers, the other a preschooler _ for a day of
activities usually reserved for 32-year-old moms.
</P>
<P>
   In the old days, before the twins, Michele zipped down the
turnpike from her big house in the woods in far-western Palm Beach
County to the citified Pompano Beach offices of North Ridge
Electric, the now-thriving company she and Rodney started from
scratch in 1977. Back then, Rod did most of the field work and
Michele did most of the office work. But now Rod does most of the
business stuff, and Michele does most of the girls' stuff _
although she's still a whiz with the books (in an accounting
crisis, she brings Gabbi to the office, carrying her up 28 steps),
and Rodney, a big bear of a man, can change Gabbi's diaper with the
best of them. And don't even mention Little Michele unless you have
an hour. ``That little pumpkin,'' he likes to say, ``just grabbed
my heart and kept it.''
</P>
<P>
   So even though Michele is still a businesswoman _ and one of
three women on the state Electrical Contractors' Licensing Board _
she is mostly a coffee-swigging, cell phone-ringing car-pool mom.
If Gabbi and Little Michele were like most twins, they would be
piling into the back seat, giggling, poking, elbowing, begging mom
for one more chocolate chip cookie; instead, climbing into the van
is a labored ritual, with Little Michele standing on the
passenger's side to push the buttons that lower the ramp, and Big
Michele wheeling Gabbi up and in and clicking the little turquoise
wheelchair into place.
</P>
<P>
   Little Michele fastens Gabbi's seat belt, and then, usually, she
says, ``Mom, can we get Chicken Nuggets?'' and Michele usually says
yes. And they are off.
</P>
<P>
   First, suburbia slips by hot and green on the way to music
class, where Little Michele is learning to play ``E for Esther
Elephant'' with her third finger on the glossy, black piano while
Gabbi dozes in the corner. Big Michele slips out for a minute to
try to persuade the piano store owner to help with a music festival
for Easter Seals, where Gabbi went to a wonderful day care and
Michele is on the board.
</P>
<P>
   It is one of Michele's favorite rules that you never do just one
thing (go to a piano lesson) when you can do two (go to a piano
lesson and help Easter Seals), and the piano lady is an easy
target. By the end of their talk, she not only pledges her
services, she also has learned the fine points of Shaken Baby
Syndrome and picked up a tip from Michele about never doing
electrical wiring while standing on an aluminum ladder.
</P>
<P>
   After music, suburbia slips by on the way to speech class, where
Miss Natalie with her gentle, sing-song voice is trying to teach
Gabbi to work her lips and tongue by tempting her with a pink
``toothette'' and sometimes a butterscotch lollipop _ so that one
day she might have the skills to eat real food. Eating is one of
Michele's biggest goals for Gabbi, one that right now seems
far-fetched and yet might actually be possible.
</P>
<P>
   But the therapist has another goal. She says Gabbi has
``wants,'' and it is her committed belief that she might be able to
learn how to ask for things. If she's hungry, say, or if she would
like to listen to a bit of Morning Magic music, she might kick her
foot or make a squeak or something. Which is why Miss Natalie has
fastened a big yellow button on Gabbi's wheelchair tray. If
somebody pushes it (optimistically, Gabbi), she is immediately and
enthusiastically rewarded with ``Farmer in the Dell.'' And Gabbi
loves ``Farmer in the Dell.''
</P>
<P>
   So the yellow button is a very big deal _ if only Gabbi could
push it.
</P>
<P>
   Little Michele, who is sitting on a swivel chair eating a
Tootsie Roll, says she would be happy to push it herself, just to
get things going, but she knows that's not really the point.
</P>
<P>
   The point is for Gabbi to do it. But it won't be today, because
today, she has fallen asleep instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe next time!'' Miss Natalie says, and then suburbia slips
by on the way to swimming class.
</P>
<P>
   It is in swimming that Gabbi excels and her sister struggles.
Little Michele is frightened of the water, more so than many kids,
but Gabbi _ blissfully unaware of the dangers _ lets it lick her
limbs as she floats face skyward, her plump, little legs relaxed as
they almost never are, except in sleep, an expression of bliss on
her pixie face.
</P>
<P>
   So that's Thursdays, and Tuesdays aren't any better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might have overbooked,'' Michele says, smiling because she
absolutely has.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if I drop something, like, say, speech, then I would
always be thinking, what if that was going to be the day Gabbi hit
the yellow button? What if that was going to be the day she took a
bite and swallowed real food?
   ``What if that was going to be the day something big happened?''
</P>
<P>
   Shaken-baby cases are notoriously difficult: The people with the
most information are also those responsible for the shaking. And
so, after Gabbi got hurt, Bart Arnold, a detective with the Palm
Beach County Sheriff's Office, took scrupulous notes.
</P>
<P>
   He talked with the hospital doctor, who said Gabbi was in
critical condition, with a bruised and bleeding brain, bruises on
her abdomen and bleeding behind her eyes, a classic sign of Shaken
Baby Syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   He talked with Monica, who said she left the twins with their
father on the Saturday in question _ Nov. 19, 1994 _ while she went
to her cashier's job at a Walgreen's pharmacy.
</P>
<P>
   And he interviewed George, who told him things went terribly
wrong after he dropped his wife off at work, then returned home to
feed the babies: He sat down on the bed, held one in each arm, then
Gabriela slipped from his arms, and he grabbed her. Afterward, she
wailed, and her eyes looked funny. She was flailing. Her cry
sounded like nothing he had ever heard before.
</P>
<P>
   That afternoon, he picked Monica up at work. She saw Gabbi and
asked him, God, what did you do? For the next 12 hours, Gabbi did
not sleep, did not move, barely ate. He and Monica worried all
weekend. Shouldn't they take Gabbi to the doctor? But George was
afraid: If they went to the hospital _ with Gabbi in this condition
_ they might lose custody of the babies. So they waited, all
weekend. On Monday, they took Gabbi to the pediatrician.
</P>
<P>
   The detective pressed further. George admitted he had a temper.
Did you ever shake the babies? No, he said. Then, ``I shake them,
just bounce them.''
</P>
<P>
   In a second interview, he was more specific. He said he grabbed
Gabbi's neck. He said he thought she was dead. He said, ``I thought
I just killed my daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   And, yes, he shook her. He was trying to rouse her, that's all.
The shaking lasted just five seconds, or 10. He wanted to get her
focused.
</P>
<P>
   One last thing. Anybody who accused him of a crime, he told the
detective, would die. ``A nine millimeter will do just fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Michele is in the kitchen, mixing Gabbi's formula.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you know what I sometimes think?'' she says. ``I sometimes
think he might as well have put a gun to her head and killed her.''
This sounds so terrible, she winces. ``But, really, she might have
been better off . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``So, really, unless they anoint that boy Pope and smoke pours
up from the Vatican, I want nothing to do with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, the last time they spoke she also was mixing
formula, getting ready to feed Gabbi through the tube. George was
in prison, serving his time for felony child abuse.
</P>
<P>
   The phone rang.
</P>
<P>
   Hi, Mom?
</P>
<P>
   Prison food's terrible.
</P>
<P>
   Please send money.
</P>
<P>
   ``And at that moment, I just snapped,'' Michele says. ``I said,
`I know you can't appreciate this, but if Little Gabbi can't enjoy
normal food, then why should you?' I asked him not to call me
again, and he honored that, because I have not heard from him since
_ and that was three years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Michele says George never admitted to her that he shook Gabbi,
but a few months ago, he wrote a reporter a letter from prison _ he
is not allowed visitors, because of his long string of disciplinary
infractions _ and in it he said he was grateful to Rod and Michele
for stepping in to raise the twins. ``I have no doubts as to there
being `a better place' for my daughters,'' he wrote. ``One does not
exist.''
</P>
<P>
   He added he would not ``attempt to justify'' his actions.
``Hell, I'm guilty.'' A well-bred man, he said, quoting Ben
Franklin, knows how to confess a fault.
</P>
<P>
   Michele read the letter _ and wondered if it really was George
who wrote it.
</P>
<P>
   Some people tell Michele she should hurry up and forgive her
son, before bitterness eats her through. But she isn't buying it.
She tried with George, she really did. And, Rodney, his stepfather,
tried too. They enrolled him in military schools. Drug programs.
Family counseling. Everything. And nothing worked. If she forgives,
she says, she opens herself up all over again to George, and this
she can't afford to do. His prison term is almost up _ in January!
_ so she needs to remain ever-vigilant. Suppose he knocks on her
door and asks to see the kids. What will she do? Call 911?
</P>
<P>
   But that is a worry for another day.
</P>
<P>
   Christie Evans and Bruce Bennett write for the Palm Beach Post,
West Palm Beach, Fla. E-mail addresses:
</P>
<P>
   christieevans(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   brucebennett(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   (MORE- SHAKEN-TAKE3-COX)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
