<DOCNO> NYT19991222.0071 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 10:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6323 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-SHAKEN23-TAKE4-COX     12-22 2059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAKEN23-TAKE4-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    (EDS: This is Take 4 of 4 takes.)
 &HT;    By Christie Evans
 &HT;    and Bruce Bennett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Five years ago, a father sat down to feed his
infant twin girls _ and something went terribly wrong. Now he's in
prison, his mother is raising his babies, and the twins no longer
match. One is healthy and smart.
</P>
<P>
   The other is broken. Michele Poole wants you to know why you
should never, ever shake a baby.
</P>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ ``Mom?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, Pumpkin?''
</P>
<P>
   ``How come you're always talking about Gabbi? How come you never
talk about me?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I do! I talk about you all the time, Michele. Didn't you just
hear me talking about how great you're doing in your swimming
lessons?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, but you talk more about Gabbi.''
</P>
<P>
   Michele adjusts the rearview mirror, finds Little Michele's
eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, honey. I'm sorry! You know what? Sometimes I have to talk
about Gabbi. Gabbi has a lot of appointments. She has a lot of
doctor's visits. So sometimes I talk about those. But I love
talking about you, too!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, how come you never call me baby? How come you always
call Gabbi baby, but not me?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I do! I call you baby all the time!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, how come you never get mad at Gabbi? You just get mad at
me?''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a little harder. Let me think about that. But you need
to tell me what you want at Burger King.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When you talk about Gabbi, just make sure you talk about me,
too. Gabbi and me, Gabbi and me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Gabbi and you, right?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Right. 'Cause otherwise it isn't fair.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Right.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mom?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Vanilla milkshake.''
</P>
<P>
   It's time to go, and it's pouring. Little Michele can't find her
sneakers, and it's pouring. The house key isn't working, and it's
pouring. The buzzer in the van won't shut up, and it's still
pouring.
</P>
<P>
   It's Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   It's chaos.
</P>
<P>
   It's therapy day.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Springsteen is playing in the waiting room.
</P>
<P>
   BEGIN ITALIC ``Sometimes, it's like someone took a knife baby
edgy and dull and cut a six-inch valley through the middle of my
soul.'' END ITALIC
</P>
<P>
   Gabbi is wearing her lime-green dress and matching socks, and
Michele has parked her wheelchair so it faces the big wall mural
depicting a beautiful garden and a greenhouse. Gabbi, with her
near-blind, far-away stare, appears to be entranced by the picture,
and watching her you think she is exactly like those hothouse
plants: If she isn't cared for and loved and watered and fed and
tended to just so, she won't survive.
</P>
<P>
   Last time at the therapist's, Little Michele and her mother were
trying to decide who would go in first when Little Michele said,
``OK, I'll go, but I'm taking Gabbi with me'' _ and then she
scooted her sister's wheelchair down the hall and into the
therapist's office and closed the door. Since everything at the
therapist's is confidential, nobody really knows what was said, not
even Big Michele. But she would pay good money.
</P>
<P>
   The therapy trips began after Little Michele turned 4 and
started asking who her ``real'' mom was. Big Michele wasn't sure
how to answer. How much should she say? Everything's so
complicated.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, on Sundays, the twins visit Monica, who was just 18
when she had them. The visits _ at the other grandparents' home _
are friendly, but tentative. Little Michele sometimes calls Monica
mom, and sometimes just Monica. And Monica is ambivalent, too.
After Gabbi got hurt, she tried to get the girls back, but then,
when they were 2, when George was in prison and she was dancing in
bars to pay the bills, she relented and signed the adoption papers.
</P>
<P>
   Michele and Rod promised she could see the twins whenever she
wanted, and they held their word. But nobody has figured out how to
explain all this to Little Michele.
</P>
<P>
   For now she knows only part of the story. She knows Gabbi hurt
her head, knows she's different, knows she goes to special schools.
But she does not know her daddy did it, does not understand the
intricacies of a baby's brain, does not realize Gabbi will be like
this the rest of her life, even when Michele and Rodney are too old
to care for her. Then, Little Michele will have to look out for her
sister, but she doesn't know that either.
</P>
<P>
   The hardest questions are yet to come: Why would a daddy want to
hurt a baby? Why would God allow such a thing? Why did Gabbi get
hurt and I didn't? Was it my fault? Will she ever get better?
</P>
<P>
   ``I need an outsider to help me with all that,'' Michele says.
</P>
<P>
   It's funny, but recently, Little Michele added some ``ghost
friends'' to her family. Their names are Billy, Sadie and Gabbi.
Big Michele loves that she included Gabbi, because Little Michele
and her ghost friends play games together, and that's more than
Gabbi gets to do in real life.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's one more thing to talk to the therapist about.
</P>
<P>
   And then, there's this:
</P>
<P>
   After Gabbi got hurt, doctors examined Little Michele and found
evidence of retinal hemorrhaging _ a sign that she, too, had been
shaken.
</P>
<P>
   So, while she is in many ways precocious, Little Michele will
always be under her parents' microscope. Sometimes children who
have been shaken as babies seem to be fine, and then later, in
school, they develop problems. Trouble concentrating. Erratic
behavior. Learning disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   So she's praying. But she's also on guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never do the crying thing,'' Michele says on the way home,
but what she means is, she dabs away the tears before they have a
chance to roll down her cheeks.
</P>
<P>
   Finally _ after months of Thursdays _ something big happened.
</P>
<P>
   It was summer, and, for the heck of it, Michele's brother Ken
threw a party, a big turkey dinner in the middle of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody came. Michele and Rodney. The twins. Michele's sister,
Ellen. Her brother, Scott. Her mother, Vivian.
</P>
<P>
   There was good china, and on the plates the stiff, white napkins
stood up like little hats.
</P>
<P>
   Little Michele sat next to Rodney. Gabbi sat next to Big
Michele. Everybody held hands during grace.
</P>
<P>
   And then _ Michele couldn't help herself. She scooped a bit of
mashed potatoes onto a spoon. She put the spoon to Gabbi's lips.
Gabbi's tongue moved around a bit. The potatoes sat for a moment in
her mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Then she ate them.
</P>
<P>
   Michele held her breath as Gabbi swallowed, but down they went,
and for an encore, Gabbi enjoyed a few bites of butternut squash.
</P>
<P>
   When the speech therapist heard, she said, ``Oh, Gabbidoodle!
You're breaking my heart!''
</P>
<P>
   School.
</P>
<P>
   Once, Gabbi got to go to The Little Place with Little Michele
for a day. There was a fire drill, and the teacher wheeled Gabbi
outside, and the kids gathered around, rubbing her arms, petting
her, really, and one girl remarked that Gabbi's soft hands felt
like gloves. But then the children noticed Gabbi's legs _ stiff as
a toy soldier's _ and one of them said, ``Gosh, doesn't she look
just like a statue?''
</P>
<P>
   Little Michele didn't say much at all. She hung back as her
classmates looked at Gabbi, and then at Little Michele, and then
back at Gabbi.
</P>
<P>
   And then they asked the teacher what one girl was to the other.
Were Michele and Gabbi sisters? The teacher thought for a moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' she finally said. ``They're twins. But one has dark
hair and one has light hair, and that's the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, since that's not the whole truth, Gabbi goes to her own
school _ the Potentials charter school in Riviera Beach. On
interview day, Michele put Gabbi in her best yellow dress and took
off, passing warehouses and a half dozen little churches with signs
advertising hope and a new life.
</P>
<P>
   Gabbi got hers.
</P>
<P>
   At Potentials, she and 22 other students get all the important
therapies _ speech, vision, occupational, physical _ and plenty of
classroom time. And the school's philosophy is: Don't worry about
what a child can't do. Find out what she can do. Because children
like Gabbi can surprise you.
</P>
<P>
   Michele knows this. She remembers when she put Gabbi under a
baby gym when she was 16 months old. A child as severely impaired
as Gabbi should not have been able to figure out how to manipulate
the gym to make the cat meow or the bear growl or the dog bark _
but one night Michele was sitting at her computer with her back to
Gabbi and she heard animal sounds.
</P>
<P>
   The next day she took Gabbi and the baby gym to Easter Seals and
everybody cheered. Gabbi was learning to push the levers that made
the sounds she loved. And if she could do that, couldn't she do
more?
</P>
<P>
   Yes.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Gabbi joins in circle time. Her favorite toy is an
electronic piano with light-up keys. She loves to paint, and she
can sit up with assistance, and just the other day (Michele
couldn't believe it) she used the toilet for the first time. The
teachers have big goals for Gabbi. They want her to recognize
herself in the mirror, learn to wash her face and brush her teeth
with help, concentrate for longer periods of time, reach out to
another child, accept a touch, express a wish.
</P>
<P>
   Gabbi is making fine progress. Her report card says she is
giggling more than ever.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, in the mountains of North Carolina, where she has
a summer place, Michele visited a studio where people like Gabbi
learn to make suspenders _ and get paid for it. It's not the money
that counts so much; it's the companionship, the glow that comes
with accomplishment. Everyone has a task at which they can excel.
One fellow comes in a few hours a day just to run his fingers over
the material, because feeling material is what he's good at.
</P>
<P>
   The man who showed Michele around said Gabbi might do well
there, someday. And at first she cried, thinking of her
granddaughter at a long table, worrying over a piece of elastic
while the radio played.
</P>
<P>
   But then she thought: Maybe it's enough, learning to make a
clasp or a hook, something to hold up a pair of pants, and taking
pride in it.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's enough working with friends and feeling useful.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's enough just having a place in life.
</P>
<P>
   In September, the twins celebrated their fifth birthday with a
Winnie the Pooh theme. Little Michele got Happenin' Hair Barbie,
and Gabbi successfully licked the ranch dressing off some carrot
sticks. And after Little Michele blew out the candles, one of the
guests, a girl of 9 who has a disabled brother, said, ``Gabbi and
Nicholas are just like everybody else, except they can't do
everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``But who cares? Because you still love them so much.''
</P>
<P>
   In October, Michele got herself on TV news. It took a little
chutzpah, calling up Channel 5 and inviting them over like that.
But, in nearby counties, two babies had just been shaken, and this
was Domestic Violence Month, and so, as she put it, ``I just
couldn't keep my mouth shut.'' And that's how she got the lead
story. Anyone who tuned in saw Little Michele riding her hot-pink
bike around the living room, and Big Michele doing her
demonstration with the egg and the bowl, and then they saw Gabbi in
her lime-green dress _ pushing the yellow button with everything
she had.
</P>
<P>
   In November, Michele flew to Texas, to meet with the Shaken Baby
Alliance, a prevention group that wants to start affiliations in
every state. It is a big job. Somebody is going to have to stand up
and shout. Travel the country. Stop in big cities and little towns.
Do radio spots and community lectures. Somebody is going to have
load up the twins. Plan an itinerary.
</P>
<P>
   And that is why, at the end of the Pooles' driveway, tucked
under the pines, a 38-foot Winnebago waits, ready for The New
Millennium Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Michele and Rodney bought it from a paralyzed race car driver,
and he said it was a good rig for a hard road.
</P>
<P>
   It's dark.
</P>
<P>
   After dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Little Michele's singing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twinkle, twinkle little star . . . how I wonder what you are .
. . up above the world so high . . . like a diamond in the sky.''
</P>
<P>
   Gabbi has fallen asleep. Little Michele kisses her cheek.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's you, Gabbi,'' she says. ``That star is you.''
</P>
<P>
   Christie Evans and Bruce Bennett write for the Palm Beach Post,
West Palm Beach, Fla. E-mail addresses:
</P>
<P>
   christieevans(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   brucebennett(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
