<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991222.0072 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 10:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6324 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-SHAKEN23-TAKE3-COX     12-22 1535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAKEN23-TAKE3-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    (EDS: This is Take 3 of 4 takes.)
 &HT;    By Christie Evans
 &HT;    and Bruce Bennett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Five years ago, a father sat down to feed his
infant twin girls _ and something went terribly wrong. Now he's in
prison, his mother is raising his babies, and the twins no longer
match. One is healthy and smart.
</P>
<P>
   The other is broken. Michele Poole wants you to know why you
should never, ever shake a baby.
</P>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ June 20, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   It is a hot, sweaty, shorts-and-bathing suit Saturday in the
twins' third year, and Gabbi and Michele have just been appointed
goodwill ambassadors for the local Easter Seals society. As Little
Ambassadors, the twins have an obligation to spread the word.
Sometimes, they dress up in adorable matching outfits ad have
their pictures taken for brochures, and sometimes they appear at
fund-raisers, where, as Michele puts it, ``I hate to say they're on
display, but, yup, they're on display.''
</P>
<P>
   On this day, the day before Father's Day, the good cause is up
the road in West Palm Beach, so Michele loads the twins into the
van and heads north to Howard Park and the Festival for Fatherhood.
She plops Gabbi down in a baby bouncer under the spreading branches
of a ficus tree, picks up Little Michele in her right arm and her
baby-doll prop in her left _ and then she is ready to make her
pitch to the straggly but attentive group of dads and the young
sons who accompany them.
</P>
<P>
   This is Little Michele, she tells the crowd. See how sparkly she
is? How smart? She's what Gabbi could be if Gabbi weren't Gabbi.
</P>
<P>
   And this is Gabbi. She was born 100 percent healthy. Oh gosh,
she was just beautiful. Before she got hurt, she was just like
Little Michele.
</P>
<P>
   The young boys in striped shirts and cut-offs crane their necks
to get a peek at the Little Ambassadors, the hurt one and the
healthy one, and then they repeat after Michele in clear, high
voices, ``Never, ever shake a baby!'' And at supper that night they
ask their daddies if shaking a baby can really do that, mess up
your brains that way.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the truth, Michele says:
</P>
<P>
   At first, you don't want to go out and tell people what happened
to your family. Don't want to talk about your brain-damaged
granddaughter. Don't want to show the world pictures of your twins.
</P>
<P>
   You don't want to get up and give a speech to a bunch of
strangers. Don't want to show them how Gabbi eats through a tube.
Don't want to tell them how before she got the tube, she was
inconsolable, and you even tried breast-feeding, but nothing came
out.
</P>
<P>
   And you certainly don't want to tell them your son did this, and
you're not sure why, but he was trouble all his life. Only _ he's
your son, so of course you love him.
</P>
<P>
   No.
</P>
<P>
   You want to draw the curtains and curl up in bed and pull the
covers over your head and maybe take a sleeping pill and disconnect
the phone and tell your husband you'll be OK, when really you don't
think you'll ever be. You want to, but you don't. Because you have
two babies now. And when you look at the healthy one you are
reminded of what the sick one could be, and when you look at the
sick one you are reminded of other babies in other places.
</P>
<P>
   Each year in America _ you know this because you've read
everything on the subject _ hundreds of babies are shaken. Some
live with brain damage; about a quarter die. So you watch the news
and you get on the Internet, and you find other people who have had
their hearts broken by the exact same thing, and some you call, and
some you only think about, day after day, until you want to shove
every last case from your mind. But you can't. Because this is
personal. The rest of the country might read, then quickly forget,
the headlines about the British nanny, but you are stroking Gabbi's
curls.
</P>
<P>
   So, no.
</P>
<P>
   You don't draw the curtains, you don't stay in bed, you don't
take the sleeping pill. There is too much to do.
</P>
<P>
   And if you don't do it _ well, then, will nothing positive come
of this at all?
</P>
<P>
   So now here she is, schlepping around Florida with her egg and
her doll. And Gabbi.
</P>
<P>
   She puts on her blue suit and heels and the red-and-silver
shaken-baby ribbon she bought for a dollar from a woman in New
Hampshire, and she hunts and pecks her way through city streets and
rural roads until she finds the right meeting room in the right
tucked-away shopping center.
</P>
<P>
   No audience is too small. No banquet hall too dumpy. She does
schools, halfway houses, parenting groups, anything. She's not
above drumming up her own business, not too bashful to call some
group she has barely heard of and say, in her best
politician/saleswoman's voice, ``This is Michele Poole. I give
talks on Shaken Baby Syndrome. When can you fit me in?''
</P>
<P>
   Once she's in the door, she doesn't need notes. The words pour
out: Anyone can shake a baby. Not just troubled kids like my son,
George. Not just people messed up on drugs. Not just poor people or
dumb people or mentally ill people. People who shake babies are
just . . . people. Some are angry, some ignorant. Many are dads, a
few are moms. Some are boyfriends, some baby-sitters. Afterwards,
some are sorry, some are not.
</P>
<P>
   At the close of every speech, she extends an invitation: If
anyone knows somebody who might be at risk to shake a baby, she
will meet that person anytime anywhere. She will explain that a
baby's brain is exceedingly fragile, that her head is large and her
neck muscles weak, that when you shake or slam something that
small, her head snaps to and fro like a Ping-Pong ball and her
brain ricochets around her skull and _ well, God, look at Gabbi.
</P>
<P>
   So far, no one has taken her up on her offer to meet one-on-one.
</P>
<P>
   And you know what?
</P>
<P>
   Some groups don't even want her, or the Little Ambassadors.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I press the issue, they tell me shaken babies are just
too depressing.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I tell them, that's exactly why you need me. That's the
whole damn point.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what would be great?'' Michele says one day while
counting the number of handicapped spaces in the Dunkin' Donuts
plaza _ an activist's obsession.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to get a big motor home, drive around the country.
No kidding! Gabbi's a great little traveler, and Little Michele
loves camping. I'd stop at every big city and little town I passed
through, and I'd get on the radio and speak at schools and maybe
get into the hospitals to talk to the moms or the nurses. I'd tell
them _ I'd show them _ what it means to shake a baby. I could get
sponsors. I could do parks and community centers. Libraries. PTAs.
I brought this up with Rodney, and he said, `Go for it.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I even have a title picked out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The New Millennium Make-a-Difference Shaken Baby Awareness and
Prevention Tour.''
</P>
<P>
   OK.
</P>
<P>
   Sure.
</P>
<P>
   It's a big dream.
</P>
<P>
   But sometimes you need a big dream to pick your spirits up off
the floor _ where they have fallen in the course of just getting
by.
</P>
<P>
   Gabriela Sabrina Poole was born at Bethesda Memorial Hospital,
Boynton Beach, Fla., on Sept. 4, 1994, and she was perfect.
</P>
<P>
   She came, literally, on the heels of her sister, Michele Marie,
who arrived minutes earlier and was named after Big Michele. Gabbi
weighed 6 pounds, 12 ounces, and Little Michele a tad less. Because
they are fraternal twins _ born of different eggs and sharing
approximately half their genes _ it was difficult, back then, to
predict how alike in appearance or temperament they might be one
day. And now, of course, it is impossible.
</P>
<P>
   But what is it about twins? Even fraternal ones sometimes seem
to share membership in a secret society, and it is this kinship
that has fascinated parents and researchers alike. In her recent
book, ``Entwined Lives,'' Nancy Segal, a psychologist and fraternal
twin herself, includes a picture of the British ``Giggle Twins,''
Barbara Herbert and Daphne Goodship. ``Each twin inspires
continuous laughter in the other,'' Segal explains in the caption,
``but what sets them off is a mystery to everyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, that sounds familiar. Even though Gabbi is Gabbi _ or
perhaps because Gabbi is Gabbi _ Little Michele has figured out a
special way to communicate with her. In the van or in the kitchen _
or when Gabbi is sleepy in bed and Little Michele climbs in with an
armful of Barbies _ she fills her lungs with air and emits a
high-pitched squeak and, almost always, Gabbi will summon herself
from her quiet reverie to respond with a fit of giggles. Gabbi
giggling is a lovely, lovely sight.
</P>
<P>
   The twins are never more twin-like _ never more one _ than at
this moment, and if Big Michele ever writes a book of her own, she
will be sure to mention the squeak and the giggle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like there's an invisible cord between them,'' she says.
``Little Michele pulls, and it just brings Gabbi right out of
herself.''
</P>
<P>
   Christie Evans and Bruce Bennett write for the Palm Beach Post,
West Palm Beach, Fla. E-mail addresses:
</P>
<P>
   christieevans(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   brucebennett(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   (MORE-SHAKEN-TAKE4-COX.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
