<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It parks, but will it start?
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The trouble with valets? They don't get enough
experience parking pieces of junk.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, they can handle a Ferrari. But do they know how to deal
with, say, a '73 Pinto blowing smoke out the back end? Nope.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, on Friday night I drove up to the front of
three fancy restaurants in downtown Austin and asked the valets to
park a butt-ugly '82 model Toyota with National Geographic photos
covering the entire body on the passenger side.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a nice set of wheels you've got there,'' said Cory
</P>
<P>
   Rohde, a valet at Sullivan's Steak House, as he opened the car
door for me. Maybe he was being complimentary because I was
leaving.
</P>
<P>
   See, Austin has become such an upscale town that we suddenly
have a number of restaurants downtown that feature guys in uniforms
who will park your car for $4 or $5, plus tip. In fact, we now have
so many valet parking services downtown that the City Council has
approved new fees and regulations for them.
</P>
<P>
   How would these valets deal with a real pile of auto parts?
</P>
<P>
   To find out, I borrowed a Toyota that used to belong to Crazy
Carl Hickerson, former perennial unsuccessful hippie candidate for
Austin's City Council.
</P>
<P>
   Crazy Carl transferred the National Geographic pictures to the
surface of the car through a crafts method known as decoupage. He
covered the passenger side of the car completely to try to hide the
damage that occurred when the car was, as Carl put it, ``rolled.''
</P>
<P>
   On the car you can see pictures of Winston Churchill, Queen
Elizabeth I and Eisenhower. A tiny blue light comes on when you
turn the air-conditioner knob. The air conditioner, however, does
not come on. A metal Cadillac emblem decorates the glove
compartment door. The car has no shocks. It is like riding in a
rock. Over the years, the car has developed its own anti-theft
system. Sometimes the ignition key locks up.
</P>
<P>
   Carl says that one time when he was driving the car on the Drag,
some college boys pulled up next to him, and one of them hollered
out the window, ``Hey, Charter can help.'' The college boy was
referring to Charter Lane, a drug rehab hospital.
</P>
<P>
   For my valet parking experiment, my friend Danny Bennett rode
along in a Federal Witness Protection Program T-shirt. We had a toy
called The Surprising Arm sticking out of the car trunk. The
Surprising Arm is a rubber hand attached to a sleeve.
</P>
<P>
   For the evening, I wore a pair of blue- and white-striped
overalls, along with a gimme cap from The Too Damn Friendly Bar in
Johnson City, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   I knew one thing: I was not overdressed.
</P>
<P>
   It was shortly after 6 p.m. Friday when Danny and I pulled up in
front of Louie's 106. A group of four or five valets was gathered
on the sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   The valets were all over this Toyota. I thought they were going
to fight over who was going to get to park it. It was as if they
were thinking, ``Thank God. Not another stinking Maserati.'' ``I
like the hand,'' one of the valets said. Another began running his
fingers over the National Geographic photos on the car.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you gotta do to offend somebody in this town?'' my
friend Danny asked me, as an aside.
</P>
<P>
   For $4 and a $1 tip, one of the valets drove the Toyota over to
a nearby mall parking garage and left it on the fifth level. But
when a valet returned to the car to drive it back, he couldn't get
the key to turn over. So a second valet sprinted across the street
to the parking garage to try to start the car. The key still
wouldn't budge.
</P>
<P>
   I got her going, though, and we headed off for Sullivan's Steak
House. We easily had the most interesting car in front of
Sullivan's. The rest of the cars parked by the curb were your
typical boring Jaguars, Corvettes and Porsches.
</P>
<P>
   Although the valets at Sullivan's parked our car for $4 and $1
tip with no questions or extremely funny looks, their attitude
toward the car was less than enthusiastic. ``Well, it could use a
little work,'' said Robert Tapia, 21. ``I especially liked the
Cadillac emblem. ``
</P>
<P>
   As we prepared to leave, the Sullivan's valets got our keys
mixed up with the others in the key box.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you have a white Lexus?'' one of the valets asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, but we'll take it,'' I said. I wanted to be the only guy
in Austin driving a Lexus in a pair of overalls.
</P>
<P>
   We didn't get the Lexus, but we did limp on over to Ruth's Chris
Steak House, a really tasty steak place where you have to take out
a bank loan to feed a party of four.
</P>
<P>
   The valets at Ruth's Chris charged us $5 to park the car, and I
tipped $1. Is this the ugliest car that's ever been here? I asked
Troy Schmidt, the head valet. ``There's one driving around with the
little toy dinosaurs on it,'' he said guardedly. But do the little
toy dinosaurs ever stop here? I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: jkelso(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
