<HEADER>
A6326 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-FASHION-MILLER23-COX     12-22 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-MILLER23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Young and old in Hollywood won't get dressed without them
 &HT;    By Staci Sturrock
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The name ``Nolan Miller'' isn't as
well-known as, say, Calvin Klein or Tommy Hilfiger.
</P>
<P>
   But, guaranteed, Americans are familiar with the Miller look
whether they know it or not.
</P>
<P>
   Nolan Miller is the man who dressed Mary Ann in gingham for
``Gilligan's Island.'' He put Peggy Lipton in hip huggers for ``The
Mod Squad.'' And he created those linebacker-wide shoulder pads for
Krystle Carrington on ``Dynasty.''
</P>
<P>
   When TV costuming budgets began to shrink, Miller shifted his
focus to developing couture and ready-to-wear lines and dressing
old-guard celebrities: Lauren Bacall, Angie Dickinson and
Ann-Margret, among them. His protege, Mark Zunino, handles the
clothing chores for Hollywood's younger set _ stars such as Heather
Locklear, Halle Berry, Courteney Cox Arquette and Shannen Doherty.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, 64, and Zunino, 37, recently presented some of their
past and present designs at a luncheon fashion show benefiting the
National Parkinson Foundation. In the big tent at Mar-a-Lago, they
sat down to talk for a few minutes before the grazing and gazing
began:
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who's your favorite celebrity to dress?
</P>
<P>
   A: (Miller): ``If I say Sophia Loren, Joan Collins is going to
kill me. If I say Joan Collins, Sophia Loren is going to kill me. .
. . I loved dressing Elizabeth Taylor because she was my fantasy
growing up. When she finally called, I thought I had died and gone
to heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   (Zunino): ``Heather Locklear. She is so sweet. She is like a
young Ann-Margret. They are to the heart, to the bone, the nicest,
sweetest people. And they both have great bodies.'' (Locklear wore
a Zunino-designed gown when she married rocker Ritchie Sambora.)
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who is on your wish list?
</P>
<P>
   A: (Miller): Catherine Deneuve. ``The ones that I really wanted
to dress are all gone now: Princess Diana, Grace Kelly . . . ``
</P>
<P>
   (Zunino): Winona Ryder. ``I love her look. She has a very
demure, sophisticated look, but there's a wild streak running
through her.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: How is dressing new Hollywood different from outfitting the
gals in the old days?
</P>
<P>
   A: (Zunino): ``The studios used to dress the actresses from head
to toe. They were brought up with that, and they expect that. Young
Hollywood has not a clue. (But) they have fun with fashion. They're
not afraid to try things. If they try something and it doesn't
work, big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   (Miller): ``There aren't many stars left _ people who act and
look like stars. It's a different world. Not too many people can
create that aura today.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: How has designing for TV changed since ``Dynasty?''
</P>
<P>
   A: (Zunino): ``(On Dynasty) it was an endless budget. Everything
was sable, cashmere. Now the money is much tighter.''
</P>
<P>
   (Miller): ``I'm still trying to live down the beads and glitz of
the ``Dynasty'' era. . . . To have a show like that! With beautiful
people who wear your clothes well, and I had the money to do it . .
. `` A typical episode's costuming budget was $35,000, but Miller
says the budget could climb to $100,000. ``It'll never happen
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Would you rather be stranded on a desert isle with Mary Ann
or Ginger?
</P>
<P>
   A: (Miller): ``Certainly not Mary Ann. That stupid Mary Ann went
on a three-hour tour without a trunk of clothes!''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why did Ginger have so many dresses, anyway?
</P>
<P>
   A: (Miller): ``I always tell people that she was a showgirl on
her way to Vegas, so she was carrying everything with her.''
</P>
<P>
   Staci Sturrock writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. stacisturrock(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
