<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 10:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6327 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-MARIBEL-ALVAREZ23-COX     12-22 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARIBEL-ALVAREZ23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The world is her shopping mall,
 &HT;    By Loretta Grantham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Maribel Alvarez recently bet on a
Dolphins game.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they won, my friend said she'd pay for me and another
friend to spend a week at Doral Saturnia,'' she says, referring to
the swank Miami spa where robe-clad socialites agonize over whether
to schedule a Swedish massage or shiatsu. ``If they lost, I'd do
some work for her for free.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, Maribel's going to Miami. And her pal's going to be out
about six grand.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS) I won five bucks on a Fins game once. And a
beer. (END ITALICS)
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: Maribel frolics with rich folks. Really rich folks.
The echelon whose wish list includes 10-carat radiant-cut diamonds,
original Renoirs and hideaways on the Riviera. Even a 1713 heirloom
rug once owned by the queen of Denmark. (And you thought your
family was tough to shop for.)
</P>
<P>
   The daughter of Cuban immigrants who sent her to boarding school
in Switzerland (''Le Rosey alumni are a key part of my network''),
Maribel is a global-scale human eBay, the pickiest of purveyors for
those with discriminating tastes.
</P>
<P>
   She'll also woo Yugoslavian royalty to show up at your cocktail
party. Or help you fill a banquet table for 10 at a charity ball.
All for a fee.
</P>
<P>
   Today, though, it's just us two at Bice, where Maribel orders
``seafood salad, no potatoes'' in Italian between puffs on a Benson
&AMP; Hedges. She also speaks French and Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   About eight months ago, Maribel _ a divorced mom of three _
created a career out of her jet-set Rolodex, launching Altima
International, a high-end concierge-type company in Palm Beach.
Next month, she'll open her upstairs Worth Avenue office with a
splashy soiree featuring ``a caviar sampling'' (beluga and sevruga
and osetra, oh my!) and all the top-shelf vodka you can guzzle.
</P>
<P>
   Her connections come from worldwide travel; serving as a
diplomat for Costa Rica (her dad dealt in oil there); and popping
up at every party from here to the Hamptons to Nepal (where she
bought the wooden-bead prayer bracelet she wears alongside her gold
Cartier watch).
</P>
<P>
   Altima's rates vary, but consultations run $125 an hour.
Marketing for a major department store, $2,000 a month. Locating a
rare painting, a percentage of the selling price (which is
determined by the selling price, usually six figures).
</P>
<P>
   ``Money is no object to many of my clients,'' says Maribel, 40,
in an Armani suit she scored on sale at Loehmann's. ``But what they
do demand is the best possible deal. That's where I come in. I do
the homework.''
</P>
<P>
   Because when you're a time-pressed tycoon, there just ain't
enough hours in the day.
</P>
<P>
   Says a client: ``She's very straightforward in business and very
knowledgeable. Everyone knows her.''
</P>
<P>
   He recently bought a $2.5 million warehouse with the help of
Maribel's cohort, Realtor Maura Landers. Then there's the art
(''$100,000 and up'') and jewelry (''$50,000 and up'').
</P>
<P>
   ``I pass these things along to her,'' the entrepreneur says,
requesting anonymity (which Maribel ensures). ``There are certain
things I just don't want to be bothered with.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS) Whew! Me, neither. Last time I hunted down a
hangar for my Gulfstream V, it was SUCH a hassle. (END ITALICS)
</P>
<P>
   Despite her links to the lofty, Maribel puts on no airs. Nor
pantyhose, nor earrings. And makeup is minimal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obvious I don't do much with my hair,'' she says,
shrugging. ``But I don't fuss with that kind of stuff. I put on a
baseball cap, and I'm there.''
</P>
<P>
   Driving her 5-year-old, beat-up blue Toyota 4-Runner. (''If you
saw it, you'd die.'')
</P>
<P>
   Maribel, who has two sons at home _ ages 11 and 4, and a
daughter, 17, at Le Rosey _ is usually at her desk by 7 in the
morning for phone calls ad naseum. Then a meeting. Then more phone
calls. Then more meetings. You get the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Today, however, she's sans cell phone so that we may eat in
peace. But the restaurant itself is noisy, still bustling with the
lunch crowd although it's nearly 3 p.m. on a weekday. No
clock-punchers here.
</P>
<P>
   Maribel, meanwhile, is one of those folks who had a privileged
upbringing but doesn't fully realize it, which is part of what
makes her so likable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't grow up with all the money in the world,'' she says,
referring to her parents and two older brothers, who left Cuba for
the States in 1959. ``We had some. But they had to sell the yacht
to send me to boarding school. I was always the poorest in the
group.''
</P>
<P>
   Widowed at 25 by her first husband, an attorney, Maribel went on
to wed an aeronautical designer. The couple, seeking a more serene
spot for the kids, moved to Palm Beach in the early '80s, then
divorced in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Her third marriage _ to a real estate investor _ ended last
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having children is wonderful, but I'm just not good at
marriage,'' Maribel says. ``Maybe I'm too independent. But I'm
still good friends with my exes.''
</P>
<P>
   And good friends with Gino, our suave maitre 'd, who glides over
to ask if we wish to conclude our lunch with cappuccino. (''No
cafe,'' she replies.)
</P>
<P>
   And good friends with Ashton de Peyster _ as in Northeast
banking fortune (even his name sounds rich!) _ who yells hello from
across the street as we walk down Worth.
</P>
<P>
   When she isn't scavenging for stuff most of us can neither
afford nor pronounce, she heads to the mountains (''I love Peru,
but I'm thinking about India'') or watches Dan Marino with her
sons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a huge Dolphins fan!'' gushes Maribel, who's on a waiting
list for her visit to Doral.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS) If only she could help Marino find someone to
catch the ball. (END ITALICS)
</P>
<P>
   Loretta Grantham writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla. E-mail: lorettagrantham(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
