<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991222.0076 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 11:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6329 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS23-TAKE     12-22 1883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS23-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: Take 1 of two takes.)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: I read recently that a chunk of ancient ocean floor was found
1,550 miles beneath the Earth's crust. How was that discovery made?
Surely no drill could reach that deep.
</P>
<P>
   A: You're right, a drill (or ``corer'') isn't involved, because
it could go no deeper than 4-5 miles. Earle Holland of Ohio State
University explained that scientists send sound waves through the
Earth's mantle layer. That way, they can determine the distances
involved by studying the time and trajectory of the return of the
sound waves to seismic monitoring stations.
</P>
<P>
   Acoustic energy travels through different types of mantle
material at different speeds, Holland added. The warmer the
material, the longer it takes for sound energy to pass through.
</P>
<P>
   Using supercomputers to analyze the travel times and paths of
thousands of seismic waves, seismologists can create a
three-dimensional image _ similar to a CAT scan of a human body _
of the Earth's interior. That technique gave them the reading of
1,550 miles.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm going to be in Washington on New Year's Eve. Some time
ago, I heard about a big celebration, but I haven't seen anything
since and can't find a source of information. Can you help?
</P>
<P>
   A: The America's Millennium celebration on the National Mall
will begin at 11 a.m. Dec. 31. President Clinton and first lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton and others will participate in a ceremony
that will include concerts and the unveiling of the National
Millennium Time Capsule. Lectures, demonstrations and performances
are scheduled at Smithsonian Institution museums.
</P>
<P>
   A ``colossal'' New Year's Eve gala at the Lincoln Memorial,
hosted by Will Smith, will focus on American music of the century
and will include appearances by Trisha Yearwood, Jessye Norman,
Kathleen Battle, Robert Duvall, the company of ``Stomp,'' and
bands, choirs and marching units of the U.S. armed forces. ``The
Unfinished Journey,'' an 18-minute Steven Spielberg film on the
highlights of the 20th century, will be shown for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   The celebration culminates in a ``Midnight Moment,'' a high-tech
sound and light display. All events are free and open to the
public. Information is available online at http://160.111.100.129/
or by calling 1-888-294-2100.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is eggnog safe? My recipe calls for cream, sugar and
uncooked, beaten egg whites and yolks. Plus a gracious plenty of
rum, brandy or bourbon. Does the booze neutralize salmonella or
other possible contaminants?
</P>
<P>
   A: The alcohol doesn't neutralize the potential risk, said Chris
Rosenbloom, a professor at Georgia State University's department of
nutrition and a spokeswoman for the American Dietetic Association.
But you can enjoy your holiday beverage without the questionable
raw eggs by using as a substitute a pasturized egg product, which
is packaged in cartons and usually can be found in the same
refrigerated section with eggs.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Headline News recently reported on grades given to U.S.
cities to identify the best ones for raising children. How did they
rank? Where can I get more information?
</P>
<P>
   A: You're referring to the Kid Friendly Cities Report Card,
issued by Zero Population Growth. Check online at
www.zpg.org/kidfriendlycities/index.html or call 1-800-767-1956 for
information. As ``kid friendly'' implies, the report card is based
on data Zero Population Growth calls ``the best available'' on the
social, economic, educational and physical environment of U.S.
cities ``where our children live, grow, learn and play.''
</P>
<P>
   The rankings of 25 major cities: Seattle, A+; San Francisco, A;
San Jose, Calif., A-; San Diego, B+; Portland, Ore., Pittsburgh and
Denver, B; Minneapolis, B-; Boston, New York and Fort Worth, Texas.
C+; Phoenix, Tampa, Dallas and Houston, C; Philadelphia, Los
Angeles and Chicago, C-; Atlanta, Cleveland, Miami, Washington and
Detroit, D; and St. Louis and Baltimore, F.
</P>
<P>
   The ratings are based on such factors as teen births, infant
mortality rate, percentage of children in pre-school, student
dropout rate, violent crimes, property crimes, unemployment rate,
percentage of children in poverty, number of bad air days, public
transportation, and average commute.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A newspaper report about compensation for Nazi slave laborers
in Germany said some U.S. companies were contributing to a fund.
What companies?
</P>
<P>
   A: General Motors and Ford Motor Co. were the major ones whose
names have been made public, but it's said that ``up to 200''
American companies with German subsidiaries are potentially
involved. According to published accounts, they would create a fund
of roughly $500 million, separate from a $5.2 billion fund
negotiated by the German government, U.S. lawyers representing
former slave laborers, and more than 250 German companies.
</P>
<P>
   Ford, one of the first to be named in a class-action suit over
Nazi-era forced labor, has said it's still considering whether to
take part in a fund. General Motors is involved because of its
German subsidiary, Opel. GM bought the German carmarker, Adam Opel,
more than 60 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Q: An article about Elian Gonzales, the Cuban child involved in
a custody battle, mentioned the Joe DiMaggio complex at a Florida
hospital. It reminded me of a question I have long wondered about.
Did DiMaggio and Marilyn Monroe have a child during their brief
marriage?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. DiMaggio's only child, Joe DiMaggio Jr., was born to the
marriage of the late Yankee Clipper and his first wife, actress
Dorothy Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I heard recently that four U.S. M1-A1 tanks were lost during
the Persian Gulf War. Do you have any details?
</P>
<P>
   A: Military officials confirmed that ``about'' four of the M1-A1
battle tanks _ each costing $2.7 million _ were lost during the
Persian Gulf War. But specifics of their loss weren't made public.
</P>
<P>
   However, it was known that an explosion in July 1991at a U.S.
Army depot at the Blackhorse Camp in Doha, Kuwait, was devastating
to equipment and personnel. More than 50 vehicles, including 14
M1-A1 tanks and Bradley Fighting Vehicles fully loaded with
ammunition, were damaged or destroyed. Eight howitzers, valued at
$1.5 million each, also were destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, officials said it was believed that the fire and
chain-reaction blasts were started by an electrical short on a
truck loaded with 155mm howitzer shells. A number of soldiers,
including 53 Americans, six Britons and a Canadian, were injured.
Most members of the 11th Armored Cavalry Regiment at Blackhorse
were on desert maneuvers at the time of the blast.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What was Mark McGwire's slugging percentage for this past
season, and how did it compare to whoever led the National League
and the Atlanta Braves in slugging percentages?
</P>
<P>
   A: Here are the NL's top 10 in slugging percentage, which will
answer all your questions, and a bit more:
</P>
<P>
   Larry Walker, Colorado Rockies, .710; Mark McGwire, St. Louis
Cardinals, .697; Sammy Sosa, Chicago Cubs, .635; Chipper Jones,
Atlanta Braves, .633; Brian Giles, Pittsburgh Pirates, .614;
Vladimir Guerrero, Montreal Expos, .600; Jeff Bagwell, Houston
Astros, .590; Todd Helton, Rockies, .587; Mike Piazza, New York
Mets, .575; Carl Everett, Astros, .571.
</P>
<P>
   A batter's slugging percentage is determined by dividing the
total number of bases of all base hits by the total number of times
at bat. Example: Say someone has 282 total bases and 440 at-bats.
Divide 282 by 440 to get the slugging percentage: .641.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's the explanation for the ``X'' in Xmas?
</P>
<P>
   A: It has historical origins. The Greek word that gives us the
English word Christ begins with the letter chi, or X, leading some
scholars to believe that the X in Xmas symbolized the cross.
</P>
<P>
   Xmas has been used to symbolize the word Christ in English since
at least 1100, when it was recorded in ``Xianity,'' for
Christianity. The Old English word for Christian recorded in the
12th century ``Anglo-Saxon Chronicle'' begins with an X, and the
word Xmas itself was used as early as the mid- 1500s.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I understand that Congress has ``borrowed'' large sums of
money from Social Security funds. Is this true?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's inaccurate to use the term ``borrowed,'' says Patti
Patterson of the Social Security Administration. A better word is
``invested,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   The trust funds in question are financial accounts in the U.S.
Treasury. Social Security and Medicare taxes, premiums and other
income are deposited into these accounts, and Social Security and
Medicare benefits are paid from them. There are four separate trust
funds: for Social Security, old-age and survivors insurance, and
disability insurance; and for Medicare, hospital insurance and
supplementary medical insurance.
</P>
<P>
   The only purposes for which these trust funds can be used are to
pay benefits and program administrative costs, according to the
agency. The trust funds hold money not needed in the current year
to pay those benefits and administrative costs so, as mandated by
law, the money is invested in special Treasury bonds guaranteed by
the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   A market rate of interest is paid to the trust funds on the
bonds they hold, and when those bonds reach maturity _ or are
needed to pay benefits _ the Treasury redeems them.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can fans send cards to wish Charles Schulz well? The
Peanuts creator is seriously ill and will discontinue the strip.
</P>
<P>
   A: Q&AMP;A printed the address not long ago, after it was reported
that Schulz had been treated for cancer, but it doesn't hurt to
repeat it now that he's said he is officially stopping. His
followers are legion, and he deserves an avalanche of fan mail.
Send cards to: Charles Schulz, One Snoopy Place, Santa Rosa, CA
95403-2665.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Vice President Al Gore went to divinity school after leaving
the Army. Which school, and for how long?
</P>
<P>
   A: After his Army enlistment ended in early autumn 1971, Gore _
who had graduated from Harvard in 1969 _ studied philosophy and
phenomenonoly at Vanderbilt University's Graduate School of
Religion in 1971-72. At the time, he also was working the night
shift at the Nashville Tennessean. Gore has explained before that
he went to divinity school ``to study the spiritual issues that
were most important to me at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1974 he enrolled in Vanderbilt's Law School, where he
remained for two years. He didn't obtain degrees from either the
divinity school or the law school.
</P>
<P>
   After learning in 1976 that Rep. Joe Evins (D-Tenn.) wouldn't be
running for re-election, Gore turned to a career in politics,
following in the footsteps of his father, Albert Gore Sr., a
Democrat who had served in the U.S. House and the U.S. Senate.
Young Al beat eight Democrats in the 1976 primary, won the general
election, and served four terms. In 1984, he was elected to the
Senate. You know the rest.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE _ END TAKE 1 OF TWO TAKES)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
