<P>
   Q: When did the minimum wage begin, and what was it? Can you
list the increases over the years?
</P>
<P>
   A: When federal minimum wage legislation went into effect in
October 1938 _ as established by the Fair Labor Standard Act of
that same year _ the minimum wage was 25 cents an hour. Amendments
have raised it many times since then. Here's the chronology:
</P>
<P>
   October 1939, 30 cents an hour; October 1945, 40 cents; January
1950, 75 cents; March 1956, $1; September 1961, $1.15; September
1963, $1.25; February 1967, $1.40; February 1968, $1.60; May 1974,
$2; January 1975, $2.10; January 1976, $2.30; January 1978, $2.65;
January 1979, $2.90; January 1980, $3.10; January 1981, $3.35;
April 1990, $3.80; April 1991, $4.25; October 1996, $4.75;
September 1997, $5.15. A minimum of $6.15 is proposed for 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When will we able to get information about tickets for the
Major League Baseball All-Star Game at Atlanta's Turner Field next
summer?
</P>
<P>
   A: Details aren't yet available. Ticket information will be
released in the spring, possibly around the time spring training
begins. The date of the game is July 11.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What should you do if you suspect your neighbors and/or their
children of stealing mail from your mailbox?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's the responsibility of the Postal Inspection Service, the
law enforcement branch of the U.S. Postal Service, to investigate
any crimes or suspected crimes related to the mail.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can I get into the audience for the Oprah Winfrey Show?
</P>
<P>
   A: You need to make a reservation for the Chicago studio taping
by calling 312-591-9222 between 9 a.m. and 5 p.m. Chicago (Central
Standard) time. Tickets aren't available by mail or e-mail, and
walk-ins aren't allowed. The program generally is taped at 9 a.m.
and noon (CST) on Tuesdays, Wednesdays and Thursdays. Days and
times of taping are subject to change.
</P>
<P>
   Audience members must be 16 or older. Anyone younger than 18
must be accompanied by a parent, and must show a birth certificate
for verification.
</P>
<P>
   The show always goes on hiatus for an indefinite period each
summer. There are no show tapings, and the reservations department
is closed. It reopens in early August to accept reservations for
tapings beginning in September.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Some news organizations have begun referring to Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright with the title ``Dr.'' When and where did
she receive a Ph.D., and in what area of study?
</P>
<P>
   A: Here is Albright's post-high school educational history. In
1959, she was awarded a B.A. with honors in political science from
Wellesley College in Massachusetts. She then studied at Johns
Hopkins University's School of Advanced International Studies in
Washington, and in 1968 earned both an M.A. and a certificate in
Russian studies from the Department of Public Law and Government at
Columbia University in New York.
</P>
<P>
   She received her Ph.D. in 1976, also from Columbia's Department
of Public Law and Government. Her doctoral dissertation was on the
part played by the press in the abortive attempt by Czech
dissidents in 1968 to loosen the grip of communism in their
country.
</P>
<P>
   Just after she received her Ph.D., Albright joined the staff of
Sen. Edmund Muskie as his chief legislative assistant. As she told
a writer at the time, ``That made it possible for Sen. Muskie to
introduce me as Dr. Albright, instead of Madeleine Albright, little
housewife.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to her own studies, Albright has been a research
professor of international affairs and director of the Women in
Foreign Service Program at Georgetown University's School of
Foreign Service in Washington, where she taught undergraduate and
graduate courses in international affairs and in Central and
Eastern European politics. In 1981, she was a senior fellow in
Soviet and Eastern European affairs at Washington's 2 by 440 to get
the slugging percentage: .641.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's the explanation for the ``X'' in Xmas?
</P>
<P>
   A: It has historical origins. The Greek word that gives us the
English word Christ begins with the letter chi, or X, leading some
scholars to believe that the X in Xmas symbolized the cross.
</P>
<P>
   Xmas has been used to symbolize the word Christ in English since
at least 1100, when it was recorded in ``Xianity,'' for
Christianity. The Old English word for Christian recorded in the
12th century ``Anglo-Saxon Chronicle'' begins with an X, and the
word Xmas itself was used as early as the mid- 1500s.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I understand that Congress has ``borrowed'' large sums of
money from Social Security funds. Is this true?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's inaccurate to use the term ``borrowed,'' says Patti
Patterson of the Social Security Administration. A better word is
``invested,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   The trust funds in question are financial accounts in the U.S.
Treasury. Social Security and Medicare taxes, premiums and other
income are deposited into these accounts, and Social Security and
Medicare benefits are paid from them. There are four separate trust
funds: for Social Security, old-age and survivors insurance, and
disability insurance; and for Medicare, hospital insurance and
supplementary medical insurance.
</P>
<P>
   The only purposes for which these trust funds can be used are to
pay benefits and program administrative costs, according to the
agency. The trust funds hold money not needed in the current year
to pay those benefits and administrative costs so, as mandated by
law, the money is invested in special Treasury bonds guaranteed by
the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   A market rate of interest is paid to the trust funds on the
bonds they hold, and when those bonds reach maturity _ or are
needed to pay benefits _ the Treasury redeems them.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can fans send cards to wish Charles Schulz well? The
Peanuts creator is seriously ill and will discontinue the strip.
</P>
<P>
   A: Q&AMP;A printed the addrey. Which school, and for how long?
</P>
<P>
   A: After his Army enlistment ended in early autumn 1971, Gore _
who had graduated from Harvard in 1969 _ studied philosophy and
phenomenonoly at Vanderbilt University's Graduate School of
Religion in 1971-72. At the time, he also was working the night
shift at the Nashville Tennessean. Gore has explained before that
he went to divinity school ``to study the spiritual issues that
were most important to me at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1974 he enrolled in Vanderbilt's Law School, where he
remained for two years. He didn't obtain degrees from either the
divinity school or the law school.
</P>
<P>
   After learning in 1976 that Rep. Joe Evins (D-Tenn.) wouldn't be
running for re-election, Gore turned to a career in politics,
following in the footsteps of his father, Albert Gore Sr., a
Democrat who had served in the U.S. House and the U.S. Senate.
Young Al beat eight Democrats in the 1976 primary, won the general
election, and served four terms. In 1984, he was elected to the
Senate. You know the rest.
</P>
