</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: Take two of two.)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: When did the minimum wage begin, and what was it? Can you
list the increases over the years?
</P>
<P>
   A: When federal minimum wage legislation went into effect in
October 1938 _ as established by the Fair Labor Standard Act of
that same year _ the minimum wage was 25 cents an hour. Amendments
have raised it many times since then. Here's the chronology:
</P>
<P>
   October 1939, 30 cents an hour; October 1945, 40 cents; January
1950, 75 cents; March 1956, $1; September 1961, $1.15; September
1963, $1.25; February 1967, $1.40; February 1968, $1.60; May 1974,
$2; January 1975, $2.10; January 1976, $2.30; January 1978, $2.65;
January 1979, $2.90; January 1980, $3.10; January 1981, $3.35;
April 1990, $3.80; April 1991, $4.25; October 1996, $4.75;
September 1997, $5.15. A minimum of $6.15 is proposed for 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When will we able to get information about tickets for the
Major League Baseball All-Star Game at Atlanta's Turner Field next
summer?
</P>
<P>
   A: Details aren't yet available. Ticket information will be
released in the spring, possibly around the time spring training
begins. The date of the game is July 11.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What should you do if you suspect your neighbors and/or their
children of stealing mail from your mailbox?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's the responsibility of the Postal Inspection Service, the
law enforcement branch of the U.S. Postal Service, to investigate
any crimes or suspected crimes related to the mail.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can I get into the audience for the Oprah Winfrey Show?
</P>
<P>
   A: You need to make a reservation for the Chicago studio taping
by calling 312-591-9222 between 9 a.m. and 5 p.m. Chicago (Central
Standard) time. Tickets aren't available by mail or e-mail, and
walk-ins aren't allowed. The program generally is taped at 9 a.m.
and noon (CST) on Tuesdays, Wednesdays and Thursdays. Days and
times of taping are subject to change.
</P>
<P>
   Audience members must be 16 or older. Anyone younger than 18
must be accompanied by a parent, and must show a birth certificate
for verification.
</P>
<P>
   The show always goes on hiatus for an indefinite period each
summer. There are no show tapings, and the reservations department
is closed. It reopens in early August to accept reservations for
tapings beginning in September.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Some news organizations have begun referring to Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright with the title ``Dr.'' When and where did
she receive a Ph.D., and in what area of study?
</P>
<P>
   A: Here is Albright's post-high school educational history. In
1959, she was awarded a B.A. with honors in political science from
Wellesley College in Massachusetts. She then studied at Johns
Hopkins University's School of Advanced International Studies in
Washington, and in 1968 earned both an M.A. and a certificate in
Russian studies from the Department of Public Law and Government at
Columbia University in New York.
</P>
<P>
   She received her Ph.D. in 1976, also from Columbia's Department
of Public Law and Government. Her doctoral dissertation was on the
part played by the press in the abortive attempt by Czech
dissidents in 1968 to loosen the grip of communism in their
country.
</P>
<P>
   Just after she received her Ph.D., Albright joined the staff of
Sen. Edmund Muskie as his chief legislative assistant. As she told
a writer at the time, ``That made it possible for Sen. Muskie to
introduce me as Dr. Albright, instead of Madeleine Albright, little
housewife.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to her own studies, Albright has been a research
professor of international affairs and director of the Women in
Foreign Service Program at Georgetown University's School of
Foreign Service in Washington, where she taught undergraduate and
graduate courses in international affairs and in Central and
Eastern European politics. In 1981, she was a senior fellow in
Soviet and Eastern European affairs at Washington's Center for
Strategic and International Studies, and in 1981-82 she was a
fellow at the Woodrow Wilson International Center for Scholars at
the Smithsonian Institution, Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, Henry Kissinger was referred to on occasion as
``Dr. Kissinger,'' so ``Dr. Albright'' isn't a first.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is there any chance that the failed Mars Polar Lander had the
same miscalculation from metric to standard as the failed Mars
Climate Observer that burned up several months ago?
</P>
<P>
   A: There's ``no way'' that the cause of the Polar Lander's
failure was the same, said Mary Hardin of NASA's Jet Propulsion
Laboratory in Pasadena, Calif. NASA teams ``double checked and
triple checked'' to make sure there were no problems with
conversions, she told Q&AMP;A, ``so we're confident that that was not
the issue.''
</P>
<P>
   However, she said JPL scientists didn't know what the problem
was with the Lander, because the scientists purposely turned off
the JPL transmitters to avoid interfering with the computer
programs that were running at the time the Lander was doing its
``complicated process'' of entry, descent and landing on Mars.
</P>
<P>
   The Lander was supposed to have attempted to reach the surface
of Mars Dec. 3, but NASA lost contact with it, despite several
attempts. The JPL said Dec. 7 that mission controllers would
continue to try to communicate with the Lander for another two
weeks or so, but expectations for success were remote.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I read that a trust fund has been set up for Travis Butler,
the 9-year-old who kept his mother's death a secret for a month for
fear he would be sent to a foster home. How can we contribute?
</P>
<P>
   A: Send donations to: National Bank of Commerce, 1 Commerce
Square, Memphis TN 38150. Make checks out to the Travis Butler
Fund, and designate on the check that it is for this account
number: 4770251.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A brief item reported that an anonymous buyer purchased a
Paul Cezanne painting for $30 million that had been stolen from a
Massachusetts home in 1978. Why wasn't it given back to the people
from whom it was taken, rather than being sold at auction?
</P>
<P>
   A: The painting, which was reported stolen 21 years ago from Dr.
Harry Bakwin, a New York child psychologist who was a major Cezanne
collector, in fact had been returned to members of the Bakwin
family. But few details of the theft and recovery are known.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times reported that the painting, ``Pewter Pitcher
and Fruit,'' was recovered recently after Lloyd's, the London
insurance exchange, approached the Art Loss Register, an
international database for stolen and missing art and antiques.
Julian Radcliffe, chairman of the Art Loss Register, said Lloyd's
had received a vague inquiry from someone seeking information
related to the painting, but he didn't know who made the inquiry or
who stole the painting. Nobody is saying how the painting was
recovered, but it ended up with members of the Bakwin family, who
decided to sell it.
</P>
<P>
   Radcliffe said that the police and/or the FBI couldn't make an
arrest in the theft, even if they knew who did it, because the
seven-year statute of limitations for such thefts had expired.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where did the term ``spam'' come from when referring to junk
e-mail? Is it a takeoff on the meat product?
</P>
<P>
   A: The term comes from the Monty Python sketch in which a
couple's attempt to order breakfast leads to the waitress reeling
off a lengthy list of entrees: ``Spam, Spam, Spam, Spam and Spam.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Will you print the poem read by Sen. Edward Kennedy at the
memorial service for the Massachusetts firemen who lost their
lives?
</P>
<P>
   A: The poem is titled ``May They Not Be Forgotten'':
</P>
<P>
   Brother when you weep for me,/ Remember that it was meant to
be./ Lay me down and when you leave,/ Remember I'll be at your
sleeve./ In every dark and choking hall,/ I'll be there as you
slowly crawl./
</P>
<P>
   On every roof in driving snow,/ I'll hold your coat and you will
know./ In cellars hot with searing heat,/ At windows where a gate
you meet,/ In closets where young children hide,/ You know I'll be
there at your side./
</P>
<P>
   The house from which I now respond/ Is overstaffed with heroes
gone./ Men who answered one last bell/ Did the job and did it
well./ As firemen, we understand/ That death's a card dealt in our
hand _ / A card we hope we never play,/ But one we hold there
anyway./ That card is something we ignore,/ As we crawl across a
weakened floor./ For we know that we're the only prayer/ For anyone
that might be there./
</P>
<P>
   So remember, as you wipe away your tears,/ The joy I knew
throughout the years./ As I did the job I loved to do,/ I pray that
thought will see you through.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
