<DOCNO> NYT19991222.0079 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 11:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6332 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-ASK-A-DIETITIAN23-COX     12-22 0498
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASK-A-DIETITIAN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ask a dietitian
 &HT;    By Karen Collins, M.S.
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Is corn considered a vegetable or a grain?
</P>
<P>
   A: Botanically and nutritionally speaking, corn is a grain. Corn
is more concentrated in starch (carbohydrate) and calories than
true vegetables such as broccoli, cucumbers and green beans.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes people who have trouble controlling their weight or
blood sugar have been building too much of their meals around
starchy foods _ potatoes and rolls or bread and starchy vegetables
_ without including abundant servings of green, red and orange
vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Corn is a good source of dietary fiber since it retains all
three of its primary layers.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are canned fruits and vegetables less nutritious than fresh?
</P>
<P>
   A: Canned fruits and veggies might not look as appealing as
their fresh counterparts, but when it comes to nutrition, don't
count them out.
</P>
<P>
   Fruits and vegetables destined for the cannery are picked at
full ripeness and processed within hours. This gives them a
nutritional head start over produce for green-grocer shelves, which
is generally picked several days earlier to withstand the stress
and time of transport. Once canned, the nutritional content remains
stable for up to two years. In contrast, fresh produce continues to
lose sensitive nutrients until consumed.
</P>
<P>
   Canning and cooking also yield some advantages. Heat breaks down
cell structures, increasing the amount of beta-carotene and
lycopene, a cancer-fighting antioxidant found in tomatoes. It also
kills bacteria, and the vacuum created during canning keeps the
contents safe until opened. Easy-to-store and ready-to-use, canned
foods offer convenience and can significantly cut meal preparation
time.
</P>
<P>
   On the downside, canning, like cooking, causes the loss of some
heat-sensitive and water-soluble nutrients, although most can be
reclaimed by using the canning liquid. Canned foods tend to be
higher in salt and sugars, which makes it advisable to look for
low-sodium and juice-packed versions.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is process cheese?
</P>
<P>
   A: Process cheese is made by combining one or more natural
cheeses with an added emulsifier. The result is a cheese that melts
evenly, slices easily and has a more stable keeping quality.
Process cheese also develops an extremely smooth texture. Like
natural cheese, process cheese may be fat-free, reduced-fat, or of
standard fat content (8 to 9 grams of fat per ounce). The protein
and mineral content-- of natural and process cheese are generally
similar, but the ingredients added to process cheese generally
about double sodium content.
</P>
<P>
   Ask a Dietitian questions were answered by Karen Collins, M.S.,
R.D. of the American Institute for Cancer Research and Dr. Janice
Stuff, a registered dietitian with the USDA/ARS Children's
Nutrition Research Center at Baylor College of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
