<DOCNO> NYT19991222.0082 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 11:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6335 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-KAUFMAN-FATHER23-COX     12-22 2352
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KAUFMAN-FATHER23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    To dad, Andy Kaufman was tender son
 &HT;    By Charles Passy
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ There is the Andy Kaufman the world
remembers. The irreverent, lost-in-the-clouds comic who entertained
crowds with his impressions of a bumbling foreigner and
hip-swiveling Elvis. And who challenged them with his act as a
brutish wrestler and foul-mouthed lounge lizard.
</P>
<P>
   And there is the Andy Kaufman that Stanley Kaufman, the late
comedian's father, remembers. The nice Jewish boy-turned-man who
never stopped calling his parents Mommy and Daddy. The son who
insisted on having his brother and sister join him atop a Macy's
Thanksgiving Day parade float. The son who helped turn every family
gathering into a virtual variety show.
</P>
<P>
   It's the former Andy Kaufman who will be on display on screens
around the country in ``Man on the Moon.''
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't stop Stanley Kaufman, a Palm Beach Gardens
resident for the past decade, from remembering what he calls the
real Andy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what the commercial aspects require,'' says the
77-year-old retiree, speaking from the patio of his home
overlooking a golf course. ``But I also know that it's not the
story of my son's life. It's a portion, and it's an exaggerated
portion.''
</P>
<P>
   If not a rags-to-riches tale, the full story is certainly an
emotional epic, beginning with Andy's days in the family's Long
Island home, where the young boy used to turn his bedroom into a
make-believe TV studio. Then, he went on to become an entertainer
at children's birthday parties and, after high school, a budding
stand-up comedian on New York's club circuit.
</P>
<P>
   The early years of ``Saturday Night Live'' made Kaufman a comic
force, offering him exposure for his Elvis, Mighty Mouse and
conga-drumming bits. The sitcom ``Taxi,'' in which he played a
clueless, foreign-born mechanic, made him a household name.
</P>
<P>
   But almost by his own maniacal design, his career started to
decline, partly because Kaufman insisted on pursuing a form of
comedy-as-performance art that required audience alienation to
succeed. And then, despite a relatively healthy lifestyle, he was
stricken with a rare lung cancer and died in 1984 at the age of 35.
</P>
<P>
   As for Stanley, there was a chapter after Andy. Following a long
career in the costume jewelry business, he moved from New York to
South Florida for the good life. And despite weathering a trio of
tragedies _ the deaths of Andy and Stanley's first and second wives
_ he appears to be enjoying it. His spacious home in a gated
community reflects his love of travel and art: Works by
photographer Irving Penn and pop-art painter Keith Haring grace the
walls.
</P>
<P>
   When he's not taking in his view of the golf course, he's out on
it, joining a group of friends for a regular game.
</P>
<P>
   But there's been little time for such pleasures in recent weeks.
He has attended events and screenings in New York and is doing the
same in Hollywood. He's been interviewed on MSNBC and ABC's ``Good
Morning America.'' Naturally, it's all because of the movie and two
new Kaufman biographies: Bill Zehme's authorized account, ``Lost in
the Funhouse'' (Delacorte Press) and former Kaufman sidekick Bob
Zmuda's more tabloid-inspired version, ``Andy Kaufman Revealed!''
(Little, Brown and Company). Zmuda is also co-executive producer of
the Milos Forman film.
</P>
<P>
   The projects have clearly elevated Kaufman's reputation. Some
critics even suggest that he faked his death as the con to end all
cons. Could it be true?
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course not,'' says Stanley. His sudden quietness catches a
visitor off guard. It's a poignant reminder that, amidst all the
hoopla, the recent events resonate on a different level for him:
This is a story, after all, of a father losing a son.
</P>
<P>
   And that father shaped the son, mostly for the better. Author
Zehme believes that, if it weren't for Stanley, Kaufman could have
easily foundered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Stanley rode him hard enough to keep him alive,'' he
says, noting Andy's teenage days of abusing drugs and skipping
school. He adds that Stanley took a keen interest in his son's
talent, even if he didn't always understand it. He begins the
second chapter of his biography with an account of Stanley and a
5-year-old Andy in an amusement-park recording booth, the father
asking the boy, ``How 'bout a little song for us?''
</P>
<P>
   ``That is so lovely,'' Zehme says. ``To see a father encourage
this performing spirit in his son at such a young age.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanley's daughter, Carol Kaufman Kerman, now married and
raising three children in the Chicago area, says her father gave
Andy the gift of freedom. Whereas most parents in the family's
predominantly Jewish community wanted their children to become
doctors and lawyers, Stanley didn't follow the herd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my father had wider boundaries than other fathers in
Great Neck,'' she says. ``He had pride in having an old tattered
couch in his living room when everybody else was getting new stuff.
He felt more real to me. And I think he gave that kind of grounding
to Andy. He certainly gave him a lot of relentless love.''
</P>
<P>
   By Stanley's admission, he was far from the perfect dad. A
thrice-decorated World War II veteran, he was given to frequent
fits of rage, especially during the post-war years when he ran his
father's struggling jewelry company. (It was eventually sold, and
Stanley started his own firm.)
</P>
<P>
   And he found plenty to yell at when it came to Kaufman, be it
his oldest child's poor grades or unkempt hair _ to say nothing of
the fact that the boy kept himself cloistered in his room for
hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was not the easiest kid in the world,'' Stanley recalls.
``He was very, very curious. He wouldn't accept the things that
were handed to him. He always questioned.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Stanley encouraged Andy, escorting him to
children's birthday parties where the teenage entertainer first
began practicing his juvenile-inspired comedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ended up with a hernia from carrying the sound projector,''
he says, joking affectionately. And he credits Andy's mother,
Janice, with being even more supportive: She's the one who kept the
house quiet and stable, particularly in the rough-and-tumble years
when Andy was heading into New York comedy clubs late at night,
looking for a break. ``He was really loved,'' says Stanley, ``and
he loved in return.''
</P>
<P>
   The father also made peace with Andy when their relationship was
fractured. Noting how his beatnik-loving son never left the house
without a copy of Jack Kerouac's ``On the Road,'' he decided to
read the novel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved it,'' he says without hesitation. Andy caught him one
day crying over a particular passage. ``Together we read, and
together we cried, and the whole thing was reconciled,'' Stanley
remembers. ``And after that, I never saw how long his hair was.''
</P>
<P>
   But did he see his comedic talent? Stanley is not without a
playful side: Ask him to pose for a photo, and he'll suggest swim
trunks for a poolside spread. And his quirky sense of humor often
helped his business: He once interrupted a tense meeting with a
group of bankers, saying it was time for jumping jacks, a stunt
that could have come straight from the mind of Andy.
</P>
<P>
   But Stanley admits he favors Andy's more traditional work,
particularly his five-year run as the helpless Latka on ``Taxi.''
Ironically, that's the comedy Andy cared for the least.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hated doing other people's material,'' Stanley says. But
the father, who managed his son's finances during his life and
oversees much of his estate today, knew that ``Taxi'' would provide
Andy with security and freedom. ``It made him an international
figure.''
</P>
<P>
   What Andy chose to do with such success shocked his fans _ and
his family. Remembering his love for the great wrestlers of
yesteryear, he created his own wrestling show _ but with a twist:
He challenged only women.
</P>
<P>
   Then he took one of his many alter egos, the loathsome nightclub
singer Tony Clifton, and appeared as the singer on stage and talk
shows, all the while insisting that he and Clifton were separate
people. It had the odd effect of turning Andy from an innocent,
not-quite-of-this-planet entertainer _ a ``man on the moon,'' if
you will _ into a pig of a showman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hated the wrestling. We didn't like Tony Clifton,'' says
Stanley, who blames Bob Zmuda _ Andy's ``so-called best friend'' _
for guiding his career in this direction. ``We sensed it was not
helping. People didn't like the character he was portraying . . .
It wasn't Andy.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's precisely the point, argues Zmuda. Andy saw the dark
side of comedy and relished the opportunity to wear as many masks
as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's exactly what Andy does, he blurs the line between
fantasy and reality,'' Zmuda explains, speaking as if Andy were
still alive. By taking it to the highest degree _ by creating an
act that would make him universally hated _ Zmuda feels Andy proved
himself the ultimate performer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Andy never wrestled or never did Clifton, nobody would
care. It's because Andy went over the line and got into these
dangerous areas,'' he says. ``His legacy is not Latka, and I know
that's hard for Stanley to swallow.''
</P>
<P>
   The difference of opinion might have remained just that were it
not for the movie, whose title comes from an REM song celebrating
Andy. Suddenly, Stanley finds himself engaged in a daily battle
with Zmuda, fighting to restore what he believes is his son's true
reputation. He's particularly angered that the film makes almost no
reference to Andy's family, even though they were brought in as
consultants and spent several days working with the screenwriters
and Carrey.
</P>
<P>
   ``His character, his personality as a human being were never
presented in the movie, and I'm not happy about that,'' Stanley
says, although he credits Carrey with an Oscar-worthy, finely
detailed performance. ``When I first saw him (on the set), I just
broke down. This was Andy.''
</P>
<P>
   The battle between Stanley and Zmuda has gone beyond the media.
In an event many believed was staged, Zmuda, disguised as Clifton,
interrupted a ``Man on the Moon'' press conference two weeks ago,
wrestling with Carrey and pretending to urinate.
</P>
<P>
   But staged or not, Stanley has had enough: The family is legally
forbidding Zmuda from making any more appearances as Clifton,
unless they're sanctioned by Universal Pictures, the studio behind
``Man on the Moon.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Zmuda has supporters of his wild-man view of Andy _
and many believe the press-conference flap was the kind of
shenanigans Andy would have scripted if he were alive. When it
comes to the darker Andy, says former girlfriend Lynne Margulies,
``I think Stanley just doesn't get why it's funny. And he's also
looking out for his son. He wants his son to be loved.''
</P>
<P>
   Margulies, a television director who's now making a documentary
about Andy for the A&AMP;E network, adds that she sees more than a
little of Stanley in Clifton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stanley really yelled a lot,'' she says, noting that, while
Andy's love for his dad ran deep, the shouting also drove him
inward. If anything, she believes Andy's childlike fantasy world _
the basis of his peculiar brand of comedy _ emerged as an escape
from a turbulent household.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even Margulies (played in the movie by Courtney Love)
says it's hard not to be charmed by Stanley, calling him ``a real
ladies' man'' and crediting him with making significant strides
toward understanding Andy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's great for him to be reflective,'' she says,
adding that Andy ``wasn't holding a grudge as far as I can tell.''
</P>
<P>
   And don't think Stanley is incapable of comprehending all of
Andy's comedy. ``I've occasionally gotten calls from Tony Clifton's
father,'' Zehme says.
</P>
<P>
   Zehme also calls Stanley ``the pillar of strength'' when it came
time for the family to face the loss of Andy. Ever the respectful
son, Andy kept his illness a secret from his parents because he
didn't want to trouble his mother, who had suffered a stroke around
the same time.
</P>
<P>
   By the time word got to Stanley, Andy was barely able to move.
In his book, Zehme describes how the grief-stricken father lifted
his son onto a hospital table for a final radiation treatment.
</P>
<P>
   But life continued for Stanley following Andy. And even the
death two years ago of his second wife, Mildred, hasn't slowed him
down. His house may seem a little too big for a 77-year-old
bachelor, but he fills it with his pistol-like personality _ and
with plenty of memorabilia from Andy's career. (His favorite of all
the photos? A picture of a grown-up Andy indulging in a dish of ice
cream, his favorite treat.)
</P>
<P>
   After the film opens, Stanley suspects life will return to
normal. He'll get back to his golf game. He'll drive up
occasionally to the apartment he keeps in New York. He'll tool
around his gated community in his '75 Buick, a car he keeps just to
get a rise out of his neighbors. And he'll visit his five
grandchildren _ three by daughter Carol, one by son Michael and one
by, yes, Andy.
</P>
<P>
   The latter was the biggest surprise of all. When Andy was barely
out of high school, a romance with a neighborhood girl led to an
unplanned pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley says Andy offered to marry the girl, but she chose
instead to give up the daughter for adoption. Jump ahead a couple
of decades and that child, named Maria, finds her way to Stanley,
who instantly embraces her as a member of the family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love her dearly. . . . She has brought Andy back into my
life as a living thing,'' he says. The two talk on the phone
several times a week. And Maria has a daughter, making Stanley a
great-grandfather of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not how Stanley views it. Instead, the proud father's
thoughts return to his late son, who would have turned 50 this
year. To him, Andy is not a man on the moon. ``Andy is a
grandfather.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Passy writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. E-mail: charlespassy(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
