<HEADER>
A6336 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-TAMALES23-COX     12-22 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAMALES23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wrapping up tradition
 &HT;    By Ricardo Gandara
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ So Grandpa Pete is telling the story about four
legs sticking out of the ground and how he was going to make them
fit in the grave.
</P>
<P>
   The family's Shetland pony died one summer day. Because of the
heat, Pete Sanchez and his wife and daughter were forced to bury
it. They dug a shallow grave and pulled the heavy animal to its
resting place _ only the pony landed on its back, its legs straight
up in the air.
</P>
<P>
   Grandpa had an idea: Get the chainsaw.
</P>
<P>
   No.
</P>
<P>
   Yes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made the sign of the cross and asked God to forgive me,'' he
recalls, pantomiming pulling the rope to start the
</P>
<P>
   saw.
</P>
<P>
   The room full of people couldn't laugh any harder. Never mind
that they hear the same story every year.
</P>
<P>
   This is the Sanchez family tamalada, where as many as 40 members
gather a week before Christmas to make tamales _ corn masa, or
dough, and pork chili meat wrapped lovingly inside corn husks _ and
memories.
</P>
<P>
   It is a communal ritual at the home of Mary and Pete Sanchez
(Grandma and Grandpa from here on) to make a load of tamales _ 76
dozen this year _ to last throughout the holidays. It simply is not
Christmas without tamales. And all that goes with them: jokes and
constant ribbing, chisme (gossip) and so much love it could engulf
the world.
</P>
<P>
   Grandma and Grandpa, 74 and 73 and married nearly 54 years, have
been hosting the tamalada more than 35 years. Its roots go back to
1934, however, when Mary Sanchez learned the art as a child from
her parents, who lived in Del Valle at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``En esos dias (In those days),'' said Grandma, ``we steamed the
tamales outside on Christmas Eve. Teniamos nacimiento y rosario
</P>
<P>
   (We had a Nativity scene and prayed the rosary). Y luego
comiamos tamales (Then we ate tamales).''
</P>
<P>
   They stayed up until 3 a.m. playing. The adults visited. She
played with her cousins while the boys lit firecrackers and tried
to prove they were men by letting them explode in their clenched
fists.
</P>
<P>
   The family tamalada is a little tamer now, but no less fun and
loud.
</P>
<P>
   Hopie Perez, the bingo player of the family and Grandma and
Grandpa's niece, kept everyone laughing with her PG-rated jokes.
``Hay fregado (loosely, 'I better watch it!'),'' she said when she
learned of a reporter in the room.
</P>
<P>
   David Varela, the gentlemanly high-school history teacher who is
married to Teresa, Grandma and Grandpa's oldest, was harassed the
most, especially about his thinning hair. ``I'm giving you Rogaine
for Christmas,'' said Robert Sanchez, who is married to Grandma and
Grandpa's granddaughter Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's OK,'' Varela said. ``I'm the best spreader.''
</P>
<P>
   Spreading the masa on the corn husk is the hardest part of
making tamales. At this tamalada, however, everyone claimed to be
an expert. Someone brought $6 plastic spreaders, but they were
chastised by the ``spooners,'' those who spread masa the
old-fashioned way with a spoon. Despite the abundance of master
spreaders, few passed Grandma's inspection.
</P>
<P>
   She ran the show. Grandma had everything set up when daughters
Teresa, Mary Capuchino and Isabel Velasquez were the first to
arrive before 9 a.m. Two hogs' heads and several pork butt roasts
were cooked, and the husks soaked overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Daughter Mary is always in charge of making the masa, and she
did it with one eye on Grandma. ``Poquito mas chile y sal (Needs a
little more chile and salt),'' said Grandma, tasting a pinch.
</P>
<P>
   ``You learn not to question what she says. She just knows,''
said the daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's quality control,'' said David Varela.
</P>
<P>
   Grandma was not shy about tweaking here and there. She'd warn
them they were putting too little masa or too much. Or, they were
making them too long. ``They're longnecks, Grandma,'' someone said.
</P>
<P>
   Another round of laughter, and they'd burst into a verse of ``We
Wish You a Merry Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   Grandma smiled. ``Me da mucho gusto (It gives me great joy),''
she said, putting her hand to her heart, ``-- ara tener a todos
aqui (to have everyone here).''
</P>
<P>
   The assembling of the tamales worked like a finely tuned
basketball team. Everyone had a job. Teresa and Isabel stayed in
the kitchen to wash dishes and fix lunch. Most people spread the
masa on husks while grandson Marcos Varela and great-granddaughter
Jackie Sanchez added the meat filling.
</P>
<P>
   They started assembling the tamales at 10:30 a.m. and by 12:45
p.m., 76 dozen were wrapped. Thirteen dozen were cooked _ a reward
lunch _ and the rest were frozen. They're to be cooked on Christmas
Eve and Christmas Day at various family gatherings.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are so good,'' said Grandpa Pete, fudging that he had
only eaten two. To complete his all-cholesterol plate, he also had
chicharrones, or pork rinds.
</P>
<P>
   And Heinz ketchup on the tamales? He's had them that way as long
as he can remember. No one has a good explanation.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is something I cannot understand,'' said David Varela.
``Ruining the taste of tamales like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Just then someone called out, ``Hey, pass the ketchup.''
</P>
<P>
   Go figure.
</P>
<P>
   What is easy to understand is the closeness of the family. The
clan gets together most major holidays. They greet each other with
hugs. The children always kiss their grandparents. The young people
respect the elders.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we stick together,'' said Jesse Sanchez, Grandma and
Grandpa's youngest, who has given them eight grandchildren. ``This
tamalada helps keep everyone united, and it's a good way to show
the kids what's important.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanging onto the tradition is good, but it's even better sitting
around, being together and belonging to a family. The Sanchezes
have this down pat.
</P>
<P>
   Ricardo Gandara writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
