<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 11:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6337 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-XMAS-BRUNCH23-COX     12-22 1168
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-XMAS-BRUNCH23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Make-ahead items allow cooks to enjoy Christmas
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ On Christmas Day, the cook responsible for the
holiday dinner is also likely to be the one picking up wrapping
paper and consulting on the assembly of toys. There's no time, it
seems, to fix brunch. People tend to pick up store-bought coffee
cakes and eat them on the run.
</P>
<P>
   But an easy holiday brunch can be a relaxing break in a busy
Christmas Day. The definition of easy is dishes that can be mostly
made ahead, and that's the key to this brunch menu.
</P>
<P>
   The star of the menu is a buttermilk pecan coffee cake that can
be assembled in the pan and refrigerated overnight. In the morning,
just slip it in the oven to bake for half an hour. This makes it
easy to serve warm coffee cake _ and this one is luscious when
still warm. As the batter rises, the cinnamon, sugar and butter
topping forms pools in the cake. And while the cake bakes, the
spicy aroma will lure family to the table.
</P>
<P>
   The menu includes another easy dish _ baked eggs. Decades ago
they were called shirred eggs, but they have been forgotten in a
world that has moved on to egg dishes such as Italian frittata.
</P>
<P>
   While these eggs can't be made ahead, they are so simple that a
novice who might be terrified of making an omelette or even
scrambled eggs can handle them.
</P>
<P>
   What you need to do in advance is buy some ramekins _ small
ovenproof dishes. They're available at most cookware stores. Look
for the size big enough to hold six ounces, or two eggs.
</P>
<P>
   The eggs are poured into the ramekins and baked. A bit of cream
poured on top and a little sprinkled cheese add a finishing touch.
</P>
<P>
   We liked the bright green color of creamed spinach as the base
for the eggs. The creamed spinach can be made the night before.
Another variation is to use cubes of ham and swiss cheese as the
base, or just a slice of ham. Other possibilities are a layer of
ratatouille or sauteed mushrooms, all of which can be made ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Grapefruit is a fruit of the winter season, and the Ruby Red
variety is perfect for a Christmas brunch. An old-fashioned
specialty is broiled grapefruit sprinkled with spiced sugar. A
recipe adding ginger to the sugar topping rounds out this brunch.
</P>
<P>
   RECIPES
</P>
<P>
   This easy cake is light and tender, and best when served warm
from the oven. For added eye appeal, scatter a few pecan halves on
top before baking.
</P>
<P>
   OVERNIGHT BUTTERMILK PECAN COFFEE CAKE
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 to 15 servings
</P>
<P>
   Cake:
</P>
<P>
   10 tablespoons butter, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup light brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   2 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 cup buttermilk
</P>
<P>
   Topping:
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup light brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup coarsely chopped pecans
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter, melted
</P>
<P>
   Place the butter and sugars in the large bowl of an electric
mixer and beat until well combined, 2 to 3 minutes. Add the eggs
and beat just until the eggs are incorporated. Combine the flour,
cinnamon, baking powder, soda and salt. Add to batter alternately
with the buttermilk. Beat a minute or two at medium low speed so
that the batter is smooth.
</P>
<P>
   Lightly oil and flour a 13-by-9-inch baking pan. Shake out any
excess flour.
</P>
<P>
   Pour the batter into the prepared pan.
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl, combine the light brown sugar, pecans and
cinnamon. Scatter this topping evenly over the batter. Dribble the
topping with melted butter. Cover the pan with plastic wrap and
refrigerate overnight.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, place a rack in the center of the oven and
preheat the oven to 350 degrees. Remove the pan from the
refrigerator and remove the plastic wrap. If the pan is glass, let
it sit at room temperature until the chill is off before putting it
into the oven. Bake the coffee cake for 30 to 32 minutes, until the
cake springs back in the center when lightly pressed with your
finger and a toothpick inserted in the center comes out clean.
Remove the pan to a wire rack to cool 15 minutes. Cut into squares
and serve warm.
</P>
<P>
   (Recipe is from the Georgia Pecan Commission.)
</P>
<P>
   Approximate nutritional analysis per serving: 351 calories, 17.7
g fat, 68 mg cholesterol, 261 mg sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Eggs are usually gently baked in a water bath, a tedious
process. We take a shortcut here and spoon a little cream over the
yolks to protect them while they bake.
</P>
<P>
   This recipe for creamed spinach departs from the traditional,
which usually calls for as much as a cup and a half of cream. This
one calls for just 1/3 cup cream, but the result is creamy and
silken.
</P>
<P>
   CREAMED SPINACH
</P>
<P>
   Makes enough for six ramekins
</P>
<P>
   3 10-ounce bags washed spinach
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons salt (for blanching spinach)
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Pull off spinach stems and discard.
</P>
<P>
   Bring 4 quarts water to a boil with the salt and add the
spinach, pushing it down into the water with a long wooden spoon.
Boil until the spinach just ``melts,'' about 30 seconds. Drain
immediately in a colander and rinse under cold running water until
the spinach no longer feels warm to the touch.
</P>
<P>
   Squeeze the water out of the spinach. Cut coarsely. Refrigerate,
covered, until ready to use.
</P>
<P>
   Season the cream generously with salt and pepper and boil it in
a medium pot or saute pan over high heat for 3 or 4 minutes, until
it gets very thick. Add the spinach and turn the heat down to
medium. Stir for a minute or two until spinach is warm and has
absorbed all the cream.
</P>
<P>
   (Recipe from James's Peterson's Vegetables (Morrow, $35).
</P>
<P>
   Approximate nutritional analysis per serving:78 calories, 5 g
fat, 18 mg cholesterol, 107 mg sodium, plus sodium in salt used for
blanching.
</P>
<P>
   TIP: If you want to gussy up this old fashioned recipe you can
grind crystallized ginger and substitute it for the ground ginger.
Or try using brown sugar instead of regular sugar. If you have
fresh mint_ and mine is still growing in my garden _ garnish the
grapefruit with a sprig or two.
</P>
<P>
   BROILED GRAPEFRUIT WITH GINGER SUGAR
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons ground ginger
</P>
<P>
   3 large Ruby Red grapefruit
</P>
<P>
   Combine the sugar and ginger. This can be done ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Halve grapefruit crosswise and run a knife around each section
to loosen the membranes. Preheat broiler.
</P>
<P>
   Arrange grapefruit, cut side up, in a baking pan just large
enough to hold them in one layer. Sprinkle evenly with sugar
mixture to cover. Broil grapefruits about three inches from the
heat until the sugar melts and tops begin to brown, about 4 to 6
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Approximate nutritional analysis per serving:127 calories, 0
fat, 0 cholesterol, 0 sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Heller writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
