<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT-ARTS
</P>
<P>
   KAUFMAN-SON _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ There is the Andy Kaufman
the world remembers. The irreverent, lost-in-the-clouds comic who
entertained crowds with his impressions of a bumbling foreigner and
hip-swiveling Elvis. And who challenged them with his act as a
brutish wrestler and foul-mouthed lounge lizard. And there is the
Andy Kaufman that Stanley Kaufman, the late comedian's father,
remembers. The nice Jewish boy-turned-man who never stopped calling
his parents Mommy and Daddy. The son who insisted on having his
brother and sister join him atop a Macy's Thanksgiving Day parade
float. The son who helped turn every family gathering into a
virtual variety show. It's the former Andy Kaufman who will be on
display on screens around the country in ``Man on the Moon.'' But
that doesn't stop the senior Kaufman from remembering what he calls
the real Andy. (Passy, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
