<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991222.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 11:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6362 &Cx1f; tab-z
r w BC-LORETTA-SANCHEZ-INTER     12-22 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LORETTA-SANCHEZ-INTERVIEW-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPITOL ASSET  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from W magazine,
contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT
at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``w'' Washington news and ``a'' general news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By SUSAN WATTERS  
 c.1999 Fairchild Publications   
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   ``I just voted against a national day of prayer, fasting and
`humiliation before God,''' says Loretta Sanchez, rolling her eyes
as she walks off the floor of the U.S. House of Representatives.
``These are the votes we're taking these days: `I can hang up more
commandments than you can.'''
</P>
<P>
   The California Democrat is disgusted, yes, but three years after
a vicious campaign battle with one of the loudest voices in
American conservatism, Bob Dornan, Sanchez also finds her
right-wing opponents strangely amusing. Even Helen Chenoweth, the
pro-militia congresswoman from Idaho who called for that national
day of ``humiliation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a wacko. But she probably meant `humility,''' says
Sanchez, who's willing to give Chenoweth the benefit of the doubt
because ``it's part of being Catholic. We always feel guilty, and
we always wear a slip.''
</P>
<P>
   Petite, flirtatious and easy to underestimate, Sanchez, 39, has
gone from being a political unknown largely written off by the
Democratic establishment to co-chairman of the party.
</P>
<P>
   She's also high on Hillary Rodham Clinton's list of pals to help
campaign in New York's Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one ever got anywhere by slaying an ant,'' says Clinton
campaign strategist James Carville, ``and she's a dragon killer.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez proved her feistiness in 1996, when she ousted Dornan
from his House seat by fewer than 1,000 votes. Stunned by his loss
after 10 terms, Dornan convinced the Republican leadership to
launch a congressional inquiry, with an idea of throwing Sanchez
out of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``It cost me $800,000 to win my first election and another
million dollars to hold onto my seat,'' she says of the 17-month
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Dornan came up with proof that more than 500 noncitizens had
voted, but unable to prove the election results wrong, the
Republicans dropped the charges. Then Sanchez whipped Dornan again
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez is generating less buzz about her legislative program _
as a junior member, she doesn't have much of an agenda to speak of
_ than about her ability to ignite the Hispanic vote, which could
play a key role in a presidential race between Vice President Al
Gore and Texas Governor George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   She admits that getting the growing demographic group to the
polls is a challenge, because, she says, ``a lot of Hispanics come
from a system where politics is not good.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez's own father, based on his experience growing up in
Mexico, warned her against running for office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good politicians get shot,'' he told her, ``and the bad ones
are bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Married for 10 years to securities trader Stephen Brixey,
Sanchez holds an MBA from American University and got her early
education compliments of the Great Society's antipoverty program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a Head Start kid, but I never realized I was poor,'' she
insists, smiling demurely as she moves in to attack. ``I didn't
know the program was aimed at the disadvantaged until 1993, when I
read in the paper about the Republicans not wanting to fund it.''
</P>
<P>
   It's Sanchez's reputation for such sugarcoated toughness that
makes her a favorite with Democrats and moderate Republicans alike,
and she has wasted no time making powerful friends.
</P>
<P>
   Housing Secretary Andrew Cuomo gushes, ``She's junior in terms
of time served in Congress, but she's senior in terms of talent.''
</P>
<P>
   And Gore gave her the cushy job of helping dispense money to
candidates from his PAC. But she bristles when asked whether the
vice president is entitled to next year's nomination by dint of his
eight years served.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shouldn't go to Al Gore just by virtue of inheritance,''
she says. ``You're talking to a person who nobody thought would
win, especially not in the primary, when the party was helping
someone else. As a Democratic chairperson, my role is to ensure
those people who want to run have the chance.''
</P>
<P>
   And Sanchez admits the vice president needs to loosen up.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he's in my district, he's not stiff,'' she says. ``But
then I turn on CSPAN and see him campaigning in New Hampshire and I
say, `Oh my God, what is this guy doing?'''
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez is anxiously awaiting next summer's Democratic
convention in Los Angeles _ politics aside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've only been to one before, in Chicago in 1996,'' she
recalls. But as a dark horse, she adds, ``I didn't get to see any
of the fun stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   This time, Sanchez will be getting invitations to all the best
parties, along with Barbra Streisand, Rob Reiner, Warren Beatty and
Annette Bening _ all of whom contributed to her second race.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't mean I can pick up the phone and say, `Hi, I'm
Loretta. Can you come over and do a concert now, Barbra?''' she
says, pausing to consider her own celebrity status. ``But I'm sure
some of them would say yes.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Susan Watters is a reporter for Fairchild Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
</TEXT>
