<SLUG> BC-TREK-LOU-DIAMOND-PHILLIPS-IN-SUPERNOVA-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FIGHT TO SAVE `SUPERNOVA' 
</HEADLINE>
 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.) (Includes a color slide and a black-and-white photo of Lou Diamond
Phillips in a scene from ``Supernova.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Diamond in the rough or unsalvageable hunk of junk?
 &HT;    On Jan. 14, moviegoers can decide for themselves precisely what
``Supernova'' is ... or was.
 &HT;    For those unaware of the ``Supernova'' saga, it's the
otherworldly tale of a would-be sci-fi blockbuster that wrapped
production in early 1998 _ with Walter Hill directing a cast that
included Angela Bassett, Lou Diamond Phillips, Robin Tunney, James
Spader, Robert Forster, Wilson Cruz and Peter Facinelli _ and has
since been subject to a series of re-edits, directorial contretemps
and release-date delays.
 &HT;    ``It is an incredibly ambitious film,'' Phillips says. ``It is,
or at least it was at the time we were working on it, more of a
cerebral sci-fi film.
 &HT;    ``I don't know what it has become,'' he adds. ``It was not a
slam-bang-'em-up. It depended on a lot of plot twists, and there
was character development going on in the piece.''
 &HT;    Phillips, the 37-year-old star of ``La Bamba,'' ``Stand and
Deliver'' and the recent ``Bats,'' signed on for ``Supernova''
because he felt Hill was taking a fairly straight-ahead story and
molding it into something interesting.
 &HT;    ``I'd actually passed on the original script,'' he recalls,
``because I didn't think the characters were there. When Walter,
who was instrumental in shaping the `Alien' franchise, came in, he
individualized each character and gave us all something specific to
do.''
 &HT;    And how did Hill improve Phillips' character, Yerzy Penalosa,
the doctor aboard the medical-rescue vessel Nightingale 229?
 &HT;    ``They gave him a love interest, for one,'' replies Phillips,
speaking by telephone from his Los Angeles home. ``I never get the
girl, man. In `Courage Under Fire' I worked with Meg Ryan,
America's sweetheart _ and I shot her.
 &HT;    ``Penalosa became a guy who's in love and gets very jealous,''
he says. ``There were two big twists in the film I thought were
very, very clever. One of them I can't reveal, but the other is
primary setup _ we find the Fountain of Youth in space.
 &HT;    ``This alien object brought aboard our ship has the ability to
reverse the aging process,'' the actor says, ``and I get involved
in a love triangle with Robin Tunney and Peter Facinelli, the guy
who brings this alien object on board.
 &HT;    ``For me, all of a sudden, there was something to play,''
Phillips adds. ``Before, I felt we were all these straight-ahead,
stock action figures. Walter came in and gave each character a
little wrinkle, something we could hang our hats on.
 &HT;    ``So we had something we could really play amidst all the
unfolding action.''
 &HT;    But rumors from the set suggest that MGM executives kept a tight
rein on Hill, forcing him to account for every minor change, for
every extra cent spent. In all his days as an actor, Phillips
acknowledges, he's never witnessed so many set visits by studio
suits.
 &HT;    Things only got worse. After filming ended, Hill and the studio
apparently failed to see eye-to-eye on the editing. Hill left the
project, and director Jack Sholder was called in to assemble
``Supernova.'' Phillips reports that he got the impression that
Sholder was trying to transform ``Supernova'' into more of a
traditional sci-fi/action film.
 &HT;    Then came an offer the producers couldn't refuse.
 &HT;    Francis Ford Coppola, director of the ``Godfather'' films and a
member of MGM/UA's board of directors, swooped in to save the day.
And so it is that ``Supernova,'' edited by Coppola and most likely
bearing a pseudonymous director's credit _ did someone page Alan
Smithee? _ will explode into theaters on Jan. 14.
 &HT;    ``This has been a fascinating process, a Hollywood film of the
highest order,'' Phillips says. ``At the end of the day, we can
say, `Francis Coppola finished the film.'
 &HT;    ``I received a wonderful letter from Francis,'' the actor adds.
``He liked the film, and asked for the opportunity to come up with
a product that the studio would be happy with and that he hoped
Walter Hill would be happy with.
 &HT;    ``It's yet to be known whether or not he achieved that,''
Phillips admits, ``but in his letter he stressed the importance of
maintaining the film's original concept. He even tossed out the
phrase `big-budget art film.'
 &HT;    ``So we'll see.''
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Supernova,'' consult the
official Website at www.mgm.com/supernova. And don't forget to
visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Inside Trek and
Sci-Fi and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
