<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ROLLER-COASTER-SAFETY (San Antonio) _ High speeds, a steep drop
and the rough nature of the Rattler roller coaster ride at Fiesta
Texas are some of its most attractive features to enthusiasts. They
also are factors that caused dozens of personal injury lawsuits to
be filed against the park, resulting in a $3.5 million group
settlement for 27 plaintiffs in 1998. By JOHN TEDESCO.
</P>
<P>
   NY-LOBBY-RULES (Albany, N.Y.) _ Falling short of the strong
measures desired by government reform advocates, the New York state
Assembly and Gov. George Pataki agreed on a tougher lobbying law
that would give the state more muscle without taking away a public
officer's ability to accept free meals. By JAMES M. ODATO.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-MOON (Undated) _ Fifteen years dead and gone _ well,
presumably dead anyway _ Andy Kaufman gets to play one more joke on
us. It comes at the very end of ``Man on the Moon,'' as the closing
credits roll (for the second time). Instead of gathering coats and
beating traffic, you are compelled to remain, half-turned in the
aisle and eyes on the screen, scanning the names of the second unit
director and the key grip and the ASPCA disclaimer. There may be
one last gag to be played, one more joke on you, and you are not
going to be a patsy. By MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GEHRIG'S-DISEASE (Albany, N.Y.) _ The recent decision by
Cephalon Inc. of West Chester, Pa., to stop making an experimental
drug has angered many patients of amyotrophic lateral sclerosis,
better known as Lou Gehrig's disease. ``It's extremely
disappointing,'' says Mary Lyon, vice president of patient services
at the ALS Association. Yet research into the disease has been
encouraging over the past decade. Scientists now know that nerve
cells can regrow and are focusing their attention on developing
drugs to prevent the loss of neurons and encourage their
regeneration. By SYLVIA WOOD.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ The last-ditch courtroom defense
for anybody charged with murder is to claim, ``I hear voices.''
Nobody ever explains why those voices always say, ``Kill this
person,'' instead of, ``Go shopping naked,'' or ``Paint the house
plaid.'' Nobody knows what Dr. Robert Bierenbaum's defense will be
to charges that he murdered his wife and dumped her body at sea
from his private plane, but it's likely to be, ``Where's the
corpse?'' By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
