<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WHERE'S THE CORPSE' NOT ALWAYS A DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The last-ditch courtroom defense for anybody
charged with murder is to claim, ``I hear voices.'' Nobody ever
explains why those voices always say, ``Kill this person,'' instead
of, ``Go shopping naked,'' or ``Paint the house plaid.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knows what Dr. Robert Bierenbaum's defense will be to
charges that he killed his wife and dumped her body at sea from his
private plane, but it's likely to be, ``Where's the corpse?''
</P>
<P>
   That's because proving murder generally requires, at a minimum,
hard evidence that the victim is dead. That has not kept the
Manhattan district attorney's office, however, from beginning to
prosecute this Albany Medical College graduate. The D.A.'s office
won't discuss its proof that Bierenbaum offed his wife, Gail, 14
years ago, but it seems to revolve around Bierenbaum's famous
temper _ that and something told investigators by a girlfriend the
plastic surgeon later romanced after moving to Las Vegas.
Bierenbaum lived and worked there before moving again to North
Dakota, where he now has a new wife and small child.
</P>
<P>
   Bierenbaum, 44, is the son of two wealthy New Jersey doctors.
The missing wife, Gail, was prone to depression and had attempted
suicide before disappearing in 1985 after yet one more nasty fight
with her husband. She had previously reported to the police that
her cranky husband had choked not only her but her cat.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Kavanagh, now a judge and for many years district attorney
of Ulster County, which is south of Albany, once got a murder
conviction without a corpse. The victim was Tony (Three Fingers)
Castellito, a Teamsters union official.
</P>
<P>
   Kavanagh put away two other mob union figures, Harold (Boom
Boom) Konigsberg and Tony (The Pro) Provenzano based largely on
testimony from a couple of thugs named Big Sal Sinno and Little
Ralphie Picardo.
</P>
<P>
   The jury heard the story of this contract killing and concluded
that Three Fingers had suffered the ultimate business setback even
though nobody knew for sure how his body had been disposed of.
Clearly, the fact that everybody here had a mob nickname helped a
lot in obtaining this conviction. And Kavanagh is the first to
admit that if he hadn't had a witness to the killing he would have
been out of luck.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Sprague, for many years the first assistant district
attorney of Philadelphia, once prosecuted a murder suspect without
a body or a witness. The defendant was a guy named Burns. He had
smacked around his live-in girlfriend, Marie Coleman, in front of
some people. Shortly thereafter, she vanished.
</P>
<P>
   From the start the cops were positive that Burns had done her
in, and they got lucky when they arrested him. As they slipped on
the cuffs, Burns boasted, ``You're gonna look like monkeys in
court. You ain't got a body.''
</P>
<P>
   Only the cops hadn't mentioned to him that they had no corpse.
</P>
<P>
   In summations to the jury, the defense lawyer was pointing out
the lack of proof that the girlfriend was even dead. As he spoke, a
women fitting the general description of Marie Coleman came into
the courtroom. Everybody gasped and stared at her. No, the defense
lawyer said, that's not Coleman. We don't know where Coleman is.
But, if even for a moment, you thought this might be her, then you
have reasonable doubt and you must acquit.
</P>
<P>
   In his own summation a few minutes later, Sprague he told the
jurors, OK, so everybody gazed at this woman when she entered
court. For a moment, everybody thought that this might be Marie
Coleman.
</P>
<P>
   One person never looked, though, Sprague pointed out. That was
Burns. He had not looked because he knew he had murdered Marie
Coleman, and this couldn't have been her.
</P>
<P>
   Sprague got his conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Now let's see if the Manhattan D.A. is quite so lucky.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
