<DOCNO> NYT19991222.0103 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 12:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6396 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-GEHRIG'S-DISEASE-HNS &LR;      12-22 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEHRIG'S-DISEASE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATIENTS PINE FOR TREATMENT OF LOU GEHRIG'S DISEASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Over the past two years, Linda McDonnell has lost
the ability to dress herself, hold a pencil, or walk more than 300
feet at a time. At night, she needs a machine to help her breathe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really can't do anything for myself,'' she said. ``I can
still use two fingers on the computer and I can talk on the phone.
I can't pick up a glass. I have to use a straw.''
</P>
<P>
   McDonnell has amyotrophic lateral sclerosis, better known as Lou
Gehrig's disease, named after the Yankee Hall of Famer who died
from it in 1941 at age 37.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, McDonnell has been encouraged by the attention
given her disease, by people like Oprah Winfrey and Mitch Albom,
best-selling author of ``Tuesdays with Morrie.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all the recent news is positive. Baseball great Jim
``Catfish'' Hunter died in September, a year after he was diagnosed
with ALS.
</P>
<P>
   The disease attacks nerve cells in the brain and spinal cord
that control the body's voluntary muscles. As the motor neurons
die, the muscles weaken and shrink. Early symptoms of ALS may
include clumsiness, unusual fatigue, slurred speech and difficulty
swallowing.
</P>
<P>
   McDonnell initially noticed problems in her hands. ``It started
out as little annoying symptoms,'' she said. ``I dropped keys, had
trouble turning keys, I was having trouble putting binder clips on
stacks of paper. I never thought it was anything.''
</P>
<P>
   As the disease progresses, it causes eventual paralysis and
death, usually in three to five years. Scientists don't know the
cause and there is no cure. Nor are there many treatment options
for the 30,000 Americans who suffer from ALS.
</P>
<P>
   A decision earlier this month by Cephalon Inc. of West Chester,
Pa., to stop producing an experimental drug called Myotrophin has
angered many ALS patients, who believe the drug helped slow the
progression of their disease.
</P>
<P>
   Only one drug is currently approved by the Food and Drug
Administration to treat ALS.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's extremely disappointing,'' said Mary Lyon, vice president
of patient services at the ALS Association of Calabasas Hills,
Calif. (800-782-4747).
</P>
<P>
   Yet research into the disease has been encouraging over the past
decade.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists now know that nerve cells can regrow and are focusing
their attention on developing drugs to prevent the loss of neurons
and encourage their regeneration.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel like were are closing in on something that has
potential,'' said Dr. Jonathan Cooper, the director of medical
rehabilitation at St. Peter's Hospital in Albany. ``Previously
research was all over the map. They were just shooting in the
dark.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite her limitations, McDonnell is hoping to do her part to
advance the research into ALS, if not slow the progression of her
own illness, by participating in a clinical trial to test an
experimental drug.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least I'm doing something proactive to help with the
research,'' she said. ``Someone has to do this. Someone has to
volunteer. I'm still physically able to do it and I'm more than
willing to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   She receives a daily injection of either a placebo or a dose of
BDNF, a naturally occurring human protein that researchers hope
will prove helpful in extending the lives of ALS patients.
McDonnell will not know until next year, however, if she actually
received the drug or any of its potential benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figure I have nothing to lose,'' she said. ``I'm 48 years
old and I have two daughters in college. I'd like to see them
graduate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the terminal nature of the disease, if (the drug is)
going to prolong your life even by six months, hey, that's great.''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, living with ALS is a daily challenge of
monumental proportions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The simplest things in life become very difficult to manage,''
Cooper said. ``We try to help people maintain their independence as
long as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Because ALS can sometimes mimic other conditions in its early
stages, many victims, including McDonnell, have trouble getting an
accurate diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just went from doctor to doctor to doctor to try to figure
out what was happening,'' she said. ``It's extremely frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, her biggest challenge is learning to live with the
disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went from being a generally vigorous, independent working
mom to someone who is totally dependent on someone else,'' she
said. ``You have to become very humble and swallow your pride.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Sylvia Wood can be reached at 518-454-5445 or by electronic
mail at swood(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-22-99 1223EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
