<P>
   &UR; ATTENTION EDITORS: &LR;  The following is the budget for the New
Scientist for material available the week of Mon., Dec. 27, 1999,
and anytime thereafter. This material is free for use for New York
Times News Service clients. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE RIGHT STUFF &LR;  _ A management consultancy near Washington
D.C., has released the first results of its attempts to quantify
for NASA the risks the crew will face on the International Space
Station. The consultancy calculates that over the next 15 years,
the station will have at least one ``loss of crew member.'' By
Charles Seife. (Slugged:
BC-INTERNATIONAL-SPACE-STATION-NEW-SCIENTIST-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTMAS SCARE MENU &LR;  _ Your Christmas dinner is full of natural
substances that give lab rats cancer, warn a group of New York
scientists who have put together a spoof Christmas menu designed to
ridicule media scare stories about pesticides in food. By Andy
Coghlan. (Slugged: BC-CHRISTMAS-SCARE-MENU-NEW-SCIENTIST-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   ENGINEERING A CURE FOR ALZHEIMER'S &LR;  _ The first trial to test
whether gene therapy can slow the progress of Alzheimer's disease
has been given the go-ahead. Researchers in California have found
that nerve growth factor can reverse memory loss in rodents and
primates. By Nell Boyce. (Slugged:
BC-CURE-FOR-ALZHEIMERS-NEW-SCIENTIST-NYTSF)
</P>
