<HEADLINE>
DEER POPULATION ON RISE AS HUNTERS DWINDLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT BRAILE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Fewer deer were killed in Massachusetts' hunting season
this fall than in any of the past four years _ good news for the
animals but bad news for a state scrambling to rein in deer in the
suburbs that have been turning up everywhere, from playgrounds to
parking lots.
</P>
<P>
   Despite making the state's deer hunting season longer than it
has ever been since regulated hunts began in 1910, wildlife
officials say unofficial results show a decline of about 8 percent
in the deer killed this year, in part because fewer hunters are
taking to the woods.
</P>
<P>
   With so few deer killed this season, which ended Saturday, ``the
potential for continued growth in our suburban deer population is
tremendous,'' said Bill Davis, a biologist with the state Division
of Fisheries and Wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   Hunters legally killed 8,564 deer from Oct. 11 through Dec. 18,
down from 9,311 last year. Meanwhile, the statewide deer population
stood at about 90,000 before this year's hunt, double what it was
in the late 1980s. And the number of hunters stalking the woods is
declining _ 87,679 hunting licenses were issued last year, down
from 129,733 in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Deer are turning up in forests and meadows where people like to
see them, but also in places where they don't, especially roads.
The division says it receives 400 to 600 reports a year of deer
struck by vehicles, up from about 200 five years ago. And it
believes that reported deer-vehicle collisions reflect only 10
percent to 20 percent of the actual number.
</P>
<P>
   Hunting has long been the primary way to control the deer
population. But hunters say hunting is on the wane, largely because
of a national decline in interest among young people and an aging
hunter population, and also for reasons specific to the state.
</P>
<P>
   A recent increase in state license fees has contributed to the
precipitous decline in hunters, who numbered 97,284 as recently as
1997.
</P>
<P>
   As the sprawl spreads out from cities, more land is being posted
as off-limits to hunters. The strong economy also works to keep
would-be hunters at work, with many opting to make a buck rather
than shoot one.
</P>
<P>
   But more than anything else, ``hunters are just getting older,
and kids nowadays are more involved in computer games and other
things,'' said John Kellstrand, a hunter and legislative agent for
the Massachusetts Sportsmen's Council.
</P>
<P>
   While the residential and commercial development spurred by a
surging economy is rarely viewed as good for nature, it is great
for deer. They roam the ``edges'' between forests and clearings,
the kind created when homes are built. They nibble on young plants
that thrive in fields where trees once grew. They savor the exotic
shrubbery surrounding many homes. ``We're really ringing the dinner
bell for deer,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Wolves and other natural predators are long gone. And in most
towns, deer cannot be shot within 500 feet of a home, if at all _
many towns prohibit or tightly restrict hunting. ``We've created de
facto refuges,'' said John McDonald, the division's deer project
leader.
</P>
<P>
   This year's archery season was extended by three weeks to a
total of six in Eastern Massachusetts, after previous moves to
lengthen the shotgun and primitive firearms seasons. The state has
also in recent years increased bag limits and doubled to 36,000 the
number of licenses issued for shooting antlerless deer, the females
that are key to herd size.
</P>
<P>
   As more people encounter deer on the highways or as freeloaders
dining on their shrubs, they are coming to view the animals as
bothersome rather than beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who may have once wanted to protect deer are now paying
to have them killed,'' McDonald said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hunters at this point are the only predators, except for
cars,'' said Paul Kress, a legislative agent for the Massachusetts
Wildlife Federation. He has lived in Carlisle for 30 years, where
he has seen deer go from being rare to common denizens of the
town's steadily developing landscape.
</P>
<P>
   He says the state can extend the season all it wants, but it
will have little effect in a part of Massachusetts where hunting is
virtually impossible anyway. In the end, he says, ``they just won't
be able to take enough deer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
