<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-BAIN PAIR'S GOAL: MANAGE $10 BILLION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; This is how good a year it's been for money managers Geoffrey
Rehnert and Marc Wolpow:
</P>
<P>
   Their midsummer departure from their longtime professional home,
Bain Capital Inc., was complicated by the approaching deadline on
an option they held to acquire a 44 percent interest in a small
independent film distributor, Artisan Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Rehnert and Wolpow, who were leaving to start their own
investment firm, quickly raised money to exercise the option and
completed the deal by July 9. Three days later, Artisan's latest
film opened, and ``The Blair Witch Project'' was on its way to
becoming a movie phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the summer wasn't bad, either.
</P>
<P>
   Rehnert and Wolpow, both managing directors at Bain, have pulled
together their firm, the Audax Group, sold a 20 percent stake in
the brand new business to three institutions for $50 million, and
raised $500 million for the first in a series of investment
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Like other money managers who dream about running their own
shop, they had to ask the question: If not now, when? With huge
amounts of investment money sloshing around and a long track
record, Rehnert and Wolpow didn't even have to market their first
buyout fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a time when there's a lot of money out there,'' Rehnert
said. ``In a different market, we would have had to be more
proactive.''
</P>
<P>
   What helped was the fact that three well-known institutions had
already agreed to buy stakes. Investments by the California Public
Employees Retirement System, Princeton University endowment
investor Nassau Capital LLC, and CIBC Capital Markets helped lift
the company's profile.
</P>
<P>
   The initial Audax fund drew institutions like SunAmerica,
FleetBoston Financial Group, and the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology. Some of their old high-profile individual clients, such
as Staples Inc. chief executive Tom Stemberg, came along, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about people and their track records,'' Stemberg
said. ``If you look at how the business works, really these guys do
it on their own, whether it's in the context of Bain or in a
smaller group.''
</P>
<P>
   What makes Audax unusual in the private equity world is that it
wants to stick its fingers in so many ``alternative investment''
pies.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the buyout fund that will target midsize companies,
Audax expects to raise $75 million for an Internet-oriented venture
capital fund and another $250 million in a mezzanine investment
fund during the first quarter of next year. It's aiming for a $500
million collateralized bond obligation fund in the second quarter
and a hedge fund sometime in the second half of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The goal: build Audax up to a firm that manages $10 billion in a
full range of alternative investments.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the clientele is strictly institutions and very wealthy
individuals. Private equity firms like Bain or the Thomas H. Lee
Co. often become involved in many types of investments. But they
usually start from a business focused on one specialty, like
venture capital or leveraged buyouts, and evolve into other
investment categories over time.
</P>
<P>
   Those specialties are what made firms like Bain and Lee famous
in the first place. Our first thought: isn't a brand-new investment
company spreading itself too thinly with a handful of different
vehicles?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if we hadn't already done it before, there would be a
danger,'' Rehnert said. ``People who don't know us might say we're
biting off an awful lot. But we had a highly successful track
record at Bain, doing exactly what we're doing now. We're doing it
with the some of the same team and $50 million of operating capital
invested by top institutional investors.''
</P>
<P>
   He and Wolpow insist there are advantages to a family of
alternative investment funds, sharing market knowledge and a better
share of the flow of investment deals.
</P>
<P>
   Some see a marketing advantage in promoting a firm that can
offer one-stop shopping for alternative investments and many
different forms of private equity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's a powerful message to investors,'' said Steven
Galante, publisher of Private Equity Analyst, an industry
newsletter based in Wellesley.
</P>
<P>
   ``It strips away some of the mystique about these buyout and
venture firms. It goes straight to the heart of the matter; `We're
a money management firm, and what we do best is invest in private
companies.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's column:
</P>
<P>
   The rankings of the most valuable public companies in
Massachusetts are being turned on their heads this year.
</P>
<P>
   Today's update: more of the same, only faster.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI Inc.'s spectacular stock run Tuesday, advancing 48 1/16 to
270 1/4, nearly moved the company ahead of FleetBoston Financial
Corp. as the third-most-valuable public company in the state.
CMGI's stock market value of $33.2 billion Tuesday was just $130
million shy of Fleet's market capitalization, according to
Bloomberg News.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
