<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 13:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6433 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-22 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER SKELETONS IN OUR CLOSET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I think it was my mother who first remarked that there are
nearly as many computers as there are human beings in my household.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, I recently bought a 4-year-old used Macintosh PowerBook
5300cs, and I own a 6-year-old Macintosh Performa 6214. I also own
a museum piece, MS-DOS-powered 1989 Toshiba 1000SE laptop, which
lacks a hard drive. And in the basement there is a new,
Hewlett-Packard Pavilion computer, tailor-made for the modern child
to evade the tiresome copyright laws enacted for the benefit of
America's recording industry monopolies.
</P>
<P>
   Are my friends' homes like this? In fact, they are. Just up the
street, David O. copped to owning an iMac and a Toshiba laptop for
work, a broken NEC M/74 laptop, a 1989 Macintosh Plus, a 1994
Macintosh IIvx, and a PowerBook 170, ``sitting in the closet and
last used to write our speech at Ari's bar mitzvah,'' which took
place three years ago. Another friend still has his Radio Shack
TRS-80 (the famous ``Trash 80''), a once-cool Amiga, ``and a bunch
of printers'' gathering dust in his closets.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshirites garage their rusted-out cars on their front
lawns; suburbanites stash their old computers in their closets. Why
can't we let go? PC Data of Reston, Va., estimates that 14 million
new personal computers are sold into US homes each year, many of
them at Christmastime. And yet only 6 percent of home computers end
up in landfills. I suspect that's because few of us feel
comfortable leaving a $1,700 appliance (real value (EQ) 0) out on
the curb for the trash guys. So where will the orphans go to live?
</P>
<P>
   There is no obvious answer, because computers are unlike any
other appliance. If your 7-year-old car or television set is in
working order, you can pass it on to a friend or relative, or sell
it for peanuts. But while a 7-year-old computer may work, it can't
do anything anyone wants to do with a computer these days. It can't
surf the Internet very well, and as for downloading must-have MP3
songs, fuggedaboutit! My new-old PowerBook doesn't have a CD-ROM
drive; good luck getting software!
</P>
<P>
   But it gets worse. You can't even give your used computers away.
``Schools don't want them, except possibly to teach keyboard
skills,'' says Barry Cranmer, who runs a nonprofit Web site called
Share the Technology (libertynet.org/share). Schools are chary of
individual donors and want network-ready computers, which means
newer models. Cranmer tries to match computer donors with needy
recipients, but admits that it's a struggle. ``People still give us
8086's and 8088's'' _ Flintstones-era, MS-DOS machines powered by
caged squirrels.
</P>
<P>
   And they're not even giving very many of those; his site lists
only one computer available for donation in Massachusetts. Judging
from its Web site (www.wco.com/dale/crp.html), a similar venture,
the Computer Recycling Project, is more or less out of business. In
downtown Boston, the Nonprofit Computer Connection's Computer
Donation Program has likewise crashed.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, old computers have no value at all, except possibly
to be broken up into kitschy microchip ``jewelry.'' At the eBay Web
auction site, for instance, someone was recently trying to hawk a
``vintage'' Macintosh 128K that has the names of Steve Jobs, Steve
Wozniak, and other members of the original Mac development crew
etched on the inside of the case. The seller wants $50. The high
bid so far? $19.95.
</P>
<P>
   The perfect solution? Not for the first time, you've come to the
right place. You may want to join the MacQuarium movement, launched
in 1992 by Andy Ihnatko, a columnist for the defunct MacUser
magazine. More or less tongue in cheek, Ihnatko suggested that
over-the-hill Macs might make nice aquariums. His original,
easy-to-follow instructions are still available at
www.microserve.com/hac/interesting/macquarium/. Sample: ``Open the
case and remove the logic board, analog board, CRT yoke and
assembly, disk drive(s), hard drive, and frame. Discard.''
</P>
<P>
   Now there are MacQuariums everywhere! (See
www.alpine.k12.ut.us/ASD/Departments/Tech/Fish/Links.html) This
should give those people in New Hampshire something to think about.
A caveman diorama mounted in that rusted-out Buick sitting on the
lawn? Why not?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-22-99 1319EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991222.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6434 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-22 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREAT READS ON A POLITICIAN'S CAREER AND HIS ENVIRONMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you want to understand politics and media in the last third
of what the labelers are calling the American Century, help is at
hand.
</P>
<P>
   In your bookstore, virtual or otherwise, ``Edward M. Kennedy: A
Biography'' (William Morrow), a 692-page epic by Adam Clymer, is a
massive and meticulous account of the career of the storied
senator, a product of seven years' labor, interviews with 300
interested parties, and 21 face-offs with Theodore.
</P>
<P>
   This is a Cheops' Tome of a book, a great pyramid testament to a
politicial career that will have no sequel. There will not be
another biography of a US senator as thorough and detailed as this,
a Kennedy intimate assured me last weekend. No, because there will
not be another career like his in the foreseeable future.
</P>
<P>
   The book's conclusion:
</P>
<P>
   ``He deserves recognition not just as the leading senator of his
time, but as one of the greats in its history, wise in the workings
of this singular institution, especially in its demand to be more
than partisan to accomplish much . . . A son of privilege, he has
always identified with the poor and the oppressed. The deaths and
tragedies around him would have led others to withdraw. He never
quits, but sails against the wind.''
</P>
<P>
   I buy that.
</P>
<P>
   Teddy went to Washington as a callow youth, kid brother of a
president, and did battle with the early-'60s status-quo that
included such repressive laws as the poll tax, which kept poor
people from voting.
</P>
<P>
   He's the legislative equivalent of a nuclear reactor, an
unquenchable volcano spouting practical concern for the Great
Unwashed. When he eulogized the six dead Worcester firefighters
Dec. 9, no figure in public life could have been as persuasive.
Because we all know Teddy's story and how many caskets he's prayed
over.
</P>
<P>
   Clymer, The New York Times's most senior Washington
correspondent, recounts a career that will not be duplicated
because of the changes in politics and government we've witnessed
since JFK's death.
</P>
<P>
   Just how the biz changed is the theme of ``No Way to Pick a
President'' (Farrar, Straus and Giroux), the story of how the
``money-driven technocracy'' of pollsters, consultants,
election-law lawyers, and spin doctors has hijacked our elections
and made ventriloquist's dummies of our victors.
</P>
<P>
   This, the 16th political book by 40-year veteran reporter Jules
Witcover, the shy half of the Germond-Witcover columnist tag-team,
documents in 303 pages how presidential elections changed _ for the
worse _ between Eisenhower's in 1952 and the one we are suffering
through now. Where Clymer explains what happened in public policy,
Witcover traces the downward spiral of the presidential-picking
process.
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, I've known both authors for decades, and can
vouch for their bona fides. Like Witcover's wisecracking partner,
Jack Germond, whose current hard-cover offering, ``Fat Man in a
Middle Seat: 40 Years of Covering Politics'' (Random House, 284
pp.) I touted in a recent column, Clymer and Witcover are members
in good standing of the Old Brigade of veteran journalists whose
fairness and judgment are widely accepted by those in the trade.
</P>
<P>
   In an era of books edited in half-arsed fashion and flogged by
TV personalities who possibly don't know any better, this should
count for something, and maybe even does. As Bob Dole would say,
``Whatever . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Witcover's poster boy for consultants-gone-berserk is the
ubiquitous Dick Morris, the brainy but conscienceless consultant
who has sold candidacies as diverse as Bill Clinton, Trent Lott,
and Bill Weld.
</P>
<P>
   Morris, who now cluck-clucks about Clinton's failings for Rupert
Murdoch's Fox television network, told Witcover he charged the
Clinton campaign about $1.5 million for all the advice on
``triangulation'' and moving-to-the-center he sold Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   It was Clinton's lust for the huge sums of money Morris was
spending on TV ads and his fees that triggered the Lincoln Bedroom
sleepovers and Buddhist Nun fund-raisers that led to the White
House fund-raising scandals investigated loudly but ineffectually
by GOP critics these past three years.
</P>
<P>
   The low point of negative campaign tactics, Witcover attests,
was the defeat of Michael Dukakis by George Bush the Elder. ``That
1988 campaign marked the greatest triumph yet of negative
television advertising concocted by hired guns.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Bush Senior relying on wiseguys like Roger Ailes, the
adman who packaged Nixon's victory in 1968 and now the chief
alchemist of Murdoch's Fox News network, and the late Lee Atwater,
whose embrace of below-the-belt tactics was legendary.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the descent of the news biz into toxic tabloid
territory is documented in ``Warp Speed: America in the Age of
Mixed Media'' (Century Foundation, 193 pp.) by Harvard's Bill
Kovach and Tom Rosenstiel. The subtitle could be ``mixed-up
media,'' for all the grim failures, ethical and judgmental,
documented in this account of the slide to the slime.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-22-99 1321EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991222.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6435 &Cx1f; taf-z
r a BC-CURE-FOR-ALZHEIMERS-(     12-22 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CURE-FOR-ALZHEIMERS-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENGINEERING A CURE FOR ALZHEIMER'S  
 (FOR RELEASE THE WEEK OF MON., DEC. 13, 1999)
</HEADLINE>
   (This article from the London-based science and technology weekly
NEW SCIENTIST is free for use for New York Times News Service
clients. Please send clippings to the New York Times Syndicate at
122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168 or fax clippings to
212-499-3382.) 
 By NELL BOYCE  
 Copyright 1999 New Scientist  
 (Distributed by New York Times Syndicate)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first trial to test whether gene therapy can slow the
progress of Alzheimer's disease has been given the go-ahead. In
theory the same technique could be used to enhance the cognitive
ability of people who aren't suffering from dementia.
</P>
<P>
   Alzheimer's is the most common cause of dementia in older
people, killing brain cells called cholinergic neurons. As the
number of elderly people in developed nations increases,
Alzheimer's is exacting an ever more devastating toll, so finding
effective ways to treat it is a top priority.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers led by Mark Tuszynski of the University of
California, San Diego, are betting that a substance called nerve
growth factor will stave off dementia not only by preventing the
death of cholinergenic neurons, but also by promoting new
connections between the cells.
</P>
<P>
   A decade of experiments on rodents and primates shows that NGF
helps protect cholinergic neurons and can reverse memory loss. In
September, for instance, Tuszynski's team showed that NGF gene
therapy could reverse age-related neural degeneration in rhesus
monkeys, with the genes remaining active for at least a year.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before Christmas, the National Institutes of Health's
Recombinant DNA Advisory Committee cleared an initial safety study
that will involve eight people with early Alzheimer's disease who
can understand and consent to the procedure. First, the researchers
will take cells called fibroblasts from the patients' skin and
genetically engineer them to produce NGF by adding extra copies of
the gene using a mouse leukemia virus modified to ensure that it
shouldn't trigger cancer. Then they will inject the NGF-producing
cells into the base of the patients' forebrains.
</P>
<P>
   Although the committee agreed that the virus that will be used
to deliver the NGF gene poses little risk, one member did question
the growth factor itself. Wilma Friedman of Columbia University in
New York noted that NGF can kill brain cells that carry a receptor
called p75 but not another called trk. However, Tuszynski points
out that cells in the basal forebrain seem to have both receptors.
</P>
<P>
   The main goal of the trial is to assess the maximum dose of
modified cells that can be safely injected. But Tuszynski will also
look to see if the disease progresses more slowly than normal. ``We
think there is a direct potential for benefit,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers have had to resort to gene therapy because NGF
injected into the blood stream doesn't readily cross the
blood-brain barrier. However, any genetic technique that affects
brain function has the potential to generate controversy. Earlier
this year, for instance, when Joe Tsien and his colleagues at
Princeton University in New Jersey created transgenic mice with
improved memories by boosting levels of the gene for a receptor on
the surface of brain cells called NMDA, there was widespread
speculation about using the human version of the gene to engineer
``supersmart'' people.
</P>
<P>
   Tuszynski plays down these fears. ``Most of these studies that
demonstrate enhanced brain function with growth factors or other
agents, like Tsien's, have been done to understand what the normal,
physiological role of a gene is,'' he says. Using similar
techniques to treat debilitating diseases such as Alzheimer's
doesn't mean that anyone is suggesting that they should be used to
improve normal human cognitive function, Tuszynski stresses.
</P>
<P>
   However, Eric Juengst, a bioethicist at Case Western Reserve
University in Cleveland, says that many gene therapies designed to
treat disease also have potential for genetically enhancing healthy
people. ``This just highlights a problem that the committee will
see increasingly,'' he says. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (This article is excerpted from New Scientist, a weekly science
and technology magazine based in London.) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-22-99 1322EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
