<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOM-BESTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO SHORTAGE OF UNSUNG PIONEERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We've heard their names often these past few weeks: Babe
Didrickson Zaharias, Jackie Joyner-Kersee, Billie Jean King,
Martina Navratilova and Chris Evert, Sonja Henie. All indisputably
changed not only the face of women's sports but also the attitudes
of those who watched it happen; beacons of athleticism and courage,
each deserves all the end-of-century attention she is finally
getting, and more.
</P>
<P>
   But there are so many others. Some are women who stood up and
proclaimed themselves athletes despite being told to sit back down;
others are women who proclaimed not a thing, but simply did what
they needed to do despite the odds, the obstacles, the ridicule.
Many are world champions or Olympic gold medalists; others have
names that may not even ring a bell. Together, they compose not a
Top 10, but merely a sampling of fearlessness and intregrity that
cannot go unheralded in this season of bests and mosts and
greatests.
</P>
<P>
   In alphabetical order:
</P>
<P>
   --Michelle Akers, who struggled through chronic fatigue syndrome
ferociously to help the US women's soccer team win last summer's
World Cup, then quietly went home to Florida to rest and spread the
word of God.
</P>
<P>
   --Ernestine Bayer, the Stratham, N.H., nonagenarian often
recognized as the matriarch of women's rowing in America. It took
her 10 years from the time she got married in 1928 to persuade her
skeptical husband (``Women don't row'') to let her take a boat out
on the Schuylkill River; within a year she would start the first
women's rowing organization in the country.
</P>
<P>
   --Hassiba Bourlmerka, the first African woman to win a world
title and the first Algerian to win an Olympic gold medal (1500
meters, 1992). Before her triumph in Barcelona she often had to
dodge rocks thrown at her on training runs; afterward she reported
receiving death threats from Islamic militants. Just this June, she
caused a furor when she refused to back down, in front of an
International Olympic Committee panel, from accusations against
Mexico of gender discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   --Teresa Edwards, the 35-year-old founding member of the
American Basketball League who is on her way to becoming a
five-time Olympian. After turning down an offer from the WNBA after
the ABL folded because she was insulted by its rookie salary offer,
one of the most respected women to ever pick up a basketball was on
her way to play in Turkey before USA Basketball called asking her
to rejoin the national team.
</P>
<P>
   --Ludmila Engquist, the Russian-born hurdler competing for
Sweden who inspired countless women when she won a bronze medal at
last summer's World Championships while undergoing chemotherapy
treatments for breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   --Chris Ernst, captain of Yale's varsity women's crew in 1976
who, along with her teammates, stripped naked (``These are the
bodies Yale is exploiting'') in an administrator's office to
protest the conditions under which they were forced to practice.
The conditions improved. Ernst is now a plumber living in
Brookline, and subject of the documentary ``A Hero for Daisy.''
</P>
<P>
   --Cammi Granato, whose graceful skating and gracious manner made
it OK for thousands of young girls to play ice hockey without
having to cut their hair and sign up as boys, as many of her 1998
Olympic gold medal teammates had to do when they were young.
</P>
<P>
   --Tegla Loroupe, the marathon world-record holder from Kenya who
spoke out against her federation's neglect of women on the day she
won her first New York Marathon in 1994 and who hasn't stopped yet.
</P>
<P>
   --Kathrine Switzer, in 1967 the first woman to officially run
the Boston Marathon. Without Switzer's determination and lobbying,
there might never have been a women's marathon in the 1984 Olympics
for Joan Benoit Samuelson to win.
</P>
<P>
   --Louise Rossetti, Phil Campbell, the late Ruth Rothfarb, and
every other recreational athlete who's still going strong in her
70s and 80s and thereby expanding the perception of what it means
to age gracefully.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-22-99 1322EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991222.0120 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 13:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6438 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-COMMENT-     12-22 1540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET BLEDSOE BE HEARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Many things have been muttered about the
problems of the New England Patriots' offense the past six weeks
and few have been printable. Yet one thing may have been missed in
all the questioning.
</P>
<P>
   The solution, at least in part, may have been missed.
</P>
<P>
   Men who are paid hundreds of thousands of dollars by Robert
Kraft have not yet found the solution, yet it lies on these pages,
you say with skepticism? Perhaps it does, and these days ``perhaps
it does'' would be a step up from where the Patriots' offense
squats at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   To refresh your memory, after a 6-2 start in which their offense
was terrorizing the NFL, the Patriots have lost five of six, been
eliminated from the playoff race, and scored only seven touchdowns.
Worse, quarterback Drew Bledsoe has been under siege and played
like it.
</P>
<P>
   Davy Crockett was not on the offensive at the Alamo. General
Custer was not on the offensive at the Little Big Horn. So who can
blame Bledsoe for not being on the offensive against NFL defenses
that are flattening him?
</P>
<P>
   In the first eight games, Bledsoe was sacked only 22 times,
threw just four interceptions, delivered 22 touchdown passes, and
was 164 of 271, a completion rate of 60.5 percent. In the last six,
defenses have taken a different approach, and New England has not
answered. Beginning with the Jets game, the Patriots' receivers
have been jammed at the line to take away the intermediate routes
Ernie Zampese's offense relies on, forcing Bledsoe to go deep or
dump the ball short, which is not his mindset or Zampese's.
</P>
<P>
   Defenses have repeatedly attacked with blitzes, particularly
zone blitzes, against New England's scant protection, a scheme that
often results in not enough blockers to cover the number of
rushers, hence the talk of Bledsoe being responsible for one of
those rushers.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is he should be able to get the ball away quickly
enough to an open man to beat the blitz. That works when the
coverage is not as aggressive at the line as it has been, but
lately Bledsoe's receivers have not had time to work free before
the pocket begins to break down, resulting in three predictable
things: increased sacks, increased interceptions, and a quarterback
who feels like Jake LaMotta in the 15th round against Sugar Ray
Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   During this terrible collapse, Bledsoe's numbers have slipped in
ways that seem almost inexplicable until you hear someone like
veteran tackle Bruce Armstrong talk of coming to the line of
scrimmage after a play has been called ``with your fingers
crossed.'' The numbers not only bear this out, they point to a
solution if Zampese and coach Pete Carroll will embrace it.
</P>
<P>
   As Armstrong was saying as diplomatically as possible, plays are
being called that too often are doomed before the snap, and Bledsoe
is not free to change them. In the Patriot offense, Bledsoe is not
allowed to check off or audible except in a few specific
situations. The theory is he can beat the defense with the play
called, which was working fine until the Jets' Bill Belichick came
up with new approaches that checkmated Zampese's.
</P>
<P>
   There are many reasons for that, and the absence of a running
game and the reduced effectiveness of the tight end position, which
is critical in Zampese's scheme, are two big ones. Because of those
weaknesses, Bledsoe needs the freedom to make his own play
selection when he fears Zampese's one is doomed, and the proof of
that is what he has done without that freedom and what has resulted
the few times he's had it.
</P>
<P>
   During this stretch that has knocked New England out of playoff
contention, Bledsoe has gone 116 of 222 for 1,462 yards (a reduced
completion rate of 52.3 percent) with five touchdown passes, 16
interceptions, and 25 sacks. He has silently gone down with the
ship, refusing to question his coaches, criticize receivers who
haven't gotten open, or rip his linemen.
</P>
<P>
   But the source of the problem and perhaps its solution may be
buried amid the rubble: Of New England's seven miserly touchdowns
during this drought, five have come on pass plays with Bledose in
the shotgun running the two-minute offense.
</P>
<P>
   Only then is he free to audibilize or check off to get his
offense out of problems posed at the line of scrimmage after he
sees the defense, and only then does he have the freedom to make
his own play selections.
</P>
<P>
   Five of seven touchdowns in a two-minute situation says
something, and not simply that defenses are laying back, because
three of those scoring passes were for 68, 45, and 31 yards to
three receivers (Shawn Jefferson, Terry Glenn, and Troy Brown), all
of whom beat coverages deep.
</P>
<P>
   What it seems to say is that it's time to unleash not only the
arm of Bledsoe but also his mind. As one offensive player, who
chose anonymity for obvious reasons, put it, ``It's totally
(expletive) ridiculous to have a guy like Bledsoe as quarterback
and not have an audible system. There are five or 10 times a game
he could get us out of a bad play or an average play into a bigger
one, but we don't even have that capability.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have real trouble with zone blitzes because of that.
They're jamming our receivers in press coverage, and the routes we
have called to beat it take time to develop. The receivers don't
have the time or the freedom to get open because they can't just
run to a spot and turn around now. So Bledsoe is holding the ball
longer, and that's resulting in hits on him or the ball going out
to guys who are still covered.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say all the blame lies with Zampese. In the
Eagles debacle, for example, Zampese called at least four plays
that should have been touchdowns. Because of poor execution, none
was.
</P>
<P>
   The most obvious was when Glenn dropped a pass in the end zone
when he was wide open.
</P>
<P>
   The second was when Zampese called a play that got Jefferson
open behind the defense, but Jefferson became slightly disoriented
as he caught the ball and was unsure of where he was on the field.
He ran out of bounds instead of into the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   The third came with Jefferson open on a corner route behind the
defense. Bledsoe saw him, but just as he went to throw, his
protection broke down a second too early, and he was hit in the
chest by William Thomas as he released the ball. As a result, the
ball looked more like a punt than a pass when it fell into the
hands of Al Harris at the 5-yard line, 10 yards short of an open
Jefferson.
</P>
<P>
   The last was on a slant route to Glenn against a blitz. He beat
the coverage, but the ball didn't get there in stride, for which
Bledsoe carries the blame.
</P>
<P>
   Four plays that should have been 6 points each time resulted in
none, not because of the scheme but because of execution, which
Bledsoe acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bad as it was, and it was pretty bad, the plays were there for
us,'' Bledsoe said Tuesday. ``Watching that thing was bad. It
didn't look good, but we had four touchdowns we just didn't get.
That wasn't coaching. That was us.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a finesse team, especially on offense. We have to make
those plays. That's how we hurt teams. We don't play with that real
attitude that we'll beat you up. We burn people in those situations
so they had to play off us, but we don't pound people. Maybe that's
my fault. I'm pretty laid-back. Maybe the team takes on my
personality.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet if he could change plays he knows will not work before the
snap or is given the freedom to call more of his own as the game
moves along, it is likely the Patriots would hit more of those
plays that burn defenses and hence Bledsoe wouldn't seem so
laid-back. The personality of his team might once again resemble
that of the 6-2 squad. How about that possibility being considered
instead of simplistic nonsense such as the ``Put Michael Bishop in
the game, man'' that talk radio denizens have adopted?
</P>
<P>
   It is time for a 60-minute game to be played in two-minute
intervals for now. It is time for Bledsoe to be given the freedom
to change the play at the line and go with what he believes might
work rather than have Armstrong trying to pass-block with fingers
crossed.
</P>
<P>
   It is no accident that defenses began to attack the Patriots
differently after their fast start. It's also no accident that the
times he has beaten those defenses for touchdowns, it's been in
two-minute situations, where he was running the team and adjusting
the call.
</P>
<P>
   The current approach is an indictment not of Zampese's play-
calling but of a system that refuses to allow room for adjustment
or input from the person most involved _ the quarterback. No one is
right all the time, as the present 1-5 collapse makes clear.
</P>
<P>
   Are the handcuffs on Bledsoe's mind the only problem? No. Has he
made some ill-conceived throws? Admittedly so. But would the
offense be better served and more productive working with more of a
two-minute philosophy in which the quarterback has more direct
control of the play calling, at least until defenses back off their
aggressive assaults on him?
</P>
<P>
   Five of seven touchdowns the last six games fairly screams that
out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
