</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-FEARS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARTY MANIA FOR MILLENNIUM IS SEEN EBBING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For some, it's the fear of terrorism. Many others
are unwilling to shell out the hundreds or even thousands of
dollars demanded for New Year's Eve extravaganzas. And still others
do not want to party until they know the Y2K bugs have been stamped
out.
</P>
<P>
   The result is the same: Faced with the only opportunity of our
lifetimes to celebrate the turning of a millennium, Americans are
planning to stay home in droves.
</P>
<P>
   They are motivated by the combination of hype and hysteria, a
whole year saturated with best-of-the-century lists, global
hand-wringing over the Y2K computer bug and potential terrorist
attacks, rhinestone-studded 2000 mementos for sale, and the extra
pressure to do something extra special for this particular New
Year.
</P>
<P>
   It is all just too much, say many who plan to miss the blowout
party scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is the anti-New Year's Eve,'' said Lisa Salvati, a
36-year-old producer in Manhattan. Despite living in a favorite New
Year's Eve party venue, Salvati says she will spend the evening in
quiet reflection with her parents.
</P>
<P>
   Salvati will not be alone. This year, 61 percent of Americans
will stay home this New Year's Eve, compared to the 66 percent who
typically stay home, according to an ABC poll released two weeks
ago. The figure was 54 percent in August, indicating a
couch-sitting trend as the year 2000 approaches.
</P>
<P>
   The Jacob K. Javits Center in New York had to cancel its ``Party
of The Century,'' where the likes of Aretha Franklin and Sting were
set to perform, because the tickets weren't selling. An expensive
charity event in Washington was also canceled because of poor
ticket sales.
</P>
<P>
   While the cheaper tickets (those costing $75) to Billy Joel's
New Year's Eve performance in Madison Square Garden have been sold
out, the $999 tickets are still available.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people got turned off by the big hoopla and the
expense,'' said Brad Johnson, a lawyer in Washington. ``I was
thinking at one point of going to Paris, but I think I'm just going
to hang out here.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, some revelers are prepared to dump massive amounts
of cash on the evening; a Florida couple is spending $100,000 for
an ultra-swanky celebration at Boston's Ritz-Carlton hotel. Others
are flying to Egypt for a New Year's celebration at the Pyramids, a
fete that costs $1,999 inclusive.
</P>
<P>
   But around the globe, event planners and travel agents are
finding ticket sales lagging.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just really one of the victims of what's going on in
the whole world, not just in our country,'' said Leslie Hayes of
Virginia-based Hayes &AMP; Associates, which planned _ and was forced
to cancel _ the ``America's New Millenium'' charity event in
downtown Washington. ``People just aren't going out.''
</P>
<P>
   The event, known as the Party With a Purpose, was to raise $1
million for 20 local charities by charging $500 to $2,000 a ticket
for a buffet meal, drinks, and a peformance by Roger Daltrey of The
Who.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very disappointed,'' said Craig Shniderman of Food for
Friends, which delivers meals to AIDS patients. But Shniderman said
he had an inkling the party wasn't selling well when he got a call
at home from a telemarketer peddling tickets to the party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime they're telemarketing tickets that are $500 to $2,000
apiece, you know the event's in trouble,'' Shniderman said.
</P>
<P>
   Special millennium packages for Caribbean cruises are going for
as little as half their original cost, though the prices were
jacked up to begin with, said Traci Irvine of Atlanta-based Travel
Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``People weren't willing to pay $3,000 for a five-day cruise,''
and the cruise liners vastly overestimated how much of a premium
people would pay for a millennial package, Irvine said.
</P>
<P>
   The Fiji Visitors Bureau is promoting packages to the island of
Taveuni, which some travelers wrongly believe is crossed by the
International Dateline (it's just very near), said Darrell Einarson
of Fiji Travel in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   But ``people are backing out'' of the trip, Einarson said.
``Huge mobs of people put down deposits, thousands of dollars, and
are not going to show,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   People don't generally give a reason for canceling, he said, but
Einarson and others said the increasing focus on the possibility of
terrorism is probably a factor.
</P>
<P>
   The US State Department has warned Americans that terrorists
might strike at midnight, and that US citizens should be on alert
at large gatherings here and abroad as the millennium changes.
</P>
<P>
   The concern was heightened by the recent arrest near Seattle of
an Algerian man, who authorities said was carrying explosives, and
the arrest Sunday of another Algerian man in Vermont. Both men
allegedly tried to enter the country from Canada with falsified
documents.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, NBC employees are being issued special building
passes for the the period around New Year's, because Rockefeller
Center could be a target, a network employee said.
</P>
<P>
   Even without threats of violence, some said, the logistics for
this New Year's Eve are just too much trouble. Baby-sitters are
hard to come by, and cabs are likely to be scarce. One New York
woman said she feared not riots in the streets, but a power outage.
What Manhattan high-rise resident wants to risk having to climb 22
flights of stairs if the elevators are not running?
</P>
<P>
   Those who do want to celebrate are tending toward smaller, less
expensive parties or large, free events, planners say.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the national prosperity, ``people aren't willing to blow
money on New Year's,'' said New Yorker Christian Spears, a
26-year-old stock trader. So Spears and his friends in the
financial-services industry are sponsoring a $250-a-head party at
Manhattan's Metropolitan Pavillion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's relatively affordable'' for the young professionals, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and Hillary Rodham Clinton are hosting a
dinner for 300 people and a reception for 800.
</P>
<P>
   Those who didn't get an invitation can still celebrate the
millennium with the Clintons. ``America's Millennium'' in
Washington is free and is expected to draw many thousands of
people. Highlighting the event will be musical performances on the
National Mall, and a short Steven Spielberg film narrated by the
president.
</P>
<P>
   But many aren't venturing out at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're kind of hunkering down,'' said Daphne Atkeson, a
46-year-old novelist in Phoenix. ``I'm going to have to set the
clock for 11:30 just to be awake at midnight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
