<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILLIPS KNOWS THE RUNDOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wade Phillips knows the feeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was coaching in Denver (1994) and we didn't have a running
game,'' said the Buffalo Bills coach. ``They were all over John
Elway. He was getting chased every play. They knew we couldn't run,
and they came after John. We start out losing four in a row . . .''
</P>
<P>
   And at the end of the year, Phillips took the fall. He was the
head coach in Denver for two years, reached the playoffs the first
season and was fired the next, when his team finished 7-9.
</P>
<P>
   Now he is trying to bring the Bills to the playoffs, and he sees
some similarities in watching game film of the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   ``New England hasn't been able to run the ball, so teams are
just coming after (Drew) Bledsoe,'' he said. ``They (the Patriots)
are putting it all on him. It's hard for anyone to do. He's still a
hell of a quarterback, and they've still got a lot of talented
guys. But when you can't run the ball, it's hard to score points.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that the Bills are tearing it up on offense. Even though
they have won five of their last seven games, they are still
struggling to score. Last Sunday night they beat the Cardinals in
Arizona, 31-21, but the last touchdown came on a return of an
onside kick. And in the three previous games, they had scored 7,
17, and 17. Why? Because their top runner, Antowain Smith, has been
hobbled by injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each week we thought he was going to play,'' said Phillips.
``He'd practice during the week, but in the warmup before the game,
he couldn't go. It messed us up some on offense. So last week, we
just decided that no matter what, Jonathan Linton was going to be
our guy, and we ran the ball well.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bills run the ball no matter what. They average 33 runs per
game, even though their average per carry is 3.9. Both Linton (167
carries, 595 yards) and Smith (162-583) average 3.6 yards per
carry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy that has run well for us is (Doug) Flutie,'' said
Phillips. ``Teams have started to play more man-to-man defense
against him this year, and that leaves him some openings in the
running game. He's run the ball something like 80 times and made
some good yardage.''
</P>
<P>
   Flutie is averaging 5.3 yards per game (82 rushes, 432 yards).
He has not thrown the ball as well as he did last season because
opposing defenses have a better read on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``A year ago we had success in the spread offense,'' said
Phillips. ``Doug was very good in that set. But like it always
happens, the defenses started to adjust to it. Now when a team
spreads out (like New England), they're going to come after the
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're lucky that Doug can run the ball the way he can, so we
can hurt them in those situations. When they blitz like that, a lot
of times they're playing man-to-man downfield. So if Doug can beat
the rush, he can make some first downs for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way it is in this business. Someone will come up
with an offense that is hard to stop. Like the run and shoot. When
it first started to have success in the league, everyone starts to
say, `Why don't all teams do that?' Then, after a couple of years,
defensive coaches figured out a way to attack. Soon the run and
shoot wasn't a big deal anymore. Now they have figured out how to
attack the spread offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``This edge from offense to defense goes back and forth all the
time in this league. The offense had the edge for awhile. Now I
think it is shifting back to defense. It's very hard to score
points consistently right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bills need this game Sunday. They are in a wild playoff
chase in the AFC. But if they do get in, the Bills could easily be
the surprise team.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Smith said two weeks ago that this is the best Buffalo
defense he has ever played with. They are a veteran playoff team
with the ability to win on the road. That will help if Smith comes
back to join Linton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this will be the week we get him back,'' said
Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
