<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6442 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-JAILHOUSE-HEALING-ART     12-22 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAILHOUSE-HEALING-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRISONERS GET A BOOK ON STARTING A NEW CHAPTER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDITH GAINES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Instead of just shaving cream and toothpaste in their
stockings this year, inmates at the Suffolk County prison will get
a surprise: a book urging them to find freedom and forgiveness
behind bars through meditation, letting go of their anger, and
getting in touch with the pain they experienced as children.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff Richard J. Rouse is giving out 1,750 copies of the thick
paperback, ``Houses of Healing,'' hoping it will show the convicts
a way to reflect on their crimes and turn their lives around.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought we'd give them something that could help develop
their consciences,'' Rouse explained. ``They're doing time anyway.
Instead of watching ``Jerry Springer,'' they can try something more
profound, like learning who they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Written by psychotherapist Robin Casarjian, ``Houses of
Healing'' has struck a chord with many prisoners and those who work
with them.
</P>
<P>
   A nonprofit group founded by Casarjian has sent about 40,000
copies to libraries in the nation's federal, state, and local
prisons, and to thousands of individual inmates. The book is free
to anyone who cannot afford an $8 donation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Houses of Healing'' asks prisoners to use their incarceration
as a period of spiritual reflection in order to gain a new
awareness of themselves and greater self-respect.
</P>
<P>
   Casarjian argues that acknowledging guilt and remorse and facing
up to the impact of their crimes can help inmates create a more
positive future, and turn the prison into a house of healing.
</P>
<P>
   She tells prisoners their lives are worth reforming _ even if
they have committed horrific crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite honestly, some of the most thoughtful, mature,
compassionate people I have ever met are people in prison doing
life and long-term sentences,'' she writes.
</P>
<P>
   For the rough-hewn Rouse, who knows some of the inmates
personally, Casarjian's approach _ with its emphasis on getting in
touch with the wounded inner child, self-forgiveness, and
self-esteem _ is a bit of a stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not hugging inmates every day or anything,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Rouse said a pilot program Casarjian launched about two
years ago seems to have caught on with prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened to convicted assailant Henry Flynn after he
attended one of Casarjian's workshops while he was at MCI-Concord
about three years ago and then read her book.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went from being an extremely depressed person to a guy who
felt free inside the walls of a prison,'' he said. He could
meditate or pray or cry without embarrassment. He was no longer
embittered by memories of abuse he suffered as a child.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was locked up and I felt totally free,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The population Rouse hopes to reach is made up of prisoners
convicted of less serious crimes, and all of them will be released
within two and a half years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to do whatever we can to get a better product coming
out the door,'' Rouse said.
</P>
<P>
   The Christmas presents, costing a total of about $12,000, are
being paid for by private donations and revenues from the sale of
products and services to inmates. No taxpayers' money is involved.
</P>
<P>
   Casarjian, 51, began her prison work in 1988. She was teaching
stress management and holistic health care in a range of corporate,
medical, and religious settings, ``talking to anyone who would give
me a pulpit,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   One day an addiction counselor asked her to address a group at
MCI-Gardner, a medium-security prison for men. Casarjian agreed,
expecting only a few inmates to attend. She was deeply moved when
120 of them appeared, and responded enthusiastically.
</P>
<P>
   She was invited to return, this time for an extended course, and
by the second week she knew she had found her calling.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had this hunger to make meaning out of their experiences
and turn their lives around,'' she recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Casarjian has given hundreds of workshops at prisons
around the country. To reach a larger audience than she could
address in person, in 1992 she formed the National Emotional
Literacy Project for Prisoners, which published ``Houses of
Healing'' three years later.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of Casarjian's approach is the conviction that
every human being has a core of goodness and sanity. But too often
this gets obscured by destructive or unhealthy
``sub-personalities'' formed to protect the self from childhood
wounds, such as violence, abuse, neglect.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, many inmates have learned ``to look at the
lampshade, instead of the light'' in themselves and others, she
says.
</P>
<P>
   She uses meditation and other stress reduction techniques, as
well as exercises designed to help probe the past, to help them see
their inner worth, forgive those who wounded them, accept
responsibility for their crimes, and move on in more constructive
ways.
</P>
<P>
   The key, she says, is forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   As long as someone holds on to resentment, ``it's like a
handcuff binding them to the person who did the hurting,'' she
says. ``And there's a level of healing and spiritual growth that
never happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Rouse and Casarjian acknowledge that this approach won't reach
everyone. But Casarjian and others who have worked with her say
they have seen scores of lives uplifted and transformed by this
work.
</P>
<P>
   Flynn, 43, said he had been in trouble with the law since age 9
for drinking, drug use, assaults, and armed robberies.
</P>
<P>
   When he was sent to MCI-Concord four years ago on assault and
battery charges, he was so depressed he didn't shower or talk to
anyone for weeks. A friend persuaded him to attend one of
Casarjian's workshops, which he wanted to do ``only slightly more
than I wanted to die,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said she helped him see the effects of physical and mental
abuse he suffered while young, see how afraid he was of the
hard-core criminals who terrorized his neighborhood, see how he
acted just like they did out of fear and for self-defense.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, he said, he began to see his own light.
</P>
<P>
   Now Flynn is out of jail, running a successful home improvement
business, and taking care of his family, he and others said. He
attributes the dramatic changes in his life to the approach he
learned in the pages of Casarjian's book.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call it a life-saving technique,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
