<HEADLINE>
PENSION PLANS, RETIREES AGITATE FOR A BIGGER CUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Marty Quinn had always thought of himself as a good and loyal
employee. For 31 years, he installed and repaired telephone wires,
rarely missing a day's work, until his retirement from Bell
Atlantic Corp. in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But now, the 59-year-old retiree is on the warpath.
</P>
<P>
   Quinn claims the pensions he and other Bell Altantic Corp.
retirees are receiving lack a key element: annual cost-of-living
increases to offset inflation.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, as far back as I can trace, we never went more
than three years without an increase in our pensions,'' said Quinn,
president of the retiree club at the International Brotherhood of
Electrical Workers, Local 2222. ``But next month, it will be nine
years.''
</P>
<P>
   After protesting changes in health care and insurance benefits,
retirees at some of the nation's biggest companies are taking a
closer look at their pension payments, and many aren't happy.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, one of the biggest issues among corporate America's
retirees today is pension plan ``stuffing,'' or overfunding. This
occurs when pension funds, fueled by a booming stock market, are
fattened by lucrative investments. A boost for retirees? Not
really, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although many of the funds are overfunded and there is plenty
of money available to make regular adjustments to retirees,
companies also have an institutional interest in not increasing
benefits,'' said Karen Ferguson, director of the Pension Rights
Center in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The reason? The excess funds in bulging pension plans can be
reported as a credit toward income, resulting in higher earnings.
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal reported in June that several companies
have benefitted from a little-known accounting rule that permits
such income credits in cases in which a company's pension assets
exceed the pension fund's current costs. The newspaper reported
that ``Bell Atlantic's plan produced a $627 million pretax credit
for the firm's 1998 income statement; GTE Corp. gained a $473
million pretax credit, while Caterpillar Inc. scored a $183 million
credit.''
</P>
<P>
   No wonder retirees are angry.
</P>
<P>
   The Coalition for Retirement Security, a retiree advocacy group
in Springfield with a million members nationwide, says it will meet
next month in Washington, D.C., to encourage Congress to require
that employers share the billions accruing in fat corporate pension
funds.
</P>
<P>
   The group may not have much luck, though.
</P>
<P>
   Pension rights experts say the group would be better off
lobbying the Securities and Exchange Commission, since its job is
to make sure corporate financial statements reflect reality. If
there is enough of a hue and cry, the SEC could try to convince the
Financial Accounting Standards Board to alter the accounting rule
by asking companies to add a footnote to their financial
statements, telling investors exactly how much of their reported
income includes pension fund surpluses. Congress could also request
that the accounting standards board update its rule, which went
into effect in 1987 for big companies.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, busloads of Bell Atlantic retirees demonstrated
outside company offices in downtown Boston. The group wants Bell
Atlantic to institute regular cost-of-living increases by tapping
into the nearly $9 billion surplus in the pension fund.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials say concerns about pensions and health benefits
will likely be the central focus of negotiations next year when
Bell Atlantic's two unions, the Communications Workers of America
and the International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers, begin
contract talks.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesman Steve Marcus said Bell Atlantic has done all it could
to help workers who retired 30 or 40 years ago. ``The company has
made a decision to target its resources toward retirees who retired
many years ago, or well before the company made improvements in its
pension benefits and savings plan,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Marcus said, Bell Atlantic authorized an increase
that will hike the pensions of workers with 30 or more years on the
job by at least 75 percent over three years. This means workers
collecting the monthly minimum of $400 will see their pensions rise
to $700 per month by July 2001.
</P>
<P>
   As for more recent retirees, Marcus said, ``You really have to
look at the entire package of benefits that Bell Atlantic provides,
including the pension, and a voluntary savings plan that has
significantly increased in value and to which the company
contributes 83 cents per dollar up to the first 6 percent of the
workers' income.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that Bell Atlantic retirees also receive medical and
dental benefits and discounted local telephone service. ``This
ranks among the best packages offered by any company in America,''
Marcus said.
</P>
<P>
   But although Bell Atlantic is offering increases to longtime
retirees, activists describe the raise as too little in an era of
high rents, food and transportation costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you put in 30 years you'll get an increase, but in today's
dollars it's really not much,'' said Ed Creegan, president of a
7,000-member retiree group for members of the Communications
Workers of America.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are seeing is that there are a lot of women who were
telephone operators and worked for the company for a long time, but
they are only getting a proportion of their total salary, which
leaves them with very, very little. And if you have 20 years, you
get nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Rita Scott was 16 when she started working for the phone company
54 years ago. By most accounts, it was an employer of choice for
women.
</P>
<P>
   Scott had six children during those years. Her mother helped her
and her husband by caring for the children until 1967, when Scott
quit to care for them full time.
</P>
<P>
   Now 70, she received a raise in her pension in July, to $350
from $261 a month. Asked how she manages to live, Scott said:
</P>
<P>
   ``When my husband died two years ago, I started receiving his
Social Security for about $1,000 per month, and his company gives
me $300. But we were paying more than $6,000 in taxes on our house
until my daughter and grandson got me a senior discount. Now, I'm
paying $2,300 a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a good worker for the phone company,'' she added. ``I
was telephone operator when I started, but then I went on to become
a supervisor. I had a good rapport with the people I worked with.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Questions, comments, story ideas? Contact Diane E. Lewis at
work(at)globe.com, or 617-929-2069.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
