<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6446 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-HOLIDAY-BONUS-BOS &LR;      12-22 1519
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-BONUS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YULE BONUSES FADING PRACTICE AT BIG COMPANIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Each Christmas, for the last 14 years, hand sewer Shirley Tracy
has received a yuletide cash bonus from her employer, L.L. Bean
Inc. of Freeport, Maine. Tucked in a personalized greeting card,
this year's gift of $100 is a time-honored tradition dating back
more than three decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``The feeling you get when you receive your gift is that you're
part of the L.L. Bean family,'' said Tracy, 55, of Bowdoinham,
Maine. ``People put in long hours. Some even put their family lives
on hold to make sure customers are taken care of. So, the gift is a
show of appreciation.''
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, L.L. Bean, the large New England catalog and
retail company with 10,000 employees, is an anomaly: Only a handful
of big firms still offer the traditional holiday bonus.
</P>
<P>
   In this tight labor market and go-go economy, compensation
specialists say, such bonuses are now as rare as the horse and
buggy, though some small firms uphold the tradition. Most large
employers now favor stock options, fiscal year-end bonuses tied to
performance, and other forms of profit-sharing, all of which fit
under the rubric ``variable compensation.''
</P>
<P>
   Firms feel that the Christmas bonus ``doesn't give as much
return on investment as the performance-related bonus, which is
given throughout the year and not just during the holidays,'' said
Cindi Fukami, a management professor at the Daniels College of
Business in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   The thriving US economy, with unemployment hovering at record
lows and productivity on the rise, has not resulted in a rash of
holiday gift-giving or cash bonuses for the vast majority of US
employees.
</P>
<P>
   Holiday gifts of food, merchandise, or cash will be distributed
this December to workers at 37 percent of 413 firms polled by the
Bureau of National Affairs Inc., down from 40 percent last year.
Only 9 percent of firms with 1,000 or more employees will
distribute cash gifts to workers, according to the BNA, a privately
held research company that focuses on public policy and employment
issues. By contrast, 25 percent of small companies polled will
offer modest cash gifts tied to the holidays rather than
profit-sharing, with median gifts of $100 for nonmanagers to about
$150 for managers.
</P>
<P>
   This nationwide shift from the traditional yuletide bonus to
performance-based rewards is as much cultural as it is financial.
The new paradigm was ushered in by downsizings, mergers, and
increased competition, all of which have come at the cost of
long-held traditions and corporate lore. And since employment
longevity is now measured in a few years rather than in decades,
rewards for work tend to be more immediate, tied to the present
rather than the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Folks who still receive holiday bonuses tend to work at
smaller, privately held companies that have had a history of
offering them. It's ingrained in their culture,'' said James
Hudner, a consultant at Towers Perrin in Boston, a human resources
consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, increasingly, the expectation is that the employees
will not be at the company indefinitely, which means the rewards
have to be a lot more tangible,'' he said. ``They must relate to
how the individual performed, or how the team performed, or how the
organization as a whole performed, as opposed to past times, when
the message with a holiday bonus was simply, `Thanks for being part
of the family.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Fukami of Daniels College said, ``The Christmas bonus is a bit
like the annual civil service raise, which means if I'm living and
breathing and sitting at my desk, then I'll get it.''
</P>
<P>
   At R.A.D. Employment Services Inc. in Boston, president Bob A.
Dorne gives cash bonuses to his 10 employees during the week
between Christmas and New Year's. ``I do it based on longevity and
how well the business is doing,'' said Dorne, who declined to
reveal the amount.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman at Millipore Corp. in Bedford, which develops,
manufactures, and sells purification products to the pharmaceutical
and research markets, couldnot remember whether the firm had ever
offered the old-fashioned holiday bonus.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have profit-sharing, which is mainly for senior managers,''
said Millipore's Barbara Russo. ``And we have a cash bonus plan for
all 2,000 employees in the United States, based on the results of
the corporation.''
</P>
<P>
   The company employs 1,500 in three facilities in Massachusetts,
about a third of its worldwide employee total. According to Russo,
the minimum cash outlay is 1 percent of a worker's salary. Awards
of 2 percent and 5 percent are also given out in February, based on
corporate financial targets.
</P>
<P>
   No bonuses were offered last year because of a downturn in the
semiconductor industry, but the company expects to reward workers
this year, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity Investments in Boston offers profit-sharing, stock, and
annual bonuses in December. ``The end of the year is when we
determine how well we perform, which means the bonus is not tied to
the holiday at all,'' said spokesman Vincent Loporchio. The company
employs 29,300 worldwide, of whom more than 12,000 work in
Massachusetts. ``Some part of our compensation program reaches
virtually all of our employees.''
</P>
<P>
   At Tom's of Maine, spokeswoman Katherine Taggersell said, ``We
want to respect our workers, but it shouldn't just apply to the
holiday. So, we don't have a Christmas bonus. Instead, we give out
24-pound turkeys at Thanksgiving. We offer perks throughout the
year, and we have profit-sharing bonuses that everybody shares in,
including front-line factory staff.'' The Kennebunk maker of
natural personal care products employs 120.
</P>
<P>
   Natick-based Zweig White &AMP; Associates, a management consulting
firm with 55 employees in five cities, offered holiday cash bonuses
when it opened its doors 11 years ago. It no longer does.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we grew larger and wanted to create a system that tied
everyone into overall performance, we switched to a program paying
25 percent of profits to employees on a quarterly basis,'' said
Mark Zweig, president and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   In a hot labor market, say specialists, stock options and other
performance-based awards can help employers recruit top workers
without raising real wages.
</P>
<P>
   ``One way to interpret these alternative forms of compensation
is that they are a way to help workers cash in on booming sales
without adjusting wage structures and raising pay for everybody,''
said Jared Bernstein, an economist at the Economic Policy Institute
in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   If the stock market falls, however, stock options and
profit-sharing cannot compete with a raise in base pay.
</P>
<P>
   Offering stock packages may also help employers overcome the
wage compression problems companies sometimes encounter during
periods of full employment. When wages compress, gaps between
entry-level pay and average professional salaries begin to close,
causing seasoned employees to leave in search of higher salaries
and better benefits.
</P>
<P>
   In the best-case scenario, both wage and salary employees
benefit from performance-based bonuses. ``When companies use
profit-sharing, most wage and salary employees will benefit,'' said
Paul Harrington, an economist at Northeastern University's Center
for Labor Market Studies. But, he added, most manufacturing
companies don't offer profit-sharing. ``Most hourly people get a
salary and that's it.''
</P>
<P>
   Where compensation varies across the spectrum, however, those in
highest demand are more likely to receive stock options or large
cash bonuses tied to year-end corporate results than is the man or
woman in front-line manufacturing, entry-level, or nonprofessional
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody really gets cash anymore,'' said Bob Lyle, business
agent of the The New England Joint Board of the Retail and
Wholesale Department Store Union. ``Mostly, it's the upper echelon
of management that gets the big bucks.''
</P>
<P>
   When Towers Perrin surveyed 500 US firms about their
compensation plans, it found that of the 59 New England firms
polled, 75 percent had some type of variable compensation plan in
place for professionals. Of those, only 50 percent had plans that
covered nonprofessional staff.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1912, L.L. Bean opened its first retail store in
1917. By then, owner Leon Leonwood Bean had a thriving business and
a small army of factory workers hand-sewing the company's trademark
moccasins, boat shoes, and slippers.
</P>
<P>
   Tracy, who began working at the Brunswick, Maine, plant in 1985,
describes hand-sewing as a dying art, and says the cash gift is a
tradition front-line workers such as herself have come to expect.
This year, L.L. Bean is giving $100 to employees with a year or
more on the job, $40 to workers with at least three months'
service, and $20 to seasonal employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot of hard work,'' Tracy said of her job. ``People
really appreciate the gift because it goes beyond what most
companies do. Even the temporary workers who haven't been here long
get something.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
