<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTLING BIGNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO -- Holiday shoppers are still mourning String Box
Books, missing its cozy atmosphere and knowledgeable service. The
place went dark on Halloween in a pattern familiar in cities and
towns: Small stores close, unable to compete with big chains and
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   In the mayoral election here, an anti-Seattle theme resounded as
chain stores became an issue. ``No more Starbucks!'' swore several
candidates, denouncing the coffee conglomerate that brews bigness
in the same city as Amazon.com, which advertises ``Earth's biggest
selection'' of books and things.
</P>
<P>
   Caffeine and literature are not just centuries-old hallmarks of
urban civilization. They are now commodities and political
footballs.
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, challenger Tom Ammiano declared war on
``gentrification,'' which he defined not as people fixing up their
houses, but as big chains displacing mom-and-pop stores. Mayor
Willie Brown dissented, saying many urban areas would welcome a
national chain.
</P>
<P>
   In the precious precincts of liberal consumerism, Starbucks is
unwelcome and McDonald's is aesthetically incorrect. But in
thousands of square miles of urban America, residents would cheer
and celebrate a Burger King. As cities revive economically, many
neighborhoods remain undeveloped. In their need to join the
mainstream, they are not fussy about brand names.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot is now among the companies that define the Dow Jones
average. Is this bad news for Hank's Hardware? Not necessarily. An
urban neighborhood is by definition a niche market where
independent merchants can thrive.
</P>
<P>
   Should government be in the business of excluding brand names
solely because of their bigness? Urban sales differ from a
big-chain retailer destabilizing the economy of a small town. The
National Trust for Historic Preservation has fought valiantly
against such projects, but cities are less fragile. Cities, in
fact, depend on change.
</P>
<P>
   Here, Brown won the election and the argument. His 20-point
victory in the nation's most liberal city reaffirmed the primacy of
the market. Even in a neighborhood Ammiano carried easily,
consumers tend to vote with their wallets. At the corner of Haight
and Ashbury streets, Ben &AMP; Jerry's, a chain, sells lots of ice
cream. At another corner, The Gap, a clothing chain, unloads tons
of duds.
</P>
<P>
   Boycotting Starbucks might be effective, but it hasn't been
tried. When one opens in a supposedly hostile neighborhood, folks
line up for lattes. In some nonchain coffee shops, Mom and Pop
don't pay too well, which may account for the help's attitude,
wretched taste in music, and massive display of nose rings and
eyebrow armor.
</P>
<P>
   Crocodile tears have lubricated the history of American
innovation. When Howard Johnson franchised his original restaurant
in Wollaston, Mass., some complained about its principal virtue of
consistency, but HoJo standards helped halt the spread of ptomaine
by independent greasy-spoon diners. When Kemmons Wilson founded
Holiday Inns in 1951, similar snickers ensued, but he offered a
cleaner alternative to fleabag motels.
</P>
<P>
   Innovation succeeds, despite pseudo-environmental and
hypocritical complaints. The most honest mourner in the last days
of String Box books confessed that he'll miss browsing, examining a
book, then going home and ordering it on the Internet: ``Hey, it's
30 percent off and no 8.5 percent sales tax.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, during the first Earth Day ceremonies, ``Pogo,'' the
creation of the late cartoonist Walt Kelly, amended the dispatch
Oliver Hazard Perry sent from the US brig Niagara in 1813. Having
conquered a larger British fleet during the War of 1812, Perry told
General William Henry Harrison, summering by the Sandusky River,
``We have met the enemy, and they are ours.''
</P>
<P>
   In today's global economy, consumerism answers its own
complaints. As Pogo said, ``We have met the enemy and he is us.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Martin F. Nolan's column appears regularly in the Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
