<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SUCCESS STORY AT FENWAY HIGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Melissa Rivera was the first student to hand in her senior
humanities portfolio last Friday at Fenway High School. This was
something, considering her two-page introduction. She wrote: ``I
dreaded having to do this assignment. I have never written a 7-10
page paper before and I did not think that I could do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Her topic was Bosnia. She wrote a 7 1/2-page research paper, a
three-page opinion paper, and an extensive bibliography that
included The Wall Street Journal, The Washington Post, National
Public Radio, The Boston Globe, and The Nation.
</P>
<P>
   She also had three pages of fiction, based on her research. She
chose to write about a child whose family was hunted down by
Croatian soldiers. Her mother was beaten to death. Her father was
executed. She fled to a hole in the wall of the building her father
was shot in. She stayed there for two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fear ran through my body every time I heard the smallest
noise,'' Rivera wrote. ``I left the hole twice to get some food
from my dad's bag. He still lay there . . . After two weeks passed,
I had run out of food . . . one night . . . I heard voices coming
up the stairs. As they got closer I knew that they were Croatian
soldiers by the heavy accents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I returned back into the hole and closed my eyes. I had been
catching a cold so I was sneezing and my nose was running. They
came into the room that I was in. I had no idea what they were
doing there, but I knew that I had to be silent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I sneezed, which got their attention. I heard footsteps
getting closer and closer to the hole, and right then the Bosnian
soldiers entered the room and started shooting the Croatian
soldiers. I began to scream and I didn't stop until a Bosnian
soldier pulled me out of the hole. One of them dropped their hat as
they saw me. I knew the face, but I was afraid, so I couldn't put a
name on it. After about 30 seconds I realized that it was my cousin
Imir.''
</P>
<P>
   Rivera knows there is editing ahead. Her teacher, Eileen
Shakespear, said her 45 humanities students will have to rewrite
their portfolio pieces several times if they want to pass. That did
not take the glow off Rivera's face. She said, ``This is the
hardest thing I've ever done,'' but once the portfolio was in, she
hardly seemed to be in a rush to leave. A few minutes later, she
was down in school office, helping a secretary fold fliers.
</P>
<P>
   This did not escape the eyes of Fenway High Director Larry
Myatt. ``She's one of those kids who we've been able to scrape away
at the anger. She's not an angry kid anymore. Now she's got all of
her dreams in front of her.''
</P>
<P>
   Rivera, 19, is on the honor roll at Fenway, the 250-student
pilot school. She is thinking about going to Suffolk, Brandeis,
Northeastern, Florida State, or Lesley College. This is a long way
from her early adolescence. She was held back twice in middle
school for poor grades. She said she was wrong not to take school
seriously, but she also felt lost in the chaos of the overwhelmed
Boston public middle schools she attended.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were no relationships between teachers and students,''
Rivera said. ``They just shoved worksheets at you, you turned them
back in, and that was the last you'd ever see of the assignment.
There was no critique, no feedback, it was like once the assignment
was over, it never existed. Spelling tests were a joke. They'd give
you these words, but no one ever discussed the context of why the
words were important, and no one ever used the words again once the
test was over.''
</P>
<P>
   Rivera said that even when she started doing better in school,
she still remained invisible to her teachers. She remembers very
little contact between teachers and her mother. She said that when
she finally graduated from middle school, a teacher walked up to
her after the ceremony, shook her hand, and said,
``Congratulations. We didn't think you'd make it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe he was trying to be funny, or maybe he was trying to
make me feel like I accomplished something, but it still hurt,''
Rivera said. ``I know I was 15 at the time, and that's old for
middle school, but it still sent me a message that they never took
me seriously even when I tried harder.''
</P>
<P>
   At Fenway, where intimacy is a trademark, Rivera was taken
seriously to the breaking point. ``At first, I couldn't get a B in
math for anything,'' she said. ``I had an assignment on patterns
that I was buggin' out so much I was almost crying.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there is no running away here. You can't hide in school
because the teachers are always on you. You can't hide at home
because the teachers will call your parents. This school isn't
rich, but everyone here cares. We have an open campus and if you
wanted to, you could just walk out. But because of the
encouragement, you don't want to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   When Rivera graduates, she could apply her short story to her
own life. She once had been a child who could have rotted away in a
hole in the wall of her public school. She is not a child who
likely would have improved enough by 10th grade to pass the MCAS.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily for her, she was pulled out by an army that cared enough
_ and had enough energy _ not to let her hide anymore.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
