<SLUG> BC-TV-GEOGRAPHIC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GEOGRAPHIC' LOOKS WAY BACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VICKI CROKE   AND DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We've read and watched enough of such compilations to know that
no ``best of'' list covering the past century can be created
without causing controversy _ every inclusion and exclusion is open
to question. Well, how about raising the stakes _ taking a look at
the world from the beginning of time to the distant future? And let
me correct that: not just the world, but the solar system, too.
</P>
<P>
   It would seem impossible, but this is National Geographic. And
it does well with big concepts. ``Adventures in Time: The National
Geographic Millennium Special,'' was so dazzling, you didn't about
your particular agenda, your own definitive list.
</P>
<P>
   Via stunning cinematography, hoisted out of the incredible vault
of documentary footage, we visit ancient tombs in Egypt; watch a
gruesomely determined band of chimpanzees hunt and kill a colobus
monkey; learn about an MIT robot that can ``learn''; and watch a
conjured-up futuristic swim team of young people who have been
cleansed of any genetic defect.
</P>
<P>
   We travel underwater and into space; we puzzle out the primitive
and progressive; we can celebrate the beauty of the planet and get
the creeps from scientific predictions of cataclysmic tornadoes,
earthquakes, monsoons, and even ``Doomsday asteroids'' that could
``strike at any time.''
</P>
<P>
   Solid and scintillating, ``Adventures in Time,'' narrated by
John Lithgow, and produced by the always impressive Nicholas Stein,
gets two opposable thumbs up.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Pops show draws a record crowd &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Holiday at Pops,'' featuring Keith Lockhart and the Boston
Pops Orchestra and a reading of `` 'Twas the Night Before
Christmas'' by Conan O'Brien, drew an audience of 1.5 million
households Saturday on the A&AMP;E Network. It was the largest audience
the annual concert has drawn in the seven years it has aired on the
cable channel. . . . The crackling debate Sunday on NBC's ``Meet
the Press'' between Democratic presidential candidates Al Gore and
Bill Bradley _ arguably the highlight of the campaign season thus
far _ drew 4.71 million viewers. That was 2 million more than CBS's
``Face the Nation'' and ABC's ``This Week,'' further establishing
the dominance of ``Meet the Press'' as the 2000 campaign gears up.
. . . Another day, another example of convergence: ABC announced
Tuesday that its Web site abcnews.com will be part of ``a daily
synchronized Internet-television experience'' with ``World News
Now,'' the network's overnight news program.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Controversial `SNL' sketch to repeat
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After considerable waffling on the status of a ``Saturday Night
Live'' skit titled ``And So This Is Hanukkah,'' NBC has announced
that the sketch, which drew complaints after its initial broadcast,
will indeed be included in the series's future rerun rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have reviewed the viewer response to the SNL sketch and
have decided that it will air again unedited,'' the network said in
a statement. ``Today's environment makes our judgment calls in
these situations increasingly difficult because we must find a
balance between being politically correct and being funny in a
nonhurtful way.''
</P>
<P>
   That didn't satisfy Abraham Foxman, national director of the
Anti-Defamation League of B'nai B'rith.
</P>
<P>
   ``It almost sounds like a poll that they never took,'' he said
Tuesday. ``Most of the people who were upset called us.''
</P>
<P>
   The sketch, which aired Dec. 4, featured impersonators of pop
stars Britney Spears, Celine Dion, and Mariah Carey in a mock
network promo explaining why they were appearing on an imaginary
Hanukkah TV special.
</P>
<P>
   The Spears character, portrayed by actress Christina Ricci, says
that Christians have forgiven Jews for ``having killed our Lord.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
