<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6470 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-GATSBY-BOS &LR;      12-22 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-GATSBY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GATSBY' A NEW AMERICAN CLASSIC BORN OF ANOTHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Out of one national classic, F. Scott Fitzgerald's
``The Great Gatsby,'' John Harbison has fashioned another, one of
the best operas composed by an American to date. The Metropolitan
Opera's premiere of ``Gatsby'' Monday night, the composer's 61st
birthday, was the culmination of a dream of decades. Obstacles
stood in the way, but in hindsight, they were fortunate ones,
because when he finally came to ``Gatsby,'' Harbison was ready.
</P>
<P>
   The composer wrote his own effective libretto, most of it
incorporating Fitzgerald's language; in creating parallels,
interconnections, deep structure, Harbison has set it up for music.
There are two intimate lounge scenes, two scenes in Wilson's garage
under the unseeing billboard eyes of Dr. T. J. Eckleburg, two big
contrasting party scenes. The text necessarily gives the characters
some of what Fitzgerald supplies only by indirection, an inner
life; the music takes us the rest of the way. The printed libretto
left one wondering how Harbison would cope with the rest of the
story once Gatsby is dead and Daisy fled; his response was to
supply some of the greatest music in any American opera,
particularly Nick's aria about inner journeys, with an
accompaniment that clicks along like wheels over metal track and
the distant sound of a train whistle. All of these shallow,
self-absorbed people, not just Gatsby, are tormented by unfulfilled
yearnings; all of them face a flickering green light at the end of
the pier that represents a dream already over, even though they
don't know it.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to think of another American opera composed with a
comparable degree of musical sophistication and sheer virtuoso
compositional chops. Many kinds of music interweave in ``Gatsby.''
Harbison takes a Haydnesque delight in musical tone-painting: There
is weather in his music, and automobiles, radios and ringing
telephones _ and that train. There is period music in a series of
'20s-style dance tunes and pop songs (with lyrics by Murray
Horwitz) _ these songs sound authentic, but only one of them
suggests anything we already know (although Kurt Weill's ``Speak
low'' hovers behind an offstage tune). The pop music defines the
character's milieu and social status (Myrtle, the wife of the
garage mechanic, sings the blues). The orchestration is colorful,
various, and luminous.
</P>
<P>
   The dialogue bounces off the rhythms, tricky and unstable when
unmoored from the songs; strong feelings and unfulfilled longings
deconstruct the stable intervals and harmonies of the songs. There
are arias (Gatsby has two of them, the second, perhaps, not adding
anything to the first), and a glorious love duet for Gatsby and
Daisy, Some the ensembles rival the great Mozart finales or the end
of Act 2 of ``Die Meistersinger'' in complexity of simultaneous
events. Above all, Harbison is flexible. The music moves easily
from scene-painting to exposition to dialogue, arioso, ensemble,
and back again. There is immediate appeal in the score but also a
network of internal reference so intricate it will take years of
repeated hearings to understand. The music also leads to outside
points of reference : Daisy and Jordan sing of boredom in the
opening scene, and it is like the ``Benares Song'' from
``Mahagonny,'' yet also like the glistening duet of the sisters at
a comparable moment in the opening act of Strauss's ``Arabella'' _
ennui lifted to the level of ecstasy. Allusive as the music
sometimes is, the language is by now entirely Harbison's own _ as
is the compassionate generosity of feeling the language expresses.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Yeargan's sets provided a somewhat flimsy background,
perhaps intentionally; Jane Greenwood's costumes were fabulous _
and Gatsby's pink suit matched Duane Schuler's sunset lighting.
Mark Lamos's direction of the intimate scenes were at times
effective, but he distanced some of them behind scrims. The party
scenes were hideously cluttered and disastrously unfocused; they
offered a very peculiar notion of what a licentious party is like.
Some performers were grossly misdirected, including the
theatrically charismatic Lorraine Hunt Lieberson, who played Myrtle
as a porn-flick slut _ the point about Myrtle is that she, like
Gatsby, aspires to a false standard of gentility, while unknowingly
representing a higher one. But Lieberson's gorgeous singing of
Myrtle's blues, with pinpoint control of colors and dynamics, was
the vocal highlight of the evening.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Hadley, a capable, likable, and uncharismatic tenor found
the role of his career in Gatsby; he sang wonderfully and even his
brilliantined posing fed into a plausible and affecting
characterization. Dawn Upshaw looked marvelous, moved deliciously,
and found herself stretched by some of Daisy's music (this opera,
like Mozart's, does belong in a smaller theater). Susan Graham and
Mark Baker were powerhouses as Jordan Baker and Tom Buchanan.
Dwayne Croft looked a little old for Nick, but he caught the wonder
of that great last aria, and ended the opera on a high G that made
the past resound into an infinite future. All the smaller roles are
worthwhile and the performers _ Richard Paul Fink, Matthew
Polenzani, William Powers, Frederick Burchinal, and Leroy Lehr _
made the most of them.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; James Levine led a snappy performance that sounded confident
and convinced of the work's merits.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered sounds of discontent appeared at the end of the first
act but a substantial welcome for cast and opera at the end turned
into a standing ovation when Levine pulled Harbison on. After the
applause was over, some additional music stole out into the
auditorium from behind the gold curtain; some very fancy voices
were singing ``Happy Birthday, Dear John.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
