<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIRED TO THE FUTURE; CHEETAH CHIC; THEY CALL HIM PRINCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH CARNEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The end of 1999 is producing a lot of miserable magazine covers
(see this week's People crown Julia Roberts the year's most
intriguing person). But in the midst of all the year and decade and
century rehashing, Wired (January) offers a refreshing antidote in
an issue devoted to the future.
</P>
<P>
   Between articles on the race to bring space travel to the masses
by ``do-it-yourself astropreneurs'' and the prospects for
drastically extending the human life span is an amusing,
stream-of-conscious ``conversation'' among a variety of thinkers
about life in the future. In keeping with Wired's propensity for
funky, sometimes unreadable, layouts, the piece packs together
quotes in no apparent order. The collection zigzags through topics
ranging from fashion to technology to the various luminaries'
wishlists. The piece is both whimsical and thought provoking.
</P>
<P>
   From Tim Berners-Lee (inventor of the World Wide Web and author
of ``Weaving the Web'') : ``We won't be using the word Internet in
2020, just as today we don't say, `I saw an interesting article on
a piece of paper today.' People will simply talk about the
information.'' Super chef Julia Child offers suggestions for
culinary innovations: ``How about fresh peas that are quicker to
shell _ you'd just pull one end of it and all the peas would pop
out! You could also have a suction gadget that would suck out the
fat and not the juice in a frying pan very quickly. (That would
probably have to be electronic, don't you think?).'' And from the
DJ Moby: ``The future smells like the Washington, D.C., subway
system.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While Wired aggressively woos the cutting-edge crowd, a stealth
hip magazine for 20-somethings is (brace yourself) National
Geographic. Why not? Visually rich, apolitical, slightly retro, the
magazine is perfect plane reading for young professionals who want
to daydream about exotic places they don't have time to visit. The
December cover features a story about cheetahs, the fastest animals
on land.
</P>
<P>
   If you get past the arresting photos, writer Richard Conniff
offers a fascinating primer on the only big cats who don't attack
humans and _ who knew? _ don't roar. (They sometimes growl, but
with each other they chirp like birds.) Though so beautiful that
Conniff finds it difficult to write about them (``My inclination
has always been to write about less popular animals on Earth,'' he
writes), he tells us that many ranchers in their African habitat
consider them vermin, which is one reason they are disappearing
from the landscape. One owner of a trophy hunting ranch in Namibia
who Conniff interviews killed 17 cheetahs last year and still lost
$24,000 worth of prize game to the cats. ``Oh!,'' the rancher is
quoted as saying. ``my heart pumps blood. One day you feel that the
cheetah also has a right to stay here. But you get angry, and the
moment you see a cheetah, you start shooting. I think you would
feel the same.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hip-hop mogul Puff Daddy's new magazine ``Notorious'' hasn't
been around long enough to probe its archive for end-of-the-year
wrap-ups, but that doesn't stop it from making a stab in its
``millennium issue.'' In the centerpiece story ``The Notorious 25''
the mag calls on today's celebrities to comment on the century's
icons: Lil Kim on Madonna, Robert F. Kennedy Jr. on Rachel Carson,
publisher Puff Daddy on Motown records founder Berry Gordy. While
some of the comments are interesting (of Muhammad Ali, Evander
Holyfield says: ``I didn't think much of Ali's mouth when I was
young, as I was brought up quite different. My family didn't follow
boxing.''), many of the pairings come off as random.
</P>
<P>
   The better feature is the cover story on the real poster boy for
1999, the Artist Formerly Known as Prince. With a new album (Rave
Un2 The Joy Fantastic) out under a new label (Arista), the artist
has been opening up more to the press. Still, the profile by
Dimitri Ehrlich serves up some delicious details from a visit to
his Minneapolis recording studio Paisley Park.
</P>
<P>
   To start, the artist who used to be called His Royal Badness has
changed his behavior since becoming friends with the former bassist
for Sly and the Family Stone, Larry Graham, a devout Christian.
Under Graham's influence, the artist has given up cursing and bans
it from Paisley Park. He also doesn't allow employees to smoke,
drink, or bring meat or fish into the building. He goes out at
night with Graham unaccompanied by bodyguards and even pumps his
own gas. At Paisley Park, he keeps a cage of white doves that make
``an eerie rooster-like crowing.'' His staff still calls him
Prince.
</P>
<P>
   The artist remains inscrutable, speaking of Prince as though he
were another person. He insists that while he released the album,
it was produced by Prince, whom he refers to in the third person.
``Our relationship is not contentious. It's an agreement. Prince
has the final say. He's the producer. And basically he came in and
took a look at that old Linn drum machine we used on our early
hits, and he said This is how we rolled it in '92, and this is how
we rollin' in 99. And that was it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
