<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-SUNDAY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ANY GIVEN SUNDAY' WINS THE GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
ANY GIVEN SUNDAY 
Directed by: Oliver Stone 
Screenplay by: Stone, John Logan 
Starring: Al Pacino, Cameron Diaz, Dennis Quaid, James Woods, Jamie
Foxx, LL Cool J, Matthew Modine, Charlton Heston,
Ann-Margret,  Aaron Eckhart, Eckhardt, John C. McGinley, Jim Brown,
Lawrence Taylor 
Running time: 161 minutes 
Rated: R (strong language and some nudity and /sexuality) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You practically need a face mask and helmet to get through
Oliver Stone's new football movie, ``Any Given Sunday.'' It keeps
coming at you, keeps hammering you, and has absolutely no business
being as entertaining as it is. If Stone ever gets tired of making
movies, his brilliant machine-gun editing alone would earn him top
dollar on a sports network. The film goes through the motions of
goofing on the things that are wrong with the game, but it's too
hooked on its own testosterone, to say nothing of football's, not
to seem like one of those long, hard-fought games in the mud that
somehow winds up in the win column.
</P>
<P>
   On any given Sunday, any pro football team can beat any other
pro football team. That tidbit of sports gospel supplies the film's
title, and it is driving Vince Lombardi wannabe Al Pacino nuts. Up
and down the sidelines he prowls, venting, venting, venting, when
he isn't looking tight-lipped and grim. Lately, he's been looking
tight-lipped and grim a lot because his Miami team has been losing
too many games. His star quarterback is ailing, the owner is
talking about selling the franchise or moving it to LA if she can
get a stadium deal, and the third-string hot dog who's so tensed up
that he begins each game by throwing up suddenly starts clicking
and referring to Pacino's Tony D'Amato as Coach Stone Age.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense he is, but the film takes the view that he isn't
necessarily wrong. He's old school, uncomfortable with the
high-pressure trimmings that have attached themselves to the big
business football has become. The hits are pretty jolting, but the
ones on the field don't reverberate as hard as the hits in the
game's new high-stakes corporate warfare. Tough as the slabs of
muscle who launch themselves at each other every Sunday may be,
they're not as tough as Cameron Diaz's team owner trying to prove
to her dead father that she can be as tough as the son he never
had. She scares the league president (a nice piece of
tongue-in-cheek casting: Charlton Heston as the Moses of pro
football).
</P>
<P>
   She's the closest the film comes to freshness and surprise.
Until she's channeled into sentimentality, it's a nice stretch for
her. The coach isn't afraid of her. He's known her since she was a
little girl and he's friends with her mother _ a rueful but stylish
former alcoholic played with warmth and economy by Ann-Margret. But
his long antennae tell him that good things are not coming. He's
not into image-mongering, he's not glib, and he doesn't want to be
bothered about turning into a marketing-oriented barracuda. Stone
(obviously enjoying himself in a cameo as a radio announcer)
presumably couldn't clear rights with the NFL, so he uses
fictitious names for his teams and league. The Miami Dolphins
become the Miami Sharks, and so on.
</P>
<P>
   The stage was set for some smart, scathing skewering of the
celebrity and sports and marketing culture we have become. Stone
begins the job but, quickly seduced by the macho aspects of the
game and this particular gang of warriors, he veers into a
celebration of chest-pounding. ``Any Given Sunday'' is far too
long, but its rambunctiousness is engaging, propelled as it is by
Stone's virtuosic quick-cutting, and the high jinks of Dennis
Quaid's veteran player, Jamie Foxx's upstart, LL Cool J's
far-from-unassertive running back, Jim Brown's rocklike defensive
coordinator, and real-life grid great Lawrence Taylor as a
concussion-prone star linebacker. Most of the high-priced grunts on
the field are good guys. Most of the guys who labor off the field
are heavies, from James Woods's dope-'em-up-and-let-'em-play team
orthopedist to John C. McGinley's self-important, flame-fanning
media snake.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not the ideal audience for ``Any Given Sunday.'' To me, the
most interesting thing about football is the shape of the ball.
That being said, and the overextended parts of ``Any Given Sunday''
being acknowledged, I have to admit to getting caught up in its
nonsense, including the corny climactic game. There's no shortage
of color and vigor in this pumped-up movie. Most of the time, it's
jock heaven. But I do wish it hadn't allowed itself to be so easily
diverted from its criticism of the game and the values that drive
it, and veer off instead into macho backslapping. In that respect,
``Any Given Sunday'' resembles the games that got away from coach
D'Amato and his players.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
