<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-MOTHER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRONG WOMEN ABOUND IN `ALL ABOUT MY MOTHER' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
ALL ABOUT MY MOTHER 
Directed and written by: Pedro Almodovar 
Starring: Cecilia Roth, Marisa Paredes, Candela Pena, Antonia San
Juan, Penelope Cruz, Rosa Maria Sarda, Fernando Fernan Gomez, Toni
Canto, Eloy Azorin 
Running time: 101 minutes (in Spanish with English subtitles) 
Rated: R (sexuality, including strong sexual dialogue, strong
language, and some drug content) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although sexual boundaries blur in Pedro Almovodar's ``All About
My Mother,'' there's never any doubt that he admires women wildly.
In his films, they're the ones who are left standing at the end,
enduring, keeping life _ such as it is _ going. They may live on
the verge of nervous breakdowns, but they cope, they deal, they
prop up the men in their lives. ``All About My Mother'' spirals
into delirium, but its source in Almodovar's regard for his own
mother and her strengths in their machista region of La Mancha is
beyond doubt. He dedicates the film to actresses who have played
actresses _ Bette Davis, Gena Rowlands, Romy Schneider. It's not
literally about his mother. But clearly her hardy, resourceful
spirit permeates the terrific women's ensemble that makes this
screwball soap opera hum.
</P>
<P>
   It's full of Almodovar's trademark saturated colors and farcical
rambunctiousness. But it's also got a tragic sense, and it
reinforces the impression that Almodovar is one of the relatively
rare filmmakers who is finding ways to sustain his stylistic
vitality while maturing from sexual iconoclast to sexual humanist.
``All About My Mother'' celebrates nurturing, maternal energies, as
expressed through a rich female lineup. At its center is Cecilia
Roth as a single mother named Manuela, who fled Barcelona for
Madrid when she found she was pregnant by a wayward lout. On the
night she promised to reveal all to her now-grown son, he has an
accident after chasing the star of a stage performance of ``A
Streetcar Named Desire.''
</P>
<P>
   Reversing her flight of 18 years earlier, Manuela takes a train
from Madrid to Barcelona to confront the boy's father. Instead,
some unruly realities start confronting her. In no time, she meets
up with an old transsexual pal (Antonia San Juan's agreeable
streetwalking pro named La Agrado), the high-strung veteran actress
playing Blanche in ``Streetcar'' (Marisa Paredes's Huma Rojo), the
actress playing Stella (Candela Pena's Nina, who is also the star's
lover), and a young nun (Penelope Cruz's Hermana Rosa) who has been
rather too charitable. The Bette Davis-like Huma Roja needs an
assistant. The nun needs mothering from someone other than her
biological mother. Manuela finds herself cast in both roles.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of energy is spent relying on the kindness of strangers,
and the film is both bleeding and goofy as Almodovar deftly plays
the one quality against the other. From the start, Almodovar has
been sympathetic to society's outsiders, especially transvestites,
never more so than here. As the film teeters giddily between ``All
About Eve'' and ``How to Marry a Millionaire,'' it keeps dancing a
few steps ahead of us. Not until close to the end do we sense a
pattern emerging. The payoff that arrives when the laughs depart is
a generous one. Nothing is resolved at the expense of the women;
never does Almodovar set them against one another. In Almodovar's
films, sex makes the world go round. But when its uproar subsides,
``All About My Mother'' emits an endearing afterglow. It's a tender
genuflection to the women's energies that keep that spinning world
from keeling over.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-22-99 1348EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991222.0139 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6481 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-SWEET-BOS &LR;      12-22 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-SWEET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SWEET AND LOWDOWN' IS APPEALING, LIGHTWEIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
SWEET AND LOWDOWN 
Written and directed by: Woody Allen 
Starring: Samantha Morton, Sean Penn, Uma Thurman, Anthony
LaPaglia, Brian Markinson, Gretchen Mol, James Urbaniak, John
Waters 
Running time: 95 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 (sexual content and some substance abuse) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Woody Allen's ``Sweet and Lowdown'' is a string of riffs on the
theme _ not exactly new to his recent movies _ that living with a
genius who lives for his art is not an emotionally rewarding
proposition. Unlike Allen's last movie, ``Celebrity,'' which was
sunk by Kenneth Branagh's fatally distracting Allen impersonation,
this film's Allen surrogate is a talented jazz guitarist played by
Sean Penn as a sort of cross between ``Pal Joey'' and Kirk
Douglas's brash musician in ``Young Man With a Horn.'' Spiritually,
the film's source is Federico Fellini's ``La Strada,'' with Penn
the new version of Anthony Quinn's weak strongman, Zampano, and
Samantha Morton filling the screen as the pure-hearted mute waif
played by Giulietta Masina.
</P>
<P>
   Time and again, the film makes its point. Although Morton's
mousy, devoted Hattie can't speak, other characters appear at
regular intervals to say things like, ``I don't need a genius to
have a good time'' or ``No genius is worth too much heartache.''
Penn's Emmet Ray, who frets over being a smaller talent than Django
Reinhardt the way Allen has fretted at coming up short when
measured against Ingmar Bergman, is believably blissed-out when
he's strumming his guitar and the music is coming out the way he
hears it in his head. But while he Emmet can handle a guitar, he
can't handle anything else, especially intimacy. He talks tough,
but fools nobody. This is a frightened, damaged guy who grew up
abused in Chicago and has, emotionally speaking, been on the run
ever since.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, he isn't much fun. He drives a snazzy roadster,
but his idea of a good time on a date is to take a girl to a
garbage dump to watch him shoot rats with a .45. Partly because
he's too selfish to admit the needs of another person, partly
because he's spooked by Hattie's emotional courage and devotion, he
feels like pushing her away to preserve the safety of his
isolation. It doesn't help that when she follows him to Hollywood
for some career-furthering, it's she who stumbles into a movie
career and not Emmet. He's the kind of guy who has flings, then
flees. The question is whether he'll be able to break the pattern
and not wind up like Zampano did, alone on the beach.
</P>
<P>
   That we care as much as we do derives from the details about
Penn, as fine an actor as we have. He easily projects Emmet's cocky
side, but also covers, with a series of hesitations and darting
beady-eyed glances, the guy's fears and emotional limits. Frankly,
it's Allen who seems to fall short here because he gives us only
the surface of Emmet, never the kind of probing that would have
done more with Emmet's self-loathing. Better he should have taken
less inspiration from Zampano and more from Laurence Olivier's
seedy Archie Rice in ``The Entertainer.'' And while Morton is more
than capable of expressing Hattie's pain, Allen mutes it. The film
needs less dress-up, more X-ray.
</P>
<P>
   It's got more than a few of Allen's bright one-liners. His
well-documented love of the period means that the musical numbers
are conjured up with great gusto and affection. Not just in the
jazz, but in the film references as well. When he meets a society
woman, dipping her toe into the deliciously disreputable world of
jazz, Emmet cracks as snappily as any '30s wise guy to the world at
large: ``Take yer hat off _ she grew up with a butler.'' Allen, who
doesn't appear as a character in the movie, turns up as one of its
mock-documentary information-supplying talking heads, gently
spoofing ``Reds.'' He's tongue-in-cheek funny, bringing throwaway
humor even to such peripheral things as a passing reference to
Eddie Condon. As apologia go, ``Sweet and Lowdown'' is agreeable
eye candy and ear candy, but it's too slight to reach as deep as it
thinks it wants to reach.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-22-99 1349EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991222.0140 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6482 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MAN-MOON-BOS &LR;      12-22 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAN-MOON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANDY KAUFMAN IS MISSING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
MAN ON THE MOON 
Directed by: Milos Forman 
Screenplay by: Scott Alexander &AMP; Larry Karaszewski 
Starring: Jim Carrey, Danny DeVito, Courtney Love, Paul Giamatti 
Running time: 118 minutes 
Rated: R (language and brief sexuality/nudity) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We live in a culture of clamor. Pols, bail bondsmen, all the way
up the evolutionary ladder, everybody blasts us with the same
message: comin'-at-ya-live-baby-and-have-I-got-needs-lemme-tell-ya!
Obnoxious neurotics are everywhere, slapping a death grip on your
eyeballs in their need for attention, but nowhere are they rewarded
as handsomely as in journalism and comedy. Even so, it's hard to
posthumously crown Andy Kaufman as the king of visionary comic
geniuses, even if the major artistic business of the century has
been the mainstreaming of alienation and Kaufman was nothing if not
alienated.
</P>
<P>
   Still, between them, Jim Carrey and Milos Forman almost bring it
off in their Kaufman biopic, ``Man on the Moon.'' As he more than
amply demonstrated in ``The Truman Show'' and ``The Cable Guy,''
Carrey has been aching to break out of the comic box. ``Man on the
Moon'' is a sideways move that rides his extraordinary capacity for
mimicry and movement. Nobody can scissor his lanky body as Carrey
can. Yet his regeneration of Kaufman depends mostly on his ability
to project stiffness, to create the impression of a man as
profoundly uncomfortable in his own body as he was on ``Saturday
Night Live.''
</P>
<P>
   There's also the matter of Kaufman's fixed, manic stare. It goes
to the heart of the late comic's way of demanding our attention by
shining a spotlight on himself, then upending our expectations by
refusing to dispense the usual kinds of comedy. You've got to love
envelope-pushing, especially in the so-called arts, which are
supposed to be about envelope-pushing, about the deepening of
awareness, but usually are only about playing it safe. That Kaufman
was an original who refused to be pigeonholed made you want to
cheer. But the glum fact is that most of his comedy was, for me at
least, a turn-off.
</P>
<P>
   Who didn't like him as Latka in ``Taxi''? Using the sweet
hangdog mode, he goofed on comedians' constant bid for our
approval. But much of the rest of the time, he threw in our faces
the fundamentally aggressive nature of comedy, the fact that it's
anger with a smile. Not for nothing did so many of the classic
comics come offstage, high after a turn that had gone well, saying,
``I killed 'em!'' Long before he died of cancer at 35 in 1984,
Kaufman had pretty much killed his own career. The surreal
absurdity of his best bits was swamped by his insistence on shoving
the audience's expectations back in its own face _ an imperative
that went over the ropes when he wrestled women.
</P>
<P>
   The problem was that while he was frequently imaginative and
original and a pioneer in conceptual performance art, he just
wasn't that funny. What you felt from him a lot of the time was
old-fashioned performer's desperation. What you get from Carrey is
a superb impersonation of Kaufman. But in the symbiotic way of
films, you also are just as aware that you are watching Jim Carrey.
Thus, Kaufman's loose-cannon danger is offset by Carrey's essential
sweetness. But he isn't playing a character, he's playing an icon.
</P>
<P>
   The Kaufman Carrey gives us is easier to take than the real
thing, but less interesting. Yet the big problem with ``Man on the
Moon'' is that it settles for being a thing of surfaces. In their
scripts for ``Ed Wood'' and ``The People vs. Larry Flynt,'' Scott
Alexander and Larry Karaszewski had more success at indicating who
the person was beneath the persona. Here, it's a case of
what-you-see-is-what-you-get, and it isn't enough. The film apes
Kaufman's gambit, which was to hide an essentially shy self behind
an outrageous persona and a need to perform, even when he stops
being Mr. Nice Guy and delights in becoming his really aggressive
alter ego, Tony Clifton, the sleazy Vegas lounge type in perpetual
attack mode.
</P>
<P>
   What was he protecting? The film never probes this question
deeply. ``Man on the Moon'' asks you to accept it as hip
hagiography and not ask too many questions. Fans of Kaufman will
probably like it more than other moviegoers. The film seems
destined to convert the converted, and few others, including Carrey
fans. He doesn't really inhabit Kaufman. Rather, Carrey seems to
drape Kaufman's bizarre brand of humor over his own already
hyperkinetic persona. He's never boring. Give him that.
</P>
<P>
   Courtney Love, who performed the role of the woman in Larry
Flynt's life for Forman, returns in another strong turn as the
woman in Kaufman's. Paul Giamatti is another plus as Bob Zmuda,
Kaufman's friend and collaborator, especially in the Tony Clifton
bits. But for all the keen-edged professionalism on parade in ``Man
on the Moon,'' it remains a frustratingly opaque study. There's
something missing, namely Kaufman. Still, there's something to be
said for the prospect of a Forman fringe-figure three-pack in video
stores, flaunting his own personal powder-keg trio _ that wacky
Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart, pornmeister Flynt, and now Kaufman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-22-99 1350EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991222.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6486 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-22 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARRIAGE LITE JUST WON'T CUT IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN MCNAMARA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Emancipation Proclamation made people uncomfortable. So did
women's suffrage. To say nothing of the social unease prompted by
interfaith marriages and school desegregation.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the governor of Vermont would deny same-sex couples the
right to marry for no more substantive reason than because he says
it ``makes me uncomfortable, the same as anybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Forget, for a moment, that ``anybody else'' is not everybody
else. When did we begin apportioning civil rights in this country
on the basis of the citizenry's comfort level?
</P>
<P>
   The Vermont Supreme Court dropped the prospect of gay marriages
into the laps of the governor and state lawmakers this week with
its decision that homosexual couples are entitled to the same
benefits and protections as married couples. The high court left it
to legislators to design the remedy to current discriminatory
practices in such commonplace matters as insurance, medical
decisions, hospital visitation, and property division in the event
of separation.
</P>
<P>
   Governor Howard Dean says gay marriage is out of the question
but a parallel ``domestic partnership'' law might work. Sort of
marriage lite, I guess.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I am missing something, but isn't ``domestic partnership''
the definition of marriage? Why would lawmakers waste energy
creating a new civil institution when an existing one would fit the
bill nicely?
</P>
<P>
   The high court ruled that the denial of equal protection to
homosexual couples violated the Common Benefits Clause of the
Vermont Constitution, a provision beautiful in its simplicity and
clarity: ``That government is, or ought to be, instituted for the
common benefit, protection and security of the people, nation or
community, and not for the particular emolument or advantage of any
single person, family or set of persons, who are a part only of
that community.''
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging that the issue of same-sex marriage ``arouses
deeply felt religious, moral and political beliefs,'' the justices
were mum on every aspect but the legal one.
</P>
<P>
   The governor and legislative leaders should do likewise and
leave the moral wrestling to the clerics and to the conscience of
their constituents. Governor Dean and Vermont lawmakers are not
being asked to make a moral judgment about same-sex couplings, only
to remedy the discrimination to which homosexual couples are now
subjected.
</P>
<P>
   The obvious solution is to extend the right to marry to gay and
lesbian couples.
</P>
<P>
   Domestic partnership proposals are no more than a political
dodge, an unconscionable sop to bigots who will tolerate
homosexuality only if it can be segregated in some parallel
universe. But gay and lesbian people do not live in a parallel
universe. They live in this one.
</P>
<P>
   Why should our brothers, sisters, aunts, uncles, sons, and
daughters be relegated to faux marriages simply to appease those
who can live more easily with discrimination than they can with
discomfort?
</P>
<P>
   Why should gays and lesbians accept the second-class status
implicit in a ``separate but equal'' domestic partnership statute?
</P>
<P>
   The debate Vermont lawmakers promise to begin after the first of
the year should focus not on what religious leaders claim the Bible
commands, but on what the state's Supreme Court justices insist
that the Constitution mandates.
</P>
<P>
   No significant social change in this nation's history has been
accomplished without disrupting some deeply held beliefs. Blacks
were slaves because whites were superior. Wives were chattel
because women were weak-minded. Amending our laws in a continuing
effort to equalize the status of all Americans has not diminished
the nation; it has enhanced it.
</P>
<P>
   Americans have learned, with varying degrees of comfort, to live
with blacks and women who vote, with couples who celebrate
Christmas and Hanukkah, with schools that teach students of
different shades side by side.
</P>
<P>
   In its decision this week, the Vermont Supreme Court justices
noted they were duty-bound to consider the legal questions raised
by the two lesbian couples and two gay men who were the plaintiffs
in this case, without regard to their personal comfort. ``Our
constitutional responsibility to consider the legal merits of
issues properly before us provides no exception for the
controversial case,'' they wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The Vermont Supreme Court unlocked the door to equality for gay
and lesbian couples. Now, it is up to the governor and state
lawmakers to push it open wide.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Eileen McNamara's e-mail address is mcnamara(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
