<HEADER>
A6491 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e BC-IVOR-CORRECTED-GWYNET     12-22 1436
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-CORRECTED-GWYNETH-PALTROW-IN-THE-TALENTED-MR-RIPLEY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SF 
 GWYNETH PALTROW: TRYING TO FORGET ABOUT HER OSCAR 
</HEADLINE>
 (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
entertainment column) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 Includes black-and-white photos and color slides of Gwyneth Paltrow
with Matt Damon in a scene from ``The Talented Mr. Ripley.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Winning her first Oscar earlier this year _ for her
career-defining performance in ``Shakespeare in Love'' (1998) _ was
a dream come true for Gwyneth Paltrow.
 &HT;    But, the 27-year-old actress says, it was also something of a
nightmare.
 &HT;    As her latest film, ``The Talented Mr. Ripley,'' prepares for a
Christmas opening, Paltrow admits that she may have been too young,
or simply too new to acting and movie stardom, to cope with the
dark side of picking up the treasured best-actress statuette. She
might have been better served, she says, if she'd had more time to
develop sufficient armor to deflect the publicity onslaught that
Oscar brings in his wake.
 &HT;    Paltrow shows up for an interview at Beverly Hills' Four Seasons
hotel looking, well, thoroughly unlike Gwyneth Paltrow. I have to
look twice, actually, to make sure that it's really her.
 &HT;    Gone is the shoulder-length, golden-blonde hair that has
reminded so many of the young Grace Kelly. Instead her locks are
dark brown, colored for her role in ``Bounce,'' which she has
recently finished shooting with her on-again/off-again boyfriend,
Ben Affleck.
 &HT;    ``I think the director of `Bounce' was sick of the whole Blonde
Gwyneth person,'' she says. ``And so was I.''
 &HT;    Wearing virtually no makeup, Paltrow nevertheless looks elegant
in an ankle-length, black-leather skirt and matching top, set off
with dazzling diamond earrings which reportedly were a gift from
Affleck.
 &HT;    The timing of her Oscar was particularly unfortunate, Paltrow
says, because her life was finally beginning to settle down after
the tabloid furor over her breakup with fiance Brad Pitt. Then
along came Oscar, and the paparazzi went on red alert.
 &HT;    ``I became a prisoner in my house,'' she recalls, ``because
after a while I just didn't want to go out. One day I was driving
and the gas gauge on my car had broken, so I ran out of gas. There
are pictures of me walking down the street with a gas can, looking
for the nearest service station, and the paparazzi didn't have the
decency to give me a ride. They just wanted those demeaning
pictures.
 &HT;    ``I wanted to go hide somewhere,'' she concludes. ``I felt I
couldn't sustain all of the energy that comes with all that
attention.''
 &HT;    The whole thing was exacerbated by the fact that her acceptance
speech became fodder for late-night comedians. Not since Sally
Field's ``You like me, you really like me'' acceptance speech for
``Places in the Heart'' (l984) had so many had so much fun with so
little.
 &HT;    At the time Paltrow's father was ill, her grandfather was dying
_ he has since died, and she still can't mention his name without
tears _ and her brother was also having health problems. Not
surprisingly, the actress broke down in front of the world's
largest audience.
 &HT;    ``The nightmare about that evening was that I had one of the
most personal moments of my life in front of the whole world,'' she
says. ``I felt so terribly exposed. Of course I'd like to go back
and change some things, but that's impossible. It's there for
posterity.''
 &HT;    She reacted in the only way she knew how, by turning inward and
taking stock of her life and career.
 &HT;    ``It made me see the emptiness in everything I had achieved,''
Paltrow says. ``It's wonderful and I appreciate it, but nothing you
can buy, nothing you can do, achieve or win, no boy, no
relationship will help you retain contentedness.''
 &HT;    She plunged back into work _ a stage stint at the Williamstown
Theater Festival and several upcoming films _ determined, she says,
not to let the award affect the direction of her career.
 &HT;    ``I have been working so hard not to let it make any changes in
my life,'' the actress says. ``I still only accept roles if I want
to do them, as an artist, not because they are a potential
award-winning role.''
 &HT;    One of those roles is Marge Sherwood, the beautiful, wealthy
girlfriend of Dickie Greenleaf (Jude Law) in writer/director
Anthony Minghella's ``The Talented Mr. Ripley.''
 &HT;    ``I liked Marge, she was very sweet,'' Paltrow says. ``But I
didn't understand how deep she was and how layered it all was until
I got there and started doing the film. I thought she was lighter.
I didn't realize she was so deep and warm and complicated, which is
a testament to my stupidity.''
 &HT;    Based on a Patricia Highsmith novel _ one that Minghella made
Paltrow promise not to read _ and set in 1950s Italy, the movie is
the fascinating story of Tom Ripley (Matt Damon), who is asked by a
millionaire shipbuilder to persuade his playboy son Dickie to come
home. Ripley becomes so fascinated by the lavish lifestyle Dickie
and Marge enjoy that he goes to extraordinary and disturbing
lengths to become exactly like them.
 &HT;    The film is gorgeously shot in some of Italy's most glorious
locales, and Paltrow and Law are as golden a couple as anything F.
Scott Fitzgerald ever conjured up. Which isn't too surprising,
since Minghella says he wrote the screenplay with Paltrow in mind
for the role of Marge.
 &HT;    ``She was the first person I cast,'' he says in a separate
interview. ``The character of Marge in the film _ womanly,
trusting, compassionate, a rebel in her own way _ has as much to do
with Gwyneth herself as it has to do with Patricia Highsmith's
Marge.''
 &HT;    It's a dark tale, one which some critics have suggested will be
too much for mainstream American audiences. Predictably, Paltrow
disagrees.
 &HT;    ``I think it's a very different movie,'' she admits. ``It's an
epic, Hollywood movie that is totally subversive.
 &HT;    ``But I think to say it will alienate middle America is to
underestimate those people as a moviegoing audience,'' Paltrow
adds. ``They like to be challenged as much as anyone else. Our
movie is about a very lonely, desperate person who wants to be
loved and will do anything to get that love. That's a universal
trait, that people want to get out of their own lives and inhabit
someone else's.''
 &HT;    At times, it seems, even lovely, blonde Oscar-winners feel that
urge.
 &HT;    ``I never wished I had someone else's life,'' she says
thoughtfully. ``I never wanted to be someone else _ but there were
many times when I felt really uncomfortable in my own skin.
 &HT;    ``I may have had celebrity quite quickly,'' she adds, ``but I've
had to work so hard to get respect and recognition. It's a bit like
Nicole Kidman _ she is one of the greatest actresses of her
generation, but she was never mentioned without reference to her
being Tom Cruise's wife. Until very recently, I was always
somebody's daughter or somebody's girlfriend.''
 &HT;    Paltrow's discomfort with her own success, Minghella says, shows
in her lack of confidence in her own ability and her deference to
other performers, such as ``Ripley'' co-star Cate Blanchett.
 &HT;    ``Gwyneth really underestimates herself as an actress,''
Minghella says. ``She was so in awe of Cate Blanchett, which is
deliciously ironic because everyone else knows what an incredible
actress and what a natural actress she is.''
 c.1999 Ivor Davis  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter and columnist.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``The Talented Mr. Ripley,''
consult the official Website at www.talentedmrripley.com. And don't
forget to visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Hollywood Stars
and other features. &QL; 
