<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   TERRORISM _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton said Americans should
enjoy their holidays as usual but to report ``anything suspicious''
in light of official alerts about possible terrorism. A roundup of
developments. (Deans, Cox News Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ITALY-MILLENNIUM _ ROME _ About 30 million pilgrims are expected
to converge upon this delicate old city for the Roman Catholic Holy
Year 2000. The preparations have been sometimes comic, and other
times impressive. In Rome alone, there will be jubilee celebrations
begin to mark the start of the third Christian millennium; 26
million visitors are expected to the Eternal City during the year.
During the 54 weeks of official celebrations Pope John Paul will
bless pilgrims every day (through January 6, 2001). Developing.
(Freeman, Cox News Service). 30.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (i) International and (l) Lifestyle categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   DRUGS-LAUNDER _ ATLANTA _ For three years, agents with the U.S.
Drug Enforcement Administration and the Internal Revenue Service
masqueraded as a metro Atlanta stock brokerage whose brokers were
willing to wink at the law to launder millions in illicit drug
profits. On Wednesday, as federal agents froze bank accounts across
the globe, the DEA announced the results of the investigation _
which has led to the seizure of an estimated $26.2 million in U.S.
currency, 3,600 kilos of cocaine, and 340 bank accounts used by
Colombian drug traffickers and the money brokers who converted
their illegal earnings into legitimate profits. The investigation
has also led to the arrest of 40 people in nine U.S. cities and two
foreign countries. Another 20 remain at large, including five
Colombian money brokers whom federal investigators have identified
as men who also traffic in illegal drugs. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 43.
</P>
<P>
   WITH GRAPHIC: Drug map.
</P>
<P>
   ABERNATHY-FOLO _ ATLANTA _ Follow-up to Tuesday's verdict in the
trial of Georgia state Sen. Ralph David Abernathy III in which he
was found guilty on 18nof 28 counts including theft by taking,
false swearing, violating the oath of office, forgery and
influencing a witness. (Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   ETHICS-TEXAS _ AUSTIN _ Beginning next year, Texans should be
able to look on the Internet to get information about campaign
contributions in state elections. But critics of the law say the
information won't be very helpful because it won't contain
addresses of donors. ``Without addresses it is impossible to know
whether contributions to a candidate from a Bob Smith and a B.
Smith from downtown Houston are from the same person,''said Fred
Lewis, executive director of Campaigns for People, an Austin
nonprofit that pushes for open government. ``It becomes even more
difficult when there are B. Smiths, R. Smiths, R.E. Smiths, Bobby
Smiths, Bob Smiths and Robert Smiths giving to hundreds of
political action committees and candidates.'' But the law says
donors' addresses must be deleted from the cyberspace reports. Now,
the question is whether addresses can be included on computer
diskettes to be offered for sale. (Herman, Austin
American-Statesman). 22.
</P>
