<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Thursday, Dec. 23:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Jerusalem) _ Israeli Prime Minister Barak and
Palestinian leader Arafat make much progress in late-night meeting
in Ramallah at home of Arafat's No. 2, Abu Mazen. The latest land
dispute is finally resolved, and they agree on prisoner release for
Ramadan. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-ONLINE (Beijing) _ With the ambivalent blessing of the
government, locally produced Web sites and chat rooms have
proliferated rapidly here in the last two years, giving Chinese a
forum for public debate and discussion _ even a degree of dissent _
that was previously unavailable. By Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   (See also CHINA-ONLINE-BIZ, under FINANCIAL)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Moscow) _ Human Rights Watch reports ``war
crimes'' and ``summary executions'' of civilians by Russian troops
in a Chechen village. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   VENEZUELA-MUDSLIDES (Dateline to kum) _ Developments on the
flood and mudslide victims in Venezuela. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   SRILANKA-ELECT (Colombo) _ The Sri Lankan president is
re-elected with 51 percent of vote. At her swearing-in, she points
to her wounds from a Saturday bomb attack and says, ``These are the
wounds of sheer naked and unadulterated hatred of man for man.'' By
Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-NUKE (Tokyo) _ The death of a worker exposed to radiation
in a September nuclear accident prompts renewed calls for curbs on
atomic energy. By Howard W. French.
</P>
<P>
   MOZAMBIQUE-ELECT (Johannesburg, South Africa) _ The presidential
election results are announced; the incumbent Chissano wins. By
Rachel Swarns.
</P>
<P>
   LONDON-MAYOR (London) _ Giving Londoners the right to choose
their own chief executive would strike most people as a long
overdue exercise. But the campaign for the first directly elected
mayor of this city of 8 million people has caught British
politicians unaware and ill-prepared, with embarrassing
consequences all around. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NEWYEAR-SITTERS (Undated) _ On New Year's Eve, many of the
1,000-some couples attending the Memphis Junior League's charity
ball at the Peabody Hotel will bring their children along. So the
parents can be free to cavort, they have coralled 40 of the Annie's
Nannies agency's adult baby sitters. They will pay the sitters $330
each, or $33 an hour for the 11-hour affair and triple the agency's
usual rate. So it will be in most big cities and their affluent
suburbs this New Year's Eve. Teen-age baby sitters stand to earn
$200 or $300 for one night's work and adults up to $400, or more
than the tab for many a partygoer's duck and champagne. By Peter T.
Kilborn.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-IOWA (Dateline to kum, Iowa) _ The vice president's
campaign day. By Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENES-INSERT (Undated) _ A surprisingly simple technique to
create transgenic monkeys has enormous potential for biomedical
research and for fertility clinics. By Gina Kolata. (1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SHUTTLE (Houston) _ The shuttle astronauts make a six-hour
spacewalk to begin reviving the Hubble Space Telescope. By Warren
E. Leary.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MIDAS-FEAST (Undated) _ University of Pennsylvania
archaeologists, working in Turkey, have analyzed the menu of King
Midas' burial feast. By John Noble Wilford. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-ONLINE-BIZ (Beijing) _ The lure of a China's online
potential has turned into a full-blown gold rush in recent months.
With the number of online users tripling this year, to almost 7
million, the Internet here has captivated foreign technology
companies, venture capitalists, and investment banks. It is not
that Chinese online companies make any money; as in Silicon Valley,
they wear their losses like a badge of honor. Nor is China anywhere
close to being a mass market. Its entire online advertising
business generated about $12 million in revenue this year. And yet,
foreign investors are betting that China will soon have one of the
world's biggest Internet markets, perhaps second only to the United
States. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   (See CHINA-ONLINE, listed under INTERNATIONAL.)
</P>
<P>
   FEN-PHEN-LIABILITY (Undated) _ Folo on reports that American
Home Products has agreed to pay as much as $500 million to settle
hundreds of Mississippi lawsuits over the fen-phen diet-drug
combination after a Mississippi judge threw out a $150 million
damage award. And looking at whether the mounting fen-phen liabilty
kill the merger with Warner-Lambert. By David J. Morrow.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ Several dozen plaintiffs
lawyers meet in Washington to coordinate their antitrust suits
against Microsoft. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   UNITED-XRAYS (Undated) _ United Health Group's recent and
well-publicized announcement that it will stop second-guessing
doctors' apparently does not apply to X-ray imaging tests in New
York, New Jersey, Connecticut and Ohio. By Milt Freudenheim.
</P>
<P>
   NAYA-BANKRUPTCY (Undated) _ Folo on reports that Naya, the
bottled water company, has filed for bankruptcy protection in
Canada. By Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   VODAFONE-MANNESMANN (London) _ Guy Wyser-Pratte, a New York
arbitrager and shareholder activist, calls for an extraordinary
general meeting of shareholders to consider the Mannesmann's
rejection of Vodafone AirTouch's $127 billion bid. By Andrew Ross
Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   DAEWOO-FORD (Seoul, South Korea) _ Ford Motor says it will hold
talks with creditors of Daewoo Motor, rivaling General Motors and
Hyundai in seeking control of the Korean auto maker. By Samuel Len.
</P>
