<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 14:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6529 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-ANYGIVENSUNDAY-T     12-22 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-ANYGIVENSUNDAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLIVER STONE DROPS THE BALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Director Oliver Stone, after waging the Vietnam War (''Platoon''
and ``Born on the Fourth of July''), solving the JFK assassination
(''JFK'') and somehow associating J.R. Ewing with the Nixon scandal
(Larry Hagman has a cameo as a powerful Texas oilman in ``Nixon''),
now has the NFL in his cross hairs with ``Any Given Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sunday'' must be the first almost-three-hour-long movie
directed by a man with attention-deficit disorder: Mr. Stone's Wild
Ride. (It looks as if it was edited with a remote control _ a
zapper _ because it can barely remain in place for one shot, let
alone an entire scene.) And there's enough noise and insanity going
on to make you think that the games are played in South Park
Stadium. The leaking testosterone from any Stone movie could power
one football game; there's enough of the stuff splashing around in
``Sunday'' to fuel the entire playoff season.
</P>
<P>
   The Stone theme of father/son relationships weighs heavily here,
too. But this time, it's more about the father than the son, or for
that matter, the daughter. Al Pacino is the father figure, Miami
Shark coach Tony D'Amato, whose better days are long behind him.
His star quarterback, Jack ``Cap'' Rooney (Dennis Quaid), who seems
to be held together with Bubble Yum and Popsicle sticks, takes a
piledriver hit that knocks onto him the injured list for a long
time. D'Amato is forced to go to a third-string quarterback, Willie
Beaman (Jamie Foxx), who's so nervous that his lunch hits the field
before he does.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sunday'' is about age resisting giving up the stage to youth,
so it has a startling amount of drive and ambition. Stone works
like a much younger man, someone who still has something to prove.
(Stone turns in a cameo as a vain TV commentator with a mess of
curls that makes him look as if he's wearing the Big Boy's
hairpiece. And, surprisingly, he has an intimate, calm voice.) The
movie is so busy it's as if Stone doesn't trust himself _ or his
audience _ to follow a leaner, more precise story. A number of
scenes have so much going on with background noise, music and sound
effects that you can't quite tell what's happening.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, ``Sunday'' is so full of movement and crosscutting that
it's like ``NFL on Fox _ the Motion Picture.'' Stone oversimplifies
the story the way that Fox Sports does its athletes' profiles. The
Sharks' owner (Cameron Diaz) is part of a dynasty _ her dad was the
first owner and D'Amato's friend. She's determined to show that she
belongs in the game as much as any man, giving Stone a chance to
make a muddle of the sexism in the game as well. She goes
nose-to-nose with D'Amato, who, like any Stone hero, is fiercely
loyal. He's his own man, although being his own man leads D'Amato
to back the right guy, Beaman, who becomes a star by making up his
own plays. And as Beaman puffs up, so does his head: He abandons
his girlfriend and alienates himself from the other players.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to dramatizing the schism between the young and the
old _ Diaz has her eye on an assistant coach (Aaron Eckhart) she
wants to replace D'Amato with _ Stone addresses the takeover by
African-Americans of the athletic culture and pop culture, which
has left many whites feeling old and out of it. Or he tries. While
watching a hilariously lame hip-hop video starring Beaman _ it
sounds like the B-side of ``Super Bowl Shuffle'' _ D'Amato mutters
something about needing a translator.
</P>
<P>
   Stone returns to the Miami that was the setting of his
``Scarface'' script, a movie that bought him heavy props from the
hip-hop community; Stone's out to return the favor by using more
black culture than he ever has before. Besides Foxx _ who, as a pro
football player, looks like he's 3/4-scale _ ``Sunday'' features
Bill Bellamy, who also lacks stature and looks as if he should be
playing in the Canadian Football League; Jim Brown as an assistant
coach; LL Cool J as a wide receiver out to take care of himself and
no one else; and Lawrence Taylor, LT himself, who holds his own
with the other actors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sunday'' may sprawl, but it doesn't linger. Stone apparently
thinks he's saying something new: that pro football, like every
other major American institution, is corrupt. Even the team doctor
(James Woods) is morally bankrupt. Evidently, Stone doesn't get
ESPN or ``Sports Illustrated,'' where this stuff comes up all the
time. And I guess he's never seen (or read the novel) ``North
Dallas Forty,'' a much better movie on the same subject.
</P>
<P>
   The movie seems terribly dated, especially now that NFL wide
receiver Rae Carruth is charged with murdering his girlfriend, a
truly sad indication of the lack of responsibility that pro
athletes feel _ men who've been treated like royalty capable of
doing no wrong. (Yet, Stone's vigor and his eyes-wide-open take on
football clearly cost ``Any Given Sunday'' any NFL cooperation. As
a result, the uniforms and logos look as if they were designed by
Pier 1.) Yet the athletes' _ and the uniforms' _ disconnection from
the real world is appropriate for this movie, because ``Any Given
Sunday'' takes place on no planet in this galaxy.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Any Given Sunday''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 1/2 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Director: Oliver Stone
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Al Pacino, Cameron Diaz
</P>
<P>
   Length: 165 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ violence, adult language, sexuality and nudity
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-22-99 1440EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
