<HEADER>
A6539 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-LIBERTYHEIGHTS-T     12-22 0653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-LIBERTYHEIGHTS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DINER' DIRECTOR MINES QUESTIONS OF RACE, CLASS AND JEWISH
EXPERIENCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Director Barry Levinson continues his onscreen love affair with
1950s Baltimore, his hometown, in ``Liberty Heights.'' The love
affair began with ``Diner,'' still his best picture, and continued
on through ``Tin Men'' and ``Avalon.'' (The Fells Point Diner from
``Diner'' makes a cameo here.) Levinson, however, has become more
and more imperial as a director.
</P>
<P>
   ``Liberty Heights'' feels like a gorgeously made David Lean
movie about the Jewish Experience in America, right down to the
casting of the blond, snub-nosed kid (Ben Foster) who plays the
young protagonist who doesn't resemble anyone in his family. Joe
Mantegna is the father, who owns a dying burlesque house to hide
his real business as a numbers runner. He does well enough to keep
his family in a solid middle-class existence. Adrien Brody is the
oldest brother, who chases an unattainable blond WASP so damaged
that she was probably cut from the first draft of a Philip Roth
novel. And Bebe Neuwirth, who looks like a million dollars, is the
mother.
</P>
<P>
   Any of the various plot lines of ``Heights'' has enough dramatic
impact to make a movie. The movie's best moments have a comic
insolence, enough to make you wish Levinson would submit to those
impulses and make a comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Foster and his friends encounter a public pool with a sign
saying the pool excludes ``Jews, Coloreds and Dogs,'' and they riff
about the order. At a party in one of the tony WASP homes, one of
Brody's pals muses, after walking past all the antiques, that the
rich don't have taste enough to buy something new. It's the anger
that registers, but Levinson is so wrapped up in his reverie that
he can't play to his strengths.
</P>
<P>
   One subplot involves Foster's crush on a young African-American
girl. It upsets his parents _ ``Kill me now,'' his mother shrieks _
and the girl's father, a doctor, also thinks romantic contact is
inappropriate. This is an aspect of black life not seen onscreen,
the fact that middle-class blacks shied also away from integration,
and for reasons much different than those of whites. But Levinson
uses his white-glove manner to dramatize it. And the crush seems
bloodless, like something that belongs at the Smithsonian.
</P>
<P>
   There's another race-based subplot; Mantegna gets involved with
black numbers runner Little Melvin in a deal that goes bad, that is
so clumsily handled that it becomes inadvertently racist. When
circumstances lead to arrests, and it's suggested that the cops are
so happy to bust a white man that they let a black man go _ and in
Baltimore, which is essentially a Southern town _ you wonder what
has come over Levinson.
</P>
<P>
   Even Levinson's love of pop music isn't enough to keep
``Heights'' going. There's a scene in which Foster and his friend
go to a James Brown show. Only the James Brown looks like Heavy D
squeezed into one of Cab Calloway's rhinestone tuxedos from ``The
Blues Brothers.'' (As a kid, I saw Brown _ he was in such constant,
beautifully coordinated motion that he seemed to be 2 inches off
the ground at all times, even when he did those drop-splits.) In
the end, it's just another opportunity that the movie squanders.
``Liberty Heights'' is another of Levinson's end-of-an-era movies.
He's made so many elegies to the past that he's become a funeral
director, and this is an exquisite corpse.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Liberty Heights''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Director: Barry Levinson
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Joe Mantegna, Bebe Neuwirth, Adrien Brody
</P>
<P>
   Length: 127 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ adult language and situations, and mild violence
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
