<DOCNO> NYT19991222.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 14:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6544 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-MOON-HNS &LR;      12-22 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-MOON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     DREW CARREY EARNS HIS STRIPES IN `MAN ON THE MOON' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK McGUIRE  
 &HT;     c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fifteen years dead and gone _ well, presumably dead anyway _ and
Andy Kaufman gets to play one more joke on us.
</P>
<P>
   It comes at the very end of ``Man on the Moon,'' as the closing
credits roll (for the second time). Instead of gathering coats and
beating traffic, you are compelled to remain, half-turned in the
aisle and eyes on the screen, scanning the names of the second unit
director and the key grip and the ASPCA disclaimer. There may be
one last gag to be played, one more joke on you, and you are not
going to be a patsy.
</P>
<P>
   No, you are not going to let Andy Kaufman get you.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Man on the Moon'' will get you, almost as much as Jim
Carrey, in the title role, gets Andy Kaufman. As Tom Hanks buried
his ``Bachelor Party''/``Money Pit''/``Joe Versus the Volcano''
past to become the most seriously bankable actor in film, Carrey
has laid to rest ``Ace Ventura.'' Carrey, who showcased his
developing talent in ``The Truman Show,'' unequivocally must be
taken seriously, now. Oscar-seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Simply, Carrey is better than the movie _ and still the movie is
a captivating psychological study of what exactly constitutes art,
or at least performance art, and an artist.
</P>
<P>
   That said, there is no Jim Carrey in this movie. You concede
that Carrey is Kaufman rather than playing him, from the moment he
appears in the opening scene, in Kaufman's Foreign Man character,
decrying the ``stupid'' movie to follow. ``I don't even like it,''
he says, before putting the needle down on a 45 rpm record on his
Ultratone and ordering the closing credits to roll (for the first
time).
</P>
<P>
   ``Man on the Moon'' (the title comes from a reverential 1993
song about Kaufman by REM, whose music permeates the movie) is at
times sad, often uncomfortable and more than a little bit
disturbing _ what is the line between individual genius and plain
nuts? _ just as Kaufman himself was to watch. Meanwhile Kaufman's
alter ego, the hyper-noxious lounge lizard Tony Clifton (Carrey
approached the movie as if it were two roles), may have been the
single most unfunny, unnerving and unpalatable character created
since, well, anyone played by Fran Drescher.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, this is no comedy, although humor subversive and
otherwise abounds. Kaufman and his sidekick/writer Bob Zmuda (Paul
Giamatti, deservedly one of the hottest character actors in
Hollywood) do their best to disrupt, annoy, challenge and _ if it
emerges as a byproduct _ entertain the people and institutions
around them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it an act or are you just addicted to causing trouble?''
asks Kaufman's girlfriend Lynne Margulies (the improving grunge
rocker/actress Courtney Love).
</P>
<P>
   Kaufman considered himself a song-and-dance man, abhorring any
characterization of him being a comic. ``I'm not a comedian,''
Kaufman tells his agent, George Shapiro (Danny DeVito) in the
movie. ``I don't do jokes. I don't even know what is funny.''
</P>
<P>
   Director Milos Forman has earned a living _ and Oscars _ by
profiling on-the-edge iconoclasts, whether they be a porn peddler
(``The People vs. Larry Flynt'') or composer (Mozart in
``Amadeus'') or provocateur (McMurphy in ``One Flew Over the
Cuckoo's Nest''). Forman plays games with some chronology (like the
timeline for Kaufman's famed Carnegie Hall concert, after which he
took the entire audience out for milk and cookies), but more
importantly he toys with the filmgoer.
</P>
<P>
   Giving equal evidence without drawing conclusions, Forman leaves
it up to you to conclude whether Kaufman was a trailblazer who was
grossly misunderstood, or if there was a reason why no one before
did what he did: He was just being a jerk.
</P>
<P>
   As a lonely kid growing up on Long Island, Kaufman was putting
on shows for no one, his crowd consisting of the plaster walls of
his bedroom. ``If you want to perform you have to have an
audience,'' his father tells him. But in many ways throughout his
career the bug-eyed yet expressionless Kaufman still performed for
himself (and Zmuda and later Margulies). His were inside gags
played out in front of a national audience.
</P>
<P>
   But Kaufman did need the crowd _ more specifically, their
reaction. He didn't quite care what that reaction was _ adulation,
revulsion, loathing _ so long as it wasn't apathy. ``I want the
audience to go through an experience,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The whole Foreign Man _ originally from Caspiar, a small island
in the Caspian Sea; it sank _ served as the basis for his Latka
Gravas ``Taxi'' character. Kaufman hated ``Taxi,'' and did his best
to subvert his presence on it.
</P>
<P>
   (Every major cast member from the sitcom save Tony Danza makes
cameos in the movie. Well, Danza and DeVito. DeVito as his Louie
DePalma ``Taxi'' character doesn't appear, because DeVito plays
agent Shapiro, and that double-exposure would be too _ what? _
Kaufmanesque?)
</P>
<P>
   Of course, a major portion of the film is devoted to Kaufman's _
here is that word again _ bizarre career move to wrestle ... women.
It backfired: (A.) the public hated it, and him; and (B.) when he
went into the ring against professional wrestler Jerry Lawler, he
almost got his neck snapped.
</P>
<P>
   Still, what the movie does not achieve is maybe the most basic
question of a biopic, yet one that in this case always will remain
unanswerable: Who was Andy Kaufman, the real Andy Kaufman?
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't know the real me,'' Kaufman pines to Margulies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't a real you,'' she replies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yeah. I forgot.''
</P>
<P>
   With Kaufman, the act blurred reality, and reality blurred the
act. When he breaks the news that he has lung cancer, a disease
that would take his life at age 35, his friends are unsure whether
it is just another bit. His family, on the other hand, is
thoroughly convinced he is putting them on. The movie's finale
leaves the door of ambiguity slightly ajar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man on the Moon'' is a serious look at an absurd man who is
brought back to life by an absurd actor who now must be taken
seriously. Andy Kaufman was the naive cynic, wanting life to all be
an act, unable to comprehend the reality resulting from his
make-believe. Could it be that in the end the joke was really on
Kaufman?
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. His electronic mail
address is mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
