<HEADER>
A6549 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-MOTHER-TEX     12-22 0526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-MOTHER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALMODOVAR'S `MOTHER' SUPERIOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Writer-director Pedro Almodovar's newest film, ``All About My
Mother,'' is one of the year's best. With it, he continues with
streak he started with last year's ``Live Flesh,'' a welcome return
to form that wasn't as groundbreaking as his earlier work _ which
included ``Women on the Verge of a Nervous Breakdown'' and ``Law of
Desire'' _ but was arresting nonetheless. His new melodrama _
heartbreak staged by a diva set in Almodovar's world of innocents,
drag queens and drug addicts _ is uniquely energetic and cinematic.
</P>
<P>
   The plot lines are like a line from the song ``Once in a
Lifetime'': ``Here comes the twister.'' Manuela (Cecilia Roth)
lives through the worst tragedy a parent can endure: the death of
her son. He's hit by a car while chasing down the star (Marisa
Paredes) of ``A Streetcar Named Desire'' for an autograph. The
boy's father is a transvestite dying of AIDS, and the father has
recently conceived a child with a nun (the luscious but opaque
Penelope Cruz).
</P>
<P>
   After suffering the loss of her son and discovering in his
journals that all he ever wanted was a relationship with his
father, Manuela gives herself over to being a mother, to fill the
void in her life. She becomes caretaker to the nun and the junkie
``Streetcar'' star. ``Mother'' is really a tribute to mothers, and
to people who lead their lives like entertainers. Almodovar's
instincts are too generous to just make audiences suffer.
</P>
<P>
   He's as much a born entertainer as the characters who populate
his work. His characters are linked by sex or blood, a chemistry
that gives his movies their unique humidity _ and humor; no one is
as fearless about laughter through tears as Almodovar. And no
director loves actresses more; this movie is a sophisticated,
intelligent showcase. Roth and Paredes are simply wonderful, and he
serves up Cruz on a platter, although she's charismatic here
because she's more comfortable with Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Our reactions to Almodovar have been tempered by time. What he
was doing in his early work, turning the ripe melodrama of Douglas
Sirk (director of ``Written on the Wind'' and ``Imitation of
Life'') and yes, Tennessee Williams, into a flamboyant emotional
cabaret was so new and exciting that he created a hunger. It was a
demand for the literally colorful brand of slapstick soap opera
that he became less capable of filling after the peak of
``Breakdown.'' This new period, which includes ``Live Flesh,'' and
the grand allusions of ``All About My Mother,'' for which he won
the best director prize at Cannes, is a much-needed second wind,
for Almodovar and his audiences.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``All About My Mother''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 4 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Director: Pedro Almodovar
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Cecilia Roth, Penelope Cruz
</P>
<P>
   Length: 105 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ adult language and situations. In Spanish with
subtitles.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
