<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 15:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6577 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-NY-LOBBY-RULES-HNS &LR;      12-22 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LOBBY-RULES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     REFORM ADVOCATES SAY NEW YORK LOBBYING MEASURE FALLS SHORT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JAMES M. ODATO  
 &HT;     c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Falling short of the strong measures desired by
government reform advocates, the state Assembly and Gov. George
Pataki agreed on a tougher lobbying law late Tuesday that would
give the state more muscle without taking away a public officer's
ability to accept free meals.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the gift-ban bill passed last week by the Senate, the
Assembly measure would allow lobbyists to bestow gifts of up to $75
on public officials. But it would severely penalize the lobbyists
for breaking the gift limit or for falsely reporting lobbying
activities.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Senate Republicans' bill, the Assembly measure would
not ban fund-raising in the Capital Region during the legislative
session. Nor does it extend to lobbying of state agencies, a
provision desired by the current lobbying oversight commission.
Assembly aides said fund-raising may be addressed in a campaign
finance bill that would be introduced next year.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of revamping the system said they would continue to
fight for broader reforms, particularly gift bans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the stuff in the proposal is quite good. The thing
that's stunning is that it doesn't do anything about gifts and it
doesn't include state agencies,'' said Blair Horner, legislative
director of the New York Public Interest Research Group.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, the bill leaves New York without a law _ since the
Senate needs to sign on _ and the current law, authorizing the New
York Temporary State Commission on Lobbying, is set to expire in 10
days.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno, a Republican from
Brunswick, may change that. He said late Tuesday that he would
bring his house back next week to vote on the Health Care Reform
Act. At that time he will discuss the Assembly lobbying bill with
his conference, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no agreement ... to act on this bill,'' he warned.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly bill represents a first, according the Assembly
aides, in that Pataki, a Republican; Assembly Speaker Sheldon
Silver, a Democrat; and the Assembly's Republican leader, John
Faso, endorsed the same measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The legislation before us achieves real and meaningful
reform,'' said Silver, who is from Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly bill would largely give the commission what it has
been seeking, greater regulatory power. But it would extend the
commission for eight years rather than make it permanent.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal targets lobbyist activity rather than public
officials and legislators, who must respond to complaints of
misbehavior before ethics boards that have been criticized by good
government groups for failing to investigate complaints.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would authorize the commission to do random audits of
lobbyists to see if they are reporting all of their activities.
</P>
<P>
   It also would require lobbyists to disclose lobbying of local
governments _ not just state government _ for communities greater
than 50,000 in population.
</P>
<P>
   If a lobbyist gave sports tickets or paid for meals valued at
more than $75, he or she would be subject to a civil penalty and
face a Class A misdemeanor. Fines would rise five times to $25,000
per violation. If the lobbyist commits the violation a second time
within five years of the first infraction, the lobbyist would face
a Class E felony charge.
</P>
<P>
   Filing fraudulent documents would carry a $50,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   Lobbyists would be required to file reports with the commission
on a bimonthly basis _ twice as frequently as current law.
Lobbyists' clients would have to do semi-annual, rather than
annual, filings.
</P>
<P>
   So the state could more easily track their activities, lobbyists
would have to disclose the numbers of bills they are lobbying for
or against, and the proposed rule or rate cases they are lobbying.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill also banned gifts, with the exception of some
items _ finger food, drinks or baseball caps, for instance _ valued
up to $25.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly bill failed to achieve some priorities of
government reform advocates who wanted gifts banned and
fund-raising outlawed in the legislative session. Yet the local
government lobbying disclosures and random audits in the bill were
among the items desired by the groups.
</P>
<P>
   Lobbying reform has become a hot topic in recent weeks because
of the impending expiration of the current law and because of
substantial publicity involving the wining and dining of public
officials by the chief lobbyist for the Philip Morris Cos. The
tobacco lobbyist also admitted filing inaccurate and false
disclosure forms to the state, resulting in a $75,000 fine against
the company and a $15,000 fine and three-year lobbying ban against
the lobbyist, Sharon Portnoy.
</P>
</TEXT>
