r e BC-FIRST100-AZR &LR;      12-22 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRST100-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRIGHT LIGHTS, SIN CITY: `PORTRAITS' OF VEGAS' MOVERS AND SHAPERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
 (RESENDING TO FIX TYPO IN HUNTINGTON PRESS WEBSITE AT END)  
 ``THE FIRST 100:  PORTRAITS OF THE MEN AND WOMEN WHO SHAPED LAS
VEGAS'' 
  
 By A.D. Hopkins and K.J. Evans from the archives of 
 the ``Las Vegas Review-Journal''  (Huntington Press, $34.95) 
 &HT;     By DAVE WALKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's not just slot-machine feeders finding the new Las Vegas to
be an irresistible attraction.
</P>
<P>
   Publishers, too, are squinting into the Strip's bright lights
and seeing dollar signs.
</P>
<P>
   Oxford University Press recently published a collection of
essays titled ``The Real Las Vegas: Life Beyond the Strip.''
Villard Books offers Andres Martinez's ``24/7: Living It Up and
Doubling Down in the New Las Vegas.'' Early next year, Bantam
Doubleday Dell will sell Pete Earley's ``Super Casino.''
</P>
<P>
   No wonder. Combine Sin City's colorful past with its current
boom, and you've got a sizzling 20th century story.
</P>
<P>
   Readers interested in the finer details of that story could
start with ``The First 100,'' a new book from Las Vegas publisher
Huntington Press.
</P>
<P>
   A collection of profiles, the book _ actually a reprint of a
massive project by the ``Las Vegas Review-Journal'' _ tells the
city's history through its people. It was an end-of-the-century
undertaking designed to document a place perpetually engaged in
furious re-invention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these people I almost cried for not getting to meet,''
said A.D. Hopkins, who with K.J. Evans oversaw the project for the
``Review-Journal.'' ``For a lot of these people, there was no
archival material. For a lot of people here, we were establishing
the archival material.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The First 100'' includes the people behind some familiar Las
Vegas names and landmarks, including John C. Fremont, Harley
Harmon, James Cashman, Pat McCarran and Benny Binion.
</P>
<P>
   Also here are the peculiarly Las Vegas histories of marquee
names such as Caesars Palace and Circus Circus builder Jay Sarno,
Donn Arden (credited with perfecting the over-the-top _ and
sometimes topless _ showroom spectacular), Benjamin (don't call him
``Bugsy'') Siegel, Frank Sinatra, Howard Hughes and Elvis Presley.
</P>
<P>
   The balance of entries examines lesser-knowns while telling the
unlikely tale of how a mixture of Mormons, mobsters and
multimillionaires built a premier vice-tourism destination from raw
desert.
</P>
<P>
   Hopkins, a 30-year Las Vegas veteran, once edited the
``Review-Journal's''history-heavy (but now, alas, defunct) Sunday
magazine, ``Nevadan.'' Hopkins personally wrote many of the
entries, as did the late K.J. Evans, another former ``Nevadan''
editor. (The entire project is also archived online at
www.lvrj.com, the paper's Web site.)
</P>
<P>
   Currently a special-projects editor for the paper, Hopkins, 56,
said a list of 300 profile subjects was suggested by readers, as
well as a committee of historians and ``Review-Journal'' staffers.
</P>
<P>
   The first big list ranged from beloved grade-school teachers to
beauty queens, bankers to burlesque stars. The final cut didn't
limit the list to the merely historically important.
</P>
<P>
   A considerable dose of imagination went into the selection
process. How else to explain the inclusion of John Seibold, who
popularized Las Vegas-based sightseeing flights over the Grand
Canyon? Or fabled hypemeister Bob Stupak, who was inspired to build
the Stratosphere Tower when a heavy windstorm blew down the sign in
front of his tacky Vegas World casino?
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of (the nominees) were important, but not very
interesting,'' Hopkins said. ``They were supposed to have a
long-term effect, but if there was a story that we wanted to tell,
we wouldn't let it slide.''
</P>
<P>
   Hopkins admitted that many of the people who didn't make the
final list were as fascinating as those who did. Take Larry Snow,
who popularized the game baccarat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baccarat makes money for hotels,'' Hopkins said. ``Sometimes
it's the difference between profit and loss.''
</P>
<P>
   Or John Stuart, who pioneered the celebrity-impersonator show.
</P>
<P>
   ``There used to be a lot of those, and it was his idea,''
Hopkins said. ``If you come up with a winning idea, a trend in
entertainment that shows no sign of of quitting, that's worth
something. That's a contribution.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there had been 150, he'd have made it.'' &QL; 
``The First 100'' can be ordered on the Web
(www.huntingtonpress.com) or by telephone (1-702-252-0655). Dave
Walker can be reached at (602) 444-8625 or
dave.walker(at)arizonarepublic.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
