<P>
   DUBBELDAM-ARCHITECTURE (New York) _ Clients willing to indulge
the futuristic whims of architects are notoriously rare. But Winka
Dubbeldam, a 35-year-old Dutch-born architect based in Manhattan,
seems to have a knack for attracting patrons susceptible to her
visual poetry: the passion of a former sculptor for combining
natural materials to achieve novel effects. Among her fans, the
famously demanding architect Peter Eisenman called her ``a very
talented, highly energetic and motivated person. She's the pulse of
the moment,'' he added. By Christopher Mason.
</P>
<P>
   GORDON-PLACE (New York) _ The writer Mary Gordon and the issue
of place. By William L. Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KEEPING-HOUSE (Undated) _ I grew up with a mother who baked
bread, ironed everything from sheets to jeans, vacuumed the carpet
in straight lines, and cleaned the entire house the night before
our cleaning person came. The running joke among my friends was,
``At the Hessers' house, you do cry over spilled milk.'' So it was
with both curiosity and skepticism that I picked up Cheryl
Mendelson's wildly comprehensive, 884-page manual, ``Home Comforts:
The Art and Science of Keeping House'' (Scribner, $35). In it, Ms.
Mendelson covers everything from dusting techniques to bleach
expiration dates. By Amanda Hesser.
</P>
<P>
   LAPIDUS-ARCHITECTURE (Miami) _ In the early 1990s, after his
wife's death, the legendary architect Morris Lapidus found himself
staring at a calendar white with blank dates. The designer of
Miami's Fontainebleau and Eden Roc hotels, Lapidus, then in his
early 90s, had retired from active practice and was sitting alone
in his ocean-front duplex, bored. In 1994, after serving on a
review panel for work by Miami architecture students, he had lunch
with a fellow juror, Deborah Desilets, and more lunches. ``He was
so removed from professional life,'' she said. ``I realized that he
had so much to give that it would be a shame not to find some way
to make it happen.'' Eventually they formed an informal
partnership, taking him from deep retirement to shallow retirement.
Now, at 97, he is back in business, sketching. By Joseph
Giovannini.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Garden questions answered. By Dora
Galitzki.
