<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-GOODIEMOB23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With Mob mentality, feet will get moving
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   An album ago, the first single out of Atlanta act Goodie Mob's
``Still Standing'' proclaimed that ``people don't dance no mo.''
Now Cee-Lo, T-Mo, Big Gipp and Khujo follow that declaration with
their most musical and danceable CD to date.
</P>
<P>
   Well, it is called ``World Party.'' And Goodie Mob has enlisted
some of the best producers in the business to entice a broader
audience off the wall and onto the floor. Longtime music providers
Organized Noize offer the easy hand-clappers ``Get Rich to This''
and ``I.C.U.,'' one-time Puff Daddy companion Deric ``D-Dot''
Angelettie hooks a muscular piano to ``Chain Swang'' and Dallas
Austin employs the electronic bounce he used on TLC's album
``Fanmail'' _ and the pop trio _ on the certain breakout single
``What It Ain't (Ghetto Enuff).''
</P>
<P>
   ``But wait,'' longtime followers of the Mob may be wondering,
``what happened to all the consciousness?'' It's still there. And
when the foursome is talking about ``Rebuilding'' instead of
picking up a 9mm gun (``Just Do It''), it's still praiseworthy.
</P>
<P>
   RAP
</P>
<P>
   ``World Party''
</P>
<P>
   Goodie Mob. LaFace Records. 14 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   _Sonia Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
