A6594 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AUDIO-JAZZ23-COX     12-22 0307
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-JAZZ23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A radiantly lyrical jazz percussionist does N.Y. proud
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the more promising jazz percussionists to emerge during
the past decade, 28-year-old Susie Ibarra enjoyed her highest
profile as the former drummer in tenor saxophonist David S. Ware's
quartet: a barnstorming outfit to which Ibarra brought a rainbow of
polyrhythmic hues and subtle devices (as Atlanta audiences
witnessed during 1998 and 1999 performances at Eyedrum and the
First Existential Congregation). Lately, she's embarked on her own
course as a bandleader. This debut disc from her trio is one of the
more openly lyrical and original albums to come out of the downtown
New York avant jazz scene this year. It features two musicians,
violinist Charles Burnham and pianist/homemade instrumentalist
Cooper-Moore, with whom the drummer enjoys an uncommonly
sympathetic rapport. That's a crucial issue, too, with music as
open and as pleasurably improvised as this.
</P>
<P>
   Over six original pieces, two alternate takes and a version of
Jimi Hendrix's ``Up From the Skies'' (a showcase for the
extraordinarily vocal nature of Burnham's violin), the trio gently
rocks out, maps the shadows of melancholy (Cooper-Moore's piano
introduction to ``Half Moon'' ushering in Burnham's fluid chamber
blues), travels through Southeast Asia and hauls out Cooper-Moore's
secret weapon, the diddley-bow, for a coda appropriately titled
``Laughter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Radiance''
</P>
<P>
   Susie Ibarra Trio. Hopscotch.
</P>
<P>
   11 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   ``Radiance'' is available through Hopscotch, P.O. Box 170279,
Times Plaza Station, Brooklyn, NY 11217.
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Dollar writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
