<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991222.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 15:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6596 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AUDIO-MINIS23-COX     12-22 0198
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CD mini review
 &HT;    By Shane Harrison,
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  DANCE POP
</P>
<P>
   ``Afterglow''
</P>
<P>
   Dot Allison. Arista. 11 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   Dot Allison first attracted attention as the winsome vocalist
for One Dove, an early '90s dance-pop group that disbanded after
one album, never making good on a promising start. With her first
solo effort, she takes the reins with surprising maturity and an
unwavering sense of purpose. This sounds like the work of a much
more experienced artist.
</P>
<P>
   Trip-hop, ambient drones and '60s psychedelia are all part of
her arsenal, but the most sublime moment is also the quietest.
``Tomorrow Never Comes'' has an achingly beautiful melody. When
Allison breathily intones the first line of the chorus (``With a
little courage, in time, you might forgive me''), the desolation is
palpable.
</P>
<P>
   There's a smoky, late-night vibe to ``Afterglow,'' but these
songs are much too thoughtful and complex for the jaded fashion
victims that brings to mind.
</P>
<P>
   _Shane Harrison writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
