<DOCNO> NYT19991222.0171 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 15:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6597 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-VIDEO-LOLA23-COX     12-22 0324
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-LOLA23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Lola' is above the average run of thrillers
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Run Lola Run'' (R)
</P>
<P>
   A pyrotechnic celebration of style over substance, this kinetic
German film is the cinematic love child of every video game and MTV
quick-cut editing trick of the past 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   It's a nonstop adrenalin kick, even though the script sometimes
can't keep pace with its leggy heroine. That's the flame-haired
Lola (Franka Potente), who runs through the streets of Berlin to
save the life of her boyfriend, Manni (Moritz Bleibtreu), a bagman
for the mob who has misplaced 100,000 marks. She has 20 minutes to
get the cash or lose Manni for good _ either to his trigger-happy
bosses or to his dangerous plan of robbing a grocery store for the
loot.
</P>
<P>
   Spinning busy elaborations on this simple tale, writer-director
Tom Tykwer finds endless ways to stimulate the minuscule attention
spans of today's twentysomethings. He has so many visual surprises
and narrative digressions in his arsenal that you can never guess
where Lola, and the movie, are racing next. Especially since he
shoots the same 20-minute dash three separate times, with obstacles
in Lola's path _ a vicious dog, a baby carriage, nuns _ causing
completely different outcomes (romantic, tragic, mystical).
</P>
<P>
   The swift, fat-free movie employs animation, different film
stock, split-screen images and sharp doses of irony. But its speed
and brevity don't quite obscure the script's thinness. You may find
yourself asking questions you shouldn't. For example, why doesn't
Lola just grab the phone and call her dad? The answer is that, if
she did, there wouldn't be a movie. And because ``Lola'' is so much
fun, you're willing to shrug and accept the artifice.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
