<DOCNO> NYT19991222.0172 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 15:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6598 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-VIDEO-MINIS23-COX     12-22 0324
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-MINIS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini views
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie and Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Summer of Sam'' (R) _ This ``Summer'' is definitely long,
but it's not so hot. The killing spree of psycho David Berkowitz in
New York's summer of '77 is just one of many stories director Spike
Lee tries to tell. Also in the mix are the blackout, Reggie
Jackson's World Series and rising tensions among some
Italian-American homeboys in the Bronx for whom it would already be
a long, hot summer without the added stress of a killer among them.
It's as if Lee had tried to make a Robert Altman movie. Not a good
idea. Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Adventures of Elmo in Grouchland'' (G) _ A kind of
extended episode of ``Sesame Street,'' this movie is recommended to
the very, very, very young. And, perhaps, to any parents curious to
see how the old gang looks after all these years (hint: Big Bird
has aged better than Bob). Essentially, little Elmo (voice by Kevin
Clash) must go to Grouchland to rescue his blanket from a meanie
named Huxley (a hammy Mandy Patinkin). Vanessa Williams appears as
the Queen of Trash. Fill in your own joke. Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``American Pie'' (R) _ It's a raunchy, throwaway, pre-adult,
R-rated high school sexcapade with dirty dialogue and more than one
risque encounter between students that's broadcast over the
Internet. There's also the grossest joke involving a beer you're
likely ever to see on film. Little in ``American Pie'' deserves
honest laughs. It rarely comes close to matching the free-spirited
hilarity of the embarrassingly funny ``There's Something About
Mary.'' (Available in R-rated and unrated versions.) Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   _Bob Longino
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gillespie and Bob Longino write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
