<HEADLINE>
DON'T THROW AWAY KEYBOARD JUST YET
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN  
c.1999 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the Holy Grails of personal computing has long been voice
recognition. Its proponents believe that it's better to talk to
your computer than use that ancient instrument of torture known as
the keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   For the last few years, the companies that make software that
can control a PC and turn words into text have said that it is
finally ready for prime time, that it's good enough for everyday
people to use comfortably. Come and get it!
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, it wasn't true then. And, it's almost not true
now.
</P>
<P>
   I've been looking at each of the new voice-recognition releases
over the last two years, but haven't found anything worth writing
about. These earlier versions took too long to train to recognize
an individual's voice and speech, and once they did, their
recognition success rates were unacceptably low.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, with each new version, these programs have gotten
better. And, the latest are the best so far, but it's largely
thanks to a pair of advances in hardware.
</P>
<P>
   The first is a set of new multimedia-enhancing code found in
Intel Corp.'s Pentium III chips, as well as in Advanced Micro
Devices' Athlon processors. This code can be used to boost the
ability of the software to hear and translate words into text more
accurately.
</P>
<P>
   The second is the development of microphones that plug into a
Universal Serial Bus, or USB, port. These bypass a computer's
traditional sound card, which takes two large variables out of the
voice-recognition equation _ card and microphone quality. Using a
USB microphone greatly increases the accuracy of what the computer
hears.
</P>
<P>
   I've been looking at two voice recognition programs, both of
which work with a USB microphone _ Dragon Systems Naturally- &QL; 
Speaking Preferred 4.0 and Lernout &AMP; Hauspie's VoiceXpress
Professional 4.0. They were tested on a computer that has a
500-megahertz Pentium III chip. While both are much better than
what was offered just two years ago, I still found them frustrating
to use. However, they're now good enough that those with
disabilities or who are seriously keyboard-phobic can use them for
everyday tasks.
</P>
<P>
   And, in case you're wondering, no, I didn't write this review
using the software. It would have driven me nuts.
</P>
<P>
   _ NaturallySpeaking Preferred USB 4.0, $249, Dragon Systems. Of
the two systems I tried, NaturallySpeaking had the best voice
recognition accuracy, but was not as good at maneuvering around
Windows 98 as I would have liked.
</P>
<P>
   However, if you are a WordPerfect user, you'll definitely want
to select this title, because it meshes so well with that word
processor. In fact, one version of the WordPerfect Office 2000
suite comes with an integrated version of NaturallySpeaking.
</P>
<P>
   As with all voice recognition products, you must spend time
training the program to recognize your voice. NaturallySpeaking has
you select a passage to read from several sources _ I chose a
chapter from Arthur C. Clarke's novel ``2001: A Space Odyssey,''
which seemed fitting _ and the computer listens while you read.
</P>
<P>
   You can go through as many training sessions as you like, each
taking about 15 minutes, but Dragon claims decent accuracy with
just one session for those who have a clear, unaccented voice.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, I was able to do fairly well, achieving about 95 percent
accuracy when I read from a document. When I just dictated off the
top of my head, though, accuracy dropped way off. I found I was
distracted by watching the process of the computer converting words
to text, and it threw off my natural rhythm of speech. Since I
trained the computer by reading to it, it was confused by the
different speech pattern.
</P>
<P>
   NaturallySpeaking also was best at using voice to correct
mistakes. Both programs bring up a text box that lets you alter
mistranslated words, and with this program I seldom had to resort
to typing in the correct letters.
</P>
<P>
   However, I found it clunky using this software to control
Windows applications. For example, inserting Web addresses into
Internet Explorer was very frustrating, as was choosing which
e-mail to open and read in Eudora Pro.
</P>
<P>
   This version comes with a headset USB microphone, which is why
it costs as much as it does. If you buy the USB microphone
separately, you can get the software for about $200.
</P>
<P>
   _ VoiceXpress Professional 4, $150, Lernout &AMP; Hauspie: Although
it doesn't say so on the box, VoiceXpress professional will work
with a USB microphone _ and a coupon for a Telex model is inside.
It comes with a basic headset microphone, but it's worth spending
the $60 for a USB version.
</P>
<P>
   VoiceXpress' package claims it can go through its training
process _ which L&AMP;H calls ``enrollment'' _ in about 12 minutes.
However, that's for reading a single passage, and I noticed at the
end of the session that it recommended I go through more enrollment
for better results, which in effect doubled the training time.
</P>
<P>
   VoiceXpress was not quite as accurate as NaturallySpeaking. I
topped out at about 90 percent accuracy when reading text, and
accuracy in simple dictation dropped off. I also found it was
harder to correct using my voice _ I frequently had to resort to
typing corrections. Even trying to spell the word verbally resulted
in errors.
</P>
<P>
   However, VoiceXpress was better at navigating Windows. It also
comes with the ability to create voice-based macros _ a series of
commands you can execute with a single word. For example, if you
have a favorite Web site, you can have VoiceXpress launch your
browser and go directly there just by saying its name.
</P>
<P>
   VoiceXpress comes with a series of small applications called
TalkingTools designed specifically to work using voice commands,
including a notepad, calculator, an address book and a time-zone
clock. There's even something called the Web Finder, which lets you
ask a question that's then sent to a Web search engine.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
