<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIVACY AT A PREMIUM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By HIAWATHA BRAY   
 c.1999 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're reading this on The Boston Globe's Web site, you know
what I look like. More's the pity.
</P>
<P>
   It's bad enough that I resemble an African-American version of
Mr. Potato Head. But I'm even more distressed by the idea that one
of you might recognize me as I flip through a copy of the National
Enquirer in the supermarket checkout line.
</P>
<P>
   I like anonymity, but I've lost it. Come to think of it, so have
the people reading this on line, and just about every other
Internet user. Once you log on, you leave an electronic trail that
can be followed right back to your home or office.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet does a great job of providing an illusion of
anonymity. You can always use zany made-up names in your e-mails,
or when signing up at a Web site. But your Internet service
provider will know your real name. Even if you don't provide your
real name to a Web site, that site does know your IP address, the
set of digits that identifies the Internet service you're using.
And that service provider can use the IP number to track you down.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are cookies, the little chunks of data that let
companies follow you as you browse the Web. Cookies used to be
harmless, because they contained no data to identify the user. But
as I reported a few months ago, some companies now have ways of
linking cookie data to your name and address. Web marketers will
know where you live.
</P>
<P>
   The only possible cure is a system that lets you travel the Net
incognito, concealing your true identity at every point along the
way. The best-known technique for this is called an anonymous
remailer. This is an Internet e-mail server that collects incoming
mail, gives it a phony e-mail address and IP number, then sends it
to its final destination.
</P>
<P>
   There are a number of such remailers on the Net, run as labors
of love by devotees of on-line privacy. But I've come across some
companies that hope to turn the hunger for privacy into a
profitable business.
</P>
<P>
   There's Proxymate, a Murray Hill, N.J., firm that's being
financed by Lucent Technologies Inc. and uses technology developed
at Lucent's Bell Labs division. The company is running a free test
of its service at www.proxymate.com. Proxymate lets the user route
all Internet activity through a server that conceals the origin of
messages.
</P>
<P>
   Say you type in the Web address for Yahoo. Instead of going
straight to the Yahoo server, your request goes to Proxymate, which
in turn contacts Yahoo. This way, Yahoo never sees your browser or
your IP address.
</P>
<P>
   When a Web site asks for your e-mail address, Proxymate can
generate a fake address that will let the site send you mail but
won't give away your true identity. You can get a different e-mail
alias for each Web site. If an alias is used to send you spam, you
simply cancel that alias; the others will still work.
</P>
<P>
   The system relies on software stored on Proxymate's own server,
so you don't need new software at your end. But it does have a weak
point _ the company needs to know your real e-mail address, so your
anonymity isn't absolute. This isn't good enough for the hackers at
Montreal-based Zero-Knowledge Systems Inc. (www.zeroknowledge.com).
</P>
<P>
   Zero-Knowledge president Austin Hill believes that even the
designers of a security system shouldn't be able to defeat that
system. So his company has come up with software called Freedom
that resides on the user's computer and encrypts all information
about the user so that nobody can retrieve it.
</P>
<P>
   Lose your Freedom password, and you're locked out forever.
</P>
<P>
   The Freedom system routes your Internet traffic through a
network of servers scattered around the world. You can set it up to
bounce your data around so wildly that nobody will ever trace it
back to you. Freedom offers alias e-mail, as well, but with a twist
_ it's encrypted to make it even more secure.
</P>
<P>
   Freedom isn't free. You'll pay $10 a year for each alias, and
there's a minimum price of $50. You can buy one alias for five
years, or buy multiple aliases _ one for shopping, one for casual
surfing, another for posting bulletin-board messages, another for
your on-line gambling addiction. And of course, one for weekly
visits to www.nationalenquirer.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Hiawatha Bray is a member of the Globe staff. He can be reached by
e-mail at Bray(at)globe.com)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-12-16-99 1345EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
