<HEADER>
A6618 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CPT-OUTLOOK-E-COMMERC     12-22 1348
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-OUTLOOK-E-COMMERCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELECTRONIC RETAILING TO A TRULY MASS MARKET IS EXPECTED
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By BOB TEDESCHI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ten years ago, Internet prognosticators sounded overzealous when
they suggested that an interconnected network of computers would
recast every facet of society.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most futuristic and Utopian predictions may never
play out, of course. But the Net does seem to be bringing
irrevocable change to one part of life: buying stuff.
</P>
<P>
   So far, online retailing has been the province of more affluent,
better-educated people who are the likeliest to have computers. But
demographic and technological trends seem likely to make electronic
retailing _ e-tailing _ a truly mass market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Especially recently, we've seen an abundance of high-end
luxury sites,'' said Ann Winblad, a founding partner of Hummer
Winblad Venture Partners, a venture capital firm. ``That'll change,
certainly in the next five years, as we'll see a lot more people
with lower incomes on the Web than today.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Winblad said that companies would continue to tinker with
the so-called free PC and free Internet access business models _
marketing techniques in which consumers are given simple PCs or
no-frills Internet access at low or even no cost, in exchange for
being captive to advertisers or to a specific set of retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the dismal track record of such approaches, she
predicted that marketers would persevere until they established a
technological link to the masses. ``It makes sense for these
companies,'' she said, ``because they can own the customer for a
lifetime of needs.''
</P>
<P>
   The impact on e-commerce will be profound, Ms. Winblad and
others said, because until now most marketing and business
assumptions have been based on an online population that has been
relatively affluent and ethnically homogenous. With a more diverse
socioeconomic mix, analysts said, users could expect a much wider
range of Internet services and products.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Paul Saffo, the director of the Institute for the
Future, a forecasting firm, expects the Internet to yield a range
of new products. ``Just as television produced new products, like
TV Guide, TV dinners and Ginsu knives,'' he said, ``we'll be buying
new stuff that never existed before because there's been no good
way to sell it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Web's ability to concentrate geographically dispersed
markets, he said, is one clue to the type of products Internet
retailing will support. ``We'll have products for audiences that
have been so widely distributed in the past that there wouldn't be
a store for them,'' Saffo said, offering the example of snakeproof
boots as a product that would have an easier time finding a market
online.
</P>
<P>
   The same market-driven forces that will push the Internet to a
broader cross section of users will also deliver what Web users
have long ached for: faster connections. Venture capitalists,
Internet executives and analysts agree that so-called broadband
connections _ high-speed Internet access through cable modems or
telephone digital subscriber lines _ will bring new possibilities
to e-commerce in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
   Broadband's arrival will be sped by the ever-increasing flow of
venture capital money, as companies that have seen huge returns on
their recent investments look for ways to reinvest in start-up
companies that focus on network technology.
</P>
<P>
   Some start-ups will be racing with established companies like
the AT&AMP;T Corp. and Qwest Communications International to build
digital links capable of carrying more data, while others will be
competing with the likes of Akamai Technologiesto move that data
more efficiently across the network.
</P>
<P>
   With faster connections, ``I think we'll see a real change in
the way consumers approach the Internet,'' said Matt Hyde, vice
president of online sales at Recreational Equipment Inc., which
sells outdoor gear. ``Since the Internet will always be on at home,
it ends up being used like an appliance. People will use it for
tasks as they come up through the day and evening.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Hyde said, people will be much more inclined to buy
commodity items like paper towels or bed linens as the need arises,
``because it'll be so incredibly convenient.''
</P>
<P>
   From an Internet retailer's perspective, high-speed access
``will close the gap between the physical and virtual when it comes
to touch and feel,'' Hyde said, ``because with broadband, retailers
can do a lot more with helping people see products and understand
what they're about.''
</P>
<P>
   In theory, Web sites will be able to overcome bandwidth and
speed constraints, and display products from every conceivable
angle, analysts said. Sites might also include interactive features
like voice recognition or personalized shopping assistants without
worrying about data traffic slowing to a crawl. But pessimists warn
that with so many more people flocking to the Web and using such
bandwidth-sapping technologies, network speed may not increase soon
enough to prevent data traffic jams.
</P>
<P>
   For some forecasters, the biggest e-tailing change will not come
from cable modems or superfast phone lines _ in fact, it will not
involve a PC at all. Wireless technology, analysts say, will take
the Internet outside the home and office and into a raft of new
devices that may, or may not, be related to today's cellular
phones, Palm Pilots and the like.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Walker, founder of Priceline.com, predicted that mobile
e-commerce ``will give people the ability to shop in the personal
time they have between doing things.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People will shop like they snack,'' Walker said. ``If you've
got 10 minutes, you'll look for a shirt, or you'll shop during a TV
commercial.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a behavioral change would require a revamping of e-commerce
sites, Walker said. Just as grocery stores were forced to create
express lanes for shoppers with time constraints, e-commerce sites
would need to create more features to let shoppers select and pay
for goods within 60 seconds. ``Retailers will have to adapt to the
time consumers say they have,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That assumes, of course, that consumers are doing business with
retailers in the first place. John Hagel, who leads the e-commerce
practice at McKinsey &AMP; Co., the management consultants, said that
consumers in the coming decade would increasingly do business with
what he called ``customer relationship businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   These businesses, he said, would be formed to serve as advocates
on behalf of buyers in their negotiations with sellers _ a sort of
union for consumers. These groups would not only provide buyers
with a wealth of information about what to purchase and at what
price, Hagel said, but they might also gather large numbers of
buyers together to effectively coerce sellers to cut their prices.
In the latter respect, these organizations would resemble two
current ``group buying'' sites _ Mercata and Accompany _ but with
much greater power in the marketplace, he predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The impact of e-commerce is to unbundle and re-structure
businesses,'' Hagel said. ``This is a prime example of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Nat Goldhaber, chief executive of Cybergold, a company that pays
consumers to respond to online advertisements, looks for
bricks-and-mortar shopping malls to ``go into very serious decline
and begin to disappear over the next 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   That hypothesis is drawn, he said, from the idea that consumers
will have ``a much more intimate relationship with manufacturers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dell Computer Corp. is the obvious example of this trend,
Goldhaber said, but he and many others in the industry expect more
manufacturers to follow suit. Meanwhile, traditional retail
shopping, he predicted, will lose its social function ``as people
use the Internet for the purpose of social interaction.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sort of a radical in this regard,'' he said. ``But no
matter how dramatic you think the Internet will change the world,
you're underestimating it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-12-19-99 1839EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
