<HEADLINE>
SOFTWARE EVOLVING INTO A SERVICE RENTED OFF THE NET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If 1999 was the year everyone started saying that Internet-based
software would replace conventional programs, 2000 will surely be
the year the transition begins in earnest.
</P>
<P>
   There are already signs of a major upheaval as the power and
accessibility of the Internet are harnessed to create software that
costs less, does more and is easier to use than today's programs.
Companies increasingly are managing some portion of their employee
communications and customer transactions over the Internet. In
homes, a 24-hour Internet connection is becoming common, and
consumers who might once have bought a calendar program now trust
their agenda to a Web site.
</P>
<P>
   As this trend takes hold over the next decade, shrink-wrapped
boxes of software on CD-ROMs or floppy disks will disappear, and
with them will go a business model based on selling a product.
Rather, software companies will make their money selling a service,
much like utilities sell electricity. Other software will be
invisible, embedded in a host of appliances that bear no
resemblance to a computer, much the way today's automobiles are
rich in processing power and software that the driver never sees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet creates an opportunity to change the way people
manage information technology,'' said Gary Bloom, executive vice
president of the Oracle Corp., the world's second-largest
independent software company. ``I believe nobody will be `buying'
software that they load on their machines. You will buy software as
a service, just the way you buy telephone service today. That is
something you could never do before Internet architecture came
along.''
</P>
<P>
   The world's largest software company, Microsoft Corp., is
finding itself under siege on this front, just as it maneuvers to
resolve the government's long-running antitrust case against it.
Linux, a free operating system created by a Finnish graduate
student, has emerged as a viable alternative to Microsoft's
Windows. And Sun Microsystems has begun offering a productivity
suite, StarOffice, free for the downloading, that is very similar
to Microsoft Office.
</P>
<P>
   Further, dozens of ``application service providers,'' or ASPs,
have sprung up to offer software over the Internet as a
subscription service, no downloading or installation required.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft and representatives of the government are currently in
their first round of settlement talks under Richard A. Posner, the
Federal appeals court judge who was selected as a mediator by the
trial judge, Thomas Penfield Jackson of federal district court.
Jackson found last month that the company had used its monopoly
power to stifle innovation, reduce competition and hurt consumers _
a finding that put considerable pressure on Microsoft to settle
within the next couple of months.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts generally believe that given the fast pace of
Internet time, any outcome will be either ineffectual or
irrelevant, because the market itself may eat at Microsoft's
dominance if the Internet software model takes hold with Microsoft
on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, analysts say the move to Internet-based software is
happening far more rapidly than the industry's last major
transition. That was the move, about 10 years ago, to client-server
architectures, in which tasks once performed by giant mainframes or
refrigerator-sized minicomputers were split between desktop
computers and servers distributed throughout an organization.
</P>
<P>
   That system proved unwieldy for many users, but it was a boon to
producers of business and accounting programs, so-called enterprise
resource planning, or ERP, software. Those makers include SAP,
Oracle and Peoplesoft, and of course Microsoft, whose Windows and
Windows NT programs are dominant.
</P>
<P>
   Tectonic technology shifts create openings for new leadership
companies, which is one reason investors have been rushing to back
companies, like Inktomi, that provide the software to creates the
Internet infrastructure for these programs. These companies are not
shy about proclaiming their role.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm absolutely convinced that the Inktomi architecture will be
the standard architecture of the Internet, and this architecture is
going to be the architecture of the enterprise as well,'' said
David Peterschmidt, Inktomi's president and chief executive. ``It
is not going to be the enterprise companies coming through the fire
wall to define the Internet. The Internet architecture is going to
go back through the fire wall to define the enterprise.''
</P>
<P>
   In one vision of the new era, the client _ the portion of the
software that resides on the user's desktop computer _ shrinks to
nothing more than a Web browser, which does not require anything so
powerful as a PC to operate. It can get by with a vestigial
operating system that the user never need see. Oracle has already
reworked its core database program and all its applications to work
this way, and many software start-ups are designing their products
in this manner.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle has also begun selling software this way, through its
Business Online unit. The Robert Mondavi Winery, for example,
manages its human resources using software running on servers at
Oracle, and Bloom said many small businesses were now opting to use
programs once intended for large corporations. ``A lot of the
start-up companies are starting out with enterprise-class apps from
the git-go,'' he said. ``If you plan on becoming a $5 billion
company, why start out with Quickbooks?''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Intuit, producer of Quickbooks, an accounting program
for small businesses, is also experimenting with renting software
services over the Web, although so far only with TurboTax, its
personal tax preparation program.
</P>
<P>
   Renting software rather than buying it will fundamentally change
the relationship between vendors and users, said Roger McNamee, a
partner in Integral Capital. ``The ASP model is about sharing risk
between vendor and customer,'' he said. The classic $30 million
client-server application put all the risk on the buyer, and buyers
were loathe to change, even if a program ran poorly because the
money was already spent. The return on investment for the buyer was
often negative, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The ASP model changes all that. ``The customer puts it in,''
McNamee said. ``If it works, they continue to pay for it. The
companies that are being optimized for this are the new start-ups,
like MarketSoft and Allegis.'' MarketSoft specializes in managing
sales leads, while Allegis' software is aimed at managing
relationships with partners.
</P>
<P>
   Even a traditional software company now finds itself in the
relationship business. Adobe Systems sells big graphics and
publishing applications, like Photoshop and Illustrator, that run
on a desktop and do not really lend themselves to electronic
distribution at current bandwidth levels. But Adobe also sees the
Web playing a greater role in its business.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-12-19-99 1824EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
