UNDATED: fresh parsley 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In large saucepan, combine stock, water, 1/4 cup oil, turmeric,
ginger and cinnamon and bring to boil. Gradually stir in couscous.
Cook, stirring, until liquid is absorbed, about 3 minutes. Stir in
cranberries, cover and let stand 15 minutes. Transfer to large bowl
and let cool to room temperature. Break up any couscous lumps with
your fingers. Stir in zucchini, carrots, scallions and garbanzo
beans.
</P>
<P>
   In small bowl, whisk lemon juice, remaining 1/4 cup oil, salt
and cayenne together. Pour over couscous salad and toss well. Cover
and refrigerate for at least 1 hour or as long as overnight. Just
before serving, taste and adjust seasoning. Garnish with chopped
parsley.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 276 calories, 10 grams fat, 41
grams carbohydrates, 7 grams protein, trace cholesterol, 115
milligrams sodium, 33 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``A Good Day for Salad,'' by Louise Fiszer and Jeannette
Ferrary (Chronicle, $17.95
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   1502: In the Gulf of Honduras, Columbus is given a drink of what
the natives call xocoatl (pronounced chocoatl). Quetzalcoatl, ``god
of the air,'' was thought to have come to Earth and taught men how
to cultivate various crops, including cacao trees. While waiting
for the god's return, his followers kept his memory alive with
rites employing chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   1519: One of explorer Hernando Cortes' men reports that Aztec
ruler Montezuma drinks 50 cups of cocoa a day, and that it is
believed to be an aphrodisiac.
</P>
<P>
   1532: A Franciscan friar writes the first full description of
vanilla in New Spain. The bean is the pod of an orchid and has been
mixed into cacao by the Aztecs.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   CHOCOLATE HAZELNUT CAKE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8
</P>
<P>
   4 eggs, separated
</P>
<P>
   1 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces unsweetened chocolate
</P>
<P>
   12 tablespoons (1 1/2 sticks) sweet (unsalted) butter
</P>
<P>
   1 cup plus 1 tablespoon cake flour
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons very finely ground skinned hazelnuts
</P>
<P>
   Hazelnut buttercream, recipe follows
</P>
<P>
   Chocolate icing, recipe follows
</P>
<P>
   8 whole hazelnuts, for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Beat egg yolks and sugar together until mixture is thick and
pale yellow.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in top of a double boiler set over simmering water,
melt chocolate with butter, whisking constantly until smooth; cool
slightly.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Grease an 8-inch springform pan.
Line bottom with a circle of wax paper. Grease paper and lightly
flour lining and sides of pan.
</P>
<P>
   Pour chocolate-butter mixture into egg mixture and stir just to
blend. Fold in flour, salt and ground hazelnuts.
</P>
<P>
   Whip egg whites until stiff and fold gently into batter.
</P>
<P>
   Pour cake batter into prepared pan and tap pan lightly on work
surface to eliminate any air bubbles.
</P>
<P>
   Set on middle rack of oven and bake for 35-40 minutes or until
edges are firm and inside is set but still somewhat soft. Don't
worry if top cracks slightly. Cool in pan, set on rack, for 1 hour.
Remove sides of pan and cool cake to room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   When cake is cool, invert it onto a serving plate and spread top
and sides with hazelnut butter cream. Refrigerate cake for 30
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Remove cake from refrigerator and spread top and sides with warm
chocolate icing. Work quickly, as icing sets.
</P>
<P>
   Decorate top of cake with eight whole hazelnuts. Refrigerate
cake for at least 1 hour before cutting and serving.
</P>
<P>
   Hazelnut butter cream:
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups shelled hazelnuts
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons corn syrup
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons brandy
</P>
<P>
   1 cup powdered sugar, sifted
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons sweet butter, softened
</P>
<P>
   Roast hazelnuts on baking sheet in a 350-degree oven for 10 to
15 minutes, or until their skins have loosened. Remove from oven
and rub between towels to remove skin.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer to bowl of food processor fitted with a steel blade and
run machine until nuts begin to form a paste, like peanut butter in
texture.
</P>
<P>
   Scrape paste into a bowl and stir in corn syrup and brandy. Let
sit for 20 minutes. This can be prepared in advance and
refrigerated. Let return to room temperature before proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   Cream powdered sugar and butter together until light and fluffy.
Add hazelnut paste and mix thoroughly.
</P>
<P>
   Chocolate icing:
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons sweet butter
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces semisweet chocolate
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons cream
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup sifted powdered sugar, approximately
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   Melt butter and chocolate together in top of a double boiler
over simmering water, whisking constantly.
</P>
<P>
   Remove pan from heat and beat in cream. Sift in powdered sugar
and vanilla. Icing should be very smooth. Spread while warm.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 850 calories, 58 grams fat, 85
grams carbohydrates, 9 grams protein, 187 milligrams cholesterol,
128 milligrams sodium, 61 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Silver Palate Cookbook,'' by Julie Russo and Sheila
Lukins (Workman, $9.95)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   618: The Chinese perfect a method of boiling down sugar cane to
make ``sand sugar.''
</P>
<P>
   1300: A French medical professor distills the first brandy.
</P>
<P>
   1453: Coffee is introduced to Constantinople by the Ottoman
Turks. Coffee has been popular in the Middle East for 100 years,
although many Muslim scholars disapprove because Mohammed didn't
drink coffee.
</P>
<P>
   1857: Louis Pasteur shows that a living organism causes the
lactic fermentation that spoils milk.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   COFFEE ROYALE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 1
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces hot coffee
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces brandy
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   Pour coffee into an Irish coffee glass. Add sugar and stir to
dissolve. Add brandy and stir. Pour the cream carefully over the
back of a teaspoon so that it floats on top of the drink.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 325 calories, 21 grams fat, 6
grams carbohydrates, 1 gram protein, 79 milligrams cholesterol, 24
milligrams sodium, 59 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Bartender's Bible,'' by Gary Regan (Harper Collins,
$12.95)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
