<HEADLINE>
EATING OUR WAY THROUGH THE MILLENNIUM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What's past is prologue for our millennium party. We're
celebrating with dishes that can be served at a sit-down meal or as
components on a party buffet. Their other commonality is that all
of these victuals have been around for centuries _ sometimes much
as we know them today, often in a much less evolved state.
</P>
<P>
   1070: Roquefort cheese first made in France. (Some historians
put the date 200 years earlier and say that Roman emperor
Charlemagne was a fan.)
</P>
<P>
   1493: Christopher Columbus finds papayas, tomatoes and
pineapples, cultivated for centuries from Paraguay to Panama, in
the West Indies.
</P>
<P>
   1493: Columbus plants sugar cane and cucumbers on Santo Domingo
(Hispaniola) with seeds from the Canary Islands.
</P>
<P>
   1522: New World tomatoes make their way to the Italian table via
the Spanish, who rule Naples.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   CHERRY TOMATOES WITH ROQUEFORT AND WATERCRESS
</P>
<P>
   Yields 24
</P>
<P>
   24 cherry tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon white wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces Roquefort cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons canola oil
</P>
<P>
   1 small bunch watercress, leaves coarsely chopped to yield about
1/2 cup, plus more for garnish
</P>
<P>
   1 small seedless cucumber, finely diced to make 1/3 cup
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon snipped fresh chives
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Using a serrated knife, slice about 1/8 inch from top of each
tomato. If tomato doesn't sit upright, trim a tiny piece from the
uncut side to create a flat bottom. (Don't cut off too much or the
filling will leak out.) With tip of a knife, gently loosen flesh
around inside of each tomato. Scoop out seeds with small melon
baller. The tomatoes can be prepared 1 hour in advance and kept at
room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   In food processor, combine vinegar and half of the cheese. Pulse
until smooth. Slowly add oil, blending until smooth and thick.
(Consistency will be thinner than mayonnaise.) Transfer mixture to
medium bowl. Stir in all but 2 tablespoons of the cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Just before serving, fold in watercress, cucumber and chives.
Season with salt and pepper to taste. Use a small spoon to fill
cherry tomatoes with mixture. Garnish with watercress leaves and
reserved cheese and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per tomato: 29 calories, 2 grams fat, 3
grams carbohydrates, 1 gram protein, 2 milligrams cholesterol, 47
milligrams sodium, 54 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Martha Stewart's Hors d'Oeuvres Handbook'' (Clarkson Potter,
$35)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   907: Mustard seeds are cultivated in China.
</P>
<P>
   1336: The Duke of Burgundy throws a banquet in Dijon, and guests
consume 300 quarts of the region's already-famous mustard.
</P>
<P>
   1607: Capt. John Smith of Jamestown, Va., writes that there is
such an ``abundance of fish, lying so thicke with their heads above
the water, as for want of nets ... we attempted to catch them with
frying pans.'' American salmon, much larger than the European
variety, swim up 30 North American rivers.
</P>
<P>
   1698: A Benedictine cellar master, Dom Pierre Perignon,
fine-tunes the champagne-making process by corking the sparkling
wine in heavy bottles to allow for a second fermentation. The
winched-in corks allow for the manufacture of the bubbles that give
champagne its effervescence.
</P>
<P>
   1756: One account credits Duc de Richelieu with inventing
mayonnaise by combining two egg yolks with 200 grams of olive oil,
the juice of half a lemon and a bit of salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   1912: German-American delicatessen owner Richard Hellman begins
packing his mayonnaise into glass jars. By 1927, he has
manufacturing plants in Chicago; San Franisco; Atlanta; Tampa,
Fla.; and Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   CELEBRATION CHAMPAGNE-POACHED SALMON
</P>
<P>
   Serves 12
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2- to 3-pound salmon fillet
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, mashed
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh dill, chopped, or 1/2 teaspoon dried dill
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup dry sparkling wine (blanc de blanc)
</P>
<P>
   Basil leaves, lemon slices and fresh dill sprigs, for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Assortment of bread slices, for serving
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Place salmon in casserole dish.
Combine next 5 ingredients and spread evenly over salmon. Pour 1/2
cup sparkling wine around the salmon. Bake for 20 minutes or until
glaze is golden brown.
</P>
<P>
   Line a platter with basil leaves. Place salmon in center of the
platter and surround with lemon wedges and fresh dill sprigs.
</P>
<P>
   This dish can be served warm from the oven or prepared the day
before, stored in the refrigerator and served chilled.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 204 calories, 13 grams fat,
trace carbohydrates, 19 grams protein, 57 milligrams cholesterol,
112 milligrams sodium, 59 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ Domaine Ste. Michelle
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   2900 B.C.: Workers at the Great Pyramid of Cheops at Giza are
fueled largely by rations of chickpeas, onions and garlic.
</P>
<P>
   1607: Sir Hugh Plat writes ``Certaine Philosophical Preparation
of Foode and Beverage for Sea-men,'' in which he names 12 foods and
medicines for sailors. He describes pasta as ``in the form of
hollow pipes, or wafers, called by the name macarone amongst the
Italian, and are not unlike (save only wantonely in forme) to the
coscos of Barbary.''
</P>
<P>
   1621: The Pilgrims celebrate the first Thanksgiving. It's not
certain if cranberries were part of the feast, but they were widely
eaten by the American Indians at that time. The Europeans called
them ``crane berries'' because of their appearance on the plant.
</P>
<P>
   1959: The FDA seizes a fraction of the cranberry crop because of
pesticide residue. Although only a minuscule amount of
contamination was found, consumers avoided cranberries that
Thanksgiving. Devastated by the loss (at the time, cranberries were
solely an autumnal dish) the cranberry industry began looking for
other outlets for its crops. That move led to cranberry juice and,
in the 1990s, craisins.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   COUSCOUS, CRANBERRY AND GARBANZO SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Serves 12
</P>
