<HEADLINE>
HOW SWEET! SWEET POTATOES MADE SMOOTH OR CRUNCHY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lots of requests answered this week.
</P>
<P>
   The first recipe is from the Food Network's ``Calling All
Cooks.'' The program was caught by a reader, but she didn't get the
ingredients written down by the end of the show. The second recipe,
for a similar dish, was sent in by Bettie Hausenfluke.
</P>
<P>
   MAMA LANE'S SWEET POTATO PUDDING
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1 egg
</P>
<P>
   2 cups grated sweet potato
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   Put all ingredients in a 5-by-9-by-2-inch baking dish. Bake in a
preheated 350-degree oven for 1 to 1 1/2 hours. Stir 2 or 3 times
to keep from burning. Bake until brown on top.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 336 calories, 8 grams fat, 62
grams carbohydrates, 4 grams protein, 56 milligrams cholesterol,
104 milligrams sodium, 22 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   CRUNCHY SWEET POTATOES
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8
</P>
<P>
   2 cups canned sweet potatoes, mashed
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   3/4 stick melted margarine
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   Mix ingredients together, put in casserole dish and cook 30-40
minutes at 300 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Topping:
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup crushed cornflakes
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped pecans
</P>
<P>
   3/4 stick melted margarine
</P>
<P>
   Mix and pour over baked potatoes. Cook 15-20 minutes at 300
degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 503 calories, 24 grams fat, 70
grams carbohydrates, 4 grams protein, 56 milligrams cholesterol,
334 milligrams sodium, 43 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   One from Southern Living: Anne Strayer found the requested
recipe for rice pudding from Southern Living's 1986 recipe
collection. It's credited to Sandy Hayes, Morristown, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   FRUITED RICE PUDDING
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup currants
</P>
<P>
   2 cups milk
</P>
<P>
   3-ounce package vanilla pudding mix
</P>
<P>
   2 cups cooked rice
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup pineapple preserves
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   Whipped cream, optional
</P>
<P>
   Pour enough boiling water over currants to cover; let stand 10
minutes. Drain and set currants aside.
</P>
<P>
   Combine milk and pudding in large saucepan. Cook over medium
heat, stirring frequently, until mixture boils. Remove from heat,
and stir in currants and remaining ingredients except whipped
cream. Pour mixture into a 1 1/2-quart serving dish; chill at least
6 hours or overnight. Serve with whipped cream, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 244 calories, 3 grams fat, 50
grams carbohydrates, 5 grams protein, 11 milligrams cholesterol, 85
milligrams sodium, 11 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   One from Luby's: Kelly Greene of Benbrook, Texas, sent in a
request for Luby's cranberry salad that is served this time of
year. This recipe is taken from the cookbook the company compiled
in 1996 to celebrate its 50th anniversary. The book is available at
the cafeterias for $9.95 and makes a terrific Christmas gift.
</P>
<P>
   LUBY'S CRANBERRY SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups water
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   12-ounce package fresh cranberries, see Note
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups cubed navel oranges
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup cubed red apple
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup banana slices
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped pecans
</P>
<P>
   Note: Buy extra bags of fresh cranberries and freeze them to
make this recipe year-round. When using frozen berries, it's not
necessary to thaw them.
</P>
<P>
   In medium saucepan, combine water, sugar and cranberries. Cook
over medium heat, stirring occasionally, just until cranberries
begin to open. Transfer to large bowl. Cover and refrigerate at
least 2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Fold in oranges, apple, banana and pecans. Cover and refrigerate
at least 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 211 calories, 1 gram fat, 52
grams carbohydrates, 1 gram protein, 0 cholesterol, 1 milligram
sodium, 6 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
