<HEADLINE>
LIKE KAUFMAN, `MAN ON THE MOON' CONFOUNDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Playing comedian Andy Kaufman, Jim Carrey pulls a Cheshire-cat
act in ``Man on the Moon:'' Everything about Carrey vanishes except
for his overbite. Detractors might call Carrey's performance a
stunt or mere impersonation, but it goes deeper than that.
</P>
<P>
   To see Carrey morph into Kaufman, the unconventional entertainer
from the late '70s and early '80s, is to see complete
transformation. But it's when Carrey takes on Kaufman's characters
_ the inept comedian ``Foreign Man,'' the obnoxious lounge singer
Tony Clifton, and, of course, Elvis _ that the depth and breadth of
the performance becomes clear. When those who remember Kaufman
forget that it's Carrey on screen, when the people who knew Kaufman
say that the resemblance is uncanny, that's when you know how much
Carrey has given himself to this role.
</P>
<P>
   Reportedly, Carrey remained in character 24-7 while he was on
the set, and that does seem excessive. But it's a sign of his
passion for this role, a passion that was so strong that the
in-demand Carrey was willing to audition _ and beat out actors as
strong as Nicolas Cage _ to play Kaufman. Passion, in fact,
surrounds this movie _ it's just not always there on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   It's tempting to speculate what the real-life Kaufman would have
thought of ``Man on the Moon'' and its attendant hype. For the past
couple of weeks, it's seemed like every time you turn on late-night
TV, someone connected to the movie was plugging it on a talk show
(who would have thought, when R.E.M.'s dense, seminal ``Murmur''
was released shortly before Kaufman died, that lead singer Michael
Stipe would spend the turn of the century shilling a major-studio
movie?). Kaufman might have been appalled at this commercialism,
but he was as much huckster as hoaxer, and he might have admired
the showmanship inherent in the buildup.
</P>
<P>
   But Kaufman's pranksterism would probably have led him to pull
the rug out from under the audience, defying expectations with,
say, two hours of Jim Carrey reading ``The Great Gatsby.'' Kaufman
was not afraid to be infuriatingly boring, if it meant being
unpredictable; ``Man on the Moon'' is never boring, but it can be
frustrating.
</P>
<P>
   If you're looking for the answers to what made Kaufman tick,
don't come here; director Milos Forman and screenwriters Scott
Alexander and Larry Karaszewski take an almost A&AMP;E Biography,
and-then-he-did-this approach to Kaufman's career. The movie's
beginning, a piece of minor brilliance with Carrey as Foreign Man
introducing the film, leads you to believe that wilder things will
be in store (this is one time that it will pay to show up on time
for a movie), but what follows is a more conventional film than
you'd expect from the writers and director of ``The People vs.
Larry Flynt.''
</P>
<P>
   Which may be wise; Kaufman was an enigma, and according to his
friend and co-writer Bob Zmuda's book ``Andy Kaufman Revealed!,''
even the people closest to Kaufman were never entirely able to
figure him out. Perhaps that's why the movie concentrates most on
Kaufman's career, downplaying his interpersonal relationships with
people such as Zmuda (''Saving Private Ryan's'' Paul Giamatti),
manager George Shapiro (Danny DeVito) and understanding girlfriend
Lynne Margulies (Courtney Love, in an underwritten role).
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many directors fascinated with pop culture, Forman is
interested in the phenomenon itself, and not in using it as a form
of ironic joke (Alexander and Karazsewski, who also wrote ``Ed
Wood,'' are his perfect kindred spirits). But in ``Man on the
Moon,'' he does more observing than interpreting. The movie has a
lot of the what of Kaufman's life, but not that much of the why _
not just the why of what drove him to bait audiences, but the why
of what drove audiences to swallow the bait, despite Kaufman's
sometimes obvious contempt. The buzz behind ``Man on the Moon''
will draw audiences to it, and Carrey's astonishing performance
will be their reward. But although they might leave it satisfied,
they'll leave it with more questions than answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man on the Moon'' is rated R for strong language, brief
nudity, sexual situations and male-female wrestling. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Film: Man on the Moon &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 1/2 on a 1-5 scale &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Director: Milos Forman &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stars: Jim Carrey, Danny DeVito &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Length: 118 min. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
