<SLUG> BC-CPT-NETWATCH21-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
MP3.com, Slate flourished during a notable Web year &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ End-of-the-year lists are as inevitable as death and
taxes. At the end of the century, it's a good thing the Web isn't
1,000 years old or even 10. This subjective list of 1999's notable
Web achievements won't make anybody think back further than
January.
</P>
<P>
   Upset of the year: MP3.com (www.mp3.com)
</P>
<P>
   It's just amazing how one Web site can single-handedly turn the
music industry upside down. MP3.com's extensive collection of
downloadable digital music, combined with the music industry's
initial reluctance to release music for sale via the Web, created a
demand for digital music that can no longer be ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Most improved player: Slate (www.slate.com)
</P>
<P>
   After so much hype, so many misfires and a failed subscription
plan, Slate has finally found its way in the online world. Its
thoughtful political coverage and stable of experienced writers
have transformed Slate from Microsoft's and Editor Michael
Kinsley's goofy hobby to a Web site actually worth reading. Expect
sparks to fly as election 2000 shifts into high gear.
</P>
<P>
   Best use of a chat room: Atlanta office worker ``Hey Y'all''
</P>
<P>
   While hiding under her desk in an Atlanta office building, Leigh
Frey signed on to the CNN current events chat room using the
pseudonym ``Hey Y'all.'' She used the chat room to get the latest
news about gunman Mark O. Barton's shooting spree in the Piedmont
Center office complex where she worked. Other chatters were
skeptical but provided needed information and words of
encouragement. Proof that community on the Web isn't just about
geeky teen-age boys looking for love.
</P>
<P>
   Best search engine that just searches: (www.google.com)
</P>
<P>
   It's just one page with a box to type in your query. No free
e-mail, no online shopping, no chat rooms, no message boards.
There's nothing to do here but search the Web, and the results are
good. You click, you search, you read. Portals are like, you know,
so five minutes ago.
</P>
<P>
   Best place to try and make a quick buck: eBay (www.ebay.com)
</P>
<P>
   From human body parts to souvenirs of the World Trade
Organization riots in Seattle, eBay proves that Web auctions are an
endless source of fascination, a great source for obscure
collectibles and an outlet for every scam artist around. EBay
catches most of them, but not before the media have a field day.
</P>
<P>
   Best example that two heads really are better than one _ and get
more attention, too: MindSpring/EarthLink, EarthLink/MindSpring
merger
</P>
<P>
   I say tomato, you say tomahto; however you look at it, it's
still going to be the second-largest Internet service provider
after behemoth America Online. With 3 million subscribers and a
prototype deal with AT&AMP;T for open access to cable lines, the
MindSpring/EarthLink combo may have extended the potential lifespan
of the ISP well into the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   Best candidate for induction into the Silicon Valley Boys Club:
CMGI President David Wetherell
</P>
<P>
   When Lycos tried to merge with Barry Diller and Ticketmaster,
majority stockholder Wetherell was there to quash the deal. He then
snapped up failing search engine AltaVista and reinvented it as a
shopping and services site, and he's not done yet. The
Massachusetts businessman proves you don't need offices in Palo
Alto to play the Web game and win.
</P>
<P>
   Best argument for holiday shopping at the mall:
</P>
<P>
   e-toys.com, Toysrus.com, kbkids.com. (tie)
</P>
<P>
   Not even little Cindy-Lou Who could save millions of online
shoppers from frustration, disappointment, out-of-stock items and
poor customer service. Why toy retailers were unprepared for one of
their biggest seasons of the year is a mystery they need to solve
before December 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Best online example that war is hell: The first-person accounts
of the war in Kosovo from Belgrade radio station B92
(www.freeb92.net)
</P>
<P>
   Many called the war in Kosovo the first Internet war as millions
of Bosnians took to their laptops and described the NATO bombing of
Belgrade. Their stories were often-chilling accounts of life during
wartime that won't be easily forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-12-20-99 1106EST &QL;
</P>
