<HEADER>
A6644 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CPT-EARLEY-COMPUTERS-     12-22 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-EARLEY-COMPUTERS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFESSIONS OF A RECOVERING NERD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(Eds: Kathleen B. Earley is president for data and Internet
services at AT&AMP;T.) 
 By KATHLEEN B. EARLEY with JULIA LAWLOR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   My husband says I've always been a workaholic. When I was a kid,
I worked all the time. I got 50 cents allowance, and in high school
I got a raise to $1 a week. That was not enough to get your big toe
into a movie theater. So I used to baby-sit a lot. In high school,
I became known for cleaning houses. I was a parking lot attendant
at the University of California at Berkeley. I also worked in the
dean's office. One summer I was accepted into a program that sent
80 students to Washington. Ninety-five percent of the students
ended up as unpaid aides to members of Congress. I was one of three
who had paying jobs.
</P>
<P>
   I attended Berkeley in the '70s, but I was never part of the
counterculture. I was one of those students who went to all their
calculus and accounting classes. Patty Hearst lived a block away
from me when she was kidnapped by the SLA. I paid no attention. I
didn't care about politics. The summer I was in Washington, Nixon
was impeached, and everyone had to explain to me what was going on.
I was an early-stage nerd.
</P>
<P>
   I have a bachelor's degree in accounting and an MBA in finance
from Berkeley. I am a very logical person, and those are extremely
logical subjects. But by age 25, I knew there was a lot more to
life than becoming just a financial person. I wanted to really
apply my skills in an area where I could keep learning. Even back
then, I knew that computing was going to be the future.
</P>
<P>
   I basically stayed in sales for the first 10 years of my career
at IBM. They did a great job of training me on the basics of
management. The biggest reward of being a manager is not making
quota or making your business plan _ those are just the minimum
requirements to keep your job. The best reward is to watch people
achieve their full potential.
</P>
<P>
   I continue to struggle with finding a balance in my life. I'm
very lucky, because my husband, Francis Reed, works at home. We
never had a nanny for our children, Deirdre, who is 13, and John,
who is 10. Francis has always taken the primary responsibility.
Still, I have long days, and I miss them growing up. If I see the
children at all, it's only in the morning. That's the price you pay
if you want a robust career.
</P>
<P>
   My husband and I are a great team, but still a lot of things
don't get done. This is not the ``Leave It to Beaver'' house. You
would never walk in our house and say, ``Isn't this beautifully
clean.'' We have a German shepherd; there are dog hairs, but it's
home.
</P>
<P>
   If there's a secret to my success, it's growing up in a family
of five girls. I was the fourth. My father had us mowing lawns,
painting rooms, changing the oil in the car. He started a girls'
softball league in the '60s _ I was an all-star first baseman. We
were sent to an all-girls high school. I was 18 or 19 before
someone intimated that I wasn't supposed to be doing something
because I was a girl. I never had any limitations placed on me.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-12-21-99 1704EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
