FTC MOVES AGAINST WEB-BASED PYRAMID SCHEMES &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Word to the con artists running illegal pyramid
schemes on the Internet: Halt.
</P>
<P>
   State and federal law enforcers Tuesday announced a crackdown on
scam operators who use new technologies to perpetrate old frauds.
The Federal Trade Commission said its staff, with the help of state
officials, has swept the Internet and found more than 600
potentially illegal pyramid sites.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcers have taken action against 23 sites so far, said
Paul Luehr, assistant director of the FTC's Bureau of Consumer
Protection. The FTC has made patrolling the Web a high priority
because illegal scams ``have the potential to take off so rapidly,
given the global reach of the Internet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the crackdown, the FTC earlier this month filed a
federal lawsuit to shut down 2Xtreme Performance International
Inc., a Dallas-based company that purported to sell nutritional
supplements. The company was using the Internet to help recruit
distributors to ``learn a guaranteed method to put $5,000 to
$10,000 in your pocket in tax savings each and every year for the
rest of your life.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials say the company used deceptive claims to
recruit consumers, who spent as much as $1,300 each to participate
in the scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Luehr said many con artists are using e-mail to lure victims and
glitzy Web sites to help persuade them of a scheme's legitimacy.
``What we're finding is that many programs are operating on and off
the Web, using info-mercials, telemarketing, e-mail and Web sites''
to build the appearance of legitimacy, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC advises consumers to learn the difference between legal
multi-level marketing plans and shady pyramid schemes. The former
are a way to sell goods or services through distributors.
Typically, these plans provide distributors with commissions from
their own sales, as well as from the sales of the people they
recruit to become distributors.
</P>
<P>
   Pyramid schemes have a similar structure, but focus on the
commissions earned for recruiting new distributors, not on the
selling of useful products or services. Such plans are widely
outlawed because they collapse when no new distributors can be
found, and everyone except for a few people at the very top of the
pyramid loses his or her money.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC offers these tips to protect yourself from a illegal
pyramid schemes:
</P>
<P>
   _ Be wary of plans that claim you'll make money through the
growth of sales made by distributors you recruit, not from sales
you make yourself.
</P>
<P>
   _ Beware of plans that ask new distributors to spend money on
high-priced inventory.
</P>
<P>
   _ Avoid plans that promise enormous earnings or claim to sell
miracle products.
</P>
<P>
   _ Beware of shills _ ``decoy'' references who the promoter pays
to describe fictional success through the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
