<HEADER>
A6655 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-VIDEO-RINGEL23-COX     12-22 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-RINGEL23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Funny thing: Comedians stand out no matter the genre
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The new movie on Andy Kaufman, ``Man on the Moon,'' reminds us
there are several different kinds of movies involving stand-up
comics. One is about stand-up; another stars a former stand-up in a
fictional setting; the third is a recorded stand-up act. Here are a
few examples:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Lenny'' (1974; R) _ Bob Fosse's biography of the late Lenny
Bruce puts something of a show-biz sugarcoating on the
controversial comedian's life and art, but Dustin Hoffman delivers
a stinging performance in the title role. Photographed in black and
white, which gives the film a kind of period grit, and surreally
structured with flashbacks, posthumous interviews, etc., the film
does manage to get across a good deal of the scabrous genius that
made Bruce a legend. Valerie Perrine, who plays his sex-kitten
stripper wife, Honey, brought a certain experience to the role;
previous to her movie career, she'd actually worked as a stripper
in Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Punchline'' (1988; R) _ Tom Hanks is a harried, driven
medical student and Sally Field is a harried, downtrodden
housewife. They meet in a class for stand-up comics where his style
is too hostile and hers is too wholesome. Each learns from the
other and, natch, they fall in love. The picture is saved from
terminal sitcom cutes by Hanks' dedication; he just won't let the
so-so material get the best of him. Social note: Six years later,
Field had ``aged'' from playing Hanks' love interest to playing his
mother in ``Forrest Gump.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Jerk'' (1979; R) _ Steve Martin made the switch from
comedy clubs to movie sets with this precursor to the ``Dumb and
Dumber'' genre of brain-dead comedy. Basically, it's the story of a
sucker (Martin) leaving home (the film's best gag: His parents are
black) to make it in the big city. One oddity: The original
director was to have been Mike Nichols, but Carl Reiner ended up
with the job.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Lady Sings the Blues'' (1972; R) _ Richard Pryor had made
maybe a half-dozen movies before critics applauded his daring
dramatic turn as Piano Man in this lush Diana Ross vehicle. The
singer-turned-actress plays the legendary Billie Holiday. Pryor's
role is essentially that of a victim-waiting-to-happen since he's
Holiday's main drug connection. Pryor loved the stretch into drama:
``Being a character, man, that makes me come alive. It's like being
in your conscious and your subconscious at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Richard Pryor Live on the Sunset Strip'' (1982; R) _
Possibly the most electrifying comedy concert ever recorded. The
title says it all: Pryor alive on the Sunset Strip. Praise the Lord
and smash the freebase pipe. Put together from two sold-out live
performances at the Hollywood Palladium, the film gives Pryor the
chance to transform himself into everything from a hungry cheetah
to Jim Brown. But the most harrowingly unforgettable bit is a
dialogue he has with his own pipe _ one of the most chillingly
accurate (yet hilarious) depictions of addiction you'll ever see.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Gilda Live'' (1980; R) _ Pure Gilda. Pure gold. Of the
original ``Saturday Night Life-ers,'' the guys had a lot easier
time breaking into movies than the women did. I guess Chevy Chase
just ``screamed'' romantic-comedy leading man while, well, what do
you do with a Gilda Radner? Gilda knew. She took her one-woman act
to Broadway, where it became a smash and Mike Nichols translated it
pretty much intact to film. A wonderfully funny 90 minutes and
without the Pryor rough-language factor.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Heartbeeps'' (1981; PG) _ Funny thing. You don't hear a word
about this in ``Man on the Moon.'' But yes, Andy Kaufman did make a
movie _ an embarrassing but somewhat sweet romantic comedy about
two robots (Kaufman and Bernadette Peters) who fall in love. What's
eerie about it is how absolutely conventional it is. You could rent
this one for the kids.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gillespie writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
