<HEADLINE>
ROCKIN' FASHION IS ON A ROLL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   How far rock 'n' roll and fashion have come together.
</P>
<P>
   During the '50s, Elvis Presley just wore what he wore: Bright
jackets, black pants, carefully coiffed hair. A generation of young
men followed suit, turning Presley's flair for dressing (which he
had long before the serious money started rolling in) into a
statement of independence and love for this weird young thing
called rock 'n' roll.
</P>
<P>
   During the '90s, Nirvana was the catalyst for thousands of
youngsters abandoning their lite-metal poodle-do's and spandex (and
Poison CDs) in favor of long straight hair, torn jeans and flannel
shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has played a fashion show, designers from Bob Mackie to
Jean-Paul Gaultier to Thierry Mugler regularly do stage outfits for
popular acts, and Tommy Hilfiger has sponsored tours. VH1 has its
own fashion awards show that features clothes and live bands, and
what a Juvenile or a Jennifer Lopez wears in a new video will be
seen on the streets within days, if not hours.
</P>
<P>
   It's been, as the famously unfashionable Grateful Dead put it, a
long strange trip _ from Elvis' off-the-rack look to Elton John's
outrageous costumes to Kiss' cartoonish metal/Kabuki outfits to
Prince's purple finery to Kurt's sloppiness. And those benchmarks,
and many others, are on view at New York's Metropolitan Museum of
Art via the ``Rock Style'' exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   Running through March 19 at the museum's Costume Institute,
``Rock Style'' is a summation of ``how much rock styles have
influenced fashion,'' according to guest curator Myra Walker, who
has been an associate professor of fashion history at the
University of North Texas since 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Walker went to New York to begin work on the exhibit at the
behest of Richard Martin, the Costume Institute curator.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knew I could do it and was very passionate about the
subject and rock 'n' roll,'' she says. ``I told him for years I
wanted to work on it.''
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit is divided into five sections: Poets and Dreamers
(including Bruce Springsteen and Janis Joplin); Icons (Elvis, the
Beatles); Brilliant Disguise (David Bowie's Ziggy Stardust); Rebels
(punks, Goths, heavy-metal fans); and High Style (Elton John,
Cher).
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of outfits have been assembled from public and private
collections, as loaners from the musicians themselves, and from the
Rock and Roll Hall of Fame and Museum, which helped organize the
exhibit. Among the performers whose clothes are featured are Elvis,
the Beatles, Elton John, Springsteen, Jimi Hendrix, Bono, Madonna
and Bjork.
</P>
<P>
   Walker grew up during the '60s and says that Joplin influenced
her style by putting together vintage and contemporary clothing, a
combination she says is coming back in vogue.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Rock Style,'' she says, is a true overview, and not
reflective of her style, except that ``my heart and soul and
passion is in it.''
</P>
<P>
   She also notes that the exhibit shows that at a certain point
rock and fashion became more important to each other; that ``line
of demarcation,'' she says, was Bowie, who carefully designed his
characters and their outfits, such as Ziggy Stardust, and took them
on tour.
</P>
<P>
   During the '80s, Madonna became a symbol to millions of teen-age
girls and young women, and she kept changing her wardrobe to fit
her music and her association with various designers. She, and
other stars of the MTV and post-MTV eras, have had a much more
immediate effect because of the proliferation of videos and music
on television 24 hours a day, something that was unthinkable before
MTV premiered.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this day and age people see imagery on their computer,
watching VH1, and on stations which cater exclusively to fashion,''
Walker says. ``There's definitely been a blurring of the lines.
Celebrities and pop singers go to some of the same designers and
you get a lot of exchange and see it on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   The show will journey to the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame and
Museum in May 2000 and will be on view there through Sept. 10.
After that, it will be at the Barbican Centre in London from Oct. 4
to Dec. 10.
</P>
<P>
   Walker will be the acting associate curator in charge of the
exhibit through December 2000, when she will return to Denton.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't a chronology of rock 'n' roll,'' she says.
``There's no possible way. But we've reached our major objective.
We've hit the high points.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
