<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-LAURA-INGRAHAM-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SHAPE OF POLITICS TO COME 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Campaign
Countdown commentary column) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Campaign
Countdown, a rotating campaign-commentary column written by former
Democratic vice-presidential candidate Geraldine Ferraro and by
MS-NBC host Laura Ingraham.)
 By LAURA INGRAHAM  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Political predictions have gotten me into trouble before. Yes, I
was one of those pundits who thought President Clinton wouldn't
make it through the winter of 1998.
 &HT;    But if public humiliation wasn't enough to make our
commander-in-chief resign, it won't stop me from making some
predictions for the new political year, as we raise our glasses to
America's accomplishments in the 20th century.
 &HT;    Here are five political trends to look for in 2000. Reminder:
past performance is not necessarily an indicator of future
prediction success. 
 -0- 
 1. FORGET NEW HAMPSHIRE AND IOWA  
 &HT;    Right now the media is desperate for a horse race in the
Democratic and Republican fields, and No. 2s Bill Bradley and John
McCain have done their best to make the 2000 presidential elections
interesting.
 &HT;    Yet, even if George W. Bush and Al Gore are beaten in New
Hampshire or win by only narrow margins in Iowa, they will clinch
the nomination in the primary states that matter on Election Day,
states such as California and New York.
 &HT;    The latest Field Poll shows that, despite all the McCain and
Bradley hype, the numbers in California have barely moved in three
months. Bush leads McCain in California 47 to 12 percent, and Gore
leads Bradley 44 to 17 percent.
 &HT;    California has 54 electoral votes, Iowa and New Hampshire
combined have 11.
 &HT;    Pop quiz: Who won New Hampshire's Democratic primary in 1992?
 &HT;    Answer: Paul Tsongas. Like Pat Buchanan, who won the GOP primary
there in 1996, Tsongas went on to get trounced on Super Tuesday.
 &HT;    Lesson: New Hampshire and Iowa are fun, quirky political states
with blocks of independent voters, but their primary and caucus
outcomes aren't likely to throw the frontrunners off stride. 
 -0- 
 2. THE IMPEACHMENT FACTOR  
 &HT;    Remember all those dire predictions about the re-election
prospects of House impeachment managers?
 &HT;    As usual, conventional political wisdom will turn out to be
wrong. Even those congressmen in tough races _ Jim Rogan, for
example, who represents a California district that includes Burbank
_ will be sent back to Washington for another term.
 &HT;    Last week a USA Today poll showed that the public attitude
toward the impeachment proceedings has shifted sharply against the
president. A year ago, only 35 percent of the public approved of
the House decision to impeach President Clinton. Today, 50 percent
say it was the right thing to do.
 &HT;    The same polls show that fewer people agree that the president
should have been acquitted in the Senate.
 &HT;    So much for legacy-building. 
 -0- 
 3. RUDY AND HILLARY  
 &HT;    In New York, coverage of the early jousting between likely
senatorial candidates Mayor Rudy Giuliani and Hillary Clinton
invariably points to a ``bruising'' campaign, with political
observers predicting that tough-guy Rudy will go bare-knuckles
against the First Lady.
 &HT;    Reality check: It won't be Giuliani taking off the kid gloves.
For the past 25 years, Hillary has been helping manage Bill
Clinton's political war rooms, which turned negative campaigning
into an art form.
 &HT;    Who can forget Clinton's relentless Mediscare campaign against
Bob Dole in 1996? And Hillary's February 1998 ``vast right-wing
conspiracy'' attack on the ``Today'' show is rightly seen as the
single event which helped turn the Lewinsky scandal against the
prosecutors.
 &HT;    Rudy can run on his record. But what is Hillary going to run on?
That's easy _ how Giuliani's policies are ``anti-children,''
``anti-family'' and ``anti-women.'' 
 -0- 
 4. ORDER IN THE COURT!  
 &HT;    After the Vermont Supreme Court's recent ruling in favor of
same-sex marriages and a federal district judge's permanent
injunction against Cleveland's school-voucher program, court
appointments will become a rallying issue for conservative voters.
 &HT;    This could redound to Bush's benefit, as Republicans see years
of legislative work go up in flames at the hands of judicial
activists who overturn the will of the people by fiat and engage in
social engineering to overthrow traditional American values.
 &HT;    But watch the gay and feminist coalitions mobilize on this one,
howling ``Bush will take away your right to choose!''
 &HT;    To which Bush might respond, ``No, that's what a liberal judge
in Cleveland did to all those low-income parents who had chosen to
opt out of failing schools.'' 
 -0- 
 5. IT'S FOREIGN POLICY, STUPID!  
 &HT;    National-security issues will be a focal point of the general
election, as George W. Bush tries to regain the political edge
Republicans had in foreign policy in the 1980s.
 &HT;    If the economy continues to hum, he will have to campaign on the
growing national-security threats posed by China's aggressive
military buildup, Russia's precarious domestic situation and
nuke-happy North Korea.
 &HT;    Bush can shake the lingering concern about his ability to lead
if he can make a strong case that the new wave of anti-American
sentiment around the world is the fault of fuzzy, misdirected
foreign-policy efforts under eight years of Clinton/Gore. 
 -0- 
 EXPECT THE UNEXPECTED  
 &HT;    The new year will give us a new class of political winners and
losers, and a new series of challenges that cannot be met by
economic prosperity alone.
 &HT;    One prediction is safe, though: Election 2000 will once again
turn conventional political wisdom on its head _ so buckle up and
enjoy the ride.
 c.1999 Laura Ingraham  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Laura Ingraham is a lawyer and the host of the MSNBC daily
program ``Watch It! With Laura Ingraham.'' She is the author of the
upcoming book, ``The Hillary Trap: Looking for Power in All the
Wrong Places,'' due from Hyperion in 2000.)
