<HEADER>
A6682 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-BUSH-CRASHADS-COX     12-22 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CRASHADS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush tests new 'crash ad' strategy
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In a new campaign tactic aimed at connecting
with local voters, Gov. George W. Bush is airing TV commercials
targeted to run during newscasts the same day the ads are produced.
</P>
<P>
   The concept, called ``crash ads'' by Bush strategists, is being
tested in New Hampshire, a key early presidential primary state
where Bush has dropped to second in the polls and fielded criticism
for not engaging in enough hand-to-hand politicking.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got a newsy feel,'' said Mark McKinnon, creator of Bush's
TV ad campaign. ``It's on tape, and it has the feel of real
immediacy. It communicates that he is there and working hard to
earn every vote.''
</P>
<P>
   McKinnon said he knows of no previous campaign that attempted to
get same-day ads on the air. Bush also has a set of more
traditional ads, filmed in advance and generally appropriate for
use in any state.
</P>
<P>
   The first crash ad was filmed Monday at a Bush campaign event at
a Manchester high school. The goal was to get it on the air during
Monday evening newscasts on the dominant local news station, but
McKinnon said it did not wind up airing until Tuesday morning
newscasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our objective is to try to get it as close to same day as
possible, within the constraints of the stations,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-second ad shows Bush, during his Monday speech, talking
about leadership and his tax-cut plan. The ad ends with words on
the screen that say, ``To be continued.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, after building huge leads in early New Hampshire polls,
now trails U.S. Sen. John McCain of Arizona. McKinnon said the
crash ads are not a response to criticism of Bush's New Hampshire
campaign efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The ads, he said, will help tell New Hampshire voters ``that we
are there, that we are working hard, talking to real voters and
answering real questions on topics of concern to New Hampshire
voters.''
</P>
<P>
   The new Bush ad is running on the same Manchester station, WMUR,
that also is airing an anti-Bush ad paid for by little-known
presidential contender Andy Martin, a frequent unsuccessful
candidate for political office in Florida. Martin was jailed last
year for contempt of court after a verbal assault on a judge.
</P>
<P>
   The ad alleges that Bush has used cocaine in the past, a charge
to which Bush has declined to respond on the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   ``George Bush had a cocaine problem. His brain suffered from
alcohol abuse. Don't trust Bush with your vote until he trusts you
with the truth about his past,'' Martin says on the ad.
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign spokesman Ari Fleischer dismissed the ad as ``an
unfortunate part of the nonsense that sometimes comes with
political campaigns.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course they are lies,'' he said of the allegations on the
ad.
</P>
<P>
   WMUR spokeswoman Julie Campasano, who handles media inquiries
about the station's advertising policies, said the station had to
run the ad.
</P>
<P>
   ``The law is the law,'' she said. ``The Federal Communications
Commission says clearly, a legally qualified candidate can say
whatever they want to say in their message, and we as a station
have no authority, permission or right to censor or otherwise edit
any of the spots.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
