r e BC-CENTURYINARTS-VISUALA     12-22 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENTURYIN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM PICASSO'S DEMOISELLES TO MAPPLETHORPE'S MEN
</HEADLINE>
 ARTS-VISUALARTS-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANDREW MARTON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Till year's end, the Star-Telegram brings you a
subjective look at the top 10 moments of the century in the arts.
Today: Visual Arts &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1907: Pablo Picasso's ``Les Demoiselles d'Avignon'' debuts. It
heralds the arrival of a colossal artist who will stand astride
almost the entire century, introducing the world to myriad
movements, from cubism to collage art.
</P>
<P>
   1909: A 48-painting exhibition in Paris of Claude Monet's
``Water Lilies'' constitutes, to that date, the most successful
contemporary art exhibition in history, presaging future
blockbuster shows.
</P>
<P>
   1910: Sigmund Freud publishes an essay, ``The Childhood of
Leonardo da Vinci,'' in which he attempts a psychological
deconstruction of the painter's work. This essay ushers in heavy
psychological interpretation as a valid form of criticism in art
writing over the next 90 years.
</P>
<P>
   1913: At a drafty space in New York, the Armory Show (which
eventually travels to Boston and Chicago) gives eager Americans
their first look at European modern art, including the
impressionists, post-impressionists and cubists _ from Claude Monet
and Henri Matisse to Vincent van Gogh and Constantin Brancusi.
Viewers are shocked and critics outraged by Marcel Duchamp's ``Nude
Descending a Staircase.''
</P>
<P>
   1929: New York's Museum of Modern Art opens, becoming a capstone
to the previous openings of Washington, D.C.'s Phillips Gallery and
the Barnes Collection in Pennsylvania. MOMA's debut also spurs the
opening of the nearby Metropolitan Museum of Art's modern
collection. All of it signifies that museums finally consider
contemporary art worthy of its own exhibition space.
</P>
<P>
   1937: The ``Degenerative Art Show'' opens during the highly
vitriolic, bigoted days of Adolf Hitler's Third Reich. In this
dyspeptic exhibit that toured most of Germany, such classic German
artists as Max Ernst, and Ernst Ludwig Kirchner, along with
Picasso, Marc Chagall, Paul Klee and Wassily Kandinsky, were all
held up to ridicule for their sacrilegious style and subject
choices. The effect of this negative exhibition was to consolidate
support for modern art and make it synonymous with opposition to
Hitler's totalitarian nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   1952: In the publication ``Art News,'' an essay by the critic
Harold Rosenberg introduces the term ``action painting'' with
reference to the work of Jackson Pollock. Pollock's style becomes
the groundbreaking prototype of art in which painting is the record
of a physical act. Pollock would later take on cult status with his
other moniker, ``Jack the Dripper.''
</P>
<P>
   1964: American hybrid imagist Robert Rauschenberg shocks the
cognoscenti by winning the Venice Biennale. This garrulous ``bad
boy'' artist almost single-handedly legitimizes modern abstract
art.
</P>
<P>
   1978: The opening of the touring show ``The Treasures of
Tutankhamun'' at New York's Metropolitan Museum of Art puts art on
the same plane as any sprawling mass-cultural event. The age of the
blockbuster art show dawns and will lead to unprecedented sums of
money spent at auction for such fashionable artists as van Gogh and
Monet. Collecting the new masters becomes the ultimate expression
of money well spent.
</P>
<P>
   1989: The controversy surrounding Robert Mapplethorpe's
photographs, some of which are deemed to be homoerotic,
single-handedly opens up the knotty debate about government funding
and art censorship. As the century draws to a close, the
Mapplethorpe dispute still focuses attention on what is ``good''
and ``bad'' art, and who should support it.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
