<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Locate hard to find items
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Having trouble finding a particular item? We'll try to
help you locate it. But due to the volume of mail, we cannot track
down every request. Readers whose queries are answered in the
column will receive a blue-and-cream canvas Buyer's Edge tote bag.
Write us at Buyer's Edge Find It, Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302; e-mail us at
buyersedge(at)ajc.com (please include your name, the city you live
in and daytime phone number); or call 404-582-7642.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am looking for clove stick candy. We used to have it around
Christmas time.
</P>
<P>
   _ Verna Zicafoose,
</P>
<P>
   Decatur
</P>
<P>
   And another sweet request: I am looking for a Peco Flake Pie.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bob Thomas, Roswell, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: Sweets for the sweet. We found these treats at the Market
Grocery Co. in the State Farmers Market, 16 Forest Parkway,
Building K. (404-361-8620). A 12-ounce box of Clove Stick Candy
(above), from the Piedmont Candy Co., is $1.59. A 6 1/2-round Peco
Pie (below) _ made of sugar, corn syrup, peanuts and coconut _ is
$1.19.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Stephenson is general manager of Market Grocery Co., which
sells primarily to wholesalers but also to the public. The store,
set in an industrial-type warehouse, is open 8 a.m-5 p.m.
Mondays-Saturdays. It stocks everything from canned goods, frozen
items and candy to cheese, meats and eggs. Most items are sold in
bulk, but you can buy individually. Stephenson accepts cash,
MasterCard, Visa and business checks but no personal checks.
</P>
<P>
   Directions: Take I-75 south to Exit 78 (Ga. 331 East/Forest
Parkway/Farmers Market). Merge onto Forest Parkway. Take a left at
the entrance to the State Farmers Market. At the first stop sign,
take a right and drive until you reach Building K.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've been collecting Celestine Sibley's books, but I don't
have all of them. Do you know where they can be bought or ordered?
</P>
<P>
   _ Ann House, Rome, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: The Atlanta-Journal Constitution columnist's books have been
selling briskly since her death Aug. 15. Trying to track down
copies can be difficult. Four Sibley books are available in local
bookstores: 1964's ``Christmas in Georgia'' (Doubleday, $14.95);
1970's ``Mothers Are Always Special'' (Doubleday, $12.95); 1997's
``The Celestine Sibley Sampler'' (Peachtree Publishers, $19.95);
and 1997's ``Atlanta's Half Century With Furman Bisher and
Celestine Sibley (Longstreet, $20).
</P>
<P>
   The other books have proven a bit more elusive. But here are a
few sources that have copies of the hard-to-find titles. At Aspen
Books in Stone Mountain (404-296-5933), owner Paul Blicksilver says
he has a waiting list for Sibley books. But he adds, ``I have many
dealers across the country who send me books daily.'' The owner
stresses ``patience.'' At the Book Review in Marietta
(770-971-1103), owner Tom Brennan has a few titles. And A Cappella
Books on Euclid Avenue (404-681-5128) stocks some of the
hard-to-find titles. The Book Shop in Brunswick (912-262-6708) is
also a source. Or go online and try www.bibliofind.com or
www.amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am a huge Sinatra fan and have been looking for what seems
like forever for his Christmas record that he recorded with his
family in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   _ Martin Miller, Alpharetta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: The Sinatra clan, including Frank and kids Nancy, Frank Jr.
and Tina, first recorded ``The Sinatra Family Wish You a Merry
Christmas'' on vinyl in 1968. But it has been unavailable to fans
for more than 25 years. Now for the first time, daughter Tina,
through Artanis (Sinatra spelled backward) Group, has released a
24-karat gold CD from the original master tapes. It's $20.99 at
Tower Records-Video-Books, 3400 Around Lenox Drive N.E.
(404-264-1217). Hits include ``It's Such a Lovely Time of the
Year,'' (Nancy), ``Santa Claus Is Comin' to Town,'' (Tina), ``Some
Children See Him'' (Frank Jr.), ``The Christmas Waltz'' (Frank) and
``The 12 Days of Christmas'' (entire family).
</P>
<P>
   Q: My mother and best friend purchased waterless cookware about
30 years ago. They both have sets that need to be replaced. I
wonder if you have any idea where to find more.
</P>
<P>
   _ Connie Ware, Marietta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   And another cookware question: In the 1980s, I purchased a set
of stainless steel cookware from Townecraft, through in-home sales.
I want to replace a broken handle on one of the pans but have been
unable to locate the company.
</P>
<P>
   _ Joyce Alexander, College Park, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: We went online for your requests and found www.conterra
</P>
<P>
   .com/ehp, a site for Eastern Home Products Cookware. Distributor
Ben Manley sells SteamControl waterless cookware, which refers to
minimum moisture cooking. The pots and pans (above) are made from
surgical stainless steel, not aluminum, and will retain their
gleaming appearance. A 17-piece set is $399. You can order online
or call 1-800-646-6633.
</P>
<P>
   The addresses of other cookware companies, including Townecraft,
are also listed on this Web site at www.conterra.com
</P>
<P>
   /ehp/other.htm. Some major names and addresses: Ekco, 9234 W.
Belmont Ave., Franklin Park, IL 61031 (847-678-8600); Regal Ware,
1675 Reigle Drive, Kewaskum, WI, 53040-2133 (414-626-2121);
Townecraft, 1 Deboer Drive, Glen Rock, NJ 07452 (1-800-977-7687)
and Vollrath, 209 Vollrath Drive, Gallaway, TN 38036
(901-867-2951).
</P>
<P>
   Note: In a recent column, we told where to find medical alert
bracelets. Reader Dan Dooley of Lawrenceville, Ga., wrote to tell
us about the MedicAlert Foundation in Turlock, Calif. This
organization keeps its members' computerized medical files on
record 24 hours a day, seven days a week, for medical personnel.
It's $15 a year, and the first year's membership is included in an
initial $35 registration fee.
</P>
<P>
   To join, you can register online at www.medicalert
</P>
<P>
   .org. Or call 1-800-432-5378. You can also write to Medic Alert,
2323 Colorado Ave., Turlock, CA 95382. Medical alert bracelets are
also available from the foundation and range from $35 to $75.
</P>
<P>
   _Contributing: Michelle C. Brooks and Richard L. Eldredge
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
