<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-GLITCHES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Y2K GLITCHES LIKELY TO OCCUR JAN. 3 AND BEYOND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Assuming the United States makes it through New
Year's weekend with few Y2K-related computer glitches, it doesn't
necessarily mean Y2K will be a non-event.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, most Y2K problems likely won't reveal themselves until
Monday, Jan. 3 when millions of Americans return to work and
school. Some Y2K experts think such glitches will continue popping
up throughout the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing to test systems before the year 2000 and it's
another thing to test them on Saturday (Jan. 1) to see if they are
running,'' said John Koskinen, the White House's Y2K czar. ``The
real test will be on Monday when...millions of transactions and
events take place as they normally do.''
</P>
<P>
   Norm Dean, the executive director of the Washington, D.C.-based
non-profit Center for Y2K and Society, believes the ``majority of
events related to Y2K will occur Jan. 3 and beyond.''
</P>
<P>
   Koskinen said there's no way to predict when Y2K-related
problems might occur but did agree that many of them won't become
necessarily become apparent on Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's highly unlikely anybody's lights or telephone are going
to go off immediately,'' Koskinen explained. He said it would
likely take a whole series of computer problems to build up before
it causes a large system to malfunction or shut down.
</P>
<P>
   While key systems in the United States like telecommunications
and electric power are expected to continue to function normally on
Jan. 1 and beyond, Koskinen said power failures could occur in
undeveloped countries beginning in early January.
</P>
<P>
   And the United States won't be immune to problems even though
the federal government and major private industries from airlines
to telecommunications have tested and re-tested their computers to
properly read the digits ``00''. If computers that contain
date-sensitive chips in them read ``00'' as the year 1900, they may
malfunction and potentially disrupt everything from air travel to
the systems that run the electric power supply.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Koskinen nor Dean predicts any large national or
regional Y2K problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we'll see planes fall out of the sky or
widespread power outages,'' Dean said. ``But there are going to be
problems in specific areas...that could affect a number of
people.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said most of the nation's one million non-profit
organizations have done nothing to address Y2K issues, which could
affect the services they provide to millions of Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Potentially causing headaches for millions more Americans is the
fact that many small businesses have done to nothing to prepare for
Y2K. The National Federation of Independent Businesses reports that
1.5 million businesses are simply taking a wait-and-see approach to
see if cash register, security or refrigeration system fails when
they open their doors on Jan. 3 after being closed for the holiday
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The only problem is that businesses may not be able to find
someone to fix their failed systems in time to keep them from going
bankrupt. Many small doctors' offices and hospitals haven't made
sure their billing systems will be able to request payments from
the federal government's Medicare and Medicaid systems and private
insurers _ problems that won't begin occurring until the end of
January.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having a computer break down in January may not affect a small
business or its employees until later in the year,'' Dean said,
explaining that employees likely won't lose their jobs on Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   A failed small business could affect a larger firm it made
something used by the large company. Those problems likely won't
crop up until the end of January or later.
</P>
<P>
   Koskinen said other Y2K problems might also surface later in
January or toward the end of the first quarter in March when the
first bills with 2000 dates on them are sent out. Last week some
water customers in West Des Moines, Iowa, for example, received
bills with a due date of Jan. 3, 1900.
</P>
<P>
   (Jennifer Corbett Dooren Name can be reached at 202-298-6920 or
at the e-mail address jennifer &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
