<HEADER>
A6705 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-COLLEGE-APPLICATI     12-22 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COLLEGE-APPLICATIONS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLINE APPLICATION FORMS ADD TO COLLEGE ADMISSION FRENZY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By LISA GUERNSEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A few years ago, applying to college meant staring at blank
forms, fighting with the typewriter, applying liberal amounts of
white-out and _ after proofreading those precious pages for the
20th time _ packing them in 8-by-11-inch envelopes and sending them
through the U.S. Postal Service.
</P>
<P>
   This year, for more students than ever before, that ritual is
history. As deadlines loom this month, an increasing number of
college-bound students are sitting in front of computers, filling
in blanks on digital applications, crossing their fingers and
clicking the button that says Submit. Xap.com, a company that
develops online applications, reports that more than 100,000
applications have been processed through its computers in the last
two months. The University of California system, which created its
own Web forms, has drawn nearly 19,000 online applicants this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what students are expecting and demanding,'' said Chris
Munoz, associate provost for enrollment management at the
University of Dayton in Ohio, a college that received almost 50
percent of its applications via the Web last year. So far this
year, Munoz said, 68 percent of applications have arrived online.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of other colleges are offering Web-based applications,
too. About 77 percent of colleges now provide online applications,
according to a November survey of more than 400 admissions offices
by the National Association for College Admission Counseling.
Nearly three-quarters of those offices said their systems allowed
applications to be sent over the Web. Others can be downloaded and
then printed or saved to a disk, which can also be mailed to
admissions offices.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Angenend and Lauren Bogue, seniors at St. Agnes Academy
in Houston, raved about online applications. They said that in
addition to having avoided the trouble of finding a typewriter,
they had had the benefit of software that filled in rote
information _ name, address and Social Security number _ after they
had entered it once. ``It's so much more efficient,'' Ms. Angenend
said.
</P>
<P>
   That efficiency, which most students tout as the best part of
applying online, may be playing a role in a larger trend _ the
tendency of students to apply to more schools, especially if they
are aiming for selective institutions.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, many guidance counselors say, high school seniors
with good grades typically applied to four, five or six schools. In
recent years, the counselors have seen the same type of students
send applications to at least eight schools, if not 10.
</P>
<P>
   The increase in applications should primarily be attributed to
the intensely competitive college admissions process, many
admissions counselors and consultants say. Statistics from the
National Center for Education Statistics project that the number of
high school graduates next spring will be the largest since 1983,
and the percentage of students going to college _ 66 percent last
year _ is at record levels.
</P>
<P>
   Although some colleges are planning to respond to the influx by
admitting more students, most Ivy League colleges and other
selective institutions say they intend to maintain their class
sizes. That means more students competing for the same number of
slots. ``There is a frenzy,'' said Debbie Skelly, a guidance
counselor at St. Agnes.
</P>
<P>
   To compensate, students who hope to attend selective schools say
they are applying to more top-tier colleges and more backup schools
than they originally planned. In many cases, they credit the
technology with making it possible.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Angenend, for example, is applying to 11 schools. Three of
them _ Texas A&AMP;M University, Tulane University and the University
of Pennsylvania _ did not offer electronic versions of the honors
applications she wanted to submit, so she filled out the forms by
hand. Harvard University had no online option for submitting the
application, so she downloaded the application, which she plans to
fill out on a computer, print and send through the mail.
</P>
<P>
   But the Internet played a major role in Ms. Angenend's decision
to apply to the other schools, she said, including Boston College,
Bowdoin College in Maine, the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology, Stanford University and Rensselaer Polytechnic
Institute in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had not considered applying to MIT before I realized that
they had an online application,'' Ms. Angenend said. Bowdoin,
Boston College and Rensselaer also became options only after she
found she could apply to them electronically. After painstakingly
filling in three paper applications and writing essays by hand
(like most of her peers, Ms. Angenend does not own a typewriter),
Ms. Angenend decided she was spending too much of her time trying
to cramp her handwriting into the forms' little lines. She said she
cringed at the thought of completing many more without the
assistance of software.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Walther, a senior at Lafayette High School in
Williamsburg, Va., also attributed several of his college choices
to the fact that the schools offered applications online. When he
first started looking at schools, he went to Web sites for the
University of Florida and Florida State, where he discovered he
could apply online. He did, finishing the applications (which
didn't require essays) in less than 20 minutes each. A few days
later, he said, he found that the University of Maryland at College
Park had an online application, too _ one that would enable him to
save his work and come back to it later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't planning to apply to College Park,'' Walther said.
``But I did it in just two afternoons.''  &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Application fees, of course, deter most students from submitting
dozens of forms online. Fees range from $15 to $65, and most Ivy
League colleges charge at least $50. But Bernice Munsey, an
educational counselor in Arlington, Va., said many parents are
starting to see those costs as minuscule compared with the price of
tuition and the importance of getting into a good school. ``The
most common parent comment I get,'' Ms. Munsey said, ``is, What's a
few more dollars for a few more applications?''
</P>
<P>
   Such comments make some admissions officers wonder whether a
combination of anxiety and technology may spur an influx of
applicants who are less than serious about attending. But in many
cases the swelling ranks of applicants are cause for cheer, they
say: After all, colleges like to brag about their selectivity. The
more applications they get, the more they can reject. And the
higher their selectivity, the better chance they have of landing a
coveted spot in annual college rankings, which use those
selectivity numbers in their ranking formulas.
</P>
<P>
   Many admissions officers say it is too early to tell whether
online applications will have any significant impact on college
selectivity. The number using technology is clearly increasing,
they say, but the majority of applicants still use paper. Some do
not have Internet-connected computers at home. Other high school
seniors are choosing to fill out some, if not all, of the forms on
paper _ even if they have the means to go online.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Chan, a senior at Clements High School in Sugar Land,
Texas, is an example. He is filling out some forms by hand and
printing others onto paper with the best quality he could find.
``I've paid attention to every detail,'' said Chan, whose first
choice is Brown University. ``I'm trying to stand out any way I
can.''
</P>
<P>
   But some schools _ like Virginia Tech in Blacksburg, Va. _ tell
students that they would actually prefer applications to be
completed over the Internet. A few, like the University of Dayton,
have even waived the application fee for those who use the Web.
Some graduate schools, like the Sloan School of Management at MIT,
will accept only applications sent online.
</P>
<P>
   Guidance counselors predict, too, that students may become more
inclined to take the technological route as the admissions season
comes to a close. Walther of Lafayette High School, for example,
envisions doing more online applications when January deadlines
have passed and nervousness kicks in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely see myself going through the Web and finding all
the ones that have February deadlines,'' Walther said. ``If I can
do it in an afternoon, why not have five more schools to get
into?''
</P>
<P>
   HOW-TO SITES
</P>
<P>
   The fastest way to find college application forms online is to
go to college Web sites. Nearly every college in the United States
has created an online admissions area by now, and many of them
include forms customized for their institutions. The most advanced
applications can be filled out and submitted over the Internet;
others are available online but must be downloaded to your computer
and then printed or saved to a disk.
</P>
<P>
   If you are a classic procrastinator and have not yet made your
college choices, you may want to browse lists of schools that offer
online applications. Several college-oriented companies are happy
to oblige. Many of them require you to set up an account first,
usually by providing at least your name, your e-mail address and a
password. Here are a few to get you started:
</P>
<P>
   APPLY: www.review.com
</P>
<P>
   Software created by the Princeton Review enables students to
download applications that automatically include basic information
they provided upon registering. The company has customized
applications for nearly 700 colleges.
</P>
<P>
   EAPPLY: www.collegequest.com
</P>
<P>
   Offers electronic versions of two standard types of applications
accepted by more than 1,000 colleges, about 100 of which can be
submitted via the Web. Created by Peterson's, a publishing company
known for its college guidebooks.
</P>
<P>
   COLLEGENET: www.collegenet.com
</P>
<P>
   Provides customized online applications for more than 400
undergraduate colleges, as well as graduate programs.
</P>
<P>
   EMBARK.COM: www.embark.com
</P>
<P>
   Offers customized online applications for more than 300
undergraduate colleges, as well as graduate programs.
</P>
<P>
   XAP.COM: www.xap.com
</P>
<P>
   Creates online applications for consortia of private colleges or
multicampus universities in California, Illinois, Massachusetts,
Texas and Wisconsin. In New York, almost every public and private
college is part of the system, which can be entered by going to
NYMentor.edu.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
