<SLUG> BC-CIR-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROUBLESOME ATTACHMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(Eds.: Please note that the word AT in parentheses has been used in
the final graf instead of the symbol, which is non-transmittable to
some newspaper systems.) 
 (af)  
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I often get attachments with an ``.exe'' file extension sent
to me by e-mail, and I can never get them to open. Is this a
problem with my Macintosh, or does this type of file get easily
corrupted?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The files you have been receiving are in a format that does
not work on the Macintosh operating system. The .exe extension you
see at the end of the file name stands for executable file, and it
is commonly found on Windows and DOS systems. The program icons for
Windows applications represent executable files.
</P>
<P>
   An executable file that is small enough to be sent by e-mail can
be anything from a bit of desktop animation to a small, compact
program. While the code these files are written in does not
generally work on the Macintosh, it is possible to view the the
files if you have software that lets you emulate Windows, or a
hardware PC card installed.
</P>
<P>
   While executable files can be helpful or fun to distribute among
friends, they are also a choice place for rogue programmers to hide
computer viruses. Computer users on any platform should be
extremely careful when downloading and opening file attachments,
and it is important to keep your antivirus software up to date.
</P>
<P>
   A good list of antivirus information links can be found at the
Federal Computer Response Capability site
(www.fedcirc.gov/antivirus.html). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
mail to Questions, Circuits, The New York Times, 229 W. 43rd St.,
New York, NY 10036-3959 or by e-mail to QandA(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
