<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6710 &Cx1f; ttj-z
i l BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV2     12-22 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV26-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAXES, TRADE RISE AS DANGEROUS ISSUES FOR DEMOCRATS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Dec. 26)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Al Gore and Bill Bradley will continue into the new
year sparring over their opposing education and health care
initiatives, each trying to convince voters that his proposals
would be best serve the American people.
</P>
<P>
   But while they are jockeying for position on those issues, two
other concerns _ taxes and trade _ pose real dangers to the
candidates as they race toward the Iowa caucuses, the New Hampshire
primary and the Democratic presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The tax assault will be launched against Democrats by the
Republicans, and the trade dispute will be fought within the
Democratic Party itself.
</P>
<P>
   No matter which presidential hopeful wins the Republican
presidential nomination, he will be armed with a tax reduction plan
as a major campaign weapon. It may be George W. Bush's excessively
large cut in taxes ($483 billion over five years), John McCain's
more modest reduction or one of the flat-tax plans advanced by
Steve Forbes or Gary Bauer.
</P>
<P>
   Whichever plan is offered by whichever candidate, it will force
the Democratic nominee to go on the defensive.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Bradley argue that the budget surplus, which remains
something of a novelty after decades of red ink, should be used to
support better education and expanded health care along with
protection of the environment.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Gore has asserted that Bradley would have to raise
taxes to pay for his proposed health reforms and Bradley has denied
it. But Gore himself has promised to balance the budget each year
he is in the White House, a goal almost impossible to achieve if
taxes are cut massively or if the nation suffers a deep recession
that decreases tax revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, in the first election of the 21st century, the two parties
will be facing off over an issue that has divided them in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, who traditionally oppose big government and federal
solutions to problems, argue for reduced taxation and the return of
revenues to those who paid them: the taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, on the other hand, would use the surplus to shore up
programs that they consider vital to the rearing of children, the
well-being of the poor and the elderly and the conservation and
protection of natural resources. In the fall, Bill Clinton vetoed a
tax cut approved by the Republican-controlled Congress that would
have slashed revenues by nearly $800 billion over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The second issue is far more baffling because free trade is a
policy favored by presidential candidates in both parties, since
Patrick Buchanan finalized his divorce from the GOP. But the issue
is far more divisive for Democrats than for Republicans, who before
World War II proudly proclaimed their belief in high protective
tariffs.
</P>
<P>
   Echoes from the chaos that greeted the World Trade Organization
on the streets of Seattle earlier this month continue to
reverberate through the Democratic Party and weaken its historical
alliance with organized labor and environmentalists. Delegates,
American government officials and Seattle residents will not soon
forget the putrid stench of tear gas that permeated the atmosphere
between Lake Washington and Puget Sound.
</P>
<P>
   It is true that anarchists turned a peaceful demonstration into
violence. But that was not difficult to accomplish with thousands
of protesters gathered to object to the WTO's closed-door meetings.
The dissidents contended that delegates at those meetings supported
the exploitation of natural resources and of children and poor
people toiling in depressing working conditions for little pay.
</P>
<P>
   Free trade is actually a tremendous boon to the economies of the
United States and its trading partners. Instead of limiting
commerce through stringent high protective tariffs, which
protectionists advocate, free trade makes it possible for America
to sell its products everywhere in the world because foreign
countries can sell their wares here.
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle uprising, however, made it clear that reforms are
required to win the trust of the people and to provide greater
equity between trading partners and the workers who make the
products that are sold.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who hosted the Seattle session, was accused of caving
in to unionists and environmentalists when he told delegates that
the people who were demonstrating in the streets should be
represented at the bargaining table.
</P>
<P>
   Writing in the Washington Post, former Secretary of State Henry
Kissinger said that ``instead of assuming the mantle of President
Truman's leadership role in inspiring the structure of the
post-World War II world, Clinton decided to play to the gallery.''
</P>
<P>
   Kissinger added that ``Clinton could have used the occasion to
put forward a farsighted program for dealing with what portends to
be one of the gravest challenges of the new century: the huge gap
between the sophistication of the dominant economic model called
globalization and traditional political thinking still based on the
nation-state.''
</P>
<P>
   It is true that Clinton sounded like a typical Democratic ward
healer when he recommended that the demonstrators' protests be
heard at the conference table.
</P>
<P>
   But, in doing so, he may have provided working men and women
some hope that reforms can be achieved.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats cannot back away from free trade without committing
flagrant hypocrisy. They were identified with the issue in the 19th
century and every one of their 20th century presidents, from
Woodrow Wilson to Clinton, has been a free trader. So, oddly
enough, has every Republican president since Dwight D. Eisenhower.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
