<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6712 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r b BC-COOKIESFORSANTA-TEX     12-22 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COOKIESFORSANTA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SANTA WILL LOVE THESE, AND SO WILL YOU
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JUNE NAYLOR RODRIGUEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The custom of putting out cookies for Santa is sugary sweet in
theory, but has anyone ever explained how to make homemade cookies
practical?
</P>
<P>
   Here's an idea: You make the batter, then let the kids make the
cookies while you fiddle with another task. So what if some are
lopsided or a bit burned? They'll have fun.
</P>
<P>
   Here are five recipes perfect for Santa or for taking to your
neighbor's Kwanzaa or New Year's party. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COOKIE-CUTTER COOKIES
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 to 8 dozen
</P>
<P>
   2 cups butter, softened
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   4 egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons vanilla
</P>
<P>
   4 1/2 cups unbleached flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Make dough by creaming together butter and sugar with a mixer.
Add egg yolks and vanilla, mixing well. Sift flour and salt
together and beat into butter mixture until well-blended. Chill
dough.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Roll dough out onto lightly floured
board to thickness of a half-inch. Cut with cookie cutters and bake
on ungreased cookie sheet, 1 inch apart. Do not brown. Remove from
cookie sheet while still warm, and cool on sheets of waxed paper.
Decorate with crushed peppermints, red hots, red sprinkles,
chocolate minichips, tiny silver-ball candies or frosting from a
tube.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Christmas From the Heart of the Home'' by Susan Branch
(Little, Brown, 1990) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SNOWBALLS
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2 1/2 dozen
</P>
<P>
   1 cup butter, softened
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 cups sifted flour
</P>
<P>
   1 cup finely chopped walnuts
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces Hershey's Kisses
</P>
<P>
   Powdered sugar, for dusting
</P>
<P>
   Cream butter and sugar well. Add flour, then walnuts. Form dough
into disk shape, then wrap in plastic. Chill at least 1/2 hour.
Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Remove foil from Kisses and insert one
inside a ball of dough, 1 inch in diameter. Make sure each Kiss is
completely covered by dough. Repeat until all dough and Kisses are
used. Bake on ungreased baking sheet for about 12 minutes, until
just cooked through. Sift with powdered sugar while still warm.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Christmas From the Heart of the Home''
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTMAS WREATHS
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2 dozen
</P>
<P>
   36 large marshmallows
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup butter
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon green food coloring
</P>
<P>
   3 1/2 cups cornflakes
</P>
<P>
   1 package candy red hots
</P>
<P>
   Over medium heat, melt marshmallows and butter together. Stir in
vanilla and food coloring. Fold in cornflakes and mix well. Drop by
tablespoons onto waxed paper. Working quickly with buttered
fingers, form into little wreaths. Decorate with candies. They will
firm as they cool. _ ``Christmas From the Heart of the Home''
</P>
<P>
   ESPRESSO CHOCOLATE COOKIES
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 dozen
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 package (12-oz.) semisweet chocolate chips
</P>
<P>
   3 squares (1 oz. each) unsweetened chocolate
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup butter
</P>
<P>
   1 cup plus 2 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   3 eggs
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons instant espresso powder
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Mix flour, baking powder and salt
in a small bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Melt half the chips, unsweetened chocolate and butter in top of
a double-boiler, stirring until smooth. Beat sugar, eggs and
espresso on high speed in bowl until ribbony, about 3 minutes. Fold
in melted chocolate. Stir in flour mixture and remaining chips.
</P>
<P>
   Drop batter, 1 tablespoon per cookie, 2 inches apart on
ungreased cookie sheets. Bake in 350 degree oven 12 minutes, until
puffed and crackly. Cool slightly on sheets, then transfer to racks
to cool.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Family Circle: Holiday Cakes &AMP; Cookies,'' December 1999
</P>
<P>
   RASPBERRY ALMOND SHORTBREAD COOKIES
</P>
<P>
   Makes 3 dozen
</P>
<P>
   Cookies:
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup butter, softened
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon almond extract
</P>
<P>
   2 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup raspberry (or blueberry or blackberry) jam
</P>
<P>
   Glaze:
</P>
<P>
   1 cup confectioners' sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons almond extract
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 teaspoons water
</P>
<P>
   Beat sugar, butter and extract in a large bowl until light and
creamy, about 3 minutes. On low speed, gradually beat in flour
until dough forms. Cover and chill at least 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Shape dough into 1-inch balls.
Place 2 inches apart on ungreased cookie sheets. With thumb, make
indentions in center of each ball and fill indentions with 1/4
teaspoon jam.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in 350 degree oven 14 to 18 minutes, until lightly browned.
Cool on rack.
</P>
<P>
   Whisk together sugar, almond extract and water in small bowl
until smooth. With a teaspoon, drizzle in thin ribbons over
cookies.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Family Circle: Holiday Cakes &AMP; Cookies''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-22-99 1645EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
