<BODY>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Thursday, Dec. 23, 1999. The N.Y. Times News Service
night supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Ramallah, West Bank) _ Despite speculation that
the resumption of Israeli-Syrian talks would derail the Palestinian
peace track, significant progress appeared to have been made by
early Wednesday morning in an intimate meeting here between Prime
Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat. It was
the first time that an Israeli prime minister had ventured into a
Palestinian-ruled city for a peace meeting, which in itself broke a
barrier in the relationship. And the setting was very casual: Barak
and Arafat met in the elegant home of the Palestinian leader's
second-in-command. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   SRILANKA-ELECT (Colombo, Sri Lanka) _ Gulping back tears, a
white bandage on her right eye from a bomb attack four days ago,
Sri Lanka's president claimed Wednesday a divine mandate to pursue
and defeat the rebels who had tried to kill her. ``These are the
wounds of sheer naked and unadulterated hatred of man for man,''
she said, her voice quavering. She called for peace, but she also
vowed ``the strongest possible action'' against the ethnic Tamil
separatists if they persisted in their 16-year insurgency. It was
victory day for President Chandrika Kumaratunga, who won a second
term in office with what, by Sri Lankan standards, was tiny
electoral majority of 51.2 percent. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   LONDON-MAYOR (London) _ Giving Londoners the right to choose
their own chief executive would strike most people as a long
overdue exercise. But the campaign for the first directly elected
mayor of this city of 8 million residents has caught British
politicians unaware and ill-prepared, with embarrassing
consequences all around. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   TERROR-CLINTON (Washington) _ President Clinton urged Americans
on Wednesday to be vigilant for possible terrorist attacks over the
holiday season but assured them that authorities were looking out
for their safety and they should enjoy themselves as usual.
(Summary from wires) By David Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   TERROR-SEATTLE (Seattle) _ Ahmed Ressam is indicted by a federal
grand jury here, charged with making false statements to U.S.
Customs, smuggling nitroglyceryn, transporting explosives,
possessing unregistered firearms and carrying explosives during a
felony. By Sam Howe Verhoverk.
</P>
<P>
   NJ-POLICE-PROFILING (Trenton, N.J.) _ The U.S. Justic Department
has forced New Jersey to accept an independent civilian monitor to
assure that its police force end racially discriminatory practices
like profiling. (Summary from wires) By David Kocieniewski.
</P>
<P>
   NEWYEAR-SITTERS (Undated) _ On New Year's Eve, many of the
1,000-some couples attending the Memphis Junior League's charity
ball at the Peabody Hotel will bring their children along. So the
parents can be free to cavort, they have coralled 40 of the Annie's
Nannies agency's adult baby sitters. They will pay the sitters $330
each, or $33 an hour for the 11-hour affair and triple the agency's
usual rate. So it will be in most big cities and their affluent
suburbs this New Year's Eve. Teen-age baby sitters stand to earn
$200 or $300 for one night's work and adults up to $400, or more
than the tab for many a partygoer's duck and champagne. By Peter T.
Kilborn.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-SENATE-RACE (Syracuse, N.Y.) _ Three days before Christmas _
and nearly 300 days until Election Day _ the race for U.S. Senate
exploded in an exchange of recriminations on Wednesday, with New
York City's Mayor Rudolph Giuliani asserting that Democrats were
conspiring to discredit him and Hillary Rodham Clinton suggesting
the mayor was consumed by an anger that could undercut his
effectiveness as a U.S senator. By Adam Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENES-INSERT (Undated) _ Scientists in Oregon report they
have developed a technique that might eventually be used to create
monkeys with added human genes, allowing those genes to be
investigated for potential treatments for human diseases. But the
scientists say they are acutely aware that their research, in which
jellyfish genes were installed in monkey embryos, raises a host of
uncomfortable questions about reproductive technology. By Gina
Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MIDAS-FEAST (Undated) _ Dirty dishes and drinking cups found
in a tomb in Turkey have given archaeologists revealing chemical
clues to what ancients considered a feast fit for a king, perhaps
the King Midas of history and the legendary golden touch. Everyone
dined on barbecued lamb or goat in a spicy stew with lentils. They
washed this down with a potent mixed drink of grape wine, barley
beer and honey mead. Judging by the size of the three huge bronze
cauldrons, the reservoirs of drink, a good and not very sober time
was had by all. By John Noble Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
</TEXT>
