<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMIC-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY MIXES WITH JOKES IN A COMIC'S PERFORMANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By SUSAN KARLIN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a darkened theater in Edinburgh, Scotland, an audience
watches a tall, gaunt man in an oversize top hat videotape himself
on stage, then train the camera on his spectators, and finally
project all the footage on screen _ all the while issuing slightly
offbeat pearls of wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stephen Hawking is often mistaken for an idiot,'' the
performer says in a clipped British accent. ``People with physical
disabilities are often mistaken for having mental ones as well. In
a similar way, athletes are often asked their opinions.''
</P>
<P>
   The people in the audience laugh, some of them nervously. The
comic remains stoic, stares into the lens. and says, ```How
self-indulgent is this?' he asks the audience as he films himself
with a camera uttering nonsense.''
</P>
<P>
   He cuts to the audience for a reaction shot. Then an image of an
exclamation point is superimposed over the video for emphasis. Then
back to our host. ``If you've never read a book in your life,'' he
says, waiting a beat, ``I suggest you keep your mouth shut.''
</P>
<P>
   The performance is punctuated by live synthesized music and
one-liners sung in operatic style by a woman in a Viking hat. Every
so often, for no apparent reason, a backstage camera picks up an
actor in a rubber monkey headmask blinking quizzically into the
lens.
</P>
<P>
   This is the surreal, hypnotic, digital world of Simon Munnery,
32, a London-based comic and computer expert. It's a theatrical
experience that creates live television on stage, while poking fun
at our obsession with it.
</P>
<P>
   The show, aptly titled ``The League Against Tedium,'' was a
success this past year at the Melbourne Comedy Festival, London's
West End and the Edinburgh Arts Festival. After another eight-week
West End run at London's New Ambassador Theater beginning Jan. 28,
the show's next stop may be New York (the details are still being
negotiated).
</P>
<P>
   What makes Munnery's show so inventive is how he integrates
technology into his comedy. Behind the simple stage set is an
orchestra of wires and laptops, which he conducts through software
he has written for this project. The effort is a result of his
dozen years knocking about the London comedy scene and two decades
of computer tinkering.
</P>
<P>
   ``Comedians speak through a mike,'' he said in an interview.
``So why not a camera? Just as a mike amplifies a voice, a camera
amplifies a face. It's simply another medium to express the
comedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Complementing the backstage camera are two additional ones
mounted on a wooden sword that Munnery holds during the
performance. The sword is furnished with six buttons linked via
radio remote control to a backstage laptop with a 250-megahertz
processor and 64 megabytes of RAM. The computer links to a
projector that flashes the finished ``show'' on the screen _ a
standard rear projection screen or sometimes just a sheet _ which
the audience watches alongside Munnery's performance. The comic
switches from camera footage to digital effect _ essentially
creating a rough cut of that evening's performance as it happens.
</P>
<P>
   Munnery's perpetually percolating imagination constantly
reinvents the show. In the months since the Edinburgh run, Munnery
has added a ``mouthcam,'' a small camera mounted on a bicycle
helmet that reaches in front of his face and enables extreme
close-ups of his lips and teeth. He has also programmed a computer
keyboard to call up images and sounds, rather than letters and
numbers, which he wears around his neck like a guitar.
</P>
<P>
   For all the skill required to master both the show's comedic
timing and technogadgetry, Munnery takes an earthy, unpretentious
approach to his art. A shy, thoughtful manner counters his manic
stage persona. He creates television but rarely watches it. He
writes software but does not have his own Web site. Rather than
hold auditions, he simply cast his friends. And when it comes to
advancing his vision, he relies more on instinct than calculation.
``I don't know where I'm heading,'' he says. ``But I know I'm on
the right path.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
