<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-GRAMM-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        TEXAS TRADE ROUTES ARE UNDER FUNDED, GRAMM SAYS
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Alex Canizares  
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Dec. 22 - Texas Sen. Phil Gramm says increased trade
across the Texas-Mexico border has put a strain on the area's
infrastructure, and he is pushing the Federal Highway
Administration to spend money on repairing highways and roads used
for international trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the North American Free Trade Agreement has been an
unmitigated success, communities along the Southwest border and
those along the trade routes in Texas have been unfairly burdened
with massive increases in resulting traffic and congestion,'' the
GOP senator said in a letter to Transportation Secretary Rodney
Slater last week.
</P>
<P>
   The administration will decide early next year how to allocate
about $140 million in congressional money set aside to improve
border highways and trade-critical routes around the nation. Gramm
authored the five-year $700 million program, which began last year.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Texas received $14 million - only 10 percent of this
year's $140 million given out nationwide. These levels pleased
Texas Transportation Commissioner David Laney, who called it a
``significant boost'' in May.
</P>
<P>
   But Gramm feels $14 million is not enough, and said the
administration is ``shortchanging'' the border with insufficient
funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at the burden that Texas is put on by NAFTA, 10
percent is not on par,'' said Gramm spokeswoman Kathy Dempsey on
Wednesday. ``There are not enough roads, and a lot of those roads
need improvement.'' The Texas Department of Transportation has
asked the federal administration for $126 million next year out of
that $140 million.
</P>
<P>
   According to Gramm, truck traffic in Texas has grown 19 percent
in three years as of May 1998, much of it due to higher trade with
Mexico. By 2012, traffic volume could nearly double on Interstate
10 and on U.S 59, Gramm said. That route will form the basis for
the proposed new highway, Interstate 69, Gramm said last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Dept. of Transportation is requesting money for next
year for 28 border and trade-related projects. Among the more
expensive projects the department would use the money for are: a
$75.8 million plan to upgrade two city and county roads in the West
Laredo trade corridor; $39.6 million to be used to widen the U.S.
83 freeway in Hidalgo County from four to six lanes; $29 million to
widen the U.S. 77/83 freeway in Harlingen through San Benito from
four to six lanes.
</P>
<P>
   If the projects are not funded or are only partially funded,
Texas transportation officials might look elsewhere for money, such
as federal loans under the State Infrastructure Bank, said Mark
Cross, spokesman for the Texas Department of Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   The border's highways struggle to compete for state funds,
because other projects in the state with heavier traffic take
priority, Cross said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
