<HEADER>
A6732 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TALES-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT     12-22 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TALES-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ONE DAY'S PERFECT WEATHER': TALES WITH A PREVIOUS LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes at end of review.) 
(nk) 
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perhaps more intellectually stimulating than emotionally
satisfying, the seven stories in Daniel Stern's new collection,
``One Day's Perfect Weather: More Twice Told Tales,'' are
nevertheless engaging and entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, a funny situation arises in ``A Man of Sorrows and
Acquainted With Grief,'' which the author notes as inspired by
``The Passion According to St. John,'' by Johann Sebastian Bach.
Kraft, a New Yorker exiled in Texas, where he conducts a small-town
high school orchestra, gets so worked up over this Bach music on
his rental-car stereo that he finds himself driving 90 mph.
</P>
<P>
   When he tries to explain this to the trooper who flags him for
speeding, the man asks him if the words are ``some kind of
Jewish.'' Kraft tries to translate, throwing in ``He was despised
and rejected, a man of sorrows and acquainted with grief,'' which
of course is actually from ``The Messiah.''
</P>
<P>
   The trooper asks Kraft to step out of his car, embraces him,
saying ``You're my brother _ my brother in Jesus,'' and demands
that he come with him to the local precinct to describe to his
friends how he was ``blinded by the light.'' The resulting
complications mix up Kraft's existence entirely.
</P>
<P>
   And instantly intriguing is ``Duet for Past and Future,''
inspired by Robert Frost's poem ``The Road Not Taken,'' about a
lawyer who goes to a concert in Indianapolis and thinks he
recognizes the cello he once played professionally and ended up
selling to pay his way through law school.
</P>
<P>
   What Stern is up to here is the same thing he did in his
previous two books, ``Twice Told Tales'' and ``Twice Upon a Time,''
which was, as he writes in his introduction to the present volume,
to take ``a text by a writer of the past whom I loved'' and make it
``basic to a fiction; as basic as a love affair, a trauma, a house,
a mother, a landscape, a lover, a job or a sexual passion.''
</P>
<P>
   He continues, ``I believe that, with or without knowing it,
regardless of the level of our education or our reading, all of us
carry within us, in more or less complex degree, the basic thrust
of Kafka, Melville, Frost, Freud and all the other great authors
who have become the very intellectual and spiritual air we
breathe.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Stern credits Nathaniel Hawthorne and Jorge Luis Borges
as his inspiration for such bridge building, as he calls it, he
might have added that some of the best-known works of the 20th
century, like Joyce's ``Ulysses,'' Eliot's ``Waste Land'' and
Pound's ``Cantos,'' were similarly inspired. Their creators, too,
like Stern, felt the weight of past literature pressing down on
them.
</P>
<P>
   The way Stern's technique works in these stories is really in
three different ways. A given work inspires the subject of each
story, as, for instance, Frost's poem ``The Oven Bird'' prompts
``The Taste of Pennies,'' about a man, Lee Binstock, who has had to
give up playing the clarinet because he has been punched in the
mouth during a traffic altercation.
</P>
<P>
   The story then weaves into its plot the work that inspired it:
Binstock gets a note recommending ``The Oven Bird'': ``You should
read it _ we should all read it.'' It comes from a man about to
commit suicide. When Binstock reads the poem and learns what
Frost's bird is saying with his song _ ``The question that he
frames in all but words/Is what to make of a diminished thing'' _
he takes it to be a message inviting him to kill himself, too.
</P>
<P>
   Finally the story reflects in various ways the meaning of the
work that inspired it. At the end of ``The Oven Bird,'' Binstock
realizes that what the poem is really saying is that you have to
make the most of your diminished state. Binstock and his wife
decide to celebrate their lives by making love and eating a big
breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   In other stories Stern plays wittily with the inspiring work's
meaning. ``Duet for Past and Present'' allows its protagonist to
rediscover in effect the road he failed to take long ago when ``two
roads diverged in a yellow wood.'' In ``Questions and Answers,''
inspired by Yeats' visionary poem, ``The Second Coming,'' a student
cheats on a test in which the poem is the subject and than seduces
her teacher to prevent him from reporting her. After the student
leaves, the telephone rings _ we don't know why _ in the apartment
where the teacher is sleeping, and the story ends with the teacher
counting the rings. Is it the ``rough beast'' of Yeats' poem
slouching toward Bethlehem to be born?
</P>
<P>
   In the strongest piece of all, ``A Philosopher's Honeymoon,''
inspired by Wallace Stevens' poem ``The Man on the Dump,'' the
meaning of the story merges with the meaning of its inspiration.
Abrams, ``a rabbi on the run,'' wakes up from a drinking binge and
finds himself on ``the dump just outside the town's limits,''
Abrams himself ``just barely inside his own limits: of drink, of
loss, hope, fatigue.'' As a Sunday morning sermon to three other
derelicts at the dump he reads a poem, ``The Man on the Dump,''
from a book he has unsuccessfully tried out on his temple's women's
reading circle, ``The Palm at the End of the Mind: Poems by Wallace
Stevens.''
</P>
<P>
   Puzzling out its meaning as the expression of ``a poet tired of
used things, fed up with living on the dump of old, received
images,'' he breathes out the last line of the poem: ``Where was it
one first heard of the truth? The the.'' He wishes he had pencil
and paper so that he could write ``a story based on a poem as he'd
wanted to do for months, maybe years.'' It would end with ``the
passionate stuttering search for the moment'' one ``first heard of
the truth, the stuttering search for the the, the the, the the the
the the the the the the the the the the the the the the the the.''
</P>
<P>
   But while the weight of past literature may reduce the rabbi to
stuttering, Stern uses it as a practicer of jujitsu might. He
absorbs the force of ``old, received images'' and spins them into
his own truths fluently and without ever falling down.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `ONE DAY'S PERFECT WEATHER: More Twice Told Tales'
</P>
<P>
   By Daniel Stern
</P>
<P>
   202 pages. Southern Methodist University Press. $19.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
