<HEADER>
A6743 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROV     12-22 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-art-ADV09-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., JAN. 9, 2000. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 Copyright 2000 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I often use boards of miscellaneous widths for my projects
because I buy hardwood that is not standard in dimension.
</P>
<P>
   When I want to saw such a board in half lengthwise I am often
dealing with an odd or awkward fraction that is very hard to divide
exactly _ if I want both halves to be exactly the same width.
</P>
<P>
   An old-timer once told me that there is an easy way to do this
with an ordinary ruler, but I forgot how. Can you help?
</P>
<P>
   A: Use a ruler that is several inches longer than the width of
the board and place it diagonally across the edges of the board as
shown in the illustration.
</P>
<P>
   Position the ruler so that one of the inch marks is exactly on
one edge of the board, and then swing the ruler so that another of
the inch marks is at the opposite edge.
</P>
<P>
   Then make a line or mark on the board that is precisely
alongside the half way mark on the ruler (half way between the
numbers on the ruler that are lined up with the edges of the
board).
</P>
<P>
   This will accurately indicate the center of the board.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We are planning to install some room air conditioners in our
upstairs corner bedrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Does it make any difference whether we install them on the side
of the house that faces toward the north or the south?
</P>
<P>
   A: When there is a choice, installing an air conditioning unit
on the side of the house where it will get the least amount of sun
is generally more efficient _ at least if the unit will be run
during daylight hours (at night it will make little difference).
</P>
<P>
   However, you can accomplish the same thing if you will put up
some kind of awning to shade the outside of the unit, or if there
is a large tree nearby to shade it from the sun.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I want to replace the aluminum wire mesh in my old screens
because there are numerous tears and holes in the mesh.
</P>
<P>
   I was told it is easier to replace this screening with
fiberglass or plastic mesh, but I notice that the old screen wire
is held in place with a plastic strip that is pressed into a
channel along the edge of the frame.
</P>
<P>
   How do I get this out so that I can install the new fiberglass
screening in the same way?
</P>
<P>
   A: The plastic strip or spline that holds the mesh in place is
simply pressed into the channel on top of the wire.
</P>
<P>
   To remove it you simply pry it out with a screwdriver or knife.
Don't worry about tearing or breaking it _ you can buy new spline
by the foot at hardware stores and home centers.
</P>
<P>
   After this has been removed, strip off the old screening then
replace it with the new mesh.
</P>
<P>
   To install the new mesh use one of the special rollers that are
sold for this purpose. Use it to press the new spline into the
channel on top of the mesh.
</P>
<P>
   Cut each piece of mesh a couple of inches oversize (in length
and width) to permit pulling it tight before you push the spline
down into the channel on top of the mesh.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Some of the dry-wall nails in our house have started to come
out in a few places.
</P>
<P>
   Can you tell us why this is happening and what we can do to
repair this damage?
</P>
<P>
   A: When nails work loose on gypsum board it is usually because
either the wrong kind of nails were originally used or because the
beams or studs have warped as the house settled.
</P>
<P>
   To repair the damage drive a dry-wall nail or screw in a couple
of inches above or below the ``popped'' nail and set its head
slightly below the surface without tearing the paper facing.
</P>
<P>
   The old nails can then be either pulled out or driven all the
way in, after which both nail holes can be covered with joint
cement.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Drawing captioned ``USING A SLANTED RULER TO DIVIDE
BOARD'' goes with this column.
</P>
<P>
   CAPTION: Placing a ruler diagonally across a board will make it
easy to locate exact center of board.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 2000 Bernard Gladstone &QL; 
 &UR; Distributed by New York Times Special Features &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
