<HEADER>
A6748 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-TOYSTORY-GAME-NYT     12-22 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-TOYSTORY-GAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVIES AND GAMES: SO ALIKE, SO DIFFERENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (bl)  
 By J.C. HERZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Years ago, when society at large became aware of product
placements in films, we invented a game called ``Spot the product
placement,'' wherein the audience would try to deduce contractual
arrangements between Hollywood and Corporate America. Of course,
there were some obvious hints outside the theater. Fast-food and
packaged good promotions were dead giveaways. But in the end, every
product on screen was suspect. It changed the nature of the
moviegoing experience in a subtle but irrevocable way.
</P>
<P>
   Video games do the same thing. In thousands of darkened theaters
screening ``Toy Story 2,'' for instance, there are two kinds of
people in the audience: the ones who play video games and the ones
who don't. And they see different things on the screen. For
nongamers, ``Toy Story 2'' is about a kidnapped cowboy doll, his
fellow toys' rescue attempt and the importance of friendship, with
some clever cultural references and jokes thrown in.
</P>
<P>
   For gamers, ``Toy Story 2'' is a preview of what they can do at
home on their PCs, Playstations and Nintendo 64s. It's a tasting
menu of environments to explore in greater depth with a keyboard or
a joypad. There is no question in their minds that this movie is
going to be a video game, and that the film itself was informed by
interactive media. The light on their faces is cinema. But what
they see is the skeleton of a game, and that changes the nature of
the moviegoing experience.
</P>
<P>
   If you've spent any time with a Playstation, the first scene of
``Toy Story 2'' is instantly recognizable as a video game scenario:
Buzz Lightyear jumps across a series of illuminated discs suspended
over a chasm. On the other side is a battery-shaped icon, obviously
a power-up. The whole setup is a well-established characteristic of
3-D platform adventure games, to the point of being a cliche.
</P>
<P>
   So when Buzz dies at the hands of Zurg, the archetypal big boss
at the end of a level, the joystick jockeys in the audience know
it's a game.
</P>
<P>
   The camera pulls back to reveal Rex the Dinosaur complaining
that it's too difficult to hit the controller buttons with his tiny
plastic arms. Any gamer can sympathize, and can also look forward
to succeeding where Rex failed.
</P>
<P>
   Playing ``Toy Story 2: The Videogame'' shows you how much cinema
and interactive media are mingling these days _ and the ways that
they remain distinct.
</P>
<P>
   On a superficial level, they are closer together than ever. Fast
processors and graphic accelerator cards bring the PC version
within spitting distance of the movie's silky, computer-generated
smoothness. Computers haven't gotten fast enough to import 3-D
models directly from the film, but some of the original motion data
is used to make the video game characters walk with the same gait
as their big-screen counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of tweaking, back and forth, regarding the 3-D
animation,'' said Dan Winters, a senior producer at Disney
Interactive, the maker of the game (Disney owns Pixar, which
produced the film). ``But I think there'll be more and more truly
shared assets in the future. There will be a day when we can take
the character of Buzz Lightyear or Woody from Pixar and use them
directly in our video game systems.''
</P>
<P>
   But even as the graphics merge, the film and the game are
structurally distinct. Film is a linear form (flashbacks and
Tarantino-esque shuffling don't alter the narrative trajectory;
they just change the order in which events are revealed). Movies
are about storytelling.
</P>
<P>
   Video games, on the other hand, are a nonlinear medium. They
have almost nothing to do with storytelling and everything to do
with movement and geography. When you're playing a video game,
storytelling is the farthest thing from your mind. You're in the
same mental space as a basketball player or a ballerina _ or a
conquistador. You are striving for a peak experience that depends
entirely on your understanding of objects in space and being able
to control them.
</P>
<P>
   People who make great video games understand this, and when they
make a video game based on a movie, their mission is to transform a
linear narrative into a series of 3-D environments. They're not
auteurs. They're architects. ``The first thing we do when we talk
to Pixar is look at the script and pick out high points of action
that are no-brainers,'' Winters said. ``OK, obviously we're going
to have a platform piece, so let's incorporate this. Or hey, a
tarmac area is really cool. We're jumping on a luggage piece,
that's a pretty good action-oriented scene, let's do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The result is a game _ a set of rules, objects and missions _
whose sequence of environments tracks to the sequence of
environments you see in the movie. The rest is apples and oranges.
It's not about loyalty, personal conflict and clever one-liners.
It's about collecting coins, finding all of Bo Peep's sheep in
hard-to-reach crevices of the house and returning Potato Head's
lost ear so he will give you the Cosmic Shield that allows you to
walk on toxic green sludge in the basement.
</P>
<P>
   It's about hopping and jumping, with target practice. It's about
mobility and being able to maneuver skillfully through your
environment.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Buzz Lightyear works so well as the hero. ``Buzz is
all about cool moves,'' Winters said. ``He's all about attachments
and cool moves.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does a swirl thing where he's an acrobat _ he jumps onto a
pole and swings around it. He can climb up on a pole. We wanted the
player to have fun just controlling Buzz Lightyear, connecting with
that character. So that's how everything is driven.''
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom says that interactive media is becoming more
and more cinematic, because the resolution of computer game images
is nibbling at the heels of video. But games are developing a
distinct grammar of their own. In fact, action movies may be
borrowing more from video games than vice versa (witness ``The
Matrix'' and ``Run Lola Run'').
</P>
<P>
   The two media converge on a superficial level, but fundamentally
they remain distinct. Invariably, gamers skip lengthy cinematic
sequences to get to the interactive part. Moviegoers don't want to
be responsible for ``Game Over'' in the second reel. Films relieve
you of that responsibility. They mitigate your risk _ you don't
have to fight the battles. You can be transported by the hero. And
amid the chase scenes, close scrapes and explosions, you can even
imagine what it would be like to play him in a video game.
</P>
<P>
   Toy Story 2: The Videogame, from Disney Interactive; for
Playstation, $49.95; for Nintendo 64, $59.95; CD-ROM for Windows 95
and 98, $29.99; all ages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
