r k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      12-22 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 FOR BRADLEY AND McCAIN, TROUBLE ON THE HOME FRONT  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The ancient truism that no man is a hero to his
servant goes back at least to Plutarch in the second century; put
another way, it means familiarity often breeds contempt.
</P>
<P>
   This theme is constantly updated with modern political examples,
in sad, hilarious or even useful ways. A classic example is the
repeated failure of Franklin Roosevelt, one of our greatest
presidents, to carry his home constituency of Hyde Park, an enclave
of conservative, wealthy New York Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The latest is the trouble Democratic presidential challenger
Bill Bradley and Republican contender John McCain are having in
winning unanimous support from officeholders back home who are
supposed to be their partisan soulmates.
</P>
<P>
   The theory of party unity is not as strong as the reality of
personal rivalry born of competing ambitions and clashing
interests.
</P>
<P>
   The locals may indeed know too much about the candidates to
endorse them without reservation, just because they share a
philosophical affiliation. And ``all bow down'' is not a winning
appeal to men and women who have their own positions of influence,
no matter how limited.
</P>
<P>
   Really strong candidates can overcome such resistance. The
coattails of a successful favorite son can serve as a ladder to
lift all with access into the perfumed White House atmosphere of
perks and power. This can be very tempting indeed.
</P>
<P>
   That's when a contrary rule applies: it is better to deal with
the bum you know than one you don't. So it has been for Texas Gov.
George Bush, who sewed up not only his state's most prominent
Republican officeholders early in the game but most of his fellow
GOP governors and a clutch of other GOP officials around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   The only Texas Republican holdout thus far is Rep. Ron Paul, who
ran for the White House in 1988 on the Libertarian Party ticket and
is currently staying mum.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore's native Tennessee, which he represented
in the House and Senate for 16 years until tapped as Bill Clinton's
running mate, is a swing state that is now more Republican than
Democratic. The four Democratic members of Congress have endorsed
him, but of course the five GOP members, the two GOP senators and
the GOP governors oppose him.
</P>
<P>
   It is the situation of Bradley and McCain that is the most
politically intriguing.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley was a senator from New Jersey for three terms and is the
first candidate from the state with a viable shot at the White
House since Woodrow Wilson, who won. Yet not one member of New
Jersey's congressional delegation _ past members as well as the
seven current Democrats _ has endorsed him. Democratic Sen. Frank
Lautenberg campaigns for Gore; his counterpart, Robert Torricelli,
vice chairman of the party's Senate campaign committee, has not
intervened in the primary.
</P>
<P>
   The basic rap against Bradley is that he was intellectually
distant and unresponsive to his colleagues' interests. He was a bit
too above the fray for the likes of those condemned to survive in
the middle of it. His record on behalf of New Jersey shows he did
deliver in some ways, but apparently he did not try as hard as he
should have.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's problem in his home state of Arizona is the opposite;
he has been in the faces of some fellow Republican too often in
ways they loathe. He's a tough guy, and if you don't go along with
him his reactions can be harsh.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jane Hull leads the battle cry against him, filling the
media with descriptions of a temper she finds uncontrollable and
disqualifying for the presidency. She has on her side several other
statewide officeholders. Former House minority leader John Rhodes,
whose retirement opened a House seat to McCain, also backs Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Yet not all Arizona politicians are hostile to McCain. The
junior senator, John Kyl, is McCain's national co-chairman. Four of
the five GOP House members back McCain. The fifth, Rep. Bob Stump,
did not respond to repeated phone calls seeking his position.
</P>
<P>
   So does it matter much whether the home team is solidly behind
the local star? It's a sign of some weakness. But it need not be
fatal, if the state's voters decide they like the guy at the top
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley and McCain need to carry their state primaries if they
are to go all the way to their party nominations. Right now that
looks doubtful in both cases.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address
means(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
