A6752 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-BIZMAGS23-COX     12-22 0513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZMAGS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fortune says Ivester was ambushed
 &HT;    By David McNaughton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ M. Douglas Ivester got mugged in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   That's Fortune's (Jan. 10) explanation for Ivester's sudden
decision to retire as chairman and chief executive officer of
Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   As Fortune tells it, Ivester was in Chicago on Dec. 1 for a
meeting with executives of McDonald's. But while he was in town, he
also met with Warren Buffett and Herbert Allen. Those ``800-pound
gorillas'' of Coca-Cola's board told Ivester he no longer was the
man for Coke, Fortune says.
</P>
<P>
   No decision was reached in Chicago about what to do next, the
magazine says. But Ivester wasted no time. On Sunday he quit, a
victim of his own arrogance and insecurity, according to Fortune.
</P>
<P>
   CLOSING THE GENDER GAP IS ALL IN THE NUMBERS
</P>
<P>
   What's a woman to do when she's looking for an employer who will
offer the most opportunities for advancement? Well, she could go to
work for one of the 25 companies identified by Working Woman
(January). All have proved they are committed to giving women a
shot at the top, the magazine says.
</P>
<P>
   At the top of the list: Avon. No. 2, and new to the list this
year: Charles Schwab.
</P>
<P>
   IT'S A TOUGH JOB, BUT SOMEBODY HAS TO DO IT
</P>
<P>
   ``Predicting the next 1,000 years is a breeze compared to
predicting the next 12 months.''
</P>
<P>
   So says Business Week in its year-end double issue (Dec. 27/Jan.
3). Nonetheless, the magazine takes a stab at predicting what
investors should watch. Among its forecasts: ``The big story of
2000 is likely to be tech stocks _ how far and how fast they will
rise.''
</P>
<P>
   Also in Business Week: If you think workers are in short supply
in the United States, take a look at Europe. It's estimated that
1.3 million information technology jobs could go begging next year.
That's on a continent with an unemployment rate of just under 10
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, which the magazine notes could hurt the region's
economic outlook, is that those without jobs don't have the needed
computer skills.
</P>
<P>
   ARE YOU ALREADY LOST ON THE INTERNET HIGHWAY?
</P>
<P>
   The heavyweights of corporate America may be moving too slowly
to embrace the Internet and the opportunities and savings it
offers, argues Barron's (Dec. 20). Of the 30 companies in the Dow
Jones industrial average, 19 seem to have comprehensive Internet
strategies, Barron's says. Another five were deemed to have ''sort
of'' gotten the point. Six just don't get it, according to the
publication.
</P>
<P>
   IT'S TAKE-YOUR-PICK TIME
</P>
<P>
   Kiplinger's Personal Finance (January) offers cutting-edge
funds. Bloomberg Personal Finance (December) provides a list of
technology stocks that bear watching.
</P>
<P>
   The theory at Kiplinger's is that technology, pharmaceuticals
and finance are the sectors in which investors should have money,
and the funds it picks are a way to get there.
</P>
<P>
   Also in Bloomberg Personal Finance: The best electronic toys for
executives.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
