<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6779 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-Y2K-GLITCHES-HNS &LR;      12-22 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-GLITCHES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     Y2K ALERT EXTENDS TO JAN. 3 AND BEYOND 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 &HT;     c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The world-wide Y2K alert doesn't end on New Year's
Day.
</P>
<P>
   Specialists in preventing Y2K computer glitches say that most
Y2K problems probably won't reveal themselves until Monday, Jan. 3,
when millions of Americans return to work and school. Some experts
think Y2K computer glitches could pop up throughout the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real test will be on Mondaywhen millions of transactions
and events take place as they normally do,'' said John Koskinen,
the White House's Y2K czar.
</P>
<P>
   Even though government and private-industry computers have been
tested to make sure they can properly read the digits ``00'' as the
year 2000, the true test will come Monday, Jan. 3, when computer
systems are used in normal operations rather than in a test-mode,
according to Koskinen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's highly unlikely anybody's lights or telephone are going
to go off immediately,'' Koskinen said. It would likely take a
whole series of computer problems to build up before a Y2K computer
collapse causes a large system to malfunction or shut down, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Norm Dean, the executive director of the Washington, D.C.-based
non-profit Center for Y2K and Society, agrees that Jan. 1 isn't the
crucial date. The ``majority of events related to Y2K will occur
Jan. 3 and beyond,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   While key U.S. systems like telecommunications and electric
power are expected to continue to function normally on Jan. 1 and
beyond, Koskinen said power failures could occur in undeveloped
countries beginning in early January.
</P>
<P>
   And the United States won't be immune to problems even though
the federal government and major private industries from airlines
to telecommunications have tested and re-tested their computers to
properly read the digits ``00.''
</P>
<P>
   If computers that contain date-sensitive chips read ``00'' as
the year 1900, they may malfunction and potentially disrupt larger
systems.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Koskinen nor Dean predicts any large national or
regional Y2K problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we'll see planes fall out of the sky or
widespread power outages,'' Dean said. ``But there are going to be
problems in specific areas...that could affect a number of
people.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said most of the nation's one million non-profit
organizations have done nothing to address Y2K issues, which could
affect the services they provide to millions of Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Another potential problem stems from the fact that many small
businesses have done nothing to prepare for Y2K. The National
Federation of Independent Businesses reports that 1.5 million small
companies are simply taking a wait-and-see approach to see if cash
registers, or security or refrigeration systems fail when they open
their doors on Jan. 3 after being closed for the holiday weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The only problem is that businesses may not be able to find
someone to fix their failed systems on a timely basis.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services
reports that many doctors' offices and hospitals haven't tested
their billing systems to make sure they will be able to request
payments from the federal government's Medicare and Medicaid
systems and private insurers _ problems that won't begin occurring
until the end of January.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having a computer break down in January may not affect a small
business or its employees until later in the year,'' Dean said,
explaining that employees likely won't lose their jobs on Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   A failed small business could affect a larger firm if the
smaller firm were a key supplier to the larger company. Those
problems likely won't crop up until the end of January or later.
</P>
<P>
   Koskinen said other Y2K problems might also surface later in
January or toward the end of the first quarter in March when the
first bills with 2000 dates on them are sent out. For example, some
water customers in West Des Moines, Iowa, last week received bills
with a due date of Jan. 3, 1900.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Jennifer Corbett Dooren Name can be reached at 202-298-6920 or
at the e-mail address jennifer &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
