</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991222.0247 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6782 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-PASSWORD-NYT &LR;      12-22 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-PASSWORD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW WAYS OF SECURING ONLINE DATA 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By PETER WAYNER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The problem with passwords is that there are so many of them, a
problem the computer industry is confronting with solutions that
range from virtual key rings to smart cards that do all of the
logging in for you.
</P>
<P>
   The basic solution is to store the passwords in a file called a
key ring. This file is usually encrypted with a master password,
ideally one that is easy to remember.
</P>
<P>
   Key rings have been used for many years, but lately researchers
have concentrated on making them easier to use by integrating them
with the many Web sites that require passwords.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers also are experimenting with putting more information
into key rings and adding automated features that look up
passwords. The latest version of the Mac OS comes with an
integrated tool that unlocks the key ring with a spoken phrase. You
can also encrypt the files on your Mac and store the password in
the central key ring.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, researchers are re-examining how key rings protect
passwords and other confidential data. Netscape's Web browser
stores the e-mail passwords of users in a primitive key ring. Last
week, several code breakers at Reliable Software Technologies in
Dulles, Va., announced that they had cracked the protection in a
short time using pencil and paper.
</P>
<P>
   Gary McGraw, the chief technology officer at Reliable Software,
which makes an extra effort to ensure that its software does not
crash, emphasized the danger of poorly designed key rings.
</P>
<P>
   Most people use the same password for everything, McGraw said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So you knock over someone's poorly protected machine at home,
get their password and then use it to get into someone's corporate
machine,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Or their bank account, or their Amazon account, or ... the list
goes on.
</P>
<P>
   One of the latest solutions to the problem is a tool called
v-GO, from the New York City based company Passlogix. The tool
stores basic passwords for Web sites and mail servers using the
common strategy of creating a central encrypted file.
</P>
<P>
   What is novel about the tool is its integration with Web
browsers to keep track of what sites are visited and what user name
and password are used at each one. The software matches the user
name and password to the URL and automatically enters the proper
data in the forms. Users can also include addresses and phone
numbers if they wish.
</P>
<P>
   The tool also allows you to change your identity as you change
sites, from ``WB123'' at one place to ``Koosbane41'' at another,
for example.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Boroditsky, the chief executive of Passlogix, says that his
company plans to integrate its key ring with public-key encryption
technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the future,'' Boroditsky said, ``we want to handle online
banking and medical records.''
</P>
<P>
   In a public-key encryption system, a person has a public key and
a private key. The public key scrambles a message and may be used
by anyone, but the private key that is needed to unscramble the
message must be kept secret by the person who holds it.
</P>
<P>
   The newer key rings promise to hold private keys and manage the
construction of digital signatures that can be used to endorse
transactions. These digital signatures are more secure than
passwords because they change with each transaction.
</P>
<P>
   A doctor might request a copy of an X-ray or a diagnosis and use
an online key ring to sign the request with a digital signature.
</P>
<P>
   Digital signatures are created by complex cryptographic codes
and are designed to mimic pen-and-paper signatures. In this case,
only someone with the password to the key ring can add a signature
to a document. Banks and other institutions that depend upon
pen-and-paper signatures hope to save time and money by recognizing
digital signatures.
</P>
<P>
   Boroditsky also said that Passlogix is exploring ways of
encouraging users to select passwords that are truly random, like
the time of day, instead of words that might be susceptible to
guessing, like a birth date, an address or the name of a child or a
pet.
</P>
<P>
   In the long term, passwords will be stored on smart cards and
other secure hardware. McGraw said that his company could have
found the passwords stored by Netscape even if Netscape had used
the most secure encryption available.
</P>
<P>
   PC software is inherently insecure because all parts of the
computer are accessible.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Farmer, the president of the Smart Card Forum, says that
the smart-card technology is being embraced by many companies that
need secure and convenient protection that goes beyond passwords.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think authentication and privacy are going to be the
driver,'' Ms. Farmer said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, American Express has taken the lead in this area by
introducing a new brand of credit card _ called Blue _ with an
embedded smart card. The company hopes that its use of the smart
card to do a better job of protecting against fraud will attract a
significant portion of transactions made over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Confronted by a smart card, a potential thief cannot simply copy
a name, credit card number and expiration date. The thief would
have to copy the data stored inside the card _ a task that the
smart card designers have tried to make impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Gilstrap, a vice president at American Express, says that
the Internet transactions are just the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a good deal of excess capacity on these cards,''
Gilstrap said. ``There's a great potential to add new features
after issuance. I can't steal the thunder from our marketing
department, but the cardholder will be able to add new features
that fits their lifestyles in the future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-22-99 1740EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991222.0248 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6787 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-2     12-22 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE END IS NEAR. REBOOT. 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (af)  
 By PETER H. LEWIS  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For many personal computer users, Y2K preparedness has meant
getting a date or finding a baby sitter and having sufficient
Champagne and MP3 party tunes on hand for New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   The digital event of the century is less than 10 days away, and
perhaps you are not quite certain whether you or your PC is going
to have the bigger hangover on Jan. 1. If so, here are some
last-minute tips.
</P>
<P>
   First, relax, it's not the very last minute. Yes, the so-called
Y2K bug is a big deal, already the costliest technology mistake in
history, and it still has the potential to cause serious problems.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, government and corporate computer managers worldwide have
been working on the problem for years, while you have been busy
playing solitaire and blasting aliens. But there is still plenty of
time to prepare your home PC for the new year.
</P>
<P>
   Most home computers and software applications made in the last
few years were designed with the Y2K transition in mind, so if
you're relatively new to computing, it may actually be in your
favor. That does not mean that the potential problems are
eliminated, just that they are minimized for newer computers.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the Y2K problem primarily affects programs that rely on
time-based calculations, which makes it of main interest to people
who use the computer for boring things like spreadsheets,
databases, personal finance programs and other accounting-type
applications. If all you do is play games, write e-mail and shop
online, you can probably forget about your PC and enjoy the
Champagne.
</P>
<P>
   There are a few basic checks that must be made to minimize the
risk of Y2K-related problems. But first, a warning. Many people
believe that the only thing they need to do to check the computer
for Y2K compliance is to reset their system clock to 12/31/99 and
11:59 p.m., switch the computer off for a couple of minutes, then
boot it up again. If everything appears to work properly, some
people may conclude that they have nothing to fear, and more than
likely they will be right.
</P>
<P>
   But Dawna Prussoff, a product manager at Symantec Corp., warned
that this simple do-it-yourself test is incomplete and could in
fact trigger the very problems that the user hopes to avoid.
Symantec has a financial interest in this issue, because it is one
of the many companies that sell Y2K diagnostic and repair programs.
</P>
<P>
   Most of these commercial Y2K utility programs cost less than
$50. Fifty bucks may seem like a lot of money for a program that
typically takes only a few minutes to diagnose what could be a
nonexistent problem. But it can also be thought of as a convenient
form of insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the most highly rated Y2K packages for Windows computers
are Symantec's Norton 2000 ($49.95, www.symantec.com/sabu/n2000/)
and Greenwich Mean Time's Check 2000 PC Deluxe ($34.95,
www.gmt-2000.com). They check your system's BIOS (basic input
output system), the operating system, major applications and in
many cases even your data files, right down to the spreadsheet
cells and database fields. In most cases they can repair any
problems they encounter.
</P>
<P>
   Both Norton 2000 and Check 2000 PC Deluxe can be downloaded from
their Web sites, which can save a trip to the store. They also come
in a package with printed documentation.
</P>
<P>
   It is also a good idea to log on to one of the many Web sites
that offer Y2K resources. (If you don't have an Internet
connection, make getting one your No. 2 New Year's resolution in
the computer category, right after backing up your hard disk.)
</P>
<P>
   There are good reference areas at the Symantec Web site and at
www.zdnet.com/zdhelp/filers/y2k/. These sites and many others, like
www.download.com, have lots of free utility programs that you can
download to test the BIOS, whose tasks include telling the
operating system what year it is. Your operating system passes
along the date and time information to your software applications.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   So, if your older BIOS thinks every year begins with a 19,
``00'' in any two-digit date fields (as in 01/01/00) will be
translated as Jan. 1, 1900, and that is when things could start
going haywire.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, the BIOS will pass all tests. In a few cases, you
may only need to download a software patch to update the BIOS to
recognize the new century. In a few rare cases, especially in older
machines, no easy BIOS software patches are available and you will
have to contact either the PC maker or the BIOS maker for help.
</P>
<P>
   In these cases, you will really have to scamper to make the
fixes in time. Or, in the rare case that you have lots of money
left over after the holiday shopping season, you can run out and
buy a new PC, put on a party hat and pretend that you are having
fun spending the last hours of 1999 transferring your old data to
the new machine.
</P>
<P>
   But even if the BIOS is up to date, there could be problems in
the operating system. Most people use Microsoft Windows, so a visit
to www.microsoft.com/technet/year2k/ is in order. There are some
known Y2K glitches in Windows 95, Windows 98 and Windows NT, but
they can almost always be fixed easily with software patches.
</P>
<P>
   The Apple Macintosh was designed from the start to handle
four-digit year dates, and thus the Mac itself is relatively immune
to most Y2K issues.
</P>
<P>
   Before they get too smug, however, Mac users must still make
sure their software applications are Y2K compliant, especially
those that perform date-based calculations. Apple has a Y2K
information page on the Web at www.apple.com/about/year2000/.
</P>
<P>
   Checking the applications on your computer is the next level of
testing. Even if the BIOS and operating systems pass the tests, the
programs themselves may get the hiccups when 2000 arrives.
</P>
<P>
   Again, the primary concerns are any programs that make
calculations based on dates and times, like databases, spreadsheets
and personal finance programs. People who run a small business on
their home PC will want to pay especially close attention to
accounting, banking and payroll programs.
</P>
<P>
   Some people have dozens of programs on their PCs, and it may be
impractical to check them all at this late date. So make a list of
the most important programs and start there. By the way, if you
manage a nuclear reactor from your home PC, it would be nice to
notify your neighbors before you go off to the first party.
</P>
<P>
   The special programs like Norton 2000 and Check 2000 PC Deluxe
maintain updated databases of hundreds of popular programs and
check them all automatically. The manual alternative is to write
down the version numbers of all your major applications and visit
each vendor's Web site to check the Y2K compliance statement.
</P>
<P>
   It may be necessary to upgrade to newer versions. Obviously,
this is something best done well ahead of the last hours of 1999.
In some cases the upgrade may be free, but in others you may have
to buy an updated version.
</P>
<P>
   America Online users can check to see if their software is
compliant by going to AOL keyword Y2K. One interesting discovery:
America Online says the relatively recent AOL version 4.0 with
Internet Explorer 4.01 ``will not be certified Y2K compliant'' and
urges customers to upgrade to AOL 5.0.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is not with AOL's software but with the Microsoft
browser. AOL 4.0 will work fine with an upgraded browser, which can
be downloaded free from Microsoft's site.
</P>
<P>
   The almost final step, and the one that is potentially the most
time consuming, is to examine your data files. Perhaps you wrote a
spreadsheet or database macro that makes date-based calculations.
As mentioned earlier, some of the better Y2K utility packages can
test data files automatically.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, as a great philosopher of the 20th century once said,
it ain't over till it's over. It is a good idea to test your
systems periodically for the first few months of 2000, especially
if people send you new files, being particularly alert for computer
viruses that come in masquerading as Y2K bug problems and fixes.
</P>
<P>
   On the bright side, all this attention about Y2K has caused PC
and software makers to plan ahead. Apple tells me my Macintosh is
capable of handling dates accurately until the year 29,940. What a
relief.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
