<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEY-DAD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACKPACK HOLDS UNTOLD SECRETS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERIC CELESTE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Upon becoming a father, I worried what sort of emotional trauma
I could cause that would send my daughter into therapy. I was
fairly cocky, as only the young and heretofore childless can be, so
I concluded that I could, through attentive parenting, ensure that
she would never be forced to endure $175-an-hour counseling. I
didn't count on ``Doughnuts for Dads.''
</P>
<P>
   My daughter, a kindergartner, was about to leave for school one
recent Wednesday morning. It was 7:30 a.m. My wife had been up
since 5:30 to exercise, shower, make breakfast, dress the daughter,
dress herself, make lunch and work up a healthy irritation at my
laziness. I rolled out of bed in time to kiss my daughter goodbye.
My daughter stood there, staring at me, confused.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, Daddy, today is `Doughnuts for Dads.' ''
</P>
<P>
   My wife and I stared at each other as if to say, ``What is she
talking about, and can I somehow blame this on you?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Honey, what is it?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doughnuts for Dads. It's today.''
</P>
<P>
   The wife seized control: ``She's probably making it up. If there
was an event today, I'd have known about it. We check her backpack
every day.'' As most readers know, the backpack is the only source
of information about what a schoolchild's day was like, since kids'
only response to parental inquiry is always, ``Nothin'.'' The
backpack is the dig site for the anthropological team of Mom and
Dad, who reconstruct the daily routine of Child by piecing together
clues from construction paper, handouts and color-coded homework
assignments. (''Ah hah. According to her homework, honey, today she
learned how to day-trade.'')
</P>
<P>
   I sized up the situation. It was 7:35, and the wife needed to
get to work. But if there was a school-sponsored event _ apparently
involving the exchange of fathers for sugar-coated dough _ I could
not miss it. A school full of every Dad EXCEPT ME is the sort of
memory that psychiatrists could later connect to the words
``breakthrough'' and ``increasing your dosage.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm jumping in the shower. Take her to school, and, if you see
anything unusual, call me,'' I said. ``I'll fly there.''
</P>
<P>
   Five minutes later, when I exited the shower, I heard the
screech of tires in the driveway. The door opened violently, and a
frantic wife appeared before me and my towel-clad splendor. ``There
are ACRES of dads there. No moms in sight. I strongly suggest you
... ''
</P>
<P>
   I was way ahead of her. No time to make it to the closet _ throw
on clothes next to bed, which are easy to find because I can smell
them; spray cologne on face to hide bad breath; think of evil
things I will do to person who put no notice of doughnut day in
daughter's backpack. It was 7:52.
</P>
<P>
   I wouldn't want to say that I exceeded the speed limit on my way
to school; given the public's waning trust in the news media, I
wouldn't want to lie, either. So let's skip the drive. When I
arrived, I saw a line of fathers and their children stretching
outside the cafeteria onto the sidewalk. We were second-to-last in
line. Last in line was a father whose daughter had told him the
incorrect day.
</P>
<P>
   As we snaked toward the doughnut table, we two sad-sack dads
discussed how insane it is that our kids so rarely let us know what
is going on day to day. (It turned out that most kids had notices
sent home about the doughnut event.) It's especially strange since,
until school begins, a child's every step outside the house is
monitored and controlled.
</P>
<P>
   That's when I saw the table. The table full of toys. The pile of
toys was growing, since each father, before securing a doughnut for
himself and his offspring, was placing a toy for charity atop the
pile.
</P>
<P>
   I turned to last-in-line dad, terror-stricken. He had that look,
that ``Oh, too bad for you'' look, on his face when he held up his
toy. ``I see my daughter told me a little more than yours,
though.''
</P>
<P>
   A scene years hence flashed in my mind. ``So, your father
withholds gifts from the needy? Let's discuss that next week. One
hundred seventy-five dollars, please.''
</P>
<P>
   (Eric Celeste's Hey Dad column appears weekly. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
