<HEADLINE>
DVD IS THE FUTURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LIZ STEVENS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I have seen the future _ and it's as clear as the pores on Billy
Bob Thornton's face.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is ``Armageddon,'' the place is Marvin Electronics in
Fort Worth, and the format _ oh, the beautiful format! _ is DVD.
</P>
<P>
   Marvin sales associate Scott Schuster has planted me in the
store's luxurious home-theater chamber, in front of a 140-inch
big-screen television, to display the technology that has
videophiles giddy. He turns down the lights, finagles with the
remote control, and there is Thornton's mug, looking more vivid and
creepy than it has ever been on home video.
</P>
<P>
   For thousands of movie buffs, DVD-Audio has given new meaning to
a trip to the video store.
</P>
<P>
   If you haven't heard of DVD, your ignorance is sure to be
short-lived. The acronym stands for digital versatile disc, and DVD
players are the fastest selling product in the history of consumer
electronics. Introduced in the United States in 1997, DVD players
will go home with 3.5 million consumers in 1999, analysts predict.
By contrast, it took six years after the VCR was introduced for
annual sales to surpass a million, in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   With DVD prices dropping to below $200 and the number of video
titles skyrocketing, DVD has become accessible to the masses.
According to the Consumer Electronics Association's 1999 Holiday
Purchase Pattern Survey, DVD players are the top item on the
holiday wish lists of people doing their Christmas shopping on the
Internet this season.
</P>
<P>
   The seduction of DVD lies in its visual and aural clarity. With
their improved resolution, DVDs make VHS tapes look as though
you're watching them through a dirty window.
</P>
<P>
   And the sound? Depending on your speaker system, DVD can make
you believe you're riding in ``Armageddon's'' asteroid-pelted
spaceship.
</P>
<P>
   The popularity of DVD, both in the electronics industry and
among consumers, effectively killed competitor DIVX and is fast
shoving laserdisc technology into obscurity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cassette tape is to the CD what the VCR tape is to DVD,''
Schuster says. ``We're selling more than we can get our hands on.''
</P>
<P>
   DVDs look just like CDs, but a basic DVD can store seven times
as much information as a standard CD. That's about 133 minutes'
worth of video and audio, enough for an entire movie plus extras.
And there are lots of extras to be had.
</P>
<P>
   DVDs can have up to eight separate audio or language tracks (so
you could watch ``Armageddon'' in Spanish or French, if you
wanted). Some videos include a film's theater trailer, interviews
with the actors and filmmakers, documentaries about the making of
the film, even alternate endings. (Want to know what might have
happened had Jeff Bridges not goofed at the end of ``Arlington
Road''? See it on DVD).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a neat toy, if you want to think of it as a toy, in the
respect that (DVDs) afford a lot of different features that people
aren't normally accustomed to with their VCR,'' says Tim McNamara,
the Consumer Electronics Association's manager of communications.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood and independent producers have embraced the format,
now even promoting DVD release dates. As of Dec. 15, 5,208
DVD-Video titles were available, according to Jeff Phillips' list,
www.thedvdlist.com. New releases include ``Ricky Martin: One Night
Only,'' as well as the 1973 classic ``Papillon.'' InfoTech, a
marketing forecast firm, predicts the availability of 20,000
DVD-Video titles by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Cost is another reason that aales of DVD players have tripled
from 1998. Low-end players can be had for less than $200, although
fully loaded models can run up to $4,000, according to the
Internet's Active Buyer's Guide (www1.activebuyersguide.com). The
discs average $20.
</P>
<P>
   The high-quality sound of the DVD-Video format is attributable
to Dolby Digital technology or Digital Theater System (DTS). All
DVDs on the market have the potential for Dolby Digital sound, but
DTS is the newer, better of the two, Schuster says. The hitch: Both
sound systems require five speakers and a subwoofer for full
effect, and most likely a separate receiver//decoder, too. Most of
us will have to settle for our television's two-speaker stereo
sound.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing DVD players seem to lack is the ability to
record. But that's set to change in 2000. Pioneer Electronics and
Philips Electronics have announced that they will introduce DVD
video recorders in the United States (Pioneer has already done so
in Japan). Still, prices will probably keep the average Joe from
taking part: $2,000 and up for the hardware and around $20 for
blank DVDs, says Michelle Abraham, a senior analyst at Cahners
In-Stat Group.
</P>
<P>
   DVD isn't just a video format. It soon hopes to be the standard
storage mechanism for audio, video and computer data. Several
companies are set to offer DVD-Audio (the next generation CD) in
2000, and newer generations of home computers include DVD-ROM
drives (to accommodate the next generation of CD-ROM).
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, don't toss the VCR. Even if it can't bring
``Armageddon'' to life in your living room, at least you've finally
figured out how to record ``Frasier'' when you're away from home.
</P>
<P>
   You have figured that out, haven't you?
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
.MDBR/ nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
