<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, Dec. 23, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   A large portion of the contiguous states will be bereft of
precipitation Thursday. One exception will be the Great Lakes
region, where snow showers will develop in concert with a weak
disturbance moving eastward. Most of the snow showers will occur in
the wake of a cold front associated with the disturbance as
increasingly cold air behind the front, which marks the core of an
arctic air mass, is moistened in transit over relatively warm
waters.
</P>
<P>
   Though some snow showers and flurries will also develop over the
northern Appalachians, only broken areas of high cirrus and
mid-level altostratus clouds will stream east of the Appalachians,
arriving during the day over the Northeast Seaboard. Nonetheless,
precipitation is unlikely along the New England and northern Middle
Atlantic seaboards.
</P>
<P>
   Spotty showers will develop over parts of southern Florida as a
slow-moving cool front interacts with a channel of moisture
streaming northeast from the southern Gulf of Mexico and the
western Caribbean. Farther west, a pall of low clouds will again
shroud the Rio Grande Valley of Texas, producing patchy drizzle and
sporadic, light showers.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the rest of the region from the Rockies to the
Pacific Ocean will be decidedly dry as a behemoth warm ridge of
high pressure reigns over the region from several thousand feet
above the ground. Moreover, almost the entire region will be sunny,
save for areas of fog and low clouds that form early in the Pacific
Northwest and only gradually shrink and dissipate during the day. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: December Warmth
</P>
<P>
   The mercury soared to 84 degrees at Shelter Cove, Calif., on
Monday, breaking the town's all-time December high. Though pockets
of record warmth were observed in northern California, cities such
as Sacramento recorded temperatures that could only be described as
seasonably warm. The weather pattern was marked by warm high
pressure several thousand feet over northern California. In many
cases, a temperature inversion aloft impeded warm air from mixing
to the ground. At Shelter Cove, winds descending the mountains to
the east helped to bring warmth to the surface.
</P>
</TEXT>
