<SLUG> BC-CENTURYINARTS-BOOKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM `ULYSSES' TO `ON THE ROAD'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Until year's end, the Star-Telegram brings you a
subjective look at the top 10 moments of the century in the arts.
Today: Books
</P>
<P>
   1922: James Joyce's dense novel ``Ulysses'' is published in
Paris. It's banned in the United States until 1933 because of
language and one especially erotic scene, but no matter. Joyce has
set a new standard for the modern American novel, and the rule is:
There are no longer any rules.
</P>
<P>
   1952: Ralph Ellison's ``Invisible Man,'' the saga of a
deliberately unnamed black protagonist searching for some basis of
self-identity, establishes that black authors can write classics
that educate as well as entertain.
</P>
<P>
   1936: Margaret Mitchell publishes ``Gone With the Wind,'' which
remains America's favorite novel written in, if not concerning, the
20th century.
</P>
<P>
   1942: The first weekly bestseller list appears in ``The New York
Times Book Review.'' Previously, only intermittent lists from
limited sources were printed. Publishers begin to base their
marketing decisions on how books fare on weekly lists instead of
promoting titles because they are well-written.
</P>
<P>
   1925: Sinclair Lewis refuses the Pulitzer Prize for his novel
``Arrowsmith,'' taking exception to the competition's tradition of
honoring books depicting ``the wholesome atmosphere of American
life.'' In response, the Pulitzer Committee announces that it will,
in the future, select ``distinguished fiction by an American
author, preferably dealing with American life.''
</P>
<P>
   1962: Theodore White's ``The Making of the President 1960''
serves as an instant primer for future presidential campaigns.
Political organizers in other states, reading about the influence
of primary elections in New Hampshire, West Virginia and Wisconsin,
hurry to organize their own primaries. The American political
system is changed forever by this book.
</P>
<P>
   1936: Dale Carnegie's ``How to Win Friends and Influence
People'' is perhaps the first bestselling ``self-help'' book; by
century's end, self-help books will dominate the publishing
marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   1917: John Reed's ``Ten Days That Shook the World,'' a
sympathetic chronicle of the 1917 Russian revolution, creates
instant controversy. Reed, eventually indicted on a sedition
charge, flees the United States for Russia and dies in 1920.
</P>
<P>
   1926: The Book-of-the-Month Club and the Literary Guild are
founded. Americans unable or unwilling to go to bookstores now have
easy mail access to many titles.
</P>
<P>
   1957: Jack Kerouac's ``On the Road'' unleashes a flood of
novels, essays and poems from ``The Beat Generation''
(Ferlinghetti, Ginsberg, et al). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HONORABLE MENTION: The publication of J.D. Salinger's ``The
Catcher in the Rye'' in 1951; it's impossible to estimate how many
American teen-agers subsequently read and are greatly affected by
this novel; 1987, when Tom Wolfe's ``The Bonfire of the Vanities''
perfectly captures American's money-and-status-obsessed society and
is, perhaps, the final great American novel of the century.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-22-99 1755EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991222.0258 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6802 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-OBRIEN-PLAY-ART-2TAKE     12-22 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBRIEN-PLAY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTS ABROAD: IRELAND'S WAYWARD WRITER, STILL RAISING EYEBROWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By LESLIE GARIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ George Mitchell, the former U.S. senator who recently
forged an unexpected alliance between Ulster's unionists and
republicans, had a hand this year in bringing ceremonial closure to
another feud, this time between Ireland's conservative
establishment and its favorite hate object, the writer Edna
O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   On behalf of Queens University in Belfast, Mitchell awarded Ms.
O'Brien a doctorate, saying in his presentation that she had
``changed the course of Irish womanhood.'' That was a far cry from
``a smear on Irish womanhood,'' the words used by a government
censor in 1960 when Ireland banned ``The Country Girls,'' Ms.
O'Brien's first novel. The censors banned her next six books as
well amid fusillades of vituperation that only increased her fame.
After James Joyce she is the best-known banned Irish writer of the
century.
</P>
<P>
   As Ms. O'Brien talks to a visitor in the small, red-walled
drawing room of her Victorian house in the Chelsea section of
London, one sees that much of her renowned beauty is still intact.
The famous auburn hair is now shorter and less wild. The
expressions that change like clouds rumple her pale skin in the
usual places, but her face retains the imperious precision of fine
carving.
</P>
<P>
   The occasion for this conversation was the opening of her first
play in 12 years, ``Our Father,'' for a limited run at the Almeida
Theater. Ms. O'Brien was in the hand-wringing stage known well by
playwrights. The play has since opened to reviews ranging from
raves to pans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a nervous creature,'' she said in her low voice, with its
lilting County Clare accent. ``So nervous that I don't know how I
get up and down the street or cook dinner because I'm always on the
edge.'' She had been up most of the previous night writing notes on
the production, she said. But working around the clock is her usual
pattern.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm writing, the job of doing it assails me night and
day,'' she said. ``I get up in the night. I rewrite the way
Penelope ripped that bloody tapestry in Homer all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Her obsessiveness has created a hefty body of work: 14 novels
(her latest, ``Wild Decembers,'' will be published in the United
States in the spring), five volumes of short stories, four plays,
plus movie and television scripts, essays, a nonfiction book about
Ireland and a new biography of Joyce, just published in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our Father'' is, in the words of Jonathan Kent, the
co-artistic director of the Almeida, ``full of hidden terrors,
hidden dangers and secrets held in the dark,'' a description that
could apply to virtually all her work. In the play four grown
siblings return to their failing farm in western Ireland to
celebrate the wedding anniversary of their pious mother and brutish
father, whom The Guardian's reviewer called ``the least lovable
father since King Lear.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the details in ``Our Father'' have been seen before in
various incarnations throughout her work, interwoven each time with
new material and revealing a different facet of the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``An artist keeps going back to very wounded moments,'' she
said. ``Sometimes you're not aware of it, but they crop up of their
own accord, because childhood and that absolute seepage of
geography, language, death and pain has gone into you. It's as
organic as anything else. But if you write something about marriage
or loss or childhood, fathers, mothers, the whole stew, it's never
a catharsis. It glues you more to them. I get the food that I am
unable to get from human intercourse.''
</P>
<P>
   That would come as a surprise to her public. The Irish writer
Colm Toibin said recently in The Observer, ``The name Edna O'Brien
is associated with sex,'' and Vanity Fair once called her ``the
playgirl of the Western world.''
</P>
<P>
   But these days the social butterfly label is inaccurate. She
spends most of her time writing in isolation, either in Ireland or
London, where she moved permanently as a teen-ager in the late
1950s when she eloped with the Czech novelist Ernest Gebler. Her
scandalized parents gave chase. That was the beginning, even before
her writing, of her troubles over things sexual.
</P>
<P>
   ``Erotic love springs from such a deep source within me that it
is like some of the elements of childhood, that trepidation and
longing,'' Ms. O'Brien said. She wore a calf-length brown velvet
skirt and a low-cut black sweater. ``The longing is for a unity
that is permanent, and life and people aren't permanent. So as we
go into the very swim of it, we are afraid that it will not last.
And that brings fear and loss even before the loss. Then there's
the destruction Ted Hughes talks about in a poem: lovers devouring
each other. Our hungers, which are always there waiting to be
unleashed, can get the better of us and frighten another person.''
</P>
<P>
   She whispered this last phrase, as she did her most emotional
declarations. ``But I wouldn't for the world regret having loved,
regardless of the final act.''
</P>
<P>
   Since her divorce in 1968 from Gebler, who died in 1998, she has
lived alone. She maintains that loneliness is necessary for a
writer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If one was fairly content, why in the name of God would one
want to go through the discipline and scariness of sitting down to
write 90,000 words?'' she asked. ``And one thing is the other.
Writing makes you lonely because you have to exile yourself. But
deeper than that is an inborn native loneliness, a spiritual void
that words, for some reason, help fill.''
</P>
<P>
   She added: ``I would say that every writer I have admired, like
Faulkner, whom I love, and Joyce, or Emily Bronte, Sylvia Plath,
Chekhov, Beckett, regardless of their particular daily history, has
a loneliness and a depth of feeling that cannot be corresponded to,
and that's why they write.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Her Joyce book is part of a new series of short biographies,
Viking Lives. British critical response to her vision of Joyce was
mostly favorable but scathing about factual inaccuracies, which
have been corrected for the American edition.
</P>
<P>
   Like Joyce, Edna O'Brien has been under attack all her life. She
said she remembered her shock and pain when her parish priest held
a ``little burning on the chapel grounds'' of her first novel.
After her mother died, Ms. O'Brien said, she found her book wrapped
in a sheet in an outhouse. Her mother had ``gone through it with
black ink, the ink of Hades as I called it, and crossed, erased,
any word that offended her. I both wept and screamed.''
</P>
<P>
   She sees the comedy in it now, just barely, she said, raising
one arched eyebrow like a storybook bad queen. ``There is a hidden
criminality in writing. While you're doing it, it is your secret.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides disapprobation, there are other similarities between
Joyce's life and hers. While they were children, both their
families were listed in the debtors magazine, Stubbs Gazette,
causing a lifelong memory of shame. And both writers became
expatriates, along with O'Casey, Beckett and Wilde. As a character
in her novel ``Time and Tide'' says, you have to be far away for
``that enchantment that distance bestows.''
</P>
<P>
   What did she learn from Joyce?
</P>
<P>
   ``Here was a man who had written `Ulysses,' who, for 17 years,
every day and sometimes night, with his eyesight almost gone and
having to feel words and use color pencils and crayons, went into
the Hades and the paradise of his mind and his imagination to write
`Finnegans Wake,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned what I already knew. No outside hostility,
criticism, adulation or anything else must detract or deter the
writer from doing the thing they have to do.''`
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
