<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON COMPUTERS AND GADGETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mercedes and Motorola Revive Idea of Car Phone &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In their early days cell phones came in two models: bulky units
that were intended to stay in cars and slightly less bulky versions
that were ostensibly for handheld use. Now Motorola and
Mercedes-Benz USA have revived the idea of the car-specific cell
phone although thankfully without the heft.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Patrone, manager of advanced products for Mercedes-Benz
US., said the company concluded that current handheld phones were
not suited to the highway. ``The small controls, the small display
you need in a light, portable phone are not the things you want in
a car,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Outside of sporting Mercedes' star logo, the Mercedes Motorola
StarTAC digital and analog cell phone looks like a regular tiny,
handheld set. But once the phone is slipped into a cradle in a 2000
model year Mercedes, special software integrates it with the car's
electronics systems.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, drivers can operate the phone using controls
on the steering wheel or dashboard while viewing information, such
as stored numbers, on a dashboard display. The system automatically
lowers the radio or CD volume during calls, and the car's radio
speakers and built-in microphone can be used for hands-free
calling. An additional option allows users to place calls with
voice commands.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are talking longer in the car as cellular rates come
down,'' said Marios Zenios, general manager of the Motorola
Telematics Communications Group. ``We're starting to see
legislation appear in this country that will require hands-free
operation.''
</P>
<P>
   The special phone and integration hardware is standard on
Mercedes' top of the line 12-cylinder models. In other Mercedeses,
the phone system costs $1,295, plus $480 for voice recognition.
However, Zenios said Motorola was developing similar systems with a
variety of automakers. ``You're going to start seeing it in lower
and lower tiers of cars,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ IAN AUSTEN &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Virtual Data Storage, Complete With Ads &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Personal computer users who want to clean their desks of
scattered storage disks, and Macintosh owners whose computers don't
have disk drives, can get 300 megabytes of storage space online.
The service is free to people who sign up at FreeDiskSpace.com
(www.freediskspace.com), that is, free to users who agree to view
advertisements and receive promotional offers.
</P>
<P>
   The 300 megabytes of virtual hard drive, which will store text,
image and music files, will hold more than 3,000 pages of text or
more than 300 minutes of MP3 music files. By comparison, standard
Zip drive disks hold 100 MB, and floppy disks hold 1.44 MB.
</P>
<P>
   FreeDiskSpace says it ensures privacy through a password system,
and security through a firewall and a daily backup procedure of all
the data being stored. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ SHELLY FREIERMAN &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New Yule Log Tradition Glows With Eerie Light &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Back in the electronic Dark Ages _ say, a decade ago or so _
many an apartment-dwelling New Yorker celebrated Christmas by
getting friends and family together, setting them up with mugs of
holiday cheer, and gathering around the television set. On the
screen, broadcast by WPIX, a local station, was a continuous-loop
tape of a yule log burning in a fireplace, accompanied by holiday
music.
</P>
<P>
   It's a measure of how much technology has improved life that
now, in the Internet Age, hearthless people everywhere can have a
virtual fire in their homes. And no longer must they rely on the
TV; now they can huddle around ... the computer.
</P>
<P>
   WPIX's original Yule Log tape is available on the Internet, at
www.wb11/yulelog.htm. It was shot in 1966 at Gracie Mansion when
Mayor John Lindsay lived there, and was last broadcast in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The presentation has been updated: now, instead of the one
soundtrack, viewers have a choice of several. And images of the
roaring fire can be saved for use as a screen saver, or printed out
to be sent to friends who don't have a fireplace _ or a computer.
</P>
<P>
   _ HENRY FOUNTAIN &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Unveils Tax Product, but Bill Gates Can't Use It &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What do you give a man with everything? Why, tax software, of
course. Microsoft's TaxSaver software started arriving in stores
this week, joining a crowded tax software market dominated by
Intuit's TurboTax product line. Microsoft joined with the
accounting giant Arthur Andersen to produce the package.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft has been talking about a tax product for years,''
said Laura Starita, an analyst at the Gartner Group, ``but it's
extremely cumbersome and not a fun business to be in.''
</P>
<P>
   The product is tightly linked to Microsoft's personal finance
manager, Money, and includes a three-month subscription to the
company's online network, MSN, and its financial portal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about the software as much as it's about how it plays
to the Web and vertical portal offerings. Microsoft is constructing
ways to bring customers to them. That's an important element for
Microsoft over time,'' Ms. Starita said.
</P>
<P>
   The standard version costs $14.95, jumping to $39.95 for the
deluxe version, which includes additional help features,
tax-related videos and free electronic filing. Billionaires, take
note: TaxSaver will take only nine digits in the dollar field for
wages, tips and other compensation. Day traders can take heart,
though. That field will accept negative numbers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ STEVEN E. BRIER
</P>
</TEXT>
