<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDENING QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By DORA GALITZKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Getting Rarer &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Growing up in southern Connecticut, we could find trailing
pine (fan-shaped branches on a runner) and princess pine (which
resembles three-inch evergreen seedlings) in the woods each winter.
I haven't seen either of these in the New York woods. Can they be
purchased and introduced into my woodsy property in Putnam County?
</P>
<P>
   A. Both princess pine (Lycopodium obscurum) and trailing pine
(L. digitatum) are two of the few remaining species of club mosses,
plants that have been around since the time that coal was first
being formed, about 300 million years ago. Unfortunately, we may
yet see them disappear altogether, since they are so appealing in
Christmas wreaths and garlands.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't surprising that you haven't seen them in the woods
recently. Both are listed as ``exploitably vulnerable'' on the New
York State Protected Native Plants List _ that is, they are likely
to become threatened if harvesting from the wild continues. They
are not currently on the protected lists in New Jersey or
Connecticut, but it is probably just a matter of time before
they're added.
</P>
<P>
   They are both difficult to cultivate and slow growing. Trailing
pine, like most other Lycopodium species, forms a complex
relationship with a fungus that lives among its roots and
contributes to its nutrition. It is almost impossible to transplant
trailing pine without destroying the relationship, so it can't be
grown commercially. Princess pine doesn't have this relationship,
but it is also very fussy about its growing conditions, so it's not
likely that you will find it in a catalog.
</P>
<P>
   Every garland or wreath you see made of these two ancient
survivors represents about 25 years' growth of plants taken from
the wild. They have survived dinosaurs, ice ages and upheavals of
all sorts. If you ask me, it seems a shame to use them in Christmas
decorations that are thrown out after a week or two.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; No Magic Potions &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. We will soon move into a new house, and I have a problem with
the landscaping. I'm 65, and I don't want to pay for large plants
or wait 20 years for small plants to mature. Gibberellic acid, the
plant growth hormone, is available from a mail-order nursery that
also sells small, inexpensive trees and shrubs. Would that hormone
be the answer to my problem?  &QL; 
A. Sounds logical, and you probably wouldn't be the first person to
be disappointed, but it isn't a magic potion.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Peter Davies, an expert in plant hormones at Cornell
University, said gibberellins are plant hormones that occur
naturally and help control growth. Gibberellic (pronounced
jib-er-EL-ic) acid makes some plants grow taller, but it does so by
an unnatural elongation of the cells, not the production of healthy
new tissue. While there has been no research into its effect on
trees, he expects that it would not work at all.
</P>
<P>
   Gibberellins do have uses in horticulture, including in the
testing of dormant seeds to see if they are still viable, but
instant landscaping isn't one of them. Buy medium-size, well-grown
plants you can enjoy watching grow, and let the future take care of
itself.
</P>
<P>
   Address questions to Garden Q&AMP;A, The New York Times, 229 West
43rd St., New York 10036, or by e-mail to gardening(AT)nytimes.com.
Those of general interest will be published. Unpublished questions
cannot be answered individually.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-22-99 1801EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991222.0264 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6809 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBO-BLACKS-SUPERBOWL     12-22 0529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBO-BLACKS-SUPERBOWL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Black vendor cite Super Bowl freeze-out
 &HT;    By Ernie Suggs
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ By the time Super Bowl XXXIV rolls around on Jan. 30,
dozens of black-owned Atlanta businesses will have reaped millions
of dollars from minority-based incentive programs.
</P>
<P>
   But Steven Muhammad, a black Atlanta businessman for 20 years,
is afraid he won't see a dime of that. Neither will the 100 or so
members of the Black Vendors Association, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad, secretary of the BVA, claims that the NFL and the
Super Bowl have purposely excluded vendors who have traditionally
set up shop in parking lots around the Georgia Dome. He said all of
the private parking lots usually reserved for vendors to sell
souvenirs and T-shirts have been snatched up by the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``They cut us out of the loop of Super Bowl financing,''
Muhammad said. ``They want to sell everything themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   But Carlos James, vice president for community relations and
opportunities for the Metro Atlanta Super Bowl XXXIV Host
Committee, said any limitation in available vendor space is based
on a need for parking spaces, not some desire to push black vendors
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fully support the city of Atlanta's laws involving street
vending,'' James said. ``We are not going to displace them or ask
them to move. It will be business as usual for them during the
Super Bowl. We have said that over and over.''
</P>
<P>
   James said the main problem revolves around new construction at
the Georgia World Congress Center that must be completed in time
for the International Woodworkers Show in the summer of 2002.
</P>
<P>
   As of right now, that project will take away more than 2,000
prime parking spaces.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are losing 2,000 parking spaces so we had to go out and
purchase private lots to accommodate people,'' James said. ``The
bid says we must provide parking spaces.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike an ordinary Sunday afternoon Falcons game, Super Bowl
Sunday will be a totally different animal, especially when it comes
to parking. James estimates that aside from the hundreds of media
trucks and vans, there will be 1,100 buses and 800 limousines
fighting for space around the Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you lose 2,000 spaces you have to make up for it,'' said
James, adding that dozens of minority and women will benefit from
contracts designed specifically for them. ``We have taken the high
road on this. It is our intent to make this a more inclusive Super
Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad said not being able to operate in those lots will ruin
business opportunities for some of his colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is going to hurt us bad financially,'' Muhammad said. ``We
have made deals with some of the merchandise vendors to buy a lot
of merchandise.''
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad tried to stress that point Wednesday when he and about
20 other vendors visited to Host Committee offices to voice their
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked to them, but we really didn't get any answers. We
got the run around,'' Muhammad said. ``But this is not over. We are
going to hit the streets next week and turn up the heat.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
