<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6812 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-CENTURYINARTS-MUSIC-T     12-22 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENTURYINARTS-MUSIC-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM CARUSO TO NIRVANA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Till year's end, the ``Star-Telegram'' brings you
a subjective look at the top 10 moments of the century in the arts.
Today: Music.
</P>
<P>
   1904: Two-sided discs are put on sale by Columbia. This will
soon lead to the success of performers such as Enrico Caruso, whose
popularity begins the craze of buying music and having it in the
home.
</P>
<P>
   1923-1927: Bessie Smith and Jimmie Rodgers make their debuts,
and Duke Ellington records the first of several theme songs, ``East
St. Louis Toodle-oo.'' Smith becomes the first blues superstar,
Rodgers becomes the first real country star with his fusion of
folk, blues, pop and Dixieland, and Ellington's legacy as one of
America's great bandleaders and composers begins in earnest.
</P>
<P>
   1945: Charlie Parker records as a bandleader for the first time,
with Miles Davis on trumpet. Parker will become the first name in
bebop and cut numerous jazz standards _ ``KoKo, Cherokee, Now's the
Time'' and more _ before dying in 1955 at age 35.
</P>
<P>
   1948: Muddy Waters records his first singles for Chicago's Chess
Records. By electrifying the sounds of Delta blues, Waters makes
songs such as ``Rollin' Stone'' and ``I Can't Be Satisfied'' that
will set the standard for Chicago blues and lead directly to the
British blues-rock explosion.
</P>
<P>
   1955-1957: The golden era of rock 'n' roll, with hits by Elvis
Presley, Jerry Lee Lewis, Chuck Berry, Carl Perkins, Little Richard
and many more. Propelled by the national premiere of ``American
Bandstand,'' rock 'n' roll explodes from coast to coast and on into
Europe. At the same time, Frank Sinatra will release several of his
all-time classics, including ``In the Wee Small Hours'' and ``A
Swingin' Affair!''
</P>
<P>
   1963-1969: Arguably the most important era in rock history,
these six years will see the full flowering of Motown and Southern
soul via acts such as Smokey Robinson and the Miracles, Aretha
Franklin, and Otis Redding; debuts by Jimi Hendrix, Bob Seger, the
Band, Simon &AMP; Garfunkel, the Grateful Dead, Van Morrison, Pink
Floyd, the Velvet Underground, Fairport Convention, Santana, the
Allman Brothers and Cream; the release of the greatest live record
ever (James Brown's ``Live at the Apollo);'' the birth of art-rock
with debuts by Jethro Tull and King Crimson; the best work by Bob
Dylan and the Rolling Stones; the folk-blues boom; ALL of the
Beatles' essential recordings; Dylan ``going electric;'' Woodstock;
Altamont; and the birth of punk and heavy metal via the '69 debut
LPs by the Stooges and the MC5.
</P>
<P>
   1972-1974: The '70s have been lambasted as a lame decade for
music, but these three years would prove to be extremely important
to rock 'n' roll. Bruce Springsteen, the Eagles, Queen, Lynyrd
Skynyrd, Aerosmith and Roxy Music all released their debuts, Bob
Marley's classic first two albums _ ``Catch a Fire'' and
``Burnin''' _ came out, and glam rock caught fire via David Bowie's
``The Rise and Fall of Ziggy Stardust and the Spiders From Mars''
and ``Diamond Dogs,'' Mott the Hoople's ``All the Young Dudes'' and
``Mott,'' and the New York Dolls' two albums.
</P>
<P>
   1977-1980: Punk/New Wave/alternative/whatever kicks to life with
classic recordings by the Sex Pistols, U2, the Clash, the Ramones,
Patti Smith, X, Motorhead, Joy Division, Blondie, XTC, Talking
Heads, Television, the Buzzcocks, the Damned, Elvis Costello and
many more.
</P>
<P>
   1986-1988: Rap's initial explosion in the marketplace via such
records as the Beastie Boys' debut, ``Licensed to Ill,'' Public
Enemy's debut, ``Yo! Bum Rush the Show,'' and Run-D.M.C.'s classic
``Raising Hell.''
</P>
<P>
   1990-1992: The last great years of change in rock music, with
debuts by Nirvana and Pearl Jam forever changing what is popular
hard rock; at the same time, R.E.M. and U2 would reassert
themselves with CDs as good as anything they cut in the '80s, maybe
better.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
