<HEADER>
A6822 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ROCK-ERA-SONGS-3TAKES     12-22 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCK-ERA-SONGS-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN ROCK'S CANON, ANYONE AND EVERYONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   ANN POWERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Here's a little post-holiday exercise for your
amusement: grab pen and paper and jot down your 10 favorite songs
dating from 1955 to now. Ponder carefully, or don't, depending on
whether you think music should be judged by the brain or the gut.
Call five friends and read them your list. Set up a date to argue
about it, to spin CDs and scream and shout. When you've done that,
you will have helped shape the rock 'n' roll canon.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always ask, how did the songs get in the hymnal? How do
they make that step?'' said the multi-instrumentalist and
songwriter Peter Holsapple, who helped decide which rock-era songs
could stand next to the likes of ``Take Me Out to the Ball Game''
and ``Summertime'' as the band leader at the year-ending ``Songs of
the Century'' program for arts at St. Ann's in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   The great works of any art form are supposed to reveal its
potential. Shakespeare makes us realize how a play can encapsulate
a world. Picasso helps us ponder the fundamentals of seeing. And
despite recent scrutiny by those seeking to expand them, the canons
these artists occupy remain fairly solid. What orchestra doesn't
play the works of Beethoven and Brahms? Even other popular music
genres have their songbooks _ jazz players and cabaret vocalists
converse through standards, their experiments starting from the
same place.
</P>
<P>
   But the best of rock 'n' roll and its siblings, rhythm and blues
and rap, is messier, and always more in dispute. Its landmarks are
often beloved and despised in equal measure, like Led Zeppelin's
fairy-tale opus, ``Stairway to Heaven,'' or most of Elvis' oeuvre.
Even seemingly unbesmirched winners like Bob Dylan face detractors
who dismiss the whole ``classic'' era of the 1960s and hold up
canons full of disco-flavored cheese or obscure garage rock as the
real thing.
</P>
<P>
   Would-be canonizers, and every fan is one, can't even agree on
basic criteria. Rhythmic innovation matters to some, while others
live for the virtuoso guitar solo. Cultists argue for the bohemian
poeticism of artists like Patti Smith, while populists scorn such
pretensions. As for a work's influence, if you're a devotee of
funk, then the Beatles don't matter. If you're a power pop lover,
they're everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I learned most of all was that rock and soul is as
complex and self-contradictory as any living thing,'' critic Dave
Marsh wrote in the definitive work of rock 'n' roll canonizing, his
1989 book ``The Heart of Rock and Soul: the 1001 Greatest Singles
Ever Made.'' The movement is definitely afoot to establish a rock
'n' roll canon, but these efforts never feel complete, to the
credit of the music and its culture. To be a rock or rap or soul
fan is to make an argument. Perhaps the first one is with your
parents, who tell you to turn down that wretched music, but soon
after come the debates with pals who form tribes around their
favorite music styles. Because this intense, if sometimes
delusional, sense of individualism rules rock 'n' roll culture, its
canon is always exploding.
</P>
<P>
   Even the closest thing to an official list, the Rock and Roll
Hall of Fame's exhibit on the 500 most influential songs, seems
designed to stimulate contention. The exhibit, an interactive
display that allows museumgoers to listen to the tracks, includes
often-scorned fare like Duran Duran's ``Hungry Like the Wolf'' and
``U Can't Touch This,'' the M.C. Hammer song that many hip-hop
acolytes think virtually destroyed rap in the 1980s. The Rock Hall
maintains a lively online forum about the songs, allowing fans to
dissect the song list and suggest their own additions. Lightly
regarded artists like Grand Funk Railroad find their defenders,
while critical sacred cows like the Velvet Underground suffer the
jibes of the unconverted.
</P>
<P>
   The positive collision of values is what's made American
culture,'' said former Living Color guitarist Vernon Reid, who has
played rock canonizer at all-star events like this month's tribute
to Prince's 1982 album ``1999'' at the Brooklyn Academy of Music.
``It's the kind of thing where the snake eats its tail and likes
the taste.''
</P>
<P>
   Rock 'n' roll was born at a violated boundary _ between white
and black, rural and urban, commercial and folk _ and even into
middle age, the music thrives on the confusion of the busy
crossroads. Popular charts, industry-based awards and critical
writings compete with equally influential informal forces. Cover
bands maintain the lifespan of songs never nominated for a Grammy;
karaoke singers choose tracks journalists despise. Cultists make
their own collections of obscurities: lounge music revivalists
lionize Martin Denny, while hardcore punks admire Bad Brains.
</P>
<P>
   From these viewpoints a glorious yelling match about greatness
ensues, and those who dare to present their canons in public can
only try to regulate the din. The ``Songs of the Century'' program
at St. Ann's was staged like a classical recital, with five singers
_ Marshall Crenshaw, Jimmie Dale Gilmore, Sandra St. Victor, Beth
Orton and Martha Wainwright _ taking turns in front of a full band.
Holsapple and the night's other curators favored familiar choices,
like ``Blowin' in the Wind.'' Then they threw in a few surprises,
to represent rock's idiosyncratic edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were changing songs until an hour and a half before the
show,'' said Holsapple. ``It could have easily been a show of
standards, kind of a lounge thing, like Bill Murray singing
`Imagine' on `Saturday Night Live.' So it was important to also do
`I Just Wasn't Made for These Times.'''
</P>
<P>
   Such a comment suggests another central debate about whether
singles or albums represent the best of rock. As fine as it is, ``I
Just Wasn't Made for These Times'' is certainly not the most famous
or most perfectly rendered Beach Boys song. Yet many would canonize
it because it appears on the 1966 album ``Pet Sounds,'' which they
consider the Beach Boys' masterpiece, arguing that a classic album
carries more weight than even its own greatest single.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Events like the BAM performance of Prince's ``1999,'' with
singers like Joan Osborne, Corey Glover, Angelique Kidjo and Toshi
Reagon performing the double record in its original sequence, are
making albums seem like rock's equivalent to oratorios. ``The
album, as a form, is very important,'' said Reid. ``It is a song
cycle. There are climaxes and points where the record takes a left
turn; these are crucial things.''
</P>
<P>
   Some rock canonizers avoid this argument by including albums and
singles on their lists. National Public Radio's recently released
compilation of the 100 most important musical works of the century,
to be presented in segments on ``All Things Considered'' and
``Weekend Edition'' throughout the next year, includes nearly every
format and style of American music from modernist symphonies to
two-minute punk songs.
</P>
<P>
   The NPR list was selected by critics, fans and songwriters. Yet
Elizabeth Blair, the producer who coordinated the project, still
wonders if such a list can be truly representative. ``You can't
make a rock canon, because the industry is controlled. Even in the
'50s it was controlled, by company executives, critics and media
program directors,'' she said, neatly implicating herself.
</P>
<P>
   It is true that the demands of business and the tastes of
executives have long affected what music reaches the public. Yet
industry-generated lists can seem as idiosyncratic as those of the
oddest fan, as they cross the borders between good and bad taste.
</P>
<P>
   BMI, which, along with ASCAP, is one of the country's main music
performing rights organizations, recently tallied the contemporary
songs most played on television and radio and in film. No. 1 was
``You've Lost That Lovin' Feelin','' the booming plea for love sung
by the Righteous Brothers, produced by Phil Spector and written by
the stellar team of Barry Mann and Cynthia Weill.
</P>
<P>
   That song is a fairly indisputable work of genius. At its heels,
however, is the wedding reception favorite ``Never My Love'' by the
Association, a group that sounded more like youth choir Up With
People than the Beatles, who occupy the third spot with
``Yesterday.''
</P>
<P>
   The BMI list continues this way, with schmaltzy soft rockers
holding their own against the milestones of rock and soul. One-hit
wonder Merilee Rush rates higher with ``Angel of the Morning'' than
the Supremes and Roy Orbison. The highest-ranking Elvis Presley
song isn't ``Hound Dog'' but ``Suspicious Minds.'' ``(I Can't Get
No) Satisfaction'' squeaks in at 91, ahead of its fellow classics
``Layla'' (93) and ``Imagine'' (96).
</P>
<P>
   The wildly varying quality on the BMI list may seem to confirm
the tendency of music programmers to promote watered-down product.
But consider another roster, this one determined strictly by fans.
``Karaoke's All Time Top 10,'' published online by Karaoke Scene
magazine, is a veritable exaltation of corn. Its critically lauded
songs, like the Patsy Cline tearjerker ``Crazy,'' are worn to the
bone. The rest is pure camp, whether deliberately fashioned, like
``Love Shack'' by the B-52s and ``YMCA'' by the Village People, or
made so by history, like Bette Midler's hyperbolic weeper ``The
Rose.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People are soppy creatures,'' said Gary Stewart, senior vice
president of Rhino Records, the leading label for anthologies.
``Ballads aren't better, but sometimes things that burn bright
don't burn long, and vice versa. I know that there's some music I
could never listen to again in the same way. Like the first Sex
Pistols record and the Clash and the early Who. Those records meant
more to me than any music did at the time. But then there are
perennials that didn't go as deep. Ballads go wide, but not deep.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart and his colleagues at Rhino have created an aesthetic
that jumps from wide to deep to reflect the rock era's intersecting
forces of silliness and profundity. The label's mid-1990s ``Have a
Nice Day'' series exhaustively chronicled pop in the 1970s, just as
that era was being reassessed by young connoisseurs who related
more to the glistening schmaltz of Sweden's Abba than the
overexposed relevance of the Rolling Stones.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart said that the interplay between pop's familiar center
and its hidden corners made anthologizing effective. ``I am against
obscurity for its own sake,'' he said. ``What's exciting to me is
finding the album cuts and the singles and the unreleased tracks
that make people say: `That's great! Why wasn't that a hit?'''
</P>
<P>
   Rhino's playful approach emphasizes the treasure-hunting spirit
that remains a key to the fan's experience of rock. Some collectors
lionize artists who have been kept from the spotlight by bad luck
or the challenging nature of their music. Less scholarly listeners
also find their treasures, often right out in the open. They create
private canons by using music in their daily lives and by
justifying their choices to their friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``The List,'' a popular new program on VH-1, captures that
process. It features celebrities, many hardly music experts,
arguing for their favorites in a given category: Best Love Song,
Sexiest Female Singer, Best Heavy Metal Group. The show evolved
from an older and far less successful program, ``Four on the
Floor,'' which had critics debating the merits of new releases.
``The List'' kept the spirit of argument but emphasized more
individual viewpoints.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realized fun was more important than making the ultimate
list,'' said Jeff Gaspin, executive vice president of programming
at VH-1. ``Music is so personal _ that's what people want to share,
their personal tastes.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR;  &LR; (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Although legendary figures like John Lennon and Jimi Hendrix get
their due on ``The List,'' the show also tends to elevate current
artists and songs, reflecting the relative youth of the panelists.
The show's emphasis on what's hot right now reinforces another
truth about how people experience pop: what they think is classic
changes from year to year. Popular music is an art form people use
informally. Most don't study it in school or turn to it for
edification, as a reading group might turn to Henry James. People
use pop to get hyped up for an evening out, warm up a lover or have
a good cry.
</P>
<P>
   Most musicians also teach themselves a repertory ruled by their
personal tastes. Vernon Reid mastered guitar by playing along to
Santana's ``Caravanserai.'' Peter Holsapple learned songcraft from
the Beatles. ``They spoke to me as a child, as a teen-ager,'' he
said. ``I'm a middle-aged guy now; they're still talking to me.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, popular music itself contains a secret canon, as
musicians interpolate themes from old favorites into their own
songs without necessarily treating them like standards. Nowhere is
this approach more influential than in hip-hop, a genre literally
built from sonic fragments.
</P>
<P>
   There was a songbook, and it's called `Ultimate Breaks and
Beats,''' said ``Chairman'' Jefferson Mao, an editor at the rap
magazine Ego Trip and a co-editor of its just-published ``Ego
Trip's Book of Rap Lists.'' Mao was referring to a 25-volume album
series compiling the most frequently used breakbeats, or snippets
of songs, used by hip-hop DJs to construct their musical collages.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the 150 cuts on these albums, like ``Funky President''
by James Brown, are well-regarded, while others, like ``Apache'' by
the Incredible Bongo Band, are barely known. But each contained a
guitar lick, vocal whoop or drum roll that became part of hip-hop's
alphabet.
</P>
<P>
   After Lenny Roberts, an amateur collector, and the DJ Afrika
Bambaataa began assembling these anthologies in 1986, the treasure
hunt of hip-hop became a much easier game. ``There are songs that,
if you dissect the samples, they are all from volume such and
such,'' said Mao. ``People found a way to mix them in one song.
It's like using `l-m-n-o' as one letter. But they still were able
to flip it in a creative way.''
</P>
<P>
   With DJs besting each other with original twists on the same
breakbeats, hip-hop became an art of references. Although copyright
restrictions that arose when original artists started suing DJs
have limited the number of samples used, a trend classicists like
Mao deeply regret, the craft of crooked assembly still dominates
hip-hop's adventurous edge.
</P>
<P>
   Now that hip-hop is a quarter century old, it is being
institutionalized, like rock before it. The Ego Trip book is part
of that process, along with the publication of ``The Vibe History
of Hip-Hop'' and the major exhibit on the subject staged at the
Rock Hall this year. Yet Mao let forth a scornful laugh at the idea
there could ever be a definitive hip-hop canon.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way to do that,'' he said. ``We did lists of the
greatest MCs and producers. We didn't want to, but people would be
beefing.'' Readers wanted those lists, he said, so they could rip
them apart. ``Everyone wants to argue. Hip-hop and rap, it's all
debate.'' So the canon-making continues, in the tradition of all
the loudmouths who've loved rock 'n' roll.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
