<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6825 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-WASSERSTEIN-ART-2TAKE     12-22 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WASSERSTEIN-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NEWEST WASSERSTEIN CREATION COMES HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By DINITIA SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Say hello to Lucy Jane Wasserstein. Mother:
Pulitzer-prize winning playwright, Wendy Wasserstein. Father: not
yet announced. Born: Sept. 12, 1999, in Mount Sinai Hospital, New
York. Weight: 790 grams, under 2 lbs. And what a production it was!
</P>
<P>
   The director Gerald Gutierrez (``The Heiress,'' ``A Delicate
Balance'') was in the delivery room. The costume designer William
Ivey Long (``Crazy for You,'' ``Chicago,'' ``Guys and Dolls'')
decorated the hospital room. Meryl Streep, Ms. Wasserstein's friend
from the Yale Drama School, sneaked in to see the baby, incognito.
The writer James Lapine (``Passion,'' ``Sunday in the Park With
George'') and the set designer Heidi Ettinger (``Big River,'' ``The
Secret Garden'') brought mother and baby home.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you haven't won a Tony, can you go?'' Ms. Ettinger asked as
she waited outside Mount Sinai's intensive care unit for Lucy Jane
to come out in her car seat for the cab ride to Ms. Wasserstein's
apartment on the Upper West Side.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wasserstein, 49, has long been called ``the voice of her
generation.'' She came of age when a new definition of what it
meant to be a woman was formulating. In a sense, she has lived most
of the stories in her plays.
</P>
<P>
   She was Holly in ``Uncommon Women'' (1977), about a Mount
Holyoke graduate and her friends who cope with the uncertainties of
identity in the new age of feminism. ``My parents used to call me
three times a week at 7 a.m. to ask me, `Are you thin, are you
married to a root-canal man, are  &UR; you &LR;  a root canal man?''' Holly
says at one point.
</P>
<P>
   Janie, the heroine in ``Isn't It Romantic'' (1983), trying to
decide whether to marry a boring doctor, fantasizes about having a
child by herself: ``I can imagine myself at 36, driving
cross-country to inseminate myself with a turkey baster.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to give birth to a little oven-stuffer roaster,''
Janie adds.
</P>
<P>
   And in ``An American Daughter'' (1997), the character Judith
Kaufman, an oncologist, has fertility treatments.
</P>
<P>
   Lucy's birth is in effect the final act of ``The Heidi
Chronicles'' (1989), in which the heroine (whose name was borrowed
from Ms. Ettinger), after much spiritual anguish and backing and
forthing, becomes a single mother and sits, rocking her baby and
singing, ``Darling, you send me. . . . Honest you do, honest you
do, honest you do.''
</P>
<P>
   The real-life baby, Lucy Jane, was born nearly three months
premature and had to stay in the neonatal intensive care unit for
two months, though her mother tried to think of her as being away
at ``a good Jewish boarding school which specializes in the
sciences,'' as usual leavening the painful with a wisecrack. ``She
came early because she knew it was hard to get in,'' Ms.
Wasserstein said. ``She's very competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wasserstein had been thinking about having a child for more
than 10 years, she said. She came from a family of four children.
``Now we're depleted,'' she said; her sister Sandra Meyer died of
cancer in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But before moving ahead, she first had to decide whether to have
the baby alone. Ms. Wasserstein has no husband, or a steady
boyfriend, for that matter. She mentions one particular
relationship with a man that didn't work out.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are a large number of men, gay and straight, whom
Ms. Wasserstein regards as ``husbands,'' she said. They include
Stephen Graham, founder of the New York Theater Workshop; William
Finn, who wrote ``Falsettos''; Andre Bishop, the artistic director
of Lincoln Center Theater; and Gutierrez. She knew that no child of
hers would lack for ``fathers.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wasserstein has always been big on ``to do'' lists. So,
around her 40th birthday, along with ``Lose weight,'' ``Write a
play'' and ``Read more,'' she put, ``Have a baby.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just assumed I would have no trouble, being a big, hearty
girl,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   When that assumption proved wrong, she began having fertility
treatments. ``I would go through periods when there was Perganol
and Clomid,'' she said. But that didn't work. ``I would stop for
two years. It's quite emotional.''
</P>
<P>
   She was 48 and had given up trying when, mourning the death of
her sister, she ran into her old fertility doctor, ``whom I
loved,'' she said. ``He said, `You should try again.' I thought `I
hate you!''' So, she decided, ``Once more, with feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   And this time Ms. Wasserstein got pregnant. Just how, she's not
saying right now, but the father is ``someone I know who I am
keeping anonymous,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   At first, the pregnancy went well. Ms. Wasserstein had a
fellowship at the American Academy in Rome, where she was writing
``Old Money,'' a play about money and class to be produced at
Lincoln Center next fall. She flew back to New York every three
weeks to check in with her doctors.
</P>
<P>
   In her sixth month, she developed pre-eclampsia, high blood
pressure with the potential for both kidney and liver failure. To
preserve the pregnancy, her doctor ordered her to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
