A6826 &Cx1f; gen-z
u f BC-STATES-LABOR-NAT     12-22 0330
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-LABOR-NAT </SLUG>

 &HT;        Temp wages going up 
 &HT;      Higher demand for more skilled workers in a fixed labor market
is a likely cause. 
 &HT;     Laura J. Winter  
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Dec. 22 -- Demand for contingent and alternative
workers is sending weekly wages up, according to statistics
released Tuesday by the Department of Labor's Bureau of Statistics.
</P>
<P>
   The number of people in this group of workers, non-permanent,
have remained at 5.8 million, while their salaries have risen by an
average of 10 percent since 1997. Independent contractors and
contract company employees outpaced other contingent workers with a
22 percent increase in wages from $523 in February 1997 to $640 in
February 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The trend toward higher wages not only reflects the increase in
demand, but makes staffing decisions more painful, said William
Dennis, a senior research fellow at the National Federation of
Independent Businesses Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The small business owner is deciding whether or not it is
worth it to hire a temporary worker or close the store three hours
earlier,'' Dennis said.
</P>
<P>
   Temporary workers since 1997 have seen their wages grow slightly
from $329 a week in 1997 to $342 this year, a 3 percent increase.
On-call workers' wages increased 9 percent from $432 in 1997 to
$472 in 1999. Other contingent workers who did not fit into any
specific category also experienced an increase as well, earning
$540 this year over the $510 two years ago, up 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis said the wage increases were more than demand and supply
reaction but also a change in the quality of worker businesses want
and can hire. The trend, he said, points to more people, especially
independent contractors, with more valuable skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mix of people working these jobs is changing,'' Dennis
said. ``Traditionally workers with lots of skills used to be
employees. What you are seeing are people with lots of skills doing
things independently.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-22-99 1821EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
