<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991222.0274 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6827 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-WASSERSTEIN-ART-2NDTA     12-22 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WASSERSTEIN-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: the hospital.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Each day at 5, cocktail hour, Gutierrez would come by. Ms.
Wasserstein would have juice and the two would ``sit around and
vote for Best Supporting Actor in the Birth of Lucy Jane'' among
the nurses and doctors. Ms. Wasserstein's friend Jane Rosenthal,
co-owner with Robert De Niro of Tribeca Productions, whose name the
playwright used for Janie in ``Isn't It Romantic,'' took over the
producing. ``It was: `Get the nightie. Get the food,''' Ms.
Wasserstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks later, Lucy was born, at about 27 weeks' gestation. At
the same time, Ms. Wasserstein's brother, Bruce, the investment
banker, whose wife was giving birth to a son elsewhere in the
hospital, went around the building proclaiming of Lucy, ``It's my
child!''
</P>
<P>
   As word of the birth got out, friends called to cheer Ms.
Wasserstein on. The director Jerry Zaks told her his daughter had
been in the same neonatal unit and was now bright and healthy.
``Everyone called and said, `My brother was premature and a brain
surgeon,''' Ms. Wasserstein said. ``As far as I know, all premature
babies are brain surgeons.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, just before Thanksgiving, Lucy was doing well enough to
go home for the holidays. Within a week, she had gained a pound,
although, Ms. Wasserstein noted, ``weight gain runs in my family.''
By mid-December, Lucy weighed nearly seven pounds and was
``speaking French in iambic pentameter,'' Ms. Wasserstein said.
``She likes Virginia Woolf.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week Ms. Rosenthal held a baby shower at her home in the
Dakota. There was a pink silk cloth on the table with big pink bows
on it, petits fours, topiary, and chocolate cigars inscribed,
``It's a girl.''
</P>
<P>
   On hand, it seemed, was much of the theater establishment,
including at least two of Lucy Jane's ``fathers,'' Graham and
Bishop. Zaks came, and Paul Rudnick and Terrence McNally. Bernard
Gersten, executive producer of Lincoln Center Theater, was there.
The decorator Mario Buatta, ``the Prince of Chintz,'' was, too.
``He once named a sheet after me,'' Ms. Wasserstein said. Linda
Janklow, chairwoman of Lincoln Center Theater, and Lynn Nesbitt,
the agent, attended. Joan Allen, who played Heidi in the original
``Heidi Chronicles,'' came, and the director Daniel Sullivan. There
was Tina Howe, Marsha Norman and Honor Moore.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, Ms. Wasserstein encapsulated her generation, sitting
at the center of a display of a new kind of mix of femininity,
wealth, power and domesticity. Ms. Rosenthal's personal assistant
mingled with her baby sitter and housekeeper. Her two daughters, in
little silk dresses, looked like children in a Sargent painting.
Lucy herself, though, was not present; it was cold season and no
one wanted her to catch anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to know when you're going to write the play about
this,'' Pat Schoenfeld, the wife of Gerald Schoenfeld, chairman of
the Shubert Organization, asked Ms. Wasserstein. (Ms. Wasserstein
is writing a prose account of her pregnancy.)
</P>
<P>
   ``How's it going?'' said Donna Hanover, wife of New York's
mayor.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's home. She's growing,'' Ms. Wasserstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was time for toasts. ``We just want to raise a glass to
our beloved Wendy,'' Ms. Rosenthal said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just bursting with joy,'' Ms. Wasserstein told the crowd.
``Peter at the end of `The Heidi Chronicles' says, `In our lives
our friends are our families.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And that has been very true in my life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
