A6828 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-AETNA-COX     12-22 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AETNA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Aetna fined for raising rates without approval
 &HT;    By Andy Miller
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _Aetna U.S. Healthcare has agreed to a $50,000 fine and
will pay refunds to employers for raising HMO rates without getting
a state agency's approval.
</P>
<P>
   Employers covering an estimated 700 consumers in Georgia were
charged the unapproved rates and will receive the refunds.
</P>
<P>
   According to a consent order signed Tuesday by Aetna U.S.
Healthcare, the company filed the rate increases with state
Insurance Commissioner John Oxendine's office in April, but didn't
get the agency's permission before implementing the higher rates in
July.
</P>
<P>
   Oxendine said the refunds would amount to an estimated $40,000.
But credits off current and future bills would run ''in the
hundreds of thousands of dollars,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   An Aetna U.S. Healthcare spokesman acknowledged Wednesday that
the company charged the new HMO rates in error. Unlike Georgia,
many other states allow new HMO rates to be implemented without
prior regulatory approval, said spokesman Walt Cherniak.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's simply a mistake,'' Cherniak said. ``We'll work
diligently to rectify the situation and promptly refund the money
back.'' The overall financial impact will be minimal, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Oxendine said the error should not have occurred. ``There's no
excuse for this happening,'' he said. ``I think they were sloppy.''
His office will continue to monitor the Aetna situation, Oxendine
added.
</P>
<P>
   After its recent acquisition of Prudential's health-care
operations, Aetna now provides health insurance for about 900,000
Georgians _ the second-largest statewide enrollment behind Blue
Cross and Blue Shield of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna, though, has the biggest membership among HMOs and similar
point-of-service plans in metro Atlanta, with 300,000 enrollees.
Through its Aetna U.S. Healthcare unit, Hartford-based Aetna is the
largest U.S. managed-care company.
</P>
<P>
   The unapproved HMO rates were charged to employers in July and
August. The Insurance Commissioner's Office notified the company of
the problem in September during a routine review.
</P>
<P>
   Oxendine's action coincides with other marketplace turmoil
involving Aetna. The insurer has triggered local and national
criticism from physicians groups for some contract provisions with
doctors. These include the insurer's ''all-products'' policy, which
requires that if a doctor treats patients in one Aetna plan, such
as a PPO, the doctor must take patients in all Aetna plans,
including those in an HMO.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna explains that the policy guarantees that if patients
switch between Aetna plan types, they won't have to change doctors.
But physicians have complained about Aetna's HMO fees and about
what they call the company's heavy-handed tactics.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have such a market share that if you say, 'I don't want
the all-products clause,' you lose 20 percent to 30 percent of your
patients,'' says Dr. Ted Lewers, chairman of the American Medical
Association's board.
</P>
<P>
   The Medical Association of Georgia, the state's largest
physicians organization, has criticized Aetna's definition of
medical necessity. MAG, in addition, has asked the U.S. Justice
Department to study the group's objections to the Prudential merger
in the metro Atlanta marketplace. Aetna counters that it's a done
deal -- including in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   And recently, Rockdale Hospital decided to stop accepting Aetna
HMO patients starting Jan. 1, after several denials of HMO payments
by the insurer.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna says it's working on a resolution with the Conyers
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
