</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991222.0277 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6830 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-MIDEASTTALKS-NYT     12-22 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIDEAST NEGOTIATORS, ON PALESTINIAN SOIL, BREAK IMPASSE
</HEADLINE>
 TALKS-NYT  (nk) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RAMALLAH, West Bank _ Despite speculation that the resumption of
Israeli-Syrian talks would derail the Palestinian peace track,
significant progress appeared to have been made early Wednesday
morning in an intimate meeting here between Prime Minister Ehud
Barak and the Palestinian leader, Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time that an Israeli prime minister had
ventured into a Palestinian-ruled city for a peace meeting, which
in itself broke a barrier in the relationship. And the setting was
very casual: Barak and Arafat met in the elegant home of the
Palestinian leader's second-in-command, Mahmoud Abbas, better known
as Abu Mazen.
</P>
<P>
   Inside Abu Mazen's villa, the two leaders talked for three hours
from late Tuesday until early Wednesday, gathered with their
associates around a banquet of salads and meat dishes. Outside,
security, both Israeli and Palestinian, was tight, but the meeting
and its location had been kept secret and there were no
disruptions.
</P>
<P>
   After the meeting, both sides said that two deadlocked issues
that have bedeviled progress in the Israeli-Palestinian talks were
essentially resolved. An Israeli transfer of 5 percent of the West
Bank, which has been delayed for five weeks, was likely to take
place within a week, both sides said. And the Israelis were also
expected to release more prisoners as a gesture for Ramadan, the
Islamic holy month now underway.
</P>
<P>
   The details were left to negotiators who did not attend the
late-night summit. Saeb Erekat, a senior Palestinian negotiator,
left an early evening negotiating session in Jerusalem Wednesday
night, declaring that not a single issue had been resolved.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear whether Erekat was sincerely downbeat or adopting
a tough posture. His negative stance stood in contrast to the
comments from two senior Palestinians who attended the late-night
meeting. Exuding confidence, they both said earlier Wednesday that
the Palestinians would ``witness results in the very near future,''
in the words of Nabil Aburdeini, a senior adviser to Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Wednesday, another senior Palestinian had suggested that
the Palestinians, who had held up the land transfer because they
were disappointed that the land consisted largely of unpopulated
desert, were persuaded to accept the original land offered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ah, we still have two other redeployments,'' the senior
Palestinian official said, referring to two more land transfers,
the first scheduled for January. The official suggested that the
Palestinians had been given assurances that more populated
territory would be included in the next Israeli withdrawals from
the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides reported that the atmosphere at the late-night
meeting was good and open, and that they would now accelerate
talks, including more face-to-face sessions between the two
leaders, in preparation for a possible February summit in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting ``renewed the trust and cooperation between the two
sides,'' Foreign Minister David Levy said on Israel Radio, adding
that the territorial transfer was imminent.
</P>
<P>
   Contradicting such optimism, Erekat suggested that summits were
atmospherics. ``We are the ones who do the negotiating,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the late-night summit, Arafat was accompanied not only by Abu
Mazen but also by Abu Ala, the speaker of the Palestinian
Legislative Council. Abu Ala, who received considerable credit for
his role as senior negotiator of the Oslo peace accord, is
technically no longer a negotiator.
</P>
<P>
   But, with his calm, business-like manner, he, as one Palestinian
analyst said is ``the man who has the keys in his hands when things
get stuck.''
</P>
<P>
   Abu Ala reportedly met more than a dozen times with former Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Barak was joined by Levy and Danny Yatom, his security adviser,
both of whom accompanied him to Washington last week.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the meeting, Barak gave Arafat a 40-minute
briefing on his meetings in Washington with the Syrian foreign
minister, Farouk al-Sharaa.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told him that he told Sharaa that we have a commitment
toward Palestinians, and that everything should be honest and
decent,'' a senior Israeli official said. ``He told him that he
told Sharaa that we are not going to play or use one track against
the other because we will lose. We will continue simultaneously.
And he said that Sharaa responded positively and said he
appreciated, understood and respected all that.''
</P>
<P>
   Israeli prime ministers have stepped onto Palestinian soil,
crossing a few yards over the border at the Erez checkpoint in
Gaza. But this represented the first genuine foray into the heart
of the Palestinian Authority's territory, and a kind of submission
to their turf. The Palestinians were decidedly the hosts at the
white stone and red brick villa in a quiet neighborhood. And they
sounded very upbeat afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will witness starting from next week progress in all
respects,'' a senior Palestinian official said. ``Barak promised to
honor all his commitments in the interim agreements. We told him
that this will create a positive atmosphere. Barak also spoke a lot
of settlement activity, and he gave positive promises. But on that
front, it's premature. We have to wait and witness that he does
what he says.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak, whose government has angered Palestinians by authorizing
new construction at Jewish settlements in the West Bank, has
promised to freeze the expansion. He has acknowledged that it was
counter-productive in his deadline pursuit of a final status
framework peace agreement by mid-February.
</P>
<P>
   But the Palestinians are wary. Formal final status negotiations
have stalled because of their concern, although quiet talks have
been continuing. One Palestinian participant in talks about land
and border issues says that even Jerusalem, the touchiest subject
and one that Israel has said is nonnegotiable, has been broached.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Israelis keep talking about the al-Aqsa mosque and the
Mount of Olives,'' he said. ``Which means they are talking about
the fate of Jerusalem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
