<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6836 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-     12-22 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING YOUR HOME ENERGY EFFICIENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most homeowners assume that a home with adequate insulation is
energy efficient. Insulation, however, will only keep interior heat
from passing through solid materials like wallboard or wood.
Weather stripping and caulking are also necessary to stop warm air
from escaping through the many gaps around the house. Together,
weatherstripping and insulation create a thermal barrier between
the inside and outside of the home.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the average homeowner assumes that the only
cracks that need caulk are around the doors and windows of the
house, but there are probably also a number of gaps in the attic
that should be closed. Attic insulation and weather stripping are
important because most heat losses in the home occur through the
roof.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the hot air in the house rises to the top of the
building causing an increase in the air pressure at the ceiling. As
the pressure increases, the hot air slips past the insulation
through open gaps. Failure to seal attic gaps can lessen the
effectiveness of the insulation by as much as half.
</P>
<P>
   The best time to seal gaps in the attic floor is before the
insulation is laid down. Lay planks across the joists and crawl to
the remote corners of the attic. Do not try to walk on the joints;
if you slip, you could fall through the ceiling. Look for gaps
around anything that projects through the ceiling. Wiring,
plumbing, vent stacks, air ducts and the chimney typically have
holes or gaps that should be sealed.
</P>
<P>
   If your attic is already insulated, the search will be a little
more difficult, but not impossible. Most attics are insulated with
fiberglass batts positioned between the joists. These can be rolled
back to expose wiring or duct work. Fiberglass can be irritating to
the skin so wear long pants, a long-sleeved shirt, gloves, goggles
and a dust mask before handling the batts. As you roll back each
batt, look for gray or black smudges on the insulation. These are
indications of air leaks nearby.
</P>
<P>
   It is harder to look for air leaks in attics that are insulated
with loose fill, because this type of insulation cannot be rolled
back. Instead, it must be scooped out into a holding container,
then replaced after the inspection. Here it might be better to hire
a professional weatherization contractor.
</P>
<P>
   Once you have detected gaps, how do you seal them to keep air
from coming through? That depends on the width of the gap and where
it is. Use latex caulk to close narrow cracks (less than 3/8-inch
wide) around pipes and wires. For wider gaps, use expanding
urethane foam. This comes in aerosol cans. Be careful when using
this foam because it is hard to remove from clothes. You can also
make plugs out of drywall or fiberglass insulation stuffed in
plastic bags and wedge these into wide cracks.
</P>
<P>
   Do not use caulk or insulation to plug gaps around the chimney
because the heat from the chimney could damage it. Instead, make a
metal collar out of roof flashing. Tack one side of the flashing to
the top of a nearby joist and push the other edge against the
chimney.
</P>
<P>
   The entry to most attics is through a hole in the attic floor.
This is usually closed with either a door or a hatch. Even though
the door is inside the house, it should have a layer of insulation
on the attic side, and weatherstripping around the edges around the
hatch.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a forced-air heating system, examine the duct work
that runs through the attic. Leaky heating ducts allow hot air to
spill into the attic and pull cold air into the heating system.
Most leaks occur at the joints between duct sections. In some
cases, the sections may actually have pulled apart, but often they
may only be loose.
</P>
<P>
   Reconnect the disjointed sections then seal all joints with duct
mastic. If the joints are wide or have a tendency to separate,
reinforce the mastic with fiberglass mesh tape or aluminum tape. Do
not use the familiar gray cloth tape, often called ''duct tape,''
because the heat from the ducts will cause it to dry out and
deteriorate. After sealing the joints, wrap the ducts with
foil-faced fiberglass insulation. Use cable ties to hold the
insulation in place.
</P>
<P>
   You may be tempted to pack insulation around recessed ceiling
lights, but don't do it. These lights generate heat so they must
have at least three inches clearance space on all sides for
cooling. If you suspect that the present lights are letting air
flow past, you can replace these fixtures with special IC fixtures
that have air-and moisture-tight housings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
