<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SRILANKA-ELECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SRI LANKA'S NEWLY RE-ELECTED PRESIDENT VOWS TO DEFEAT REBELS 
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOMBO, Sri Lanka _ Gulping back tears, a white bandage on her
right eye from a bomb attack four days ago, Sri Lanka's president
claimed a divine mandate Wednesday to pursue and defeat the rebels
who had tried to kill her.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the wounds of sheer naked and unadulterated hatred
of man for man,'' she said, her voice quavering. She called for
peace, but she also vowed ``the strongest possible action'' against
the ethnic Tamil separatists if they persisted in their 16-year
insurgency.
</P>
<P>
   It was victory day for President Chandrika Kumaratunga, who won
a second term in office with what, by Sri Lankan standards, was a
tiny electoral majority of 51.2 percent _ just over the 50 percent
needed to win.
</P>
<P>
   That represented a sheer drop from the 62 percent she had won in
1994 with a promise to end the fighting. In a sort of emblem of the
futility of successive government policies, that promise has been
replaced by an aggressive military campaign that was given the name
``war for peace.''
</P>
<P>
   The result has been an upsurge in the fighting and, since early
November, catastrophic government losses of troops and territory in
the northern Jaffna Peninsula, which the rebels claim as a
homeland.
</P>
<P>
   Sri Lanka's war is an ethnic conflict growing out of deep
historical hatreds that have only been sharpened as each side turns
more cruelly on the other in this nation of 18 million people.
</P>
<P>
   Its roots are in British colonial times when the Tamil minority
was favored in education and administrative positions. After
independence in 1948, the 74 percent Sinhalese majority turned
against the Tamils, removing them from positions of influence and
disenfranchizing many of them.
</P>
<P>
   The last 16 years have been marked by ambushes, assassinations
and massacres of entire villages in which the victims have
overwhelmingly been civilians. The war has now taken more than
60,000 lives, made refugees of one in every 18 people and turned
parts of this lovely island nation into a place of unending
bloodshed and deepening despair.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody could be sure, but many now believe that the suicide bomb
attack against Mrs. Kumaratunga at her final election rally on
Saturday gave the president the sympathy vote she needed to win.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike former prime minister Rajiv Gandhi of India in 1991 and
several Sri Lankan leaders before her, Mrs. Kumaratunga, 54,
survived the attack. But at least 24 other people were killed and
scores were wounded when the bomber detonated the explosives.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Kumaratunga seemed to find a deep significance in her
survival and the election victory that followed, saying, ``The gods
have seen fit to honor me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This victory is without doubt a very special and portentous
gift of the gods,'' she said, ``for I believe that there now stands
before you the one leader who is the single most qualified to lead
us to the peace we long for.''
</P>
<P>
   But buried in the electoral numbers of her victory was what
seemed to be a warning of harsher divisions in a nation whose
patience with the conflict has worn thin.
</P>
<P>
   Radhika Coomaraswamy, a political analyst with the International
Center for Ethnic Studies, a private policy group, said the
electorate seemed to have become more fractured, potentially
complicating future efforts to find a peaceful resolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``What strikes me when I look at the results is the extreme
polarization of the country, the fact that the minority votes
seemed to go quite heavily in favor of the UNP and that the urban
centers seem to have gone heavily in favor of the UNP,'' she said,
using the initials for the opposition United National Party.
</P>
<P>
   This is the party of Ranil Wickremesinghe, who placed second in
the multiparty field with 43 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``So it is important for Chandrika to realize that this is a
country more and more divided, both along race and class lines,''
Ms. Coomaraswamy said, referring to the president by her first
name.
</P>
<P>
   These are new political divisions that have appeared since the
last election, she said. In particular, Tamils have been feeling
the effects of daily official harassment, suspicion, discrimination
and frequent military and police checkpoints.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an overemphasis on security,'' said D.B.S. Jeyaraj, a
Sri Lankan journalist who follows the insurgency closely. ``A lot
of Tamils are harassed. A lot are arrested and kept without
trial.''
</P>
<P>
   The president seemed to take these issues into account in her
speech Wednesday, in which she condemned ``hatred and its curse and
destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   She urged Tamil citizens to join her in seeking a peaceful
solution and to ``use every ounce of influence'' to bring the
separatist leader, Vellupillai Prabhakaran, to the negotiating
table.
</P>
<P>
   ``I urge you to persuade with every conceivable argument anyone
who is a member or a supporter of the LTTE to renounce violence and
join us in establishing peace,'' she said, using the initials of
the insurgent group, the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eeelam.
</P>
<P>
   In a policy that took second place to her aggressive military
campaign, Mrs. Kumaratunga has said she will seek constitutional
changes that would give greater autonomy to regional governments.
</P>
<P>
   This would go part way to meeting the rebel demands by giving
them greater say over the heavily Tamil north and east, where they
have sought to create a separate state.
</P>
<P>
   But the president also sounded a warlike note Wednesday, saying,
``Let all the citizens of this country be warned that this
government will not for one second be deterred from taking the
strongest possible action against anyone who supports terror.''
</P>
<P>
   But strong actions have already been tried and have brought only
further bloodshed, Ms. Coomaraswamy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her strategy has not succeeded; it is a failure,'' she said.
``She has to rethink her policy and she has to rethink it with the
help of the international community. That is absolutely essential.
If she does not do that, there will be disaster here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
