<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6843 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-ROLLER-COASTER-SAFETY     12-22 1510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROLLER-COASTER-SAFETY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SOME INJURIES LINKED TO TEXAS ROLLER COASTER GO UNREPORTED 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Attn: Texas)  
 &HT;     (Eds: Sydne Purvis is CQ)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN TEDESCO  
 &HT;     c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Frank Sanchez, a 29-year-old postal carrier, was
screaming.
</P>
<P>
   He clung to a handrail on a warm, Sunday afternoon as a ride at
a San Antonio theme park sent him plummeting to Earth.
</P>
<P>
   It ``really shakes you up'' Sanchez yelled as the Rattler wound
its way through a long, dipping spiral.
</P>
<P>
   Built seven years ago out of Southern yellow pine and Douglas
fir, the Rattler is the flagship roller coaster at Fiesta Texas, a
mountain of timber located near a limestone cliff and a waterfall.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez, rattled but smiling after his encounter with the
towering ride, said he thought the shaking cars were going to
hurtle off the track.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was rough,'' he said. ``It feels like you're going to be
sore after the ride.''
</P>
<P>
   High speeds, a steep drop and the rough nature of the Rattler
are some of its most attractive features to roller-coaster
enthusiasts.
</P>
<P>
   They also are factors that caused dozens of personal injury
lawsuits to be filed against the park, resulting in a $3.5 million
group settlement for 27 plaintiffs in January 1998, lawyers
announced at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Among the documents San Antonio lawyer Randall Jackson came
across during litigation against Fiesta Texas were hundreds of
ambulance reports made during the park's early years.
</P>
<P>
   From 1992 to 1993, Fiesta Texas reported to the state Department
of Insurance that only 13 people were treated for neck and back
injuries on the Rattler and other rides. But the park left out
reports of at least 110 other people who suffered from similar or
more serious injuries. All of them were treated by medical
personnel and transported to hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was dangerous, because they (Fiesta Texas) wanted to set
all these world records and create this extremely scary ride to
attract people to the park,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   The park didn't report the case of a 28-year-old woman with a
possible broken collarbone who ``couldn't remember'' her accident.
Instances of guests suffering unconsciousness and loss of memory
from head injuries went unreported. One teen-age guest who rode the
Rattler simply freaked out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patient states he is scared and doesn't understand why,'' a
paramedic for the park's private ambulance service wrote in his
report.
</P>
<P>
   In other unreported incidents, a paramedic wrote of a
57-year-old Rattler victim: ``(Patient) says she can't walk and it
hurts to stand.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Due to the severity of the injury I was unable to obtain a
statement'' from the patient, wrote another paramedic, who helped
treat a 39-year-old woman.
</P>
<P>
   Several other people who suffered neck injuries said they could
not feel their legs, arms and extremities.
</P>
<P>
   Confusion about what to do with less serious precautionary
transports _ patients who were X-rayed but didn't appear to be
seriously injured _ led Fiesta Texas officials to ask whether such
incidents have to be accounted for.
</P>
<P>
   It was a pertinent question. In all, Fiesta Texas medical
personnel treated 227 people for ride-related injuries during the
park's first two seasons. Almost all of them complained of neck and
back pain.
</P>
<P>
   About 80 patients were precautionary transports, while 30 others
had more serious symptoms. The rest were treated and released at
the park.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is medical treatment?'' asked Phil Villareal, then the
safety manager at Fiesta Texas, during an Aug. 26, 1993, public
hearing in Austin. ``If I give you an X-ray and say you got just a
muscle strain and I give you some Motrin, is that medical
treatment?''
</P>
<P>
   By the time the question was raised, plans already were in the
works to tame the roller coaster. Months later, Fiesta Texas
shortened the Rattler's first drop from 166 to 122 feet, and
authorities decided in October 1994 that precautionary transports
should be reported.
</P>
<P>
   Park officials said the Rattler's modifications were made in
response to guest feedback.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Serff, who came on board as Fiesta Texas' manager in the
summer of 1993, said he couldn't explain the apparent discrepancy
in reporting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure how to answer that,'' said Serff, who is now
president of the Texas Travel Industry Association. ``I'm sure
there was good rationale.''
</P>
<P>
   Villareal, the past safety manager of Fiesta Texas, said the
park complied with state law as far as he remembered.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was based on what they required,'' Villareal said. ``That's
about as far as I can tell you.''
</P>
<P>
   A subsidiary of USAA and Nashville-based Opryland originally
owned Fiesta Texas, but Six Flags took over the park in January
1996 in a 10-year lease arrangement. Oklahoma City-based Premier
Parks acquired Six Flags in April 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone seems to enjoy the Rattler now as they do all of our
other roller-coaster offerings,'' Fiesta Texas spokeswoman Sydne
Purvis said. ``There has been no controversy surrounding it (since
Six Flags took over). It is one of the favorite wooden roller
coasters in existence.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Six Flags bought the park in 1996, 80 people have been
transported from Fiesta Texas to local hospitals, dispatch records
show. During that same period, the park reported 32 injuries to the
Insurance Department _ less than half of all its reported injuries
since the park's opening.
</P>
<P>
   Purvis said Fiesta Texas routinely transports anyone who
requests an ambulance, and not all of the recent injuries occurred
on rides. She declined to provide copies of recent ambulance run
reports with patient names blacked out, saying such records were
proprietary.
</P>
<P>
   Under a practice encouraged by the Insurance Department, Fiesta
Texas doesn't report injuries if guests seek medical treatment on
their own and notify the park later, Purvis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the guest should decide several days later that there is a
problem, and they did not seek out medical attention immediately,
then obviously it's very difficult to track them,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities say the policy makes sense and applies to all ride
owners. Otherwise, people could claim they suffered injuries at a
park without even being there.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the procedure isn't foolproof. On May 1, 1998, Lydia
Quiroga, a 23-year-old tortilla maker from Brownsville, cut her
head while on a water ride at Fiesta Texas, court documents allege.
</P>
<P>
   Quiroga went to the first-aid station, where workers told her
how to get to a hospital, said her lawyer, Eddie Lucio of Dallas.
The woman required three stitches and she was later diagnosed with
a dislocated jaw, according to her medical records.
</P>
<P>
   Lucio said Fiesta Texas offered Quiroga a discount pass when she
asked if the park could help pay her medical bills. Quiroga sued.
State authorities have no record of the alleged injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel they were really insensitive,'' Lucio said of Fiesta
Texas. ``There was no feeling of, `Let's help her, let's talk to
her afterward to make sure everything's OK.'''
</P>
<P>
   On July 19, 1997, Jean Accord of Austin was watching the evening
laser show at Fiesta Texas when her 12-year-old son, Michael Garza,
walked up to her in tears.
</P>
<P>
   The boy said he hit his head while riding the Rattler, and
Accord could see some redness on his forehead. But Garza insisted
he was fine and the group of family and friends went back to their
room at the Omni Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   At 3 a.m. the next morning, Garza woke up his mother. There was
a large bump on his forehead and his nose was bleeding, Accord
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he had a really bad headache,'' Accord said in an
interview. ``His pillow was full of blood.''
</P>
<P>
   Garza was diagnosed with two hematomas on his head and a mild
concussion, according to emergency room reports from Brackenridge
Hospital in Austin. Accord took her son to the same hospital a
second time after he began vomiting and complaining of dizziness, a
side effect of some head injuries.
</P>
<P>
   When Garza's mother called Fiesta Texas the day after the
injury, she was continually put on hold and transferred from person
to person, she said. An employee finally talked to her after
several tries. He told her to get a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `We're not going to do anything because there's no
report,''' Accord said of the conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Fiesta Texas didn't report the alleged injury to the Insurance
Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't aware of the severity of the injury until hours
later,'' Accord said. ``The physician said this particular injury
wouldn't have shown up right away. I contacted them (Fiesta Texas)
immediately as soon as I found out about it. They kept telling me
there's no injury report.''
</P>
<P>
   Insurance Department spokesman Mark Hanna acknowledged that
injuries go unaccounted for if guests notify the park after the
fact. ``It's hard to keep track of an injury that really doesn't
surface until some time later,'' Hanna said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
