<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6845 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-ETHICS-TEXAS-COX     12-22 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ETHICS-TEXAS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Privacy issues raised over Internet campaign fund lists
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The Texas Ethics Commission is churning, slowly,
toward allowing Texans to use the Internet to see who's giving to
state political campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   But the law requiring Internet publication, in the name of
privacy, forbids the Ethics Commission from including home
addresses of donors on the Web site version of the reports. That
information still would be available on paper reports filed at the
Ethics Commission headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the law, passed earlier this year, say a list without
addresses is not much of a list. They are trying to make sure that
computer diskettes available for purchase from the agency will
include addresses. The Ethics Commission has asked Attorney General
John Cornyn to decide that issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without addresses it is impossible to know whether
contributions to a candidate from a Bob Smith and a B. Smith from
downtown Houston are from the same person,'' Fred Lewis, executive
director of Campaigns for People, an Austin nonprofit group that
pushes for open government. told Cornyn in a legal brief. ``It
becomes even more difficult when there are B. Smiths, R. Smiths,
R.E. Smiths, Bobby Smiths, Bob Smiths and Robert Smiths giving to
hundreds of political action committees and candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas will join 31 states that have at least some portions of
the reports posted on web sites. Another 11 states have systems in
the works.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Holman of the California-based Center for Governmental
Studies said Texas has done a good thing by going to Internet
posting of campaign finance reports. But Holman said Texas but did
a bad thing by deleting addresses from the reports. Very few states
(California is one) have deleted addresses from the reports on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most states put the same information up on web sites that they
put on paper,'' he said, adding that the argument against including
addresses is based on protecting donors from commercial and
political solicitations. ``I don't consider that a good reason not
to publish addresses on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   The skirmish over donors' home addresses is the latest front in
the computer-age battle between privacy and disclosure. Until the
evolution of cyberspace, public records generally were sheets of
paper available only to people willing to make a trip to the
Capitol, the courthouse or city hall. The records were public, but
required an effort to procure.
</P>
<P>
   Now, thanks to the Internet, people with a computer and a modem
can quickly find out things like the appraised value of their
neighbors' homes or lawsuits involving their in-laws.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Texas law, sponsored by Austin Rep. Sherri Greenberg,
addresses ``must remain available on the report maintained in the
commission's office but may not be available electronically at that
office.''
</P>
<P>
   The question pending with Cornyn is whether addresses will be
included on computer diskette versions of the reports that the
Ethics Commission must make available ``at a reasonable cost.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis argues that the section of the law that says donors'
addresses ``may not be available electronically'' at the Ethics
Commission office does not apply to computer diskettes.
</P>
<P>
   ``A computer diskette is not itself electronic. It does not use
electricity and is not an electronic device,'' Lewis wrote in his
brief to Cornyn.
</P>
<P>
   Suzy Woodford of Common Cause fears that the law, intended to
help Texans get a clear idea of whose money is behind candidates,
could become a step backward if Cornyn rules that the diskette
versions of the list do not have to include addresses.
</P>
<P>
   Woodford's organization, in the name of privacy, supported the
effort to keep donors' addresses off the Internet version of the
reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are crazies out there ... ,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But Woodford believes home addresses should be on the diskette
version. And she fears that a Cornyn ruling to the contrary could
inspire some lawmakers to take a shot at removing addresses from
all versions of the reports, including the paper ones available for
scrutiny at the agency office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see this as the beginning of going down a slippery slope,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   While awaiting Cornyn's ruling on its request for an opinion on
the diskette question, the Ethics Commission is moving forward with
its plans for electronic dissemination. The agency recently signed
a $525,000 contract with California-based SDR Technologies Inc. to
develop the software for the electronic reports. The reports are
expected to be available on the Internet in July.
</P>
<P>
   The law requires the reports to be in a format that allows the
data to be exported into spreadsheets.
</P>
<P>
   But any version of the reports without donors' addresses are of
questionable value, according to Lewis. In Texas, where there is no
limit on the generosity of political donors, disclosure is the only
way ``to regulate campaigns and special influence,'' he told
Cornyn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas already makes it difficult to identify contributors (and
the special interests they represent) by not requiring contributors
to list their employer and occupation,'' Lewis told Cornyn.
``Taking away addresses will make the task virtually impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   And because addresses are so crucial, they also become quite
valuable. Currently, companies that make a buck by compiling
mailing lists of politically active Texans spend hours looking at
the paper reports and copying the names and addresses line by line.
</P>
<P>
   Making those lists available on computer diskettes could make
their jobs easier, but it also could make their product much less
valuable.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
