<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BONDS MIXED AS REVISIONS IN GROWTH NUMBERS HAVE LITTLE EFFECT 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Treasury securities were mixed Wednesday, as the government's
auction of $15 million of two-year notes weighed on the bond
market.
</P>
<P>
   Traders said the market largely ignored the unexpected upward
revision to third-quarter growth because those numbers seemed like
very old news.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the attention was on whether there would be any
interest in the two-year auction. The Dec. 31 settlement date on
the notes was expected to discourage many investors concerned about
year 2000 problems from participating in the note sale. Problems
associated with the settlement date were probably priced in, some
traders said.
</P>
<P>
   The 6[ percent coupon rate at auction matched that of an
outstanding five-year maturity originally issued Dec. 31, 1996. Its
yield at auction was 6.233 percent, the highest since 6.328 at the
May 1997 auction more than two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   By late in the day, the 30-year Treasury bond was up 2/32, to 95
23/32. Its yield, which moves in the opposite direction, fell to
6.45 percent from 6.46 percent on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the session, the government reported that third-quarter
gross domestic product was revised upward to 5.7 percent from the
5.5 percent reported last month. Even though the market reacted
little to the change, the data provided more evidence of the
economy's strength.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Fine, chief market analyst at Chase Asset Management,
said that, as expected, the Federal Open Market Committee kept
monetary policy unchanged at its December meeting on Tuesday ``in
order to minimize market gyrations during the Y2K transition
period, but despite its officially stated neutral bias, the Fed is
aware of the inflation risks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Further pre-emptive tightening is widely anticipated during
the first quarter of next year in the absence of any evidence
pointing to a slackening of economic growth to a noninflationary
pace,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With the Fed poised to raise rates again in the first quarter,
some investors might have been reluctant to buy into the auction of
two-year notes, which are among the most sensitive to changes in
Fed rate policy.
</P>
<P>
   Demand was weaker than at the last auction, judging by the
bid-to-cover ratio, which gauges demand by comparing the number of
bids with the amount of securities sold. The bid to cover was
2.10-1, down from 2.46-1 at the sale on Nov. 23. For the last six
auctions the average ratio has been 2.23-1.
</P>
<P>
   Still, after the recent rise in yields, some investors found the
securities attractive. In the last month, two-year yields have
climbed the most of all Treasury securities due in more than one
year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
