<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PROBOWL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jaguars, Ravens pack Pro Bowl picks
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   With two of the best records in the NFL, the Jacksonville
Jaguars and St. Louis Rams are popular picks to play in Super Bowl
XXXIV in the Georgia Dome on Jan. 30.
</P>
<P>
   Both of those teams also will be well represented in the Feb. 6
Pro Bowl in Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   The Jaguars, who have the league's best record at 13-1, placed
an NFL-high seven players on the AFC all-star squad. Baltimore
placed five players on the team, with Oakland and Tennessee sending
four apiece.
</P>
<P>
   In the NFC, the Rams and the Tampa Bay Buccaneers each had six
players selected to the team. Dallas, Detroit and Minnesota each
had five players voted to the squad.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons, who had six players in the game after last season's
improbable flight to the Super Bowl, failed to have anyone selected
this year.
</P>
<P>
   The 42-man rosters were chosen by a combination of voting by
fans, coaches and players. A 43rd ``need'' player, chosen by each
team's head coach, must be a linebacker or a defensive end.
</P>
<P>
   Fan voting counted as one-third of the total, and each NFL team
had two equal votes, those of the coach and a consensus vote of the
players. No one was permitted to choose a player on his own team.
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville wide receiver Jimmy Smith, offensive tackle Tony
Boselli, defensive end Tony Brackens, outside linebacker Kevin
Hardy and free safety Carnell Lake all were chosen as starters.
</P>
<P>
   Jaguars quarterback Mark Brunell is a backup to Indianapolis'
Peyton Manning, who was voted the AFC starter in only his second
season. Colts receiver Marvin Harrison and rookie running back
Edgerrin James also were chosen first-time starters.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee's Jevon Kearse, who leads the AFC with 13 1/2 sacks,
became the first AFC rookie defensive end named to the team since
the AFL-NFL merger in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams had six players voted NFC starters _ quarterback Kurt
Warner, receiver Isaac Bruce, running back Marshall Faulk,
offensive tackle Orlando Pace, defensive end Kevin Carter and
cornerback Todd Lyght.
</P>
<P>
   The Buccaneers, who have a one-game lead over Detroit in the NFC
Central, had five players voted starters. Defensive tackle Warren
Sapp, linebackers Derrick Brooks and Hardy Nickerson and strong
safety John Lynch all were chosen on defense. The Bucs' Mike
Alstott is the starting fullback.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
