<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6853 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-DEAN-SMITH-BOOK-REVIE     12-22 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEAN-SMITH-BOOK-REVIEW-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`A COACH'S LIFE': INSIGHT BUT LITTLE CONTROVERSY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., Kan.)  (Eds: Publication notes at end of review)  
(rk) 
 By BEN STEELMAN   
 Wilmington (N.C.) Morning Star   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dean Smith has coached in the Olympics, won two national titles,
broken Adolph Rupp's record of games won and had a sports temple,
``the Dean Dome,'' named in his honor at the University of North
Carolina at Chapel Hill. Now, he has produced a book called ``A
Coach's Life.''
</P>
<P>
   No, Dean Smith did not invent basketball, although the
connection's close; at the University of Kansas, young Dean played
for Phog Allen, who had played for James Naismith himself.
(Actually, Smith writes, ``Doc'' Allen was starting to get ``a
little absent-minded by the early 1950s, and his assistant, Dick
Harp may have been a greater influence.)
</P>
<P>
   And yes, once upon a time, they did burn Dean Smith in effigy at
Chapel Hill. That was back in 1964, when the Tar Heels _ still
reeling from the effects of NCAA sanctions and the scandals that
led to the abolition of the Dixie Classic Tournament _ ended the
season 12-12 and in fifth place in the Atlantic Coast Conference.
Thereafter, Carolina never finished lower than third in the ACC;
the last time it won fewer than 20 games was in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Coach's Life'' tells the story of that remarkable dynasty
from the point of view of the coach's bench.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan, plays a big part, of course. (Smith confirms the
account of his recruiting in David Halberstam's recent book, and
gives assistants Roy Williams and Eddie Fogler full credit for
scouting the young prospect.)
</P>
<P>
   But there are other names, too. What's remarkable, in fact, has
been the postgraduate record of North Carolina teams. Many players
and coaching assistants went on to become leaders themselves in the
NCAA and pro ranks, such as Roy Williams at Kansas, Eddie Fogler at
South Carolina, George Karl with the Milwaukee Bucks or Mitch
Kupchack, the general manager of the L.A. Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   And the roster of Smith's All-Americans also includes dozens of
doctors, lawyers, pastors, career military officers, teachers and a
chairman of Chase Manhattan Corp. (Bill Harrison, '66).
</P>
<P>
   Dean Smith not only taught his players to be champs; somehow, he
also taught them to be gentlemen. Even their peccadilloes, such as
Phil Ford's recent DWI, pale beside the outrages that seem routine
these days in the pro and college ranks.
</P>
<P>
   How did he do it? The secret seems to lie in Emporia, Kan.,
where young Dean grew up until his sophomore year. A small prairie
town, Emporia was once known as the home of William Allen White,
the local editor, who was still a nationally respected commentator
when young Dean reached high school. Smith calls himself a Democrat
now, but his principles seem close to White's version of
progressive Republicanism.
</P>
<P>
   More to the point, he was the son of schoolteachers and devout
American (Northern) Baptists. His dad, Alfred Smith, the Emporia
high school coach, showed him how to dress down a player without
cursing; more to the point, he put a black player on his team in
the depths of the Depression, despite grumblings that could have
threatened his job.
</P>
<P>
   Smith points out that he did not desegregate the ACC; Maryland
fielded blacks several seasons before he did. Yet he recruited
Charlie Scott when it was still controversial to do so, and his
outspoken promotion of racial harmony undoubtedly helped the whole
state, not just in sports.
</P>
<P>
   While he studied and learned from many coaches, his chief
influences were undoubtedly Dick Harp, who helped introduce the
pressure defense at Kansas, and Bob Spear, his boss when Smith was
assistant coach at the Air Force Academy. Hemmed in by height
restrictions _ no cadet could be taller than 6-foot-4 _ and
shortened practice times, Spear focused on team-play strategies
that could neutralize an opponent's stars. Smith would evolve his
ideas into such mutant monsters as the Four Corners.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Coach's Life'' plays with one disadvantage; Smith clearly
believes that if you can't say something nice, don't say anything.
He still defends his old boss, Frank McGuire against charges of
recruiting violations; the worst he'll accuse him of is sloppy
expense reporting. He even says nice things about his ex-wife _ and
the summary of his failed first marriage in one paragraph tells you
how carefully this gentleman guards his privacy.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `A COACH'S LIFE'
</P>
<P>
   By Dean Smith with John Kilgo and Sandy Jenkins
</P>
<P>
   Random House, $25
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (The Wilmington Star in Wilmington, N.C., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
