<HEADER>
A6855 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLYMPICS-COST-NYT &LR;      12-22 0577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLYMPICS-COST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIC GAMES COSTLY FOR THE U.S., REPORT SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By IRVIN MOLOTSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal report released Tuesday found that the
staging of Olympic Games in the United States, which is widely
viewed as financed by corporate sponsors, also costs the federal
government hundreds of millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The report said that $200 million in federal money would be
spent for the 2002 Winter Olympic Games in Salt Lake City ``for
safety- and security-related services, which would not have been
used for this purpose if the Games were not being hosted there.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitt Romney, president of the Salt Lake Organizing Committee,
said when asked about the report, ``My guess is that $400 million
to $500 million in federal funds will be spent for projects that
are exclusively Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   Romney said that half of that would go toward anti-terrorism
activities conducted by the Justice Department and half to
transportation and highways. ``Half a billion dollars is a lot of
money, but it is money well spent,'' Romney said. ``The Olympics
are a great symbol of peace on the world stage and good business
for the hosting country.''
</P>
<P>
   Lower but substantial amounts of federal money were spent at the
1984 Summer Games in Los Angeles and the 1996 Summer Games in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The study was conducted by the General Accounting Office, the
principal investigative agency of Congress, and was limited to
federal money, excluding whatever is spent by state and local
governments.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are certainly state and municipal funds that must go
into infrastructure,'' said Dennis Fitzgibbons, a congressional
aide who made the report available. ``Many Olympics projects do not
qualify for federal dollars. We do not have a good accounting on
how much state and municipal spending there is.''
</P>
<P>
   Fitzgibbons is deputy staff director for the minority Democrats
on the House Commerce Committee. The ranking Democrat on that
committee, Rep. John D. Dingell of Michigan, asked for the study
last January following reports of abuses and gift-taking by Olympic
officials.
</P>
<P>
   It was given a bipartisan tone when Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz.,
joined the request. He is chairman of the Senate Commerce, Science
and Transportation Committee.
</P>
<P>
   When Dingell requested the study, he said: ``I am fully aware
that the Olympics are generally considered a
private-sector-financed endeavor. Nevertheless, the level of
federal funds that must be used to support a host city is
formidable.''
</P>
<P>
   In releasing the study Tuesday, Dingell said that the award of
the Olympics to a city has become ``the impetus for massive amounts
of federal largesse,'' although ``there has been no conscious
decision by the taxpayers or their representatives to spend the
money on the Games.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That needs to change, especially when the taxpayers' tab for
the Salt Lake Games may approach almost $2 billion, according to
the GAO,'' Dingell said. ``This is an amount far in excess of
previous estimates.''
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman for the U.S. Olympic Committee, Mike Moran, said
in Colorado Springs: ``The cost of the Games has been borne in this
country by the private sector. Nobody's tried to hide the federal
money. The government commitment has always been known.'' The $2
billion that Dingell referred to includes $1.1 billion that would
eventually have been provided to Utah even if the Olympics were not
held there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
