A6856 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-UN-NEWYEAR-BOS &LR;      12-22 0466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-NEWYEAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREATS BRING ORDER TO CLOSE UN NEW YEAR'S EVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE LAURIA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ ``Credible'' terrorist threats prompted UN
officials Wednesday to order the closing of their headquarters on
New Year's Eve, in what is believed to be the first shutdown of the
massive complex in midtown Manhattan in decades.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to close the headquarters was announced to
reporters during a day of high-level security meetings here.
</P>
<P>
   One official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said UN
headquarters routinely receives threats, but most are dismissed as
hoaxes. He refused to provide details but said the latest threats
were ``credible'' and being taken seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, the FBI has sent an intelligence report to thousands
of state and local police describing apocalyptic groups who
``advocate or call for violent action beginning in the year 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Included in these groups are ``radical elements of private
citizen militias who fear that the United Nations will initiate an
armed takeover of the United States and subsequently establish a
One World Government,'' the FBI says.
</P>
<P>
   The UN's chief of security, Michael McCann, said officially that
there is no terrorist threat from any US militia group or any other
source against the building at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   However, the other UN official said security has decided not to
disclose what have been described as the most serious threats
against the UN complex since February 1997, when a letter bomb was
intercepted by UN security before it reached a Lebanese journalist
based here.
</P>
<P>
   Three years earlier, then-Secretary General Boutros
Boutros-Ghali ordered sandbags placed in an underground garage and
restricted visitors to UN headquarters after federal authorities
uncovered a plot by Islamic militants to blow up several New York
landmarks, including UN headquarters, in the wake of the World
Trade Center bombing. Since then, the United Nations has installed
metal detectors at the staff entrance and a new high-security gate
at the vehicle entrance.
</P>
<P>
   McCann said additional security will be added to the building,
which will be closed on 1 p.m. on Dec. 31. It will reopen to
non-essential staff Jan. 4 at the earliest, a UN official said. It
is the first time in memory that UN headquarters was closed to all
but essential staff because of a potential security threat, said
McCann.
</P>
<P>
   He said New York City police, as part of their heightened
anti-terrorist alert throughout the city, would provide additional
security in front of the First Avenue headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   McCann took the unusual step of asking reporters to cooperate
with security measures by reporting any suspicious person or
object.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
