<SLUG> BC-NAYA-BANKRUPTCY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAYA, THE BOTTLER OF SPRING WATER, SEEKS BANKRUPTCY PROTECTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Naya Inc., the bottler of spring water, has filed for bankruptcy
protection in Canada, in a reversal of the stellar rise that had
much to do with its having once been distributed by Coca-Cola Co.'s
largest bottler.
</P>
<P>
   Naya's president, Stu Levitan, said Wednesday that the company,
which is based in Mirabel, Quebec, would continue to fill orders
while it reorganizes. It filed for protection from creditors on
Dec. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Until May, about 65 percent of Naya's bottled water had been
distributed by Coca-Cola Enterprises, which gave it access to
stores and other outlets across the United States and Canada. When
Coca-Cola introduced its own bottled water, Dasani, this year, the
bottler stopped carrying Naya after six months, although in many
markets it still offers Evian, a French spring water sold by Danone
SA.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to embark on a new system of distribution in the U.S.
and Canada,'' Levitan said, noting that the company now uses a
combination of direct-store delivery and retail warehouse delivery.
``It took a lot of money to get this thing seeded, and financing
didn't happen as fast as we thought it would.''
</P>
<P>
   A receiver has been appointed by Canadian bankruptcy regulators,
said Anita Jarjour, a Naya spokeswoman. While the changeover to the
new distribution network has gone well, she said, ``we still have
some work to do, and that's why we found ourselves in this
position.''
</P>
<P>
   The privately held Naya entered the bottled-water market about
five years ago with a catchy slogan _ ``Hungry for life, thirsty
for Naya'' _ a hot product and the additional advantage of plugging
into the Coca-Cola system. It grew about 30 percent a year,
becoming emblematic of the surge in sales of single-serve bottled
water that began in the early 1990s. Naya was so successful that in
1997, Coca-Cola Enterprises tried unsuccessfully to buy the
company.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Naya ran advertisements in industry publications
thanking Coca-Cola Enterprises for its help over the last five
years and proclaiming that it had been ``a great relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Other ads took shots at Dasani, suggesting that because it was
not a spring water _ it is filtered tap water, with added minerals
_ Coca-Cola was ``emphasizing cost savings over quality.''
</P>
<P>
   One industry expert said the loss of Coca-Cola Enterprises as a
distributor would set any company back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Naya probably stood to lose at least 30 percent of its
volume,'' said John D. Sicher, the editor of Beverage Digest, an
industry newsletter. ``That probably changed the entire financial
dynamic of the company.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
