<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6858 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-DRUGS-LAUNDER23-COX     12-22 1368
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUGS-LAUNDER23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DEA agents seize $26 million, infiltrate drug ring by posing as
stockbrokers
 &HT;    By R. Robin McDonald
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For three years, agents with the U.S. Drug Enforcement
Administration and the Internal Revenue Service masqueraded as
stockbrokers who were willing to wink at the law to launder
millions of dollars in illicit drug profits.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, as federal agents froze bank accounts across the
globe, the DEA and the IRS announced the results of the
investigation _ which has led to the seizure of an estimated $26.2
million in U.S. currency, 4 tons of cocaine and 340 bank accounts
used by Colombian drug traffickers and the money brokers who
converted their illegal earnings into legitimate profits.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation has also led to the arrest of 47 people in
nine U.S. cities and two foreign countries. Thirteen others remain
at large, including five Colombian money brokers whom federal
investigators have identified as men who also traffic in illegal
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Those five men _ two from Pereira, Colombia, one from Bogota and
two from Medellin _ have been indicted by a federal grand jury in
Atlanta and warrants have been issued for their arrests. Several
have ties to the Cali drug cartel, federal investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   Federal authorities said Wednesday they intend to seek
extradition of the five to this country for prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defendants in this case took millions of dollars in U.S.
money and took millions in pesos and laundered them without the
money ever leaving this country,'' said Assistant U.S. Attorney
Larry Anderson, who will prosecute the case.
</P>
<P>
   The three-year investigation began in September 1996 when DEA
agents discovered nearly 400 kilos of cocaine in a shipment of fish
destined for Spain, said John J. Andrejko, special agent in charge
of the DEA's Atlanta field division.
</P>
<P>
   The firm that exported the fish was a subsidiary of Colapia USA,
which maintained its small corporate office in Marietta, Ga., and
housed its shipping operations in a central warehouse in Doraville,
Ga., Andrejko said. One of the firm's owners was later convicted in
Miami of laundering $42 million for Colombian drug lords, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the investigation unfolded, the DEA in Atlanta was able to
infiltrate part of that Colombian drug trafficking organization,''
Andrejko said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were able to learn that the Colombian traffickers
responsible for that shipment were also looking for new customers
for drugs, people interested in going in as partners and people
able to move and launder their drug proceeds,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made it known we could provide all those services.''
</P>
<P>
   The DEA did so by establishing a licensed stock brokerage in
Tucker, Ga., in a secluded office park on Northlake Parkway,
Andrejko said. It marked the first time that federal agents have
used a legitimate stock brokerage as a prop for a drug
investigation, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Through that brokerage, known as Airmark Investments, DEA and
IRS agents targeted the black market peso exchange, where Columbian
money brokers buy, sell or trade foreign currency at exchange rates
as much as 16 percent higher than legitimate banks, said DEA
spokesman Bill Malarney.
</P>
<P>
   Those black market peso brokers, he said, are often willing to
launder drug money for Colombia drug traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   At Airmark, ``We had the authority to do trades,'' said Albert
``Skip'' Latson, a veteran of other money laundering stings who
supervised this investigation, code-named ``Operation Juno'' for
the Roman goddess whose temple minted Roman coins.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were only offering services to our clients, not to the
general public. We found, once we started it, they weren't too
concerned about investing or buying stock. ... Their primary reason
was that they were already making about 400 percent on their
(cocaine) investment.''
</P>
<P>
   Illegal drug sales, according to U.S. Customs, generate an
estimated $57 billion annually, almost all of it in cash. But
strict federal cash reporting laws have made it difficult for drug
dealers to deposit dirty cash _ profits from illegal drug sales _
at a U.S. bank without arousing suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   So drug traffickers have to find other ways of retrieving the
cash from their foreign drug transactions without alerting federal
authorities who can, by law, seize money generated through crime.
</P>
<P>
   Many of them have turned to the black market peso exchange, said
Andre Martin, special agent in charge of the criminal division of
the IRS in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Drug traffickers will contact a peso broker, who may do business
with both legitimate and illegitimate enterprises. The broker, for
a hefty fee, will transfer Colombian pesos to a Colombian drug
trafficker. In return, the peso broker will have access to sacks of
cash in a U.S. or European city _ the actual profits from drug
sales.
</P>
<P>
   But the money broker needs a way to legitimize those cash
assets. That's the role the Tucker stock brokerage played, Andrejko
said. Only because it was a federal sting operation did federal
authorities know that the firm's gross revenues were actually
suitcases full of drug money, rather than cash entrusted to Airmark
by legitimate investors.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, hundreds of otherwise legitimate business owners may
easily become accomplices who, wittingly or unwittingly, help drug
traffickers wash their dirty money, Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   When Colombian importers place orders for American goods, they
will often make cash payments to a peso broker. But rather than
wire the cash from a legitimate bank account in Colombia, the
broker will pay for the foreign goods or merchandise through third
parties that are either sham operations that have no ties to the
importers, such as the Tucker stock brokerage, or whose owners are
willing take in suitcases full of cash and report it as legitimate
profit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The drug proceeds are so massive it boggles the mind,'' Latson
said. ``We had offers for $20 million at a time. ... Our system for
doing it was to launder as little as possible for the maximum
enforcement benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   No actual cash pickups occurred in Atlanta or at the brokerage,
Andrejko said. But it was manned by agents well-versed in the
intricacies of stock transactions in case their illicit clients
actually expressed an interest in buying stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``They never did,'' Andrejko said. ``And we never strongly
encouraged that.''
</P>
<P>
   What the investigation allowed federal agents to do was identify
drug sales networks in a host of U.S. cities and 340 bank accounts
in South America, the United States, the Caribbean and Switzerland
where drug money was funneled once it was washed through legitimate
businesses or front companies into the international banking
system.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the money was picked up by our undercover agents, it was
wire-transferred into undercover bank accounts the government
controlled,'' Andrejko said. ``Instructions were given to
undercover agents as to where traffickers wanted that money sent.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal agents arranged wire transfers of dirty cash gleaned
from multiple U.S. drug sales through a maze of international
accounts, Andrejko said.
</P>
<P>
   Before the investigation ended, the DEA and the IRS had
laundered about $14.5 million in drug money, Andrejko said. But
agents also have seized more than $10 million from drug operations
in New York, Dallas, Houston, Providence, R.I., Miami, Fort
Lauderdale, Chicago, Newark, N.J., San Juan, P.R., Rome, Italy and
Spain uncovered during ``Operation Juno,'' Andrejko said. And
authorities in seven countries were in the process of seizing an
additional $16 million in bank accounts Wednesday, he said. ``I
always referred to the stock brokerage firm as the nerve center,''
Andrejko said. ``That's where all the telecommunications center was
located. That's where the fax machine was. That's where all the
calls came in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed to establish an office so if the traffickers wanted
to come and check on where we were located ... we would give have a
legitimate company to give the appearance of a legitimate business
enterprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
