<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6861 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-KEEPING-HOUSE-750(2TA     12-22 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KEEPING-HOUSE-750(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLOSE TO HOME: KEEPING HOUSE JUST LIKE MOM 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I grew up with a mother who baked bread, ironed everything from
sheets to jeans, vacuumed the carpet in straight lines and cleaned
the entire house the night before our cleaning person came. The
running joke among my friends was, ``At the Hessers' house, you do
cry over spilled milk.''
</P>
<P>
   So it was with both curiosity and skepticism that I picked up
Cheryl Mendelson's wildly comprehensive, 884-page manual, ``Home
Comforts: The Art and Science of Keeping House'' (Scribner, $35).
In it, Ms. Mendelson covers everything from dusting techniques to
bleach expiration dates.
</P>
<P>
   I have inherited my mother's fussiness and skills, and I have
also read Mrs. Beeton and other old household guides. But I had
never come across one that was current enough to apply to, say, the
age of the washing machine. I was eager to compare my mother's
methods to a pro's, but I was equally anxious to justify my own
high standards.
</P>
<P>
   Housekeeping is no longer the respected craft it once was. In my
generation (younger than Lestoil, older than the Internet), people
are expected to be so casual about their homes that schedules
(Monday, washing; Tuesday, ironing) are a thing of the past. Having
a home with a sense of order is a sign that they are uptight and
rigid, and ripe for parody on a sitcom. Among my friends, I have
often kept a secret: I was all for being clean and neat, and I knew
how to use starch.
</P>
<P>
   So I wondered: Could Ms. Mendelson help my friends who don't
have a clue how to make a bed, wash windows or fluff a down
comforter? Or would her book be a disappointment?
</P>
<P>
   Martha Stewart, for one, fails to impress me. It is all too
clear that she has assistance, getting those fresh Araucana hens'
eggs into the house each morning. She is not about good
housekeeping, my mother says. She is about having a good house.
</P>
<P>
   What's appealing about Ms. Mendelson is that she makes no
assumptions about what high-thread-count linens, antiques, silver
and Miele vacuum cleaners people have. She is concerned instead
that they have a well-run household. And she is full of
revelations.
</P>
<P>
   A tablecloth, Ms. Mendelson writes, should extend 8 to 12 inches
past the edge of the table; for a formal dinner, 12 to 18 inches. A
tablecloth, she adds, is allowed to have a single fold running the
length of the table.
</P>
<P>
   This was news. Tablecloths? How passe. My friends don't use
them. I do, and I have on occasion pulled out my iron and tried to
flatten that fold. That won't happen again.
</P>
<P>
   I read on. In the section on washing dishes, Ms. Mendelson
instructs: ``Fill your dish pan or sink no more than two-thirds
full with water as hot as your hands can bear. This will be hotter
than your bath water. It should be a bit uncomfortable to leave
your hands in it for a sustained period.'' That's my method, too.
So far, so good.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mendelson is adamant that people not use the same dish
towels to dry their hands and dry the dishes, and my mother agrees.
But here I am in the clear, too. It's not that I never use a dish
towel to dry my hands; it's that I rarely ever use one to dry a
dish. To me, that is the line between kitchen work being fun and
kitchen work being work.
</P>
<P>
   Page after page, the instructions continued with the same
incredible detail. It was reassuring to come across techniques that
were familiar to me, like folding sheets and mitering a bed corner.
All this was reassuring in the sense that there were standard
methods, that my mother was not just being particular and that I
measured up.
</P>
<P>
   I learned a new way to fill a duvet, and read about damp
dusting, a technique I had never heard of. But when I turned to a
page with a graphic of how to clean up dirt, I had to put the book
down. Who could possibly need instruction in sweeping, I thought.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, Ms. Mendelson is addressing an audience like my
friends, people who may not even own a broom. She is as
businesslike, clinical and thorough as she has to be in this day
and age.
</P>
<P>
   So I went back and read the dirt and broom section. Turns out,
it was fascinating. Ms. Mendelson discusses the pros and cons of
brooms, then describes smart sweeping, which for her means
collecting dirt in the center of the room (the shortest distance
from the walls), and keeping the broom close to the floor, so dirt
isn't thrown into the air. Ms. Mendelson, who is a Harvard lawyer
and structures her arguments like one, may convince slovenly
readers to stop reading and sweep the floor or at least make their
beds.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The illustration of how full to fill your dryer at first seemed
fairly ridiculous. But then I recalled seeing friends stuff their
dryers full and wonder why their socks were damp.
</P>
<P>
   The book is filled with such practical information. Over the
next week, I found myself going back to it with my own questions.
How does Ms. Mendelson recommend drying sweaters? There's a special
flat square rack that sits a few inches off the floor. How does she
iron clothing? It takes her 12 pages to say, but those are 12 pages
packed with detailed information and illustrations. I had never
seen a sleeve board before and never thought to keep a damp sponge
handy to dampen a wrinkle before ironing it.
</P>
<P>
   The book stumbled on a few questions. A friend called to ask me
how to get candle wax out of her carpet. I checked and found there
was nothing in the book on candle wax. Nor was there advice on how
to get rid of Indian meal moths, a recent problem for me.
</P>
<P>
   But eventually I realized that I was missing the point. Ms.
Mendelson offers few cures for minor household dilemmas because
there are plenty of books that will tell you how to remove stains
and fill dents. What is most interesting about this book is Ms.
Mendelson's point of view. Though she is happy to describe the
method she uses, she acknowledges that keeping house is a matter of
individuality.
</P>
<P>
   But since almost no one discusses housekeeping anymore, how
would anyone know enough to develop an individual housekeeping
system? Which is why this book feels like such an anomaly. It
represents a kind of writing that practically doesn't exist
anymore. The household guides of the last century were not as
detailed as Ms. Mendelson's guide, but in them readers could learn
how to keep cows, make a compost heap and build an ice house.
</P>
<P>
   For sociological reasons, housekeeping guides fell out of favor
in this century. And they fell out of favor at almost the same time
that the number of cookbooks expanded phenomenally. Innovations
like the dish washer, vacuum cleaner and clothes dryer, Ms.
Mendelson writes, promised to make housekeeping easier. Then, when
women moved into the work force, housekeeping began to seem
old-fashioned. Knowledge was not passed down, leaving many people
not only unwilling to do housework but also ill equipped.
</P>
<P>
   In her introduction, she explains why housekeeping is important,
and why it should be revived. She articulates what I had never
realized when I was fluffing sofa pillows and cleaning windows.
These chores have very little to do with being meticulous and
clean, she says. Instead, they are the means to psychological well
being. It doesn't really matter how someone folds a towel, but it
provides a foundation if a person has a system for folding towels.
</P>
<P>
   Faking it is not an option. ``I know from experience,'' Ms.
Mendelson writes, ``that you cannot make a home by imitating the
household chores and crafts of a past era. Ironically, people are
led into the error of playing house instead of keeping house by a
genuine desire for a home and its comforts.''
</P>
<P>
   My mother's house was immaculate, but it was also warm and
welcoming; friends visited frequently. There was never a sense of
chaos, just comfort.
</P>
<P>
   In my friends' homes, this feeling is practically nonexistent.
Many feel more like hotels than homes. ``As people turn more and
more to outside institutions to have their needs met (for food,
comfort, clean laundry, relaxation, entertainment, society,
rest),'' Ms. Mendelson writes, ``domestic skills and expectations
further diminish, in turn decreasing the chance that people's homes
can satisfy their needs. The result is far too many people who long
for home even though they seem to have one.''
</P>
<P>
   Americans have tried to provide comfort with material goods. An
imposing, soft-cushioned sofa does not necessarily make a warm
living room. But a clean and well-ordered living room _ no matter
what the furnishings _ has soul.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mendelson's book offers an interesting glimpse of how one
woman runs her home. It is admirable and enviable. Now, if I can
just convince my friends.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
