<HEADER>
A6864 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-FILM-BRESSON-COMMENT-     12-22 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BRESSON-COMMENT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBERT BRESSON: A PURE VISION OF CINEMA 
</HEADLINE>
   By BOB GRAHAM  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The films of Robert Bresson were not filmed novels or filmed
stage plays. They were not like paintings or pretexts for special
effects.
</P>
<P>
   They were pure cinema.
</P>
<P>
   Bresson was the rigorous, ascetic master of French cinema. He
died over the weekend in Paris at the age of 98.
</P>
<P>
   In that extraordinarily long life, he always was true to his own
vision, never courted popular approval and ended up with one of the
most influential bodies of work in the history of the art.
</P>
<P>
   Many would say that any list of his masterpieces would have to
be led by ``Pickpocket'' (1959) and include his other masterpieces
of the '50s: ``Journal d'un cure de campagne'' (Diary of a Country
Priest), ``Un condamne a mort s'est echappe'' (A Condemned Man
Escapes).
</P>
<P>
   Coming to filmmaking late _ he made his first when he was 33 _
Bresson worked slowly but methodically. His last film, ``L'Argent''
(Money) was released in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   He had continued to live in a fifth-floor walkup on Quai de
Bourbon on Paris' Isle St. Louis, an island in the Seine.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Scarlet, artistic director of the San Francisco
International Film Festival, recalls visiting him there in 1988 and
taking him out to the Champs Elysees to have his picture taken.
</P>
<P>
   He was spry and looked around the boulevard, and in his high,
reedy voice said, ``So that's how women are dressing these days,''
Scarlet recalls, which led him to believe that it had been a while
since Bresson had been out.
</P>
<P>
   Fashion was never of much interest to Bresson anyway, Scarlet
says, either in the literal or broader senses. When ``L'Argent''
won a prize at the Cannes Film Festival, an international
marketplace, the announcement of the award was hooted. ``The idea
of Bresson at Cannes was sort of like having Mother Teresa at a
fashion show,'' Scarlet says. ``His presence reveals the sham and
emptiness of everything around it.''
</P>
<P>
   He never had a smash box-office success or won an Academy Award,
Scarlet says, ``which I am sure never bothered him a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Bresson's writing about film was as spare and evocative as his
making of them. His ``Notes sur le cinematographe'' (Notes on
Filmmaking, Paris, 1975) amounts to a series of maxims. ``The truth
of filmmaking cannot be the truth of the theater, of the novel nor
the truth of painting,'' he wrote. What film captures must be
intrinsically different from what other arts capture.
</P>
<P>
   ``His films are about what all films should be about,'' Scarlet
says. ``They are a reminder of what we lose track of, that film is
not all those other arts. He was a keeper of the flame and a
reminder to all filmmakers that you're not really making film
unless you use to the maximum the extraordinary language of film.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the curious things about Bresson is that he avoided using
professional actors. Their ``histrionics'' interfered. He used
amateur actors speaking almost in monotone. Emotions, including
very deep ones, were conveyed by the succession of images:
close-ups of details, telling dolly shots and resetting of the
frame to intensify the effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pickpocket'' is a good example. A sequence on the Paris Metro
shows the pickpocket at work. It is all built on close-ups,
glances, hands, bodies, eyes. There is no dialogue, but
nonetheless, Scarlet says, it is tense and upsetting.
</P>
<P>
   Bresson's films could be very moving as well. In ``Au Hasard,
Balthazar'' (By Chance, Balthazar, 1966), the lives and vices of a
number of persons are seen through the eyes of a dumb beast, a
donkey that passes through their hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``His works are not difficult, yet `Balthazar' is utterly
mysterious,'' Scarlet says. ``It is hard to figure out how it can
continue to move you even if you have seen it 10 times.''
</P>
<P>
   Scarlet is fortunate. The nature of his work allows him to see
great films 10 times. Otherwise, he says, the availability of good
subtitled prints of Bresson's work in this country is ``shameful.''
</P>
<P>
   The film festival honored Bresson with a retrospective of eight
films when he won the Akira Kurosawa Award for lifetime achievement
in 1988, but access still remains shamefully limited today, he
says. The Pacific Film Archive in Berkeley presented another
retrospective last year, but it was a touring show organized in
Toronto. ``The condition of American prints is unacceptable,''
Scarlet says.
</P>
<P>
   If people want to regard Bresson's work as almost religious or
metaphysical, the films will bear such a view. ``His movies have a
particular force,'' Scarlet says. ``They show us that the reality
of this world demands our attentiveness. By looking very closely at
what this world is, he thought it would reveal another world.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
