<DOCNO> NYT19991222.0311 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6869 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-VH1-ROCKCOLLECTORS-TE     12-22 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VH1-ROCKCOLLECTORS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAUL OF FAME: VH1 SHOW APPRAISES ROCK MEMORABILIA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The question is so obvious.
</P>
<P>
   Does Bill Brand, executive producer of the new ``VH1 Rock
Collectors,'' have his own secret cache of rock artifacts?
</P>
<P>
   A guitar signed by Carlos Santana, perhaps?
</P>
<P>
   A U2 ticket autographed by Bono?
</P>
<P>
   A rare Beatles lunchbox?
</P>
<P>
   No, no and ... no. But if the show (which airs 11 a.m.
Saturdays) says anything, it says that Joe and Jane Doe out there
may well have some piece of history that's worth anywhere from a
couple of hundred to several thousand dollars.
</P>
<P>
   And that, Brand is betting, is the appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to tap into people's memories and their
stories,'' says Brand, who with only a little prompting 'fesses up
to owning a picture of Paul McCartney taken by Linda McCartney, and
a fistful of laminated backstage passes. ``One woman I met lived in
a little town in Ohio in the '50s, and people there burned rock 'n'
roll albums. She hid her Elvis album under a bed. That album now is
worth about $200, but her memory is priceless. And it's part of our
history.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Collectors,'' which premiered Nov. 27, is keyed to such
memories: While the show has several facets, its main feature is
having people come forward and have items appraised by, among
others, experts from Sotheby's auction house and the Rock and Roll
Hall of Fame and Museum.
</P>
<P>
   So far, those items have included a scrap/autograph book
including personal notes from the Beatles (Ringo Starr and Pete
Best!), found to be worth $10,000; Bob Dylan's typewritten lyrics
from the ``Blonde on Blonde'' sessions, left behind at a Nashville
studio, appraised at $50,000; and a 78 by shadowy blues legend
Charlie Patton, bought at a yard sale for $3 and now worth $8,000.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for the show, Brand says, came up at a brainstorming
meeting this year. As a test, a call was put out in Cleveland that
appraisers would be at the rock museum for one day in June.
</P>
<P>
   More than 150 people showed up. Brand's response: ``We've got a
show here, folks.''
</P>
<P>
   And they did. Subsequent stops have been made in Miami, Austin
and Las Vegas. Footage from all three stops was incorporated into
the show's debut: One man in Miami had a contract signed by Jimi
Hendrix and plucked from a London trash bin (estimated value:
$5,000-$10,000); a woman in Vegas had several promotional fliers of
several shows in San Francisco during the height of the
flower-power years _ estimated value, $400-$700.
</P>
<P>
   Rock auctions will also figure into the ``Collectors'' format:
The first show had Mariah Carey talking about her love of Marilyn
Monroe; she subsequently bought Monroe's personal piano at a
Christie's auction for $600,000.
</P>
<P>
   Also shown was a Christie's auction, at which dozens of Eric
Clapton's guitars were on the block to raise funds for a
drug-treatment center he had built in Antigua. One of them was the
famous ``Brownie,'' long his favorite guitar _ and the one he used
for the ``Layla &AMP; Other Assorted Love Songs'' sessions _ which
fetched $450,000.
</P>
<P>
   The show also featured Boy George browsing in a New York store
specializing in star memorabilia _ and finding a doll of himself
from the days when Culture Club was one of the biggest bands in the
world. ``It doesn't look anything like me a'tall,'' he said with a
laugh.
</P>
<P>
   But the show needed to be more interactive, so two features were
added. One showcases the home movies of memorabilia collectors. The
other is the launch of the VH1.com auction site; Mariah Carey,
Billy Joel, the Backstreet Boys, Fender Guitars and the Hard Rock
Cafe have all contributed items, the sale proceeds of which will go
to the VH1 Save the Music program, which works to restore music
programs in public schools.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, items appraised on the show will be put up for
auction, and the site will also be home to American Music
Memorabilia Professionals, which provides its own items for sale
and verifies the authenticity of other items on the site. The
auction site will be updated every week, Brand says, whether the
show that week is new or a rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're creating a market for people who want to buy and
sell things,'' says Brand. ``It sparks interest in people to say,
`What do I have stored away that might be worth something?' Most of
us won't get rich from this. People are looking at it for the
memories and the stories.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
