<HEADER>
A6905 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-THEATER-LES-MIZ-KID-L     12-22 0547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-LES-MIZ-KID-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HED GOES HERE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By EVAN HENERSON 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If it's December, we must be in Los Angeles. Which
means this year, at least, Cameron Teitelman will be home for the
holidays.
</P>
<P>
   Since joining the national tour of ``Les Miserables'' in July,
the 11- year-old Calabasas resident has traveled to Canada, across
the United States and back. He began in Washington, D.C. _ where he
performed at a private function for U.S. Sen. Dianne Feinstein,
D-Calif., then it was on to Montreal, Cleveland, Spokane, Portland,
Tempe, San Diego, Sacramento, Fresno, Colorado Springs...
</P>
<P>
   ``Lots of cities,'' says the dark-haired Cameron, with a grin.
``I still feel more like I'm home here (in L.A.). I get to wake up
in my own bed, play with my own computer and my own toys. That kind
of stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Les Miserables,'' Cameron plays Gavroche, the resourceful
street urchin who lives by his wits and joins the student revolt
along the barricades in 1832 Paris. Gavroche _ a scene-stealer of a
role _ has a couple of musical solos, as well as a memorable, er,
exit scene that is Cameron's favorite part of the show. ``Les Miz''
plays at the Ahmanson Theatre in Los Angeles through Feb. 12 before
heading to Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Cameron works every other performance, sharing the role with
Christopher Carlson, who has become Cameron's new best friend. Also
on the tour are the two girls who play young versions of heroines
Cosette and Eponine, and a teacher travels along to make sure that
everybody keeps up with school work. Cameron's father, Sanford, a
television producer, travels with Cameron on the tour. On the road,
mom Judy, brother Brandon and kid sister Marissa visit whenever and
wherever possible.
</P>
<P>
   But this is no extended holiday for Cameron. He finds himself up
and in school at the theater by 11 a.m. Then it's dinner, and back
to the theater by 7 p.m. His day is done by 11 p.m, a couple of
hours sooner on the nights when Christopher Carlson performs.
</P>
<P>
   That's eight performances, six days a week, day in and day out,
from city to city, a schedule some kids his age might find a bit
trying. But Cameron is having a blast. Besides, in the Teitelman
family, where everybody except Sanford is a performer, there was no
thought about turning down a gig like this.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the call came that Cameron got the part,'' says Sanford
Teitelman, ``in that split instant, my wife acknowledged that `Yes,
he will go, he will do well, and we will live with it. And by the
way, Sandy, you're going to do the tour with him.' So I was
drafted.''
</P>
<P>
   The tour has no ending date, which means that Cameron can face
the bullets on the barricades as long as he's under 55 inches or
until he wants to quit. To hear him talk about his travels and the
friendships with fellow cast and crew members, Cameron seems in no
hurry to outgrow Gavroche's rags.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love this show. I love this show so much. When I first saw
it, I was dazzled. I was like, `Oh my gosh!''' says Cameron, who
saw two movie versions of ``Les Miserables'' before auditioning.
``Even when I went on audition, I was really excited. I am so lucky
to have gotten this part.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's Ts.HX6
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
