to enter the long-distance markets would at least receive a
sympathetic hearing. In fact, had been rejected outright, the very
viability of the Telecommunications Act of 1996, which opened the
door for the Bells to sell long-distance service, might have come
into question on Capitol Hill. By Seth Schiesel.
