<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6910 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r l BC-FASHION-PONCHOS-FEATU     12-22 0378
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-PONCHOS-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUT YOUR HEAD THROUGH THE HOLE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By  BARBARA DE WITT 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Clint Eastwood wore them in westerns.
</P>
<P>
   Valerie Harper wore them as the hip window dresser Rhoda in
``The Mary Tyler Moore Show.''
</P>
<P>
   More recently they've been spotted on Sarah Jessica Parker in
that steamy new cable series, ``Sex and the City.''
</P>
<P>
   The subject is ponchos, those blankets with a hole in the center
and fringe on the edges that have been ridiculed for more than 20
years. Yep, right up there with the other p-word (polyester) and
leisure suits.
</P>
<P>
   Like other staples of the hippie-chick and handcrafted-fashion
era, the poncho has been resurrected. Once again that
one-size-fits-all item has style status, especially with those
new-again jeans sporting fabric trim and fringe around the ankles.
</P>
<P>
   But ponchos didn't always have such respectability. They got
their start as a utilitarian garment, mostly used as rain gear for
cowboys and soldiers, although they did inspire a type of women's
cloak in the late 1800s.
</P>
<P>
   Ponchos as we know them today were the creation of Bonnie
Cashin, an Oakland designer who was famous for clean, uncomplicated
designs. Back in the late '60s she made oversize plaid ponchos with
hoods in luxurious fabrics such as mohair and wool and teamed them
with plaid fringed skirts. Soon everybody was designing their own
version at all price levels and in all types of fabrics, including
corduroy.
</P>
<P>
   Now designers are doing it again. Max Azria of BCBG has short
red ones woven so loosely you can stick a fist through the
stitches, and J. Crew has designed them long and heavy enough to be
used as coats for a California winter.
</P>
<P>
   Others, such as Morgan De Toi, have made them light and airy in
mohair, while traditionalists such as Harve Benard have favored a
long-and-lean elegance. But if you're going to do the retro scene
with attitude, don't fool around with hybrids.
</P>
<P>
   Go for the one that screams '70s, from its stripes or granny
squares to its pompons at the neckline. Consider a hood (but don't
wear it on your head), and look for fringe made of yarn, instead of
the satiny lamp shade fringe.
</P>
<P>
   That's poncho panache. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-22-99 1938EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991222.0335 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6911 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-ROCKER-BRADLEY23-     12-22 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROCKER-BRADLEY23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dump Rocker in a New York minute
 &HT;    By Mark Bradley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Don't send him to sensitivity training. Don't enroll
him in anger-management class. Don't fine him. Don't even suspend
him.
</P>
<P>
   Get rid of him.
</P>
<P>
   John Rocker should have no place on the Atlanta Braves. He has
dishonored the organization. He has offended everyone with a
functioning mind. He has stamped himself as a buffoon.
</P>
<P>
   Get rid of him.
</P>
<P>
   This shouldn't be a hard call. From a business perspective, can
the global conglomerate Time Warner stand to have one of its most
visible employees spewing bile _ that's bile as opposed to phlegm,
which is what Rocker disgorged at the now-infamous Georgia 400
tollbooth _ toward all points of the globe? This from Rocker:
``Asians and Koreans and Vietnamese and Indians and Russians and
Spanish people. ... How the hell did they get in this country?''
</P>
<P>
   Get rid of him.
</P>
<P>
   From a baseball perspective, Rocker has become clubhouse poison.
According to Sports Illustrated, he called a black teammate ``a fat
monkey.'' He ripped Ozzie Guillen for not making a play behind him.
He essentially called his manager a liar. Harmony in the workplace
is a key reason why the Braves win their division without fail. So
long as he remains here, Rocker will stand as an irrevocable
breach.
</P>
<P>
   Get rid of him.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves made a trade Wednesday, a big one, a good one. Nobody
much noticed. Everything was Rocker, Rocker, Rocker. Rudy Giuliani,
mayor of New York, demanded an apology. John Schuerholz, the
Braves' GM, was forced to conduct the most awkward news conference
in the history of telecommunications, addressing the trade first
and Rocker second, which was akin to a TV anchor saying, ``And in
other news today, Neil Armstrong set foot on the moon.''
</P>
<P>
   Get rid of him.
</P>
<P>
   Athletes are notoriously clannish. Ordinarily, they rally around
one another, extending the benefit of the doubt past the point of
common sense. They ``reserve judgment.'' They reach for the
``maybe-he-was-taken-out-of-context'' hook. That didn't happen
Wednesday. Brian Jordan and Leo Mazzone spoke at length on radio on
``790 The Zone,'' and neither offered even a tepid defense of
Rocker. Which says it all.
</P>
<P>
   Get rid of him.
</P>
<P>
   Back to the trade. The Braves acquired Quilvio Veras and Reggie
Sanders. Veras is from the Dominican Republic. Sanders is
African-American. Imagine the scene in spring training: ``Welcome
to the team, guys, and shake hands with John Rocker, our closer.
Here we like to think of ourselves as one big happy family.''
Imagine the day pitchers and catchers report, when Rocker greets
Javy Lopez, who is from Puerto Rico, or Eddie Perez, who is from
Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   Get rid of him.
</P>
<P>
   Through his agent, Rocker released a statement saying, ``I am
contrite,'' but noting that, hey, people make mistakes. The SI
story wasn't a mistake but a revelation, a deeper glimpse into a
troubled heart. It was only a matter of time before Rocker,
hurtling through life at 110 mph with the volume cranked up to 11,
slammed into something. The Braves needn't feel any obligation to
be there when he does it again. They can find another closer, and
if they can't _ well, better to lose with dignity than to win with
a lout.
</P>
<P>
   Get rid of him.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
