<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6913 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-JAPAN-NUKE-710&AMP;ADD-NY     12-22 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-NUKE-710&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEATH OF INJURED WORKER PUTS NEW PRESSURE ON JAPAN'S ATOMIC ENERGY
PROGRAM 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The death late Tuesday of a worker exposed to radiation
in Japan's worst nuclear accident brought renewed calls Wednesday
for curbs on the country's atomic energy program.
</P>
<P>
   The worker, Hisashi Ouchi, 35, was hurt on Sept. 30 in an
accident at a nuclear fuel plant near Tokyo that also critically
injured two other workers. Scores of nearby residents were exposed
to radiation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a victim of a myth perpetrated by the national
government and the nuclear power industry that nuclear energy is
safe,'' said Tatsuya Murakami, the mayor of Tokaimura, where the
accident took place. ``We must speak frankly to the government and
to the industry if we are to coexist with nuclear energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Japan's nuclear power industry has been on the defensive since
the accident, opening a rare chapter in this country's history
where citizens have effectively brought pressure to bear on the
tacit coalition between government and business in a major
industry.
</P>
<P>
   In a front-page commentary Wednesday, the Asahi Shimbun, a
leading newspaper, noted that the 1979 accident at Three Mile
Island had led to the end of the expansion of nuclear power in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's government may have been heedless about the dangers of
nuclear energy, the newspaper wrote. But after the accident in
Tokaimura, it said, the people ``are starting to feel genuine
horror and concern about nuclear power generation, perhaps for the
first time in their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi offered his condolences to Ouchi's
family, and said ``the government has been working so that such an
accident will never be repeated.''
</P>
<P>
   Far more than most people, many Japanese have associated all
things nuclear with death and destruction, a legacy of the atomic
bombings of this country by the United States in 1945. The nuclear
power industry, which supplies over 30 percent of the country's
electricity, was able to thrive here only after unstinting efforts
to cultivate an image of extraordinary safety.
</P>
<P>
   For many here, the Tokaimura accident, which resulted from
procedural lapses not only shattered the safety myth, but also,
given the gruesome conditions of Ouchi's death, will recall
memories of the bombings.
</P>
<P>
   Recent pressure by civic groups and a strong shift in public
opinion against nuclear power have already forced several of the
largest power plants to cancel or postpone plans to upgrade their
operations. A particular target of local opposition has been the
planned use of a hybrid fuel containing both uranium and plutonium
by so-called light-water plants that were originally designed to
burn uranium only.
</P>
<P>
   Local skepticism about the safety of such plans has been
heightened by the news that a British company that was Japan's
principal supplier for the new fuels falsified safety reports.
</P>
<P>
   The Tokaimura fuel reprocessing plant, where Ouchi worked, was a
cornerstone of Japan's ambitious program for plutonium use, which
stems from a dream for national energy independence in a country
that has no oil reserves.
</P>
<P>
   Under this plan, Japan has sought to recover plutonium from the
spent fuel rods of its many light-water reactors. Once purified,
the plutonium _ a raw ingredient for nuclear weapons _ is mixed
with uranium and then made into pellets for burning.
</P>
<P>
   Nuclear energy experts have long warned that the mixed fuel
increases the risk of rupture inside the cores of power plants.
Moreover, they say, in case of a catastrophic accident, plutonium
and its byproducts are far more lethal than uranium.
</P>
<P>
   What few had foreseen, though, was the kind of blunder that
occurred at Tokaimura, where poorly trained workers were following
crude shortcuts, mixing nuclear fuels by hand with steel buckets.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, these shortcuts, some of which were included in an
illegal manual distributed by the plant's management, led to a
miscalculation in which more than seven times the normal amount of
fuel was poured into a container. A result was a nuclear chain
reaction that took nearly a day to bring to a halt, and the
critical injury of the three workers directly involved.
</P>
<P>
   In the space of a few minutes, Ouchi, the worst-hit worker, was
exposed to 400 times the maximum amount of radiation a nuclear
plant worker is allowed to received in an entire year.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Perhaps in part because of dread of the backlash against nuclear
power, the government went to extraordinary lengths to save Ouchi's
life.
</P>
<P>
   Although he had not regained consciousness since mid-October,
doctors at the University of Tokyo Hospital had been ordered to
spare no means to save him. According to the doctors involved in
his care, 10 liters of blood were transfused into his body daily in
recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In late November, Ouchi had to be resuscitated after his heart
failed. Since then, doctors said, his skin, which suffered severe
peeling after the accident and never healed, had been oozing more
and more bodily fluids.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors said that despite the administration of huge amounts of
pain killing drugs, even in his unconscious state the patient
winced and showed other signs of agony when receiving treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We learned a lot from 81 days of unprecedented treatment,''
said Kazuhiko Maekawa, the doctor who led the team treating Ouchi.
``But we were also made aware of the limits of today's medical
science.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
