r l BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     12-22 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET BYGONES BE BYGONES
</HEADLINE>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 Copyright 1999 Chronicle Publishing Company
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Bill Clinton  &LR; says, in the year-end issue of People magazine,
that  &UR; Pete Rose  &LR; should be allowed into the baseball Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think just about everybody ought to get a second chance. ...
I'd like to see what he did right and what he did well somehow
accepted.''
</P>
<P>
   He also mentions one of the good things he's learned while being
president: how to use the StairMaster. And the White House perk
he'll miss most is the movie theater.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Bill and  &UR; Hillary Clinton  &LR; will serve more than a half-ton
of fruitcake at White House holiday parties this year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CONSUMING INTERESTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - Advertising Age says that the World Wrestling Federation,
``itself under fire for tasteless content in its programming,'' has
rejected a Duncan yo-yo ad that featured children brandishing a
finger that's commonly used for gesturing and yo-yoing. ``This is a
controversial spot,'' said ad man  &UR; Ernest Fossa &LR; , one of the ad's
creators. ``But how do you break through the clutter? Kids don't
pay attention to anything.''
</P>
<P>
   - The cosmetics company Lancome is trying to make its image
``more contemporary, more relevant, more accessible,'' company
president  &UR; Marc Menesguen  &LR; told the New York Times, so steps are
being taken. First, a new print ad leaves some of a model's
freckles visible, a move a company official called ``bold'' and
``confident.'' Second, Rouge Magnetic lipstick is losing the accent
mark over the ``e'' in Magnetic.
</P>
<P>
   - InStyle magazine says that a company called MIT has a
prototype of a musical denim jacket. A touch of the embroidery
starts the garment ``playing'' any number of tunes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GIFT GUIDE NO. 12 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Mother Jones calls readers' attentions to the Slingshot
Collective's Y2K ``organizer for rabble rousers.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a pocket calendar that includes reminders of such dates
as March 15 (when Turkish fascists attacked students in 1977); July
11 (when miners in Idaho seized mines in 1892); December 22 (when
Mexican paramilitary forces murdered refugees in 1977). ``In a
shocking breach of anarcho-orthodoxy,'' says Mother Jones, ``the
organizer does list Columbus Day rather than `Indigenous People's
Day.' But who's complaining?''
</P>
<P>
   The calendar costs $5, and is available from Slingshot
Collective, 3124 Shattuck, Berkeley CA 94705.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. The Earth Island Journal praises  &UR; Jay Leno  &LR; for using
chairs, desk and tables on his set made of ``environmentally
certified'' timber from EcoTimber International, ``harvested in
Papua New Guinea by a small-scale sustainably managed,
community-run forestry project ... certified under the Smart Wood
Program of the Rainforest Alliance.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Al Franken &LR; , apparently the  &UR; Bob Hope &LR;  of the Clinton era, is
performing on a Christmas tour for U.S. troops in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   - Details magazine says that mah-jongg is making a comeback, and
the maestro of mah-jongg is  &UR; Roman Coppola &LR; , who holds weekly
mah-jongg parties in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Donald Trump &LR; 's girlfriend,  &UR; Melania Knauss &LR; , posed on his
private jet, nude, for a photo spread in a new issue of British GQ.
Although he told the New York Daily News ``She sure doesn't look
like  &UR; Barbara Bush &LR; ,'' he insists he's not bothered about it
ruining his presidential chances.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CENTURY RE-CELEBRATED &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Jim &LR;  and  &UR; Nancy Bundschu &LR; , owners of Gundlach-Bundschu Winery,
will celebrate the New Year with a gala dinner with friends in
their cave, singing a song written 100 years ago by  &UR; Charles &LR; 
 &UR; Bundschu &LR; , Jim's grandfather. The lyrics of the song for January 1,
1900, which dealt with the controversial question of when a new
century begins, include:
</P>
<P>
   ``You may count a year which way you please/ All we want is
happiness and peace,/ Your chronological distinction cuts no ice/
On nineteen hundred we hope to see no flies.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Without Gottlieb Daimler's internal combustion engine, there
would have been no world wars, no atomic bombings, no threat of
worldwide nuclear destruction, no space exploration, nor, for that
matter, any Vietnam War. ... Which did more to get the sexual
carnival rolling, the pill or the drive-straight-to-the-room
motel?''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Tom Wolfe &LR; , in Rolling Stone, on the technological innovation
that he thinks has most profoundly changed 20th century life.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
