<P>
   For Thursday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   US-TERRORISM (Washington) _ President Clinton leads a chorus of
federal officials in encouraging Americans to celebrate this
holiday season, but to be extra cautious amid fears of related
terrorism at home and abroad. FBI counter-terrorism chief Dale
Watson
</P>
<P>
   says threats have been issued against the United States. By JOHN
HENRY and STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-GLITCHES (Washington) _ Assuming the United States makes it
through New Year's weekend with few Y2K-related computer glitches,
it doesn't necessarily mean Y2K will be a non-event. In fact, most
Y2K problems likely won't reveal themselves until Monday, Jan. 3,
when millions of Americans return to work and school. By JENNIFER
CORBETT DOOREN. (1stld-writethru filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-DRUG (San Francisco) _ Three weeks after a company
suspended development of a new AIDS drug because of harsh side
effects, a study at the University of California at San Francisco
indicates that the drug adefovir is effective for some patients who
have become resistant to other treatments. By ULYSSES TORASSA.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NASA-SHUTTLE (Houston) _ Two astronauts float out of space
shuttle Discovery for the first of three days of spacewalking
repairs to the ailing Hubble Space Telescope. By MARK CARREAU.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-SAINTS (New Orleans) _ Even for a franchise that has been as
historically inept as the New Orleans Saints, this season is
shaping up as one of the worst in memory. Between Mike Ditka's
frequent outbursts and Ricky Williams' more-frequent injuries, the
Saints have been a walking and talking disaster area this season.
As they head into their final two games of the season _ and
possibly of the Ditka era in New Orleans _ the Saints see one way
to salvage something from their lost year. And that would be to
knock off the Dallas Cowboys on Christmas Eve. By JOHN McCLAIN.
</P>
<P>
   With: FBN-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   FBC-LINEBACKERU (College Station, Texas) _ Penn State long has
been known as ``Linebacker U'' for its proud tradition of producing
stellar linebackers. But Texas A&AMP;M boasts its own legacy of
producing star linebackers, and the Aggies intend to show the
Nittany Lions which school is really ``Linebacker U'' in next
week's Alamo Bowl. By NEIL HOHLFELD.
</P>
<P>
   BKC-OU-CINCY (Norman, Okla.) _ Oklahoma plays host to No.
4-ranked Cincinnati in a nationally televised non-conference
college basketball matchup. By JEROME SOLOMON.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ In keeping with the standard truism
that no man is a hero to his valet, both Democratic presidential
challenger Bill Bradley and Republican contender John McCain are
having trouble winning the support of the officeholders who are
their political soulmates at home. Do the locals know too much
about them or is this just routine jealousy at play? By MARIANNE
MEANS. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   FOR SUNDAY:
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MRS.CLINTON-VIEQUES (New York) _ If Hillary Rodham Clinton wants
to gauge the political fallout of the Vieques controversy on her
burgeoning New York Senate campaign, all she has to do is stop for
lunch at La Fonda Boricua, a chummy walk-in luncheonette in the
heart of the Spanish-speaking neighborhoods of East Harlem known as
``El Barrio.'' ``Everybody's talking about Vieques,'' says Jorge
Ayala, the easy-going, Puerto Rico-born owner of the bustling
restaurant. By STEWART M. POWELL. (1stld-writethru filed in the
``a'' and ``p'' categories.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ Al Gore and Bill Bradley will
continue into the new year sparring over their opposing education
and health-care initiatives, each trying to convict voters that his
proposals would be best for the American people. But while they are
jockeying for position on those issues, two others _ taxes and
trade _ pose real dangers to the candidates as they race toward the
Iowa caucuses. By ROBERT THOMPSON. (Already filed.)
</P>
