<SLUG> BC-BHUTAN-REFUGEES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BHUTAN, NEPAL AND U.N. GRAPPLE WITH LITTLE-NOTICED REFUGEE CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Bhutan, a Himalayan kingdom caught in a
decade-long refugee crisis that has opened the little-known country
to charges of ``ethnic cleansing,'' has released all prisoners that
human rights groups regarded as political detainees, according to
Bhutan's representative at the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   The case shows the limits of what the U.N. high commissioner for
refugees can do, even though tens of thousands of people say they
have been made refugees by events in Bhutan. The Bhutanese say that
the number is far smaller, and that only one side of the story has
been heard, through aid organizations, diplomats and politicians in
neighboring Nepal.
</P>
<P>
   With huge refugee crises elsewhere, there has been little effort
internationally to settle the dispute, which on the surface seems
not very complicated. In part because of the standoff, Bhutan ranks
low on international surveys of democracy, at least one of which
has been used as evidence by officials in New York to bar the
purchase of a property by the Bhutan government to house its U.N.
mission.
</P>
<P>
   Bhutan's representative at the United Nations, Om Pradhan, said
Monday that the decision to free about 200 prisoners, among them
many common criminals, had been made by King Jigme Singye
Wangchuck. ``We let them all go,'' Pradhan said.
</P>
<P>
   The king celebrated 25 years on the throne this year and has
gradually introduced political reforms in what was until very
recently an absolute monarchy.
</P>
<P>
   About 40 prisoners known as anti-nationals in Bhutan were among
those released, including Tek Nath Rizal, who was convicted of
leading an uprising against the king. The only prisoners not freed
were those in jail for murder and the desecration of sacred relics,
Bhutan's only newspaper, Kuensel, reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
   For the past decade, Bhutan, whose people are mostly ethnically
Tibetan Buddhists who speak a Tibetan-based language, has been the
target of an ethnic Nepali movement along the southern border. A
sparsely populated temperate and semitropical zone there was
drawing illegal immigrants from overpopulated Nepal and the
Darjeeling hill country and the northeast of India. The newcomers
to this area of Bhutan rapidly augmented the local ethnic Nepali
population, mostly Hindus, raising fears that they would eventually
outnumber the Bhutanese Buddhists.
</P>
<P>
   When Bhutan began expelling people it said were not citizens,
ethnic Nepalis around the region responded with accusations of
``ethnic cleansing,'' and a rebellion began in southern Bhutan.
Rizal, a former adviser to the king, first tried to have a census
stopped because, he said, it was alienating the people of the
south. The government said he then turned to persuading Bhutanese
Nepalis that the census was a ruse to expel them and take their
land.
</P>
<P>
   Rizal was first detained in 1988, then pardoned by the king. In
1989 he was arrested again after moving to Nepal to organize a
movement against Bhutan, and was sentenced by a court to life
imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of people fled or were forced out of Bhutan in the
years of unrest that followed. More than 80,000 are in refugee
camps in Nepal.
</P>
<P>
   Bhutan says most are probably not Bhutanese citizens but poor
ethnic Nepalis from India or Nepal drawn to the camps for the
benefits and to keep alive the anti-Buddhist campaign.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
