<HEADLINE>
THE WHEELS THAT POWERED THE `TWO FAT LADIES'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUESTION:.MDNM/ One of the hosts of the cooking show ``Two Fat
Ladies'' died recently. What kind of motorcycle were she and the
other host known for riding? _ F.H.
</P>
<P>
   ANSWER:.MDNM/ Jennifer Paterson, who died of cancer Aug. 10 at
age 71, rode a Triumph Thunderbird motorcycle with co-host Clarissa
Dickson Wright in a sidecar.
</P>
<P>
   Paterson, a ``Spectator'' magazine cook, columnist and BBC
television contributor for many years, was first teamed with Wright
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Repeats of the show, which champions butter, bacon and other
gastronomically incorrect fare, air on Saturdays and Sundays on the
Food Network cable channel. One inspiration for the program's title
was the expression ``two fat ladies,'' which signifies a pair of
eights in bingo.
</P>
<P>
   Q:.MDNM/ Where can I write to Babyface? _ C.D., Huntsville, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   A:.MDNM/ Write to Kenneth ``Babyface'' Edmonds in care of
Edmonds Entertainment, 1635 N. Cahuenga Blvd., Fifth Floor, Los
Angeles, CA 90028.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds, 41, has won 10 Grammy Awards as a songwriter and
producer. His work includes ``End of the Road'' by Boyz II Men and
``I Will Always Love You'' by Whitney Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Two of his most recent projects are ``In the Life of Chris
Gaines'' by Garth Brooks and ``24/7'' by his brother, Kevon
Edmonds.
</P>
<P>
   In July, Indiana Gov. Frank O'Bannon renamed 25 miles of
Interstate 65 as Kenneth ``Babyface'' Edmonds Highway. The road
runs through his hometown, Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Q:.MDNM/ How can I request a catalog from the Smithsonian
Institute? _ B.C., Fort Worth, texas
</P>
<P>
   A:.MDNM/ For a free ``Smithsonian Catalogue,'' call (800)
322-0344 or visit the Web site www.si.edu.
</P>
<P>
   The Smithsonian sells jewelry, home decorations, educational
toys, art and other items with ties to its museum collections.
Current offerings include a World War II leather bomber jacket,
Kit-Cat clock, metal detector and ``Wizard of Oz'' ornaments.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
