<P>
   BRUSH-HAZARD (Los Angeles) -- The dual fires that roared through
hundreds of acres early Wednesday in Glendale and near Ojai were
dramatic reminders of the extremely hazardous conditions this
winter. After weeks of dry, hot and windy weather -- the second
consecutive La Nina winter -- officials have extended fire season,
posted numerous red-flag alerts and warned residents that brush
clearance should now be considered a life-and-death matter.
Firefighters are predeploying 16 engines in the San Fernando Valley
and hopeful that efforts to make utilities, public agencies
including Caltrans, and large property owners comply with brush
clearance rules will prevent a major conflagration. By Harrison
Sheppard (Will move on the ``n'' California and the ``n'' national
news wires.)
</P>
<P>
   BATTLE-FIRE (Los Angeles) -- Working against darkness and 60 mph
high winds, 500 firefighters from departments throughout Southern
California bulldozed fire breaks and undertook risky helicopter
water drops to keep the fire above Glendale away from homes until
Super Scoopers could be brought in at daylight Wednesday, bringing
the 600-acre fire under control. With its resources taxed, traffic
nightmares and hours to go before the fire is expected to be out,
Glendale City officials declared a local state of emergency. With
update on investigation into cause. By Donna Huffaker (Will move on
the ``n'' California and the ``n'' national news wires.)
</P>
<P>
   ORDEAL-FIRE (Los Angeles) -- Hundreds of Glendale and La Canada
Flintridge residents spent a tension-filled night watching flames
and smoke burn closer and closer to their homes. Fire officials
said as many as 100 homes were in harm's way. Many evacuated and
returned early Wednesday relieved to find homes in tact. Also
looking at brush clearance compliance in the area. By Donna
Huffaker (Will move on the ``n'' California and the ``n'' national
news wires.)
</P>
<P>
   FLU-SURGE (Los Angeles) -- Overwhelmed by calls for runs to
emergency rooms from cold and flu victims, Los Angeles city
paramedics are seeking permission from county officials to break
protocol and be allowed to return to duty before patients are
assigned hospital beds. It is the latest problem caused by the
seasonal surge in flu cases and a sharp rise in wind-worsened
respiratory ailments. Heavy smoke from Wednesday's fire above
Glendale was expected to aggravate respiratory conditions in
residents as far away as Venice. By Rick Orlov (Will move on the
``n'' California and the ``n'' national news wires.)
</P>
<P>
   GIFTS-RESTORED (Los Angeles) -- Droves of do-gooders have more
than replaced the 60 gifts stolen by Grinch burglars at a North
Hollywood homeless shelter. More than 50 people -- most anonymous
-- donated at least 150 toys Wednesday. Some people also rolled up
their sleeves to help sort the toys, the executive director said.
Others are making cash donations and in one case, a Chatsworth man
who is walking around the world has volunteered to knock on doors
asking for donations while walking about 30 miles from Chatsworth
to the shelter while on his Christmas break on Thursday. By Lisa
Van Proyen (Will move on the ``n'' California and the ``n''
national news wires.)
</P>
<P>
   AUDIT-LAUSD (Los Angeles) -- A state audit released Wednesday
blasts the Los Angeles Unified School District's way of selecting
school sites, a process that resulted in building 11 schools on or
near sites with hazardous substances. The State Auditor found the
site-selection process fails to provide information to decision
makers and doesn't effectively engage the community. By Terri Hardy
(Will move on the ``n'' California news wire.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
