<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHASEN-VIDEO-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE END OF A HOLLYWOOD ERA OF HIGH STYLE AND HIGH FAT  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 26) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OFF THE MENU: THE LAST DAYS OF CHASEN'S &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998; directed by Shari Springer Berman and Robert Pulcini. New
Video. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   90 minutes. $24.95. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Frank Sinatra and Mia Farrow celebrated their first (and last)
anniversary there. When she was making ``Cleopatra,'' Elizabeth
Taylor had the chili flown to Rome. One evening Shirley Temple had
a drink invented especially for her. And on another occasion, as
Fay Wray tells the story, Orson Welles picked up a container of
flaming sterno and threw it at John Houseman.
</P>
<P>
   Frozen in time, swimming in cholesterol, Chasen's restaurant was
the very essence of Hollywood for six decades. When it closed in
1995, the so-called golden age went with it, or so it was said.
``This town knows it,'' claims a Chasen's habitue in Ms. Berman and
Pulcini's documentary about the restaurant and the celebrities who
crowded the place as if they were straight from the set of ``Sunset
Boulevard.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, the film is about the care and feeding of celebrity
by chefs, waiters, bartenders and maitre d's who, by virtue of
their position, served as links between the famous and the rest of
us. And serve they did, with pride and slavish devotion.
</P>
<P>
   Alfred Hitchcock, Clark Gable, James Stewart, Barbara Stanwyck,
Kirk Douglas, Ava Gardner, Gary Cooper and their ilk patronized the
place nightly, as did a raft of producers, directors and
politicians and a menagerie of movers and shakers and their
hangers-on.
</P>
<P>
   In all those years, only Hitchcock and Lew Wasserman, head of
Universal, were granted regular tables. On any given night, it was
not uncommon to find J. Edgar Hoover at one table and the gangster
Mickey Cohen at another. ``When the Watergate crowd was in town,
what you saw on TV was in here that night,'' one observer comments.
</P>
<P>
   In the film, the hobo steak being cooked tableside is poked
across a lake of melted butter. ``No calories in that stuff,
right?'' says the producer David Brown, who points out that one of
Chasen's problems was that today there are no more eaters.
</P>
<P>
   The restaurant was always a masculine place. A Mexican bartender
named Pepe Ruiz mixes an absolute killer of a drink for Ed McMahon,
Johnny Carson's ex-sidekick, who calls him the ``most important
Hispanic in Southern California.'' The famous could patronize at
will at Chasen's. The staff stays adoring.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was over. ``It's closing because we don't come here
anymore,'' says the television host Tom Snyder. The crowd was
gravitating to hipper, trendier places. In the last days, though,
they all piled into Chasen's: Sharon Stone, Quentin Tarantino, Jay
Leno, Madonna.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you die, everybody comes to the funeral,'' Ruiz says.
Sylvester Stallone is turned away with six people. The management
turns to ``loss prevention.''
</P>
<P>
   A woman friend of Daryl F. Gates, former police chief of Los
Angeles, tries to take a lamp. Across town, someone notes, a new
Chasen's has opened with lighter cuisine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-22-99 2005EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991222.0350 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6936 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NEWYEAR-SITTERS-ART-2     12-22 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWYEAR-SITTERS-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SITTERS _ OF BABIES, PETS AND BUILDINGS _ IN SHORT SUPPLY FOR NEW
YEAR'S EVE 
</HEADLINE>
 
 (ATTN: Tenn., N.J., Md., Va., Mass., Ill.) (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT clients. Non-subscribers can
make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By PETER T. KILBORN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On New Year's Eve, many of the 1,000-some couples attending the
Memphis Junior League's charity ball at the Peabody Hotel will take
their children along. So the parents can be free to cavort, they
have corralled 40 baby sitters from the Annie's Nannies agency.
Each sitter will be paid $330 for the 11-hour affair, triple the
agency's usual rate.
</P>
<P>
   So it will be in most big cities and their affluent suburbs this
New Year's Eve. Baby sitters, whether teen-age amateurs or
professional adults like those from Annie's Nannies, stand to earn
up to $100 an hour for one night's work, or more than many a
partygoer's champagne.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents around here are really strapped,'' said 15-year-old
Emily Redburn of affluent Montclair, N.J. She said a friend at a
deli told her of a couple looking for a sitter for the night.
``Really cool,'' Emily said. ``It's two kids, ages 11 and 9.
They're going to call me.''
</P>
<P>
   In spite of reports of a more tranquil millennium-crossing than
first forecast, with many hotels and restaurants hoping for guests
and chopping prices, placement services say they are running short
of the nation's sitters _ baby sitters, pet sitters and building
sitters, or security guards _ who free others to celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   By most accounts, demand for sitters and guards this New Year's
Eve far exceeds that of previous years. More people plan to go out,
and more businesses want protection against vandalism and system
and power failures if computers go awry. Meanwhile, the supply of
sitters is lower than usual, with more taking the night off
themselves. Many an agency's answering machine says its sitters are
booked through New Year's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting more requests than I've ever had,'' said Nate
Wood, a senior vice president at Blackhawk Inc. in Suitland, Md.,
near Washington, which places security guards. Blackhawk has
exhausted its reserve supply of guards filling the swollen demand
of regular clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone wants security,'' Wood said, ``for cabarets, for
special events. All of our banks want extra coverage. All of our
retail clients. We've been driven all the way to the end of our
means.''
</P>
<P>
   To feed and tend pets, Sit-a-Pet in Arlington, Va., normally
charges $17 for a half-hour visit with one pet once a day and $2
for each additional dog or cat. But to induce more of her 70
sitters to stay on the job, the agency's owner, Debbie Hollander,
said, ``We have a millennium policy. For anyone using us the 31st
or the 1st, it's an additional $25 a day.''
</P>
<P>
   But in terms of the pay, the cream of this crop is
entrepreneurial teen-agers and adult women who care for children.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen-year-old Ingrid Aguero of Miami and her cousin, Amy
Rejaian, 14, will watch children in Ingrid's home. They have lined
up three children so far, ages 8 months to 7 years to spend the
night. For the three, they will earn $135, and they are advertising
on the Internet for more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought it would be too much to charge at first,'' Ingrid
said. ``But, really, almost everyone is going out, and they would
pay anything for a sitter on that night.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In the New York suburb of Ridgewood, N.J., 13-year-old Alex
Ortiz, whose father will be at work on New Year's Eve and whose
mother will be at home, plans to have two or three children ages 3
to 6 come to his home around 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll eat dinner here,'' said Alex, who has honed his
sitting skills watching two younger sisters. ``And I'll entertain
them. They'll spend the night, and their parents will pick them up
around 10 or 11 in the morning.'' Alex plans to ask $150 per child
and has already signed one up.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the demand for sitters is ``high, high, high,''
said Heidi Davalos of the Baby Sitters Guild placement service. She
is charging a minimum of $250 for five hours for up to five
children. The $250 is deposited upon signing a contract and is
nonrefundable, a common arrangement for New Year's Eve. ``We're
fully booked,'' Ms. Davalos said, with 100 sitters assigned.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Tokayer, owner of Family Helpers in the town of Dobbs
Ferry, north of New York City, said she had not had many requests
for sitters, but in defiance of the law of economics that says low
demand means low prices, ``I keep hearing of people who will be
making hundreds and hundreds of dollars,'' Ms. Tokayer said. Rather
than quote a price, she refers callers directly to sitters to
negotiate one.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, Priscilla Garnache, owner of Boston's Best Baby
Sitters-Nannies, said, ``We're obviously very booked. We have
placed about 20 for New Year's Eve. If I had 200, I'm sure I could
place 200.'' She is charging a family with three children $225 for
five hours.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as Las Vegas has discovered, the sky is not the limit.
Anticipating a high demand from high rollers at the casino hotels
there, the Nannies and Grannies agency set a charge of $500 to
watch one or two children in the hotels' bedrooms for four hours,
or more than 10 times the usual fee of $45. But parents have been
balking, and as in other big cities, hotel bookings have been fewer
than expected. ``So we have readjusted that down to $350,'' H.D.
Hale, the agency's general manager, said.
</P>
<P>
   In all these cities, security guards also are in high demand.
Agencies say that calls for guards have soared, less in response to
a need for crowd control and crime deterrence than to worries that
buildings' computer-controlled locks, elevators and other systems
will go berserk when the clock strikes midnight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mostly, people are concerned about access control,'' said
Michael Julian, New York City regional vice president for
Spectaguard. Banks, for example, link their vaults and doors to
clocks that could misread the debut of the millennium and open
after midnight, and apartment buildings could lock out returning
revelers. ``What we're talking about is locks more than anything
else,'' Julian said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Spectaguard will have 600 guards on the job on New Year's Eve in
New York, 200 more than on a typical weekend night.
</P>
<P>
   The guards, most of whom normally earn less than $10 an hour,
can expect big rewards for giving up their night on the town. ``You
have to give them some inducement to work,'' said Richard Hamilton,
president of Watson Security Agency of DC, who said he had more
than doubled his guards' pay, to $25 and $30 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Calvery, manager of the Burns International office in
Vienna, Va., said that for a lack of extra personnel, he had turned
down a customer who offered $80 an hour. In Chicago, Mike
Ragnanese, district manager for Pinkerton's there, declined to
disclose how much he charges. But he said that some agencies would
charge as much as $100 an hour for one guard.
</P>
<P>
   At its offices nationwide, the Wackenhut Corp. is paying bonuses
to off-duty guards who stay home. Then, if the guards are called
in, they will receive holiday pay and an additional bonus. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-22-99 2012EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991222.0352 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6939 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FILM-RIPLEY-REVIEW-LA     12-22 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-RIPLEY-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VERY `TALENTED' INDEED
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: EMBARGOED until Friday, Dec. 24. Fact box below) 
Our rating: 3 1/2 stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Talented Mr. Ripley'' is as luxurious a psycho-thriller as
anyone could wish for. Sumptuous, sensual, stately and twisted,
it's a class act all the way _ especially in its insistence on
viewing abundant beauty with an uneasy eye.
</P>
<P>
   Filmed in just about every corner of Italy you'd ever want to
see, the movie is a sunny noir exercise in the tradition of
Hitchcock's continental romps _ but very, very different from the
master's work in its particular sense of dread.
</P>
<P>
   Screenwriter-director Anthony Minghella, who so successfully
cracked the all-but-unfilmable ``English Patient'' last time out,
has faithfully reproduced the peculiar, clammy atmosphere of
Patricia Highsmith's source novel while deepening its characters
and adding new ones, enriching their relationships, slightly but
significantly altering the time frame and investing the whole
narrative with subtle but lacerating social observations.
</P>
<P>
   Highsmith also provided the material for one of Hitchcock's
masterpieces, ``Strangers on a Train.'' This movie takes that
story's theme of criminal identity-swapping distressingly further.
The not-so-subliminal subtext here is that affection withheld can
be substituted, by those bold and desperate enough to take the
steps, by stealing the love object's very self.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Ripley, played more as a borderline personality than as the
book's calculating sociopath by a quicksilver Matt Damon, seems
such a decent, likable young man that he earns the trust of a
wealthy New York shipbuilder (James Rebhorn) on first sight.
Mistaking Ripley for a Princeton grad _ he was wearing a borrowed
school blazer while playing piano at a tony cocktail party _ Mr.
Greenleaf offers to pay the young man's way to Italy if he'll help
talk the industrialist's errant, ex-Princetonian son into returning
home and making something of his life.
</P>
<P>
   Ripley, who lives in a coldwater basement and works as a men's
room attendant at Carnegie Hall, jumps at the offer. It's the late
1950s, Italy is overrun with rich, high-living American jazz
hounds, and the second he sets foot on the sun-kissed peninsula, it
is evident that Ripley will not be in any hurry to accomplish his
mission. In fact, once he insinuates himself into the orbit of
charming hedonist Dickie Greenleaf (British actor Jude Law, perfect
as a gracious but utterly self-centered American aristocrat) and
Dickie's pleasant, well-bred girlfriend (who else but Gwyneth
Paltrow?), Ripley becomes so intoxicated with the sweet life that
it's not much of a surprise, later on, when he demonstrates the
capacity to kill in order to keep living it. Ripley also becomes
inordinately intoxicated with fickle benefactor Dickie, which isn't
hard but, we just know, can only lead to trouble.
</P>
<P>
   In one of recent cinema's more potent conspiracies between
director and actor, Minghella and Damon create a superficially
admirable if slightly pathetic chap whose unformed sexuality,
poignant neediness and uncanny ability to deceive his way through
any predicament _ except the ones that mean the most to him
emotionally _ turns viewers into non-resisting accomplices. Ripley
proves ruthless and conscienceless _ but Damon, rather
miraculously, never lets us think for a minute that he doesn't have
a soul. Between that, the forbidden yearnings (it is still the
1950s, after all) and the impressive mimickry the role requires,
Damon makes us complicit in acts and urges we would certainly never
really approve of. It's the trickiest, and one of the finest,
performances of the year.
</P>
<P>
   And he sings a decent ``My Funny Valentine'' to boot.
</P>
<P>
   Cate Blanchett, Philip Seymour Hoffman and Jack Davenport round
out the superb cast. John Seale's luscious, sparkling
cinematography captures all the natural and historic beauty of
Italy _ watching it is like taking the Grand Tour with a deranged
guide. The soundtrack boasts expertly chosen bop classics that
composer Gabriel Yared somehow manages to complement with a lush
classical score.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Ripley's'' overriding virtue, perhaps, is its unerring
intelligence. With sure takes on the entitled thoughtlessness and
capricious cruelty of the rich, the special kind of poison only a
disappointed father can distill and how the sexual politics of the
time rendered the most obvious of motives unthinkable (and
dismissed truth when a woman spoke it), ``Ripley'' is perceptive in
a manner more thrillers should be.
</P>
<P>
   And even though it takes its good time getting to the
suspenseful stuff _ which can fairly be viewed as either a strength
or the film's one notable flaw _ once the traps start springing,
the tension level is delicioso.
</P>
<P>
   _____ &QL; 
The film: ``The Talented Mr. Ripley'' (R; violence, nudity,
language). &QL; 
The stars: Matt Damon, Gwyneth Paltrow, Jude Law, Cate Blanchett,
Philip Seymour Hoffman. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Written and directed by Anthony Minghella, based
on Patricia Hoghsmith's novel. Produced by William Horberg and Tom
Sternberg. Released by Paramount Pictures. &QL; 
Running time: Two hours, 19 minutes. &QL; 
Playing: Opens Christmas Day. &QL; 
Our rating: 3 1/2 stars &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
