<HEADLINE>
CANADA MOVES TO TIGHTEN SECURITY ALONG BORDER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ A Montreal woman arrested at a remote border crossing
in Vermont Sunday had made at least one earlier trip to New England
in recent days, raising fears that she may have already delivered
explosives or terrorist operatives, sources in the United States
and Canada said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Canada, meanwhile, moved to tighten security amid reports of
terrorist groups operating within its borders. The move came after
an unusual joint announcement by US Attorney General Janet Reno and
Canadian Solicitor General Lawrence MacAulay that the ``two
countries are working together to to deal with any potential threat
to security of citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators increasingly believe Montreal may be the key point
of connection in a radical Islamic terrorist conspiracy targeting
the United States. All of the three individuals arrested in Vermont
and Washington state have close ties to an ``Algerian underground''
in Canada's second-largest city.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent arrests came when Lucia Garofalo _ a 35-year-old
Quebecer with marriage ties to the Middle East _ was taken into
custody in Beecher Falls, Vt., after sniffer dogs trained to detect
bombmaking materials found trace amounts of explosives in her
Chrysler Neon. Accompanying Garofalo, and also still being held in
federal custody in Burlington, Vt., was Bouabide Chamchi, a
20-year-old Algerian living in Montreal, who was allegedly in
possession of an altered French passport.
</P>
<P>
   Like Ahmed Ressem, 32 _ the Algerian arrested in Washington
state last week with a carload of bombmaking gear _ Chamchi has
links to a Montreal-based ring of Algerian car thieves and break-in
artists whose criminal activities, police believe, are a way of
raising funds for terrorism abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Garofalo and Chamchi have only been charged with immigration
violations, including possession of a falsified French passport.
</P>
<P>
   However, Ressem was indicted by a federal grand jury in Seattle
Wednesday in connection with his Dec. 14 attempt to smuggle
nitroglycerine, timing devices and explosives material into the
United States from British Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Ressem made his home in Montreal. News reports have linked him
to radical Islamic training camps in the Middle East. He has also
been linked to Algerian groups in France who use bank robbery and
other crimes to raise funds, a pattern similar to the groups with
which he may have been involved in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities on both sides of the border are especially alarmed
that on Dec. 6 Garofalo and an Algerian male _ tentatively
identified as Mustafa Roubici of Montreal _ crossed from Canada in
the same car in which she and Chamchi were apprehended on the later
trip. She crossed back into Canada on Dec. 12.
</P>
<P>
   In her successful entry to the United States, as as well as an
attempt on Dec. 15 in which she raised the suspicions of US border
authorities and was turned back, Garofalo went to extremely remote
border posts in Vermont and New Hampshire, none of them on a direct
route from Montreal to Boston, where she claimed to be headed. On
each occasion she was accompanied by different men of Middle
Eastern origin.
</P>
<P>
   The worst fear of investigators, although it remains only a
theory, is that on an earlier trip the car may have succesfully
carried bomb materials or terrorist operatives into the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's scarier than a carload of explosives?'' said an
investigator in Canada, answering his own rhetorical question: ``A
car with explosives residue that may have already made a successful
delivery somewhere. That's the very worst-case scenario.''
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement sources stressed, however, that the trace
amounts of explosives detected in her car could have an innocent
explanation _ such as the earlier transport of hunting weapons or
ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   A massive cross-border investigation into Garofalo, Chamchi,
Ressam, and other Montreal-based Islamic radicals continued as
federal, provincial and local police tried to piece together her
movements in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Little is known about Garofalo. According to a US official, her
husband is an Algerian recently deported from Canada who presently
resides in Europe. She may also have family ties to Libya,
according US prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 6, she and two male passengers entered the US through a
border crossing near Pittsburg, N.H., guarded only by a
surveillance camera and two-way speakers. A US immigration official
questioned her via the speaker but did not require the three
travelers to report to the nearest manned border post to show
identification.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 12, she returned to Canada at Stanstead, Quebec,
accompanied by the man identified as Roubici. Although he carried
no travel documents, he told Canadian authorities he was an
Algerian living in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   He was permitted to enter Canada, although officials there
reported his movement to US immigration officials since he appeared
to have been in the United States illegally.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 15, Garofalo attempted to enter the United States at
Pittsburg again. She was accompanied by a man who identified
himself as Ahmed Saheen of Pakistan. Because of the odd time, 2:35
a.m. and her curious route from Montreal, the US border inspector
grilled her more closely over the speaker system, and instructed
her to open the trunk of the vehicle. The surveillance camera
showed it to be full of boxes and luggage. She was instructed to
come around to a manned border station, but instead, law
enforcement officials say, she drove back to Canada.
</P>
<P>
   On all occasions, Garofalo said her destination was Boston.
</P>
<P>
   One law enforcment source speculated that Garofalo may work as a
``mule'' carrying illegal immigrants from the Middle East into the
United States, and may have no specific knowledge of their plans or
what they have in their possession.
</P>
<P>
   The Algerian facing charges in Seattle, Ressam, is suspected of
being an operative for a loose group of Islamic radicals with
connections to Canada and France. He had lived in Montreal after
applying for refugee status upon arriving in Canada from France in
February 1994. He claimed that the Algerian military had
``unjustly'' accused him of ``arms dealing'' on behalf of Islamic
radicals, according to Canadian news reports.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fact he arrived carrying a fake French passport and
other falsified documents, Ressam was allowed to remain in Canada
with no restrictions other than a requirement that he check in
monthly with immigration authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials have not established a clear
connection between Ressam and Garofalo or Chamchi, the pair
arrested in Vermont. But sources said all three have strong links
to an underground of Algerian radicals residing in Montreal and
involved in criminal enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   Ressam was arrested on at least three occasions and convicted
once on charges of breaking into motor vehicles and stealing items
such as computers and cellphones. Chamchi has been charged at least
twice with stealing cars and breaking into motor vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Such crimes are the trademark of an Montreal-based Algerian
group, with links to France, suspected of using car theft and
extortion to raise money for ``financing terrorism,'' said a
Canadian intelligence official.
</P>
<P>
   According to authorities, Chamchi was in possession of an
``altered'' French passport in the name of Boudjemaa Ben Ali when
arrested in Vermont _ much as Ressam had carried false French
papers on his original entry to Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Chamchi and Garofalo told US officials that they drove
accidentally into Vermont while ``looking for a retaurant,''
according to federal officials.
</P>
<P>
   Canada Wednesday bowed to intense pressure from the United
States and critics at home to intensify anti-terrorist security at
airports and other entry points. The precautions include a
beefed-up guard by the Royal Canadian Mounted Police outside the US
Embassy in Ottawa. Closer checks of people entering Canada from
overseas were also being made at airports.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Judy Rakowsky of the Globe staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
