<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6945 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-YANKS-IRABU-ART-5     12-22 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-YANKS-IRABU-ART-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES TRADE IRABU TO MONTREAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Canada, Japan)  (ART ADV: A photo of Hideki Irabu NYT32 is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) (th) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ He was the American League pitcher of the month once
in each of the last two seasons, displaying the kind of dazzling
pitching the Yankees anticipated when they spent months three years
ago trying to secure the right to sign Hideki Irabu.
</P>
<P>
   But in too many other months Irabu confounded the Yankees with
his efforts, creating more consternation than congratulations.
</P>
<P>
   Those other months, plus the presence of Ed Yarnall, a young
left-hander, prompted the Yankees to look for a trade, and
Wednesday they sent the Japanese pitcher to another country. They
shipped him to the Montreal Expos for a minor league pitcher, Jake
Westbrook, and two young players to be selected from a short list
the teams agreed to.
</P>
<P>
   The Expos' new controlling owner, Jeffrey Loria, was so eager to
acquire Irabu, whose approval was needed for a trade to Montreal,
that he agreed to restructure the option year in his contract for
2001. The Expos guaranteed $2.5 million of the $4 million salary
and provided for more of it to be guaranteed incrementally
depending on the number of innings Irabu pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not doing this for the short term,'' said Loria, who
earlier in the week signed Graeme Lloyd, a former teammate of Irabu
to a three-year, $9 million contract. ``We're interested in
improving the starting rotation and he'll be one of the top three
starters. He's a tremendous addition to this rotation. Hideki's got
one of the meanest split-fingers I've ever seen. The exit sign has
been taken down, and we're looking to bring in quality players.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Nomura, the 30-year-old right-hander's agent, said Irabu was
``somewhat surprised'' by the trade, ``but he's happy with the deal
we cut with Montreal. He's happy that he's wanted up there. Jeff
Loria certainly was a big thing. He really supports Hideki.''
</P>
<P>
   Loria supported him with his checkbook. Irabu has a $2 million
salary for next season. Under the deal with the Expos, if he
pitches 150 innings next season, his 2001 salary will be $3
million; if 165 innings, $3.5 million; if 180 innings, the full $4
million.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees were interested in opening a spot in their rotation
for Yarnall, who impressed them with his aggressive style of
pitching during two brief stays with the team last season.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what the Yankees like about Yarnall, general manager Brian
Cashman said, ``What's not to like? He has no scare. He's
deceptive. His fastball gets right on the hitter in a deceptive
way. His arm angle makes him deceptive. Lefties and righties aren't
comfortable against him. Having the ability to pitch with deception
is key today, especially coming from the left side.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't that long ago that Yankees officials were talking that
glowingly about Irabu. More recently, however, the words that
reverberated around his name were fat and toad, which together
formed an appellation hung on him by George Steinbrenner, who was
displeased with Irabu's pitching and fielding effort in spring
training exhibition games.
</P>
<P>
   But in the winter of 1996-97, the owner was Irabu's No. 1 fan.
The San Diego Padres owned rights to him, but the Yankees pressed
them to trade those rights as Irabu made it known that he would
sign only with the Yankees. The Yankees gave the Padres $3 million
in the deal that was made April 22, 1997, then signed the pitcher
five weeks later to a four-year, $12.8 million contract.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   When Irabu made his first major league start, against Detroit
July 10 of that season, he produced the kind of performance the
hype had promised, getting eight of his first 12 outs on strikeouts
and limiting the Tigers to two runs and five hits in 6 2/3 innings.
But Brian Hunter, the Tigers' center fielder, offered a note of
caution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure he had some nice stuff,'' Hunter said, ``but you get a
team with a little more experience, he's not going to have that
success.''
</P>
<P>
   Five days later the Cleveland Indians battered Irabu for five
runs and nine hits in five innings.
</P>
<P>
   In May of 1998, Irabu was named AL pitcher of the month for his
4-1 record and 1.44 earned run average in six starts. But he had a
winning record in only one other month that season. He was pitcher
of the month again last July for his 4-0 record and 2.64 ERA in six
starts. That stretch was part of an eight-game winning streak that
lasted into August.
</P>
<P>
   ``He carried us with eight consecutive wins,'' Cashman said.
``We saw those flashes of brilliance that attracted us. But
obviously there were times when there were inconsistencies.''
</P>
<P>
   Cashman said that maybe Irabu will benefit from the change. ``He
was always under the microscope in New York,'' the general manager
said. ``Maybe he can relax more in Montreal, where expectations
aren't as high. In New York it's a tough situation. It's not for
everybody. I'm not saying it wasn't for Hideki. But playing
elsewhere can be easier for some players. That might be the case
with Hideki.''
</P>
<P>
   Yarnall came to the Yankees last February in the trade that sent
Mike Lowell, a young third baseman, to Florida. But Yarnall began
his professional career as the Mets' third-round pick in the 1996
amateur draft. He was part of the package the Mets gave the Marlins
for Mike Piazza in May, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In two starts and three relief appearances with the Yankees last
season, he had a 1-0 record and 3.71 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Westbrook was Colorado's first-round pick in the same draft but
now has been traded twice. The Rockies sent him to the Expos two
years ago in a deal for second baseman Mike Lansing. A 22-year-old
right-handed starter, he had an 11-5 record and 3.92 ERA for Class
AA Harrisburg last season. He has a 41-25 record in four minor
league seasons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
