<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6958 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-GIFT-CERTIFICATES-(TR     12-22 1351
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIFT-CERTIFICATES-(TRIMS)-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB START-UP KNOWS VALUE OF ITS CONVENTIONAL BACK-OFFICE WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: optional sidebar at end of story) 
(bl) 
 By STEVE LOHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jonas Lee has a Harvard M.B.A. and has worked for a
blue-chip management consulting firm. But he now knows that no
business school course or consulting firm project can possibly
prepare you for the daily frenzy at an Internet start-up,
particularly during a make-or-break holiday season.
</P>
<P>
   Lee is the 33-year-old president of GiftCertificates.com, an
online marketer of gift certificates. He ticks off a list of minor
mishaps, including running out of glue sticks used to seal
envelopes at 2 a.m. (``You go to every all-night convenience store
you can find'') and trying to fix an ink-choked printer that was
ruining envelopes at 3 a.m. (``You race out to the 24-hour Home
Depot in Queens and get a little vacuum cleaner.'')
</P>
<P>
   The fortunes of GiftCertificates.com, like those of so many
Internet retailers, will be determined largely by how well it copes
with such mundane matters as order-handling, packing, shipping and
answering customers' questions over the phone. And that means it
must deftly manage and motivate the people who do this work _ not
M.B.A.'s or techies, the expected dot-com denizens, but mostly high
school graduates.
</P>
<P>
   This is the home truth about e-commerce, as the Internet becomes
more mainstream _ that so much of it is old-fashioned ``commerce''
instead of the technological wizardry of ``E.''
</P>
<P>
   GiftCerticates.com occupies two floors of a building on Seventh
Avenue and 35th Street in Manhattan's garment district. Most of the
management team, the Web site designers and software programmers
are on the sixth floor, while the customer service, order-tracking,
packing and shipping operations are two floors up.
</P>
<P>
   The eighth floor hums through three shifts, round-the-clock,
with workers fielding customer calls in one room and tracking,
packing and shipping gift-certificates in another room. Work in the
order room is called ``feeding the green dragon,'' because the
small conveyor belt that ferries gray trays filled with
gift-certificate orders has a green metal frame.
</P>
<P>
   The floor is staffed mainly by workers in their teens to 30s,
mostly black and Hispanic, graduates of the city's public high
schools. They are paid hourly wages, and many are hired just for
the holiday season. Jeans and sweatshirts are the order of the day.
Two workers have brought their radios, one tuned to a rap station,
the other playing classic soul.
</P>
<P>
   Such hires have brought the GiftCertificates.com payroll to
roughly 140 people, more than double its size three months ago.
Among the temporary workers is Sparkle Taylor, 19, who says she has
had seven or eight jobs in the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Taylor, a customer service representative, sits at a
personal computer, wearing a headset and navigating through
information on the company's Web site to answer questions. Some
callers want information about the more than 200 retailers and
restaurants whose gift certificates the company offers. Others are
newcomers to online shopping and simply want someone to talk them
through the process of buying by computer.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Taylor has done telephone work before, selling long-distance
service for a phone company and doing surveys for a market research
firm. ``That was all outbound _ people can get very hostile,'' she
said. ``In customer service, they need you. I like it here.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Like other temporary workers at GiftCertificates.com, she said
the company was paying pretty good wages _ $12 an hour in customer
service and $10.50 an hour in order fulfillment.
</P>
<P>
   The holiday season also provides an audition for permanent jobs.
``My short-term goal is to have them keep me full time,'' said Ms.
Taylor, who joined the company three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   If the company does well, Lee said, the plan is to keep a
payroll of 100 to 110 people, meaning about half of the temps would
be offered permanent jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stars have already been identified,'' Lee noted. ``You can
tell who really cares, especially in a wartime situation like
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Jose Camacho, who works in the order fulfillment room, is a
permanent worker at the company and a veteran by the standards of
GiftCertificates.com. He joined at the end of August, leaving a job
as a purchasing manager in art supplies store. Three months later
was promoted from fulfillment representative to supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yep, I'm moving up the ladder,'' said Camacho, 28, during his
4 p.m. to 1 a.m. shift last Wednesday. ``I've been here almost four
months and it feels like four years,'' he added, offering a
shop-floor view of Internet time as hiring, training and production
all go on all at once.
</P>
<P>
   Motivational signs alongside the conveyor belt encourage workers
to ``Do Us Proud'' and show the target number of orders to be
handled hourly at each station. A sign above the urinal in the
men's room reminds them of the ``Eight Steps'' in the fulfillment
process; a day earlier, there were ``Seven Steps.'' When a new
shipping record was set last week, each worker in the department
was given a $25 bonus on the spot _ in gift certificates.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   (The eighth-floor work force is proof that personal affluence
and technological literacy do is not necessarily go hand in hand.
Even though Ms. Taylor does not yet own a personal computer, she
has two free e-mail accounts, which she uses from friends'
computers or from work. Camacho learned of the job opening at
GiftCertificates.com one Sunday evening while browsing through
online classified ads using his WebTV.)
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   To further motivate its employees, both management and hourly,
GiftCertificates.com is offering stock options to every full-time
worker, as many Internet start-ups do.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``You bet the stock options are a big deal to me,'' said
Amaryllis Diaz, 28, a supervisor in the customer service
department.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Diaz left a customer-service job at an industrial printing
company she had held for years. Like others in operations at the
Internet start-up, who are typically paid annual salaries of
$20,000 to $40,000, she said she wanted to ``get in on a company
that had a lot of potential, just as it was taking off. It just
seemed more exciting than my other job.''
</P>
<P>
   She views stock options not as the equivalent of a winning
lottery ticket _ as they can be for the founding executives of a
startup _ but as potentially providing a modest nest egg. ``I've
got two kids,'' Ms. Diaz said. ``It could be a nice bonus.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The financial calculus of joining an Internet start-up was more
complicated for the 10 members of the management team at
GiftCertificates.com. If things go well, the payoff for them could
be many millions of dollars, but the risk can be greater, too, at
least in the near term.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Stephenson, the company's 35-year-old chief financial
officer, abandoned a roughly $1 million-a-year job as an investment
banker at Merrill Lynch in August to go to GiftCertificates.com,
where his salary is about one-tenth as much. Leland Harden, 37, the
executive vice president for business development, walked away from
$5 million in unexercised stock options, at current prices, when he
left a larger Internet company in April.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   When they speak of why they came on board, they sound very much
like Ms. Diaz. ``You can try to think it to death all you like,
but, heck, you really do it for the adventure,'' Harden said.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a shared adventure this holiday season on the eighth
floor. Every member of the management team pitches in to take
shifts ``picking and packing'' in the fulfillment department. So do
family members, including Stephenson's wife, Cathy, who is
expecting the couple's first child on Christmas eve.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Special steps have been taken for the eighth-floor employees.
Last week, for example, a masseuse was brought in to ease the
strain on the weary necks and shoulders of those picking and
packing at a frenetic pace.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Lee is often there, packing envelopes, picking trash off the
floor and offering words of praise and encouragement. ``A big part
of my job is being a cheerleader, doing things for people and
showing them you care,'' he said. ``If you don't, there is a real
potential for an upstairs-downstairs, us-and-them mentality to set
in. We can't afford that.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   With only two days left till Christmas, GiftCertificates.com
stands a chance of being one of the emboldened survivors of the
Internet winter of 1999. Its goal for the holiday season was about
$20 million in sales, and a steady surge of orders recently has
made that target seem attainable. ``A few weeks ago, I was worried
that we wouldn't hit it,'' Lee said. ``It's been a nail-biting
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   His anxiety is explained by the pace at which money is going out
the door. GiftCertificates.com, which raised roughly $24 million
this year in venture capital, plans to spend $12 million in the
last three months of the year on advertising alone _ in newspapers
and magazines, on billboards and buses, and over the radio,
featuring actress Sophia Loren as the Web site's spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   The venture backers are optimistic but not patient. William
Ackman of Gotham Partners, a New York investment firm and a large
shareholder, observed, ``We'll know whether this company succeeds
or fails before long. Sometime next year.''
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GIFT CERTIFICATES MAY PROVIDE NICHE FOR A FEW E-COMMERCE FIRMS &QL; 
 &LR;   &UR; By STEVE LOHR &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   GiftCertificates.com is one of a handful of Internet start-ups
trying to build an online marketplace for gift certificates. The
Web retailing category, analysts say, may well prove to be a good
niche business for the winners.
</P>
<P>
   ``One or two of these companies could emerge with businesses of
a couple hundred million dollars annually over the next 5 or 10
years,'' said Ken Cassar, an analyst for Jupiter Communications.
``But I can't see one of these companies ever becoming a
multibillion-dollar business.''
</P>
<P>
   The business thinking behind a company like GiftCertificates.com
is that gift certificates are a sizable market _ more than $11
billion a year _ that is waiting to be transformed by the Internet.
Like books or records, gift certificates are something that
consumers do not necessarily have to inspect in person before
purchasing. And for most retailers, gift certificates represent a
couple of percent of yearly sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``For most retailers, gift certificates are an afterthought,''
said Jonas Lee, the president. ``For us, it's the only thought.''
</P>
<P>
   Retailers do tend to view gift certificate Web sites as a
complement to their bricks-and-mortar businesses instead of as a
threat.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``We see working with them as a way to drive business to our
stores _ a person who receives a gift certificate walks through our
doors to use it,'' said Michele Cerwin, a marketing executive at
Chanel Inc., one of the more than 200 retailers and restaurants
that offer their certificates on GiftCertificates.com.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   at GiftCertificates.com executives talk hopefully of helping to
transform the image of their product from a last-minute option into
``a new category, more of an everyday expression of love and
affection,'' said Bertina Ceccarelli, executive vice president for
marketing.
</P>
<P>
   The company's offerings are shipped in a variety of packaging,
from gold envelopes to a velvet case with a ribbon. Web resellers
like GiftCertificates.com buy their certificates from retailers at
a 10 to 20 percent discount from their face value _ a discount
retailers are willing to offer because many consumers either don't
use the full value of the certificates or go to a store to use a
gift certificate and then buy additional merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   And as with certificates sold to anyone, the retailers also get
the immediate use of the cash on certificates they sell to
resellers before they are exchanged for goods.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   GiftCertificates.com and Giftpoint.com, analysts say, seem to be
the early leaders. In November, the most recent month for which
data is available from Media Metrix, a Web traffic monitor,
Giftpoint.com had slightly more visitors than GiftCertificates.com,
and both were well ahead of other rivals, including Flooz.com and
Webcertificates.com.
</P>
<P>
   More important than window shoppers, of course, are buyers. In
November, GiftCertificates.com showed the largest gain in online
purchases of any Web site from the previous month, up 462 percent,
according to Nextcard, which tracks the Internet buying of 100,000
Visa card holders. Still, its previous sales were modest, so it is
not yet clear how significant, or lasting, such a surge will prove
to be.
</P>
<P>
   There are hopeful signs, but they are preliminary ones at best.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
