r l BC-JONES-RELIGION-COLUMN     12-22 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JONES-RELIGION-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEMORIES OF CHRISTMASES PAST EASE TRANSITION TO NEW AGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   My 3-foot-high Christmas tree shines brightly in one corner of
my condominium. It is there because of a sudden decision. I was
inside one of those giant stores that have almost everything, and
the little tree seemed to beckon.
</P>
<P>
   My tree was nearly as pitiful-looking as the meager tree that
Charlie Brown picked out in ``A Charlie Brown Christmas,'' that
classic TV offering and the first animated special made by the
great Charles Schulz.
</P>
<P>
   My tree was miraculously transformed, just like Charlie Brown's.
We strung red, green and yellow lights on it and added a silver
garland. A white angel with a halo glows on top. It looks good.
</P>
<P>
   Every time I walk into my living room, I switch on the lights
and admire the tree. For me, it recaptures the spirit of Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Although there are many versions of how Christmas trees
originated, the practice stems at least partly from our
nature-worshipping ancestors in Northern Europe. They saw
evergreens as symbols of eternal life. Druids thought mistletoe was
magical.
</P>
<P>
   Some historians credit Martin Luther with starting the Christmas
tree custom. He is said to have been inspired by the sight of an
evergreen tree with bright stars shining above it. He put up his
own evergreen and decorated it with lighted candles.
</P>
<P>
   Many people without relatives at home don't bother to put up
Christmas trees. I've sometimes done that.
</P>
<P>
   But having a tree rekindles memories of the warmth and love of
past Christmases. During my childhood, our family Christmas trees
were centers of happy celebrations. We even had one of those
silvery aluminum trees. It still brightened our home.
</P>
<P>
   Starting before I can remember, our family cut our Christmas
trees from a tall evergreen on the farm where I was born in North
Texas. The tree still stands, although a little lopsided. We still
visit it. It brings back fond memories of a struggling but blessed
family.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the Christmas tree tradition is partially based on
non-Christian influences is not surprising. Early church fathers
were adept at taking over holidays of indigenous religions.
</P>
<P>
   The early church did not celebrate Christ's birthday. The focus
was on Christ's death and resurrection. Some thought it was sinful
to commemorate Christ's natural birth, believing that it diminished
his divine nature, according to ``Sacred Origins of Profound
Things,'' by Charles Panati.
</P>
<P>
   Many influences brought on the celebration of Christmas in Roman
times. One was a rival religion, called Mithraism, which was seen
as a threat to Christianity. The ruins of Mithran temples have been
excavated around the world, including one I saw last summer in the
heart of London.
</P>
<P>
   Mithra worshippers had a Dec. 25 holiday commemorating the birth
of Mithras, ``the invincible sun god.'' December was also the time
of the feast of Saturn, (Saturnalia) a time of wild merrymaking.
</P>
<P>
   When pagan festivals were outlawed during the fourth century,
the Dec. 25 date was adopted as the birthday of Jesus, according to
``The Illustrated Guide to World Religions.'' The style of
observance was prayerful, a Christ's Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Some Christian denominations, including Jehovah's Witnesses, do
not celebrate Christmas because of its association with
non-Christian festivals.
</P>
<P>
   But I prize this celebration of the birth of a child who brought
profound love into the world. During Christmas, we tend to take
more seriously Jesus' admonition to love our neighbors and even our
enemies. It is a time when we don't forget to share our love with
our family members and our friends.
</P>
<P>
   As Victor Hugo wrote in his 1862 novel ``Les Miserables,'' ``The
supreme happiness of life is the conviction that we are loved.''
And sharing that kind of love is the true meaning of this joyous
holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Merry Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
