u w BC-CLINTON-SHOPPING-NYT     12-22 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SHOPPING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: S.D.)  
 MERCHANTS WARY OVER LAST-MINUTE VISIT FROM FIRST PROCRASTINATOR 
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton plans to embark on his annual
Christmas shopping trip on Friday afternoon, joining thousands of
other procrastinating holiday shoppers searching for the perfect
gift.
</P>
<P>
   The news has shopkeepers here alternating between delight and
dread at the prospect of a presidential visit and the disruption it
can create.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he is buying something, he is usually pretty generous,''
said Andrew Twillman, vice president of the Washington Pen Co. at
Union Station, a mall at the train station here. ``But if he
doesn't buy anything, you are shut down for nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Twillman, who noted that Clinton has made 11th-hour purchases
from him in the past, said that the section of the mall where the
president shops is blocked off from the rest of the shopping area.
And Clinton's last-minute shopping occurs at a prime time for
retailers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is publicity, but two hours of business as usual the day
before Christmas would be pretty good,'' Twillman added.
</P>
<P>
   Others like the novelty of seeing the president doing his own
shopping for the holiday.
</P>
<P>
   David Mowery, the historical consultant and salesman at
Political Americana, a shop in the Union Station mall that sells
political memorabilia, said he was expecting the president this
year, and would wait for him to arrive.
</P>
<P>
   The store displays old campaign buttons and bumper stickers,
``Mondale and Ferraro for America,'' and campaign posters,
``Kennedy for President _ Leadership for the 60's.'' Democratic
merchandise lines one side of the store, Republican items on the
other.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will point him toward the Democrat side,'' Mowery said,
adding that the president, who he referred to as the First
Customer, has a collection of political buttons. ``I am absolutely
looking forward to it.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that the store had some new FDR buttons, and one from
William Jennings Bryan, that he would like to show Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   A large photograph of the president inspecting the showcase of
political buttons hangs at the entrance to the store. Clinton
visited in 1997 while shopping with his daughter, Chelsea.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Camp, manager of Brookstone, a specialty gift shop, said
he was ``well-informed of the traditional visit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would love to meet him, even with the checkered history,''
Camp said, adding that if the president asked for recommendations,
he would point to what he called the store's ``tempurpedic
products,'' which are promoted as relieving pressure and stress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I might suggest the massage chair,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Clinton did the bulk of his shopping at a store in
the Peace Corps headquarters in downtown Washington _ a building
that Hillary Rodham Clinton dedicated in September 1998 _ before
joining Chelsea for their traditional Christmas Eve shopping
excursion at the Union Station mall. The Peace Corps store sells
merchandise from countries around the world and uses the proceeds
to support Peace Corps volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   And for the first time this year, said Nanda Chitre, a White
House spokeswoman, Clinton skipped at least one early trip to the
mall in favor of shopping online. From his antique wooden desk in
the Oval Office, he used a Compaq laptop computer adorned with the
presidential seal to order jewelry and children's books. The
president ordered horsehair bracelets from a Web site run by a
private nonprofit group that helps raise money for the people of
the Oglala Lakota Nation in southwestern South Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Chitre said the president's practice was to pick things up
on trips, particularly international trips, so he might already
``have a stockpile of gifts.''
</P>
<P>
   Twillman, at the pen company, with his eye on the bottom line,
did finally yield a bit on the prospect of serving the president of
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would welcome him with open arms,'' he said. ``I just wish
he would come back in January.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
