<HEADER>
A6972 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CUBAN-BOY-NYT     12-22 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUBAN BOY TO REMAIN IN  MIAMI FOR CHRISTMAS, INS SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
 By DAVID GONZALEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Elian Gonzalez, the 6-year-old Cuban refugee who was
rescued from an inner tube off the Florida Coast on Thanksgiving
Day, will remain in Miami at least through Christmas, immigration
officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Immigration and Naturalization Service faxed a letter to
Spencer Eig, Elian's lawyer, saying it had postponed an inspection
interview with the boy that was originally scheduled for Thursday.
The interview is part of the agency's procedure for determining a
person's admissibility into the United States while his immigration
status is decided.
</P>
<P>
   INS Commissioner Doris Meissner will ultimately rule on whether
the boy will stay with relatives in Florida, as Cuban exiles have
demanded, or be returned to his father in Cuba, as the father and
the Cuban government have demanded.
</P>
<P>
   The letter also offered reassurances that Elian will remain with
his Miami relatives and would not be placed in foster care. In
recent days there had been worried whispers that the boy would be
either taken away from his father's Miami relatives or even
deported to Cuba this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point we did not have all the information we needed to
complete his inspection,'' said Maria Cardona, an INS spokeswoman.
``We did not think it was important for him to come and meet with
INS inspectors. A decision is not going to be forthcoming this
week.''
</P>
<P>
   Eig said, ``I am very pleased with this development because
there was a concern that Elian would be railroaded out of the
country tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are pleased about this because it gives Elian an
opportunity to relax and for him to obtain due process of law. Due
process is not the fastest way to make a decision, but it is the
fairest way,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration service officials said their decision to postpone
the interview did not affect the more important question of who
will speak for the boy's interests. Since arriving here after a
journey that claimed the life of his mother and 10 others, the boy
has been at the center of an international custody dispute between
his father in Cuba and relatives in Miami, both of whom insist they
are looking out for the child's best interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision we need to make is who can speak on the child's
behalf regarding the immigration issues involved in this case,''
Ms. Cardona said. ``INS's decision in this regard can be made
before, during or after the inspection is completed. The January 21
inspection date is not magical and it has no bearing on our
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the frayed relations between the United States and Cuba,
the tug of war over Elian's fate has been fraught with larger
political meaning. Exile groups in Miami have embraced the child,
with local politicians visiting his Miami hone bearing gifts and
encouragement. Elian's lawyer has filed a request for political
asylum for the schoolboy, saying he had a fear of persecution
should he be returned to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would not go back to the custody of his father, he would go
into the custody of Fidel Castro for the purposes of being used as
a trophy in parades all around the country as a symbol of Castro's
victory over the United States,'' Eig said. ``We pointed out to the
INS that would be particularly horrifying to Elian because he would
be turned into a symbol of the regime that drove his own mother to
her death.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the custody impasse began, throngs of protesters in Cuba
have taken to the streets nine times to demand the boy's return. In
Havana on Wednesday, protesters with flags and banners brought
traffic to a standstill as they streamed through seaside avenue by
the American Interests Section chanting ``Free Elian.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban officials have accused the exile community of using the
boy as a political pawn, wooing him with toys and attention.
President Fidel Castro has also said that if the boy is returned,
there would be no triumphant parades. One Cuban official who spoke
on the condition of anonymity said that his government wanted to
see the child come back to as normal a home environment as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``What has been done in Miami is part of a show that the people
are doing every day,'' said the official. ``The boy is suffering.
His mother is dead and he has to be with his father.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
