<HEADLINE>
CLINTON URGES CAUTION IN WAKE OF TERRORISM FEARS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional trims) 
 
By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton led a chorus of federal officials
Wednesday in encouraging Americans to celebrate the holiday season
but to be extra cautious amid fears of year 2000-related terrorism
at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would ask them (Americans) to just be aware of their
circumstances and if they see anything suspicious to report it
immediately,'' Clinton said during a visit to a Washington soup
kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   The president said U.S. law enforcement agencies are ``taking
extraordinary efforts'' to thwart potential terrorism after the
arrest last week of a suspected terrorist in Washington state.
These steps include increasing the number of security personnel and
enhancing safety operations at U.S. airports, borders and docks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Houston, as in other coastal U.S. cities, security will be
beefed up at the port. Also, Bush Intercontinental Airport, like
other facilities around the country, will have more uniformed
police and bomb-sniffing dogs on patrol, federal officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard and Customs Service have also increased staffing
in the Houston area, and the Port of Houston authority has
instructed its police to be on a ``heightened state of awareness,''
authority spokeswoman Esther De Ipolyi said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Senior Justice and Defense department officials joined Clinton's
call for cautious celebration between now and mid-January, saying
their agencies are working around the clock to uncover potential
terrorist threats before they can occur.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration's comments came just hours before an
Algerian national pleaded innocent to charges related to his
alleged smuggling of bomb-making equipment into the United States.
The Dec. 14 arrest of Ahmed Ressam in Port Angeles, Wash.,
heightened federal and public concern that terrorists might strike
during the holiday season.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and Canadian officials are searching for three men
suspected of working with Ressam, The Associated Press reported.
Ressam, when arrested by the Customs Service, had enough
nitroglycerin and bomb-making materials in his car to bring down a
large building, law enforcement officials said.
</P>
<P>
   He could face up to 40 years in prison if convicted in a Seattle
federal court of all five charges on which he was indicted
Wednesday. The charges include smuggling bomb-making equipment,
transporting explosives, possessing unregistered firearms, carrying
explosives during a felony and lying to Customs Service officials.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. law enforcement officials suspect Ressam, 32, might be
linked to an Islamic fundamentalist group, based on unconfirmed
intelligence data, The New York Times reported Wednesday. The
newspaper also cited French officials as saying Ressam might have
links to an Algerian terrorist group that set off bombs in France
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But even before Ressam's capture, U.S. law enforcement was
already on increased alert to potential terrorism due to concern
that terrorists might strike at U.S. interests at the dawn of 2000,
federal officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder Jr. called a news conference
Wednesday to assuage public concerns about possible terrorism. He
said the government has received no specific threats of planned
terrorist attacks against specific U.S. targets.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Holder urged Americans to be on guard if they
attend crowded new year celebrations scheduled across the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ask people to be more cautious, more vigilant, more aware of
their surroundings,'' said Holder, the Justice Department's No. 2
official. But Holder downplayed growing public concern of potential
holiday terrorism, saying he ``would encourage people'' to attend
large outdoor celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not want to unnecessarily alarm people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant FBI Director Dale Watson, who heads the bureau's
counterterrorism division, said law enforcement agents are on ``a
heightened state of alert.''
</P>
<P>
   Watson, who joined Holder at the news conference, said the FBI
was reacting to no specific threat of terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   As for threats abroad, Defense Secretary William Cohen said U.S.
intelligence agencies are ``cooperating worldwide with their
counterparts'' to uncover any planned terrorist attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a sharing of intelligence to make sure that we have
the latest possible information to make sure that we can deter and
detect and discourage any attempts on American lives anywhere in
the world,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the State Department late Tuesday night issued its
second travelers' warning in 11 days alerting Americans to the
possibility of terrorism abroad following the arrest of militants
in Jordan last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot rule out the possibility that attacks still may be
planned for this and other parts of the world,'' the department
said.
</P>
<P>
   The recent travel advisory followed the Jordanian capture last
week of 13 members of Osama bin Laden's terrorist group. The
terrorists said they were planning attacks against U.S. and Israeli
interests, Jordanian officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The United States suspects bin Laden, an exiled Saudi, of
masterminding the bombing last year of two U.S. embassies in East
Africa, which killed more than 250 people and injured more than
5,000 others. Bin Laden has made general threats of terrorism
against the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The terrorism concern also prompted federal and local police in
Washington, D.C., to search in vain Wednesday for a blue van, with
Texas license plates, that someone reported as looking suspicious.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, U.S. Customs Service agents in the Bahamas
detained an American who was acting suspiciously and was found
carrying wires and magnetic coils. FBI officials questioned him in
Nassau, but a thorough search of the suspect uncovered nothing more
alarming, the State Department reported.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
A U.S. Customs spokesman in Washington said the man was wanted in
Texas but would not disclose the details of that case.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Also, federal officials Monday caught a second Algerian national
trying to sneak into the United States. Border Patrol agents in
Beecher Falls, Vt., captured Bouabide Chamchi, who was allegedly
carrying a fake passport.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials are investigating whether Chamchi and Ressam
are connected and whether either is linked to a terrorist
organization.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
