<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLOY'S FUTURE UP IN THE AIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ Lawyer Milloy, the only Patriots player to be named
to the AFC Pro Bowl starting team Wednesday, has dropped more than
a few hints that he may want to play football elsewhere next
season.
</P>
<P>
   One problem: The Patriots might not make it easy for him to walk
away.
</P>
<P>
   Milloy, who will be an unrestricted free agent at season's end,
was quite down Wednesday about the team's failure to make the
playoffs for the first time since being selected in the second
round out of Washington in 1996. Asked if he was returning to the
Patriots, Milloy said, ``I can't answer that question.''
</P>
<P>
   Milloy's comments about his Pro Bowl honor belied his feelings
about the status of the team: ``I'm tired of walking around like a
zombie,'' said Milloy. ``Not being able to vie for a championship
is very disappointing. We have so much talent on this team that to
be out of it . . . I'm disappointed. I'm team-oriented and I get
individual accolades through team success. . . . It's an individual
achievement. There's definite gratification for me and my family.
But when the team isn't involved, it doesn't mean as much to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Milloy and the Patriots negotiated during the bye week in
November and came to a philosophical understanding of where Milloy
would fit. Milloy also met with owner Robert Kraft and came away
feeling positive about a deal. No dollars were offered, but
Milloy's representatives made it clear that Milloy, now a two-time
Pro Bowler, would be the league's highest-paid safety, which meant
a six- or seven-year deal worth about $30 million-$35 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots, however, have the option of slapping a franchise
tag on Milloy, which means he would play for the team at the
average salary of the top five players at that position. Milloy, of
course, could still go elsewhere, but as a franchise player, his
new team would have to give the Patriots two No. 1 draft picks.
</P>
<P>
   Safeties aren't generally franchised, and the Patriots have
never franchised a player. They came close to doing it with Willie
McGinest last year, but in the end McGinest got his five-year deal
worth $25 million, including an $8 million signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Patriots vice president Andy Wasynczuk detests the franchise tag
and has avoided it all costs. Wednesday he hesitated but used it in
Milloy's case, feeling that he and Milloy's agent, Ray Anderson,
have negotiated in good faith and thinks there's no reason the
sides can't work something out.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of time for Ray and I to talk,'' said Wasynczuk.
``We'd made very good progress and we decided to pick it up at the
end of the season. We'll stick to that.''
</P>
<P>
   The league and the NFL Players Association have extended the
period a team has exclusive time to sign its own unrestricted free
agents. It used to be two weeks after the Super Bowl, but now it
will be March 1 before players can pursue other employment.
</P>
<P>
   The downside of franchising Milloy would be that he would likely
hold out if he was that unhappy, as did Seattle receiver Joey
Galloway and Cincinnati receiver Carl Pickens the last two years.
Milloy hasn't said he'll do that, either. But right now he's not in
a great state of mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be truthfully honest, I don't know what's going to happen
after this year,'' he said. ``Individually, I know that based on my
performance, I'm going to make a little more money than before.
That's certain being here or someplace else. I owe this
organization my exisiting contract. I owe my teammates two more
games and they're going to get my all.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty much finished. Everything is gonna affect it. I'll
weight out every scenario. I'll put myself in position to win a
championship. I'm going to lay out every possible scenario. If you
know me, it doesn't matter how much money I make. I'd be miserable
if I don't win. You can get paid a lot of money and not be happy,''
said Milloy, dropping another hint.
</P>
<P>
   He was quick to add that looking around the room he wasn't the
only player who might be with another team next year, which worries
him about where the team might be going.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not the only player in this situation,'' he said. ``One of
the players I respect so much a player who plays like me, but he's
on the other side of the ball is Troy Brown, and there's Shawn
Jefferson and Steve Israel . . . This team could drastically
change. That's why you have that zombie effect around here.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, he doesn't believe the Patriots belong watching the
playoffs. ``There's so much talent, that's the other reason it's so
frustrating,'' he said. ``Take nothing away from Cleveland and
Philly and Cincinnati, but we have the talent. We should have
beaten those teams.''
</P>
<P>
   He will get his happiness this Christmas, not necessarily from
the Pro Bowl berth, but more so from his daughter, who will visit
from the Seattle area.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing some shopping, putting together a turkey, wrapping
presents by myself, and putting a Christmas tree up,'' he said.
``I'm looking forward to that. I'm trying to channel my negative
energy to her. You need family in your spare time. She always gives
me a smile, which is important to me because I'm not the best
person to be around when we're losing.''
</P>
<P>
   While some players and Pete Carroll speak of salvaging something
the rest of the season, Milloy already feels all is lost. He
doesn't believe anyone can save themselves in the next two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too late for that,'' said Milloy. ``I've already told you
guys that just because you do something the final two weeks that
doesn't make up for messing up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
