<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6981 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-BORDER-TERROR-BOS &LR;      12-22 1209
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDER-TERROR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEADS IN TERRORISM THREAT LINKED TO BOSTON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY AND JUDY RAKOWSKY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ US authorities were tracking leads from around the
world Wednesday amid worries over end-of-the-year terror attacks
following the arrests in Vermont and Washington state of two
Algerian men, one of whom sought to enter the United States with
bomb-making materials.
</P>
<P>
   In Seattle Wednesday, a federal grand jury indicted Ahmed
Ressam, 32, who was charged with transporting explosives,
possessing unregistered firearms, smuggling nitroglycerin, and
giving false information to border guards.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the new leads, US officials said, were linked to New
England, specifically the Boston area. In addition, there was
generalized concern about higher risk in New England because of the
ease in slipping across the porous US-Canada border.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, seeking to awaken Americans to the threat of
terrorist attacks in the coming days and weeks, asked the public to
be watchful for any suspicious activity _ and if witnessed, to
contact police. Still, he said that Americans should not ``stop
their holiday activities. I think they ought to go and enjoy the
season.''
</P>
<P>
   In New England, one investigation focused on a Montreal woman,
arrested Sunday with Algerian native Bouabide Chamchi at the remote
Beecher Falls, Vt., crossing. She successfully crossed the
US-Canada border earlier in December with two Algerian nationals,
telling border officials her destination was Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators were also seeking three men in connection with a
bombing plot in Jordan, one of whom was last known to live at 15
Appleton St. in Everett, Mass. and has a Massachusetts driving
license. He was identified by law enforcement sources as Raed
Hajazi, 21.
</P>
<P>
   In the White House and at the State Department, Defense
Department, and other national security agencies, debate flourished
for the third consecutive day on how best to alert the public to
the threats while trying not to ruin the holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Said one US official who attended several of the high-level
meetings: ``The problem is, how do you make people concerned but
not send them running to the bomb shelters?''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, after visiting a Washington soup kitchen, said, ``For
all citizens, I would say they ought to go about their holidays and
enjoy themselves and make the most of it. But I would ask them to
just be aware of their circumstances and, if they see anything
suspicious, to report it immediately, and meanwhile to know that we
are doing everything we possibly can.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the government was making ``extraordinary efforts . . .
based on the incident out in the Pacific Northwest and what we
know.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities, however, still had not made any definitive
connection between the Algerian-born Ressem and Osama bin Laden, a
wealthy Saudi Arabian sought by the United States for masterminding
the 1998 US embassy bombings in Africa. There is a widespread
assumption among intelligence officials that Ressem has ties to bin
Laden associates, likely during time he spent in France three years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Carefully choosing his words at a news conference, Deputy
Attorney General Eric Holder assessed the threat of a terrorist
attack: ``We do not have any specific information about particular
targets.''
</P>
<P>
   US officials said Holder, and other top US officials, had agreed
to stick to the phrases ``specific information'' and ``particular
targets'' because they were technically true and also useful in
alleviating fears. US intelligence officials, though, had amassed
several leads on general threats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we have general reporting that concerns us? Absolutely,''
said an administration official, speaking on condition of
anonymity. ``That's why we have have taken steps to raise the alert
status on the borders and issued the two warnings'' for Americans
living or travelling overseas.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department issued a second warning late Tuesday that
said, ``The US government believes that terrorists may be planning
to conduct attacks including against official and non-official
Americans, in and around the New Year period (from now through
mid-January 2000) with particular emphasis on locations where large
groups of people may congregate for millennial or religious
festivities.''
</P>
<P>
   US officials believe that if a terrorist group decides to attack
Americans it could happen anywhere in the world, and it could
happen in coordinated fashion in multiple locations. In August
1998, bin Laden's organization was believed responsible for two
almost simultaneous attacks on US embassies in Kenya and Tanzania
that killed more than 200 people.
</P>
<P>
   If terrorist attacks were to happen in the United States, the
most vulnerable places may be New England, New York City and parts
of the West Coast, US officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very concerned the Osama bin Laden group has cells set
up in New York, a little on the West Coast, and in quieter areas of
the upper East Coast, such as Connecticut, Massachusetts, New
Hampshire, Vermont and Maine,'' said a second US official, speaking
on condition of anonymity and refusing to give further details.
``The reason we're so concerned about New England is that there has
been so little attention paid in the past to the border crossings
up there.'' Those border crossings have been substantially
tightened in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, another US official said he believed the government
warnings made it safer for people to attend public gatherings.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about specific information on threats in New England, the
official said, ``Anyone who was not taking these threats seriously
is taking it seriously now. It's going to be important for First
Night in Boston, and all the other First Nights going on around New
England, that people are vigilant. In the end, that benefits
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   An Israeli expert on terrorism, Boaz Ganor, said the arrests of
the two Algerian men _ if either or both are linked to terrorist
plans _ may break up a ring of terrorists. ``There is going to be
concern about what those people say in custody,'' Ganor said.
</P>
<P>
   But Neil Livingstone, chairman of GlobalOptions, a security and
crisis management company in Washington, said he believed the
arrests represented only the ``tip of the iceberg'' of terrorists'
plans.
</P>
<P>
   He predicted 10 to 15 terrorist attacks globally around the turn
of the millennium, possibly coming from several groups ``because
terrorists know that by marking the millennium with whatever they
do, they will be immortalized.''
</P>
<P>
   Livingstone and several US officials noted that the threat
worldwide was perhaps greatest in Jordan and Israel, where
authorities expect upward of 1.5 million tourists to descend on the
tiny state in the holiday season. Also vulnerable are US troops
stationed in Bosnia because of lax security around the borders, US
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But Livingstone said from a terrorist's perspective, the biggest
target remains the United States. ``If you can score the United
States, that's like getting center on the bull's eye,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Donnelly reported from Washington; Rakowsky from Boston.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
