<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6987 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-CHINA-FILMS-ART-$ADV2     12-22 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-FILMS-ART-$ADV26-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FETED ABROAD, AND NO LONGER BANNED IN BEIJING  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 26) 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 Erik Eckholm is co-chief of the Beijing bureau of The New York
Times.  
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   These are exhilarating, and perhaps a bit frightening, times for
Zhang Yuan, 36, who is increasingly described in international film
circles as perhaps the most gifted and original filmmaker of his
generation, even though his movies have not been widely seen at
home or abroad.
</P>
<P>
   His past films, including ``Beijing Bastards'' (1992) and ``East
Palace, West Palace'' (1996), were banned in China because they
dealt with hidden subjects like alienated youths and furtive
homosexual encounters. That they were stylistically off-beat as
well _ ``Beijing Bastards'' was a deliberately raw, improvised
slice of life in the rock underground _ compounded his sins in the
eyes of Communist censors.
</P>
<P>
   The commercial market abroad for serious Chinese movies is quite
limited. But Zhang's seven feature films, including fiction and
documentaries, have become favorites on the international art-house
and film-festival circuit. Known for years as an intriguing
underground filmmaker, he is now swamped with invitations to appear
at festivals and seminars.
</P>
<P>
   Just in the last several weeks, Zhang _ a stocky man with a baby
face, the eyes of Edward G. Robinson and an explosion of curly hair
that could shame Gene Wilder _ attended a screening of his films at
the National Gallery of Art in Washington, spoke at a three-day
Zhang Yuan retrospective held by the Harvard Film Archive,
discussed his films at the University of Massac at Amherst,
traveled to London for a museum screening and then went on to
Argentina, where he helped judge a film festival.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recognize in his work a mastery of the medium,'' said Bruce
Jenkins, curator of the Harvard Film Archive, explaining why it
sponsored such a big program for a young, still-evolving director.
``You can already tell he'll have an impressive body of work, that
he'll be as important to his generation of filmmakers as Chen Kaige
and Zhang Yimou have been to theirs.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins was referring to the ``fifth generation'' masters who
are in their late 40s and came out of the Beijing Film Academy
years before Zhang Yuan.
</P>
<P>
   More compelling to Zhang than the global acclaim, but also
potentially more perilous to his art, is the shaky bridge he is
crossing at home. Only two years ago, angry Chinese authorities
confiscated his passport when he tried to go to the Cannes
International Film Festival, where ``East Palace, West Palace'' had
been entered, and threatened him with prosecution if he tried to
make another film on the sly.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Zhang has just made two features in cooperation with the
government's film bureau, one fictional and one a documentary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been making films for almost 10 years now, and virtually
nothing has been seen by Chinese audiences,'' Zhang said in a
recent interview in Beijing, between trips to Boston and London.
``That's something that has really frustrated and pained me.''
</P>
<P>
   So to reach his home audience _ and avoid possible arrest _ he
allowed the censors to review the scripts and edited versions of
his new features. In the case of both the fictional feature,
``Seventeen Years,'' and the full-length documentary, ``Crazy
English,'' some last-minute cuts were required, Zhang said. And
now, ``Seventeen Years'' is scheduled to open commercially in
Beijing next month, and prospects are good for the documentary to
be released here, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``All artists have to make choices, and these become
limitations,'' Zhang said, obviously troubled by the subject and
aware that some younger artists here are wondering whether he has
lost his edge. ``Limitations are not necessarily all bad,'' he
continued, ``but as an artist you still have to make sure that what
you are doing remains real.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the background, Zhang is proud of his two new films and
at this stage would welcome more commercial success. While ``East
Palace, West Palace'' has played art houses in many countries and
brought in some money, Zhang has had to spend a large share of his
time over the last decade shooting commercials and rock videos for
a living, and trawling Europe and Asia for financial backers. He
and his wife, Ning Dai, a screenwriter, live well by Beijing
standards, but he still answers his own phone and makes all his own
arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   In September, ``Seventeen Years'' won him the best-director
award at the Venice Film Festival. It does not yet have an American
distributor, but deals have been signed in Italy, Japan, Brazil and
several other countries.
</P>
<P>
   The film tells the story of a girl who murders her taunting
sister, then after 17 years in prison gets a leave to visit home to
see her aged, bitter parents. It will not be mistaken for a
Hollywood thriller: it proceeds quietly, the drama propelled by
silences and glances as much as by dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   But with its clean direction, Vermeeresque lighting and
memorable characters, and a simple, wrenching story with a happy
ending, the film may appeal to a broader audience here than Zhang's
more ponderous early films would have.
</P>
<P>
   The new documentary, ``Crazy English,'' is about Li Yang, a
wildly successful promoter who leads auditoriums full of Chinese in
shouting out English phrases _ the path, he says, to overcoming
inhibitions, learning English and making China strong. The feature
has no narration; rather, it just lets Li keep talking, and he is
so nimble and funny that the technique works.
</P>
<P>
   Some Western critics have suggested that the film is a subtle
expose of mob psychology, with allusions to Mao Zedong's Cultural
Revolution. Hearing that, Zhang laughs and says, ``That's going too
far.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if Li Yang does have that tendency, it's a funny and cool
one,'' he says. He hopes for a public television showing in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   It's remarkable that Zhang ever got to make films at all, let
alone develop an original sensibility. He was born in 1963 in the
southern city of Nanjing. He had poor health, he says, and
cultivated a love of painting. Only at about age 20 did he become
interested in writing and film and learn that the Beijing Film
Academy, China's elite training ground, had reopened in 1978, after
the end of the Cultural Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, the academy advertised for a new batch of students.
Tens of thousands applied, including Zhang, who had little
knowledge of film but apparently did so spectacularly well in
essays and interviews that he was one of 16 students accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Up to that point the only foreign films that Zhang, like most
Chinese, had seen were from the Soviet Union, North Korea and
Yugoslavia. But the academy had copies of the best movies appearing
in the United States and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was like someone who'd been starved for a long time,'' he
recalled. While specializing in cinematography, he devoured the
films of Martin Scorsese, watching ``Taxi Driver,'' ``Mean
Streets'' and others dozens of times. He also studied the work of
Italian directors like Antonioni and Fellini.
</P>
<P>
   But his biggest revelation, Zhang said, was seeing Chinese films
of the 1930s. ``That was a time when Chinese arts were at their
liveliest,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   From the opening scene of his first film, ``Mama,'' about a
mother and her retarded child, which was completed in 1990, Zhang
established himself as a fresh cinematic voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nearly every one of Zhang Yuan's films has broken thematic and
stylistic ground,'' said Yaohua Shi, an expert on Chinese film at
the University of Massachusetts who served as host for Zhang and
his works recently. ``He has opted for a gritty, deliberately
unglamorous cinematic technique or the documentary style, often
avoiding visual pyrotechnics.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Zhang had made ``Mama'' through official channels, it
was not viewed favorably by officials and received almost no
distribution, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point I realized that if I really wanted to express my
own views about society, then I needed total independence,'' Zhang
said.
</P>
<P>
   The film he wanted to make next, ``Beijing Bastards,'' which
portrayed the amoral, apolitical lives of an underground youth
culture, could not remotely have passed official muster. ``They
couldn't have reviewed a script because we didn't have one!'' he
said of the 1992 film, which featured the alienated rock songs of
Cui Jian.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes called China's first independent feature, ``Beijing
Bastards'' was filmed with an intentionally rough quality
reminiscent of Andy Warhol, and it captured the attention of
cognoscenti.
</P>
<P>
   After a documentary about Tiananmen Square, Zhang made ``Sons,''
a realistic fiction about a father's alcoholism and insanity.
</P>
<P>
   ``East Palace, West Palace,'' in 1996, showed a new
sophistication and secured Zhang's reputation abroad. Showing the
gay underworld of city parks and a police officer's homoerotic pull
toward a masochistic cruiser, it examined themes that are simply
not discussed in public here.
</P>
<P>
   It may be no coincidence that in May 1996, China's cabinet
passed new ``Rules for Administration of Films'' that, among other
vague provisions, proscribed the making of movies that ``threaten
the security, reputation and interests of the state.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that the new film law specifically banned
independent filmmaking, outside the official studio system,'' said
Chris Berry, an expert on the Asian cinema at La Trobe University
in Melbourne, Australia. ``Before that it was a gray area.''
</P>
<P>
   Zhang says that after the 1997 clash over the showing of ``East
Palace, West Palace'' at the Cannes Film Festival, and the loss of
his passport, he knew he was at an impasse. ``If I had continued to
work the same way, I'd probably have lost my freedom,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After eight months of limbo, Zhang was given his passport back,
and he began intensive discussions with the film authorities,
leading to agreement in 1998 that he could resume making movies.
</P>
<P>
   Now, even as he eagerly anticipates his first Chinese commercial
release, he can't stop thinking about the strictures. ``An artist
has to express his point of view fully and without any
constraint,'' he said. ``If an artist can't do that, then there's
no hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Will he always be able to find topics that excite him and are
acceptable to the censors? ``I have no idea,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deng Xiaoping used a parable to describe how we should run our
economy,'' Zhang said, ```Crossing the river by feeling the stones,
one at a time.'''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``I think China's artists also have to think this
way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
