<HEADLINE>
BELL ATLANTIC GETS LONG-DISTANCE OK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic Corp. became Wednesday the first Baby Bell local
telephone carrier to gain federal approval to offer long-distance
service.
</P>
<P>
   After getting the go-ahead to enter the long-distance market in
New York, the company now will seek federal permission by the
middle of next year to offer the same service in Massachusetts,
followed by Pennsylvania and New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   In a landmark decision that launches a new era of competition,
the Federal Communications Commission Wednesday said the nation's
second-largest local phone company can offer the same wide range of
voice and advanced data communications in New York that AT&AMP;T Corp.,
MCI Worldcom Inc. and other long-distance carriers provide. These
companies are expected to mount a vigorous defense in the
marketplace against Bell Atlantic's attempts to capture
long-distance residential and business customers in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC approval, which was expected, puts the Baby Bells back
into the lucrative $100 billion-a-year long-distance market, an
arena the Bells had been barred from since they were spun out from
AT&AMP;T Corp. in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   ``The FCC's actions in New York is the most important
telecommunications decision of this decade. This is the now the
beginning of the end of local monopolies across America,'' said US
Representative Edward J. Markey, a Democrat from Malden, Mass., who
is the ranking Democrat on the House telecommunications, trade and
consumer protection subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it is possible for Massachusetts and other states to get
in line. I think this decision is to telecommunications what the
collapse of the Berlin Wall was to freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   For consumers, more competition promises choice, better prices,
new services and the end of local phone monopolies _ the central
premise of the Telecommunications Act of 1996. The law specified
the market-opening steps that regional Bell companies were required
to make before they could enter the long-distance business.
</P>
<P>
   Until Wednesday, the FCC had denied five long-distance
applications by regional Bell companies. The FCC, in its decision,
said Bell Atlantic can begin offering service in New York early
next year, and the company set Jan. 5 as its kickoff date.
</P>
<P>
   ``The road to this moment has not been easy,'' said FCC chairman
William Kennard.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone was pleased with Bell Atlantic's long-distance
entry into New York. AT&AMP;T said it is considering legal actions
challenging the FCC's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``While Bell Atlantic has made real progress in New York, its
application still falls well short of the law's requirement in at
least two areas critical to competition,'' said AT&AMP;T general
counsel Jim Cicconi, in a statement. One of those areas concerns
how quickly and smoothly orders from customers switching from Bell
Atlantic to another long-distance carrier are handled.
</P>
<P>
   MCI, by contrast, said it was looking forward to battling Bell
Atlantic in New York's highly competitive long-distance market.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Ivan Seidenberg, Bell Atlantic's chairman, said his
company expects to seek FCC approval during the first half of 2000
to offer long-distance service in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will build on this (New York) success as quickly as
possible,'' said Seidenberg, noting that Massachusetts is the next
state where Bell Atlantic will seek FCC approval, followed by
Pennsylvania and New Jersey. The New York phone giant serves 13
states from Maine to Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, SBC Communications Inc., the San Antonio-based phone
giant, said it plans to file its application to offer long-distance
service in Texas with the FCC in early January.
</P>
<P>
   Since September, Bell Atlantic has been testing its Bay State
computer and communications systems to meet a 14-point checklist
required for FCC approval. A key test requires Bell Atlantic to
quickly switch customers to a competitor upon the customer's
request. That means making sure telephone records, phone lines and
billing information are shifted smoothly through a computerized
operational support system.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, as in Massachusetts, this testing is overseen by
KPMG Worldwide, the giant accounting and consulting firm. In a
process involving parallel federal and state approvals, KPMG is
expected to complete its testing for the Bay State's Department of
Telecommunications and Energy in late March. On Tuesday, the DTE
completed a series of regulatory hearings on Bell Atlantic's
long-distance plans.
</P>
<P>
   DTE commmissioner Paul B. Vasington Wednesday said that the
commission could give its recommendation in June if Bell Atlantic
meets regulatory requirements.
</P>
<P>
   He said Bell Atlantic then would file an application with the
FCC (the document was 88,500 pages long for New York) detailing how
it opened its local markets to competition and complied with the
Telecommunications Act of 1996. The DTE also would write a report,
based on the KPMG findings. Both documents then would be sent to
the FCC, which has 90 days to make its decision.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, AT&AMP;T and MCI are watching how Bay State regulators
handle Bell Atlantic's long-distance application, MCI claims the
local phone company is not far along in its testing yet. ``We're
watching them very closely,'' said spokeswoman Elena French.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T plans to offer local telephone service via cable when its
proposed acquisition of cable television giant MediaOne Group is
completed next year. Unlike New York, where AT&AMP;T has hardly any
cable ownership, MediaOne controls about 60 percent of the state's
cable TV industry with more than 1 million customers.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic shares were down 1 1/16 to close at 64 1/2
Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
