<SLUG> BC-POLICEMAN-SHOT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD SAMARITAN COP SHOT THROUGH CAR DOOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KERA RITTER AND KIRSTEN ANDELMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLYOKE, Mass. _ Patrolman John DiNapoli wasn't supposed to be
on the beat Wednesday morning when he volunteered to help break up
a fight in a rough part of town. The impulse cost him his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could have kept on going and nobody would have known the
difference,'' Holyoke Police Chief Marc Cournoyer said. ``But that
would not have been John.''
</P>
<P>
   DiNapoli, a 21-year veteran whose normal duties involved
administrative work and classroom stints as McGruff the Crime Dog,
was killed when the suspect he was chasing spun around, drew a gun
and fired into DiNapoli's unmarked car, police said.
</P>
<P>
   DiNapoli, 52, wounded in the abdomen, shoulder, arm and heart,
died minutes later at a Springfield hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting touched off a massive, intense manhunt for the
suspect, Eddie Morales, who was charged in a warrant with
DiNapoli's murder and was still at large Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   DiNapoli, the father of two grown children, joined the force
after a friend who was a police officer was killed in the line of
duty in 1977. Officer James Gatzounas died from a heart attack
while breaking up a fight. Gatzounas was the last Holyoke officer
on the 130-person force to die in the line of duty and DiNapoli was
the first to die of gunshot wounds.
</P>
<P>
   Morales, 27, had lived in the neighborhood around Sergeant and
Walnut streets, the scene of the fight. Police said he was known to
authorities in both cities and Holyoke residents reported that
Morales was connected to a gang that patterned itself after the
Latin Kings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Morales, he's trouble,'' said Tom Obuchowski, a longtime
Holyoke resident who grew up with DiNapoli's children.
</P>
<P>
   After the killing several dozen city and State Police officers,
some dressed in SWAT team gear, searched buildings, blocked off
streets and put up checkpoints in a furious search for Morales. A
State Police helicopter hovered overhead and police ordered
children from some neighborhoods to stay in school until their
parents could retrieve them.
</P>
<P>
   The full-scale search ultimately was called off at about 2:30
p.m., but officers said they were still confident Morales would be
found.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, residents of the neighborhood where DiNapoli
was killed have complained that the area has been overrun by gangs,
drug dealers and prostitutes. Police have lately stepped up their
presence there, residents said. Some suggested that the shooting
may have been a response to their increased attention.
</P>
<P>
   DiNapoli had just dropped off a fellow officer at Juvenile Court
when he heard the call about the fight. The nearest on-duty
officers were several blocks away, Holyoke police officials said.
DiNapoli was a block and a half away, and figured he could help.
Police would not say whether he had a weapon.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he did this morning was typical of police officers and
typical of him. He responded to a call he thought he could assist
in.'' said Arthur Therrien, a training officer with the department,
who shared an office with DiNapoli.
</P>
<P>
   As police searched for Morales, residents hung out windows and
lingered on streetcorners, watching the spectacle. As the hours
passed, many shrugged and grumbled that the supsect was probably
long gone.
</P>
<P>
   Cournoyer issued a plea to Morales to give himself up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to stop looking for you until we find you,''
the chief said.
</P>
<P>
   Cournoyer said Morales shouldn't worry that police will mistreat
him because of the alleged crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would extend to him my personal guarantee he will be treated
with the utmost respect,'' Cournoyer said. ``One thing that's very
important to John DiNapoli is that he would not want anyone to
jeopardize their career or the investigation because of emotional
feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   He asked anyone with information about Morales to call the
police department at 413-536-6431.
</P>
<P>
   DiNapoli was the second police officer in the state to die on
duty this month. Wareham police Officer Christopher Argentinis was
killed when struck by a State Police cruiser as he tried to help
chase a suspect Dec. 11.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Joanna Weiss of the Globe Staff contributed to this report. Wire
service material was used in its preparation.)
</P>
</TEXT>
