<SLUG> BC-SCUDDER-FINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCUDDER KEMPER TO PAY $250,000 FOR IMPROPER TRADES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scudder Kemper Investments Inc. will pay a $250,000 fine to
settle federal allegations that a former employee in its Boston
office lost more than $16 million in unauthorized trades.
</P>
<P>
   Scudder and the former trader, Michael T. Sullivan, did not
admit to or deny the findings of an investigation conducted by the
Securities and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   But Scudder agreed to the fine under an adminstrative order the
SEC issued Wednesday. Sullivan, who resigned after the improper
trades were discovered in 1998, will be barred from the securities
industry for at least five years. He lacks the resources to pay a
civil penalty, the SEC determined.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan's former supervisor, Gary Paul Johnson, was also cited
by the commission. He did not admit to or deny the charges, either,
but agreed to be suspended as an investment adviser for three
months and to pay a $10,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   According to the settlement documents, from at least July 1997
through October 1998, Sullivan ``repeatedly ignored loss limits''
and other financial controls and concealed his activities by
miscoding order tickets and forging supervisors' signatures.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had to disguise that activity, or theoretically his
supervisors would have known,'' said Juan Marcelino, the SEC's
district administrator in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Federal investigators also faulted Johnson for not detecting the
losses. In addition, the SEC found that Scudder's ``controls and
procedures were not designed reasonably to prevent and detect the
trader's activities,'' according to the order.
</P>
<P>
   Scudder, the big mutual-fund company owned by Swiss-based Zurich
Financial Services Group, has about 1,000 employees in Eastern
Massachsetts, centered in downtown Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Scudder said it discovered the improper trades through its own
reviews and called them to the SEC's attention late last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This individual violated our written policies and practices,''
the firm said in a prepared statement. Scudder spokeswoman Eleanor
Mascheroni declined to discuss whether insurance covers the losses.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's attorney, Joseph Goldstein of the Kirkpatrick &AMP;
Lockhart firm in Washington, declined to comment. Efforts to reach
Sullian via his attorney didn't succeed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan, now 37, joined Scudder in 1984 and according to the
SEC was working as a derivatives trader in 1996, when the firm
implemented a trading program that gave him and other officers new
powers to initiate trades, within certain limits. From July 1997
until he left the company in 1998, Sullivan exceeded those limits
on 12 out of 20 institutional accounts.
</P>
<P>
   But he avoided detection by making it appear some of his trades
were of a type not subject to the program's limits, the SEC wrote,
using forged signatures on order tickets or simply failing to file
those documents as required.
</P>
<P>
   Scudder's Mascheroni declined to say who at Scudder first
noticed the losses, though Scudder has since halted the trading
program in question.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, 50, left Scudder this year for reasons Mascheroni
declined to discuss. He previously had oversight of Scudder's
derivatives trading desk and, the SEC wrote, ``knew or should have
known of certain significant irregulaties.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor were porfolio managers given enough information to monitor
the trades that were conducted on behalf of their accounts, the SEC
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Scudder said that as a result of the investigation it has
``implemented enhancements to its policies and procedures related
to derivatives trading.'' Mascheroni declined to discuss specific
changes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
