<SLUG> BC-FILM-GALAXYQUEST-TEX </SLUG>
 
Looking for a smart, spoofy movie this holiday season? 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Populated with sitcom actors and a self-mocking Sigourney Weaver
and Alan Rickman, the cast of ``Galaxy Quest'' appears to be made
up of people who were left out of a hipster comedy like ``Mystery
Men'' _ and got their revenge by throwing a more entertaining
party. It can be a joy watching actors have a good time, especially
in this largely morose holiday-movie season, and ``Galaxy Quest's''
performers seem to be having the time of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   The actors they're playing, however, aren't _ at least not at
the beginning of the movie. They're the stars of a long-canceled
``Star Trek''-like TV show called ``Galaxy Quest,'' apparently
doomed forever to a life of show-convention appearances and
reaching the point William Shatner did on a ``Saturday Night Live''
sketch when he began screaming, ``Get a life, people!'' at obsessed
fans.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out, though, that among ``Galaxy Quest's'' devotees are
four aliens disguised as humans (who apparently got their earthly
fashion sense from an old Devo album cover). They believe the show
is real and recruit the star, Jason Nesmith (Tim Allen), to aid in
their battle against some horrifically ugly enemy aliens (led by
British actor Robin Sachs, doing a great villain turn from within
an 80-pound costume).
</P>
<P>
   It's when Nesmith figures out that the aliens, and their ship,
are real that the movie really comes to life _ and it doesn't waste
a lot of time getting to that point. As Nesmith brings the rest of
his ``crew'' on board, Allen portrays him with growing childlike
glee, as if he were already thinking about counting his ``Toy Story
2'' money. His exuberance turns him into the movie's ``captain,''
inspiring his supporting cast to join the battle.
</P>
<P>
   Although ``Quest'' has a tendency to lurch back and forth like a
starship in a meteor shower, switching from comedy to
straightforward science-fiction and throwing in scattered shrill or
maudlin moments, it always rights itself before it goes off course.
Credit that to director Dean Parisot's trust in his cast and his
ability to keep things flying at a fast pace.
</P>
<P>
   Parisot's trust allows for some sharp scene-stealing by Rickman,
whose comic disdain is perfectly suited to a dignified actor stuck
in pseudo-Klingon makeup, and by Tony Shalhoub, as the show's
technical sergeant who proves to have as much sardonic panache in
real life as he did on the show.
</P>
<P>
   Weaver and Daryl Mitchell show good-humored sportsmanship in
enduring the kind of token roles they would have had on a TV series
(Mitchell is probably happy to be in anything that's not
``Veronica's Closet''), while Sam Rockwell is the extraneous guest
star who seems destined not to survive the mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``Galaxy Quest'' might look like goofy fun at first glance, but
it's actually very smart; this is the first live-action comedy in
recent memory to not include potty humor or crotch-injury jokes.
Screenwriters David Howard and Robert Gordon actually find humor in
words, with deceptively throwaway dialogue given sharp twists by
the timing of Allen, Rickman and Shalhoub. A smart, spoofy
major-studio comedy _ fortunately, it hasn't become an alien
concept.
</P>
<P>
   ``Galaxy Quest'' is rated PG for cartoonish violence, occasional
profanity, and Sigourney Weaver's cleavage. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Galaxy Quest'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 1/2 on a 1-5 scale &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Director: Dean Parisot &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stars: Tim Allen, Sigourney Weaver &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Length: 102 min. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
.MDRV/ nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
