<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-PARQUET-2ND </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
   TAKE-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... of bounds.  8. Bird steals from Isiah: Bird picks off Isiah Thomas's inbounds
pass with five seconds left and feeds an off-balance pass to Dennis
Johnson for the winning basket in a 108-107 victory over the
Pistons in Game 5 of the Eastern Conference Finals, May 26, 1987. 
 
9. Parish belts Laimbeer: In the same game as the Bird steal,
Robert Parish and Bill Laimbeer get into a scuffle and Parish fires
off a few punches, which earns him a $7,500 fine and one-game
suspension, not to mention the adoration of Garden fans. 
 
10. Henderson's steal: Gerald Henderson steals James Worthy's pass
to Byron Scott with 13 seconds left and the game tied at 113 in
Game 2 of the Finals May 31, 1984. The Celtics go on to beat the
Lakers in overtime, 124-121. 
 
11. Heard's buzzer-beater: Phoenix's Gar Heard, taking an inbounds
pass with just one second showing on the clock, hits an improbable
22-footer to send Game 6 of the Finals into a third overtime,
setting up a 128-126 triple-overtime Celtics victory June 4, 1976. 
 
12. Magic's hook shot: In Game 4 of the Finals against the Lakers,
June 9, 1987 _ after Bird had hit a 3-pointer to put the Celtics
ahead _ Magic Johnson curls in a shot over the heads of Bird,
Parish, and McHale to give Los Angeles a 107-106 victory. 
 
13. Sam Jones grabs a chair: In a playoff game against the
Phiadelphia Warriors April 1, 1962, Jones is fouled _ hard _ by
Wilt Chamberlain. With thoughts of retaliation, but realizing he
was at a bit of a height disadvantage, Jones arms himself with a
photographer's stool, just in case. 
 
14. Cowens hits the floor: With the score tied in the final minute
in a playoff game against the Milwaukee Bucks May 10, 1974, Dave
Cowens, switching off his man, knocks the ball away from Oscar
Robertson, and dived after it to force a 24-second violation. The
Celtics eventually lost in overtime. 
 
15. Wilt vs. Russell: Bill Russell and Chamberlain jump center
court at Boston in 68 games, a total of more than 270 vertical
showdowns. 
 
16. McHale's towel: Before stepping to the free throw line, McHale
would go through a ritual that included making use of a towel left
under the basket to wipe off the sweat. 
 
17. Red's cigar: Opponents _ and everyone in the Garden _ knew when
coach Red Auerbach felt the Celtics had the game securely in hand,
as he would light up his famous victory cigar. 
 
18. A pigeon takes the floor: With the Celtics trailing Game 5 of
their playoff series with the Pistons, May 9, 1991, a pigeon
suddenly appears on the parquet, holding up play. Moments later,
the bird reappears as Parish is approaching the foul line. It must
have been a lucky pigeon, as the Celtics rally for a 109-103
victory. 
 
19. Keeping time: Tony Nota served as timekeeper at the Garden for
many years, though it was hard to keep track of how many times he
was fired _ then rehired _ by Auerbach. 
 
20. Heinsohn's hook: Celtics forward Tommy Heinsohn liked this spot
_ among others _ for his patented hook shot that was a big part of
his career 18.6 scoring average. 
 
21. Kareem's hook shot: Kareem Abdul-Jabbar hits an amazing hook
shot from the corner to give Milwaukee a 102-101 victory over the
Celtics May 10, 1974 to force Game 7 in the 1974 Finals. 
 
22. Bird's fractured cheek: Bird hits his face hard on the floor
with 4:23 left in the half of a deciding Game 5 with Indiana May 5,
1991. He's not on the court when the second half begins, but with
6:46 left in the third quarter, the crowd goes wild when Bird
emerges from the locker room and helps lead the Celtics to a
122-121 victory.
<TEXT>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
