<SLUG> BC-FILM-ANGELAS-ASHES-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPELLING `ANGELA'S ASHES' LOSES SOMETHING IN TRANSLATION
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: EMBARGOED until Friday, Dec. 24) 
Our rating: 2 1/2 stars 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The film version of ``Angela's Ashes,'' Frank McCourt's Pulitzer
Prize-winning memoir, was probably a doomed venture from the
outset, given that the elements that made the book such a wonderful
read _ McCourt's language and inimitable voice _ simply cannot be
transferred to the screen. And while director Alan Parker manages
to capture the book's abject poverty and misery (perhaps a little
too well), his rather superficial adaptation too often fails to
convey McCourt's wry humor, which made the memoir so delightful.
</P>
<P>
   Parker, who co-wrote the screenplay adaptation with Laura Jones,
also made a fatal tactical error by deciding to re-create just
about every event in the book. That's a tall order, even given the
film's generous twp-hour, 25-minute running length. To cram
everything in, Parker rushes the audience from one episode to the
next, the economical treatment robbing the story of its emotional
wallop.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, there are plenty of wallop-packing events in
``Angela's Ashes.'' The McCourts _ long-suffering Angela (Emily
Watson); her alcoholic husband, Malachy (Robert Carlyle); and their
four children _ made the unusual move of emigrating back to Ireland
from the United States. Attempting to escape the poverty of New
York in the 1930s, the McCourts find conditions far worse in
Ireland. Their situation isn't helped much by the perpetual
dampness of Limerick and Malachy's northern accent. (Few will hire
him because of it.) When Malachy does work, he tends to take his
paycheck directly to the local pub.
</P>
<P>
   Soldiering through the cold and hunger is young Frank, the
oldest of the McCourt children. Parker employs three young actors
(Joe Breen, Ciaran Owens, Michael Legge) to portray Frank at ages
5, 10 and 16, and they do so with remarkable consistency and
cohesion.
</P>
<P>
   Readers of ``Angela's Ashes'' (and there are millions of them)
will undoubtedly enjoy seeing some of the book's scenes come to
life. Indeed, production designer Geoffrey Kirkland has re-created
the McCourts' lowly Limerick neighborhood with such incredible
detail that McCourt himself thought he had entered a time warp when
he visited the set one day. The film's washed-out photography,
combined with the eternal gray skies and moist landscapes,
marvelously evoke McCourt's Ireland and its miserable poverty.
</P>
<P>
   But to truly succeed and stand on its own, the movie needs to
illuminate more than soggy scenery. Parker's ``Angela's Ashes''
isn't a washout, but neither does it approach the book's soaring
lyricism. Mostly, it's just unnecessary. &QL; 
____ &QL; 
The film: ``Angela's Ashes'' (R; sexual content and some
language). &QL; 
The stars: Emily Watson, Robert Carlyle. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by Alan Parker. Screenplay by Parker
and Laura Jones, based on the memoir by Frank McCourt. Released by
Paramount Pictures. &QL; 
Running time: Two hours, 25 minutes. &QL; 
Playing: Opening Christmas Day. &QL; 
Our rating: 2 1/2 stars &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
