A7002 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-SENATE-RACE-NYT &LR;      12-22 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-RACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN NEW YORK, THE MAYOR AND MRS. CLINTON TRADE CHARGE AND
COUNTER-CHARGE
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani asserted on Wednesday that
Democrats in Washington and New York were conspiring to discredit
him as he prepared to run for the U.S. Senate, while Hillary Rodham
Clinton suggested that Giuliani was consumed by an anger that could
undercut his effectiveness in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady and the mayor made their remarks at almost
precisely the same moment, though in different parts of the state
and without knowledge of what the other was saying.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bronx, Giuliani contended that Democrats acting at Mrs.
Clinton's behest were waging an orchestrated campaign to damage his
candidacy, taking note of an investigation by the Brooklyn district
attorney into his chief political adviser, Bruce Teitelbaum, and
the federal takeover of a $60 million city homeless program ordered
by Andrew Cuomo, the secretary of housing and urban development.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are all involved in politics,'' Giuliani declared at a
groundbreaking in Hunts Point. ``They are all thinking about how
they can help Al Gore, Hillary Clinton. I wish they would stop it.
It actually is silly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to be like living on Mars not to figure out what's
going on,'' he said. ``This is Clinton politics come to New York.
It's what they used to do in Arkansas.''
</P>
<P>
   In Syracuse, Mrs. Clinton went from packing Salvation Army
holiday food bags for poor families to a news conference in which
she described Giuliani as someone who was ``getting angry all the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time Mrs. Clinton has raised what her aides
have advised her to make a central thrust of her campaign against
Giuliani, and she swiftly offered up the criticism when she was
asked her views on whether Cuomo had been politically motivated in
acting against the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it made the mayor angry,'' Mrs. Clinton said, smiling
broadly as she ratcheted her candidacy up to a new level. ``But you
know, the mayor always gets angered about things that go on, and I
think we ought to keep our focus on what is the best way to deliver
the services that people in need in New York City require.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have anything to add, other than I can't be responding
every time the mayor gets angry,'' she said. ``Because that's all I
would do.''
</P>
<P>
   But a moment later, in response to a question by a reporter,
Mrs. Clinton suggested that Giuliani's style would be problematic
in the U.S. Senate, as she previewed what is likely to be one of
her campaign's dominant themes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you go to the United States Senate, you are one of 100,''
she said. ``If they don't vote for the position you want them vote
for, you can't fire them, you can't go out and hire yourself some
new senators from somewhere else in the country. You have to work
with them.''
</P>
<P>
   The comments of the two prospective candidates came on a brisk
winter day three days before Christmas, but sounded in tone and
intensity like the kind of charge-and-counter-charge that might be
expected three days before Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   For Giuliani, it was a day to display his hardest-hitting
campaign style, as he shifted from attacks on Cuomo to Mrs. Clinton
to Charles J. Hynes, the Brooklyn district attorney, to the media.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the day clearly marked a new phase in Mrs.
Clinton's voyage from being a first lady to being a candidate in
New York. As such, it might serve to calm the concerns of some
Democrats worried that she does not have the stomach for the kind
of political brawling that seems inevitable in the contest to
replace Daniel Patrick Moynihan, the Democrat who is retiring.
</P>
<P>
   And the first lady, facing a new round of questions about her
fund-raising practices, sought to gain the offensive by declaring
that she was prepared to renounce the use of so-called soft-money,
the largely unregulated campaign contributions that have already
played a prominent role in Clinton fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not unilaterally do that,'' she said. ``But I would
certainly entertain a complete agreement on the part of any
opponents in my race that everyone would avoid the use of soft
money and not permit any independent expenditures on a candidates'
behalf.''
</P>
<P>
   But Teitelbaum dismissed Mrs. Clinton's statement as a gimmick.
``The continued stories about abuses of the campaign finance law
and the Clintons' use of soft money is obviously a concern and this
is an attempt to head off the damage of further revelations that
will likely surface,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's remarks about Democratic efforts against him were in
response to two events that have buffeted City Hall. The first is
an investigation by Hynes, the Democratic district attorney of
Brooklyn, into whether Teitelbaum, when he served as Giuliani's
chief of staff, improperly intervened to help Orthodox Jewish
supporters in Brooklyn who were involved in a dispute with the
city's Buildings Department.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani called on Hynes to drop the investigation, describing
it as specious and unfair. Kevin Davitt, a spokesman for Hynes,
rejected the request. ``Absolutely not,'' Davitt said. ``It goes
forward. Despite the mayor's best wishes.''
</P>
<P>
   The second event was the announcement on Tuesday by Cuomo, a
Democrat who is one of Mrs. Clinton's top unofficial advisers, that
HUD was taking over control of homeless service grants that had
been administered by the city. Cuomo said he acted in response to a
federal court ruling that found that City Hall had improperly
blocked an AIDS service organization from receiving funds.
</P>
<P>
   But as he made that announcement, Cuomo affirmed his support for
Mrs. Clinton in the Senate race, in a remark that some of Mrs.
Clinton's supporters described on Wednesday as troublesome, because
it allowed Giuliani to discredit Cuomo's criticism.
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo was unavailable to comment on Giuliani's statements, an
aide said on Wednesday. But Mrs. Clinton disputed any suggestion
that Cuomo had acted politically. ``To me, the judge in the case is
the one who made the point the mayor has engaged in retaliatory
action, and there has been a conscious decision on the part of the
mayor's office to take away funding from some groups for political
purposes,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
