<DOCNO> NYT19991222.0393 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7005 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKN-CELTICS-PARQUET-2     12-22 1270
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-PARQUET-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER BOSTON SPORTS ICON FALLS TO PROGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A security guard had been on watch since Tuesday, the
parquet being under a 24-hour watch. World-famous, you know, just
as the Celtics' name if not the Celtics' team these days.
</P>
<P>
   The security guard was leaning against stacks of new parquet,
all crated so nicely and crisply, but his eyes were on the old
parquet only feet away . . . the dingy parquet, the precious
parquet, stacked as always, slivers and bolts protruding
haphazardly.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night was turning into the wee hours of Wednesday
morning. And now the parquet was being lifted for its final trip,
out onto the floor, the A sections (A-1, A-2, A-3) being laid first
far down on on the west end of the FleetCenter, and then the B
sections and the C sections and on and on, all 264 pieces of the
sacred parquet.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the pieces, 5 feet by 5 feet. Pieces of maple, say some.
Pieces of oak, say others.
</P>
<P>
   (Truth is not easy to come by when it comes to the parquet
floor. Legends abound. Tales expand.)
</P>
<P>
   But pieces of Boston sports history, say all.
</P>
<P>
   Forklifts grabbed sections and whooshed away, pieces of
cardboard sticking out from the slabs of parquet _ old cardboard,
mind you, very old cardboard _ protecting one piece from the one
atop of it. This was all happening in a back area of the
FleetCenter, a desolate back area. A visitor walked by and peeled
off a sliver of wood from the G-2 section of parquet _ the foul
line for the east end was stacked right next to it. Slivers were
easy to come by.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people get really psyched up about all this,'' said Steve
Shannon of Malden, who's been hauling the parquet around for 10 or
so years now. ``But I'm not one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   No sentiment? No emotion? ``Yeahhh . . . I guess there's a lot
of history involved and stuff but . . . I'm not going to stand out
there and get all emotional about it,'' said Shannon. ``It's just a
floor . . . that's all . . . a floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Forklifts were whistling about, horns honking, so the subtle
nuances of history were hard to discern. But, out on the arena
floor, were the men of the bull gang, the ones who touch the
parquet scores of times a year, the men most close to the wood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nah, I'm not going to miss it,'' said a gravelly voice, the
voice of Charlie Gravell of Everett, who was standing where
midcourt would be in an hour or so, more or less overseeing the
bull gang place the parquet into place for the last time. ``It's
about time they got a new floor here.''
</P>
<P>
   Gravell has been with the bull gang since 1958, like so many of
the others who started first as a part-timer and then moved up to
full-time duty. ``Forty-one years is a long time with the floor,''
Gravell conceded, and he is the senior parquet-handler.
</P>
<P>
   No tears shed for the last time? ``Not me.''
</P>
<P>
   None? ``We needed a new floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Anything you're going to miss about the parquet? ``Yeah . . .
it's easy to put down. The new one's going to be harder.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now, it was early Wednesday morning and any evidence the Bruins
had been on the ice a few hours earlier was gone. Pieces of common,
everyday wood had been laid over the ice and the parquet _ piece by
piece _ was placed over the wood. The job takes about two hours
more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never lost a piece,'' said Gravell, now 61. ``But some
pieces were broke . . . you know, people tried to steal it. The
only time I ever saw a piece break was during a high school
tournament . . . the piece broke right in the center, halfway up,
right during the game. We had to take it up and put a new piece
in.''
</P>
<P>
   The old myths that a sneaker could get lost in the holes in the
parquet are just that to Gravell _ myths. ``That's what they say,''
he said. ``But you're going to have a gap between the pieces anyway
. . . you can't put 'em tight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``.''Gravell added yet another voice to the revisionists who
swear this parquet floor is not the original parquet, but one that
was put in place during the early 1950s after the original had been
brought over from the Boston Arena, where the Celtics first played.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Bob) Cousy didn't like the other floor,'' said Gravell. The
parquet of the original floor was much thinner ``and about 8 feet
long,'' said Gravell. ``But Cousy didn't like it, so they took it
out and brought this one in.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins game had been over for some two hours. By now the
parquet had been laid out to the foul line extended on the east end
and Ed D'Onofrio was standing by a stack of parquet out near
midcourt. ``I'm the cardboard guy,'' said D'Onofrio.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, D'Ononfrio would whip away the protective piece of
elderly cardboard each time other bull gangers lugged away a piece
of elderly parquet. ``I've done everything,'' said D'Onofrio, also
of Everett, ``but since I'm the oldest one (63), I get to do
this.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More time passed. The parquet expanded. As men lugged a piece
from a forklift and put it in place, Al Fiore walked by with a long
screwdriver and aligned the bolts that fasten the board to its
adjoining piece.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty years I've been on this floor,'' said Fiore.
</P>
<P>
   Any tears about leaving it? ``Nahh . . . except it's going to
take double the work with the new floor.''
</P>
<P>
   No attachment at all? ``Well, if we were still in the old
building . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Where the parquet was as much Boston Garden as the second
balcony. But this is the FleetCenter and the security guard was
still guarding the last pieces of parquet as the hours turned more
wee. Staring at a floor for hours can be . . . well, boring so,
from time to time, Mark Petit-ma would bring a soft drink to the
guard, whose eyes never left the parquet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MAJOR MOMENTS IN PARQUET HISTORY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Cousy's free throws: Bob Cousy hits 30 of 32 free throws
while playing 66 minutes as the Celtics win their first postseason
series with a 111-105 victory over Syracuse in four overtimes March
21, 1953. Cousy also hit a 30-footer at the buzzer of the third OT
to tie it again at 99. &QL; 
 &QL; 
2. ``Havlicek stole the ball'': John Havlicek grabs Hal Greer's
inbounds pass intended for Chet Walker, enabling the Celtics to
defeat the Philadelphia 76ers, 110-109, in Game 7 of the Eastern
Division finals, April 15, 1965. &QL; 
 &QL; 
3. Selvy's missed shot: Lakers guard Frank Selvy fails to hit an
open 12-foot, baseline jumper at the end of regulation, and the
Celtics go on to win Game 7 in overtime, 110-107, for their fifth
NBA title, April 18, 1962. &QL; 
 &QL; 
4. Jordan's 63-point game: Michael Jordan dunks over Kevin McHale
for 2 of his playoff-record 63 points in Chicago's 135-131
double-overtime loss to the Celtics in Game 2 of their Eastern
Conference first-round series, April 20, 1986. &QL; 
 &QL; 
5. Tree bites man: In the midst of a bench-clearing fight in Game 3
of their first-round playoff series, April 24, 1983, Atlanta's Tree
Rollins bites Danny Ainge's finger. Rollins is fined $5,000 and
suspended for five games. &QL; 
 &QL; 
6. Lewis collapses: Reggie Lewis falls to the floor with 6:26 left
in the first quarter against Charlotte April 29, 1993. He returns
in the third quarter, but leaves again with 5:45 left in the third.
He dies three months later. &QL; 
 &QL; 
7. Bird switche: In a 98-95 victory over Houston in Game 1
of the NBA Finals May 5, 1981, Larry Bird hits one of his most
famous shots _ a flying follow of his own miss that he converts by
switching from his right hand to left hand in midair, with his
momentum carrying him out of bounds. &QL; 
 &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
