<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7009 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-GLORIOUS-GRINCH-TEX     12-22 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLORIOUS-GRINCH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW ``THE GRINCH'' GAVE CHRISTMAS TO ONE LITTLE BOY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is one ironclad, cannot-be-broken rule about Christmas in
my house:
</P>
<P>
   ``How the Grinch Stole Christmas!'' must be watched _ twice, if
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Frosty? Sure. The Scrooge? OK. Pick a version of it and get back
to me. ``A Christmas Story?'' Definitely. A football game? Dandy.
Knock yourself out;_ put on those thick comfy socks and a big ol'
comfy sweater, wrap the blanket around you (or, if you're fortunate
enough, you and your sweetie), top off the eggnog and kick back. I
understand.
</P>
<P>
   But I gots to have my Grinch. And poor little Max, with the
antlers tied to his head. And Cindy-Lou Who, asking ``Why Santy?
Why?'' And that moment when the Grinch realizes the errors of his
ways and hoists _ ``with the strength of 10 Grinches, plus two!'' _
the sleigh holding all the Whos' presents atop his shoulders and
his heart grows three times and he rides pell-mell down the side of
Mount Crumpit and goes from cad to cool daddy.
</P>
<P>
   Ladies and gentlemen, boys and girls, THIS is Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   I accept no substitutes.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps this is because the TV adaptation of the classic 1957
Dr. Seuss book debuted in 1966, when I was 4. I saw it that first
year, or the next, and immediately fell in love _ not because I
loved Dr. Seuss (well, what child didn't?), but because it was a
rollicking good tale, the songs were fun and great to sing along
to. How can one resist a phrase like ``seasick crocodile,'' after
all? And at the end, everybody is happy and getting presents and
eating roast beast, which sounded good to a chubby little carnivore
like myself.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the Grinch came to represent Christmas to me _
not as much as getting to see the grandparents or acquiring more
free swag from the parents, naturally, but certainly more than
anything else on the tube. Living in Michigan, I just felt sorry
for those poor souls I saw shivering through Christmas parades. As
for football, well, it was great, but by the time the game was on I
was stuffed and sleepy and didn't much care who won or lost.
</P>
<P>
   So it was the Grinch who rocked my yuletide world. Thinking back
on it now, I can see myself sitting on our couch in front of the
TV, Dad in his La-Z-Boy to my right, Mom next to me. The tree is
set up, the lights glowing and flickering, and outside the big
front window there is snow swirling and a silent tableau of winter,
our lawn a smooth blue-white blanket.
</P>
<P>
   My dog, Finnegan, a St. Bernard as sweet as he is large and
prone to drooling on every available surface, is sitting on the
floor, having positioned himself so that his head and ears are
within easy reach for scratching. I no doubt have just come in from
a day of sledding or skating or both, and I am perfectly warm and
comfortable and secure.
</P>
<P>
   And what, plopped down in this Hallmark scene, am I watching?
Disgust, cunning, thievery and deceit on a grand scale and,
finally, redemption. ``Grinch'' is an uplifting tale, no question,
but perhaps the most interesting part of it is that we don't know
why this guy is so angry at the Whos, why he's up there on that
mountain.
</P>
<P>
   Was it a broken love affair? Being cast out of the societal unit
for general unpleasantness and bad teeth? Was he exiled by the Mob?
What?
</P>
<P>
   People compare the Grinch with Scrooge, and that's fair _ but
also beside the point. With Scrooge, the back story (how he came to
be such a, well, such a Grinch) IS the story: We can understand why
he has turned his back on everyone and turned inward.
</P>
<P>
   The Grinch has no back story; he's a man without a country or a
life or a history. Oh, we know he hates Christmas and the noise the
Whos make, and he isn't a big fan of roast beast, but that's
precious little to go on. What's his deal?
</P>
<P>
   Ask a little boy that, and you've created a monster. I thought
up all sorts of scenarios for the Grinch's lonely exile on the top
of the mountain and always wondered how he could stay warm up there
and where he got food. If things got really tight, would he eat
Max? And for that matter, why was Max _ a dog who clearly loved
Christmas _ up there with him? Had Max been kidnapped?
</P>
<P>
   There were no answers, which was at least part of the reason I
loved the show so much. ``The Grinch'' didn't declare; it suggested
and insinuated, which is always more fun. At the same time, what
most appealed was the knowledge that love would triumph over hate
and everyone would get their presents and the Grinch might someday
move down off that mountain and everyone would be friends, which
was important to me when I was 7 or 8.
</P>
<P>
   This was a good thing to believe at that age, and I believed it
_ believed it in the face of all the problems coming out of
Detroit, in the face of the body counts from Vietnam, in the face
of the riots and confrontations constantly on television. The
world, it seemed to me in 1968 and '69 and '70, had gone mad, or
maybe was always mad (I had nothing to compare the present with,
after all) and here, for one half-hour each year, was love
triumphing over hate.
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't have articulated this back then, but I knew it in my
bones. A bad man becomes good, and everyone is happy. Cool!
</P>
<P>
   It was a good reminder of the innate goodness of people and the
season. I wanted my presents, don't get me wrong, but the gentle
message would always stick with me and help me remember that
friends and relatives really do matter.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't realize until years later what an amazing collaboration
``Grinch'' was: The Dr. Seuss book, which came out in 1957, told
the tale well enough, but it was the collaboration of Ted Geisel
and master animator Chuck Jones (and the music of Eugene Poddany,
and Boris Karloff's narration, and all the rest) that made it what
it was: Jones made the Grinch green and his eyes a sickly yellow
and the two, together, fleshed the story out. Karloff's narration
is tale-telling at its finest. The whole package works as a
morality tale and a rollicking good cartoon and a Christmas fable.
</P>
<P>
   I wouldn't understand all this for years, but when I did it made
viewing ``The Grinch'' even more of a once-a-year treat.
</P>
<P>
   It became a talisman of sorts, an unchanging sweetness that
called to mind what was a very safe, happy childhood indeed. Which
is perhaps why I never went in for Grinch coffee mugs and the rest.
The Grinch is not mine, of course, but the story and the experience
of watching the show are part of my celebration of the season and
part of the reason that even during my most obnoxious and cynical
teen-age years I always watched. And always will. Christmas Day is
within our grasp, as long as we have hands to clasp. Amen to that.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
