u s BC-BBN-BRAVES-PADRES23-C     12-22 0416
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-PADRES23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves acquire leadoff hitter
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ On a distracting day, the Atlanta Braves quietly
morphed into something new Wednesday. Again.
</P>
<P>
   In a major deal that alters the club's offensive profile, the
Braves addressed their clearest deficiency, acquiring from San
Diego second baseman and leadoff hitter Quilvio Veras and
outfielder Reggie Sanders. The deal, rumored for weeks, was
expanded to include Wally Joyner, an Atlanta native who serves as
insurance against the cancer recovery of first baseman Andres
Galarraga.
</P>
<P>
   The cost _ second baseman Bret Boone, lifetime Brave Ryan Klesko
and pitching prospect Jason Shiell _ wasn't cheap. But the club,
diminished at the top of the order by losing free-agent outfielder
Gerald Williams, added a prototypical leadoff hitter in Veras.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt it was essential that we improve the upper part of our
lineup,'' general manager John Schuerholz said, ``and with the
acquisition of Sanders and Veras, who between them stole 66 bases
and scored a lot of runs (187) ... it provides us with a much
better opportunity to create and produce runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta saved money, sending nearly $15 million in payroll
obligation to San Diego for just over $10 million (Sanders at $3.7
million, Joyner at $3.375 million and Veras worth an approximate $3
million through arbitration). The finances fueled speculation that
Klesko, due nearly $11 million the next two seasons, might not last
long as a Padre.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't know if it's one of these deals where you get traded
and the next thing you know, the next day you're traded again to
another team,'' said Klesko, who hit .297 with 21 homers and 80
RBIs last season.
</P>
<P>
   Veras, who missed 30 games due in part to leg trouble last
season, had a .377 on-base percentage, 42 points higher than
Williams. Boone, an All-Star two years ago, lasted just one year in
Atlanta (.252, career-high 112 strikeouts), though his desire to
leave the club was exaggerated in the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't ask for the trade,'' he said. ``I ended up not asking
for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves will have one of the game's tightest outfields _
Sanders in left, Andruw Jones in center and Brian Jordan in right.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ought to be able to cover two or three sections of foul
territory in left field and two or three sections in right field,''
Schuerholz said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
