<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7013 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUSH-FOREIGN-POLICY-1     12-22 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-FOREIGN-POLICY-1000(TRIMS)-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOV. BUSH TURNS INCREASINGLY TO CADRE OF EXPERTS FOR FOREIGN POLICY
ADVICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush of Texas is counting on a
small group of conservative experts steeped in the intricacies of
arms control, military budgets and geopolitical security to counsel
him on a subject that has caused him the most trouble in his
presidential campaign: foreign affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The task of helping Bush translate his core principles for
America's role in the world into concrete policies lies largely in
the hands of eight hawkish advisers with broad experience under
President Ronald Reagan or Bush's father, President George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Like Reagan when he ran for president, Gov. Bush has no broad
foreign policy experience. But unlike Reagan, who had a long
history of preaching against communism, Bush has no similar guiding
philosophy. As a result, his foreign policy stumbles, like flubbing
a pop quiz on world leaders, have only amplified the role his
advisers play.
</P>
<P>
   After months of briefings and informal discussions, the
advisers' influence over Bush has become more evident with every
speech, news conference and debate. Perhaps even more than the
other candidates, it is not unusual to hear the advisers' words
coming out of Bush's mouth.
</P>
<P>
   This kitchen cabinet is a tight-knit, strong-willed group led by
Condoleezza Rice, a Russia specialist in President Bush's National
Security Council, and Paul D. Wolfowitz, a senior Pentagon official
in the Bush administration and former ambassador to Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also consults with two unofficial senior advisers, Richard
B. Cheney, President Bush's secretary of defense, and George P.
Shultz, Reagan's secretary of state. Conspicuously absent is the
elder Bush, who has not sought a foreign policy role, largely to
give his son a degree of independence, aides said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the advisers have known each other for more than a
decade, forging close ties as Cold Warriors combatting the Soviet
Union, as mediators helping to reunify Germany, or as Pentagon
strategists leading the allied victory over Iraq in the 1991
Persian Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   Advisers bristle at the notion that they are tutoring a novice.
They argue that Bush surprised them by articulating a set of broad
foreign policy principles and priorities _ from missile defenses to
free trade to what he calls The Big Ones: Russia, China and India
_that need refining, not revamping.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this drill has involved is fleshing out the sense he has
about things, rather than introducing things he didn't know
anything about,'' said Dov S. Zakheim, a former deputy under
secretary of defense for Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush's words have a familiar ring, at times echoing his
advisers' public pronouncements as well as their private counsel
given in hours of free-wheeling, rapid-fire discussions in
conference calls and in meetings at the governor's mansion here
over the last year. Advisers say he has yet to overrule them on any
major issue.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In August, for example, Ms. Rice, the governor's top foreign
policy adviser, described to The National Journal how a future Bush
administration would curtail the Clinton administration's penchant
for dispatching troops on far-flung humanitarian or peacekeeping
missions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would be more selective in our military involvements,'' she
said. ``One downside of having this extraordinary power, relative
to the rest of the world, is that you can easily become
overextended. That risks erosion of domestic support for America's
global role and international resentment of what many see as an
arrogant and reckless power.''
</P>
<P>
   Six weeks later, in Bush's defense policy speech on Sept. 23, he
issued a similar warning: ``We must be selective in the use of our
military, precisely because America has other great
responsibilities that cannot be slighted or compromised.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Several advisers, including Richard Perle, an assistant
secretary of defense under Reagan, have advocated that the United
States withdraw from the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty if
Russia refuses to negotiate changes that would allow both countries
to field national systems to protect against limited long-range
missile attacks. The governor heartily embraced that position.
</P>
<P>
   Bush rarely has to choose between stark divisions in his
advisers. Last spring, his aides split over whether the United
States should support NATO military action to protect Kosovar
Albanians. Zakheim publicly opposed it. Wolfowitz supported it.
Bush reluctantly backed President Clinton's decision to intervene,
persuaded that broader European interests were at stake.
</P>
<P>
   His aides insist that they are often reinforcing and fine-tuning
Bush's gut instincts, making it difficult to single out any one
adviser's influence. ``It's like making sausage,'' Ms. Rice said in
an interview at Bush campaign headquarters here. ``We get in there,
slog through together, and ideas emerge.''
</P>
<P>
   The foreign policy team members, who call themselves the
Vulcans, after a statue of the Roman god of fire and metalworking
in Birmingham, Ala., Ms. Rice's hometown, sprang from a meeting in
August 1998 that President Bush set up at his summer residence in
Kennebunkport, Maine, between his son and Ms. Rice.
</P>
<P>
   Within a few months, Ms. Rice, who stepped down in June as
provost of Stanford University, agreed to head the governor's
foreign policy team. Together with Wolfowitz, she chose a seasoned
cadre of experts who, like Bush, champion internationalism, voice a
tougher security approach to dealing with China and Russia, and
promise an overhaul of Pentagon spending and strategy.
</P>
<P>
   But surprisingly for a candidate who preaches the virtues of the
global marketplace, Bush's foreign policy team has only one expert
in international economics _ Robert B. Zoellick, an undersecretary
of state in the Bush administration _ and no specialists in Africa
or Latin America. The campaign has a separate team of economic
aides, with whom Ms. Rice and Zoellick coordinate.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's a weakness in the team, it's that it's heavy on
security issues,'' acknowledged Ms. Rice, who said she was seeking
to diversify the group.
</P>
<P>
   In their dealings with Bush, the advisers rely on a familiar
working model. ``This operation runs a little bit like we'd run the
N.S.C., with the daily briefing he gets, making sure there's press
guidance, and worrying about speeches where your policy gets
honed,'' said Ms. Rice, who studied international relations at the
University of Denver under Josef Korbel, the father of Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in some ways, the most important thing in a campaign is to
try to keep focused on the fact that there are a lot of audiences
reading what you're saying, including foreign audiences, foreign
governments,'' Ms. Rice said.
</P>
<P>
   To keep that message sharp, the team has a routine. At nine
o'clock every Monday morning, the advisers hook up by phone from
across the country _ sometimes from overseas _ to swap diplomatic
gossip, dissect world events and polish Bush's approach to
international affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Each Sunday evening, Ms. Rice, Wolfowitz, Bush and a few other
top aides here hold a conference call to review global hotspots and
talk about issues that have caught the governor's eye. ``It's a
little bit more relaxed opportunity to discuss foreign policy, and
a chance for him to talk directly to us,'' said Ms. Rice, who
shuttles between here and Stanford, where she is a senior fellow at
the Hoover Institution.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rice periodically reaches outside the foreign policy brain
trust for insights. Gen. Colin L. Powell, the former chairman of
the Joint Chiefs of Staff, has met with Bush and critiqued his
defense policy speech.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Paul Coverdell, a Georgia Republican on the Foreign
Relations Committee who is Bush's point man in the Senate, briefed
the governor's top aides on Senate Republicans' strategy to oppose
a global treaty banning underground nuclear testing. The Senate
rejected the pact in October. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The musings of Bush's advisers are also important because they
give a glimpse into the people who will undoubtedly fill the top
ranks of the Pentagon, State Department and National Security
Council if he is elected.
</P>
<P>
   When tensions in Asia ran high last summer over the rejection by
Taiwan's president, Lee Teng-hui, of the longstanding ``one China''
formula, Richard L. Armitage, a senior Pentagon official in the
Reagan administration, caused a stir in Australia when he told The
Australian Financial Review that Australia ``must stand ready to
give military support to the U.S. if Washington goes to war with
China'' over Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Armitage emphasized that Washington did not want to go to war
with China, and that there was a low risk of conflict. But if a
misjudgment triggered fighting, he said the United States would
expect Australia to help with ``the dirty, hard and dangerous
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Steven J. Hadley, a Pentagon arms control expert in the Bush
administration, has spoken eloquently on linking changes in the
Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty to reductions in the U.S. and Russian
nuclear stockpiles, bringing them well below the levels allowed
under the Start II treaty.
</P>
<P>
   In the Persian Gulf, Wolfowitz has not ruled out using U.S.
troops to support Iraqi insurgents in toppling Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will take American forces to create a protected area in
which opposition forces can organize and to which units from
Saddam's army can defect,'' Wolfowitz wrote in The New Republic in
December 1998. ``This policy is risky. But it is less risky than
the present course, which is leading us to the day that we are
obliged to face Saddam ourselves, when he is armed with weapons of
unparalleled destructiveness.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike his father or Clinton, Bush is not likely to immerse
himself in the arcana of policy, leaving more running room for his
advisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not a policy wonk and he never will be,'' Perle said.
``But he's going to convey a sense of who he is and how he'd
exercise authority.''
</P>
</TEXT>
