<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7020 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FILM-PALTROW-FEATURE-     12-22 1552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-PALTROW-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TALENTED MS. PALTROW
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: EMBARGOED until Friday, Dec. 24) 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It just doesn't seem like awards season without Gwyneth
Paltrow's name being mentioned everywhere. But after the whirlwind
year that culminated last March when she won the best actress Oscar
for ``Shakespeare in Love,'' the 27-year-old superstar is more than
happy to be out of the spotlight for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, I've only felt sort of the traumatic part of it,''
says the lithe, articulate actress, looking atypically dour with
her trademark golden hair dyed brunet. ``I haven't felt any of the
lightness and joy that everybody expects that I would be feeling,
or felt at some point.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, it's just so nerve-wracking,'' adds Paltrow,
whose weepy acceptance speeches earlier this year sometimes looked
more like a nervous breakdown. ``It goes on for months, and it's so
exhausting and draining. I mean, you think, `Is this some
popularity contest?' You just think about yourself in all these
different ways, what you're wearing ... and everybody is focusing
on you.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason why the focus is less intense this time
around is that although Paltrow's latest movie, ``The Talented Mr.
Ripley,'' is receiving glowing reviews and a good share of
preliminary nominations, her work in it is so subtly expert that,
at least according to her co- star, its brilliance is easily
overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's her best work, actually,'' says longtime pal Matt
Damon, who, like others associated with ``Ripley,'' received a
Golden Globe nomination this week. ``I hope it's noticed. I mean,
`Shakespeare in Love' was an incredible performance, but because
she played so many different characters, it attracted a lot of
attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this is so subtle, and it's such a wonderfully dark
journey that her character goes on,'' Damon continues. ``She looks
about a thousand years older at the end of the movie than at the
beginning. And all without any `Look at me, look at me'; just very
precise, beautiful work.''
</P>
<P>
   In a role expanded by screenwriter-director Anthony Minghella
(``The English Patient'') from Patricia Highsmith's source novel,
Paltrow plays Marge Sherwood, an aristocratic (of course) young
American trying to become a writer in 1950s Italy. She's happily
living La Dolce Vita with Dickie Greenleaf (Jude Law), the
handsome, charming and totally self-absorbed heir to a shipping
fortune. When Dickie's disgusted father sends the slippery Tom
Ripley (Damon) to Europe in hope of retrieving his hedonistic son,
the underprivileged Ripley falls under Dickie's seductive spell,
too.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ripley and Marge become good friends, she grows
suspicious of him after Dickie suddenly ditches both of them. By
the time she's tracked Ripley across the peninsula, she's convinced
of the worst.
</P>
<P>
   Although ``Talented Mr. Ripley'' serves up more prestige power
than just about any other film this season (Minghella's ``Patient''
won loads of Oscars, including best picture, and Cate Blanchett,
another of last year's best actress nominees, is also in the cast),
its lying, murdering protagonist and bisexual undercurrents aren't
the usual elements of A-list Hollywood productions. But that's what
intrigued the actress, who made the film last year before the
awards madness hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was so different,'' Paltrow says. ``It had
qualities of a great, beautiful, epic Hollywood movie while being
totally subversive and un-Hollywood at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   The project also boasted the substantial added attraction of a
six- month shoot in Rome, Naples, Palermo, the pristine isle of
Ischia, Venice _ basically, everywhere you'd want to spend a lot of
time in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   But the faraway production was not a happy experience for the
normally travel-happy Paltrow. Her father, TV show producer and
director Bruce Paltrow, was ill during much of the period, and a
beloved grandfather was close to death. Although the cast and crew
did everything in their power to make Paltrow feel better, she
simply couldn't take her mind off of the troubles back home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The actual work was cathartic,'' she explains. ``But you
didn't get to do it for very many minutes during the day. There was
a lot of sitting around, and that part was very hard for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all got homesick,'' she quickly adds, trying to avoid
sounding self-pitying. ``Everybody has this image of going to Italy
for six months being so great. But meanwhile, that's a long time to
be away from the people you love. You're mostly in a hotel room,
having room service and going, `This is my life?' It's just not
what people think.''
</P>
<P>
   The two movies Paltrow's made since ``Ripley'' were a little
easier to handle. For one thing, her father recovered substantially
enough to direct one of them, ``Duets,'' a romantic comedy set in a
karaoke bar.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was just the opposite'' of feeling isolated in Europe,
Paltrow says. ``He spoiled me so much! It was great.''
</P>
<P>
   It also felt good to make the romantic drama ``Bounce'' with
former boyfriend Ben Affleck. ``We had a great time doing it,'' she
says. ``We are still great friends in the real sense of the word.''
</P>
<P>
   But even though it was wonderful to reach out and have others
there after a year of tumultuous highs and lows, Paltrow realized
that what she really needed to do was work on herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, for a long time, `Oh, if I get to this level I'll
be happy' or `If I earn this amount of money I'll be happy' or `If
I could just buy that, I'll be happy,''' she reveals. ``What I've
come to realize is _ and I think that I am successful to have
learned this lesson _ that nothing I can buy, no boy, no painting,
no anything fulfills you. It's all within you, and people are
looking in the wrong direction.''
</P>
<P>
   For the past year, Paltrow has seriously pursued yoga and
meditation, searching for inner peace while trying to detach
herself from worldly concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We forget that we are spirits, not just heads that walk around
on these bodies,'' she observes. ``Once you realize that you're
just humble and little, you feel a lot of power.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Paltrow has basically learned the essence of most
fables, religions and philosophies here. But actually feeling it,
this most accomplished of young actresses acknowledges, is a
different thing from reading or hearing about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely something you have to discover yourself,'' she
says. ``Like with any real lesson in life, nobody can tell you
anything. You've got to experience it, you've got to go through it,
you've got to understand it for yourself. That's how you learn, by
making big mistakes and saying, `I should've listened to my
parents.'''
</P>
<P>
   If she had listened to her parents, Paltrow might be a lawyer
now. Though her dad oversaw such acclaimed shows as ``St.
Elsewhere'' and ``The White Shadow,'' and her mother, Blythe
Danner, has long been a respected stage and screen actress, they
weren't necessarily thrilled with their daughter's decision to
pursue show business.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted me to finish college,'' she recalls. ``But after
Daddy saw a dress rehearsal of a play I was doing, he came
backstage, and he was kind of misty-eyed _ we have a crying problem
in my family _ and he said, `Y'know, I don't think you should go
back to college.'''
</P>
<P>
   How many kids hear those golden words? And Dad was right.
Paltrow made an indelible impression in her first adult film role
as a hard-hearted grifter in ``Flesh and Bone.'' She soon
established herself as an indie film princess (James Ivory's
``Jefferson in Paris,'' Paul Thomas Anderson's ``Hard Eight''), a
deft mimic of British accents (``Emma,'' ``Sliding Doors,''
``Shakespeare in Love'') and a reliable Hollywood star (``Seven,''
``A Perfect Murder'').
</P>
<P>
   In the process, she also became a reluctant celebrity. Her
romance with Brad Pitt was a media circus of major proportions, but
even at its most intrusive, she handled the press with
characteristic poise and humor.
</P>
<P>
   But that, understandably, has gotten more than tiresome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wish that I could find a way to be less out there,''
Paltrow says. ``But it's hard. You do a film, and the studio wants
you to support the movie, do magazine covers and press, and that
just puts you out there more.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I would think, at a certain point, the American public
just can't take any more,'' she adds with a chuckle. ``You would
hope, anyway. You would hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the media tires of Gwyneth-watching or not, perhaps the
most important lesson Paltrow has learned from her year of
astounding highs, shattering lows and quiet contemplation is
something that she really already knew: that she's in the movie
game because she loves it. And that she can only play it on her own
terms, not according to the demands of stardom or commerce _ or
even awards considerations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't even think about that,'' she admits. ``I just want to
do what I want to do, and I want to do things that I respond to. If
I let outside influences or pressure in terms of what other
people's expectations are of me affect my choices, then I'm not an
artist anymore. Then I'm a businesswoman, and that's not who I
am.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
