<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7021 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-ROCKER-MAIN23-COX     12-22 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROCKER-MAIN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Even Braves offended by Rocker rant
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ John Rocker went to bed Tuesday night a brash, young
baseball star. He awoke Wednesday morning a pariah.
</P>
<P>
   In a scathing published report that sent shockwaves through
baseball, Rocker lashed out at minorities, questioned the Atlanta
Braves' competitiveness and despaired of riding a New York subway
system sitting ``...next to some queer with AIDS, right next to
some dude who just got of jail for the fourth time. ...''
</P>
<P>
   And he was just warming up. In the new issue of Sports
Illustrated, Rocker went on to disparage women, Asians, Russians
and even Hispanics, a remarkable comment given that both his
catchers with the Braves, Javy Lopez and Eddie Perez, are Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   If Rocker's on-field tirades against New York fans were ever
truly entertaining, they aren't anymore. He faces fines or
suspension from Major League Baseball, though both the
commissioner's office as well as the Braves put off any punitive
response until Rocker has a chance to account for his remarks.
``While John admitted having said these things,'' Braves general
manager John Schuerholz said, ``he told me (Wednesday) that over
the course of a 7 1/2-hour conversation with this writer (SI's Jeff
Pearlman) in the presence of his girlfriend, that these comments
weren't offered _ and again, I'm not offering a defense for John
Rocker; I'm just saying what he said to me _ in the vein or in the
spirit that they appeared in this article.''
</P>
<P>
   Club owner Ted Turner, out of town on a holiday vacation, had no
immediate response, nor did manager Bobby Cox, who has enjoyed
uncommon tranquility during his current 10-year stint in the Braves
dugout. But Rocker, who was able to inflame the passions of New
York fans in both Shea Stadium and Yankee Stadium, this time has
offended a legion of fans, his teammates and the game itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can issue all the apologies you want,'' pitcher Tom
Glavine said, ``but you're still going to have to face some angry
people, particularly the players, the African-American guys, Latin
guys, all the people he offended, and that by no means excludes the
rest of us, either. I could not stand any further from what he
said.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker, who was in Orlando, Fla., participating in a charity
softball game for Nicaragua relief, was not initially available for
comment. But his Texas-based agent, Randal Hendricks, released a
statement in which Rocker explained that what had begun as another
rant against New York grew in focus and rage the longer he went.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone makes mistakes and I hope everyone can put this aside
and begin with a fresh start in the 2000 season,'' Rocker's
statement read. ``I am contrite.''
</P>
<P>
   That may be more difficult than he anticipates. Some of the
strongest response came from within Rocker's team.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what I read, there was enough to make anybody angry,
especially your teammates and members of management,'' said right
fielder Brian Jordan, who suggested the Braves trade Rocker.
``That's pretty bad.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in a society now where people are not afraid of the
ramifications of what they say and what they do,'' Glavine added.
``You can say and do whatever you want and just go ahead and issue
an apology and everything's OK.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it's not. It's not right. You can read all the apologies
you want but this will carry a whole lot more weight in our
clubhouse than what it will carry anywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker, who just completed his first full year in the majors,
emerged from being just another kid with a fastball last season
into one of the game's most wicked closers, reaching speeds of 97
mph while striking out 104 batters in 72 1/3 innings. His 38 saves
were the second most by a reliever in Braves history and his
reputation only grew in the postseason, when he recorded a win and
two saves and allowed just five hits and no earned runs over 13
October innings.
</P>
<P>
   But his tirades against New York fans, punctuated by spitting
and obscene gestures, drew as much attention. The Braves, including
Cox, cautioned Rocker to tone down his act but he declined, and in
this week's article he denied Cox or anyone ever addressed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very disappointing and upsetting,'' said pitching coach
Leo Mazzone. ``Baseball is a very humbling game and the kid's going
to end up being humbled physically and mentally or be out of the
game. And from somebody with only one full season? I mean, look in
the clubhouse and see the class of the Glavines and the Smoltzes
and the Madduxes.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Rocker's harshest targets was the Braves themselves.
Ridiculing the club's quiet, buttoned-down image, he took issue
with the stoicism that Glavine, John Smoltz and Greg Maddux have
perpetuated.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the fiery guys _ we get annoyed at their stoicism,''
Rocker is quoted as saying. ``There needs to be more atmosphere in
our clubhouse. I don't mean loud music and hooting and hollering.
But I don't think having the atmosphere of a doctor's office
helps.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
