<SLUG> BC-DOCTOR-SUSPENDED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLEGED NEGLIGENCE RESULTS IN DOCTOR'S SUSPENSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Massachusetts officials have summarily suspended a
doctor's license to practice because of repeated instances of
alleged negligent care _ the first time in years that the state has
cited medical malpractice in taking such an emergency action.
</P>
<P>
   The Board of Registration in Medicine has charged 61-year-old
Dr. Joseph P. Whalen of Concord with missing obvious heart attacks
in two patients and misdiagnosing prostate and colon cancer in two
others. One of the four patients, a 43-year-old man, died.
</P>
<P>
   Whalen, a 1965 Boston University Medical School graduate, is a
former Harvard Community Health Plan staff member now employed as a
prison doctor at Nashua Street Jail and other state and county
correctional facilities. Neither he nor his attorney could be
reached.
</P>
<P>
   The medical board has previously used its summary suspension
powers against physicians accused of sexually abusing patients or
selling drugs, or those who are clearly impaired by alcohol or drug
abuse, said Nancy Achin Sullivan, the board's executive director.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is significant,'' Sullivan said of the action against
Whalen. To suspend a license, the seven-member board must find that
the public safety, health, or welfare would be endangered by
allowing the doctor to practice pending sometimes-lengthy
disciplinary proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to ``a pattern of substandard practice between 1990
and 1996,'' the board charged Whalen with lying on his 1997 license
renewal application when he answered ``no'' to a question on
whether he had been subject to disciplinary actions in the previous
two years.
</P>
<P>
   The board said that in one case involving a 75-year-old diabetic
man, Whalen allegedly failed to diagnose a heart attack over a
12-day period, despite repeated abnormal electrocardiograms that
documented the ailment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, even to a layman, this patient was in the midst of an
acute cardiac event,'' the board's expert consultant on the case,
Dr. Henry Maltz, a Harvard Vanguard Medical Associates doctor from
Wellesley, wrote in a letter to the licensure panel.
</P>
<P>
   In another case, a 43-year-old male patient at a Harvard
Community Health Plan in Chelmsford died from widely spread colon
cancer after Whalen allegedly failed to diagnose the disease.
</P>
<P>
   The colon cancer patient had been seeing Whalen for more than a
year, complaining of rectal bleeding, before the malignancy was
finally diagnosed in June, 1991. Whalen never ordered appropriate
tests for colon cancer and assured the patient ``that he had
nothing wrong with him aside from hemorrhoids,'' according to
medical board documents.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, Whalen's alleged error was compounded by another
physician, who thought the patient's fatigue was caused by anemia
and prescribed iron supplements rather than investigate the cause
of the bleeding.
</P>
<P>
   The second physician was not named in documents on Whalen's
case, and board officials could not say whether that doctor also
worked at Harvard Community Health Plan. By law the board may not
comment on complaints or investigations that are pending.
</P>
<P>
   After that episode, Whalen continued to work at the Harvard
Plan's Chelmsford center until the spring of 1997, when the health
plan suspended his clinical privileges following his alleged
misdiagnosis of the diabetic patient's heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the board in May, 1997, Whalen admitted fault in
failing to take adequate steps to evaluate the patient's abnormal
electrocardiogram and said he resigned ``because of my chagrin and
dismay over my handling of this case.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he told the board that the heart attack case was ``an
isolated incident'' and said he had worked at the Harvard Plan
since 1989 ``without incident,'' failing to mention the 1990 colon
cancer misdiagnosis or another 1994 misdiagnosis of a severe heart
problem.
</P>
<P>
   The board also listed 15 other complaints against Whalen by
Harvard Plan patients, including another alleging cancer
misdiagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   The 1994 case involved a 63-year-old woman who came to the
Harvard Plan's Peabody center, moaning and complaining of back
pain. A nurse noted her skin had ``a grayish pallor'' and asked
Whalen to look at the woman's electrocardiogram results, according
to board documents.
</P>
<P>
   Maltz, the expert consultant, told the board earlier this month
that the woman's EKG showed she was having a heart attack. ``This
is NOT a subtle finding,'' Maltz wrote. ``I believe that an average
third-year medical student could have properly interpreted this
EKG.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Whalen diagnosed a chronic kidney problem and sent her
home, according to the investigation. Three days later she was
rushed to Salem Hospital, where doctors diagnosed the heart attack,
heart failure, and an electrical problem called total heart block,
which required emergency surgery for insertion of a pacemaker. She
also suffered a minor stroke. She subsequently filed a malpractice
suit against Whalen.
</P>
<P>
   In a fourth case, a 57-year-old man had an abnormal blood test
possibly signalling prostate cancer, but the board's investigation
found that Whalen attributed the result to nonmalignant prostate
enlargement.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-six months later, a repeat blood test showed an even
higher abnormal result. A urologist then performed a biopsy showing
prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   In a complaint to the state board, the prostate cancer patient
stated ``that he was very, very angry and distraught, and that his
chances for a cure. . . may have been extremely compromised,'' a
board investigator wrote. The patient has filed a malpractice suit.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, Whalen told the board that the abnormal blood test
came back late. ``There is no question that there were problems at
that time with reporting of lab results,'' Whalen told the board.
``I could have kept a log of patients who had pending lab results,
but the volume was too great.''
</P>
<P>
   Whalen is entitled to a hearing on the board's action within
seven days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
