<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7023 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-MIDEASTTALKS-1STLD-WR     12-22 1163
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIDEAST NEGOTIATORS, ON PALESTINIAN SOIL, BREAK IMPASSE
</HEADLINE>
 TALKS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT  (Eds: SUBS 6th graf, `It was ...,' to correct name of Arafat's
spokesman; subs 3rd graf in optional material, `While the ...,' to
the end, to expand on Palestianian concerns over Israeli-Syrian
talks, add details; No pickup.) 
(nk) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RAMALLAH, West Bank _ Despite speculation that the resumption of
Israeli-Syrian talks would derail the Palestinian peace track,
significant progress appeared to have been made early Wednesday
morning in an intimate meeting here overnight between Prime
Minister Ehud Barak and the Palestinian leader, Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time that an Israeli prime minister had
ventured into a Palestinian-controlled city for a peace meeting,
which in itself broke a barrier in the relationship. And the
setting was very casual: Barak and Arafat met in the elegant home
of the Palestinian leader's second-in-command, Mahmoud Abbas,
better known as Abu Mazen, his revolutionary name.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the villa, the two leaders talked for three hours, from
late Tuesday until early Wednesday, gathered with associates around
a banquet of Arabic salads and meat dishes. The security, both
Israeli and Palestinian, was tight, but the meeting and its
location had been kept secret and there were no disruptions.
</P>
<P>
   After the meeting, both sides said that two deadlocked issues
that have bedeviled progress were essentially resolved. An Israeli
transfer of 5 percent of the West Bank, which has been delayed for
five weeks, is now likely to take place within a week, both sides
said. And the Israelis are also expected to release more prisoners
as a gesture for Ramadan, the Islamic holy month, which ends early
next month.
</P>
<P>
   The details were left to negotiators who did not attend the
talks, and Saeb Erekat, a senior Palestinian negotiator, had left
an early evening session in Jerusalem declaring that not a single
issue had been resolved.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear whether Erekat was sincerely downbeat or adopting
a tough posture. His stance contrasted with the comments from two
senior Palestinians who attended the late-night meeting. Exuding
confidence, one of them, Nabil Abu Rudeineh, a spokesman for
Arafat, said early Wednesday that the Palestinians would ``witness
results in the very near future.''
</P>
<P>
   Another senior Palestinian had suggested that the Palestinians,
who had held up the land transfer because its is largely
unpopulated desert, were persuaded to accept the original offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ah, we still have two other redeployments,'' the official
said, referring to land transfers, the first scheduled for January.
The official suggested that the Palestinians had been given
assurances that more populated territory would be included in the
next Israeli withdrawals from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides reported that the atmosphere at the late-night
meeting was good and open, and that they would now accelerate
talks, including more face-to-face sessions between the two
leaders, in preparation for a possible meeting in the United States
in February.
</P>
<P>
   The talks ``renewed the trust and cooperation between the two
sides,'' Foreign Minister David Levy said on Israel radio, adding
that the transfer of land was imminent.
</P>
<P>
   During the talks, Arafat was accompanied not only by Abu Mazen
but also by Abu Ala, the speaker of the Palestinian Legislative
Council. Abu Ala (also a revolutionary name) was senior negotiator
of the Oslo peace accord, but is technically no longer a
negotiator.
</P>
<P>
   But with his calm, businesslike manner, he, as one Palestinian
analyst said, is ``the man who has the keys in his hands when
things get stuck.''
</P>
<P>
   Abu Ala reportedly met more than a dozen times with former Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Barak was joined by Levy and Danny Yatom, his security adviser,
both of whom accompanied him to Washington last week.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the meeting, Barak gave Arafat a 40-minute
briefing on his meetings in Washington with the Syrian foreign
minister, Farouk al-Sharaa.
</P>
<P>
   While the Israelis and Syrians were meeting in Washington, the
Palestinians publicly expressed support for the idea that another
peace front had been re-opened. But they privately voiced concern
that their negotiations would suffer, especially because the
Palestinians and Syrians, with bad blood between them, are unlikely
to work as allies against Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians said they feared Barak would adopt a firmer
line on territorial concessions in the West Bank because he is
considered likely to return the Golan Heights to Syria; the Israeli
public, it was predicted, could not swallow too much at once. The
Israelis also worried that Barak would not have time to conduct two
full-scale rounds at once.
</P>
<P>
   But Barak pledged to the Palestinians that he would strive to
prove their fears unjustified.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told Arafat that he told al-Sharaa that we have a
commitment toward Palestinians, and that everything should be
honest and decent,'' a senior Israeli official said. ``He told him
that he told al-Sharaa that we are not going to play or use one
track against the other because we will lose. We will continue
simultaneously. And he said that al-Sharaa responded positively and
said he appreciated, understood and respected all that.''
</P>
<P>
   Israeli prime ministers have stepped onto Palestinian soil,
crossing a few yards over the border at the Erez checkpoint in
Gaza. But this represented the first genuine foray into the heart
of the Palestinian Authority's territory, and a kind of submission
to their turf. The Palestinians were decidedly the hosts at the
white stone and red brick villa in a quiet neighborhood. And they
sounded very upbeat afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will witness starting from next week progress in all
respects,'' a senior Palestinian official said. ``Barak promised to
honor all his commitments in the interim agreements. We told him
that this will create a positive atmosphere. Barak also spoke a lot
of settlement activity, and he gave positive promises. But on that
front, it's premature. We have to wait and witness that he does
what he says.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak, whose government has angered Palestinians by authorizing
new construction at Jewish settlements in the West Bank, has
promised to freeze the expansion. He has acknowledged that it was
counter-productive in his pursuit of a final status framework
agreement by mid-February.
</P>
<P>
   But the Palestinians are wary. Formal final status negotiations
have stalled because of their concern, though quiet talks have
continued. One Palestinian participant in talks on land and borders
says even Jerusalem, a subject Israel says is nonnegotiable, has
been broached.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Israelis keep talking about the Al-Aksa mosque and the
Mount of Olives,'' he said, ``which means they are talking about
the fate of Jerusalem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
