<SLUG> BC-U.N.-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. PANEL AGREES ON TWO-YEAR BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ A General Assembly committee reached agreement
Wednesday on a two-year budget for the organization that U.S.
diplomats hope will fall within the ``nominal no-growth'' spending
demanded by the U.S. Congress in return for releasing money to pay
overdue U.S. debts.
</P>
<P>
   The budget is expected to be approved by the full General
Assembly on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The two-year budget for the headquarters _ not including money
to be spent on agencies like UNICEF or the World Heath
Organization, which raise their own funds _ has been held to $2.535
billion, $2 million more than the previous budget, diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   The American demand for a no-growth budget, which some U.N.
officials see as hamstringing the organization for domestic
political reasons in Washington, was one of many conditions that
Congress attached to payments to the United Nations. The United
States is now more than $1 billion in debt, a sum close to the U.N.
operating expenses for one year.
</P>
<P>
   The most difficult congressional condition remains to be
settled, a demand to lower U.S. payments to the organization. The
payments are linked to the proportion of the world economy in the
hands of the United States. That issue will be taken up in the new
year.
</P>
</TEXT>
