<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA: TALKS WITH U.S.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott discussed arms control
and other issues with Prime Minister Vladimir Putin, but the two
appeared to make little headway. The Defense Ministry again
ridiculed United States proposals to alter the 1972 antiballistic
missile treaty to permit a limited defense against rogue missiles,
saying the treaty is the basis of arms control.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA, BELARUS: PACT APPROVED
</P>
<P>
   Legislators in Russia and Belarus voted to ratify a treaty
moving the two nations closer to economic union, but still well
short of political merger. The treaty, signed this month by the
Russian and Belarussian presidents, calls for a unified tax system
by 2001 and a common currency by 2005, but is mostly short on
details. It replaces a similar document signed in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: PINOCHET HEALTH CHECK
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Augusto Pinochet, the former Chilean dictator, will be
given an independent medical examination on Jan. 5, the government
said. Pinochet, 84, has complained of poor health as he waits for
possible extradition to Spain on charges of torture.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: EASING QUARANTINE
</P>
<P>
   Starting Feb. 28, cats and dogs entering Britain from European
Union countries, Switzerland and Norway will not be subject to the
usual six months in quarantine. The government said that as part of
a pilot program, pets vaccinated against rabies and that have been
fitted with an identity microchip, among other things, will forgo
the usual stay in a government-approved kennel.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   NAMIBIA: U.S. WARNING
</P>
<P>
   The American Embassy issued a warning against travel in
northeast Namibia, where fighting between Angolan rebels and
Angolan and Namibian forces persists. Angolan troops have recently
operated openly in northern Namibia, using the area to mount
attacks on rebel bases in Angola's extreme southeast. The attacks
have prompted rebel strikes against Namibian forces.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: BUDGET IMPASSE
</P>
<P>
   Congress, meeting in extraordinary session to vote on next
year's budget, defeated the bill offered by President Ernesto
Zedillo's party as well as an alternative bill from the opposition,
which includes slightly more spending for health and education.
Lawmakers renewed negotiations, with some urging a second session
after Christmas but before the New Year, when the budget must be
approved to avoid a constitutional crisis.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: GOLAN RE-EDUCATION
</P>
<P>
   Education Minister Yossi Sarid sent a letter to school
principals urging them to open up classrooms to discussion of a
possible withdrawal from the Golan Heights. Calling it ``a
controversial and burning issue on the national agenda,'' he said
viewpoints supporting and opposing withdrawal as a condition of
peace with Syria should be presented.
</P>
</TEXT>
