<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-WILNER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALDON MAY BE THIS YEAR'S SURPRISE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
 &HT;     By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KAIE, Hawaii _ This time last year, Wally Szczerbiak was best
known as the guy with the spelling-bee name. By March, the
Miami-Ohio forward was a consensus All-American. By June, he was a
lottery pick.
</P>
<P>
   Who's the next Szczerbiak _ the next great player to emerge from
a mid-level school, dominate March Madness and attract hoards of
NBA scouts?
</P>
<P>
   The Pearl Harbor Classic seems a good place to start, since the
best player in the eight-team event is not a McDonald's
All-American from UCLA but B.B. Waldon, South Florida's unknown
sophomore forward.
</P>
<P>
   Waldon, from Lakeland, Fla., was a teammate of UCLA receiver
Freddie Mitchell at Kathleen High. He did not attend summer camps
following his freshman and sophomore seasons, so he existed outside
national recruiting radar.
</P>
<P>
   Miami, Florida and West Virginia showed some interest, but
Waldon, whose given name is Benitez Bernard, chose South Florida,
in Tampa, 25 minutes from Lakeland.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Waldon) bought into the vision we sold him on, which was that
we'd build around him,'' said Bulls coach Seth Greenberg, the
former Long Beach State boss. ``Out of high school, he wasn't a
great student. He was a good student, and I think that scared some
people off. But mostly, he's a hometown kid. He's homesick right
now (in Hawaii). He's very much a homeboy. His parents attend every
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Waldon, a skinny 6-8 forward, averaged 16.3 points and seven
rebounds last year. Tuesday night, in a victory over The Citadel,
he made 12 of 15 shots and scored a career-high 31. He is quick, he
has a soft touch, he rebounds, and he's a dedicated passer. He can
score from the low post or the 3-point line. Give him two years to
add strength and refine his perimeter game, and he's a first-round
draft pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I followed Szczerbiak last year, but not real closely,''
Waldon said. ``He's a great player. I'm hoping that one of these
days, people will find out there's a guy at South Florida they
should watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Impressive company:!off! Waldon isn't the only player with a
small reputation and a big game. Here's five names to watch in
March and beyond:
</P>
<P>
   _Bradley wing guard Rob Dye. A converted point guard, Dye is the
best player in the Missouri Valley Conference, and Bradley's the
best team. A 6-1 senior, Dye's averaging 17.6 points and played his
best game against Illinois: 19 points, seven rebounds and four
steals.
</P>
<P>
   _Oakland (Mich.) forward Dan Champagne. A 6-6 junior, Champagne
is out several weeks with dislocated bones in his hand. He played
in six games before the injury, averaged 18 points and 6.3 rebounds
and shot 56.3 percent from the field. He scored 26 against
Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   _Siena shooting guard Marcus Faison. The much-traveled son of a
military man, Faison was prepared to sign with New Mexico out of
high school. When the Lobos landed Lamont Long, Faison switched to
Siena. A 6-5 senior, he averages 18.6 points and seven rebounds.
He's also shooting 50 percent from 3-point range. Count Siena as a
team to avoid in March.
</P>
<P>
   _Texas Christian's Marquise Gainous. A nagging ankle injury has
limited Gainous' production this season, but when he gets healthy,
watch out. A 6-9 senior, Gainous scored 40 points twice last season
and will have several NBA scouts watching when the Horned Frogs
play Louisiana Tech tonight.
</P>
<P>
   _Austin Peay wing man Trenton Hassell. The best player in the
Ohio Valley Conference, Hassell is a superb rebounder for his 6-5
frame (8.5 per game). He's also averaging 19 points and 5.3 assists
and shooting 58.5 percent from the field. If Austin Peay can squirm
its way into the NCAA Tournament _ Murray State is the league
favorite _ Hassell will have a national audience for the first time
in his career.
</P>
<P>
   Season to forget? After losing to Wofford, Wisconsin-Green Bay
and Oregon State (by 18 points), Clemson is being compared to the
worst teams in ACC history.
</P>
<P>
   That short, ignominious list includes 1955 Clemson (2-21), 1986
Wake Forest (8-21) and 1989 Maryland (9-20). The Tigers were 5-5
entering Wednesday night's game against George Washington, and they
don't figure to win many in conference play.
</P>
<P>
   The showdown: Barring an upset, Stanford will be undefeated and
ranked No. 1 when the Cardinal hosts Arizona on Jan. 8.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, coach Mike Montgomery downplayed Stanford's ascention
to the top spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's other stuff,'' he said. ``We've just got to be good
enough to compete in our conference.''
</P>
<P>
   That shouldn't be a problem. Stanford and Arizona are the
early-season favorites, while UCLA must prove itself: The Bruins
have lost three of their last four to Arizona and six of their last
seven to Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   Around the Pac-10: The fire alarm at Cal's new Haas Pavilion
went off six minutes before tipoff last weekend against UC Irvine,
forcing evacuation. It was the second consecutive game the alarm
has sounded.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon State coach Eddie Payne is worried the Beavers have lost
their defensive passion. After an offseason of compliments and
lofty (for them) preseason predictions, perhaps expectations have
softened the Beavs.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Consistent: Arizona State guard Eddie House was 0 of 16 from
the field against Brigham Young. In his next game, 11 days later,
House scored 46 points, on 18-of-29 shooting, against San Diego
State.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's reserve center Robertas Javtokas is disgruntled about
playing time and didn't show for the Nebraska game last week. He'd
be the third player to leave Arizona this season, following Ruben
Douglas and Luke Recker. Yes, depth is a concern in Tucson. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
