<HEADER>
A7035 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-RESIGNATION     12-22 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-RESIGNATION-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT'S CHIEF FINANCIAL OFFICER TO BECOME CEO OF WORLDWIDE
FIBER 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: This replaces MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST)  
(lh) 
 By STEVE LOHR and JOEL BRINKLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Microsoft's chief financial officer, Gregory Maffei, resigned
Wednesday to join a Canadian builder of high-speed
telecommunications networks, becoming the latest Microsoft
executive to depart for entrepreneurial opportunities elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Maffei, 39, will become the chief executive of Worldwide Fiber
of Vancouver, British Columbia, a private company that is
aggressively building a fiber-optic network in North America and
across the Atlantic Ocean. Such high-speed networks are seen as
increasingly valuable assets as Internet traffic and data
communications surge.
</P>
<P>
   Maffei's departure, according to industry analysts, should have
little impact on Microsoft Corp. His resignation was announced
after the close of trading Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, Maffei had displayed some restlessness at
Microsoft, showing an interest in finding the top job at another
company. Earlier this year, Bill Gates, the Microsoft chairman,
vetoed an effort to recruit Maffei to Roadrunner, a high-speed
Internet service in which Microsoft had a 10-percent stake.
</P>
<P>
   Paradoxically, it was Maffei who had negotiated that veto power
for Gates, as Microsoft's lead negotiator in the flurry of
investment deals the company has made with cable television and
telecommunications companies in the last couple of years. When
Gates used that veto to prevent Maffei from leaving, analysts say,
it was probably only a matter of time before his top financial
strategist left.
</P>
<P>
   ``That had to put a strain in the relationship,'' said Richard
Sherlund, an analyst for Goldman Sachs &AMP; Co. ``Besides, if you want
to be a chief executive officer, the opportunities are pretty
limited at Microsoft.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Gates and Mics president, Steven Ballmer, are young
and show no signs of wanting to leave.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone call from Jamaica, where he was vacationing,
Maffei said he had no animosity whatsoever toward the Microsoft
leadership. ``Microsoft has been a tremendous place to be for my
seven years,'' he said. ``But I was interested in running my own
company, and this is a great opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   To build its fiber-optic networks, Worldwide Fiber has tapped
the private capital markets and developed close relations with Wall
Street investment bankers. It was one of those investment bankers,
Jill Greenthal of DLJ, that first approached Maffei with the idea
of heading up the Canadian company, Maffei said.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two months, Maffei sold Microsoft shares worth about
$35 million, according to filings with the Securities and Exchange
Commission. The filings stated he held options on another 1.71
million shares, and 1.14 million of those options could be
exercised. The rest he will leave on the table when he departs in
January.
</P>
<P>
   Maffei is expected to receive some compensation for Worldwide
Fiber for those unexercisable options. Besides, the Canadian
company plans to sell shares to the public sometime during the
first half of 2000. The initial public offering, if successful,
could prove a handsome payoff for the new chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   At Microsoft, Maffei will be succeeded by John Connors, 40, an
11-year veteran at Microsoft, who has served as controller, chief
information officer and, most recentd of the enterprise
sales group. Connors said he expected a ``seamless transition'' to
his new job, noting he had either hired or worked with many of the
800 people in finance and administration who he will now be
overseeing.
</P>
<P>
   Among the possible financial challenges that lie ahead is the
company's potential exposure in a series of civil class actions.
Fortified by the judge's partial verdict last month in the
government's antitrust case against the software giant, lawyers
nationwide have filed about 70 private suits against Microsoft in
the last month.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, at least 45 lawyers attended a meeting at a
Washington law firm or joined by conference call in an effort to
coordinate their efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``A large majority of the people who have filed state or federal
actions participated,'' said Michael Hausfeld, a lawyer in the
Washington firm Cohen, Milstein, Hausfeld &AMP; Toll, where the
two-hour conference was held. ``There are a lot of different
issues, divergent views, and we are attempting as best we can to
coordinate. It was a very interactive process.''
</P>
<P>
   The suits vary. Many accuse Microsoft of overcharging buyers for
the Windows operating system and seek triple damages. That charge
is based on Microsoft's admission, in documents, that it charged
$89 for Windows 98, the highest reasonable profit-maximizing price
_ an admission that the judge cited to support his finding that
Microsoft holds monopoly power.
</P>
<P>
   But even the suits raising that charge differ in the length of
time they claim Microsoft is guilty of overcharging. And other
suits raise entirely different issues, leading the lawyers to admit
that it would be no easy task consolidating them. Still, they
described consolidation as essential.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of case needs to be organized,'' said Stanley
Chesley, a Cincinnati lawyer. ``Microsoft is very well organized.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
