<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERROR-SEATTLE-555&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALGERIAN PLEADS NOT GUILTY TO CARRYING EXPLOSIVES INTO U.S. 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also TERROR-CLINTON) 
(nk) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Ahmed Ressam, the 32-year-old Algerian man arrested
last week when Customs agents discovered what they said was a cache
of bomb-making components in his rental car moments after he drove
off a ferry from Canada, was indicted by a federal grand jury
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Under heavy security, Ressam was led into the U.S. Courthouse
here, and he listened intently as the proceedings were explained to
him in Arabic by a court translator. Through his lawyer, Tom
Hillier, the chief public defender in Seattle, Ressam pleaded not
guilty to the five counts in the indictment, which charges him with
illegally carrying explosives and making false statements to
customs authorities.
</P>
<P>
   But the indictment made no mention of any broader plot linking
Ressam to any terrorist network. The authorities here and in Canada
say they are looking for others who may have been associated with
Ressam, including an unidentified man who stayed with him for
nearly three weeks in a motel in Vancouver, British Columbia, just
before Ressam left for the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Other than briefly saying yes in Arabic to the translator when
he was asked if he understood the charges against him and his pleas
to them, Ressam said nothing during his appearance before a U.S.
magistrate, John Weinberg, who ordered Ressam to remain held
without bail.
</P>
<P>
   Francis J. Diskin, an assistant U.S. attorney, told the
magistrate that the materials found in Ressam's car, including a
nitroglycerine-type chemical, urea powder and timing devices, could
``easily have taken down a building'' had they been assembled into
a bomb.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted of the charges, Ressam could face up to 40 years in
prison. Federal prosecutors may also try to indict him on
additional or superseding charges if they assemble evidence of a
broader conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   Hillier declined to discuss any of his conversations with
Ressam. Speaking to reporters outside the courthouse Wednesday
afternoon, he did say of his client: ``He's scared. He's in a
foreign country, in difficult circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Katrina C. Pflaumer, the U.S. attorney in Seattle, declined to
say whether federal officials had concluded that Ressam was part of
a larger plot to set off bombs during the holiday season in the
United States. In characterizing the charges lodged against Ressam
Wednesday, she said: ``This is not a terrorism indictment.''
</P>
<P>
   But she did issue what amounted to an unusual plea to anyone who
might have been involved in such plots to renounce them by
contacting authorities now.
</P>
<P>
   ``For anyone out there with any information about any similar
devices or plots,'' she said, ``we urge them to come forward.''
</P>
<P>
   When he was arrested last Tuesday shortly after driving off the
ferry at Port Angeles, Wash., Ressam possessed two ferry ticket
stubs, prompting some speculation that an accomplice may have
walked off the boat as a foot passenger and taken off once Ressam
was detained. The FBI asked the public for help on Wednesday in
identifying everyone who traveled on the ferry Coho from Victoria,
British Columbia, on Dec. 14, the day Ressam was arrested.
</P>
<P>
   And the hunt for the man who stayed with Ressam in Vancouver,
described by motel employees as a light-skinned man who speaks
English without a discernible accent, continued in both countries
Wednesday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In ordering Ressam held without bail, Weinberg cited the
evidence suggesting that he was carrying material for a powerful
bomb, his outstanding warrants in Canada for theft charges, the
fact that he held plane tickets to leave the United States the day
after he had planned to stay in Seattle, and his use of a fake
passport and Quebec driver's license.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no conditions that can be set that would ensure his
appearance and the safety of the community,'' said Weinberg.
</P>
<P>
   Ressam, a short, slight man with close-cropped black hair,
appeared to listen intently during the brief proceedings,
occasionally rubbing his eyes or the bridge of his nose. He stared
at the magistrate and looked around the room at one point, but he
showed no visible emotions. He was dressed in a light blue
short-sleeved shirt and blue pants.
</P>
<P>
   In Canada, authorities said Wednesday they are continuing to
investigate Ressam's possible ties to a low-level crime ring, based
in Montreal, that is believed to have helped finance an armed
Islamic group seeking to overthrow the Algerian government and
replace it with an Islamic ruling body. Ressam has a criminal
record for petty theft in Montreal, and is wanted on other theft
charges in the province of Quebec.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
