<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7051 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT &LR;      12-22 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   American Home Products To Settle Fen-Phen Cases &QL;
</P>
<P>
   American Home Products agreed to pay $350 million to settle
1,400 cases brought in Mississippi over its diet drug combination
fen-phen, a liability that could endanger its proposed $70 billion
merger with Warner-Lambert. The company moved to settle the cases
after a Mississippi jury had awarded $150 million in compensatory
damages to five plaintiffs, four of whom said the drugs had caused
them to develop an often fatal lung illness.
</P>
<P>
   Egypt to Ship Natural Gas to Israel
</P>
<P>
   Egypt will provide natural gas to Israel through a long-delayed
pipeline in a deal that will radically change Israel's energy
policy and its economic relationship with its most powerful
neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   Naya Seeks Bankruptcy Protection
</P>
<P>
   Naya, the bottler of spring water, has filed for bankruptcy
protection in Canada in a reversal of the stellar rise that had
much to do with its having once been distributed by Coca-Cola's
largest bottler. Naya entered the bottled-water market about five
years ago with the advantage of plugging into the Coca-Cola system.
But the bottler stopped carrying Naya after Coca-Cola introduced
its own bottled water this year, and Naya had to set up a different
distribution system.
</P>
<P>
   Investor Vows Mannesmann Fight
</P>
<P>
   Upset by the refusal of the board of Mannesmann, the German
telecommunications concern, to negotiate with Vodafone AirTouch of
Britain, Guy Wyser-Pratte, the American arbitrager, said he would
wage a campaign to oust the company's management if it does not
seek to strike a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq and S&AMP;P Reach Records
</P>
<P>
   Led by technology companies like Microsoft, the Nasdaq composite
index and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index climbed to records.
Nasdaq gained 26.15 points, or 0.67 percent, to 3,937.30, and is up
nearly 80 percent for the year. The S.&AMP; P.'s 500 increased 2.70
points, to 1,436.13. The Dow Jones industrial average edged up 3.06
points, to 11,203.60.
</P>
<P>
   UnitedHealth Keeps Some Controls
</P>
<P>
   Doctors said UnitedHealth Group, which was widely praised after
it said it was eliminating tight controls over decisions by
physicians, was still requiring prior approval for some procedures.
United said most prior approvals would be eliminated by Jan. 1,
2001.
</P>
<P>
   Daewoo Motor to Solicit Highest Bid
</P>
<P>
   Daewoo Motor became the object of a potential bidding brawl
between General Motors and Ford after the South Korean government
decided to solicit offers instead of negotiate with a single buyer.
</P>
<P>
   Corel Warns of Fourth-Quarter Loss
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Corel, the maker of WordPerfect software, fell 29
percent after the company forecast an unexpected fourth-quarter
loss because of lower sales of its software and
higher-than-expected operating costs. Shares of Corel fell $5.375,
to $13.1875, and slipped to $12 at one point. Just two weeks ago,
Corel stock was at a 52-week high of $44.50.
</P>
<P>
   WTO Backs U.S. Against Europe
</P>
<P>
   The World Trade Organization has backed the United States in a
trade battle with Europe, ruling that Washington can still use a
much-contested law to retaliate against nations it deems guilty of
unfair trade practices.
</P>
<P>
   Weis Markets to Consider a Sale
</P>
<P>
   The two groups of cousins who jointly control Weis Markets
agreed to explore all options for increasing shareholder value,
including selling the 164-store chain of supermarkets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
