<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7055 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     12-22 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: ISN'T ANYONE LISTENING? 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kathy Redmond cried when she first heard the name, and the
horrible story that went with it. This was when the breath of life
was still within Cherica Adams. Rae Carruth, the Carolina Panthers'
wide receiver whose son Adams was carrying, was already implicated
in the shooting by law enforcement in Charlotte, N.C. But where was
the national news media? Where was the outcry?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not until she died, not until Carruth fled, did people pay
attention,'' Redmond said Wednesday. ``Not until it was another
O.J. story.''
</P>
<P>
   Having absorbed the sordid allegations, Sound Bite City was
already moving blindly past the larger lesson and on to fresh, new
outrages, including the rock-headed ramblings this week in a
national sports magazine of the Atlanta Braves' reliever, John
Rocker, on urban diversity.
</P>
<P>
   Not Redmond, though. She wasn't about to let go of the story
that hit home, like a sickening yet somewhat predictable punch to
the stomach.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, what happened, if it's what they're saying it is, is
not shocking,'' said Redmond, the 26-year-old founder of the
growing National Coalition of Women Against Violent Athletes.
``I've been saying that we're going to see a lot more of this until
people start admitting that the situation with athletes is out of
control.''
</P>
<P>
   If Carruth was, as charged, the mastermind of a plot to rid
himself of his pregnant girlfriend, we should make no mistake about
it: This tragedy will not stand alone, based on its sheer
cold-bloodedness. It will, more than anything, have been the
inevitable climax to a late 20th century nightmare of sustained
violence perpetrated by athletes against women. It may be the last
wake-up call to every coach and commissioner, every university
administrator and back-room enabler.
</P>
<P>
   From her desk at the communications position she holds in
Denver, Redmond said that she was, sadly, already seeing the
familiar trappings of how such stories are spun. She was
remembering how athletes are acquitted of crimes at a far greater
rate than anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   She has seen the portrayals of Carruth as a well-meaning, if not
monogamous, soul _ a young man who leaped from the American
underclass into the jock elite world of money and fame. She has
seen the portrayal of Adams as a woman who sought the company of
athletes and partied hard.
</P>
<P>
   If Adams' lifestyle is instructional, it should only be as a
window into the athletes' lives. You hear about the paternity suits
and ask why these guys can't just use condoms. Anyone who has spent
time around famous athletes knows that many regard women in the
same vein _ easily obtainable, utterly disposable.
</P>
<P>
   As a college junior, Redmond stepped forward to charge Christian
Peter with raping her, two weeks after she first arrived at the
University of Nebraska. Peter, then a Cornhuskers star, now with
the New York Giants, was a white kid from the New Jersey suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're speaking to somebody who has heard complaints and
charges of women about men from every race, every class,'' Redmond
said. ``This issue is about guys who are taught to believe they are
above the rules, above the law, no matter where they are from.''
</P>
<P>
   I asked Redmond if she had read Bernard Lefkowitz's 1997 book,
``Our Guys'' (University of California Press). The story of the
1989 rape of a 17-year-old ``educable mentally retarded'' girl by a
gang of high school athletes in affluent Glen Ridge, N.J., was a
chilling condemnation of how our athletically gifted are raised.
</P>
<P>
   She had not read the book, but said, interestingly, that it was
making the rounds at Columbine High in Littleton, Colo. Redmond, a
1991 graduate of that tortured school, was outspoken after last
spring's shootings. She said she believed that the school's
athletes were living in the wild, wild west.
</P>
<P>
   Social scientists will never know how much, if at all, that
figured in the bloodshed. But then, Redmond would argue that the
wrong message continues to be sent. She wonders why $10 million has
been appropriated for a new athletic stadium at the school, while
parents raise money to repair the damage to the shot-up library.
</P>
<P>
   We could ask hundreds of elected officials similar questions.
Few people seem to have the courage or energy to even attempt to
treat the sickness in sports. Redmond, for her part, has developed
``Out of Bounds,'' a proactive program for athletes deemed
potentially violent. She offered it to Columbine, and other schools
in the district. The school board told her it was too expensive and
she was too outspoken.
</P>
<P>
   Now Redmond is talking to the Dallas Cowboys. They are, for now,
listening. She promises to keep talking, until more people listen.
</P>
</TEXT>
