r f BC-MEDIABYTES-MEDIABYTES     12-22 1485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIABYTES-MEDIABYTES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIABYTES/DAN FOST 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Bloomberg Uncovers Hush-Hush Stories 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 Chronicle Publishing Company &QC;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
When publicly traded companies have information that will likely
affect their stock price, many of them give that information to big
investors and analysts.
</P>
<P>
   As the fictional tabloid publisher Sid Hudgens said in ``L.A.
Confidential,'' that information is often imparted ``off the
record, on the Q.T. and very hush-hush.'' Only once the stock price
moves does the company then release the news to small investors,
the press and the public.
</P>
<P>
   While the Securities and Exchange Commission contemplates a new
rule change cracking down on that sort of ``selective disclosure,''
Bloomberg News has been hammering the issue for several years.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Bloomberg launched a new category on its proprietary
news terminals. Labeled ``Hush,'' the Princeton, N.J., financial
news service wrote a story every time a company excluded the press
or public from a conference call or investor conference.
</P>
<P>
   Such exclusions happen quite regularly, although that may be
changing, thanks in part to the Internet, and thanks to SEC
Chairman Arthur Levitt, who is pushing for the new rules. And
thanks, also, to Bloomberg and others in the press.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the bull market of the 1990s, the most disturbing
characteristic has been the unlevel playing field that's developed
between bigger institutions and individual investors,'' Bloomberg
News Editor in Chief Matt Winkler said this week, while in San
Francisco to inspect his troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's necessary to document with depth reporting the most
explicit examples of where selective disclosure has led to some
shareholders having an advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, Bloomberg reporters have found their way onto a call
that companies wanted to restrict; firms such as Microsoft, Fane and General Motors have all threatened Bloomberg with lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have welcomed it,'' Winkler said. Even though his
lawyers said he'd lose such a fight, ``I thought, it's better to
lose than to capitulate.''
</P>
<P>
   Not too many people see Bloomberg's ``Hush'' stories, and very
few news outlets pick them up. But the companies know they're
there, and it rankles.
</P>
<P>
   Papers like the Miami Herald did pick up a big  &LR; Bloomberg story
at the end of 1998, Winkler said, that described a lavish
conference in Phoenix conducted by Credit Suisse First Boston, at
which disk-drivemaker Western Digital Corp. revealed it would have
a banner year in 1999, causing its stock to jump 37 percent in one
day _ its biggest one-day gain ever.
</P>
<P>
   Winkler said he's leaned on Levitt at the SEC to pick up the
issue. An SEC spokesman said Levitt's been outspoken on the issue
since February 1998 and is now pushing the new rules, which could
require companies to release information to the SEC or the press at
the same time they give it to analysts and big investors. The rules
would carry monetary penalties.
</P>
<P>
   ``The press has played an important role in shedding light on
this issue,'' said Chris Ullman, director of public affairs at the
SEC.
</P>
<P>
   Some trade associations opposing the new regulations have argued
that requiring equal disclosure will mean less disclosure _ that
companies will be so fearful of accusations of selective disclosure
that they won't disclose anything.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, they argue that while sophisticated Wall Street
analysts can interpret their complex information, individual
investors might overreact.
</P>
<P>
   Neal Lipschutz, a senior editor and columnist for Dow Jones
Newswire, called such a position ``paternalistic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't wash,'' Lipschutz said. ``If someone loses money,
that's their responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he said, the same companies often accuse the
``sophisticated'' analysts of misinterpreting their statements into
something that moves the market.
</P>
<P>
   Dow Jones is among the media firms that have picked up the
crusade. The company, which also publishes the Wall Street Journal,
backed out of Donaldson Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette's investor conference
earlier this month when it learned that the bank was not allowing
reporters in to cover the presentations.
</P>
<P>
   With the rise of the Internet, more and more companies are
finding it easier to open up their conference calls and
presentations. While only one-third of public companies had done so
a year ago, the figure is now up to 50 percent, said the SEC's
Ullman.
</P>
<P>
   Bloomberg plans to keep pounding away at the issue, firm in its
conviction it's on the side of open access to information _ an easy
principle for a media watchdog to uphold.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing like transparency to expose something that's
unfair,'' Winkler said. ``That's what makes being a journalist so
much fun.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MONKEYING AROUND &QL; 
Former San Francisco Examiner reporter Steven Chin seems like the
perfect guy to build a Web portal for Asian Americans, and now he's
going to get the chance.
</P>
<P>
   Chin, who built a journalistic career covering the Bay Area's
Asian American communities, just sold his Web design firm, Monkey
King Media, to A.Media, publishers of A.Magazine: Inside Asian
America. He now has the resources and the platform to launch a
comprehensive site for Asian Americans, to debut next year at the
Web address of www.a-space.com. (That hyphen is not especially
elegant; the company would prefer to have www.a.space.com, but it
would need to buy that address from Space.com, former CNN Moneyline
anchor Lou Dobbs' portal for all things outer space.)
</P>
<P>
   Chin wouldn't disclose how much Monkey King sold for, but he
noted that A.Media just closed a round of angel investor financing
to the tune of $1.5 million, and he'll be able to triple the size
of his staff, now at five people. He'll stay in San Francisco, and
become executive vice president of internet development for New
York's A.Media.
</P>
<P>
   A.Magazine brings a strong ad sales team, rich content and a
strong offline brand, Chin said, but it lacked digital expertise.
Monkey King will figure out how to put A.Magazine's content online,
while it continues to provide Web services to nonprofits and other
entities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ad sales was an important part of the equation for me,'' Chin
said. As a veteran of the failed  &LR; Channel A, an &LR;  failed effort at
Asian American oriented Web site, television &LR;  programming,  &LR; Chin
said he knows how hard it can be ``to sell this market.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TA-TA, TISH &QL; 
Just as Upside magazine prepares to substantially beef up its Web
presence, it's losing its star columnist, Tish Williams, to
TheStreet.com.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who wrote the gossipy Daily Tish for www.upside.com,
will write the same sort of column three times a week for TheStreet
starting in January.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, 27, started at Upside in a swirl of controversy. She
had written a weekly sex column for the Stanford Daily while an
undergraduate, then took a job as a technical writer for a
telecommunications consulting firm. Upside chief executive David
Bunnell brought her in to add life to the fledgling Web site four
years ago, but some employees quit WHY? &LR;   &LR; and another Web site
published rumors of her outsized salary.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Bunnell said, Williams helped build the foundation
for a successful Web operation _ one that should benefit from a
soon-to-be announced $10 million round of financing. ``She's had a
big role in helping me get the online operation off the ground,''
he said. ``We're sorry to see her go. She'll do really well at
TheStreet.''
</P>
<P>
   TheStreet Editor in Chief Dave Kansas said adding Williams to
his stable of established columnists such as Herb Greenberg and
Adam Lashinsky is a coup. ``One of the big questions about
independent online publications is, can they get the talent?'' he
said. ``We're one of the few that has succeeded in getting
high-profile talent to come on board.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams is excited to join a lineup TheStreet has advertised as
``Murderers' Row.'' As her own fame grows, she quipped, ``Next
year, I'll be bringing out a line of crafts and home accessories.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
FISH FRENZY &QL; 
Even by the go-go standards of the high-flying New Economy
magazines, Red Herring Communications seems to be soaring through
the roof. In a little over a year, the Herring will have nearly
tripled its staff, from 80 at the start of this year to more than
220 by next year.
</P>
<P>
   The hiring binge went into high gear about two months ago at the
Herring headquarters in the old Hamm's brewery building in
Multimedia Gulch. More than 30 people have been hired, bringing
head count at year's end to 170, according to company president and
CEO Chris Alden. Even as it woos writers away from Forbes, Wired
and Money magazines most of the growth is coming at the company's
Web operation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
