<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7064 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-CARDS-CARDS_SFCHRON &LR;      12-22 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARDS-CARDS </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Procrastinators Rejoice Over Easy-to-Send E-mail
Holiday  Greetings 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Carrie Kirby &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 Chronicle Publishing Company &QC;  &LR; 
 &LR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &LR; 'Twas the night before Christmas, when all through the house &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Not a creature was stirring, except for my mouse. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  I selected the image and message with care, &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Clicked ``send,'' and in seconds my cards all were there. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   So you waited until it was too late again, and you can't settle
down for that long winter's nap with the guilt of all those unsent
season's greetings piled on the desk.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get your kerchief in a bundle, Mamma. This is 1999 and the
Internet is there to bail you out.
</P>
<P>
   Electronic greeting cards, cards that you send by e-mail, have
been around for several years, and they're getting easier to use
and more customizable. To send one, you go to an e-greeting site
such as Hallmark.com, choose a card, type in a friend's e-mail
address and a personalized message and click Send.
</P>
<P>
   The way your friend views the card depends on the Web site you
use; some send cards right in an e-mail message, while others send
a link to the card's location on their Web site. Sometimes, the
recipient has to visit the Web site and type in a code number to
retrieve the card. Of course, the easier it is for your friend to
retrieve the card, the more likely it is that he or she will bother
to view it.
</P>
<P>
   It seems like there are more Web sites offering free e-cards
than there are toys in the jolly old elf's sack. And it's not just
Christmas. You can fire off greetings for Kwanzaa, Ramadan, New
Year's and winter solstice just as easily.
</P>
<P>
   You don't hear a lot of people saying they're sending e-cards
instead of paper ones _ maybe it's the stigma of doing something
easy while others are wearing their fingers down to nubs addressing
hundreds of envelopes.
</P>
<P>
   But someone's out there doing it, because Web sites that offer
e-cards surge in popularity every year during the holiday season,
according to Media Metrix. During the week ending December 12,
flowers, gifts and greetings sites grew 36 percent compared with
the week before, more than any other category that Media Metrix
measures. Hallmark.com and Egreetings.com both showed up on Media
Metrix's lists of Web sites with the fastest popularity growth in
November and the beginning of December.
</P>
<P>
   Egreetings.com went public December 17, priced at $10, but its
share price has declined to less than $9. Its visitor count, on the
other hand, has increased 120 percent over this time last year.
</P>
<P>
   As a symbol of this field's success, consider ExciteAtHome's
purchase of Blue Mountain Arts for nearly $780 million earlier this
month.
</P>
<P>
   Media Metrix spokesperson Stacie Leone credits a unique traffic
model for the success of Blue Mountain Arts and other e-cards
sites. ``When you're sent a greeting card, you have to go back to
the site to receive it,'' Leone said. That at least doubles a
site's traffic, and card recipients may stick around to send a card
to someone else, creating a seamless word-of-mouth advertising
force.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blue Mountain Arts didn't do any advertising when they started
(in 1996), and look at them now,'' Leone said.
</P>
<P>
   After sending a few e-cards this year, San Francisco resident
Jack Karp said he'll never go back to paper cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sent out 30 or 40 cards in an hour. There's a better range
of cards than you would find in the store _ they even have
interfaith cards that say `Happy Everything.' And if I had done all
those paper cards it would have cost me $30 and taken an entire day
to mail them,'' Karp said.
</P>
<P>
   While some e-cards look a lot like traditional greeting cards,
with a static picture and a space for a personal message, others
are interactive experiences, with animated shorts, music and even
games.
</P>
<P>
   Your e-card experience can be as personal as you want it to be.
Some people pick one picture they like, type in all their friends'
e-mail addresses, slap on a standard greeting, and dispense with
the whole holiday tradition in 10 minutes. Others select a
different image for each recipient or insert a photograph of their
own family, write long personal messages, choose a special tune to
accompany each card, and even manipulate the background color and
font. The end result is a lot more intimate than receiving one of
200 identical cards with a photocopied holiday letter inside.
</P>
<P>
   E-cards can be a lifesaver for Americans living abroad who would
otherwise need to send cards weeks early and invest heavily in
postage. Leslie Burgoine, an American copy editor who lives in
Beijing, sent most of her cards on the Internet this year and
enjoyed the experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only drawback is that you can't decorate with e-cards like
you can with real cards _ you can't really stand them on your
mantel,'' Burgoine said.
</P>
<P>
   You could always print your e-cards on a color printer and tape
them up, but any animation and sound effects are lost. Capturing
e-card images as desktop patterns is easier than printing, but
equally limited.
</P>
<P>
   If you also forgot to buy a present for someone on your list,
the spirit of e-commerce can rescue you there too. Blue Mountain
Arts lets you charge a donation to charity on your credit card and
send someone a note that you have donated in their name. A whole
range of sites, including AOL Shopping and GiftCertificates.com,
let you send a gift certificate by e-mail or print one out directly
from the Web site.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
