<HEADER>
A7068 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-COLUMN-MOSS-NYT &LR;      12-22 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COLUMN-MOSS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON PRO FOOTBALL: MOOD SWINGS AND ALL, MOSS RULES
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Where Randy Moss goes, a crowd will follow. On the
field, it is usually an army of defensive backs trailing him like
puppies. Off the field, there may be no athlete in professional
football whose every word, movement or action is dissected like
those of Moss, the moody Minnesota Vikings wide receiver who is
redefining his position.
</P>
<P>
   Moss is fretted over like a grandmother crossing a busy street.
When he sneezes, the owner of the Vikings catches a cold.
</P>
<P>
   And on Monday night outside of the Metrodome, it was freezing
cold, about minus 4. Balmy for Minnesota this time of year. But
Moss was sweating, because inside the steamy locker room it was 80
degrees warmer and he was still perspiring from yet another
impressive game. It was a performance that would make even the most
cynical, hardened football observer simply say, ``Wow.''
</P>
<P>
   Moss is being chased again, this time by the news media, which
have surrounded him, circling, waiting to hear what he has to say
as he squeezes his wiry 6-feet-4 inch frame into that tiny space.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Green Bay Packers on Monday, he had five catches for
131 yards and two touchdowns, again showing up big in a big game.
This is becoming the Moss way. The larger the stakes, the quicker
he comes out of that telephone booth sporting his purple helmet and
cape. The only thing missing is X-ray vision.
</P>
<P>
   Moss, who will test the New York Giants on Sunday at the
Meadowlands in a crucial game for New York, fielded questions
mostly about the game; but a few were about Moss' strange demeanor
these last few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   This may come as a surprise to some, but Randy Moss gets bored,
even on the field, even with all of that furious action going on
around him.
</P>
<P>
   He tires of sitting all day in hotel rooms, on game day, waiting
for the game to begin. He gets irked when the ball does not come
his way. He mopes. He pouts. He boycotts the local news media.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings' owner, Red McCombs, a less overbearing version of
the Washington Redskins' owner, Daniel Snyder, challenged Moss'
recent habits on the field, which have been erratic. Moss has
seemed uninterested and frustrated at times; he will make a blazing
touchdown catch one minutes, then a few minutes later will fumble a
punt return. McCombs asked Moss, publicly, to display more of the
``spectacular'' and less of the ``garbage.''
</P>
<P>
   The response? ``He's our owner; he owns me,'' Moss said. ``He
owns this team. He owns our coaches. He owns coach Green, and I
think he's entitled to say anything he wants to.''
</P>
<P>
   Moss admitted that he has not been completely into football for
much of the last half of the season, which is scary, because this
year he set a team record with six 100-yard receiving games. He has
10 touchdown catches, making Moss and Cris Carter the only players
in Vikings history to have consecutive 10-touchdown seasons. His
1,214 receiving yards after 14 games are also a team record.
</P>
<P>
   This is disinterested? The Giants would take 10 years of Moss'
disinterest.
</P>
<P>
   What Moss has demonstrated more than anything is exasperation,
and such bouts tend to make him seem spoiled. The best example of
this happened against Tampa Bay on Dec. 6, when Moss turned his
back to the sideline while Buccaneers defensive back Donnie Abraham
was returning an interception.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two weeks, Moss has dropped seven passes and has
fumbled three times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really wasn't into my game recently,'' he said. ``I was
moping around. I was always wondering if we were going to get the
ball to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Moss was asked to explain further. ``I really don't want to say
`bored,''' he said. ``I think I'm just being too relaxed. There
have been times when I've been bored, just dragging along and stuff
like that, on the field and off the field. I don't think I've been
moping around in a bad way. It's just how I feel on game day.''
</P>
<P>
   Moss also said that one of the toughest things he has to do is
sit in his hotel room all day waiting for the game to start. His
lower back apparently has been stiffening, and the waiting,
especially on the road, takes its toll on his concentration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Laying in that hotel bed all day, my back has been bothering
me,'' he said. ``It has been hard for me to get motivated.''
</P>
<P>
   Moss is a strange mix of superstar and simple man. He still uses
words like ``golly'' when talking, but is becoming a well-known
commercial commodity. His face is increasingly popping up on the
tube.
</P>
<P>
   It seems that Moss is experiencing a sort of sophomore slump,
though it seems ridiculous that such a label would apply,
considering the tremendous year he is having. But this is a
different Moss than the one who burst onto the scene as a rookie
last season. Moss still has not adjusted to the fact that as great
as he is, he is still just one of many weapons on the Vikings
offense. He will never again be the only weapon, like he was at
Marshall University.
</P>
<P>
   ``Randy has had a good year,'' Dennis Green said. ``He's not
perfect. He hasn't had a perfect season, but he is a tremendous
player and he's a weapon returning kicks.''
</P>
<P>
   Green has not received enough credit for making the smart
decision to use Moss on punt returns. The same way Deion Sanders
causes the entire stadium to hold its breath when he lines up for a
return, Moss is having the same effect.
</P>
<P>
   Green was asked if he fears losing his star player to punt
returns, the way the Giants lost cornerback Jason Sehorn for all of
last season to a knee injury while returning punts.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Green said. ``Jason was a defensive player making the
adjustment to an offensive type of position. Randy has been playing
offense his entire life. That does make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   That is Moss: a difference maker. No one scares a defense like
he does. Which means a lot of teams will be frightened for a long
time to come.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
