<SLUG> BC-TIMES-SQUARE-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: KODAK GIVES ITS TIMES SQUARE BILLBOARD A FACE LIFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By COURTNEY KANE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One of the original extravagant signs at the
crossroads of the world has undergone a face lift to keep up with
its glitzy high-technology neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   After 15 years, Eastman Kodak Co. recently renovated its
billboard, which has been a fixture in Times Square since it was
designed as part of the exterior of the Marriott Marquis Hotel on
Broadway between 45th and 46th Streets.
</P>
<P>
   The gigantic billboard _ which outdoor-advertising executives
refer to as spectaculars _ has always featured an illuminated image
of stunning photography accompanied by the Kodak logo. Now, the new
sign, which is 52 feet high by 70 feet wide, is not only 20 percent
larger than its predecessor but is brighter and features a
state-of-the-art Sony Jumbotron screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Signage in Times Square has been changing dramatically over
the past several years,'' said Mike Ianzito, director for marketing
communications at Eastman Kodak, which is based in Rochester. ``It
was really our goal to bring it up to current times. With all the
advances in technology, we decided to recreate the Kodarama with a
completely new concept in lighting and imagery.''
</P>
<P>
   The new 1,800-square-foot Kodak image area, which the company
refers to as the Kodarama, is divided into three areas: a 15-by-60
foot primary display that takes up the lower half featuring
eye-catching photographs like those its predecessor displayed over
the years. In the upper right portion is the Sony Jumbotron video
screen. And the other section is either used as an extension of the
main display or to show images of Kodak products and promotions.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the new video capability, we can show our commercials or
do live telecasts from the Olympics or other venues,'' Ianzito
said. In addition, Kodak will be able to create direct links to its
Web site, displaying Web pages like Kodak Photoquilt, where
consumers send in their most meaningful photos.
</P>
<P>
   The content of the billboard, created by the New York office of
the Ogilvy &AMP; Mather Worldwide unit of WPP Group, will ideally
change every few months or so, Ianzito said. But through January
the display will feature Kodak's ``millennium gallery,'' which will
cycle through images of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   The entire image area features a black-and-white aerial view of
a construction worker waving from a girder above the Manhattan
skyline in the 1930s. The picture remains for five seconds, then
the screen dissolves into a three-minute slide show of images from
famous to everyday moments in this century. At various times, title
cards state: ``A picture speaks so loudly . . . just listen.''
</P>
<P>
   One image, for instance, is Winston Churchill flashing his ``V''
for victory sign, fading into Mickey Mantle with his four fingers
up in the air signifying a grand slam home run, to President
Richard M. Nixon bidding farewell in front of a helicopter. Those
famous moments in 20th century history, which are in no particular
order, are interspersed with ordinary moments like people at the
beach in the 1920s or a picture of a family having dinner.
</P>
<P>
   The renovation of the sign is indicative of the ever-changing
Times Square landscape. The Kodak sign is the second spectacular to
be revamped, after the transformation of the Coca-Cola billboard
eight and a half years ago. In the mid-1980s, those two were the
only major American companies with billboards in Times Square, when
the area's bleak, seedy appearance discouraged tourists and New
Yorkers alike.
</P>
<P>
   But over the years, the improvements in Times Square's economic
and physical health transformed the lineup of marketers planting,
or replanting, their brands on billboards there. And the square is
now bursting with electronic spectaculars that feature huge video
screens, message centers, electronic strips or ribbons, printed
vinyl that changes and, of course, flashing neon.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Forte, chief executive of Spectacolor Communications
Inc. in New York, which specializes in Times Square signs and is
handling Kodak's job, said: ``Everybody gives the credit to Disney
as the turning point to Times Square. But Times Square has always
been Times Square. It was always an entertainment mecca. Although
it had its slow days, I think people always wanted Times Square to
come back.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``great signs'' in the square now have three components in
common, Forte said. ``They all have something that is permanent for
the corporate name. They all have something that is spectacular,
and something that is changeable.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Kodak nor Spectacolor would disclose the cost of the
Kodak sign or discuss the multiyear contract to lease the space.
However, leases usually cost millions, plus there are millions more
to build, operate and maintain the billboards. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-22-99 2157EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
