<DOCNO> NYT19991222.0443 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7071 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-WTO-U.S.-EUROPE-490&AMP;A     12-22 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WTO-U.S.-EUROPE-490&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. WINS ROUND IN TRADE WAR WITH EUROPE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The World Trade Organization has backed the United
States in a trade battle with Europe, ruling that Washington can
still use a much-contested law to take retaliatory measures against
nations it deems guilty of unfair trade practices.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling is a narrow but important victory for the United
States. The Clinton administration suffered a humiliating blow in
Seattle earlier this month, when it hosted global trade talks that
collapsed amid sometimes violent street protests and sharp
disagreements among major trading partners.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials had worried that if the trade organization ruled
against the United States and demanded that it change domestic
trade laws, some members of Congress, as well as unions, consumer
and environmental groups, would have new reasons to attack the
Geneva-based trade group and thwart Washington's hopes of beginning
a new round of world trade liberalization.
</P>
<P>
   A report by a trade organization panel released Wednesday in
Geneva found that Section 301 legislation, which empowers the
United States to impose sanctions against foreign governments in
trade disputes, does not violate international trade agreements.
The European Union and many other countries that joined Europe's
case have long argued that the United States uses the law to punish
countries unilaterally, flying in the face of international trade
norms.
</P>
<P>
   The case, brought in late 1998, was a response to Washington's
action in a dispute over Europe's rules on importing bananas. The
trade organization sided with the United States in that dispute.
But under Section 301 Washington began taking retaliatory action _
drawing up a list of European exports to be taxed at punitive rates
_ before the trade organization gave the go-ahead.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Washington did not impose the sanctions until it got
trade organization approval. The ruling on the validity of Section
301, which can be appealed, suggested that the United States can
take retaliatory steps against unfair trade practices provided that
the law is not used to circumvent the trade organization, trade
experts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have maintained all along that Section 301 is consistent
with our WTO obligations, and are pleased that the panel concurs,''
Charlene Barshefsky, the U.S. trade representative, said in a
statement. ``Section 301 has served, and will continue to serve, as
a cornerstone of our efforts to enforce our international trade
rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Section 301 has rankled America's major trading partners since
Congress first passed the law in 1974. During trade battles with
Japan in the 1980s and early 1990s, for example, the United States
used the law to retaliate against what it called Japan's predatory
trade practices, prompting Japan to complain that Washington was
taking international trade rules into its own hands. Japan was
among the 16 countries that joined as third parties in Europe's
case against the United States.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Any trade organization ruling in favor of Europe in this case
would have been a double blow to the Clinton administration, which
has not only sought to protect the law but also to strengthen the
tepid support for the trade group. In Seattle, opponents of the
administration's trade agenda orchestrated a large protest against
globalization. One key charge: the trade organization violates the
sovereignty of member nations by forcing them to repeal laws that
restrict trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Psychologically it's a very important victory,'' said Claude
E. Barfield, a trade policy expert at the American Enterprise
Institute. ``Otherwise you would have had people saying that it's
another example of the WTO ruling against us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
