<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MANNESMANN-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: MANNESMANN-VODAFONE FIGHT TAKES ON DECIDEDLY AMERICAN
TONE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The battleground for the struggle between Mannesmann
A.G., the German telecommunications conglomerate, and its unwanted
suitor, Vodafone AirTouch of Britain, may be in Europe, but it has
all the trappings of a Wall Street scuffle, complete with Wall
Street investment bankers and tactics.
</P>
<P>
   Upset by the refusal of Mannesmann's board to negotiate with
Vodafone, a prominent American arbitrager who has bought shares in
Mannesmann said Wednesday he would wage a campaign to oust the
company's management if it did not seek to strike a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Guy Wyser-Pratte, the Wall Street investor known for his
penchant for starting proxy fights against management boards he
considers obstinate, said he would immediately begin seeking powers
of attorney from Mannesmann shareholders to vote to withdraw
confidence from Mannesmann's management and to convene a special
meeting if they refused to negotiate with Vodafone, the British
mobile phone operator.
</P>
<P>
   Wyser-Pratte's move came as Chris Gent, Vodafone's chief
executive, was preparing to present the company's formal offering
document to Mannesmann and its shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   That presentation, set for Thursday, officially begins
Vodafone's all-stock bid, which was worth $127.7 billion when first
made a month ago and is now worth substantially more because the
share values of both companies have risen. Vodafone has said it
would exchange 53.7 of its shares for each Mannesmann share.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vodafone has a lucrative bid on the table and they say they
are willing to talk and these Mannesmann fellows say: `fortress
Germany,''' Wyser-Pratte said in a phone interview from his office
on Wall Street. ``Our hope is that Mannesmann will do the right
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Mannesmann officials have called Vodafone's offer too low, and
the company's chief executive, Klaus Esser, has said he does not
want to merge with Vodafone regardless of price.
</P>
<P>
   As an arbitrager, who makes a living by buying and selling
shares based on where he thinks their value is headed, Wyser-Pratte
has a vested interest in seeing Mannesmann reach an agreement with
Vodafone; he bought shares of Mannesmann hoping that the company
would be sold to Vodafone at far more than he paid. Wyser-Pratte
would not say how many shares of Mannesmann he owns or what they
cost him.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for Mannesmann and Vodafone declined to comment on
Wyser-Pratte's plan to pressure the Mannesmann board.
</P>
<P>
   Several Mannesmann shareholders here and in the United States,
who spoke on the condition on anonymity, said they were unsure
Wyser-Pratte would be able to persuade enough shareholders to kick
out Mannesmann's board.
</P>
<P>
   But at the very least, they said, he might create shareholder
resentment toward the company's management, depending on how
Mannesmann deals with his threat. If it treats him dismissively,
they said, that may be regarded as a sign of arrogance that could
ultimately create support for Vodafone.
</P>
<P>
   Wyser-Pratte pledged to ``introduce a withdrawal-of-confidence
resolution at the Year 2000 ordinary shareholders meeting, if the
extraordinary meeting is not held in a timely fashion.'' For
Wyser-Pratte to even call a special meeting, he needs to persuade 5
percent of Mannesmann's shareholders to vote for one. Wyser-Pratte
has hired Innisfree M &UR;  &LR; &AMP; &UR;  &LR; A, a firm that specializes in proxy
soliciting, to help him rally shareholders to call the special
meeting. It is unclear how many votes Wyser-Pratte would need to
win to oust Mannesmann's board.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the chances of calling a meeting are excellent,''
Wyser-Pratte said. ``Just look at the stock price,'' he added,
noting that Mannesmann shares are still trading for less than
Vodafone's offer price.
</P>
<P>
   Mannesmann stock closed Wednesday at 231.15 euros, or about
$233, a share, while Vodafones offer values the company at 254
euros, or about $256.54, a share.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of both Mannesmann and Vodafone fell Wednesday.
Mannesmann dropped 2.7 percent. Vodafone fell 1.75 pence, to 296.75
pence, or about $4.78, a share.
</P>
<P>
   Wyser-Pratte is not the first Mannesmann shareholder to try his
hand at persuading the company to negotiate with Vodafone, though
he is the first to do it through a proxy fight.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, three German shareholders tried to prevent
Mannesmann from opposing Vodafone's offer in a lawsuit, but a
German court rejected the shareholders' case.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
