<SLUG> BC-OBIT-WELTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUTH WELTING, 51, A SOPRANO ADMIRED FOR COLORATURA ROLES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., Tenn.)  (js) 
 By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ruth Welting, a soprano who sang a wide variety of roles at the
Metropolitan Opera between 1976 and 1994, died on Dec. 16 at her
home in Asheville, N.C. She was 51.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was cervical cancer, said her manager, Robert
Lombardo.
</P>
<P>
   Through most of her career, Ms. Welting was admired for the
strong upper register that allowed her to play coloratura roles
with an unusual fluidity. Among her specialties were the Queen of
the Night in Mozart's ``Zauberfloete,'' Olympia in Offenbach's
``Tales of Hoffmann'' and Zerbinetta in Strauss' ``Ariadne auf
Naxos,'' all of which she sang at the Met. Zerbinetta was her debut
role in 1976, as it had been at the Royal Opera in Covent Garden in
London in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   She also gave notable performances as the Fairy Godmother in
Massenet's ``Cendrillon'' in Paris, Washington and San Francisco,
and Marie in Donizetti's ``Fille du Regiment'' in Barcelona and
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Welting was born in Memphis in 1949 and studied voice
privately with Daniel Ferro in New York, Luigi Ricci in Rome and
Jeanne Reiss in Paris. In 1968 she was a winner of the Metropolitan
Opera National Council Auditions, and in 1970 she made her debut at
the New York City Opera as Blonde in Mozart's ``Abduction From the
Seraglio.'' She was also praised for her City Opera performances as
Zerbinetta and as Gilda in Verdi's ``Rigoletto.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Ms. Welting began quietly cutting back on her
performances, having grown disillusioned with the music business
and tired of repeating the roles she had been singing for 20 years.
Intent on pursuing a more recent interest in government and foreign
affairs, she entered Syracuse University in 1994 and graduated in
1998 with a degree in liberal studies. She was continuing her
studies at the Maxwell School of Government at Syracuse University
at the time of her death.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Welting is survived by her mother, Mary Frances Welting, and
two sisters, Rozelind Merryman and Elizabeth Childers, all of
Memphis.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-22-99 2201EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991222.0448 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7077 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-TERROR-TUNNELS-NYT     12-22 0470
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TERROR-TUNNELS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.J. MAN ARRESTED IN BOMB THREAT TO NEW YORK CITY TUNNELS
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By KEVIN FLYNN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The authorities posted police officers and
bomb-sniffing dogs at several tunnels leading into New York City on
Wednesday morning after a New Jersey man posted a threatening
message on the Internet saying that a van filled with explosives
would be left in a tunnel leading into the city, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Federal agents later arrested a Newark, N.J., man, Renato
DeSousa Flor, and charged him with having sent the threatening
message to a chat room operated by America Online.
</P>
<P>
   Although no explosives were recovered at Flor's home, the
authorities had taken the threat seriously and earlier in the day
had assigned the police to check trucks entering the Holland and
Lincoln Tunnels from New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   America Online contacted the authorities after reading the
threatening message, and members of the Joint Terrorism Task Force
arrested Flor at his home, according to an FBI statement released
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet message had been posted early Wednesday to an
e-mail address used by Flor, according to the criminal complaint.
</P>
<P>
   In the complaint, FBI Agent Jeffrey A. Farrar said the message
warned the FBI and CIA that a blue van with explosives, accompanied
by two cars, would be parked sideways in the middle of a tunnel.
``Then the driver will get inside one of the cars and exit the
tunnel,'' the message said.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear from the complaint whether the threat had
specified a particular tunnel, but the FBI statement said the
message had specified the Holland and Lincoln Tunnels. The
complaint said Flor had admitted sending the e-mail message.
</P>
<P>
   The rapid response to an Internet threat was an indication of
how carefully the authorities are taking security precautions for
the millennial New Year's Eve celebration. But New York officials
have said they have not received any credible threats against the
city.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no guarantees against terrorism when you live in a
free society,'' Police Commissioner Howard Safir said at a news
conference Wednesday. ``But I believe that we are doing everything
humanly possible to make sure that it is a safe and enjoyable
millennium celebration for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Safir said 35,000 police officers, double the usual number, are
assigned to work during the celebration, which will last until 6
a.m. on New Year's Day. In addition to confiscating open containers
of alcohol, Safir said the officers would look out for people
carrying ``packages, knapsacks and briefcases that may be
suspicious.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said, ``we will be doing lots of sweeps with
both dogs and other equipment to make sure that all of the venues
that are going to be used are safe.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
