<SLUG> BC-UNITED-XRAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTORS COMPLAIN ABOUT PROMISE BY H.M.O.
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATT: Minn., N.Y., N.J., Md.)   (rk) 
 By MILT FREUDENHEIM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UnitedHealth Group, the big managed-care company, was widely
praised last month after it said it was eliminating tight controls
over decisions by physicians, which the doctors derided as
``second-guessing.'' United said that doctors would no longer need
advance authorization for most treatments and that the company
would not refuse payment afterward.
</P>
<P>
   But doctors in the UnitedHealthcare network said Wednesday that
guidelines they had just received were still highly restrictive.
They said United was still requiring prior approval, called
``pre-certification,'' for expensive computerized imaging tests,
physical rehabilitation and prescription drugs as well as mental
health and drug and alcohol treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Silverstein, a marketing vice president of United, based in
Minnetonka, Minn., said the authorization requirements would end as
subcontracts are revised with companies that supervise the
arrangements. He said most prior approvals would be eliminated by
Jan. 1, 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Even without the approvals, United will still require advance
notification for many such procedures. But Dr. Craig Keyes, chief
medical officer of the United units in New York and New Jersey,
said that even the notifications might be dropped if, for example,
``over the next two or three months we find it is not helpful to
call someone before doing a CT scan.''
</P>
<P>
   Some doctors were skeptical about the new policies. ``They made
everybody think that they didn't have to get all this
pre-certification, and it's not true,'' said Dr. Patricia Klein, a
neurologist in Westwood, N.J. Dr. Klein, who heads a legislative
policy group of the New Jersey Medical Society, said she was
considering leaving the United Healthcare network.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a subcontractor, you control the subcontractor,''
said Dr. Ted Lewers, board chairman of the American Medical
Association, which praised United's announcement last month. He
said the company might have to buy out some subcontracts but ``if
they are going to give their word, they should stand by the word.
It appears they are not doing so,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to specialist physicians in the New York and New
Jersey area, the company also said this month that it had hired
Magellan Specialty Health, a company in Columbia, Md., that reviews
charges by physicians. It said Magellan would ``provide support''
in carrying out its new programs.
</P>
<P>
   Magellan said, in an undated letter that some specialists
received on Dec. 10, that these doctors would have to supply
medical records to justify higher-level payments for difficult
cases. Without the paperwork, payments would be lower, it said.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors in the area have dealt with the company before. The New
Jersey Medical Society said Magellan ``had presented great
difficulties to New Jersey physicians in the past and has been
dropped by other HMOs in the state.'' Dr. Klein said that Magellan
had routinely lowered her payments when it worked for another
insurance company, NYLcare.
</P>
<P>
   Keyes said he was aware of the complaints. He said Magellan had
controlled the payments of claims for NYLcare. Under its contract
with United, Magellan will be limited to an advisory role; United
will make its own decisions about payments, he said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
