A7081 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-OUT-ROBINSON-LADN     12-22 1168
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-ROBINSON-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBINSON IS A TRAIL BLAZER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH MARTIN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Hikers look forward to the new and unanticipated
beyond the next bend. For John W. Robinson, that has included a
writing trail that started with youthful jaunts and matured with a
role as unofficial interpreter of Southern California's mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, 70, of Fullerton has written 12 books, a few of them
local classics, including ``Trails of the Angeles,'' now in its
18th printing with 80,000 sold, and a history of its rugged high
country called ``San Gabriels.'' Other histories revolve around the
San Jacinto and San Bernardino mountains.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of people who don't know about these
mountains,'' Robinson said, describing the San Gabriels, in
particular, as overused yet underappreciated. ``Many people don't
know the treasure they have.''
</P>
<P>
   To those who do, it is Wilderness Press' ``Trails of the
Angeles: 100 Hikes in the San Gabriels'' that peak-baggers consider
their bible; they all but hold its author up on a pedestal.
</P>
<P>
   It all began ordinarily enough for the man who would be king of
the mountains.
</P>
<P>
   As a youth, he hiked in the Sierra Nevada mountain range, went
on YMCA treks and attended summer camp. His first local trip was to
the top of San Gabriel Peak; adult guides ``told kids there were
watermelons on top,'' he said. Yeah, right, like there are
strawberries atop Strawberry Peak.
</P>
<P>
   He graduated from USC in 1951 with a major in social studies and
a minor in history, long before the other John Robinson had any
association with the university. Following a two-year stint in the
Army he began what would become a 33-year teaching career. He
started a routine that lasted until his retirement in 1988:
teaching during the week, hiking once a weekend.
</P>
<P>
   A few of the sojourns spurred Robinson's early interest in
history. Walking among the Mount Lowe ruins _ a railway to its
zenith past broken- down resorts and near-abandoned mines piqued
his curiosity. Soon he was devoting one day a weekend to research
and the other to hiking.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson first intended to write a book only about Mount Lowe,
but his interest expanded. The result _ his third book after a
couple of what he termed minor efforts _ was ``Trails of the
Angeles,'' a mix of generous portions of the past and detailed
trail descriptions. The winning combination is endearing to
wafflestompers.
</P>
<P>
   Hikers scrambling through boulders on the 6-mile Mount Hillyer
Trail near Chilao learn it was a hideout of late 19th century
bandit Tiburcio Vasquez (who also took to holing up in an area
farther to the west that would later be known as Vasquez Rocks).
The 230-page ``Trails of the Angeles'' also reveals to those on a
couple of trails from Vincent Gap that Charles Tom Vincent was a
fugitive who discovered a gold lode in 1894.
</P>
<P>
   Although Robinson is most associated with the San Gabriels, he
has hiked many of the prime backcountry in North America.
Regionally, the San Jacintos west of Palm Springs are his favorite
mountains. He backpacks in the Sierra every summer and has visited
Alaska a half-dozen times. Among the high points of his hiking
experience was seeing five grizzly bears in Montana.
</P>
<P>
   Visiting Alaska, he said, allows ``a feeling of true primeval
wilderness. It's a feeling you don't get in the Lower 48, like
you've gone back 1,000 years in time.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson's latest book project, tentatively titled ``Gateways to
Southern California,'' is a history of the travel routes into the
state's lower end horse trails, wagon roads and early highways.
Like many of his projects, it started as something else _ a history
of mountain passes _ and has kept evolving.
</P>
<P>
   And like all his books, this one involves extended periods in
the library. He has spent hundreds of hours reading Southern
California papers printed from 1851 to 1890. But he enjoys research
and meeting people, especially old-timers with choice stories and
anecdotes.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson's travels have taken him to trails both well-trod and
not taken, but their point of departure is familiar: a love of the
outdoors and a natural curiosity about the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just feel good being in the mountains,'' he said. ``Even
though you're exhausted, you're spiritually refreshed. I need this
experience to keep me a whole person.''
</P>
<P>
   That zeal is duplicated in the completeness of his writing. For
example, ``Trails of the Angeles'' functions as a trailhead for
``San Gabriels,'' which, with his titles chronicling the San
Bernardinos and San Jacintos, is part of his trilogy of ``urban
mountain ranges.''
</P>
<P>
   ``San Gabriels'' shows that the need for watershed protection
was a major impetus to the development of Angeles National Forest
as a protected area. Robinson follows each slow step in the
building of Angeles Crest Highway from 1929 to 1957, starting with
pressure from the automobile and gas lobbies and a series of
disastrous blazes in the 1920s that kept burning because they could
not be reached by firefighters.
</P>
<P>
   He considers the trilogy most important among his books because
of the importance of explaining the wilderness experience and the
need for preservation.
</P>
<P>
   Bridge to Nowhere hike &QL; 
is a winter wonderland &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
By Rich Martin
</P>
<P>
   John W. Robinson had a hard time listing his favorite hikes of
the San Gabriel Mountains, and rated the top one in part for
seasonal reasons: It's a good trip during the winter, when snow and
cold weather can make the higher mountains impassable.
</P>
<P>
   His choice: The so-called Bridge to Nowhere hike, reached by
taking the Foothill Freeway (210) east and traveling north on
Highway 39 in Azusa. Turn right on San Gabriel Canyon Road and
drive 8 miles to the ranger station.
</P>
<P>
   The 9-mile hike crosses and recrosses the East Fork of the San
Gabriel River to a site known as the Narrows.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a little bit of variety,'' he said, with the deepest,
``most spectacular gorge in Southern California.'' All is contained
in a stunning forest in the shadow of an 8,000-foot peak.
</P>
<P>
   The route ends in an oddity _ a bridge that survived a 1938
flood. Most of a long-ago highway was washed out by the deluge and
not rebuilt, leaving the bridge span as an eerie testimonial to
nature's wrath.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Can't fail trails &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Other hikes in the Angeles National Forest particularly revered by
John W. Robinson:
</P>
<P>
   _Crystal Lake (reached by taking Highway 39 north) to Windy Gap,
and from there to Mount Islip.
</P>
<P>
   _Dawson Saddle, highest point along Angeles Crest Highway east
of Mount Williamson, to Throop Peak or Mount Baden-Powell.
</P>
<P>
   _Mount Waterman from Buckhorn.
</P>
<P>
   _Icehouse Canyon in the Mount Baldy area, which affords ``all
kinds of options,'' including loop trails and peak-bagging.
</P>
<P>
   Others he enjoys are San Gabriel Peak (near Red Box), Mount
Hillyer in the Chilao area and the so-called Bridge to Nowhere,
reached by taking Highway 39 north.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
