<HEADER>
A7085 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN     12-22 0470
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFS TO BE SEEN, HEARD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The NBA's latest fan-friendly innovation _
microphoned referees _ makes its debut Saturday, when the Lakers
play host to the San Antonio Spurs on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   To Lakers coach Phil Jackson, the NBA's ``fan''-tastic marketing
ploy is anything but fantastic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ridiculous,'' he said, ``but that's part of the
showmanship that the commissioner has done with this league, and
it's been successful, because he's been open. And I don't know if
they're pushing the envelope on this one or not, but I can tell you
an occasion when a referee was miked, and I thought he cost us a
ballgame in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the 1992 Finals against the Portland Trail Blazers, and
referee Jess Kersey was wearing a microphone for an NBA
Entertainment video (not the TV audience), and as Jackson recalls,
Michael Jordan used a profanity while complaining to Kersey about a
call.
</P>
<P>
   ``And Jess felt he had to call a technical (foul) on him,''
Jackson said, ``and really it was an embarrassing situation for him
and for Michael. It wasn't a big protest, but it balanced out the
scale on some level they got a basket, a technical, suddenly it's a
six-point game with three minutes to go and changed the nature of
the ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I complained after that about miking referees and I'm
surprised that they would consider it,'' he said. ``I think it
takes away from the judgmental nature, because...instead of being
able to do your job consciously, without thought, you have to be
self-conscious, and that's going to screw things up.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch report: Travis Knight, on the injured list since Dec.10
because of a right-ankle sprain, might be activated in time for
Saturday's game. Considering the Spurs' twin-tower lineup of
7-footers Tim Duncan and David Robinson, the Lakers are likely to
need every available big body.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thought is there, and we will consider (activating
Knight),'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal has gotten into foul trouble in the past
dueling Duncan and Robinson, and the Lakers' only active backup
center is 6-11 John Salley. The 7-foot Knight has played sparingly
this season. He's made just 15 appearances, averaging 5.1 minutes,
1.6 rebounds and 0.7 points.
</P>
<P>
   All-Stars: O'Neal is the top vote-getter among all Western
Conference players in the first All-Star fan balloting returns.
O'Neal has 275,487 votes, and a huge lead over the Spurs' Robinson
(98,944) among West centers.
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant is currently third among Western Conference guards,
with 142,328 votes. He trails Seattle's Gary Payton (146,360) and
Phoenix's Jason Kidd (165,727).
</P>
<P>
   Glen Rice is seventh among forwards, with 43,926 votes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
