<SLUG> BC-TOYSRUS-SHORTAGES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOYS `R' US FALLS BEHIND ON SHIPPING
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What could possibly be worse than venturing into a toy store two
days before Christmas?
</P>
<P>
   Having to go to the toy store when you thought you had your toy
shopping done a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   Toys R Us said Wednesday that its Internet site will not be able
to fulfill all of the orders it had promised to ship by Christmas.
And to make good, it sent those customers left in the lurch free
$100 gift certificates that it says will arrive by overnight
courier Thursday morning. That gives parents two days to take those
gift certificates into local Toys R Us stores to try to buy a gift.
Or they can simply give the certificates to their children.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sat down yesterday and felt that there were some orders
that we were not able to ship for Christmas,'' John Barbour, the
chief executive of Toysrus.com said Wednesday.
   ``Rather than take the risk of disappointing people, we wanted
to make sure people had time to make other arrangements.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbour said that fewer than 5 percent of the company's holiday
orders are affected, but he declined to be more specific or to say
the total cost of the gift certificates.
</P>
<P>
   Since the average order is about $60, Barbour said, most
customers will be able to buy more or bigger gifts than they had
planned on.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways, we're trying to appease people for letting them
down,'' he said. Customers will have the option of canceling their
order from the online service or waiting for shipment after
Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Customers said the move is hardly enough, especially because
many of the most popular toys are sold out in stores by now.
</P>
<P>
   ``This does nothing to appease a child on Christmas morning when
he doesn't find his present,'' said Kevin Davitt, who is still
waiting for an order from Toysrus.com. ``A 6-year-old doesn't want
a gift certificate, he wants his Nintendo or his Pokemon.''
</P>
<P>
   Davitt, a publicist from Glen Rock, N.J., ordered two video
games for his 6-year-old son on Dec. 13, agreeing to pay $19.90 for
express shipping. Toysrus said the shipment would arrive in five
days.
</P>
<P>
   Toys R Us was a small player on the Internet until the middle of
November when it mailed out 62 million catalogs offering free
shipping for orders from its Web site. Since then its Web site has
been so busy that many customers couldn't even get in, and those
that did place orders found that items often arrived weeks after
they were promised, if at all.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it could not promise Christmas delivery for
customers who ordered with regular shipment after Dec. 10 and with
express shipment after Dec. 15.
</P>
<P>
   This hardly dented traffic to the company's Internet site. Last
week, Toysrus.com was the fifth most visited online store, with 1.6
million visitors, according to Media Metrix, a New York research
firm.
</P>
<P>
   Barbour said that the problem is largely in the company's
warehouse, which has not been able to pack and ship the orders,
even though the toys are sitting on its shelves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's taken us longer to get through the complex process of
fulfilling orders than anyone expected,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other online companies have also run into problems fulfilling
all their orders. EToys, for example, says there is a ``small
percentage'' of purchases that it won't be able to ship by
Christmas. Unlike Toysrus, the problem at eToys is that its Web
site continued to sell some hot items, like Pokemon toys, even
after its warehouse ran out of stock. The company has sent e-mail
to these customers, an eToys spokesman said, in recent days,
suggesting alternate items. While eToys has given away some gift
certificates, they have generally not been amounts as large as
$100.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many customers say their biggest frustration with
Toysrus has been that the company wasn't able to accurately predict
its shipping time.
</P>
<P>
   ``My biggest beef in retrospect was the total absence of any
customer service,'' said Joseph C. Petillo, an attorney in East
Windsor, N.J. He just received an order placed with Toysrus at the
end of November, just in time for his son's birthday on Thursday.
``I wouldn't have felt so bad if they had given me the opportunity
to cancel and shop elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
