<SLUG> BC-WEIS-MARKETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEIS MARKETS TO CONSIDER A SALE, PLEASING DISSIDENT SHAREHOLDERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The two groups of cousins who jointly control Weis Markets
agreed Wednesday to explore all options for enhancing shareholder
value, including selling the 164-store chain of supermarkets,
ending the threat of a proxy fight by one faction.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement could be a first step toward determining a price
at which the cousins who run Weis could buy out the shares owned by
their cousins or, perhaps, to a sale of the 92-year-old company.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Weis, which have risen about 18 percent in recent
weeks, closed Wednesday at $41.4375, off 50 cents. With the recent
run-up, shares now trade at about the same level as 12 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   For some time a group including Janet Weis, the 80-year-old
widow of Sigfried Weis, the company's former chairman, and the
families of their three daughters, have wanted to sell the chain
and cash out their 41 percent interest; at the current share price,
that stake is worth about $700 million. They formed a committee and
were threatening a proxy fight to add two more seats to the
company's seven-member board, but they agreed Wednesday to drop
those efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Robert F. Weis, the current chairman whose family also owns 41
percent of the company, said after the stock market closed: ``We
have initiated a process that will allow the full board of Weis
Markets to determine what is in our collective best interest with
full information concerning our financial and strategic
alternatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Weis reiterated that the company was not for sale. ``However, in
an effort to avoid the continuing disruption to our company of a
proxy contest and the inevitable attendant litigation,'' he said,
``we have agreed to include this alternative and a recapitalization
within the range of options that we have asked Morgan Stanley to
explore.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Weis and another dissident shareholder, Sidney Apfelbaum,
issued a statement saying that ``we are pleased that we can proceed
forward on a consensual basis.''
</P>
<P>
   The statements suggested that the company's investment banker,
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, would fully share information with the
dissidents' adviser, Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   Weis Markets, which is based in Sunbury, Pa., has long been an
exceptionally profitable chain, at one time earning a third as much
in profits as the giant Safeway chain on sales volume only 5
percent as large, according to Forbes magazine. But Walmart Stores'
the recent drive into Weis territory has raised questions about the
chain's future.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for both sides declined further comment Wednesday
night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
