<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BELL-LONGDISTANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: WRONG CALL ON BELL ATLANTIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, Dec. 23:
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission's approval of Bell
Atlantic's application to enter the market for long-distance
service in New York state looks more like a bow to political
pressure than to consumer protection. The 1996 Telecommunications
Act requires that for Bell Atlantic to gain permission to go after
the long-distance customers of AT&AMP;T and other competitors, it must
first open up its own network of wires and switches so that these
competitors get a fair shot at wooing Bell Atlantic's customers for
local service. Bell Atlantic comes close, but does not pass some
key tests.
</P>
<P>
   The commission could have held up approval for a couple of
months until Bell Atlantic showed it was fully ready. But having
already turned aside several previous applications from Bell
companies, it responded to pressure to prove the '96 act was
creating competition by finally approving one. The danger with
compromised standards is that Bell Atlantic could wield its power
to wall off its local market even as it moves to crush competitors
in long-distance and Internet services.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic owns the only telephone wire into most homes and
businesses. The '96 act requires that Bells rent their wires,
switches and other equipment to AT&AMP;T and other potential
competitors so that they can reach local customers, offering them
an attractive combination of local, long-distance, Internet and
wireless services. Then the act invites Bell to offer the same
services so that customers would get a battle for their business.
The commission's job is to ensure that Bell Atlantic does not use
its chokehold over its network to create problems for customers who
ask to switch to AT&AMP;T, MCI Worldcom or others.
</P>
<P>
   Under the heavy thumb of the New York Public Service Commission,
Bell Atlantic has taken tremendous strides over the past 18 months
or so to comply with the '96 act. The state authority even had an
independent company, KPMG Peat Marwick, create a fictitious
telephone company, placing orders to see if Bell Atlantic met its
demands for equipment rental. The state authority also kept track
of actual orders placed by MCI and others.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic made an excessive number of mistakes, even putting
a few customer phones out of order when it switched their wires. It
also fumbled too often when providing equipment for high-speed
Internet access and renting its entire network of switches and
wires to competitors. Despite these shortfalls _ each correctible
within a couple of months if not weeks _ the state authority
recommended to the FCC that it approve Bell Atlantic's application.
The Department of Justice, scrutinizing the state's data,
disagreed. Wednesday the commission waved Justice's objections
aside and settled for what Bell Atlantic had already achieved,
threatening stiff penalties if its performance deteriorates after
it gains entrance into long distance.
</P>
<P>
   Having acted prematurely, the commission faces two challenges.
The first is to carry out the threat to hammer Bell Atlantic with
fines if its actions prevent competitors from serving their
customers as well as Bell Atlantic serves its own. The second is to
make sure that every other application by a Bell company to enter
long distance is held to no lower standard than has been set for
Bell Atlantic in New York. If it does both, the commission might
still create the strong competition that Congress promised and
consumers expect.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
