<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-EGYPT-GAS-500&AMP;ADD-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL TO IMPORT NATURAL GAS FROM EGYPT 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Egypt will provide natural gas to Israel through a
long-delayed ``peace pipeline'' across the Sinai Desert, the prime
minister's office said Wednesday night, announcing a deal that will
radically change Israel's energy policy and its economic
relationship with its most powerful neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   Gas should be flowing to Israel within two years, a spokesman
for Prime Minister Ehud Barak said, though pricing and other
details must still be negotiated by the Israeli and Egyptian
companies directly handling the transaction.
</P>
<P>
   For Israel, which has never relied on a Middle Eastern energy
supplier, the Egyptian gas deal represents a profound strategic and
psychological shift.
</P>
<P>
   And for Egypt, a pipeline from the Nile Delta to Israel's
Mediterranean coast represents a significant thawing of what has
been termed the ``cold peace'' with its Jewish neighbor. Two
decades after the signing of their landmark Camp David peace pact,
Egypt and Israel have maintained a frigid diplomatic distance, and
only minimal economic ties.
</P>
<P>
   Egypt's approval of the gas deal is clearly intended as a reward
for what it sees as Barak's serious peacemaking efforts in the
region.
</P>
<P>
   By some industry estimates, gas exports to Israel through the
new pipeline could reach 4 billion cubic meters yearly, a deal
worth billions over the pipeline's lifetime. The deal would foster
unprecedented interdependence: Egypt would become Israel's most
important energy supplier, and Israel would become a major source
of Egyptian export earnings.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The announcement Wednesday also constitutes a business triumph
for the Italian-Egyptian consortium that began building the
pipeline last year, when a bilateral sales pact appeared far from
certain. Officially, the 150-mile pipeline was destined only for El
Arish, a Sinai beach town 30 miles from Israel. A spur line from El
Arish to a small new power plant in the Gaza Strip was discussed
with the Palestinian Authority.
</P>
<P>
   But ENI-Agip, the Italian oil and gas company financing the
pipeline, had acknowledged that its real goal was to supply gas to
Israel _ and, later, via undersea pipeline up the eastern
Mediterranean shore, to Lebanon, Syria, and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Out-pumping Shell, British Gas, and BP-Amoco, ENI-Agip has
become the largest foreign developer of Egypt's gas fields, which
produce 2.3 billion cubic feet a day. Its Sinai pipeline venture is
a partnership with the state-owned Egyptian General Petroleum Corp.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Israel has always been wholly dependent on imported fuel, buying
oil from Norway, Mexico and other distant non-OPEC suppliers, and
shipping in coal for power plants from Colombia, South Africa and
Australia. For most of its independent life, Israel was prevented
by boycotts from buying oil or gas from its Arab neighbors. But
even as Egypt and some Persian Gulf exporters tentatively expressed
a willingness to sell, some Israeli political leaders and military
strategists argued that Israel should continue to rely only on
suppliers far removed from the enmities of the Middle East.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   State power company officials in Israel had long favored
importing Egyptian gas, a cheaper and cleaner alternative to their
present imports. A national energy plan stated that Israel should
aim to produce a quarter of its electricity with natural gas by
2005. But diplomatic friction intervened. Breaking the impasse,
Barak discussed the project ``extensively'' with Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak earlier this year, expressing Israel's desire to
purchase the gas, the prime minister's office said Wednesday
evening.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday morning, in a meeting in the parliament building here,
the Egyptian ambassador to Israel notified Barak that his
government had formally approved the sale of gas to Israel. Barak's
response _ that Israel is equally willing to buy _ was certain to
be welcomed by industrialists and environmentalists but criticized
by the right-wing opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Mubarak had refused to authorize gas sales to the previous
Israeli government of Benjamin Netanyahu. Angering Netanyahu, the
Egyptian leader openly linked the gas deal to progress in peace
talks with the Palestinians. In response, the Netanyahu government
suggested that such political considerations could make Egypt an
unreliable long-term supplier, even if Egypt were willing to
proceed with the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Ariel Sharon, now the leader of the right-wing opposition, led
resistance in the last government to Egyptian natural gas imports.
He vigorously argued in favor of costly but in his view safer
alternatives, such as liquefied natural gas terminals and undersea
pipelines from Turkey or Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Despite opposition skepticism, the gas import deal could be a
prelude to further energy cooperation with Egypt, analysts believe.
Jordan and Egypt recently connected their electricity networks with
a cable under the Red Sea. Israel and the Palestinian Authority are
now expected to discuss linking their interconnected power grids
with the two neighboring countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
