<DOCNO> NYT19991222.0460 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 22:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7091 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-N.Y.-SENATE-NYT &LR;      12-22 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-N.Y.-SENATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: 'TIS THE SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, Dec. 22:
</P>
<P>
   What is it about this Christmas that is driving New York's
political leaders into a frenzy of vilification? The answer is that
two strong candidates for Senate are preparing for a titanic
struggle with a level of bitterness already at full boil. On
Wednesday Mayor Rudolph Giuliani asserted that the Democrats were
conspiring to get him, while Hillary Rodham Clinton declared that
the mayor lacked the temperament to serve in the Senate.
Specifically, Giuliani sees politics in a decision by Andrew Cuomo,
secretary of housing and urban development, to seize control of a
federally funded homelessness program, as well as in a separate
grand jury investigation into City Hall's handling of building
inspections.
</P>
<P>
   As housing secretary, Cuomo has the right to ensure that federal
money is spent properly. But seizing control of a $60 million
program was an abrupt and extreme step. Since the secretary is a
booster of Mrs. Clinton's candidacy, the mayor was also within his
rights to see politics behind Cuomo's action. The mayor, on the
other hand, has little justification in criticizing the
investigation by the federal and local prosecutors in Brooklyn into
whether his former chief of staff, Bruce Teitelbaum, tried to help
politically connected developers in their disputes with the city's
Buildings Department.
</P>
<P>
   Under Giuliani, New York City has kept up a multifaceted
approach on homelessness, emphasizing mental health and drug
rehabilitation services as well as shelter. Lately, however, the
mayor has stirred a furor with a series of excessively harsh policy
initiatives, some of which are being challenged in court. At issue
in the dispute with Cuomo, however, is not the move to arrest
homeless people or force them out of shelters and possibly remove
their children if they refuse to work. Rather it is a federal court
ruling in November that the city had improperly withheld funds from
a group called Housing Works in retaliation for its rallies
attacking Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo says the court decision forced him to act to protect the
integrity of federal funding for homeless services. But the court
ruling dealt with only a small part of the $60 million, and City
Hall has said that it is prepared to finance Housing Works if its
appeals in court are rejected. It would have been better if Cuomo
had allowed the legal process to work. But now that he has acted,
he must follow through on his pledge to put the decision on
distributing federal money into the hands of a nonpolitical entity
in the city.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Brooklyn inquiry, it ill behooves Giuliani, a former
federal prosecutor, to charge politics in an effort to investigate
a matter that came to light when a building collapsed in Brooklyn
last month, killing one person. According to reports in The New
York Times, a former building commissioner has told prosecutors
that Teitelbaum, the mayor's former chief of staff and now the
director of his Senate campaign, pressured him to remove an
inspector who had had run-ins with politically connected developers
in Williamsburg. Such an allegation is serious and must be cleared
up by a pursuit of the facts. By attacking the prosecutors in this
fashion, Giuliani is imitating President and Mrs. Clinton's least
attractive political tactic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-22-99 2232EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
