<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 22:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7093 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-IOWA-1STLD-WRITE     12-22 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-IOWA-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE, IN IOWA, JABS AT BRADLEY OVER FARM PROBLEMS AND PRESCHOOL
FUNDING 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Updates with Gore's comments from farm forum, Bradley calling
Gore's preschool proposal a voucher program.) 
 (nk) 
 By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMES, Iowa _ Vice President Al Gore campaigned through central
Iowa on Wednesday and sparred at long distance with former Sen.
Bill Bradley over farm problems and pre-school education.
</P>
<P>
   Before speaking here at a forum sponsored by the Iowa Farmers
Union, Gore used half a dozen radio and television interviews to
complain that Bradley had declined to debate him over farm issues
here Wednesday or next month in Cedar Rapids. ``Senator Bradley has
refused to have a specific debate on farm policy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's spokesman, Eric Hauser, responded from West Orange,
N.J., that there were other forums where the two would appear
together. ``We'll be talking about agriculture a lot with Al Gore
in Iowa, and we look forward to it,'' Hauser said.
</P>
<P>
   Then Bradley, the former three-term senator from New Jersey,
said through his campaign staff: ``For seven years, the
Clinton/Gore administration has presided over a farm crisis of
historic proportions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've needed strong leadership for fundamental changes in our
farm programs, and the administration has not provided it.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Farmers Union forum, the vice president renewed his
criticism of Bradley's absence and promised that in a Gore
administration, farm policy would be ``explicitly directed at
saving the viability of family farms.'' Among other things, he
vowed that the Packers and Stockyards Act would be enforced to
prevent price discrimination by packers against small farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Much of his criticism was directed at the Freedom to Farm Act of
1996, passed by a Republican-controlled Congress but signed into
law by President Clinton. The vice president said it had an
inadequate safety net to protect farmers when prices slumped.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, the only presidential candidate who has not stopped
stumping for Christmas, began his campaign day Wednesday at 6 a.m.
at a Des Moines school by appearing at a ``town meeting''
sponsored, and briefly broadcast, by ABC's ``Good Morning
America.'' There he sketched a 10-year, $50 billion proposal for a
``universal preschool initiative that will make high quality
preschool available to every 3 year old in America and expand
coverage to 3-year olds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most learning takes place in the first few years of life,'' he
said, ``and if kids get off to a great start before they ever get
to kindergarten, the chances for them to succeed in life, to have
good jobs, to lead fulfilling lives, is greatly enhanced.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the Gore proposal, federal matching grants to states would
allow 4-year-olds greater access to preschool. With some parents
sure not to take advantage of the opportunity, he said, the
leftover funds could be used for programs for 3-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   The Bradley campaign promptly criticized the proposal as
delivering less than it promised. Based on a Gore campaign estimate
that 75 percent of 4-year-olds would be enrolled, it noted that 64
percent now were in preschool. ``Al Gore,'' the Bradley campaign
said, ``would spend $50 billion to enroll an additional 11 percent
of the nation's 4-year-olds in preschool.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bradley campaign also described the approach envisioned by
Gore as a voucher program, since it would allow parents to use
public money to place their children in private-school programs.
Bradley aides suggested that the vice president was being
hypocritical, because he has criticized Bradley for having
supported an experimental school voucher program when he was a
senator.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore's campaign said that what he proposed was different
from a voucher system, because it would give money not to
individual families but to the states, which would run the program.
</P>
<P>
   The sniping proceeded. Gore spokesman Chris Lehane issued a
statement saying Bradley was launching ``misleading attacks on
Gore's bold plan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Since Bradley has failed to offer a comprehensive education
plan and is running from his 18-year-record of supporting private
school vouchers and tax credits,'' the statement said, ``all his
campaign can do is divert and attack.''
</P>
<P>
   In a more general campaign appearance at a breakfast meeting
with Jewish supporters in Des Moines, Gore stressed his experience,
saying he knew how to ``keep the economy going,'' and said he had
maintained a 100 percent pro-Israel voting record in the House,
``compiled on the basis of inner instinct,'' despite having almost
no Jewish constituents to lobby him.
</P>
<P>
   He took credit for his 1991 vote to authorize President Bush to
make war on Iraq, a position Bradley, as senator, opposed. But for
Congress' voting to support the war, he said, Saddam Hussein
``would still be in Kuwait.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehane said that after Gore returned to Washington on Wednesday
night, the vice president would not campaign again until next year.
although he might issue some statements next week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
