<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 22:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7094 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-ART-1     12-22 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-ART-1STLEDE-WRITETHRU-535&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN TROOPS KILLED CIVILIANS IN CHECHEN TOWN, HUMAN RIGHTS GROUP
SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS 10th graf to CORRECT name of village from SLEPTSOVSKAYA to
ORDZHONIKIDZEVSKAYA. ) 
(ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ After interviewing refugees from the fighting in
Chechnya, an international human rights group said Wednesday that
Russian troops had pillaged a small village there this month and
killed 17 civilians.
</P>
<P>
   The group, Human Rights Watch, said it had conducted interviews
with 15 survivors and that the killings took place in the village
of Alkhan-Yurt, a settlement 10 miles southwest of the Chechen
capital, Grozny, which has been the scene of fierce fighting.
</P>
<P>
   The allegation has emerged as an important test of the Russian
military's credibility, its ability to maintain discipline in its
ranks and its concern for Chechnya's civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Russian military spokesmen have denied that the episode could
have taken place, even as an investigation by Russian authorities
appears to be under way.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of Human Rights Watch have been interviewing
Chechen civilians as they have fled to neighboring Ingushetia,
chronicling abuses by both Russian troops and Chechen rebels.
Residents from Alkhan-Yurt have told them that Russian soldiers
engaged in widespread looting, shooting anyone who tried to stop
them.
</P>
<P>
   Khamid Khazuyev, a local policeman, was one of the victims,
according to Rachel Denber, a deputy director of Human Rights Watch
who helped document the episode. Many of the town's residents had
given Khazuyev their possessions to look after. Russian soldiers on
an armored personnel carrier shot him dead on Dec. 4, raided his
house and burned the home, according to accounts provided to Human
Rights Watch by Khazuyev's wife and neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have interviewed 15 people from this town whose testimony
was credible and mutually confirming,'' Ms. Denber said. ``It has
given us a pretty clear picture of the atrocity that happened at
Alkhan-Yurt.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time that Chechnya's civilians have
complained of abuses on the part of the Russian military. During
the 1994-1996 war, Russian troops went on a rampage in the village
of Samashki, throwing grenades into cellars occupied by civilians.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Moscow asserts, it is determined to win over the
Chechen population by restoring basic services and opening schools
and to deprive the Islamic fighters of the popular support that
would make it easier for them to wage a prolonged guerrilla war.
</P>
<P>
   When there have been abuses, the Russians have sometimes made a
show of punishing the culprits. Russian authorities arrested a
group of soldiers who drove their armored personnel carrier into
the market at Ordzhonikidzevskaya in Ingushetia and killed a young
woman who refused to sell them vodka.
</P>
<P>
   The case of Alkhan-Yurt, however, has produced a somewhat
muddled response from Russian authorities. A Russian spokesman
threatened to sue Human Rights Watch for defaming the Russian
military, though the organization says it has been told a military
inquiry is under way.
</P>
<P>
   ``The actions of the Russian troops, including Interior Ministry
troops, are under the strict control of the military prosecutor's
office,'' said Alexander Mikhailov, a senior official at the
Russian government agency that organizes news coverage of the war.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The trouble in Alkhan-Yurt began after it was occupied by a
group of Islamic militants, including Chechen and Middle Eastern
fighters. Hoping to avoid a Russian attack on their settlement,
village elders sought to persuade the rebels to leave. They also
appealed to Gen. Vladimir Shamanov, the commander of the Western
Group of Forces, which had surrounded the town.
</P>
<P>
   But the militants threatened the villagers and insisted on
staying. Soon the town turned into a battleground. Russian forces
pummeled the town with artillery and then fought the militants for
control of the destroyed village.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers finally entered the village on Dec. 1 and appeared
to believe that the losses they had sustained in taking the town
gave them the right to loot it. The soldiers were ``kontraktniki,''
volunteers who join the Russian military for pay, residents say.
</P>
<P>
   The rampage continued for two weeks, but the villagers who fled
say the first five days were the worst. According to accounts by
Human Rights Watch, the Russian soldiers threw grenades into
civilian shelters and summarily executed villagers.
</P>
<P>
   Hanpasha Dudayev, 60, was one of the first to be killed. He was
shot when he tried to stop Russian troops from raiding his home in
what human rights workers said was a grisly pattern.
</P>
<P>
   At first, the Russian troops sought to prevent the villagers
from leaving. But three later bribed their way out and made their
way to Ingushetia, where talk about Alkhan-Yurt began to surface.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, Malak Sidulayev, a millionaire Chechen
businessmen who comes from the town and supports the Russians in
the war, has sought to publicize the abuses. He arranged a visit by
the British Broadcasting Corp., which has asserted that more than
40 Chechens were killed by Russian troops.
</P>
<P>
   Sidulayev and Human Rights Watch say they believe that the
Russian military is investigating the episode. Human Rights Watch
has urged the United Nations to appoint an independent commission
to investigate human rights violations by Russian forces in
Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand that the military is now investigating what
happened, but it is imperative that international agencies also be
part of the investigation,'' Ms. Denber said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
