<HEADER>
A7102 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-HOLIDAY-MOOD-NYT &LR;      12-22 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HOLIDAY-MOOD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTMASTIME MANHATTAN, ALWAYS FRENZIED, GOES MOONSTRUCK
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By GLENN COLLINS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In this, the last holiday aria of the century, New
York is a town of signs and portents. It's a pre-millennial
menagerie, a sideshow city, a place of small curiosities and large
paradoxes.
</P>
<P>
   Regard the handwritten signs posted Wednesday in Forbidden
Planet, the science-fiction comic-book emporium on East 13th
Street. Decorated with cheery plastic holly and red ribbons, they
proclaimed a message to the future: ``Merry Christmas from the 20th
century.''
</P>
<P>
   But merry Christmas to whom? Consider the conservatively dressed
gentleman in the silk tie and black cashmere overcoat who
tirelessly roamed midtown Manhattan in recent days. Like a prophet
of doom, he bewildered tourists with his messages of millennial
wrath.
</P>
<P>
   Call it the moonstruck Christmas _ celebrated under the
brightest, closest moon of the year _ or call it fin-de-siecle
lunacy. Whatever. The fact is that Susie Gaeta, a full-time
professional dog walker for Lee's Pet Care, finally succumbed to
the urge to dress her dogs in Santa suits this week. Strutting in
Midtown, Minnie the Italian greyhound, Amelia the Irish setter mix,
Zachary the Wheaton terrier and Remi the short-haired pointer _ all
of them drew oohs and aahs from adoring crowds at the apparition of
their red-and-white caps and coats (with black buttons, of course).
They had attained the status of seasonal wonder.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the greatest oddity of this week was the New York
Paradox: In certain places, at certain times, the city had an eerie
emptiness, revealing the defection of office workers who had
already taken that early holiday slide. But elsewhere? Let's just
say it took about an ice age for shivering skaters to traverse the
overflowing lines at the Rockefeller Plaza rink.
</P>
<P>
   ``Though some office workers are on vacation, there are many
more tourists driving into Manhattan,'' said Inspector James
Hegarty, commander of the Traffic Control Division. The net effect,
he explained, is that ``the week before Christmas is the busiest of
the year.''
</P>
<P>
   How busy? Even the clerks and secretaries in the division have
been directed out into the streets for enforcement duty in recent
days, Hegarty said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet on Wall Street, so many people have been taking
pre-Christmas days off that at odd times the cathedral-ish spaces
of the World Financial Center have been strangely quiet, though
incongruously a-riot with golden cascades of Christmas lights.
</P>
<P>
   Tanya Kolenko and her 67-year-old father-in-law, Anatoly, were
taking a breather there in splendid isolation on a quiet bench
under a titanic palm tree. They had logged just about enough
wonders for a while, thank you. ``I'm taking him sightseeing, and
this place is really a sight,'' she said. Kolenko, who lives in
Chisinau in Moldova, is spending the week visiting his son's family
in Bensonhurst.
</P>
<P>
   Across West Street, Tom Costanzo, an engineer for the Port
Authority, waited at the America's Coffee shop outside One World
Trade Center while his favorite barista, Peter Harris, barista-ized
his coffee. Harris allowed that he didn't mind holiday vacation
absences all that much. ``It's a great opportunity,'' Costanzo
said, ``when the phones stop ringing. You can really catch up on
your work.''
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, for the first time this year customers ``want
silver and gold trim on their wreaths and flower arrangements,''
said Thomas Barbagianis, an owner of Ariston Florist on Fifth
Avenue at 14th Street, ``probably because everyone hopes to get
rich in the millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   If the city trembled with terrorist jitters or Y2K paranoia, all
of that seemed to be repressed in a frenzy of shop-till-you-drop
acquisitiveness. Lorenzo Gori-Montanelli, a photographer who lives
in Lower Manhattan, did brisk business at his Curbstone Inc. stall
in the Union Square flea market selling his original photographs of
fire hydrants, manhole covers and wooden water towers. He had
transformed them into refrigerator magnets, T-shirts and clocks.
``It's a tricky way to get people to buy your photography,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   At times, lines at the Saks Fifth Avenue and Macy's store
windows were longer than ever, but conditions were sort of chancy
outside the stores this season as they were everywhere else. The
trip into the big town was nothing less than ``our big American
extravaganza,'' said Sarah Ahlgrim, who had driven from Westport,
Conn., with her three children and her 68-year-old father, Jim
Conduit. He was visiting from his home in Nottingham, England.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this place is a zoo now, what would you call it at the
millennium?'' asked Chuck Re, who was strolling nearby at
Rockefeller Plaza, holding hands with his wife, Judi. Re, a
storage-company manager from Southbury, Conn., had hoisted his
2-year-old daughter, Maggie Murphy Re, to his shoulders. The family
was ``doing the Music Hall, doing Macy's, doing Schwarz's,'' he
explained, referring to F.A.O.
</P>
<P>
   Everywhere, holiday spells had transformed the mundane.
Wednesday, World Financial Center workers who rushed to the
mainland over the no man's land of West Street on the enclosed
pedestrian bridge were in actuality traversing the Holiday Bridge
Market. The collection of more than a dozen temporary stores formed
``Santa's Winter Wonderland,'' the signs announced.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, while New York puzzled over the signs and portents
of all that is new, the city seemed to find comfort in much that is
old. People flocked to the traditional, to the tried-and-true, to
St. Patrick's Cathedral, to Saks Fifth Avenue, to the twin towers.
And of course, they swarmed to Gage &AMP; Tollner, a restaurant on
Fulton Street in Brooklyn, which is 120 years old ``and now
celebrating the turn of the century for the second time,'' said
Nato Giordano, the general manager.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night at 6 _ just as it will be done Thursday night
and just as it was done on the last Christmas of the last century _
a waiter held high a glowing wax candle wick. Methodically, he
lighted the 36 brass gas lamps in the venerable dining room.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a calming thing,'' Giordano said, gazing at the lamps as
they imparted a soft glow to the wreaths about the dining room.
``People are more stressed out this year than I can remember,'' he
said. ``Then they step through those revolving doors, and they're
in this whole other world. I think they can't wait until all this
is over.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
