</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-RAPTORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EWING COMES THROUGH AS KNICKS EDGE RAPTORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ He had not taken a shot in the fourth quarter and for
all of 47 minutes stood in the background like an old sofa. Patrick
Ewing was comfortable and still usable, but no longer the focal
point of this plush, new living room. With 21.3 seconds left and
the game against the Raptors tied, the Knicks seemed
discombobulated on offense when Larry Johnson dumped the ball
inside to the aging warrior.
</P>
<P>
   But with the shot clock about to expire, Ewing turned around on
Antonio Davis and released a soft, fall-away jump shot a few inches
right of the free-throw line. It rattled in, Madison Square Garden
rose and roared, and suddenly all of Vince Carter's scintillating
vertical leap and Latrell Sprewell's scoring savvy mattered little.
</P>
<P>
   In the last game of the century inside Madison Square Garden,
the old man delivered a 91-90 victory over the Toronto Raptors.
Despite some shaky free-throwing shooting in the final seconds from
Sprewell, the Knicks managed to survive and record their seventh
victory in the last eight games.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell was awesome for 10 minutes of the second half, ending
with 25 points to lead New York. And Allan Houston was his reliable
self from the perimeter for most of the night, chipping in 18
points. But Ewing (eight points, eight rebounds) brought the Knicks
home after a wild Toronto comeback from 15 points down in the final
eight minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Carter, the brilliant rookie, threw down five dunks and led
everyone with 36 points. He made 13 of 25 shots, none bigger than a
rainbow jumper with 40.7 seconds left. Coming off a screen from
Davis, his right foot slightly kicked up like, yes, Michael Jordan,
Carter tied the game at 86-86 with that shot.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks came down on offense with no cohesion. Johnson had
the ball at the top of the key and kept motioning for Sprewell to
go down in the post to start the play. But Sprewell stood there on
the perimeter, unsure of where to go. Sensing doom, Johnson tried
to dribble out of trouble before finding Ewing, who essentially
brought an end to a regular-season keepsake.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell went to the line with 2.3 seconds left and New York
nursing only a one-point lead. Having missed one free throw
already, he missed the first and, it seemed, purposely missed the
second free throw. Doug Christie's off-balance half-court, runner
from the right side then barely grazed the rim as the Knicks
escaped.
</P>
<P>
   New York had an 82-67 lead with 8:34 left, but Toronto made it a
game, going on a 15-2 run that trimmed the lead to just 84-82 with
2:11 left. Carter scored the last four points of the run as the
Knicks collapsed on offense and rotated badly on defense.
</P>
<P>
   Before then, it was all Sprewell.
</P>
<P>
   In a burst somewhat reminiscent of his Game 5 explosion in the
playoff finals last June, Sprewell scored 12 straight points at the
end of the third quarter and the outset of the fourth to help the
Knicks pull away. Losing his man by dribbling hard and driving to
either side, he would stop and pull up for medium-range jump shots
that fell softly through the net, his right arm held high,
following each shot through the rim.
</P>
<P>
   He was feeling it, and there was nothing the Raptors could do to
simmer him down.
</P>
<P>
   For the second straight game, Van Gundy elected to go with a
bigger lineup featuring Houston and Sprewell in the backcourt,
Marcus Camby alongside Johnson and Ewing on the frontline and
Charlie Ward on the bench to start the game.
</P>
<P>
   The move paid dividends in overtime against the Charlotte
Hornets on Monday night, and the Knicks parlayed that performance
into an even more convincing effort for most of the evening
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   They still had to contend with Carter, the most breathtaking
player in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   So explosive around the basket, the muscular 6-foot-6-inch
forward resembled a young Dominique Wilkens in the first half. He
wowed the Garden early, catching what appeared to be an errant
alley-oop pass from Doug Christie somewhere near the rafters. He
caught the ball at its apex before throwing it down hard with his
right hand.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, he caught a pass on the right block, took one
power dribble underneath the basket and slammed the ball through as
Sprewell fouled him. He was not only too quick and athletic; at 22
years old he was also too strong.
</P>
<P>
   When he wasn't dunking, Carter was depositing long jumps shots
with regularity. He had 18 points at intermission, hitting 7 of 11
shots over whatever helpless Knicks defender was assigned to guard
him. At times, though, he became such a focal point of Toronto's
offense that the other Raptors scorers, including Tracy McGrady and
Christie, were reduced to minor roles.
</P>
<P>
   Even with Sprewell's second-half binge, other Knicks contributed
and blended in seamlessly. Toronto has the amazing player. For now,
New York still has the better team.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
