<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-FLYERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELIAS SCORES TWO GOALS AS DEVILS WIN BY ONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The Devils and the Flyers, the strongest
teams in the Atlantic Division as the season nears its midway
point, met for the third time Wednesday night and the Devils got
the upper hand with a 3-2 victory.
</P>
<P>
   But even though this was a game between two of the league's best
teams and longtime divisional rivals, there were still 1,000 empty
seats at Continental Arena, which has yet to see a sellout after 19
games this season. The Devils failed to sellout even a game against
the Rangers on Dec. 1.
</P>
<P>
   A large contingent in the crowd of 18,098 Wednesday cheered for
the visitors, but everyone in the building cheered for Coach Roger
Neilson of the Flyers, who is undergoing chemotherapy for bone
cancer and will have a bone marrow transplant late in February.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils posted their second victory of the season over the
Flyers (19-11-5), who lead the division with 44 points, 1 more than
the Devils (19-11-3).
</P>
<P>
   Patrik Elias' second goal of the game, on a power play 7 minutes
30 seconds into the third period, broke a 2-2 tie as the Devils
bounced back after they lost to the Islanders Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Elias opened the scoring with 5:36 left before the first
intermission when he picked up the puck off the left boards and
beat John Vanbiesbrouck from close range. It was his fifth goal of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Arnott gave the Devils a two-goal lead 6:03 into the
middle period. He sneaked behind the Flyers' defense on the left
and converted a pass from Elias. The goal was Arnott's ninth of the
season and came during the first manpower advantage for the Devils.
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers, who came into the game as the league's most
efficient team on the power play, failed on their first advantage,
which lasted only 43 seconds. But they capitalized on their second
one, only 20 seconds after it started.
</P>
<P>
   John LeClair scored the goal, his 19th, as he swatted the puck
out of the air after a shot by Eric Desjardins with 6:10 left in
the period.
</P>
<P>
   It got worse for the Devils. Keith Jones tied the game 30
seconds later, when he scored on a rebound from a shot by LeClair
and scored his third goal of the season. It sent the teams into the
second intermission tied at 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   On a night of emotion for the ailing Flyers' coach, the first
truly warm moment came in the sixth minute of the game, when
Neilson was greeted with a standing ovation after he appeared on
the scoreboard screen standing behind the Flyers' bench during a
break. A graphic on the scoreboard read ``Good Luck, Roger. Our
Thoughts &AMP; Prayers Are With You.''
</P>
<P>
   Neilson waved to the crowd in appreciation. Before the game,
standing against the wall outside the Flyers' dressing room, the
67-year-old coach said he was touched by the outpouring of support
from people in hockey.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hockey community is a little closer than most sports,''
Neilson said. ``I've heard from a couple of players and coaches
from every team. Even from referees.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Wednesday night's referees, Paul Stewart, who was treated
for colon cancer last year, held a cordial conversation with
Neilson before the game. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
