<SLUG> BC-Y2K-SITE-CLOSED-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILMMAKER SAYS U.S. SUPPRESSED HIS WORK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Mich.)  (js) 
 By C.J. CHIVERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Last summer, as he contemplated the news media's
coverage of plans for New Year's Eve, Michael Zieper, an
independent film maker, conceived a script that would explore the
themes of distrust for the government and public anxiety over the
new century. What if, he wondered, the U.S. Army were to incite an
enormous race riot at the stroke of midnight on Dec. 31, as the
streets become darkened by computer-related power failures? What if
it were to happen in Times Square?
</P>
<P>
   Zieper's musings became the subject of ``Military Takeover of
New York City,'' a six-minute film he produced and posted on the
Internet in October. Wednesday, the authorities' response to the
film became the subject of a federal lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Acting on behalf of Zieper, 39, and Mark Wieger, 38, an
independent Web site operator, the American Civil Liberties Union
filed a suit claiming that the FBI and the U.S. attorney's office
in New York used coercion to suppress the film, which was made as
if it were a secret military training tape of ways to provoke a
Midtown riot.
</P>
<P>
   According to the suit, an FBI special agent and an assistant U.
S. attorney pressured Wieger to block access to the movie's Web
address, which is http://www.crowdedtheater.com, telling him by
telephone in November that they did not want any more people
viewing it and that his business could suffer if he did not comply
with their wishes.
</P>
<P>
   Wieger at first agreed to the request, deleting the film from
the Web on Nov. 15. But about 10 days later, after being inundated
with complaints from Internet users, he restored the movie to his
server, where it remains available for viewing, albeit with a new
link Zieper designed to explain that it is fiction. Zieper, who
lives in New Jersey, and Wieger, who lives in Michigan, said that
the government had not inquired further about the movie since it
was restored to the Web.
</P>
<P>
   The suit claims that the FBI and the U.S. attorney's office
violated Zieper's and Wieger's rights to due process and free
speech by pressuring them to restrict access to the film without
any court review of the film's contents. It seeks unspecified
monetary damages, lawyers' fees and a court declaration that
``Military Takeover of New York'' is constitutionally protected.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make it very clear today that we applaud the FBI's
effort to fight real threats of terrorism, including those that
surround the millennium,'' said Ann Beeson, a lawyer with the Civil
Liberties Union. ``But censoring artists is certainly not the way
to make people safe this New Year's Eve.''
</P>
<P>
   Both the FBI and the U.S. attorney's office declined to comment.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Military Takeover of New York City'' has only one character:
an Army officer whose face is never seen. He is merely a voice
talking over a tape of Times Square traffic, telling his soldiers _
Cracker, Raven, Hobo and Boyzen _ what their missions will be on
New Year's Eve. The officer's plan is simple. A woman will falsely
claim that she was raped. Soldiers in civilian clothes will
circulate through the crowd and spread rumors and fear. And as
computer glitches cause power failures and confusion, the crowd's
unease will erupt in violence and chaos, forcing the military to
``sweep and clear'' Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is how it all goes down; I'm going to walk you through
it,'' the officer says, and then he does, giving each of his team
members instructions in blunt, sometimes profanity-laced language.
</P>
<P>
   Zieper and the ACLU say that the film is meant to provoke
serious discussion of serious issues: the public's concerns about
millennium-related problems, the depth of the nation's racial
problems and distrust for the government. And they say the film was
made in the spirit of Orson Welles' ``War of the Worlds,'' a 1938
radio drama about an alien invasion that some listeners mistook for
a newscast.
</P>
<P>
   Emily Whitfield, a Civil Liberties Union spokeswoman, said the
government had overreacted. ``It's akin to them hearing about `The
Blair Witch Project' and running off into the woods to hunt down
the witch,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
