<HEADLINE>
SITES CHALLENGE, BUT DON'T NECESSARILY TOP BCS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOMMY CUMMINGS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Someone is either defending the process or they're looking for
an alternative to the Bowl Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   And if you're looking for a good argument about the computer
system that determines college football's top two teams, try
cyberspace. Scores of amateur Webmasters have set up sites touting
their own rankings or power-rating formulas, and they all put in
their 2 cents on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Billingsley of Nashville, Tenn., who updates his
rankings weekly on the College Football Resource Center (cfrc.com),
said the idea of incorporating computers into the football
championship picture works for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I also recognize that very few computer formulas actually
reflect a purely objective poll,'' Billingsley said. ``A program is
only as good as the programmer.''
</P>
<P>
   Billingsley said the BCS rankings is a nice balance between
polls subjective to emotional and personal input, such as The
Associated Press and the USA Today/ESPN Coaches' Poll, and those
that are objective, such as the computer polls.
</P>
<P>
   But ``I would be absolutely against using only computers to
determine the championship game,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Palm, a systems bank analyst in Chicago who operates his
own rankings at CollegeRPI.com, ``prefers'' using computers and a
formula to determine playoff teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each of these computer rankings is essentially one man's
opinion,'' he said. ``I think it helps to have some statistical
measure of teams to use at least as a guideline, and the more
opinions, the merrier.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Massey, a Virginia Tech graduate student in Vicksburg,
Va., who ranks teams on his Massey's Ratings and Rankings site
(www.mratings.com), has an interesting spin on the matter. It's one
that, if used by the BCS, would have taken Virginia Tech out of the
Nokia Sugar Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Massey said he'd like to see the BCS ratings used as a guide
rather than the rule. A final decision could be vetoed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This might answer some concerns of a cold, hard math formula
in a game full of emotions and circumstances that don't show up in
the numbers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It's not all amateurs who have their eye on determining playoff
finalists. ISL United States, a marketing group in Norwalk, Ct.,
launched College Football Playoff 2000 (collegefootballplayoff.com)
to solicit support for a $3 billion playoff proposal. Fans can
voice their support with e-mail postcards directed at Division I-A
university presidents.
</P>
<P>
   Fans who support the official line can access the Bowl
Championship Series official site (abccfb.go.com), which is
operated by ABC Sports Online. The site has interactive and
multimedia features and updates.
</P>
<P>
   The unofficial word, of course, is all over the 'Net. David
Wilson of Madison, Wis., recognized the varying opinions and
created a portal (www.cae.wisc.edu/(tilde)dwilson/rsfc/rate).
</P>
<P>
   Massey said he recognizes the healthy debate caused by the BSC.
</P>
<P>
   ``While there may be room for some improvement, the BSC has
worked successfully in its two years of existence,'' he said. ``And
it has been a great topic of discussion for college football
fans.''
</P>
<P>
   BOWL SITES
</P>
<P>
   The five best:
</P>
<P>
   Sugar (www.nokiasugarbowl.com): Have all your plug-ins because
this one glows and pulsates. Don't miss the Trivia Blitz.
</P>
<P>
   Cotton (www.cottonbowl.org): Word puzzle in Fun and Games
section is tough. Don't miss the Video Vault section.
</P>
<P>
   Holiday (www.sandiegoinsider.com/partners/holidaybowl): Plenty
of interactivity.
</P>
<P>
   Fiesta (www.accessarizona.com/partners/fiestabowl): Don't miss
360-degree tour of Sun Devil Stadium on this busy site.
</P>
<P>
   Alamo (www.alamobowl.com): Lots of historical content and links
to other sports sites. The five worst:
</P>
<P>
   Rose (www.tournamentofroses.com): Granddaddy of them all hasn't
mastered cyberspace yet. Everything you wanted to know about
Pasadena, Calif., though.
</P>
<P>
   Mobile Alabama (www.mobilealbowl.com): Nothing but a bunch of
news releases.
</P>
<P>
   Humanitarian (www.humanitarianbowl.org): It's in Boise, Idaho,
for Pete's sake.
</P>
<P>
   Insight.com (www.insight.com): It is two clicks from main page,
but it doesn't have the bells and whistles one would expect.
</P>
<P>
   Citrus (www.fcsports.com): Dazzling opening page, but not much
else on the game except links to the participants' official sites.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
