<SLUG> BC-FBC-WILLINGHAM-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT WAS DESTINY FOR WILLINGHAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SANTA MONICA _ Win or lose Jan. 1, Stanford head coach Tyrone
Willingham stands shoulder-to-shoulder with greatness.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the only other Cardinal coaches who have won the
conference and earned a Rose Bowl berth are legends named Pop
Warner, Clark Shaughnessy, Chuck Taylor and John Ralston. It's
something that even Bill ``the Genius'' Walsh never accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   As the 20th Century draws to a close, Willingham will forever be
remembered as the first coach of African-American descent to coach
a team in the ``Granddaddy of them All.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it carries some significance,'' Willingham said.
``It's not as important to me as it is to some others . . . I'm
just saddened that it's coming at this time and not a lot sooner.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, perhaps it was Willingham's destiny.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Jacksonville, N.C., Willingham, who turns 46 next
week, earned his degree in physical education from Michigan State
University in 1977. He also earned three letters there in both
football and baseball as a walk-on.
</P>
<P>
   As the Spartans' quarterback, Willingham was named the team's
most inspirational player in 1976. The next year he was awarded the
Big Ten Medal of Honor as the outstanding Scholar-Athlete in the
conference. In baseball he received the Sportsmanship Award in 1975
and was an All-Big Ten selection in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   From there Willingham went on to coaching assignments at Central
Michigan, Michigan State, North Carolina State, Rice University,
Stanford and the Minnesota Vikings before taking the head coaching
job at Stanford in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Willingham led the Cardinal to the Liberty Bowl in 1995 and the
Sun Bowl in 1996. Doing so made him just the third coach in
Stanford history to lead the team to consecutive bowl games in his
first two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But Willingham cautions those who would look to him as a hero or
desire to follow in his footsteps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that no kid looks at me and says he wants to be like
me,'' Willingham said. ``I hope that that kid's eyes are set on
being better than coach Willingham. He should say, `I want to be
better, not just the same as coach Willingham.' ''
</P>
<P>
   That said, Willingham does admit there are those who had a big
influence on his career. His role models include his mother and
father as well as Dennis Green, head coach of the Minnesota Vikings
and a former head coach at Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without a question, my mother and father have been my greatest
role models,'' Willingham said. ``I must include Dennis Green as
one of my influences. I spent six years coaching with Denny and
enjoyed his philosophy and could see the vision he had, not only
for himself but for the young men in his program.''
</P>
<P>
   Watching Willingham coach his team at Santa Monica College, it's
hard to imagine the soft-spoken guy with the polo shirt, khaki
shorts and perfectly fit Stanford cap has a reputation as a
disciplinarian.
</P>
<P>
   Then he takes the whistle dangling around his neck on a thick
cord that says ``Stanford'' and blows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the description of being a disciplinarian is true,''
Willingham admits. ``But, more importantly ... it has to be timely
... I think I have to be tough in some cases and a grandfather in
other cases.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever he is, Willingham, whose record at Stanford is 30-26-1,
is revered by his players and those who know him.
</P>
<P>
   He took a team that was 3-7-1 in 1994 and turned it into a 7-4-1
bowl team in 1995. In 1996, the team went 7-5 overall beating
Michigan State 38-0 in the Sun Bowl. In 1997, the
Willingham-coached Cardinal finished 5-6. Last year they were a
disappointing 3-8, but the turnaround has earned Willingham several
admirers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like Tyrone a whole lot,'' said former Cardinal quarterback
Jim Plunkett, who led the team to the 1971 Rose Bowl. ``I'm glad to
see him doing so well and winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Troy Walters, who was offered a scholarship to
Stanford by Willingham when every other Division I-A school had
turned him down, was just as kind.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's probably the best coach I've ever had,'' Walters said.
``He's right up there with the great ones.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
