<HEADLINE>
MENIAL TASKS DEMEANING? NOT EVERYBODY SEES IT THAT WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Whaddya wanna do? Flip burgers yer whole
life?
</P>
<P>
   Flipping burgers is the cliche of the moment. We use it to mean
a low-wage, low-skill, limited-future job. We assume the listener
will say, ``No way, man,'' and be imbued with ambition and
career-climbing goals.
</P>
<P>
   Beware of that assumption.
</P>
<P>
   Last week I visited two sheltered workshops where four workers
were each honored for completing 30 years of simple assembly and
piecework _ with nearly perfect attendance records.
</P>
<P>
   On the day I visited IBS Industries in Blue Springs, Dennis
Parish's work consisted of putting two clear plastic vials and two
white plastic caps in a small clear plastic bag and putting the
assembled bag in a box with others. Then doing it again and again
and again.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, do you still like coming to work after all these years?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not?'' Dennis responded, with an economy of words but an
expression that spoke volumes.
</P>
<P>
   After a short time with him and his best friend and co-worker,
Butch Baker, it was easy to interpret his ``Why not?''
</P>
<P>
   What he said was: Why wouldn't I like coming here, where I joke
with my friends, where I'm complimented on a job well done, where
I'm rewarded for my efforts (even if it's just a fraction of the
minimum wage) and where I am a productive member of society who
adds value to my employer and to the companies with which it does
business?
</P>
<P>
   So, congratulations to Dennis Parish, Butch Baker, Marty Mann in
Blue Springs and Jimmy Campbell in Independence, and to their
fellow IBS workers who, whether they have 30 years on the job or
three, show diligence, a positive attitude and joy in their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't necessary, of course, to look to workers who have Down
syndrome to find examples of fulfillment at work. I have, over
several months, corresponded with a man who had been looking for
work, found temporary employment with the state of Missouri and
then re-entered the job market.
</P>
<P>
   A family at his church recognized he needed income and offered
him work in a Dairy Queen they own and operate in Cameron, Mo. Phil
Luebbert said he wrestled with himself but quickly ``made the
mental adjustment'' to be a burger flipper.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a blessing this job has turned into,'' Luebbert wrote.
``The little job here at Dairy Queen has intangible (psychological,
spiritual, moral) benefits which far outweigh what we usually think
of as job benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although this DQ pays less than half of what I earned at the
state, in many ways I have received more permanent, personal
benefits, such as faith in people, the existence of fairness, a
cheerful work environment...
</P>
<P>
   ``This job is so valuable, for I can weigh future jobs against
it (do they measure up?), and I have a renewed attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Luebbert thanks his DQ owners, Joe and Velma Seuferling, and
managers, Rita and Rodney Long, for that renewal.
</P>
<P>
   All the workers named in this column have found fulfillment at
work _ sometimes to the top of their abilities, sometimes only a
surface tap. That peace is a lovely gift.
</P>
<P>
   I hope you get it, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-22-99 2344EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991222.0476 </DOCNO>
