A7255 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-KANSAS-CUTS-KAN &LR;      12-22 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KANSAS-CUTS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNOR CALLS ON STATE LEGISLATORS TO QUICKLY ENDORSE CUTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN A. DVORAK  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOPEKA, Kan. _ Proposed reductions in the Kansas budget are
going deeper than expected, and Gov. Bill Graves called on state
legislators Wednesday to quickly endorse cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a pretty tight fiscal situation,'' Graves said. He
added that legislators needed to realize the severity of the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Putting off tough decisions, he warned, will lead only to more
uncertainty over state spending in 2000 and worse trouble in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Graves said his proposed reductions in the general tax money
state agencies spent would average 1.6 percent. That equals about
$70 million altogether. Several months ago Graves said he would
institute reductions of 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The budget pinch comes despite a healthy Kansas economy. Boom
times have slowed a bit, however. Also, legislators in the past _
with support from Graves _ approved big tax cuts without curtailing
spending.
</P>
<P>
   Money will be one of the thorniest issues when the 2000 session
of the Kansas Legislature begins Jan. 10.
</P>
<P>
   Graves, a Republican, refused Wednesday to specify the state
programs he wanted reduced. Aid to public schools, however,
represents a possible target for cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Increasing the reductions from 1 percent to 1.6 percent does not
indicate that budget problems have worsened, the governor said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we've gone through, on an agency-by-agency,
budget-by-budget review, we found places where we thought we could
shave more,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not all agencies will see their budgets lowered. ``We found
places where we needed to add money,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Leading members of the Senate and House reacted differently
after hearing Graves' request for fast decisions next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'll pull together,'' said Senate President Dick
Bond, an Overland Park Republican. ``If it isn't done early, then
it won't be done at all, and the budgetary process will be in
chaos.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor said he would like a budget reduction bill passed
by about Jan. 21, and Bond echoed the call.
</P>
<P>
   However, Rep. Bill Reardon of Kansas City urged caution.
</P>
<P>
   The amount of state tax revenue coming in for 2000 is not
certain yet, said Reardon, top Democrat on the House Budget
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might well be better off to wait,'' he said. Of the call
for fast action, Reardon said: ``It's being portrayed as good
government, but I'm not sure it is good government.''
</P>
<P>
   Reardon said he feared that programs strongly favored by
Democrats, such as aid to public schools, faced cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans outnumber Democrats in the Legislature. But
Republicans have feuded among themselves for several years. As a
result, Graves and his GOP allies do not always get their way.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. David Adkins, a Leawood Republican who is chairman of the
House Appropriations Committee, said he wanted legislators to pass
a budget bill quickly, maybe in just one week.
</P>
<P>
   But the House is not always predictable, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are factions in the House who might see this as an
opportunity to throw a wrench in the works,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the pressure will be interest groups that will lobby
hard in an attempt to avoid reductions in state programs they
favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would expect,'' Graves said, ``that every constituency that
is negatively affected will express their concerns.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
