<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-22 23:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7256 &Cx1f; kan-z
r w BC-FLIPFLOP-CONSEQUENCES     12-22 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLIPFLOP-CONSEQUENCES-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Politicians can't ignore flip-flops' potential fallout  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ 'Tis the season to be wary, as candidates on the
road to the White House engineer some sharp political U-turns that
may be detours from their past.
</P>
<P>
   Take Pat Buchanan, one of the more rigidly conservative
combatants ever to sport a lapel button. Seeking the presidential
nomination on the Reform ticket, he bolted the Republican Party,
where his roots go back three decades to Richard Nixon's
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan has welcomed the endorsement of longtime liberal
activist Lenora Fulani and said he would accept help from
homosexuals _ provided they lead scandal-free lives. This is the
same Pat Buchanan who delivered a fire-breathing speech against
liberalism at the 1992 GOP convention.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic hopeful Bill Bradley, meanwhile, embraced federal
subsidies for ethanol once he hit the campaign trail in Iowa.
Ethanol is a corn-based alternative fuel that potentially opens
another market for farmers. As a senator from New Jersey, Bradley
opposed such subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   The political flip-flop. It's a staple of the campaign season
and a time-honored tool to adjust to changing political
circumstances. But beware of the possible fallout.
</P>
<P>
   Former President George Bush learned that after reneging on his
``read my lips, no new taxes'' pledge in 1988. It came back to
haunt him in the 1992 campaign after he had supported a tax
increase as part of a budget deal with Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't help him any,'' said Ron Kaufman, a former political
director in the Bush White House. ``If a candidate is perceived to
be less than genuine or perceived to be hypocritical, it hurts.''
</P>
<P>
   Politicians should be allowed to change their positions, of
course, whether or not a campaign is on the horizon. Conditions
shift, and people are expected to adapt.
</P>
<P>
   The time frame, however, can be crucial. ``If someone changes
his view over 10 years, it's less damaging than if someone changes
over 10 days,'' said John Green, director of the Ray Bliss
Institute of Politics at Ohio's University of Akron.
</P>
<P>
   That was evident at a recent debate between the Republican
presidential candidates, when Texas Gov. George W. Bush thought he
had ensnared publisher Steve Forbes in his own words. Noting that
Forbes now opposes raising the eligibility age for Social Security
benefits, Bush unearthed a 1977 column in which Forbes had written
just the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   That was his opinion ``20-some-odd years ago when the system was
in crisis,'' Forbes countered, not now.
</P>
<P>
   In a more recent change of political emphasis, Forbes has been
outspoken against abortion, hoping to attract support from
religious conservatives. During his first presidential campaign
four years ago, however, Forbes avoided all talk on the subject,
saying only that he hoped abortion would ``vanish.''
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore has flip-flopped on tobacco. The
Democratic front-runner once touted his past as a tobacco farmer,
and he also has benefited from tobacco-industry contributions. But
at the 1996 Democratic convention, Gore gave a heartfelt speech
about the death from lung cancer of his sister, a longtime smoker.
</P>
<P>
   ``The impact his sister's death took awhile to really seep in
and what it meant about the impact of tobacco,'' Gore spokesman
Chris Lehane said. ``There is no one who has been a more outspoken
critic of the tobacco industry than Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign, meanwhile, has set its sights on Bradley's
political pivots. The two Democrats are in a dead heat as they
battle for votes in New Hampshire, scene of the first presidential
primary on Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has charged that Bradley has flip-flopped on school
vouchers because he supported some experimental programs while in
the Senate but now says he opposes them. Bradley's ``view is
vouchers are not the answer, but if they improve public education,
we'd be foolish to write something off that could help kids,''
Bradley campaign spokesman Eric Hauser said.
</P>
<P>
   There also is the switch on ethanol, to which Hauser readily
pleads ``guilty.'' But Hauser said that in running for president,
Bradley adopted a broader view because he saw that the subsidy
could help a state whose farm economy was in bad shape. Hauser also
said the benefits of the subsidy were no longer going to just a
single company, as they had previously.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians such as Bradley and Gore often are susceptible to
flip-flops because they have such long track records.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an accident that we rarely elect presidents from
Congress,'' said Will Marshall, president of the Progressive Policy
Institute, a centrist Democratic think tank. ``Members of Congress
are forced to take thousands of votes on myriad issues....A lot of
times, the meaning of them is misrepresented.''
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush, the GOP front-runner and son of the former
president, has not been in the public eye for very long, but the
Democratic National Committee says he has made a political
about-face or two.
</P>
<P>
   They accuse him of waffling on guns by supporting a bill
requiring background checks for weapons buyers at gun shows only
after the bill died in committee in the Texas Legislature. They
also charged that he refused to revive it.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Mindy Tucker said the background check bill
affected only storefront sales of guns, not sales at shows, so it
wouldn't have had any practical effect.
</P>
<P>
   Many voters already are so cynical about politics that one more
perceived flip-flop may hardly cause a wrinkle in the political
landscape. They've come to expect it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If candidates were more open when they're accused of changing
their positions, it wouldn't feed the cynicism,'' said Wayne
Fields, an expert in political rhetoric at Washington University in
St. Louis. ``Honesty works far better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
