<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SATURDAY-SCHOOL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARENTS REACT TO DISTRICT'S PLAN FOR SATURDAY CLASSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN HOFFMANN  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The reaction was mixed Wednesday to the
announcement that the Kansas City School District had selected more
than 2,000 students to attend Saturday classes to avoid being held
back a grade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would love for my son to go,'' said Latonya Thomaston, whose
fourth-grade son, Michael, was selected for the courses. ``If they
see he is behind in certain areas and they think it will help him
get his grades back up, I'm all for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomaston said she liked the fact that the district would
provide busing, because she lacked transportation. She said Michael
typically spent his Saturdays ``getting out of bed, eating
breakfast and then playing a game.'' She said he could skip a few
hours of video games if it would help him in math and reading.
</P>
<P>
   Several parents expressed similar thoughts about their children.
But others connected to the district were concerned.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton Adams, who has a daughter at Lincoln Prep High School,
said he was not opposed to the concept.
</P>
<P>
   ``What worries me is whether they are going to change the method
of instruction so that this extra day actually benefits the kids,''
Adams said. ``Simply adding another day of sitting at a desk won't
cut it.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams said he hoped that the district would attract only
top-quality teachers for the Saturday classes and that they would
find innovative ways to teach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a challenge for them because if these kids aren't
picking it up (in class) Monday through Friday, it's not going to
be any easier on Saturday,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   District officials sent out letters to teachers on Tuesday
explaining the program and asking for instructors. Officials had
not determined how many teachers would be willing to give up free
time on Saturdays. Teachers who signed up for the duty would be
paid extra.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Morgan, president of the local teachers union, could not be
reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Besides district teachers, school officials would use
paraprofessionals and volunteers to help instruct the youths. On
Wednesday three persons phoned The Star to ask how they could
volunteer their time for the Saturday classes.
</P>
<P>
   Because district officials were still working out details of the
program, it was unclear how much support staff, such as custodians,
security officers, administrators and secretaries, might be needed.
The district will provide free lunch and transportation to all
students who take the classes.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of the program also had not been determined, but state
funding was made available by the same legislation that allowed
districts to mandate Saturday school.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Sitze, director of the Missouri Student Improvement
Program, said the idea of Saturday school was not unique to the
Kansas City district.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been a lot of districts looking at this and saying,
`We've got kids that could use this' &UR; '' Sitze said. ``A number of
them are taking advantage of the legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   The law, enacted in August, states in part that ``no public
school student shall be promoted to a higher grade level unless
that student has a reading ability at or above one grade level
below the student's grade level.'' The law also allows school
districts to require remediation for any student in danger of
failing.
</P>
<P>
   Classes are to run from 8 a.m. to 12:30 p.m. each Saturday
beginning Jan. 22. The classes will be at 11 district schools,
including Van Horn and Southeast high schools, Central and King
middle schools and Troost, Gladstone and Weeks elementaries.
Classes for elementary and middle school students run through March
25; high school students will take classes until May 20.
</P>
<P>
   Students were chosen because they were in danger of failing
their grade level and had scored low on standardized tests.
</P>
<P>
   Beth Hammock, a spokeswoman for the district, said letters had
been mailed to parents and guardians of about 2,000 elementary and
middle school students. Those students will be required to attend
the classes, which focus on math and language arts.
</P>
<P>
   That is ideal for Julia Lee Harbin, whose granddaughter, Deauna
Harbin, has been chosen to attend Saturday school. Deauna is a
fourth-grader at Knox Elementary.
</P>
<P>
   ``She wanted me to get her (extra help) for reading,'' the
grandmother said. ``She's up on Saturday (mornings) anyway. This
will help her.''
</P>
<P>
   Letters soon will go out to about 300 high school students
selected by the district. The high school students are not required
to attend the Saturday classes but will receive one-half credit if
they do. An African-American history class, necessary to graduate
from the district, will be offered to seniors who attend, along
with math and language arts instruction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
