<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILITIA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIOLENCE NOT ON MILITIA'S Y2K LIST
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DENNIS WAGNER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Steve Porak, a Phoenix patriot, doesn't mind sharing his plan
for New Year's Eve:
</P>
<P>
   ``At 10 o'clock, I'm going to be in bed, sleeping,'' Porak said.
``If something's going to happen, it'll be there when I wake up in
the morning. . . . Y2K is a bunch of baloney.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Porak says, those who fear terrorism from militias
don't understand the U.S. Constitution or the people who zealously
defend it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The militias' goal is to preserve the union of the 50 states.
The militia are you and me.''
</P>
<P>
   That argument echoes the stand ard line from constitutionalist
out fits sprinkled across the nation, including Arizona:
</P>
<P>
   If you're worried about mayhem on New Year's Eve, don't worry
about them.
</P>
<P>
   They disavow Oklahoma City bomber Timothy McVeigh as well as an
Arizona Patriots unit that plotted similar attacks here 13 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   They claim the federal govern ment framed 12 Team Viper militia
members who allegedly plotted a terror campaign in Arizona in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   They know nothing of the 1996 sabotage of an Amtrak passenger
train west of Phoenix by some group calling itself ``Sons of the
Gestapo.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that militia members pretend to be passive. They defy the
Internal Revenue Service, defend the right to bear arms and decry
anything re sembling a New World Order.
</P>
<P>
   But, mostly, they keep to them selves _ shunning publicity as
they spread their dogma across the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Lieberman, chairman of the Anti-Defamation League in Ari
zona, said many militias are truly patriotic, but their membership
is infiltrated by violent racists.
</P>
<P>
   Because the ADL is ``a typical target of those groups,''
Lieberman added, staff members are on alert through New Year's Eve,
and Jewish synagogues have been advised to beware.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the national ADL just released a newsletter, Y2K
Paranoia, about extremist fears and plans for marking the
millennium. The report describes apocalyptic fears and Ar
mageddonlike fighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope, certainly, that nothing happens,'' Lieberman said.
``We're taking precautions.''
</P>
<P>
   The Southern Poverty Law Cen ter, a non-profit organization that
tracks anti-government groups, lists 171 militias nationwide among
435 active patriot organizations. A dozen were identified in
Arizona, going by names such as Unorganized Militia of Arizona and
First Mounted Rangers. But experts point out that other groups
operate clandestinely.
</P>
<P>
   FBI spokeswoman Susan Her skovits, asked about Y2K terrorist
concerns, said there is no informa tion she can share with the
public. Earlier this year, FBI special agent in charge, Guadalupe
Gonzales, noted that Arizona has more anti-government groups than
other states, but law enforcement cannot investigate them unless
there is a threat of violence.
</P>
<P>
   Patriot outfits are diverse and disjointed. Many subscribe to
the motto on an Arizona Viper Reserves Web page: ``Never initiate
force, nor tolerate tyranny.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, such groups may see tyranny where others do
not.
</P>
<P>
   That's apparent on the Internet. Lieberman said the ADL keeps
tabs on 800 far-right Web sites, many of which mix elaborate
conspiracy theories with anti-Semitism, herbal health tips,
survivalist guides, gun sales and get-rich-quick schemes.
</P>
<P>
   William Cooper, a shortwave ra dio broadcaster from Eagar,
touted his non-violence even while threat ening bloodshed against
federal agents if they tried to arrest him on indictments for tax
evasion and bank fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Jack McLamb, a former Phoenix sergeant who founded Police
Against the New World Order, consistently downplays violence as as
he encourages sovereign citizens to organize and arm themselves
against the ``globalists.''
</P>
<P>
   And, although Porak and others insist that Timothy McVeigh was
not part of the militia movement, there is contrary evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Long before he killed 168 people and wounded hundreds more in
Oklahoma City, McVeigh was a fan of Cooper's broadcasts _ and of
McLamb's anti-government tracts.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many insist, the media have misportrayed militia outfits
as ag gressors when their real purpose is to protect the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know anybody that believes the garbage you guys are
printing,'' Porak noted.
</P>
<P>
   Michael ``Big Mike'' Stevens, a self-described ``anti-liberal''
who publishes the SHF News, said the true believers he knows will
be hunkered down until the Y2K ca lamity ends.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if militia types might launch an offensive, Stevens said,
laughing, ``Nobody in their right mind. They aren't the ones who
will go out and start (stuff).'' &QL; 
Dennis Wagner can be reached at &QL; 
dennis.wagner &LR; arizonarepublic.com or at (602) 444-8874. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
